<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TOP ISLANDERS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ If Tuesday's dramatic victory wasn't enough to
give the struggling New York Rangers new life, maybe Wednesday
night's inspiring 3-2 victory over the rival New York Islanders
will be.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who were coming off an exhilarating overtime
triumph against the Florida Panthers, extended their winning streak
to three games with a combination of timely scoring and splendid
goaltending. It was the Rangers' second victory over the Islanders
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, who lost their third straight game, did not help
themselves by failing to convert on several juicy scoring chances
in the second and third periods. They outshot the Rangers by 25-17
and dominated the final 40 minutes of play, but could not beat
Rangers goalie Mike Richter. Tommy Salo, the Islanders' goalie,
made several difficult saves, but it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders appeared to cut the Rangers' lead to 3-2 at 8
minutes 28 seconds of the third period on a shot by Joe Sacco. The
home team requested a review of the play, which was never signaled
to be a goal by Referee Stephen Walkom or the goal judge. The
Islanders were not awarded it because the replay was inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   With 4.5 seconds remaining in the game, the Islanders' Claude
Lapointe scored to make it 3-2. But by then, it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put ourselves in a pretty big hole with four straight
losses at the start of the season,'' said Brian Leetch, the
Rangers' captain. ``We've been a .500 club since. We're starting to
get some good things going now.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Islander Coach Mike Milbury said: ``I thought we worked hard and
didn't get any breaks. A few pucks hit posts, a couple trickled
through legs.''
</P>
<P>
   given us the offense we were looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky gave the Rangers a 3-1 lead a 4:10 of the third
period when he skated through the Islanders defense and backhanded
the puck past Salo.
</P>
</TEXT>
