<HEADLINE>
THQ ACQUIRES RIVAL IN GERMAN MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Video-game maker THQ Inc. said Wednesday that it
has paid $6million for a German competitor in an effort to expand
its European presence.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, THQ bought Rushware Microhandelsgesellschaft and
its subsidiaries, Softgold Computerspiele and ABC Spielspass.
Softgold specializes in publishing and localizing personal computer
and console video games, while ABC is Rushware's distribution arm.
</P>
<P>
   THQ Chief Executive Officer Brian Farrell said the purchase is
an instrumental part of his company's plan to increase its
international sales. ``We now have direct distribution capabilities
in a market that has a population of over 80 million (people),''
Farrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Rushware will continue for at least the next 21 months to
distribute PC and Sony PlayStation products developed by LucasArts
Entertainment in German-speaking Europe, including an upcoming
title based on director George Lucas' pending ``Star Wars: Episode
One _ The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   THQ paid for the German game house with $1.5 million in cash and
$4.5 million in THQ stock. The company's shares rose $1.3125
Wednesday to close at $28.50.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
