<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ARMS (Cartagena, Colombia) _ Sixteen months ago, the
Clinton administration lifted a de facto ban on sales of the most
advanced American weapons to countries in Latin America, but there
are few signs that any country in South or Central America will be
able to purchase the sorts of sophisticated weapons covered by the
ruling anytime soon. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-ART-AUCTION (New York) _ The twice-a-year sale of
American Indian art at Sotheby's didn't go as planned. Nineteen of
the objects, including six that a number of Indian tribes had asked
to be withdrawn from the auction block, were withdrawn by the
auction house or the consignors for legal reasons. Three other
objects _ a Plains ceremonial club, a Yurok ceremonial dance apron
and a 16th or 17th century Aleut wood mask _ that Indians had also
asked to be withdrawn from the sale were bought by three determined
individuals who wanted to see the items returned to the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-SEATTLE (Everett, Wash.) _ For all the talk of Microsoft
exercising global dominance from the empire's capital here, most
residents know that the big engine for jobs remains Boeing Co., so
when it announced it was cutting 20 percent of its worldwide
workforce over the next two years, with many of those 48,000 cuts
in jobs targeted for the Seattle area, the news hit like a chill
winter wind. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-MANHUNT (Huntsville) _ Although authorities said
confidently that they would catch Martin Gurule, the first
death-row inmate to escape from the prison, they have been unable
to do so. Now they are adding a helicopter to the search, and the
people who prosecuted the killer have hired body guards. By Rick
Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CONSERVATIVES _ Even as the House Judiciary Committee
moves to expand its impeachment inquiry, a growing number of
conservatives _ from Huffington to Kristol to Bennett _ are
quietly, grudgingly giving up any hope that President Clinton will
lose his job. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-TEXACO (Undated) _ With Exxon and Mobil deciding to join
hands, the pressure on other major oil companies to find a partner
intensified Wednesday _ something that was acknowledged by Peter
Bijur, the chairman and chief executive of Texaco Inc. By Agis
Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-ROCKEFELLER _ An interview with David Rockefeller. By
Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-GAS-STATIONS _ The view from an Exxon station and a Mobil
station. By David M. Halbfinger.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-OPEC (Undated) _ Where the Exxon-Mobil deal leaves OPEC
and the other oil giants. By Youssef M. Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-EXECS (Undated) _ What the executives are going to make
from the deal. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-ARMS-MAKERS (Brussels, Belgium) _ Even as global
pressures drive Europe to a tighter single market and a new single
currency, similar pressures are forcing a consolidation of the
weapons and aviation industries. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-MARKETPLACE _ After Boeing Co. and McDonnell Douglas
Corp. announced their historic $16 billion merger in 1996, European
officials nearly blocked the deal because they were so worried that
the new American aerospace giant would pose an unfair threat to
Airbus Industrie, the European consortium that is Boeing's sole
competitor making large passenger jets. But now, almost exactly two
years later, Boeing looks like it is the company running out of gas
while Airbus appears to be steadily gaining strength. By Laurence
Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-ECONSCENE _ When the Clinton administration begins a
two-day conference next week at the White House on fixing Social
Security, the most radical option on the table, and darling of
Republicans, will be one that would allow individuals to deposit
part of their payroll taxes into private retirement accounts rather
than into the existing government fund. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-AD-COLUMN _ In what appears to be the most elaborate and
costly effort of its kind by a tobacco company, Philip Morris
U.S.A., the nation's largest cigarette maker, plans to spend at
least $100 million a year to discourage children and teen-agers
from smoking at a time when underage smoking has risen drastically.
By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
