<HEADER>
A0324 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OJ-JERSEY-COLUMN-LADN     12-03 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OJ-JERSEY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O.J. JERSEY FLAP SHOWS NO SIGN OF GOING AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If anyone thinks the name O.J. Simpson doesn't
still push people's buttons in this town, you should have been
answering my phone Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 people called and left messages offering insights,
insults and bids after the column I wrote Tuesday on a family
aiming to sell a USC football jersey O.J. wore in his great game
against UCLA in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to give the money to a charity, most likely a
shelter for battered women.
</P>
<P>
   The public reaction was overwhelming. Nobody could agree on
anything. Verbal barbs and bullets were flying all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of callers, mostly male, were willing to pony up $100 to
$200 for the jersey just so they could throw a party _ and burn it.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of people thought it should be donated to a charity,
which could then pin it up on a dartboard _ and sell darts at $20 a
pop to throw at the jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of people also thought O.J. is still getting a raw
deal in the media _ and that his old jersey should be given back to
him, not auctioned off for charity.
</P>
<P>
   One guy threw some pretty interesting, colorful names at me for
being anti-O.J., then proceeded to spend the next minute belching
steadily into my phone until the tape ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Hands down, he got my vote as the most unique caller.
</P>
<P>
   Most O.J. supporters just chose to yell. One woman was screaming
herself into such a fit about how O.J. was railroaded, she had to
pause to sit down.
</P>
<P>
   But those were mainly the fringe reactions. The majority of
callers were legitimately interested in bidding on the jersey O.J.
wore in the 1968 USC-UCLA game.
</P>
<P>
   The bids ranged from $25 from a guy who said he was one of the
working poor to $12,500 by a guy who didn't return my call to see
if the offer was legit.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt it, since all the sports memorabilia people I talked to
were telling me O.J. stuff is hard to move these days. A few
callers, though, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one of the best O.J. collections around,'' said Al
Beardsley of Burbank. ``I turned down $8,000 for a signed O.J.
jersey. There's still plenty of O.J. memorabilia interest out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Beardsley said he'd like to bid on this jersey. But he couldn't
go too high because he's saving most of his money for O.J.'s
Heisman Trophy, which goes on the auction block in February, along
with 100 items seized from his former Brentwood home.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people interested in buying the jersey, and the
intense reaction of many of the callers, was surprising and
startling, said Pat Moore, wife of Gene Grobman. Grobman and his
brother-in-law, Mitch Kaye, have shared O.J.'s jersey these past 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye, a student physical therapist with the USC team back in
1968, said he took O.J.'s jersey from the locker room after the
UCLA game and gave it to his sister-in-law as a wedding anniversary
gift.
</P>
<P>
   He said O.J. didn't object to his taking the jersey. Kaye
offered to return it to him in early 1994, but before they could
meet, the slayings of Simpson's ex-wife Nicole Brown Simpson and
her friend Ronald Goldman occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Although a lot of people thought the two families shouldn't be
trying to auction off the jersey and should just give it back to
O.J. or USC, Moore said she's glad they went public trying to sell
the jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``This jersey is important,'' she said. ``During the (Simpson)
murder trial, some charities that help battered women came about or
survived because more people became aware of this terrible problem
and got involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If by selling this jersey, and giving the money to a battered
women's shelter, it continues to help shed more light on this
problem, we'll all feel very gratified.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as what happens to O.J.'s old football jersey next, it's
up to Moore, her husband and brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   An offer to auction it off at a major fund-raiser for a
nonprofit organization at the Skirball Center fell through
Wednesday when the auctioneer balked, saying it would be a mistake
to include any O.J. memorabilia in the auction.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I will be giving Moore the names of other local
charities and organizations that called and expressed an interest
in auctioning off the jersey at their fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I will give her the telephone numbers of individuals who
seemed serious in offering a legitimate bid for the jersey.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 0021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-CITYHALL-NYT &LR;      12-03 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-CITYHALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CITY HALL, BEHIND BARRICADES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Dec. 3:
</P>
<P>
   In an age when terrorists are on the loose, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has every right to be concerned about protecting New
York's City Hall from attack. The bombings of the World Trade
Center and of the federal building in Oklahoma City and the
spraying of bullets around the Capitol in Washington are ample
proof of the threat. But there is always a danger that the concrete
barricades and police blockades now surrounding City Hall to thwart
terrorists will stifle dissent and frustrate public access to the
nerve center of government. Security is an issue that calls for an
exquisite balance of competing values, and full public discussion
of the reasons for it. The mayor and the City Council need to think
these through.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, protesters have lost their traditional right
to hold press conferences on the City Hall steps. Casual visitors
are barred from walking on the premises, and police now shoo even
City Council members away from the front porch that always served
as an informal meeting place for the politicians, advocates,
journalists and dissidents who make up the city's political
community.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani says the restrictions are necessary because of security
concerns connected to an upcoming terrorist trial. He has a duty to
state more clearly the nature of the threat. Giuliani's critics,
meanwhile, attribute the new controls to his aversion to dissent
and even minimal amounts of disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The danger that security measures can repress dissent was seen
in the administration's handling of a press conference by an AIDS
service organization this week. Members of the group, Housing
Works, won a court order giving them the right to hold a public
event in the City Hall parking lot. The demonstrators, who numbered
less than 200, were sent through outdoor metal detectors. Their
spokesmen were then corralled into a small pen surrounded by
barriers, separated from their hundred-odd supporters. The media
were herded into another pen. Inspectors from the Department of
Environmental Protection bearing noise meters monitored a reading
of the names of people who had died from AIDS, to make sure the
roll call of victims was not exceeding official decibel limits. A
reporter who attempted to watch the activity from the City Hall
porch was ordered to go inside by officers who asserted that there
was a danger the demonstrators might rush the building.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council needs to take a serious look at the entire set
of policies that has cut City Hall off from the public. Giuliani
and his police commissioner seem to regard use of the City Hall
steps and porch as a potential threat. Yet they apparently felt it
was safe to allow thousands of people to come to the City Hall
grounds for rallies on behalf of the Yankees and John Glenn. The
police have now been given the discretion to decide which visitors
have a good reason for entering City Hall, but they have no formal
guidelines for making those judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Council Speaker Peter Vallone met with the mayor Wednesday and
appeared to believe that Giuliani was willing to compromise, allow
more public access and reduce the repressive atmosphere around the
building. But later Giuliani said he had agreed only to permit tour
groups for a limited number of set hours. The mayor compared his
precautions to those taken to protect the Capitol in Washington,
which has been the scene of many violent incidents. But the public
is in fact welcome in the Capitol. Like City Hall, it is guarded by
police who require all visitors to pass through metal detectors.
But Congress, in its attempts to balance security with the public's
right of access, has declined to impose further restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to risk vetoing a precaution that might turn out to
be crucial in averting violence. But Giuliani must show the city
that his actions are based on more than a conviction that he knows
better than anyone how to handle public safety issues. Fear cannot
be the single factor that determines how the business of the city
is conducted, and if extraordinarily tight security is warranted,
the reason can be explained to the public without compromising
police intelligence sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
