<HEADER>
A0349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-AUCTION-1STLD-     12-03 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-AUCTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTHEBY'S AUCTION IS SOMETHING ELSE ENTIRELY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An auction of American Indian art at Sotheby's in
Manhattan turned out to be less of an auction than expected on
Wednesday, after protests by several Indian tribes that argued that
their cultural heritage should not be sold into private hands.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen of the objects, including six that several tribes had
asked to be removed from the auction block, were withdrawn by the
auction house or the consignors for legal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In three other cases, objects that Indians had also requested be
withdrawn _ a Plains ceremonial club, a Yurok ceremonial dance
apron and a 16th- or 17th-century Aleut wooden mask _ went to
buyers who said they intended to turn them over to the tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, the lines were drawn between those who
support the Indians' right to repossess sacred objects and those
who believe that objects in private hands should remain so.
</P>
<P>
   In the former camp is Elizabeth Sackler, who advised the
successful bidders for the three disputed items. Ms. Sackler, the
daughter of the antiquities collector Arthur Sackler, is the
founder and president of the American Indian Ritual Object
Repatriation Foundation in Manhattan. She created the foundation
after another Indian auction at Sotheby's in 1991, where she bought
and returned to the tribes three masks, two Hopi and one Navajo,
that the Indians consider sacred and had asked to be withdrawn from
the sale.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side was the anthropologist Edmund Carpenter, who
said that he was ``saddened'' by the auction's direction. ``Disgust
is too positive,'' he said. ``It's a sad scene.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he deplored a 1990 federal statute that provides for the
return of many Indian objects to the tribes, but makes no provision
for housing or caring for the objects.
</P>
<P>
   An Eskimo wood mask consigned by Carpenter's wife, Adelaide de
Menil, and sought by the Aleuts was purchased by a California
woman, Anne Bleecker Corcos, for $46,000. Ms. Corcos, the head of a
nonprofit organization that supports Indian issues, said she
planned to return the mask to the Aleuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a personal thing,'' she said. ``I feel it's important for
native Americans to receive these things back, especially those of
ceremonial and spiritual value.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Rockefeller Roberts, president of Fund of the Four
Directories, a group that offers grants to Indian causes, bought
the Yurok apron for $11,500 ``because this is an object that the
Yurok nation has identified as sacred to their spiritual practices
and cultural lineage.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Gutstein, an IBM administrator at the company's
headquarters in Armonk, N.Y., paid $7,475 for a Plains ceremonial
club that the Fort Peck Assiniboine and Sioux Tribes of Montana had
asked be withdrawn from auction. ``My interest,'' he said, ``was to
return it to its owners. It's a ritual object that has meaning to
its community and serves a binding role.''
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, more than 600 lots of American Indian art were at
auction on Wednesday, and in most cases, their sale was not in
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 19 objects that were pulled from the sale at the last
minute because of unresolved legal issues, 7 were withdrawn because
Sotheby's said further research was needed to ascertain whether
tribes claiming the items had been notified.
</P>
<P>
   In the other cases, items were withdrawn because the auction
house had not determined whether the feathers on them were covered
by a 1916 act regulating the sale of feathers from certain
migratory birds.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items was a bentwood hunting hat from the Aleut
Indians. Representatives of the tribe had protested the hat's sale.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Menil, the hat's consignor, and Carpenter had rejected
requests to withdraw the hat and the Aleut mask, saying that they
feared the objects would not be properly cared for by the tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I,'' Carpenter said, ``have been vigilant in
protecting these objects for future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutstein and his wife, Nancy, have set up two scholarships (for
a young man and young woman) at each of the 30 American Indian
tribal colleges in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A three-member delegation of Aleuts from the Aleutian/Pribilof
Islands Association that had flown in from Alaska for the sale
expressed pleasure at the outcome on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are finally breaking the ice and working toward gathering
items, spiritual, ritual and cultural items,'' said Dimitri
Philemonof, who heads the association.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the wood mask to be returned to the Aleuts, Allison
Young, the cultural heritage director of the association, said,
``There are no words to describe the joy the people in the region
will feel when they see the ancestral object.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
