<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0352 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     12-03 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN ESCAPES LIFE IN FISH BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ At last the appointed time had arrived for the
Angels to unveil their rare acquisition. Alas, the
long-sought-after proof that Disney does indeed have deep pockets
and discriminating tastes was late arriving (tell Angels fans about
it!).
</P>
<P>
   So for an hour Wednesday all anyone in the assemblage at Edison
Field saw of Mo Vaughn was his likeness luminating the outfield
Jumbotron.
</P>
<P>
   As the seconds passed like centuries, suits with cell phones
paced the restaurant area behind home plate as nervously as
secret-service agents. Imagine their panic, misplacing something
that weighs 250 pounds and is worth $80 million. It turns out
Vaughn wasn't lost, just stuck in traffic, first in the skies above
a fogged-in LAX and then on the 405 Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Where Vaughn came from, some wild story about him having been in
an accident or having decided to slip into a bar for a quick scotch
surely would have beaten him to the ballpark. But this being the
blase capital of the country, Vaughn's entrance was greeted with
warm applause.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, this offseason's most-sought-after slugger, signed with
the Angels primarily because he covets a World Series ring to wear
next to his diamond-encrusted pinkie ring (the jewels form a 42,
his jersey number).
</P>
<P>
   However, it made it a whole lot easier pulling up roots from his
native New England knowing he was going to a place where people
aren't inclined to suspect the worst should he show up an hour late
for an engagement.
</P>
<P>
   As hockey icon Wayne Gretzky and basketball superstar Shaquille
O'Neal found out before him, Southern California might be teeming
with people, but it offers something elementary that a small market
cannot: breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be yourself here and that's an added plus,'' said the
30-year-old Vaughn, flashing a smile that outsparkled his
mismatched pair of diamond-studded earrings and the
thick-as-his-biceps gold chain around his neck. ``Everybody out
here is relaxed and takes things as they come. I look forward to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is coming off an eight-year marriage with the Boston Red
Sox that ended badly, with each side excoriating the other. The
ballplayer who won the 1995 American League MVP award earlier this
year charged the front office with hiring somebody to tail him.
General manager Dan Duquette countered by voicing concerns over
Vaughn's drinking habits in the wake of three separate incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who is single, sounded much like a jilted suitor as he
tried to make sense of the Red Sox's failure to try to sign him
during a two-week window following the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not believe (Boston) did not bargain with me,'' said
the first baseman, who is coming off a season in which he hit 40
home runs and batted .337. ``When you have been in an organization
as long as I had, sometimes people tend to begin to take for
granted your efforts. I really feel like it's their loss.''
</P>
<P>
   All the big fish are nearly gone from baseball's freshly stocked
pond, and the Red Sox have yet to reel in a sizable free agent.
They got nibbles from outfielder Bernie Williams before he
re-signed with the Yankees, but that was about it. Asked to comment
about Boston's futile fishing expedition, Vaughn smartly declined
to take the bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Sox have enough to worry about without me trying to
make them look bad,'' he said. ``I've got too much class as a man
and a person to belittle somebody else because of my good fate. I
hold no grudges against the Red Sox, you know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   We do know this: Whatever transpired in Boston is history. After
all, California is the land of sunshine, second chances and
Disneyland, the self-proclaimed happiest place on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had anything to hide about my life or about
myself,'' Vaughn said. ``I'm a little tired of the controversy. I
hope I get judged for what I do on the field. That's all I think is
important.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, when you're the highest-paid player in baseball,
there is no foul territory in your life. Every move you make, good
or bad, becomes fair game for your fans and foes alike. We hope
Vaughn remembers to conduct himself as an Angel on and off the
field.
</P>
<P>
   He's lucky in that he already has a sizable support group, as
evidenced by the handful of Angels players who showed up at Edison
Field Wednesday to welcome him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I came here,'' quipped pitcher Chuck Finley,
``is to find out which half of Disneyland they gave Mo.''
</P>
<P>
   Silly Chuck, everybody knows it was Tomorrowland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
