<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-OILERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES' STREAK ENDS  
 OILERS TAKE CHARGE TO FINISH OFF UNBEATEN ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ As they filed out of the dressing room for
the start of the third period, the Coyotes looked like a team that
was facing the final 20 minutes of their season.
</P>
<P>
   Like the final period of Game 7 in the Stanley Cup Finals.
Wednesday night's game against the Edmonton Oilers wasn't nearly
that important. Not by a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   But try telling that to the emotionally charged Coyotes, who
overcame a 2-1 deficit in the second period and grabbed an early
third-period lead, only to watch Edmonton storm back for a 4-3
victory at the Skyreach Centre.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Buchberger and Rem Murray scored goals 1 minute and 35
seconds apart for the Oilers, who got some revenge for a recent 3-2
overtime loss in Phoenix by putting an end to several of the
Coyotes' streaks.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is their 14-game unbeaten streak, which already was a club
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is their eight-game winning streak, which ended one shy of
tying a club record.
</P>
<P>
   And gone is their unprecedented string of 17 straight games
without allowing more than two goals, which stopped two shy of
tying the NHL's modern-day mark set by Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was bound to happen. You can't win every game,''
Keith Tkachuk said. ``But it was a weird game. We felt we should
have won. We put 48 shots on net. . . . I mean, 48 shot? And we
only scored three goals. But stats prove you should win the hockey
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes (14-3-2) had their work cut out for them all night.
They fell behind early, and had to play catch-up the rest of the
way until Tkachuk gave them their first lead at the 1:17 mark of
the third when he redirected Jyrki Lumme's slap shot past Mikhail
Shtalenkov on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk's 13th goal, which Shtalenkov never saw, wasn't enough,
however. Neither was their season-high 48 shots. The Coyotes'
usually clamping defense didn't shut down the Oilers like it has
everyone else since a season-opening 4-1 loss to the Ottawa
Senators. Goalie Nikolai Khabibulin, who routinely has come up with
huge, game-saving performances down the stretch, also wasn't
himself.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he didn't seem to be on his game from the beginning of
pre-game warm-ups. The NHL's second-ranked netminder, who entered
the game with a 1.57 goals-against average, allowed four goals on
22 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been unbelievable for us all year, though,'' Tkachuk
said. ``It wasn't Niki's fault. We just made a couple bad decisions
out there, a few mistakes we normally don't make.''
</P>
<P>
   The goals by Buchberger and Murray were back-breakers, not just
streak-busters. Buchberger tied the score at 3 at the 9:54 mark
when he wristed a shot to the far top shelf past Khabibulin. Then
at 11:29, defenseman Tom Poti rifled a blast that Khabibulin
knocked down, but couldn't control.
</P>
<P>
   With the puck resting at his knees, Murray swept in and jammed
it into the net, bringing the crowd to the feet and the Coyotes to
the sudden realization that they weren't bring to go the rest of
the season without a loss.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game, however, that Phoenix had been winning during
its torrid early-season start. It just never seemed to be their
night from the moment Edmonton left wing Dean McAmmond scored his
first goal of the year with 1:48 left in the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Teppo Numminen couldn't pinch Pat Falloon off the
boards before his centering pass found McAmmond. Coyotes center
Jeremy Roenick, who dropped deep to cover McAmmond in the slot,
couldn't knock him out of the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we weren't going to go on forever, but this loss
hurts, though,'' Coyotes center Daniel Briere said. ``We played so
well and this is a little hard to take. But at the same time, we
need to take a lesson and learn something from this. If we keep
playing hard, good things are going to keep happening for us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
