<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0359 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZ     12-03 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM GETS NASTY; IT'S ABOUT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Diamondbacks way of life has met sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   No eulogy is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have someone who can compete in any sport, you give
him space,'' Jerry Colangelo said. ``If that means he has long
hair, he has long hair. You've got to be flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a 97-loss season comes many promising things, but
nothing more refreshing than this drastic change in policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks don't need choirboys. They don't need
clean-shaven robots. They don't need pretentious talk about
character and good citizens and appearance codes better suited for
the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks need nasty. And with Randy Johnson, that's just
what they're getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be days when he's very temperamental,'' Colangelo
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as Johnson's two agents spewed damage control like
oscillating sprinklers, as Johnson harped about the importance of
family, an interesting thing happened. The manager, Buck Showalter,
didn't say a word. And then he left the proceedings for an
afternoon engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Showalter is ecstatic over inheriting a pitcher of
Johnson's pedigree. But his vision of a homogenous clubhouse of
crew cuts has been trampled, replaced with the reality of now: If a
guy can play, who cares if his tongue is pierced and Marilyn Manson
lyrics decorate his locker?
</P>
<P>
   This could be a significant shift in power, a sign that the
Diamondbacks are now being built with Colangelo's vision rather
than Showalter's. Or it could be the simple case of bending around
unique talent. Either way, it was a much-needed change.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Diamondbacks were bad and boring. They entered
the league with an abundance of attitude and no one to back it up.
They were quickly exposed as a bunch of puppies, all yap and no
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have the attitude of Greg Swindell, the chair-throwing
fire of Todd Stottlemyre, and best of all, the menacing scowl of
Johnson. A faceless team is finally growing an identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every fifth day that I go out there, I'll bring something to
this team that they haven't had before, that the fans haven't seen
before,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   This won't be easy on us, mind you. If the Diamondbacks wanted
revenge on the media, the ones they blame for the outrage over
ticket prices, they couldn't have done much better, save for Albert
Belle.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did his best to distance himself from the strained
relationships of his past on Wednesday, but most journalists who
have covered the Big Unit have a few war stories to tell. And a
television reporter who showed up at his home in Paradise Valley on
Tuesday is already banned for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   He is moody, surly, a lightning rod in the clubhouse. Just what
the Diamondbacks need.
</P>
<P>
   Although mercurial, Johnson also carries a genuine warrior's
mentality. In 1996, he underwent significant back surgery. Given
Johnson's size, that's like treating a giraffe with a sore throat.
Nevertheless, the following season, he pitched 213 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Brian Holman, a former teammate who tells a
wonderful story. Once upon a time, before Johnson became an
enigmatic star, he was a minor league pitcher at Indianapolis. And
once upon a time, he drilled a minor league batter with a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   The minor league batter started toward the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy screamed at him, `Don't mess with me, I'll take your
life,' '' Holman said. ``The guy went right to first base.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is risk in giving a 35-year-old pitcher a
multiyear contract. There are no guarantees he'll stay healthy or
happy. Nothing guaranteed except for the $53 million he's owed by
the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   But he is emotional, disciplined, animated. And every time he
pitches, it's an event. He brings an infusion of energy and
attitude much needed on Jefferson Street, especially entering a
season when the stadium is no longer a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to play, you've got to pay,'' Colangelo said.
``These days, there's no halfway. You either go all the way or you
go to sleep. And I'm not going to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, neither will the fans. With the arrival of
Johnson, the Buck _ and the boring _ stops here. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
