<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS SEEKING A TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers gained a second opportunity to
acquire a No. 1 starter yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Roger Clemens, 36, who lives in the Houston suburb
of Katy, informed the Toronto Blue Jays of his desire to be traded
to an organization closer to his home or traded to a playoff
contender.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and Houston Astros fit both descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we'll talk about it,'' Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin said. ``We're one of the clubs he'd want to go to.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees general manager Brian Cashman yesterday
acknowledged his team's interest, and the Cleveland Indians likely
will be interested in acquiring Clemens, too.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, who spent his vacation last week with general managers
Gord Ash of the Blue Jays and Walt Jocketty of the St. Louis
Cardinals, made inquiries then regarding Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Ash, though, replied that the Blue Jays did not plan to part
with Clemens ``unless the demand came that he wanted to be
traded,'' Melvin said. That occurred yesterday afternoon, less than
48 hours after the Rangers learned that left-hander Randy Johnson
spurned their four-year contract offer worth $50 million to sign
with the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' representatives, Alan and Randy Hendricks, secured a
gentlemen's agreement with Ash that the five-time Cy Young Award
recipient could demand a trade if the Blue Jays did not appear to
be a playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize they would have a decent team,'' said Randy
Hendricks, who telephoned Ash to make the demand. ``The reality is,
they're not prepared to add players and contend at the highest
level.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers inquired about Clemens before the July trade
deadline, but nothing materialized. Melvin and Ash discussed a
trade that would send Clemens to the Rangers for left fielder Rusty
Greer, left-hander Darren Oliver and minor-league catcher Cesar
King, a Blue Jays official said then.
</P>
<P>
   The two organizations never found common ground for a trade,
because the Blue Jays reportedly wanted Ruben Mateo instead of
King, and it remains to be seen whether it can be accomplished now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Melvin said. ``I'll have to talk to Gord
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays hope to trade Clemens within 10 days, and Major
League Baseball's winter meetings _ scheduled Dec. 11-15 in
Nashville, Tenn. _ will provide a convenient forum for Ash.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly not done with any acrimony or with any anger
on either side,'' Ash said. ``I think it's important not to let his
drag out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays are not seeking prospects in return for Clemens,
who will earn $8.25 million annually for the 1999 and 2000 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're really going to be interested in future
returns,'' Ash said. ``We're looking more for present value. I want
clubs to come forward and tell us what they're prepared to do. I
don't want to put any parameters on it.'' Selling the name Rangers
owner Tom Hicks' agenda includes upcoming discussions regarding the
sale of the naming rights to The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just now starting that process,'' Hicks said. ``We're
setting up some meetings within the next couple of weeks. We'd like
to get that done before this season.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants received a 25-year contract worth $50
million _ including $24 million up front _ for the sale of the name
of their new ballpark to Pac-Bell. The Giants' new ballpark is
scheduled to be ready for the 2000 season. Briefly The Rangers
designated reserve infielder Domingo Cedeno for assignment. The
Rangers must trade or release Cedeno within 10 days or assign him
outright to the minor leagues. Cedeno can reject any minor-league
assignment and elect free agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers signed catcher Mike Hubbard and assigned the
27-year-old to Triple-A Oklahoma of the Pacific Coast League.
Hubbard, who this past season hit .145 with one home run and three
runs batted in during 32 games for the Montreal Expos, will receive
an invitation to spring training as a non-roster player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
