</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S DANGER IN THE DESERT AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - He reminds you of one of the Dalton gang. The tall one
they call Slim.
</P>
<P>
   His blue eyes are deep-set, watchful. The thick mustache is the
saloon variety, made for stud poker and collecting sarsasparilla
foam.
</P>
<P>
   The tangle of brown curls cascade to a powerful set of shoulders
so wide that when he slipped on the new uniform top with his last
name printed across the back, the team publicist drew a breath and
held it, fearing size 52 might be too small.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 10, he looked almost uncomfortable in a business suit
and tie.
</P>
<P>
   It is easier to imagine him in faded jeans _ holster riding low
on his hip _ or better yet, in Diamondbacks colors, a towering
angular figure on the mound, those blue eyes narrowed in
concentration, peering coldly over the webbing of his glove.
</P>
<P>
   How many hours have those eyes spent staring toward home plate?
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball's my life,'' he said. ``Been doing it since I was 7
years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Little League. High school. In college, at USC, he played on the
same team with Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   He once said of those wild, wild days, ``I could throw real
hard. But about every third pitch hit the backstop on the fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time the thrower developed into a fearsome pitcher. Today,
ball in hand, hidden behind his back, he is the most intimidating
presence in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine crouching over the plate, heart thumping as he begins
the windup. All arms and legs and knees and elbows. His long left
arm comes over his shoulder, a bullwhip. The ball flies into the
batter's face like a hawk.
</P>
<P>
   How fast _ 95? 98? 100 mph? ``I don't have any trick pitches,''
he said. The scariest competitor in baseball doesn't need any.
</P>
<P>
   There is an air of danger about him. If what Yogi said is true,
that 90 percent of baseball is half mental, some batters step to
the plate with two strikes against them.
</P>
<P>
   When he delivers a fastball beneath a batter's chin it likely is
no accident. They used to call it crop-dusting although in this
case the term is a little genteel.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about a single-engine plane gliding lazily
over a field of alfalfa or sweet corn, spraying a thick white
cloud.
</P>
<P>
   When this guy comes high and inside, the mental picture is that
of an F-16 fighter. The ground shakes with its thunder. A voice in
the batter's mind screams, ``Code Red!'' No time to react. This guy
doesn't dust. He strafes.
</P>
<P>
   This, in part, may help explain why a few players have reached
the prayerful decision to take themselves out of the lineup when he
is scheduled to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference, he looked into the audience. His
mother was there, as was the memory of his late father. His wife,
Mrs. Unit, was holding two of their three small children. The
smallest squirmed and chewed on a plush toy rattlesnake _ a symbol
of daddy's new employer and his game-day disposition.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged them with a brief smile. ````They,'''' he said,
of his family, ``don't even come around me on the day I pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The watchful eyes show no fatigue. Nor does his arm. As they say
at the theater, we know what he did last summer. Acquired after
mid-season by the Astros _ ``Houston, We Have Liftoff'' the
``Sports Illustrated'' cover read _ the ex-Mariner won 10 games and
lost one. His earned-run average was 1.28. He pitched well in the
playoffs against the Padres, but the Astros' bats fell silent.
</P>
<P>
   He had back surgery at age 33. Now he is 35. A gamble?
Certainly. ``Pitchers are like racehorses,'' said Gerry Hunsicker,
the Astros' general manager. ``The expensive ones break down just
like the inexpensive ones. Only the risk is greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Colangelo saw what we saw last season. ``It was like men
playing against boys to some degree,'' he said. So he took the risk
and in keeping with baseball's financial insanity offered one
pitcher $52 million (plus per diem).
</P>
<P>
   The player who makes his home in Paradise Valley accepted. He
``put family over money,'' his agent said _ one of those noble
statements that makes the public gag.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Diamondbacks overpay? Of course they did. But don't
blame the new ace of the pitching staff for accepting the home
team's open-armed generosity. Who among us wouldn't take the money?
</P>
<P>
   In return, the ball club gets a marquee player. ``El Unit-o
Grande.'' An athlete who will fill the ballpark. Create excitement
in any language. Give his team some much-needed personality. Make
the players around him better.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry finally got the big man he wanted. Too bad he doesn't play
for the Suns. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
