<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0364 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PROGOLF-GIVING-AZ     12-03 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PROGOLF-GIVING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLFERS ADD TWIST TO GIFT PLAN _ THEY DELIVER, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Salvation Army estimates there are 37,000 needy
kids in the Valley, many of whom will wake up on Christmas morning
without presents under their trees. Many won't even have trees.
Living on the street can be mean in that way.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Magee and Gary McCord were aware of these depressing
facts of life when they founded the Santa Claus Classic in 1994. By
enlisting the help of their fellow PGA Tour professionals who live
in the Phoenix area, they were able to do something about it,
raising more than $1 million over the past five years for
underprivileged kids at Christmastime.
</P>
<P>
   As the Santa Claus Classic grew, the pros wanted to do more than
just raise money for the human services agencies that take care of
these impoverished families. That's why they will take half of this
year's proceeds _ $100,000 _ and go directly to the kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary and I decided last summer that we wanted to make a bigger
impact and really see some tangible results this Christmas,'' Magee
said. ``We made up our mind that we'd round up $100,000 worth of
toys and give them out personally, along with Santa Claus, to each
kid who needs one.''
</P>
<P>
   Distributing 5,000 toys, however, was a much bigger undertaking
than Magee and McCord had imagined. But remember, these guys are
globetrotting professional golfers with a lot of connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it turned out, I was playing in a pro-am in Cape Cod
(Mass.) not long after Gary and I decided to take on the toy
mission,'' Magee said. ``One of the guys I happened to be paired
with was a friend named Bob Nakasone, the (chief executive officer)
of Toys `R' Us.''
</P>
<P>
   Magee didn't even have to twist Nakasone's arm to get the toy
company involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob said he would love to do it,'' Magee said. ``From that
point, it was just a matter of getting down the logistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would get the toys and how they would be distributed came
from input from family service agencies, Magee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to the Salvation Army's computer and all of its
information, we've been able to plan this thing right down to the
age and the gender of most of the kids who will receive toys,''
Magee said.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the Santa Claus gift giveaways takes place from 9
a.m. to noon Saturday at the Phoenix/South Mountain Family Services
Center at the South Mountain Park Activity Complex, 10919 S.
Central Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the rest of the toys are being loaded in Los Angeles
on special pallets, each one earmarked for specific giveaway dates,
which also include: Dec. 11 at 3:30 p.m. at the Phoenix/Sky Harbor
Family Services Center at the Ann Ott School Cafeteria, 1801 S.
12th St.; Dec. 12 at 9 a.m., Phoenix/West Phoenix Human Services
Center at Maryvale Baseball Park, 3600 N. 51st Ave.; Dec. 15 at
8:30 a.m., Santa Claus Classic Day at the Salvation Army Family
Services Center, 2702 E. Washington; and Dec. 25 at 11 a.m.,
Salvation Army Christmas Day Dinner at the Phoenix Civic Plaza, 225
E. Adams.
</P>
<P>
   What really depicts the Christmas spirit of the giveaway is that
three of the five Santa Claus gift sessions will take place before
this year's tournament, Dec. 18 at the TPC of Scottsdale. In other
words, the toys were given to the pros to distribute to the
children basically on good faith, as well as at a reduced cost,
from Toys `R' Us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted to have such a positive relationship with the
Santa Claus Classic people and to provide them with our toys for
this unique program,'' said Toby Cogswell, the area director for
Toy `R' Us. ``We see every day how important it is to youngsters to
receive gifts during this time of year, and it makes us proud to be
able to help out.''
</P>
<P>
   Magee said the list of those who deserve a special tip of the
golf cap for pulling off this Christmas miracle is a long one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary and I got the ball rolling, but a lot of people have
played key roles, like my good friend John Russell, who is the
tournament director,'' the Paradise Valley pro said. ``And this
year, because of the uniqueness of what we had planned, I also had
to lean on my neighbor, Richard Jackson, for some help in
coordinating all this stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``But over the years, all the tour guys in the Valley have taken
part at one time or another, plus a few of the ladies from the
LPGA. Don't forget, besides all the amateurs who pay to play in the
Santa Claus tournament, the players also pitch in some money to
help the kids, too. I think that's pretty neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, others think so, too, such as ESPN and The Golf
Channel, which plan to air featured broadcasts on several of the
Santa Claus giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The look on a child's face at Christmas time is one of the
most precious things in all the world,'' said Magee, who will be on
hand with several of his brethren at each stop on the Santa Claus
tour.
</P>
<P>
   Those family agencies who keep track of the needy are especially
grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Santa Claus Classic has been a godsend,'' said Lt. Colonel
Olin Hogan of the Salvation Army. ``The commitment to the community
of Phoenix will enable us to make thousands of children smile on
Christmas morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Hurtado, human services director for the city of Phoenix,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being fortunate enough to pair up with the Santa Claus Classic
is a genuine reason to smile this holiday season,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
