<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM GIVES RICE INCENTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Cardinals defensive end  &UR; Simeon Rice never has
met New York Giants offensive line coach  &UR; John Matsko.
</P>
<P>
   So he has no idea whether Matsko, the former Cardinals and
University of Arizona assistant, called him ``a coward,'' as two
listeners reported this week on a Valley radio station.
</P>
<P>
   The listeners said that Matsko told them one reason the Giants
had dominated the Cardinals the past two seasons was because Rice
was ``a coward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that,'' Rice said. ``I say that not from the
perspective of someone calling me that, but I'll use that. Thank
you. I appreciate knowing that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who play Sunday at Sun Devil Stadium, have beaten
the Cardinals three consecutive times, including a 34-7 victory on
Oct. 18 in Giants Stadium. In those three games, the Giants have
rushed for 581 yards, often running right at Rice, who weighs 260
pounds, small for a defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was presented with the situation in the past that Simeon
can't play the run,'' Rice said. ``Then I went out and dominated
the run. I like that, even if he didn't say that. I'll take that.''
</P>
<P>
   Matsko said he never called Rice a coward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding me?'' Matsko said from Tucson, where the
Giants are practicing this week. ``I've watched that guy play. I've
got great respect for that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice is leading the Cardinals in sacks with nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of situations, I'm from the new school,'' Rice said.
``But I've got an old work ethic. I have a throwback work ethic. My
mentality is that of a throwback player, go out there and grind,
play hurt. I've done that.'' &QL; 
Decision remains &QL; 
 &UR; Jamir Miller doesn't know where he will play Sunday _ outside or
middle linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   He was moved to middle linebacker Tuesday because of knee
injuries to
 &UR; Ronald McKinnon and  &UR; Mark Maddox and worked there in practice
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin said Miller looked ``pretty good'' playing
inside but that he will be able to make a better evaluation after
today's workout in pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't made a final decision,'' Miller said. ``When we get
the pads on and start banging, I'll know more. We'll see how I
feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were healthy, it wouldn't be an issue. But I have the
(dislocated) wrist, and there's a lot more pounding in there than
playing outside.''
</P>
<P>
   If Miller starts at middle linebacker,  &UR; Patrick Sapp will
replace him at left outside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals have other injury problems at outside
linebacker.  &UR; Tony
 &UR; McCombs, who starts on the right side, missed Wednesday's workout
because of a toe injury. He is expected to play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Toothache &QL; 
Giants wide receiver  &UR; Ike Hilliard missed practice Wednesday in
Tucson because of a tooth injury. He had two teeth pulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spent too much time on Halloween when he was a kid,'' said
Giants Coach  &UR; Jim Fassel, former Cardinals offensive coordinator. &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Kicker  &UR; Joe Nedney (knee) was placed on injured reserve to make
room on the roster for his replacement,  &UR; Chris Jacke.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox, out for the past two games, returned to practice
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Cardinals have forced only three turnovers in
their past three games, they still lead the NFL in takeaways with
30.
</P>
<P>
   Running back  &UR; Adrian Murrell and his wife,  &UR; Tanya, are the proud
parents of a baby girl born Tuesday. Aryn Brice, who weighed 6
pounds, 10 ounces, is their second child. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
