<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS COME UP SHORT WITH TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Arizona State more than messed with Texas in the
first women's basketball game between the schools Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite enough to win, but enough to force the Longhorns into
overtime before falling, 77-75, before 1,042 at Wells Fargo Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've been in a basketball game,'' said Texas' Jody
Conradt, the winningest coach in NCAA Division I history. ``Both
teams played about as hard as they could play. We felt frustration
at losing two leads and some of it was our not handling the ball,
but a lot of it was Arizona State being aggressive defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU (2-2) trailed by 16 at halftime then used a 16-4 run to
close with six, 55-49, at the 10:34 mark. But the young Sun Devils
spun somewhat out of control trying to press their comeback, and
Texas (2-3) scored all but two points of a 14-0 run on layups to
lead 69-49 with 7:28 left. Amazingly, ASU was not done yet.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting guard Kitch Kitchen had seven of her team-high 16
points in a 16-2 run to bring the Sun Devils within 71-65 at the
2:22 mark. After that, ASU had to foul and hope for missed free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Texas obliged, going 4 for 11 from the foul line down the
stretch. Then, ASU scored on three critical possessions in the
final 37 seconds: a three-pointer by Shelly Tom; a running
five-footer by point guard Natalie Tucker; and a two-footer by
freshman Leah Combs to tie the score at 75 with 14 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ASU continued to press, and Tom was charged with a quick foul
that Kim Lummus converted into two of her four points. Lummus was
coming off a 26-point game against three-time defending national
champion Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd trade those 26 for these two tonight,'' said Conradt, who
called timeout at 11.2 seconds to set her defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns showed press then smartly dropped back to protect
against a 3-pointer and better prepare for ASU picks. When Tucker
found no one open in the post, she drove toward the baseline and
was bumped but not enough to warrant a foul in leaving a 3-footer
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played the first half like we played (No. 11) Rutgers,''
ASU Coach Charli Turner Thorne said, referring to a 67-48 loss
Sunday. ``We're still learning how to play hard. We played the
second half like the team we're going to be. Texas is too good to
waste the first 20 minutes and spot them 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could have learned everything in the Rutgers game,
but I'm not sure that's too realistic. I hope these two games
together turns the light bulb on for this team in terms of how hard
they have to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman center Rashunda Johnson scored eight of Texas' first 14
points as the Longhorns built a seven-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ASU still was within five, 20-15, with 10:19 left before
intermission when Texas went on an 8-0 run thanks to its veteran
perimeter. a pair of baskets each by seniors Vanessa Wallace and
Dee Smith and junior Edwina Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns stretched that run to 12-1, going up 32-16, and
maintained the 16-point margin at half, 44-28.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, working too often from short range, fired 65.6 percent in
the first half. The Sun Devils, by contrast, were at 30 percent and
16.7 (1-for-6) from three-point. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
