<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE DEMOTION, VENERABLE PRO MOON GOING OUT WITH HEAD HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Maybe it is not such a great thing to be 42, in
terrific shape, maybe the best of your life.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Moon's body tells him to keep on trucking.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is not such a great thing that with 21 years of
professional experience, Moon's football IQ makes him a walking
telestrator, ready to break down zone coverages at the drop of a
hat.
</P>
<P>
   His mind tells him he has seen it all.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all those years Moon spent learning to play coolly under
pressure has muted the most critical ingredient for success as an
NFL quarterback _ the ability to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all those miles of pass completions, all the career
accomplishments that make Moon's section in the Seahawk media guide
as thick as this week's playbook, can't explain why Moon's career
looks like it is coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is, I can accept it,'' Moon said Wednesday. ``I've
beaten all the odds. I've done everything and more than anyone,
including myself, dreamed of. I've had a good, good career, and
like any athlete I want to play as long as I can. You can't come
back. It's never the same. That's why I wanted to get it all out of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Moon was on the sideline, watching a 26-year-old
``nobody'' named Jon Kitna lead the Seahawks to a victory over the
Oilers, Moon's old team.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday, Moon again will be on the sideline, watching Kitna
get his third NFL start when the Hawks visit the Meadowlands for a
date with the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Moon appeared on ESPN's ``Up Close'' and was completely
surprised when the host asked how Moon felt about being benched for
the rest of the season in favor of Kitna. Turned out to be an
erroneous report, which Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson and Moon
clarified Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the starter until he wants to start me,'' Moon said.
``I'm fine with that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the point is, with Kitna getting the call to be the
``spark'' for this moribund offense ranked 25th in the league, the
door has been opened on the inevitable discussion about Moon's
future, or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   With four games left in a Seahawk season that very likely will
end without a playoff berth, and with Moon likely to be on the
sideline the rest of the way _ why would he start once the Hawks
are mathematically eliminated? _ the Moon story in Seattle is in
all likelihood being concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because Moon's salary and bonuses would count $5 million
against next year's cap _ a huge number that will make it all but
necessary for the Hawks to cut him. Also, Moon has said will not
play another season unless he is the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing well up until the game in Kansas City (where he
suffered broken ribs). I had the most touchdown passes. I had only
one interception,'' Moon said.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, though, with his sore ribs keeping him out of
practice and barely able to tolerate cortisone shots, Moon's clout
did not serve him or the team well. Moon was able to talk Erickson
into letting him start against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The result was terrible. Moon played three painful quarters. The
Hawks lost, falling to 3-3, squandering their 3-0 start and all but
demonstrating that this playoff hopeful team had taken a step
backward from 1997, when Moon set club passing records and won the
Pro Bowl MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Moon, ever the diplomat, has accepted responsibility for the
offense's struggles this season, but he is hardly the sole culprit.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant factor was Erickson's decision to play
smash-mouth offense with the addition of running back Ricky
Watters. Next, when the offense did look to pass, there was special
emphasis on getting the ball to Joey Galloway _ a good idea, except
that the new formations made it tough for other receivers like Mike
Pritchard and James McKnight to get into a flow.
</P>
<P>
   These things all amounted to Moon struggling to find his own
rhythm. Finally, right before the loss to Dallas two weeks ago,
Moon said Erickson came to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said we've got to get back to spinning it,'' Moon said.
``That's what Dennis calls it. So he wanted to open up the passing
game. I agreed. I mean, if we're going to go down, we should do
what we do best.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with a game plan better suited to Moon's passing, he
could not make plays. The Cowboys pummeled the pocket-rooted Moon,
who went 15-for-28 for 201 yards with an interception.
</P>
<P>
   If that was Moon's final start as a Seahawk, surely he can look
and see an offensive line that did not help him by committing so
many penalties. He can look at a coaching staff that took too long
to get back to what the Seahawks and Moon did so well in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact remains, the Hawks need something now that Moon
could not give them. Even Moon does not dispute this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so sure that if I was the coach, I wouldn't do exactly
the same thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the cool head of one of the NFL's most veteran veterans.
He is not happy about his backup status. But Moon is picking his
head up now. The horizon is wide open, including an alluring dream
of being part of an NFL ownership group for putting a team back in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Time has a funny way of passing you by, even when your mind and
body tell you you're still No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 0119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
