<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0372 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     12-03 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ College basketball at this point in the season can be a
lot like listening to the orchestra tune up before the concert _
plenty of off-key notes that don't mean anything.
</P>
<P>
   If this were the 100 meters for the Olympic gold medal, the
sprinters would barely have begun to stretch. If it were the opera,
the fat lady would still be gargling. If a political campaign, the
candidates wouldn't even have thought up the first lies.
</P>
<P>
   In two nights of the Great Eight spilling across the floor at
the United Center, the artwork looked hardly of museum quality.
</P>
<P>
   It took three games for a team to finally crack 50-percent
shooting. It took a second night to eventually get an upset when
unranked Rhode Island picked off Utah 70-63. It took the back end
of a pair of marquee doubleheaders to at last get a sparkling duel
of individual stars in Rams freshman Lamar Odom and Utes senior
Andre Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the history of this event says it is not only a
made-for-prime-time dress rehearsal but a barometer of things to
come. Consider that a year ago Utah, Kentucky and North Carolina
won three of the four games in the Great Eight and went on to make
up three-quarters of the Final Four in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're looking for early favorites to plug into your
brackets in March, try UConn, Kentucky, Duke and upstart Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
   What did we learn?
</P>
<P>
   That while UConn may be ranked No. 1 in the polls, Duke is back
and may be once again the team to beat. Despite a second-half run
by Michigan State that held their winning margin down to 73-67, the
Blue Devils have it all in the speed, agility and strength inside
of Elton Brand, the long-range sniping of Trajan Langdon, the
quarterbacking of William Avery and the rest of a roster that's
deeper than an advanced philosophy class.
</P>
<P>
   That while the hype machine that is labeling the 6-10 Odom
another Magic Johnson is unfair and oh-so-premature, this is a
unique talent. On one trip down the floor, he grabs a long
offensive rebound, does a 360-spin and stabs a 3-pointer right in
the face of a defender. On another, he weaves through traffic down
the lane and slides a nice no-look pass for a layup. And he follows
Utah's fleet Miller all the way down the floor on a fast break,
then erases a layup with a monster blocked shot that had the dozens
of NBA scouts who were present drooling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great opportunity for me and my team,'' Odom said.
``I always tell them, `When the scouts come to see me, they see
you, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gee, maybe someday he'll let them ride in his limousine with
him.
</P>
<P>
   We learned that with seniors Wayne Turner and Scott Padgett to
lead his bunch, Kentucky coach Tubby Smith has enough talent on
hand to make a run at another title.
</P>
<P>
   We learned that while UConn has a couple of great talents in
reed-thin Richard Hamilton and stevedore look-alike Khalid El-Amin,
the Huskies will live up to the early high rating only if the likes
of junior center Jake Voskuhl from Katy and Strake Jesuit High
gives them solid play up front as well.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches have similar views about this kind of December
encounter with other giants. After working out some of the kinks in
assorted exotic ports of call from Hawaii to Puerto Rico to Alaska,
this is an opportunity to get back to the basics in a
meat-and-potatoes town and make a few determinations about their
teams that will pay off in the only season that really counts:
March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``In (college) football, you lose a game early in a big matchup
against another power, and you might take yourself out of the
running for a championship,'' said Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski.
``But to me, in basketball, if you play in these situations, it can
actually enhance your chances of doing well in the postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   The rankings at this time of the year have all the impact of a
ceiling fan turning in a hurricane. It hardly matters who is No. 1
in the first week of December. Unless, of course, it happens to be
you, and, as with the Huskies from UConn, it is only the second
time that has happened in the history of your school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like an NCAA Tournament atmosphere,'' said Huskies
coach Jim Calhoun. ``It's very comparable as far as the matchups
and the site. It gives you a chance to evaluate what your kids are
going to be like when the heat is on.''
</P>
<P>
   We heard about turnovers attributed to slippery basketballs and
saw so many shots clank off rims that were called too tight. We saw
that it was only December in the long race to March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   But never too early to start filling in your bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Fran Blinebury on the Sports Page radio show on KPRC
(950 AM) from 5-7 p.m. weekdays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
