<HEADLINE>
TV REPORTER GETS AN EARFUL FROM JOHNSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There were the dozen or so television vehicles, even a
Hummer stretch limo that cost a local radio station big bucks to
rent. It was The Event of the off-season. The Big Unit speaks.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 media members crowded into a room at Bank One
Ballpark on Wednesday for Randy Johnson's first Phoenix press
conference, and the frenzy surrounding it rivaled the day Charles
Barkley joined the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody was there.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost everybody. One person, you see, had the opportunity
to meet Johnson at his Paradise Valley home on Tuesday. Gil Tyree
of Channel 3 (KTVK), who showed up uninvited in the gated
community, reportedly was met with a stream of harsh words from
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things that are do's and don'ts,'' Johnson
said. ``Coming to my home is a don't. It's the only place I have to
unwind, to have solitude. I don't feel my home is the place to do
an interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that one of his daughters was sick Tuesday and that
she was taken to the hospital shortly after Tyree left.
</P>
<P>
   Tyree said he was told by the assignment editor and his
immediate supervisor to go to Johnson's house for an interview. ``I
was in a very difficult situation,'' Tyree said. ``I was told to
get the story. What could I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he would make himself available to the media every
day of the season _ when he wasn't pitching. That's when he turns
into a bear.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also tried to push across the idea that money, more than
$52 million, was not an issue, saying he could have gotten more in
Los Angeles or New York. That went over big with a crowd that was
scrambling for the last of the free softs drinks and popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Johnson did a much better job handling the media than
his agents. One of them even told the gathering what questions
should be avoided. ``Hold off asking the tough questions for
another day.''
</P>
<P>
   His plea went unheeded, and he visually showed displeasure when
unpleasant questions were asked. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
