<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-JOHNSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SWEET PEA' HAPPY TO BE HOME  
 DIAMONDBACKS WERE PICK IN '96 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - As early as February 1996, Randy Johnson said he had
an interest in pitching for Arizona's new major league team.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander had just purchased a home in the Valley and had
reported to spring training in Peoria with the Seattle Mariners
when he told ``The'' ``Republic,'' ``I've got two years left here
(with the Mariners) and then I'll be down, playing with the
Diamondbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he was a year off _ the Mariners exercised a team option
for 1998 and later traded him to Houston _ Johnson fulfilled his
own prophecy Wednesday when he officially joined the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wore a charcoal pinstriped suit as he arrived for a news
conference in a party suite overlooking right field at Bank One
Ballpark. Before he sat down at a table filled with a row of
microphones, he walked over to his mother, Carol, who came from
northern California for the special occasion, and smothered her
with a long-armed embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Sweet Pea,'' she cooed, kissing him on the cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Pea? That's a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been called many things on the field and in the
clubhouse, probably a few unprintables, but never that.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time for the man who throws peas to help transform the
team from a National League side dish into the main course.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson talked about the importance of chemistry in the
clubhouse. In Seattle, he interacted at times, particularly with
outfielder Jay Buhner, but at other times maintained his distance.
In Houston, the pattern was similar, although some of it was
attributable to unfamiliarity with his teammates. Johnson did
develop a kinship with reliever Billy Wagner, who like him is
left-handed and has above-average velocity.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson hardly saw his wife and three children during his six
weeks in Houston, but he said he was welcomed by the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were extremely friendly,'' he said. ``They offered me a
car, help with whatever was needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar wheels will carry Johnson to Tucson for spring training
beginning Feb. 18. That's when he said the chemistry will begin,
but it already has begun in many respects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to (pitcher) Andy Benes the other day, and he
was talking about the young rotation,'' Johnson said. ``It didn't
offer him many opportunities to talk shop, and now he has that with
me and Todd (Stottlemyre). We're bookends.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson hopes to co-author an early chapter with Kelly Stinnett,
who likely will be his primary catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to give Kelly a call, wherever he is (Oklahoma).
Maybe he can hop on a plane and come here so we can get in some
early work,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't take long, Johnson said, for a good working
relationship to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining in the NL likely will have Johnson shaking his head in
frustration for a while as he attempts to get a grip on hitting. He
has five career hits in 55 at-bats, 32 of those coming after his
July 31 trade to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've gotta hit now,'' he said with a sigh. ``When I was
in Houston, people said it was kind of comical, that the bat looked
like a toothpick in my hands. But I'm taking a great deal of pride
in hitting. And I know that I'll have to make contact with the
bunting. I'm going to go into the cage, do whatever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson certainly is not lacking confidence, and can rattle off
many of his career statistics. But he is quick to point out that he
is not perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't walk on water,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
