<SLUG> BC-BKC-EIGHT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON NEEDN'T FRET; LOSS TO UCONN WON'T MEAN MUCH IN MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The University of Washington basketball team arrived
Monday in the city of big shoulders, fresh off the program's first
victory in an eight-team tournament in 23 years. So even was the
Huskies' performance in the Big Island Invitational, they gave off
the sense they might have graduated to an elite dozen or so in
college hoops.
</P>
<P>
   They left here Wednesday, taking their act to a different time
zone again, repeating the kinds of things they said late last
February in a season-turning loss at California. Rather than the
top dozen, their last 15 minutes of a 69-48 defeat to Connecticut
only certified them for maybe the top gross in the college game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were awful,'' said a bulky fellow with a scruffy beard in
a nondescript brown sweater, idly watching the second night of the
Great Eight doubleheader. He was George Karl, the ex-Sonics coach
now with Milwaukee, as always more straightforward than diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't get killed by the pressure, but I thought it wore
at them at both ends. It affects shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   It was cause for celebration when the Huskies were named to the
Great Eight last spring, a fill-in for Stanford from the 1998 NCAA
final eight. UW coach Bob Bender wasn't inclined to stray from that
opinion despite the 21-point loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, and certainly everybody in our locker room
is disappointed,'' Bender said. ``But I believe this whole
experience will make us a better basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to know what to make of the UW's wide loss. But
the inclination is to guess it may be sound and fury signifying
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In big-time college football, scheduling is done with the same
care as diamond-cutting, lest it imperil a conference or national
championship. That doesn't happen in college basketball, which
sorts out the chaff with a postseason tournament. The top-shelf
programs are willing to risk losing early, knowing it has next to
nothing to do with the real season in March.
</P>
<P>
   With the proliferation of quality early tournaments and the
influence of TV, the matchups are prodigious but the meaning is
minimal. When the NCAA basketball committee selects teams for the
tournament, it tends to treat early-season results with a
collective shrug. Duke and Stanford, the 1-2 teams in the coaches'
preseason poll, already have lost.
</P>
<P>
   Although the talent was monstrous here _ Lamar Odom, Richard
Hamilton, Andre Miller, Elton Brand and Todd MacCulloch were
eyeballed closely by a passel of NBA scouts _ the atmosphere at the
United Center was befitting the impact of the games. They were like
scrimmages, albeit high-level ones.
</P>
<P>
   Too, the season is beginning earlier than ever _ Nov. 7, the
better to squeeze in attractive matchups for TV _ which makes for
less practice and more unpredictability. Earlier this decade, NCAA
rules prohibited first games before Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' snorted Dick ``Hoops'' Weiss, longtime
observer of the game for the New York Daily News. ``First-semester
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider: When Washington faced Connecticut last March in the
NCAA tournament, the UW hadn't played in the previous four days.
Washington prepared for this meeting with UConn with three games in
the previous four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Washington) looked tired,'' said Danny Ainge, the Phoenix
Suns coach. ``But they played hard.''
</P>
<P>
   As bad as the Huskies looked in the final 15 minutes, finishing
with their lowest point total since 1994, they can take some good
things away. For the second straight time, Connecticut had more
turnovers, often the virus with which UConn shatters opponents.
Still, a few of those by Washington resulted in immediate
Connecticut baskets.
</P>
<P>
   It may develop that Washington misses Patrick Femerling, the 7-1
forward who left a year early to sign a pro contract in Germany.
The Huskies never found a way to use him in effective offensive
tandem with MacCulloch, but his size and athletic ability
discouraged opponents defensively and protected MacCulloch.
</P>
<P>
   Bender is preaching toughness as the Huskies prepare for two
more games on the road, at Boise State Saturday and Gonzaga
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At least he's got games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going nuts,'' said Karl, looking bored. He'd kill for a
game, even one of these college shakedowns in early December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
