<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS HAVEN'T FORGOTTEN '97 DEBACLE AGAINST JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Chad Brown's first game as a Seahawk made a
lasting impression.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps depression is a better description of the
season-opening, 4-1 loss to the New York Jets last year at the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was embarrassing. They did stuff at will,'' Brown said
Wednesday, when the Seahawks began preparing for Sunday's rematch
with the Jets at the Meadowlands. ``They got us off balance and
knocked us over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was ugly, especially because of all the expectations the
Seahawks carried into that game after the free-agent signings of
Brown, a Pro Bowl linebacker; quarterback Warren Moon, cornerback
Willie Williams, defensive tackle Dan Saleaumua and strong safety
Bennie Blades; and the additions of cornerback Shawn Springs and
tackle Walter Jones in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   These Jets, 8-4 and tied for first in the AFC East, are better
than those Jets, who finished 9-7 and out of the playoffs in their
first season under coach Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' have scored more points (315) than every team in the
AFC except the unbeaten Denver Broncos. Vinny Testaverde is the
conference's top-rated passer (104.0). Running back Curtis Martin
last week became only the sixth player in NFL history to rush for
1,000 yards in each of his first four seasons. The mismatched duo
of Keyshawn Johnson (56 for 832, eight TDs) and Wayne Chrebet (56
for 830, six TDs) have put up almost identical receiving numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' defense ranks fourth in the league and has held five
of its last six opponents to fewer than 225 yards in total offense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Seahawk personnel harbor we-owe-'em-one feelings.
But defensive end Michael Sinclair said there already is enough
riding on this game to provide ample motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to think about the Jets beating us last year. We
know what happened,'' Sinclair said. ``But this is an important
game. We're playing on one of the largest stages in the world. We
know their fans will be rowdy. They're one of the hottest teams in
the NFL right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm already motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown agrees. ``This is a completely different year. A different
team. A different time of year. We're fighting for a playoff spot.
So I'm not going to go back and look at that (game video). I don't
need additional motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dennis Erickson is one who can't get the taste of last
year's slap in the face out of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the video on, vomited halfway through it and threw it
away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was kidding. Wasn't he?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always remember that,'' Erickson said. ``To get
embarrassed and humiliated. I wasn't proud of how we played. I
don't think anybody who played was very proud of how we played in
that game. Again, I'll remember that for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 0124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
