A0383 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     12-03 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EXCUSES BUT SAME OLD RESULT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Kings coach Larry Robinson tried something new
Wednesday night, praising his team rather than burying it, and
excusing its latest loss as the result of a hot arena, a grueling
travel schedule and bad bounces.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line was the same as in nine of the last 10
games. This time, it was a 3-1 setback to the Toronto Maple Leafs
in the second leg of a three-game trip that ends tonight in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto (14-9-2) got two goals by Sergei Berezin, three assists
by Mats Sundin, all its scoring on the power play and 27 saves by
Curtis Joseph in notching its seventh consecutive home victory
before a sellout crowd of 15,726 at Maple Leaf Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (6-15-3) got a shorthanded tying goal by Vladimir
Tsyplakov eight minutes into the third period, then tossed the game
right back to the Leafs by taking two penalties and allowing goals
to Berezin and Dimitri Yushkevich in the next five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a fragile team like ours, we have negative stuff going
through our heads,'' defenseman Doug Bodger said. ``The guys didn't
give up, but we're getting into a deep hole. It's tough to get out
of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' performance was better than the one they gave in a
loss by an identical score two nights earlier in Montreal. They
made fewer defensive mistakes, gambled less on offense and had a
number of decent scoring chances. Still, though Robinson had
implored his players to create traffic in front of the opposing
net, there was not nearly enough of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys did a great job letting me see the puck and that's
key,'' Joseph said tellingly.
</P>
<P>
   And on one occasion when a King went to the net, it cost them,
with an apparent first-period go-ahead goal by Craig Johnson
nullified because Josh Green was in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings stayed composed, but were undone by needless
penalties, Toronto scoring in the second period with Mark Visheau
in the box, and in the third with Glen Murray and Ray Ferraro
serving penalties.
</P>
<P>
   During another Visheau penalty, Tsyplakov recorded the Kings'
ninth shorthanded goal of the season, a double-edged statistic
because it is the same number of goals the Kings have scored on the
power play. The Kings were 0 for 4 against Toronto with the man
advantage despite adjustments by Robinson. The penalty killing,
meanwhile, has declined lately, too, after being impenetrable early
in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, asked to rate his team's performance, Robinson said, ``It
was a great effort. Of the goals they scored, one, Berezin was
trying to get out of the way and the puck hits him, the second one
hit (Sean) O'Donnell's stick...that's the way it's going. Two
penalties hurt us and I thought they were a little borderline. We
shoot the puck and it goes off a stick and into the corner. They
shoot the puck and it goes off a stick and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so hot in the building and you could see by the end of
the second period and the third period, guys were starting to slow
down a little bit. (Toronto) hasn't played in four days. It's a
little easier for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson made a curious decision when the Kings had a man
advantage with 2:20 left and his team down two goals, never opting
to pull goalie Jamie Storr to gain a two-man advantage and
afterward acknowledging he was trying to limit the final deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had scored early on the power play, I probably would
have done it,'' Robinson said. ``But when you're down by two, I
think at this point, the guys feel dejected enough. You pull the
goalie there and then they score to make it 4-1, I think it's just
a bigger downer for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 0131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
