<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0388 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-03 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE Yankees are going to make a run at him, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles will be there, too. Cleveland might be in
the hunt, so might Anaheim, and so might the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the well-funded Atlanta Braves? Anything is
possible when it comes to the Braves, although adding Roger Clemens
to a staff that has three Cy Young winners not only would be
unfair, it would be a baseball merger along the lines of Exxon and
Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   But with much more gas.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, the best pitcher in baseball no matter what kind of
Units one uses to measure greatness, officially is on the trade
market today. Late Wednesday, he asked the Toronto Blue Jays for a
trade and the Jays said they would grant it.
</P>
<P>
   It means virtually every team in the majors will give it a shot.
It means everyone will look hard at their lineup and try to find a
deal the Jays cannot refuse.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone will chase the Rocket. Everyone will check budgets and
salary caps. But not everyone is the Astros or Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of Wednesday's news called for Clemens to go only to a
contender, which Toronto also said it will try to accommodate.
Which leads to something altogether tantalizing.
</P>
<P>
   Barely more than a handful of teams in reality are in the hunt.
But only two of those teams woke up today knowing they must have
the early lead in the race for the Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   One of those teams is the Texas Rangers, with all their deep
pockets, deep talent and thin skin, after their scrambling entry
into the 1998 playoffs and quick elimination by the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The other team is the Astros, who are on the verge of either the
World Series or a nervous breakdown, depending on how this Clemens
deal goes.
</P>
<P>
   You thought a homesick Ken Caminiti passing on $21.5 million
from Detroit put a lot of pressure on Drayton McLane Jr. and Gerry
Hunsicker to come through with a deal in the clutch?
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed. But as significant and pressure-packed as
Caminiti's signing had to be for McLane and Hunsicker, it was a
mere candlestick compared to the Clemens inferno raging before them
today.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti was a sweet kind of pressure. Clemens is the kind of
pressure that could leave a sour taste in so many mouths,
especially if it is the Rangers who get him.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Two words: Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   This same Astros organization made countless new hometown
friends in 1979 when it signed Ryan, the free-agent local hero, to
the first $1 million-a-year contract in major-league sports.
</P>
<P>
   It was a move that immediately gave the Astros a heart, changed
the perception and complexion of the club in this city and gave it
a national identity. It also made the Astros a contender for the
National League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Some eight years later, everything changed when Ryan had to pack
and leave for the Metroplex and the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros suddenly became the team that couldn't. Houston was
outdone by its rival from the Metroplex. Disgruntled fans forgot
their way to the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Ryan still was firing rockets, so to speak, just
up the road.
</P>
<P>
   He added no-hitters to his unprecedented list. He broke his own
strikeout record every time he stepped onto the hill. He became an
icon for the rest of the baseball world and a cruel reminder of
what could have been for Astros fans.
</P>
<P>
   And now, here is Clemens. Nolan of the Nineties.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is looking for a way to get to a title contender while
also hoping to get a little closer to home. He'll take New York or
Los Angeles, if that is the deal the Blue Jays ultimately make. But
he wants the Astros or the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   McLane and Hunsicker must be sick over the pressure they now
will be under. That is, when they're not giddy over it. After all,
how many opportunities to legitimately deal for a player of
Clemens' caliber and aura ever come along?
</P>
<P>
   This is a player who not only is a notch above even Randy
Johnson but is a bona fide legend in this town and this state even
before he comes home. Nolan of the Nineties.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Astros surely will be among the teams vigorously
chasing this deal. This is Clemens, possibly coming home and
possibly completing the circle that was broken when the Rangers
swiped Ryan a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, no guarantees the Astros will be able to
find a way to make the deal, much less fit Clemens' salary into
their budget.
</P>
<P>
   So many things must go right if it is going to happen for the
Astros. There would be so many legitimate excuses if it doesn't.
But surely, today McLane and Hunsicker are trying to find a way,
because they know there's only one thing worse than losing this
kind of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   And that's losing it to the Rangers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
