<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0414 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCHOOP-LADN     12-03 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCHOOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARON IS BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA Bruins danced and dunked their way to
victory Wednesday night at Pauley Pavilion, but the loudest ovation
was for a substitution.
</P>
<P>
   With 13:22 remaining in the first half, sophomore guard Baron
Davis checked in for the first time this season _ ending his
eight-month rehabilitation as the Bruins ended their two-game
losing streak, disposing of Delaware State 109-67.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has been practicing for weeks and was cleared to play
Wednesday afternoon by UCLA surgeon Gerald Finerman. He played 16
minutes and will remain on a restricted-minutes program for several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The rehabilitation) is about what I anticipated, but it's not
what Baron anticipated,'' Finerman said. ``My thought was to have
him pretty well back by January. That's seven or eight months (from
the injury). That's the appropriate time table.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd have liked to have played in the first game (Santa Clara)
and in Puerto Rico, but we didn't feel he was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The manner in which Davis' reconstructed left knee responded to
exertion sped his recovery. Once he was cleared to practice _ first
for noncontact work, then full throttle _ there was little if any
swelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very important aspect of his recovery,'' Finerman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The range of motion in Davis' left knee is virtually identical
to that of his right, Finerman said. But there's no way to measure
the strength of the repaired anterior cruciate ligament, which he
tore in the NCAA Tournament's second round against Michigan. He'll
wear a brace during practices and games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be hampered this year by the brace,'' Finerman said.
``We'll have a decision next year about whether to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis entered the game to a standing ovation, received a hug
from guard Earl Watson, then went about his business _ dashing
around the court at high speed, slashing to the basket and finding
open teammates.
</P>
<P>
   His first assist took all of 18 seconds: He hit Rico Hines in
the right corner for a 3-pointer on his first offensive series.
With 11:47 left, he made two free throws for his first points of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Davis moved well but has not regained the quickness and leaping
ability that defined his pre-injury style. More, his conditioning
and timing are months behind, and he played in spurts of three or
four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll play in game conditions for limited periods,'' Finerman
said. ``It's a progression of the intensity he's been working at.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' return overshadowed several noteworthy performances.
Freshman forward Jerome Moiso scored 11 of UCLA's first 16 points
as it charged to an early double-digit lead. Hines, perhaps the
Bruins' most improved shooter, made three 3-pointers in the half as
they extended the lead to 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, UCLA (3-2) played as expected against an overmatched
opponent. (Delaware State lost to New Hampshire and Drake before
Thanksgiving.) The Bruins dominated the rebounding and scored at
will from close range. They substituted freely _ although without
the rapid-fire style of the Puerto Rico Shootout _ and used
pressure defense to force 15 Delaware State turnovers in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Despite UCLA's large early lead, the Hornets did not wilt _ at
least not immediately. The Bruins committed 15 fouls in the first
half, enabling Delaware State to make more free throws (15) than
field goals (nine) and pull within 24-15 with 12 minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hornets would get no closer. Travis Reed's three-point
play pushed UCLA's lead to 12 and began a stretch of 23 points in
10 possessions. JaRon Rush, who did not start, scored from the
lane, then Ray Young tipped in a Davis miss for a 31-15 lead. The
surge ended with Rush's 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: UCLA used its fourth different starting lineup, with
Watson, Moiso, Dan Gadzuric, Matt Barnes and Ryan Bailey. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins play Oklahoma State on Saturday in the Wooden Classic
in Anaheim, then take a week off before facing Nevada-Las Vegas on
Dec. 12 at Pauley Pavilion. . . .
</P>
<P>
   UCLA scored 100 points for the 150th time in school history.
</P>
</TEXT>
