<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROBINSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLV HIRES ROBINSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former USC coach John Robinson has accepted the
head-coaching position at Nevada-Las Vegas and is expected to be
formally introduced as the Rebels' new coach today.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 63, accepted the job less than a year after he was
fired by USC, where he led the Trojans to four Rose Bowl titles and
a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   After interviewing twice with UNLV officials last week, Robinson
delayed taking the job after being approached by another school.
According to sources in Hawaii, Robinson was courted this week by
the University of Hawaii, which fired coach Fred vonAppen last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson decided to stick with UNLV, however, which offered a
multiyear deal believed to be worth at least $400,000 per year,
along with several promises to upgrade the football program.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who flew to Las Vegas on Wednesday, could not be
reached for comment. He has been busy the past few days putting
together a coaching staff, which is full of members from his
previous staffs at USC.
</P>
<P>
   He has asked Notre Dame quarterbacks coach Mike Sanford to be
his assistant head coach, offensive coordinator and quarterbacks
coach. Sanford coached at USC for nine years before leaving for
Notre Dame in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has also offered former USC assistant Jeff McInerney
the defensive coordinator's position. McInerney is the defensive
line coach at Oregon State. Another former USC assistant, Doug
Smith, is expected to become the Rebels' offensive-line coach.
</P>
<P>
   Former USC linebacker Joe Barry, an assistant at Northern
Arizona, has also been offered a position on the staff. A current
UNLV assistant, former USC player and assistant DelVaughn
Alexander, is expected to retain his position.
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation that Robinson might have been
interested in USC offensive coordinator Hue Jackson, but sources
said there is no chance of that happening.
</P>
<P>
   UNLV athletic director Charles Cavagnaro hired Robinson because
he wanted a high-profile coach, and several of the school's
boosters agreed to contribute money to help pay for Robinson's
salary and other improvements in the football program. The Rebels
will join the new Mountain West Conference next season. They plan
to expand their football stadium to 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was fired by USC last December after four seasons in
his second tenure at the university. He was 37-22-2 but just 12-11
the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, he left USC with a 104-35-4 record, four Rose Bowl
titles and the 1978 national championship. Robinson also coached
the Los Angeles Rams for nine seasons (1983-91) and went 79-74.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Robinson won his 100th game at USC last season with
a 35-21 victory over UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   Among those Cavagnaro also considered were Indianapolis Colts
assistant coach Rod Marinelli, a former assistant under Robinson at
USC, Colorado State coach Sonny Lubick and Missouri assistant Ricky
Hunley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
