<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RHODE ISLAND'S ODOM GOOD FOR COLLEGE GAME, EVEN IF FOR ONE YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Coaches want to create on-the-floor mismatches. They
want the opposition to be constantly adjusting. They want players
for whom the other team has no answer.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Odom is the kind of player who makes coaches' daydreams
come true. He is a player who creates problems for the other coach
and solves problems for his.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Rhode Island coach Jim Harrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can play the point,'' Harrick said. ``He can play the wing.
He can play inside, just like we thought. He could play any
position we need him to.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom, by the way, is 6-foot-10. Offensively, he is an all-around
talent. Last night in the Great Eight Basketball Classic, Odom was
the key as the Rams (4-3) beat No. 21 Utah, 70-63.
</P>
<P>
   When Rhode Island, which trailed throughout the first half,
needed a basket, the lefty-shooting Odom scored. When it needed a
pass for a score, Odom made it. For the Rams, he was _ and will be
_ the X factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Lamar gains more experience, we'll run our offense
entirely through him. He handled the ball very well. He had a nice
line,'' said Harrick, reciting Odom's 15 points, six rebounds, six
assists, one turnover and two blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   Ask TCU about his all-around ability. In the Horned Frogs'
season opener Nov. 9, Odom had 19 points, 14 rebounds and nine
assists in the Rams' 87-85 victory. He leads the team in scoring,
rebounding and assists.
</P>
<P>
   When Odom plays well, the Rams win. In the team's first six
games, he shot 67 percent in the team's three victories, 24 percent
in the three losses. ``He's got to perform, or we'll get beat,''
Harrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Odom's journey to Rhode Island is a story that raises eyebrows
and red flags. In high school, the New York native attended three
high schools his junior and senior years. He wanted to attend
Nevada-Las Vegas, but left there after his standardized test score
was questioned.
</P>
<P>
   He wound up at Rhode Island, but spent last season going to
school to prove his academic ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing college ball was something I always wanted to do,''
said Odom, who is listed as a sophomore. ``I'm having a lot of fun
right now. I'm not in a rush. I'm looking forward to playing
another couple of years of college basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Insert your sarcastic ``Yeah, right.'' Questions remain about
Odom's commitment to class. It was probably unintentional, but in
an ESPN feature on Odom, he was shown strolling across campus _ and
nary a book was in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that these Great Eight games are being played in the
United Center, The House That Michael Built, wasn't lost on Odom.
Neither was the fact that a bunch of idled NBA guys _ Tim Floyd,
Wes Unseld, Danny Ainge, Kevin McHale _ were in the house.
</P>
<P>
   And Odom knows that last spring's lure of declaring for the NBA
draft was fool's gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of guys sitting around with nothing to do,''
he said. ``And they're probably watching college basketball games.
I'm playing.''
</P>
<P>
   With the early departures of players such as Antawn Jamison and
Paul Pierce, the college game needs the influx of players like
Odom, even if he's a one-year wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You going to put a small guy on him? He'll post him up,''
Harrick said, barely containing his glee about coaching such a
talent. ``You put a big guy on him, he can go past him. He has some
skills that are beyond a guy his size. It
</P>
<P>
   makes us very versatile and hard to guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way of saying ``mismatch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
