r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEMOCRATS-SFC     12-03 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEMOCRATS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DEMOCRATS SAY SEX LIES DON'T WARRANT IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Congress careens toward a historic vote on
impeachment, Democrats have settled on a three-pronged defense of
their president _ his offense is not so serious; you can't prove he
did it; and the inquiry is grossly unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, the 16 Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee
have returned to these points, whether their witness is independent
counsel Kenneth Starr, who testified two weeks ago, or the former
coach of the University of South Carolina women's basketball team,
who testified Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The defense does not paint a handsome portrait of the 42nd
president of the United States. No one on the House Judiciary
Committee, even President Clinton's staunchest defenders, has
rebutted the specific facts contained in Starr's report, which
chronicled Clinton's sexual relationship with a young White House
intern and his subsequent efforts to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Democratic case resonates with a large segment of the
public, which long ago tired of the scandal. And if the arguments
can be used to persuade even 15 of the House's 228 Republicans to
vote against impeachment, the matter will likely die on the House
floor in the next couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question before us is not whether or not perjury is a
crime or whether it applies to sex or whether it applies in civil
cases,'' said Rep. Robert Scott, D-Va., responding to a litany of
specific issues raised by GOP witnesses during the impeachment
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question before us is whether or not we should vote to
impeach the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer for every Democratic member of the committee _ and
for all but perhaps three of the 206 Democrats in the House _ is
no.
</P>
<P>
   It would take ``a meteor to hit,'' said Rep. Ellen Tauscher,
D-Calif., when asked what it would compel her to change her
position against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Tauscher, one of only 31 Democrats to vote in favor of the
impeachment inquiry this fall, described Clinton's behavior as
``indefensible and inappropriate,'' but said it is unworthy of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have struggled all year with how to condemn Clinton's
actions without handing Republicans a club with which to destroy
their party's leader. The impeachment inquiry has helped Democrats
coalesce around the same message offered by Tauscher _ Clinton's
behavior is wrong but does not warrant his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know that the president's actions are not impeachable
and that these proceedings should end,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y., who has been saying publicly what nearly all Democrats
concede privately.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has repeatedly declared that he believes Clinton lied to
the American people, lied during a civil deposition and lied to a
criminal grand jury
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schumer contends impeachment is too drastic a punishment,
warning that ``we're hurdling headlong into a constitutional crisis
which the American people, in their wisdom, have begged us to rein
in and reject.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic defense rests on the proposition that some lies
are less egregious than others. Former federal Judge A. Leon
Higginbotham Jr., called to testify before the Judiciary Committee
this week by Democrats, argued that ``perjury has gradations,''
noting that nobody would impeach a president for lying about how
fast he was driving if he were disputing a speeding ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, many Democrats have argued that lying about sex under
oath does not warrant a penalty so severe that Congress has imposed
it against one president in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced that the president's answers regarding his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky are great and dangerous
offenses,'' said Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., who accused previous
GOP presidents of engaging in far more serious dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   People ``understand intuitively that the framers of the
Constitution reserved high crimes and misdemeanors for the abuses
practiced by Presidents Reagan and Bush and not for President
Clinton's misleading statements about an embarrassing affair,''
Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of going softer on ``sex lies'' is flatly rejected by
many Republicans, who find it particularly repugnant that the
nation's chief law enforcement officer would seek to deceive the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   They have portrayed their case against Clinton as one of simple
fairness, noting that thousands of other Americans have been
punished for perjury. That is why the GOP brought forth two
witnesses this week who had successfully been prosecuted for lying
under oath about their sex lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're exploring whether there's one rule of law for the
powerful, for the rulers, and another one for the ruled,''
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., snapped at one point after
Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., wondered aloud about the usefulness of
this week's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   As the Judiciary Committee approaches the end of its inquiry _
the committee is expected to finish its work next week _ Democrats
have begun to argue that the GOP has neglected its burden to
corroborate the evidence contained in the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   No one has produced any evidence _ or even offered any
assertions _ to contradict Starr's findings. But Democrats are
aware that to confirm the information _ let along prove the case
beyond a reasonable doubt _ Republicans would need to call
witnesses to discuss highly personal matters, such as the intimate
details of Clinton and Lewinsky's sexual affair.
</P>
<P>
   Without that evidence, Democrats maintain that there is no proof
Clinton lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen no proof that he committed perjury,'' Rep. Jerrold
Nadler, D-N.Y., said at one point Tuesday, prompting an exasperated
Hyde to respond: ``Well, have lunch with Mr. Schumer, maybe he will
inform you.''
</P>
<P>
   As a final piece of their strategy, Democrats are embracing a
message put forth by the White House since the first days of the
scandal _ attack the investigation as unfair, overzealous and a
distraction from important matters.
</P>
<P>
   Every Democrat on the committee has taken a moment to criticize
the process employed by either Starr or the GOP-run impeachment
panel. House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt wrote a letter to
outgoing Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., this week, in which he
expressed his ``deepest concern regarding the management of the
House investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was his turn to question witnesses this week, Rep.
Robert Wexler, D-Fla., demurred, looking into the television
cameras instead and complained: ``I am afraid that this committee
has become the theater of the absurd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
