<HEADER>
A0484 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACESTATION-PROJECT-     12-03 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACESTATION-PROJECT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONAUTS SET TO BEGIN BUILDING HISTORY'S BIGGEST PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    A last-minute halt to the scheduled launch of the Space Shuttle
Endeavor before dawn Thursday posptoned the start of construction
in orbit for the long-planned International Space Station.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five American astronauts and a Russian cosmonaut were prepared
as the first crew to begin assembling the most complex, most costly
and arguably the most dangerous single construction project in
history, but Space Agency officials said the launch could come at
any time during the next two days, and even later after if need be
after a two-day stand-down.
</P>
<P>
   The multibillion-dollar project _ which is dominated by American
initiatives but includes 15 other nations _ will require 45 space
missions over the next five years to assemble the huge structure as
it orbits nearly 250 miles above Earth.
</P>
<P>
   To NASA chief Daniel Goldin, the station is ``an unprecedented
undertaking in scientific, technological and international
experimentation.''
</P>
<P>
   But many researchers fear that the station's rapidly mounting
costs may threaten budgets for future robotic exploration of the
solar system, its asteroids and the distant birthplace of comets _
ventures like the hugely successful Pathfinder mission to Mars and
the Galileo exploration of Jupiter and its moons.
</P>
<P>
   Those probes were tiny craft, but when completed in 2004, the
740-ton International Space Station will stretch longer than a
football field; deploy a half-acre span of solar power panels;
carry eight miles of electric wiring and 52 computers; and link six
laboratories to living quarters for seven scientists and engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the enterprise is to conduct at least a decade of
unique scientific research that is possible only in the weightless
environment of space. The hope is that such research will yield
everything from basic insights into the formation of the universe
to practical advances in human health and industrial materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a world community living and working together in
space, improving life on Earth and expanding humanity's horizons
for the 21st century,'' said Goldin.
</P>
<P>
   The main mission for the crew of the shuttle Endeavour after it
is launched is to link the first two modules of the space station
together _ the historic start of the venture.
</P>
<P>
   One module is the 20-ton Russian unmanned unit dubbed Zarya, or
Sunrise, which is already in orbit waiting to provide propulsion,
power and communications for construction crews during the early
stages of assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour is to haul up the first American module, named Unity,
which will be mated in space with Zarya by two of the astronauts,
working six hours at a stretch, outside the shuttle. It will take
them three successive spacewalks while tethered for safety to the
shuttle to do the job. &QL; 
 &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  A large-scale space station was first proposed by President
Ronald Reagan in 1984, and the European Space Agency signed on two
years later. At that time, the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration budgeted $8.5 billion for its share of the project.
Russia joined in the project when the Cold War ended.
</P>
<P>
   Under President Clinton, the U.S. share rose to $17.4 billion,
and NASA's most recent estimate says the price could reach $24.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only the beginning, for although the other 15 nations
are supposed to contribute up to $15 billion more, the Russian
space agency is virtually bankrupt and their program is in
disarray. Russian Proton rockets and Soyuz spacecraft, however, are
vital to the enterprise, and America may well have to pick up much
of the original Russian contribution, estimated at about $8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   So construction and hardware alone will cost at least $40
billion between now and 2004, and with five years of shuttle
missions budgeted at $3 billion a year, the final space station
cost could well exceed $100 billion during its planned 10-year
operational lifetime. &QL; 
 &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  The station's science and engineering missions are by no means
settled yet, but their extraordinarily ambitious and varied
experiments seem to promise something for almost everyone in
science _ at least as NASA officials describe them.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments in the ``microgravity'' laboratories, for example,
could yield such results as ``better electronic devices, improved
telecommunications, and stronger, more durable artificial limbs,''
NASA says.
</P>
<P>
   Physicists and chemists aboard the station will study how to
attack earthly pollution and global warming, while other
experiments will be designed to improve the accuracy of
``noninvasive medical diagnostics,'' according to NASA mission
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term studies are expected to add greatly to knowledge about
the effects of weightlessness on the human body gained during past
shuttle flights and long-term stays by Russians and Americans
aboard Russia's 13-year-old Mir space station. That kind of
information is essential if humans are ever to venture for months,
or even years, to distant planets.
</P>
<P>
   And with an eight-foot centrifuge aboard the American laboratory
module in the International Space Station, scientists will study
the effects of varying artificial gravity on cultured cells and
tissues, plants, insects, rats, mice, fish and on the eggs of birds
and reptiles.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the station is completed in 2004, a team of
Americans and Russians will mount Expedition 1, the first to take
up residence in the station and begin research in space in January
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Later will come other international teams with members from
Belgium, Brazil, Britain, Canada, Denmark, France, Germany, Italy,
Japan, the Netherlands, Norway, Spain, Sweden and Switzerland. Many
of the nations will be sending researchers qualified as astronauts,
while others will work only on the ground, using data gathered by
their equipment aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Although Goldin sees this international aspect as the opening of
a truly global commitment to research in space, others outside NASA
view it more as political.
</P>
<P>
   Says John Pike, director of the Space Policy Project of the
American Federation of Scientists: ``The space station is obviously
important, and we've never done anything like this before. But it's
not really a science project, and in no way are we doing it for its
scientific value.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a political project, a foreign policy project, a national
security project _ and a national prestige project, too.'' &QL; 
 &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Then there is the safety issue. All space flight is dangerous,
of course, and the death of seven astronauts when the Challenger
exploded minutes after launch on January 28, 1986, is testimony to
the dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 45 flights needed to carry people plus nearly a
million pounds of hardware to the space station during
construction, 34 will be American and 11 will be Russian. Each
launch has its dangers, but beyond that lie the perils of outer
space _ from tiny micrometeoroids no larger than marbles bombarding
and perhaps puncturing vital space station components to
unanticipated explosive malfunctions of the station's complex
equipment and life-support systems.
</P>
<P>
   Studies at NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston assume there
will be some damage from collisions with orbiting space debris or
meteors, while other studies by federal agencies calculate that
there is at least a 40 percent chance of fatal accidents during the
construction period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space flight is always dangerous,'' says John Pike. ``Even
building a skyscraper or a bridge on Earth takes lives, so you have
to assume that constructing this enormous project in space will be
even more dangerous. It's very likely that some life will be
lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
