<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDS03-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWANN ROLLS DICE  
 SURGICAL PROCEDURE COULD EXTEND CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The surgical procedure that Cardinals defensive
tackle Eric Swann is scheduled to undergo Monday in Vail, Colo., is
far more than just another arthroscopic ``flush'' of his arthritic
right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. J. Richard Steadman, who will perform the surgery, is one of
the pioneers of a relatively new and revolutionary procedure called
``microfracture,'' which could potentially prolong the career of a
player with Swann's problem for years.
</P>
<P>
   Swann's agent, Steve Zucker, confirmed Wednesday that Swann will
undergo a full microfracture procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the procedure stimulates the patient's healing
systems to create new cartilage-like tissue to replace defective or
missing cartilage. Cartilage is the body's padding between bone
surfaces, and Swann has been playing, literally, with bone in
contact with bone.
</P>
<P>
   It's not uncommon in professional athletes, but it is for a
player as young as Swann, 28. Already, Swann has undergone surgery
six times on his knees, twice on the left and four on the right,
including a arthroscopic flush that was performed Oct. 28 because
of continued pain and swelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could go ahead and try to play the rest of the season on
it, but Dr. Steadman told him the knee is weaker now than it was
before the last procedure,'' Zucker said. ``He told Eric that his
career might be in danger if he doesn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric is getting bashed in Phoenix, but when it's all over
with, this may allow him to go and play eight more years for the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric . . . wants to be out there playing with those guys.
They're in the playoff race, and he wants to be part of this. But
Dr. Steadman didn't give him much of a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Russell Chick, the Cardinals orthopedic surgeon, would not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Since Swann made the decision to undergo another surgery, he has
been widely criticized, and his toughness has been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the procedure he will undergo is not easy. It requires
extensive _ and painful _ rehabilitation, including what is known
as Continuous Passive Motion, in which the patient's leg is moved
constantly by a machine for up to eight hours a day for several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It also requires that the patient remain on crutches for six to
eight weeks. Total rehabilitation takes six to seven months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric is really going to have to work hard at this,'' Zucker
said. ``They've told him there is a 70 percent chance for
improvement and a 30 percent chance that he'll end up the same as
when he started. The rehabilitation is the key, and he'll be
staying up there in Colorado for it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the procedure offers a lot of promise for an athlete
such as Swann, who has severe, localized arthritis in his knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two or three procedures employed for localized
arthritic defects,'' said Dr. Richard Emerson, the Suns orthopedic
surgeon who has performed the microfracture procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson emphasized that he is not familiar with Swann's
particular case and could only comment in general about treatment
options.
</P>
<P>
   ``One option is a cartilage transfer,'' Emerson said.
``Cartilage from a safe zone in the knee is transferred to the area
with the defect. It's like lawn plugs in your yard. The intention
is to cover the defect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second is a microfracture technique. Dr. Steadman is one
of the people who developed that technique.''
</P>
<P>
   The cartilage transfer and the microfracture procedures can be
done in unison, further improving the patient's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The third technique, Emerson said, is one developed in Sweden
that entails taking a biopsy of cartilage tissue and making a
culture from which new tissue is grown. It then is re-implanted in
the defective area of the knee. It is a more expensive procedure
and requires more time because it takes about three weeks to grow
the tissue.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Steadman said he will not be available for
comment until next week. But according to literature provided by
the Steadman-Hawkins Clinic, in the microfracture procedure small
holes, or ``microfractures,'' are drilled into the bone near the
defective cartilage. This releases bone marrow cells and ``growth
factors'' into the defect.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to stimulate the body's healing systems to form new
cartilage-like tissue.
</P>
<P>
   The joint first is cleared of any damaged tissue. In Swann's
case, there shouldn't be much because he just underwent the
cleaning Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   After the holes are drilled, allowing the rich growth material
into the defective area, a replacement surface of cartilage-like
cushion between bare bone surfaces is formed in the knee.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steadman's literature, he has performed the
procedure on more than 300 patients ranging in age from 13 to 69
over the past five years, and preliminary results show that many
patients experience improved function and decreased pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Eric talked with Dr. Steadman, he was both sad and
happy,'' Zucker said. ``He's sad that his season is over, but he's
happy that at least he knows it's going to be fixed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
