<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-FINLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS, FINLEY NEAR DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Randy Johnson and his family had no sooner pulled away
from Bank One Ballpark on Wednesday afternoon when managing general
partner Jerry Colangelo was back on the phone working yet another
blockbuster deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks appeared to be on the verge of landing center
fielder Steve Finley late Wednesday night after Colangelo basically
blew any other offer the one-time All-Star had away with his own
four-year $20 million proposal, several major league sources
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Finley had his representative, Tommy Tanzer, attempt to work out
an 11th hour deal that would have kept Finley in San Diego, where
he has played the past four seasons. The Padres, however, were
unwilling to budge off their three-year offer that would have paid
Finley $12 million. Finley and the Padres said their goodbyes late
in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very close to being an ex-Padre,'' Finley told the ``San
Diego'' ``Union-Tribune.'' ``We're as close to having a deal done
as you can be and not have a signed contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Diamondbacks General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr.
were unsuccessful. Colangelo, who was en route to New York City for
another round of NBA bargaining sessions, also was unavailable.
With Garagiola, who will attend an owners meeting today in Chicago,
and Colangelo both out of town, the deal might not be final until
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, or Diamondbucks as they're being called in
some baseball circles, decided to go after Finley, who has averaged
151 games over the past four seasons, to shore up their outfield,
which is generally considered their weak link.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal becomes official, the Diamondbacks will have signed
six free agents in the past three weeks, having guaranteed $116.9
million for the services of Johnson ($52.4 million), Todd
Stottlemyre ($32 million), Greg Swindell ($5.7 million), Armando
Reynoso ($5 million), Greg Colbrunn ($1.8 million) and Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Colangelo insisted the Diamondbacks were through pursuing
big-ticket free agents once they landed Johnson three days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who turns 34 next March, has seen his batting average
and, more important, his on-base percentage slide in the wrong
direction in each of the past two seasons. After batting .298 with
with 30 home runs and 95 RBIs in 1996 and finishing 10th in the
Most Valuable Player balloting, Finley saw his average slip to .261
the next year and .249 this year.
</P>
<P>
   More startling, Finley's on-base percentages of .313 and .301
the past two seasons ranked last among the Padres eight regulars
each season. But Finley, who was hampered by a bunion that required
surgery leaving him on crutches most of last winter, recently
admitted he may have gotten too carried away with his phenomenal
1996 season and attempted to become more of a home run hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to force the issue, and my body wouldn't respond,''
Finley told the ``San Diego Union-Tribune'' two weeks ago. ``Last
year my swing got a little long because I was trying to force
things that were not there. It was more of a pride thing. I let my
pride get in the way. That is one thing we've always talked about
in our clubhouse: Check your pride at the door. That's one thing I
failed to do, as far as my hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's primary attribute, one which won him consecutive Gold
Gloves in 1995 and '96, is his ability to track down fly balls as
well as anyone in the game. With Bank One Ballpark's expansive and
quirky center field, this was definitely a concern for the
ballclub.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 0931EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
