<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0679 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-AFFAIR-1000&AMP;A     12-03 1959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-AFFAIR-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRANSATLANTIC LOVE AFFAIR
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Letters to Nelson Algren
</P>
<P>
   By Simone de Beauvoir.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 559 pp. New York: The New Press. $27.50.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; HOT AND EPISTOLARY &QL; 
 &UR; By MIM UDOVITCH &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In April 1947, Jean-Paul Sartre changed his plans, and as a
result Simone de Beauvoir extended her stay in America, where she
had recently completed a lecture tour, long enough to begin the
affair with Nelson Algren chronicled in the letters to him
collected in ``A Transatlantic Love Affair.'' The Algren-Beauvoir
relationship, which lasted in one form or another for almost two
decades, began its long, episodic disintegration a little more than
a year after it began. Misled, perhaps, by her habit of addressing
him as ``beloved husband'' and describing herself as ``your loving
wife'' (and on one occasion, ``your naked moaning wife''), Algren
asked Beauvoir to marry him. And while it is only fair to note that
he was no more willing to move to France, or even to learn French,
than she was to move to Chicago, it is also clear that although in
the end she was technically the rejectee, she wanted only courtship
where he wanted marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Beauvoir's behavior, and her explanation for her
refusal of Algren's proposals, mimics (and makes as little logical
sense as) a married man's excuses to his mistress: Darling, I love
you more than anything, but my previous commitments make it
impossible for us to be together; nevertheless, you are the most
important thing in my life (except Sartre). After Beauvoir had
spent a year writing things like ``When I think of seeing you, of
feeling you, I become all dizzy in my head. . . . My throat becomes
so tight, and my mouth dry. It will come true, in less than a month
it will come true,'' she again changed her plans at the last minute
because Sartre changed his, reducing her time with Algren from
three months to two. (``I've often wondered what part his sudden
disappointment actually played in our affair,'' she writes,
cluelessly, in her roman a clef, ``The Mandarins.'')
</P>
<P>
   Beauvoir's relationship with Algren could be said to have
existed at some point midway between being and nothingness: in
touch from 1947 to 1964, they spent less than a year and a half in
each other's physical presence, mostly in holiday pursuits, with
much of that time, according to Beauvoir's other autobiographical
writings, filled with anxiety, frustration and petty
dissatisfaction. ``I wandered through the crowd of strangers
gulping down one drink after another,'' she writes in ``After the
War: Force of Circumstance,'' the first volume of her third memoir,
of one trip to Chicago. ``I literally didn't know what to do with
myself.'' In her letters to Algren, in a medium that is by
definition controlled by the mediator, she creates the epistolary
equivalent of a bodice-ripper: She is a protofeminist,
existentialist Frenchwoman trapped in a masochistic, asexual
relationship with a four-foot-ten, walleyed, amphetamine-addicted
genius. He is a lyrical, wry, urban-realist writer from Chicago, an
advocate for the downtrodden and a former member of the Communist
Party. Despite his underrecognized greater gift as a novelist and
eventual neurotic, alcoholic decline, and her superior, not to say
groundbreaking, contribution to the world of 20th-century arts and
letters, together they share an ardent anti-Gaullist love.
</P>
<P>
   Simone de Beauvoir may have loved Algren more than anyone
(except Sartre), but, as she would have been the first to tell you,
she was also better than practically anyone (except Sartre). ``I do
not respect many people,'' she says. In the course of these
letters, she also remarks that she does not care very much for her
woman friends; her sister; her sister's paintings; Sartre's mother
and her own mother; and, among many other things, the French
occupation of Algeria. She does not care for John F. Kennedy (``I
hate this grinning boy and his grinning wife''). She finds it too
tedious when newspaper people show up at train stations when she
and Sartre are traveling, boring her with their stupid questions
about existentialism. Following one dinner with the novelist
Violette Leduc, whom she invariably refers to as an ``ugly woman,''
she writes: ``She gave me the manuscript of a book she is writing
and it is a diary in which she tells everything about her love for
me. It is a wonderful book.''
</P>
<P>
   To reduce Beauvoir to her personal-ad components, she likes
Giacometti, Charlie Chaplin, the picturesque poor, travel,
landscapes, Scotch and not much else (except Sartre). In general,
there is little in her correspondence with Algren to contradict the
impression made by earlier diaries and letters that she is a very,
very smart woman but also a more unpleasant person than practically
anyone (again, need I add, except Sartre). What little there is,
however, is very sweet. The relationship was passionate; Sartre was
no good in bed, Beauvoir informs Algren, while he has aroused in
her ``great new sexual longing and happiness.'' This does not say
much for her previous longtime man-on-the-side, the writer Jacques
Bost, or for Arthur Koestler, with whom she had a one-night stand.
``We were attracted by each other but in the same time there were
'political discrepancies,' '' she solemnly tells Algren. ``He
thought I was not anti-Communist enough.'' Nor does it speak well
for the lesbian affairs she conducted while carrying out the
seduction of her young lycee students in order to later pimp them
over to her partner in superiority. Nevertheless, she is, in the
letters, often surprisingly adorable, partly because of the
linguistic limitations imposed by writing in English (``I felt I
could not sleep before telling you I love you so much; it seemed
very urging''). In fact, at times she sounds positively like a
Gabor sister. ``I should like you to put him K.O.,'' she says of
Louis Bromfield, an enemy of existentialism with whom Algren was to
participate in a panel on writing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-AFFAIR-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: on writing.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, there is an unmistakable tone of condescension running
through these letters. Beauvoir's diary of the trip on which she
met Algren, AMERICA DAY BY DAY (forthcoming in translation in
January, University of California, $27.50), extends this attitude
to the entire country; she evidently felt that the United States
was a simple enough proposition to a thinker like herself that she
could see the true meaning of the place from Harlem to Hollywood
just by passing through. Beauvoir arranged to have Algren's writing
published in the journal she edited with Sartre, Les Temps
Modernes, but this comes across more as radical-chic territorial
scent-marking than an act of respect; she rarely makes any comment
on the work except that it is difficult to translate. She
periodically complains that Algren will not learn French, and
therefore cannot read most of her publications, but on some level
she must have known that his role as theoretical boy-toy would have
been compromised if he could. All too often she uses baby talk that
seems to proceed not only from fondness but from the belief that
she is actually addressing a small child: ``When you look at the
landscape . . . you feel on the moon rather than on earth,'' she
writes. ``Would you like to be on the moon with me, darling, or
would you be afraid?'' Her viewing Algren as an object -- and, not
being one to waste material, a subject -- is supported by his not
having been her first choice when Sartre told her to stay in
America so that he could spend more time with his passionate love
of the time, Dolores Vanetti. (What were these people thinking?)
She first called a married man in New York, but he turned her down.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point in terms of literary valuation, this
correspondence does not reflect any respect for Algren's
intellectual opinion. His letters are not included, but Beauvoir's
responses make clear his attempts at literary dialogue and her
dismissals. Yes, she has read Melville, or James or Dreiser. A long
while ago. When she was quite a young girl. ``Thank you for so much
more than a book,'' she writes, ``even by Edith Wharton.'' They
never like the same movies. During the period covered here, the
industrious and prolific Beauvoir wrote ``The Second Sex'' and
``Memoirs of a Dutiful Daughter,'' and he wrote ``The Man With the
Golden Arm,'' which won the National Book Award. But the letters
contain little information on these undertakings beyond that they
were occurring: ``I work hard on the book about women. When it will
be written, darling, men will know everything about women and so
they will not be interested in them anymore. It will do a big
change in the world. But for crocodiles and frogs indeed,'' she
says, using their pet names, ``it will not make any difference at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   The letters are also sometimes unintentionally comical in their
juxtaposition of pillow talk and events, in a way that boiled down
to its essence might produce a postcard reading, ``Beloved, how I
long and long to be in your arms. There was an article about Sartre
in the newspaper today, with pictures. We tried to stop fascism
again, but still no luck. Wish you were here!'' In the preface,
Sylvie Le Bon de Beauvoir, who was Beauvoir's final companion and
adopted daughter, asserts that the letters are unique because the
cultural difference between the correspondents necessitated
explanation. This is true, but it's difficult to see how the record
is aided by an explanation like ``They were tremendously interested
by Sartre's 'Flies'; it was written during German occupation, and
the general meaning was: when you have put yourself in a bad mess,
don't have remorses about it, but try to act and make things
better.'' We also learn that one night everybody got drunk and
Koestler punched Camus.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Beauvoir expresses what Colette and Proust have
taught me to believe is a classically convoluted French literary
approach to love: she is sad that they are apart, and writing in
floods of tears, but she is happy in her sadness because they are
together in it. Or something like that. Her pain was probably none
the less real for it. Nor was her love for Algren likely to have
been any less real for the fact that what she writes has been also
said in a thousand Cole Porter lyrics. Nor, in fact, is the value
of her work diminished by her having such an annoying personality.
For her era, the way she lived and what she wrote, in ``The Second
Sex'' especially, was intellectually courageous almost beyond
overstatement. Her commitment to her work, and to the processing of
her life into her work, was the source of her final break with
Algren: he reacted publicly and bitterly to her portrayal of him in
``The Mandarins'' and ``Force of Circumstance.'' Given the
negligible role he is allotted and its opposition to the constant
assertion in Beauvoir's letters that he was the center of her
world, this is unsurprising. So is the fact that a woman who wrote,
in ``The Second Sex,'' that sex ``in effect puts woman into a state
of dependency on man'' opted for a union of the mind, as, in a
different way, she did with Sartre. In the end, the self-reflexive
romance of ``A Transatlantic Love Affair'' demonstrates a sadly
Cartesian proposition: I write love letters, therefore I love.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Mim Udovitch is a contributing editor for Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 0950EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0680 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SEAT-1000&AMP;ADD     12-03 1565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SEAT-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 HOT SEAT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theater Criticism for The New York Times, 1980-1993.
</P>
<P>
   By Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 1,050 pp. New York: Random House. $39.95.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; TWO ON THE AISLE &QL; 
 &UR; By HARLOW ROBINSON &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Critics _ especially theater critics _ must expect to be hated.
The wiser among them even enjoy the contempt, for they understand
their colorful and essential role as villains in the larger drama
of the theatrical enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Few drama critics have inspired more fear, loathing and
indignation, however, than Frank Rich, the legendary ``Butcher of
Broadway.'' From 1980 to 1993, Rich served as the chief drama
critic for The New York Times. Now, in the aptly titled ``Hot
Seat,'' he has assembled approximately one-quarter of the reviews
and essays he delivered from that bully pulpit, formerly occupied
by Alexander Woolcott, Brooks Atkinson and Walter Kerr. Equipped
with an introduction, some hindsight, some insider gossip and a few
amusing ``best'' and ``worst'' lists, the result is an exuberant,
enthralling and wistful volume no less valuable as
social-economic-political history than as a definitive chronicle of
the era's theatrical activity.
</P>
<P>
   Rich sooner or later incurred the wrath of almost everyone he
wrote about. He was denounced repeatedly from the stage at the Tony
Awards. Directors, producers and actors regularly accused him of
single-handedly closing their shows. The producer David Merrick
even called Rich ``a savage dog'' on ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Exit the Critic,'' published as a valedictory in The New
York Times Magazine in early 1994 and anthologized here, Rich
expresses a wry amusement at the furious passions his reviews used
to unleash: ``Critics may not be, as is generally presumed,
frustrated actors or playwrights, but few of us mind playing our
assigned role in the timeless sideshows of the rialto.'' Elsewhere,
he muses that the virulence of the hatred directed at his strong
opinions was directly proportionate to the theater's growing
inability to compete with television and film for mainstream
American audiences, performers and writers. To blame Frank Rich was
far easier than to confront the unpleasant fact that many, if not
most, of the seats in the dwindling number of Broadway theaters
were being filled by foreign tourists barely fluent in English but
happy to pay the ever-increasing ticket prices for shows with
mountains of scenery and deafening miking.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hot Seat,'' Rich is eager to debunk the myth of his and The
Times's omnipotence. Obviously, the crowds didn't stay away because
of his lukewarm response to ``Cats'' (``If you blink, you'll miss
the plot'') and most of the other blockbusters by Andrew Lloyd
Webber. Nor did his praise of high-minded productions like ``The
Grapes of Wrath'' or ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses'' keep them open.
Rich cites further examples in lists like ``The Power of The Times
Revisited 1: Rave Reviews, Short Broadway Runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you think about Rich's opinions, there's no denying
that he's an impressive writer and thinker. Residing in New York
for much of the period, I turned eagerly each morning to his
artfully fashioned pieces, anticipating another good column and at
least a few laughs. Rereading them now, I have been happily
reliving the sights, smells, sounds and words of many wonderful,
and some god-awful, evenings in the theater and experiencing others
that I missed.
</P>
<P>
   Who was better at the lethal apercu than Frank Rich?
</P>
<P>
   ``Had the actor Philip Casnoff not been beaned by a falling slab
of scenery at a press preview last week, 'Shogun: The Musical'
might have been best remembered as the first Broadway musical
extravaganza to beguile an audience with a song about a dildo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Capped Teeth and Caesar Salad,'' a song from ``Song &AMP; Dance,''
starring Bernadette Peters, ``recycles Beverly Hills jokes that had
seen better days when Joan Rivers was still in college.''
</P>
<P>
   It's only fair, too, to remember the conditions under which Rich
labored. Writing on deadline with impatient editors breathing down
his neck, he still managed to construct apparently seamless
miniature essays. As an occasional critic myself, I tell you this
takes talent, discipline and nerves.
</P>
<P>
   There was much more to Rich's success than nasty quips and
one-liners. If anything, the sting of his reviews has faded with
time, and what remains behind are different, more enduring
qualities: a thorough historical and artistic knowledge of American
and British theatrical tradition; an encyclopedic familiarity with
the work of a wide variety of performers, directors and playwrights
currently active in the theater; and an infectious passion for this
evanescent and impossible medium.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the ``330-odd pieces'' collected here tend to
favor shows the critic enjoyed (almost anything by Stephen
Sondheim) or judged significant artistically (``House of Blue
Leaves,'' ``M. Butterfly,'' ``Cinders'') or commercially (``Cats,''
``Phantom of the Opera''). But Rich has also been careful to
include famous bombs. For him, nothing will top the notorious
``Moose Murders'': ``A visit to 'Moose Murders' is what will
separate the connoisseurs of Broadway disaster from mere
dilettantes for many moons to come.''
</P>
<P>
   As engrossing as the reviews themselves may be, the juiciest
parts of ``Hot Seat'' are the spicy italicized postscripts
sprinkled here and there. These include sobering ``Whatever
happened to . . .?'' vignettes, as well as dishy tales of backstage
intrigue. At the end of his largely favorable notice on the revival
of ``The King and I'' with Yul Brynner, Rich relates how the
imperious star (``not an easy guy'') demanded to be transported by
motorcade the few blocks from the theater to an appearance on
``Nightline.'' To the review of the revival of ``The Front Page,''
staged by Jerry Zaks, that finally brought the Vivian Beaumont
Theater at Lincoln Center back to life in 1986 he appends a
well-informed commentary on why thrust stages like the one at the
Beaumont proved so unsuccessful wherever they were built.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-SEAT-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: were built.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While no one will mistake ``Hot Seat'' for a novel, it contains
numerous narrative strands. Probably the most important, and most
poignant, are the story of AIDS and the arrival of numerous gay
characters in plays and musicals both on and Off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   News of the strange new epidemic hit the Times just as Rich
began his tenure there. One of the first AIDS play he saw was
William Hoffman's ``As Is'' in 1985. To his credit, Rich got out
front early on the issue, and reviewed (for the most part
favorably) the growing number of AIDS plays that appeared in the
coming years, from Larry Kramer's ``Normal Heart'' (which he admits
he at first undervalued) to Richard Greenberg's ``Eastern
Standard'' (an overlooked minor masterpiece, I agree) to Tony
Kushner's ``Angels in America: Millennium Approaches'' and ``Angels
in America: Perestroika.'' That Rich chooses to end the final
season in ``Hot Seat'' with his adoring, even transcendent, review
of ``Perestroika'' shows just how highly he rates Kushner's
emotional and artistic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Remembered here, too, are the numerous important theater people
lost to AIDS: among them, the playwrights Scott McPherson and Harry
Kondoleon; the choreographer Michael Bennett; and Charles Ludlam,
the wild and wildly gifted director of the Ridiculous Theatrical
Company. In a wise and humane 1992 Sunday essay, Rich describes how
he took his two sons (then aged 12 and 8) to see the gay musical
``Falsettos.'' ``I wanted to take my children to an entertainment,
a musical no less, that reinforces the notion that there are many
ways to be masculine.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, this essay (``Discovering Family Values at
'Falsettos' ``), not dissimilar to the pieces Rich now produces for
the Times Op-Ed page, marked the beginning of his transition to
another kind of writing. As he tells it in ``Exit the Critic,'' the
incessant attacks on his personal and professional integrity began
to wear him down. The disappearance of serious musicals and dramas
from Broadway, and the vastly changed economics of producing and
ticket prices, depressed him. But the last straw was the deaths of
his mother and the visionary New York producer Joseph Papp, founder
of the Public Theater. The joy had gone out of the work. ``I found
myself more interested in writing about the world itself rather
than just the theater's vision of that world.'' It was time to move
on.
</P>
<P>
   When the playwright Herb Gardner received the Tony Award for
Best Play for ``I'm Not Rappaport'' more than 12 years ago, he
bragged to the audience that his success showed that ``there's life
after Frank Rich.'' Judging by this vibrant, eloquent and often
moving collection, the same can be said for Frank Rich himself.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Harlow Robinson is the chairman of the department of modern
languages at Northeastern University, and the author of biographies
of Sergei Prokofiev and Sol Hurok.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
