</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0682 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-TRAVEL-1000&AMP;A     12-03 2277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-TRAVEL-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL
</HEADLINE>
  By BILL BRYSON 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Travel writing is the most accommodating _ one might almost say
promiscuous _ of genres. Write a book that might otherwise be
shelved under memoir, social commentary, humor or even popular
science, and as long as you leave the property at some point, you
can call it travel writing.
</P>
<P>
   You may not even have to do that. Certainly I think we can
assume that Michael Pauls and Dana Facaros did not leave the
terrestrial realm to write THE TRAVELLERS' GUIDE TO MARS
(Cadogan/Globe Pequot, paper, $6.95), a breezy and painlessly
informative survey of what you could expect to find on the red
planet if you had 13 months to travel there and back and $640,000
for the estimated cost of a round-trip ticket _ and if such an
enterprise were technically achievable. Since this is popular
science merely rendered in a novel way, the question is whether it
should be reviewed as a travel book. The answer, I suppose, is that
it just has been.
</P>
<P>
   Given the definitional uncertainties of travel writing, it's
hardly surprising that the field has begun to attract the attention
of academics like Patrick Holland and Graham Huggan. Never mind the
zippy alliteration of their title. TOURISTS WITH TYPEWRITERS:
Critical Reflections on Contemporary Travel Writing (University of
Michigan, $32.50) is heavyweight stuff, what the authors themselves
might call (indeed, do call) a ``metacommentary.'' An introductory
passage setting out the book's goals asks eight suitably hefty
questions _ ``What might a taxonomy of contemporary travel
narratives look like, and how might it tally with travel writing's
inventory of spatialized cultural myths?'' is a fair example _ then
concludes, ``All of these questions are essayed, if hardly
answered, in this study.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I can't argue with that. What Holland and Huggan offer is
an ambitious trawl through the immense and busy world of the modern
travel narrative. Alas, they don't like much of what they see.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chatwin often resorts to ``camp affectations,'' Tim Cahill
and Redmond O'Hanlon to clownish buffoonery. Mary Morris is given
to ``trancelike reveries redolent of New Age psychobabble.''
National Geographic, meanwhile, gets it in the neck for its ''
'soft primitivist' photographs . . . which so often focus on the
erogenous zones of the female (native) body,'' an assertion that's
at least a generation out of date and was decidedly arguable even
then.
</P>
<P>
   And on it goes. Although they generally approve of him, they
find that Pico Iyer is guilty of being ``too knowing, too
up-to-the-minute.'' Diane Ackerman's language ``lapses at times
into the precious,'' and Robert D. Kaplan writes prose that
``entraps itself in a kind of apocalyptic banality'' _ rather rich,
I would submit, from a pair who routinely produce sentences like
``Travel has recently emerged as a crucial epistemological category
for the displacement of normative values and homogenizing,
essentialist views.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does that mean exactly? It means: Put this volume aside
and go find yourself a real book _ perhaps Rick Ridgeway's latest,
THE SHADOW OF KILIMANJARO: On Foot Across East Africa (Holt,
$27.50). In 1996, Ridgeway, a celebrated mountaineer and
adventurer, decided to hike across south-central Kenya from the
summit of Mount Kilimanjaro at the Tanzanian border to the Indian
Ocean at Malindi, a distance of about 300 miles. This is classic
territory, the part of the mythical Dark Continent that gave us
``Out of Africa,'' ``White Mischief,'' Mau Mau uprisings, Masai
warriors and big-game hunters, among much else.
</P>
<P>
   Promising stuff. So when I read in the early pages that Ridgeway
needed just three weeks to accomplish the trek, that he was to be
accompanied and protected by a corps of heavily armed guides and
that each night they would arrive at a luxuriously appointed camp
(folding chairs, hot showers, dining tent) set up by an advance
party, this seemed, even by my forgiving standards, a trifle tame.
A memorable vacation perhaps, but hardly the stuff of gripping
adventure narrative.
</P>
<P>
   I am happy to report that I was quite wrong. To begin with,
Ridgeway is a graceful and engaging companion, and East Africa _
specifically the vast Tsavo National Park, through which he and his
guides ventured _ teems with danger, challenge and excitement.
Lions, elephants, hippos, crocodiles, Cape buffaloes and leopards
are just some of the megafauna that might _ and often do _ come
charging through the brush.
</P>
<P>
   Into all this, Ridgeway deftly weaves compact and absorbing
interludes about the history of conservation in East Africa, the
fate of displaced tribes, the rise and fall of big-game hunting and
the uneasy relationship between European interlopers and local
people. He also tells a good story _ for example, this account of
the time his guide, Iain Allan, took a party of tourists on a trek
into the bush and hired Masai tribesmen with spears to protect the
camps at night:
</P>
<P>
   ``One evening when everyone was gathered around the fire, a
lioness suddenly stepped out of the bush not more than 20 feet
away. Iain told the clients not to move while he stood and turned
to wave the Masai into position. To his chagrin all of them had
dropped their spears and were climbing a tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Allan drove the lioness off by shouting at it, to the immense
delight of the tourists. Then he fired all the Masai warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure of a more indirect sort abounds in James C. Simmons's
CASTAWAY IN PARADISE: The Incredible Adventures of True-Life
Robinson Crusoes (Sheridan House, paper, $14.95). Originally
published in hardcover in 1993, this is more a popular history than
a travel book. No matter. Simmons's scrupulously researched tales
of people led by misfortune or choice to take up hermit existences
on lonely atolls and surf-fringed isles is, at every turn,
irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-TRAVEL-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: irresistible.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He begins with the man who started it all, the Scottish mariner
Alexander Selkirk, whose experiences as a castaway on Mas a Tierra
Island, 400 miles off the Chilean coast, from 1704 to 1709 provided
the rough material for Daniel Defoe's classic novel 10 years later.
Selkirk, it's worth noting, went ashore voluntarily _ he didn't get
along with the captain of his ship _ and was better provisioned
than his fictional counterpart. He also had the considerable
advantage of being in a lush, well-watered tropical paradise that
abounded with fruit, fish and game. (Even so, the experience quite
unhinged him. After being rescued, he returned to Scotland but
failed to adjust to society and passed his days in a cave above his
hometown. He returned to sea and died of a fever off the African
coast.)
</P>
<P>
   Rather less lucky _ certainly less willing _ was Charles H.
Barnard, whose ordeal a century later is all but forgotten now. By
all accounts a kindly and unassuming fellow, Barnard was an
American ship captain who was on a sealing expedition in the South
Atlantic in 1813 when he came across a group of shipwrecked,
half-starved British sailors and their passengers _ some 45 people
in all _ on an uninhabited island in the Falklands archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   Barnard unhesitatingly took the castaways aboard, even though
Britain and America were at war, and agreed to convey them to a
neutral port in South America. He then went ashore with a party of
four men to shoot and gather game to feed the extra mouths. Upon
returning, he discovered that the British had stolen away with his
ship and left him and his companions stranded on a featureless,
barren waste at the edge of winter with nothing but their rowboat,
a few knives, a blanket, a dog named Cent and the clothes they
stood up in.
</P>
<P>
   Against all odds, the men survived the winter _ but worse was to
come for poor old Captain Barnard. Six months after his abandonment
by the British, Barnard returned from a day's hunting to find that
the four other men were rowing away in the boat, leaving him with
nothing at all. (The others would eventually return, begging
forgiveness, which Barnard characteristically granted.) Altogether,
Barnard and his hapless mates were stranded for 18 months before a
passing ship rescued them.
</P>
<P>
   Barnard returned to New York and wrote a book about his ordeal,
which sold a few hundred copies before it (and he) vanished from
the scene. ``Nothing about his later life is known,'' Simmons
notes, though I think we can safely assume that Barnard offered no
more assistance to British sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Against such tales of privation, it comes as something of a
relief to turn to the bright, cheerful prose of Heinrich Boll's
IRISH JOURNAL (Marlboro/Northwestern University, paper, $12.95).
First published in Germany in 1957 but not translated into English
(by Leila Vennewitz) until a decade later, ``Irish Journal''
recounts a trip made by the future Nobel laureate and his family in
the mid-1950's to look at and admire ``the only people in Europe
that never set out to conquer.''
</P>
<P>
   Now reissued in paperback, ``Irish Journal'' has a beguiling, if
inevitably dated, charm that perfectly suits the landscape and
temperament of its subject. True to its title, it is much more
journal than book, with chapters that are often little more than
disconnected sketches and jottings. The main strand of plot,
insofar as there is one, concerns Boll's increasingly hilarious and
futile attempts to change German marks into Irish pounds, and the
almost infinite credit he is offered at every turn by merchants and
officials who assume that he will one day settle up.
</P>
<P>
   More contemporary, but equally relaxed and amiable in tone, is
Bruce Berger's lyrical ALMOST AN ISLAND: Travels in Baja California
(University of Arizona, cloth, $39.95; paper, $17.95). A poet and
musician, Berger first ventured into the Baja peninsula _ a barren
but beautiful ``800-mile dead end'' _ in 1968 and has been
returning ever since, often for long periods.
</P>
<P>
   Physically and geologically distinct from the rest of Mexico,
the Baja peninsula has always been a place apart. The original
inhabitants, Berger notes, were a people who ``lacked the least
fumblings of agriculture or the simplest storage devices of pottery
or woven baskets'' but were accomplished artists, covering canyon
walls with intricate paintings up to 150 feet long and 30 feet high
_ ``the greatest primitive murals in the Western Hemisphere.''
</P>
<P>
   The inhabitants of this region have always evinced a certain
streak of engaging eccentricity. When an early Spanish missionary
named Father Ugarte ``threatened one tribe with the flames of hell,
they were enchanted to learn of a place where they would never be
cold and asked him how to get there.'' Members of another tribe
amused themselves by teaching him obscenities when he asked for
translations of terms in the Roman Catholic litany.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the innocence and remoteness that once characterized
Baja California has long since vanished. Thirty years ago, the
peninsula was practically unpaved and just as practically unknown.
Now a modern highway gives it a paved spine and access to the
outside world, and resort hotels stand on once pristine beaches.
Berger writes about the changes with both dismay and understanding.
Discussing with a Mexican acquaintance the sweeping transformation
of the community of San Ignacio, he observes:
</P>
<P>
   ``The man asked me to put myself in the place of an Ignaciano
trying to get his wife as quickly as possible to the hospital in
Santa Rosalia over hours of primitive road. . . . I, in turn,
argued that the accelerated pace would provoke new ills, encourage
the young to leave and aggravate the need for hospitals. It is a
classic argument that neither side ever wins, and it left me
certain that the highway would go through because highways simply
did.''
</P>
<P>
   I am not normally much of one for anthologies _ too much like
snacking _ but I am happy to make an exception for THE BEST OF
OUTSIDE: The First 20 Years (Vintage Departures, paper, $14),
assembled by the editors of the popular magazine. There has never
been a magazine quite like it. What could easily have been a
tedious monthly paean to running shoes, rock scrambling and the
like became instead, quite unexpectedly, a repository of some truly
exceptional writing. Gathered here are 31 pieces from the
magazine's first two decades. Among the particular pleasures are
Jonathan Raban on messing about in boats, Tim Cahill on a trip to
cannibal country in the Indonesian half of New Guinea, and David
Quammen on the famous and forbidding lizards known as Komodo
dragons, also in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the implied commitment to exertion in its title, Outside
has never felt entirely bound to the idea of vigorous activity.
Here, for instance, are the unimprovable opening lines of an Ian
Frazier essay on a persistent but decidedly unadventurous aspect of
modern life: ``In New York City, where I live, plastic bags get
stuck in trees. Especially in the winter, the wind lifts them and
fixes them by their handles in high upper branches, where they
become, compared to ordinary litter, immortal.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not travel writing, either. Perhaps that's why I like it
so much.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bryson's most recent book is ``A Walk in the Woods:
Rediscovering America on the Appalachian Trail.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
