<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0683 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PASSAGE-NYTSF     12-03 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PASSAGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 PASSAGE EAST
<TEXT>
<P>
   Illustrated and written by Ian Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Commentary by John Maxtone-Graham.
</P>
<P>
   159 pp. Charlottesville, Va.: Howell Press. $60.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; EAST OF SUEZ &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL KENNEDY &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   For the past 15 or more years, anyone really interested in the
naval and maritime history of the Western world has been rejoicing
at the output of the supreme artist of the era of the armored
warships, Ian Marshall, a soft-spoken former architect, very
British but now resident in Maine. In marine art terms, Marshall's
work is coming close to the reputation achieved by the fabulous
Patrick O'Brian novels about naval warfare during Napoleonic times.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall was trained as an architect in South Africa and the
United States and practiced that calling for many years. Somewhere
along the way, he began to sketch watercolors of ``armored ships''
-- that is, of naval vessels built after the Industrial Revolution,
craft that were of iron or steel construction, propelled by steam
power, carrying guns far larger than any that could be handled
easily on land, and therefore quite the most formidable instruments
of war of their day. At a certain time in the history of
great-power politics -- shall we say, 1860 to 1941 -- the fate of
world affairs much depended on how these mastodons performed in
battle. All this is wonderfully captured in Marshall's earlier
books, especially ``Armored Ships'' and ``Ironclads and Paddlers,''
in which each warship he presents is placed in a historic setting,
like H.M.S. Warspite blowing up German destroyers in Narvik fjord
in 1940 or the U.S.S. New Jersey steaming through the Panama Canal
after its intervention in Lebanon in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to Marshall than the extraordinary knowledge
he has acquired of these large battle vessels, or his elegiac and
often Turneresque paintings of them. Happily, it is also the case
that Marshall in his youth was taken by his parents on the famous
maritime route from Britain to the East -- that is, from London or
southern France to Suez, Aden, Bombay, Colombo, Madras, Calcutta
and then further east to Penang, Singapore and Hong Kong. This
passage he now seeks to recapture in his new book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passage East'' is, therefore, both an artistic and a
historical tribute to one of the most remarkable sea voyages of the
past century -- the outward passage of large numbers of Britons
(aristocrats, civil servants, merchants, soldiers, maids) from
London to India, and return of the same, perhaps years later. The
very journey became so romanticized for Britons that apocryphal
stories gained credible circulation, like the word ``posh'' having
been coined from an acronym used by a steamship line for the most
expensive cabins, ``port out, starboard home'' (and thus shaded
from the blistering sun as the vessels plied to India and back).
This was one of the great cultural interchanges of the time, albeit
one-sided since so many fewer Indians (apart from nabobs and
Brahmins) traveled in turn to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   What Marshall is so good and expert at is capturing the cultural
and social life on board these elegant, well-furnished liners,
perhaps a little more understandable to us now that we have seen
the movie ``Titanic.'' The sense and purpose of this portrayal
evokes and stimulates an appreciation of a more regulated, socially
exclusive time when ``West'' went to ``East'' in a self-satisfied
mood. By 1947, the Raj was finished but hardly any of the earnest
passengers on a P &AMP; O (Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation
Company) liner would have guessed that a mere 10 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs and Marshall's own sketches are carefully and
intelligently mixed with the text of this entertaining work. Also
important is the substantive essay contributed by the famous marine
historian John Maxtone-Graham, who has written much about the
Atlantic crossing but now offers his own reflections on the
``passage east.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, this is a worthy work. It is simultaneously a
coffee-table book that we would all like to receive from a rich
uncle, and a work of superb artistry and scholarship that
illuminates one of the fascinating aspects of intercultural traffic
during the past century. One hundred years ago, Kipling wrote,
``Oh, East is East, and West is West, and never the twain shall
meet.'' Reading ``Passage East,'' even from its primarily maritime
perspective, but with Marshall's portrayal of the swarms of
bumboats surrounding a newly arrived Royal India liner in, say,
Calcutta, it is hard not to disagree. This is not just a nostalgic
essay in imperial, Western history; it is a beautifully captured
commentary on part of our disappearing century.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kennedy is Dilworth Professor of History and director of
International Security Studies at Yale University. He is the author
of, among other books, ``The Rise and Fall of British Naval
Mastery.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
