<HEADER>
A0684 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MUSHROOMS-NYT     12-03 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MUSHROOMS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MAGICAL MUSHROOMS, MISCHIEVOUS MOLDS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By George W. Hudler.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 248 pp.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton, N.J.: Princeton University Press. $29.95.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; AIN'T WE GOT FUNGI &QL; 
 &UR; By ALLEN LACY &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, when George W. Hudler got his first glimpse of
fungus spores through a microscope in a laboratory section of a
course in forest pathology at the University of Minnesota, he
underwent a conversion experience. ``At that moment,'' he writes in
the preface to his highly engaging book on the transactions between
fungi and human beings, ``my life took on new meaning.'' He had a
fresh enthusiasm that ``propelled me through two graduate degrees
and into my present position as professor of plant pathology at
Cornell University.''
</P>
<P>
   At Cornell, Hudler has openly preached the good news -- and the
not so good news -- about the kingdom of the fungi. Over the past
decade, a couple of thousand students have enrolled in Magical
Mushrooms, Mischievous Molds (otherwise known as Plant Pathology
201). The course now serves as the basis for an utterly delightful
book that can be read by anyone who can hardly tell a shiitake from
a morel.
</P>
<P>
   After two lucid introductory chapters on the taxonomy,
physiology, anatomy and reproductive behavior of fungi, Hudler gets
down to his main task, dividing these forms of life into those that
are inimical to our interests and those that benefit us beyond any
possibility of doubt. The villains come first, starting with those
fungi that affect the plant life of special significance to
humankind. In Europe in 1845, Phytophthora infestans, an organism
that causes a fatal blight of potatoes, made its first appearance.
The following year in Ireland, where these tubers were an almost
exclusive dietary staple, the potato famine ran its tragic course.
Within a decade, hundreds of thousands died from starvation, a
million more from associated diseases like typhus and cholera. It
hardly needs mentioning that the resulting immigration from Ireland
to the United States significantly changed American culture,
religion and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magical Mushrooms, Mischievous Molds'' also explores other
plant diseases: rusts of wheat and other grains; the powdery mildew
and the downy mildew that afflicted European vineyards in the last
century; and the chestnut blight, Dutch elm disease and dogwood
anthracnose that more recently have altered the ecology of American
forests and destroyed untold numbers of handsome trees in our
communities. Other, more sinister fungi attack us not indirectly,
by affecting plant life, but head on, by harming us. Ringworm, jock
itch and athlete's foot are all fungal diseases, but they are mere
discomforts. Candidiasis (yeast infections and thrush) can be more
serious. Worst of all are several respiratory diseases that can be
fatal, particularly for people whose immune systems have been
compromised by other diseases. These include histoplasmosis (caused
by an organism common in bird dung), aspergillosis (from several
species of a mold of grain and hay) and coccidioidomycosis (from a
fungus of desert soils whose spores are released into the
atmosphere by farming and even earthquakes).
</P>
<P>
   SO far, it seems, Hudler hasn't been very encouraging about the
fungi among us. Perhaps, he says, he has led us to conclude that
they are ``rotten, disgusting, vile creations, hellbent on mucking
up what is otherwise a pretty good life on Planet Earth.'' But this
is by no means the burden of his book: rather, ``for all the
problems the fungi have caused, they have also extended our lives
and made them far more enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't surprise anyone that the first item in Hudler's
catalogue of beneficial fungi is Penicillium notatum, a mold whose
antibiotic properties were discovered accidentally by Alexander
Fleming in 1928. Penicillin, the drug derived from it in large
quantities right at the end of World War II, saved great numbers of
lives. Because many microbes eventually developed resistance to its
antibiotic properties, it has been more or less superseded by other
drugs of fungal origin, such as cephalosporin. (But penicillin
still has its uses. Were it not for massive injec-tions of it to
treat a particularly nasty kind of pneumonia I came down with last
February in the aftermath of surgery, it's a good guess that
someone else would be reviewing ``Magical Mushrooms.'')
</P>
<P>
   In sum, Hudler makes an excellent brief on behalf of the fungi.
They provide us with many blessings and benefits. Some of them give
us wine, beer and leavened bread. The omnivores among us have a
keen appreciation for broiled portobellos atop our filet mignon;
vegetarians for the portobellos in themselves, not as
accompaniments. Other fungi help us fight against diseases that
might weaken or destroy us without their assistance. Still others
-- and not the least important among them -- are responsible for
tidying up our planet by digesting plant debris. Without their
help, we and everything else would be smothered in biomass.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Allen Lacy is a professor of philosophy at Richard Stockton
College of New Jersey, where he also teaches horticulture. His
latest book is ``The Inviting Garden: Gardening for the Senses,
Mind, and Spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
