<HEADER>
A0685 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CROCODILE-NYT     12-03 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CROCODILE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN'S BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  By JUDITH VIORST 
 ------- 
 THE CHRISTMAS CROCODILE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Bonny Becker.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated by David Small.
</P>
<P>
   Unpaged. New York: Simon &AMP; Schuster Books for Young Readers.
$16. (Ages 4 to 8) &QL; 
 &UR; SANTA MOUSE AND THE RATDEER
</P>
<P>
   Written and illustrated by Thacher Hurd.
</P>
<P>
   Unpaged. New York: HarperCollins Publishers. $14.95. (Ages 3 to
6) &QL; 
 &UR; WOLF CHRISTMAS
</P>
<P>
   By Daniel Pinkwater.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated by Jill Pinkwater.
</P>
<P>
   Unpaged. New York: Marshall Cavendish. $15.95. (Ages 4 to 8) &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Every holiday is marked with a new batch of picture books
straining to say something original. This is not an easy task,
especially at Christmas, when writers often feel compelled to
deliver yet another rendition of that estimable message, ``Peace on
earth, good will toward men.'' The offerings this season include
the exotic ``Wolf Christmas'' and the amiable ``Santa Mouse and the
Ratdeer,'' and in both, on the night before you-know-what, all is
(sooner or later) calm and bright. But the naughty team of Bonny
Becker and David Small have opted for mayhem over tranquillity in
their outrageous and hilarious book ``The Christmas Crocodile,'' in
which Alice Jayne finds an irrepressible crocodile under the tree
on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christmas Crocodile didn't mean to be bad, not really,''
we are told right up front and several times thereafter, but by the
second page the animal has already devoured a couple of presents _
Father's shoe, the wreath in the hall _ and he's working on the
roast. Uncle Theodore, who used to hunt wild game and still dresses
in high boots and full uniform, wants to send the Christmas
Crocodile to Africa, or maybe turn him into a pair of shoes. Aunt
Figgy thinks he ought to be put in an orphanage. Alice Jayne, on
the other hand, would very much like to keep him, and as the night
wears on, other members of the family come to believe that maybe
he's learned to behave himself after all.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance. By the time Christmas arrives, he has consumed _
among many, many, many other items _ 29 crumpets, 5 golden oranges,
the left stove-top burner, Aunt Figgy's hot water bottle, Uncle
Theodore's Zulu robe, Father's red earmuffs, Mother's comforter,
the tree and all _ well, almost all _ of the presents.
</P>
<P>
   Becker's zany tale is wonderfully complemented by Small's witty
drawings of a grand, old-fashioned house inhabited by Alice Jayne,
her dotty relatives and one house-wrecking crocodile with a very
expressive face. As already noted, the Christmas Crocodile didn't
mean to be bad, but I am happy to report that at the end of this
captivating book he is just as voracious as ever, having learned
absolutely nothing about good manners or self-control.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, everyone in ``Santa Mouse and the Ratdeer'' ends up
behaving quite nicely, although Christmas Eve doesn't start off all
that promisingly. It is a dark and stormy night. Santa is late,
disorganized and in a rotten mood. His ratdeer _ Blunder, Basher,
Lousy, Loopy, Bugsy and Twizzlebum _ are also grumpy, perhaps
because of their excessively adorable names. And then disaster
strikes: Santa's sleigh malfunctions and plunges into a snowbank,
scattering presents everywhere and dumping Santa and his ratdeer
into the snows of the North Woods.
</P>
<P>
   There is not much grace under pressure. Santa shivers on a rock
while his fed-up ratdeer, ditching him, head off in search of a
beach. Is Christmas done for? Not to worry. Fortunately for the
morals and morale of this crowd, the ratdeer find, instead of a
beach, a sweet little mouse girl called Rosie, whose warm cookies,
hot chocolate and blazing fire restore good will to their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Thacher Hurd accompanies his text with serviceable drawings,
heavy on the traditional reds and greens of Christmas. He makes
Christmas Eve by the fire look cozy indeed. I suppose it is
reassuring to see Santa _ his belly full, his sleigh repaired, his
ratdeer smiling _ riding smoothly into the starry night to complete
his appointed rounds. But having just laughed my way through ``The
Christmas Crocodile,'' I guess I was hoping for something a bit
more irreverent.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing irreverent about ``Wolf Christmas,'' but Daniel
Pinkwater's particular perspective and Jill Pinkwater's haunting
drawings take us far from the realm of the ordinary. This is a
Christmas Eve story told from the point of view of a young wolf,
who, with the other pups in the family, is scampering about in the
moonlit snowy woods while the older wolves watch over them. Then
Uncle Louis _ a funny wolf who always has interesting things to
show and tell _ invites them all on a very unusual journey, leading
them to a hillside below which dwells a community of humans. Aren't
they dangerous? one of the adult wolves wonders. But Uncle Louis
explains that this is a special night for humans, and that on this
special night they are quite peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   The wolves, looking down at the cluster of homes bedecked with
colored lights and exuding ``hot smoky smells, and strange meat
smells and sweet smells,'' don't see any humans but hear them
singing inside. They like what they hear. And celebrating that
moment of peace on earth and their shared _ not humanity but
animality _ the wolves throw back their heads, and they sing too.
</P>
<P>
   This simple and beautifu1 book, which steps into the souls of
the wolves, offers a fresh take on a fine old theme. And much as I
adore ``The Christmas Crocodile,'' I was glad he was not on that
hillside, disrupting the singing.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Judith Viorst is the author of many books for adults and
children, including ``Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No
Good, Very Bad Day,'' her musical version of which is currently
being performed at the Kennedy Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
