<HEADER>
A0687 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SANTA-NYTSF     12-03 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SANTA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 HOW SANTA GOT HIS JOB
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Stephen Krensky.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated by S. D. Schindler.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15. (Ages 4 to 6) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ---- &QL; 
 &UR; CHILDREN'S BOOKS &QL; 
 &UR; By WILL JOYNER &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Who says Santa doesn't have a resume? In this quick, quirky
tale, Stephen Krensky imagines a frenetic occupational past for the
jolly fellow. Bluntly put, the young Santa can't hold a job _ or at
least is too much of a perfectionist to hold a job for very long.
Along the way, though, as he skips from cleaning chimneys to
cooking in a diner to caring for the residents of a zoo, he picks
up the skills, attitudes and extra pounds that will let him
eventually realize his potential amid a bunch of very understanding
elves. (In the zoo, for example, the animals teach him how to know
who's sleeping and who's awake.) At first, the message here _ that
no job is ideal and that all jobs require patience and training _
seems oddly placed in a holiday-season picture book. But, come to
think of it, the secular world's Christmas, with its garish display
of consumer expectations, is a fine time for young children to
think about the work that precedes all those fruits of labor. Each
episode of Santa's early job history is a little too short on
dramatic content; no other character is even given a name. In his
straightforward sentences, however, Krensky maintains the kind of
unpatronizing, faintly ironic tone that 5-year-olds appreciate
because it allows them to assume they're being let in on adult
observations. And the simplicity of the words is nicely balanced by
the busy sophistication of S. D. Schindler's illustrations, which
are full of clues that set the story in the 1950's, in a city a lot
like New York. Every drawing is so intricately composed that child
and parent alike will want to linger before turning a page _ to try
to figure out why that woman in the swank hat is leering at young
Santa as he races down a sidewalk, for instance, or, after the tale
shifts to a snowy spot way out of town, what exactly those elves
are thinking as their new colleague signs a contract to deliver
toys in such a radically new way.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 0951EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0688 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MICHELANGELO-     12-03 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MICHELANGELO-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MICHELANGELO'S SURPRISE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Written and illustrated by Tony Parillo.
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $16. (Ages 5 to 9) &QL; 
 &UR; BRAVO, ZAN ANGELO!
</P>
<P>
   A Commedia Dell'Arte Tale.
</P>
<P>
   Written and illustrated by Niki Daly.
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $16. (Ages 5 and up) &QL; 
 &UR; CHILDREN'S BOOKS &QL; 
 &UR; By MARY SIMONS &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Because I am a part-time resident of Italy, my four
grandchildren, aged 4 to 12, have traveled widely there during
their summer vacations. There is nothing like seeing the ``real
thing'' to make culture come alive to a young CD-ROM-TV generation,
but picture books have a special capacity to inspire imagination as
well as prompt memories.
</P>
<P>
   Both ``Michelangelo's Surprise,'' set in a Medici palace in
Florence, and ``Bravo, Zan Angelo!,'' a tale that takes place in an
18th-century version of Venice, can only help to reinforce the
anticipation and memories of the lucky children who travel or those
who just dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelangelo's Surprise'' is a supposedly true story of a day
in 1494 when, after a rare snowfall, Michelangelo's benefactor
Piero de' Medici summoned the young artist (he was just 19) to
build a snow sculpture in his palace courtyard. Though Michelangelo
was arguably the finest artist of the Renaissance, Tony Parillo, an
American teacher and artist, has offered a story that is slight,
and has only three short paragraphs to tell readers something about
the artist's career. Still, the surprise _ that Michelangelo
created from snow not a jolly fellow with a corncob pipe but a
colossal human form with a fierce face _ may forever change a
child's idea of a snowman. Unfortunately, the illustrations fail to
capture the line and color of the 15th century and may actually be
disturbing to small children.
</P>
<P>
   Niki Daly is a South African artist and children's book
illustrator, and his watercolors of Venice are another thing
altogether. For any child (or adult) who has walked the little
squares and narrow streets of that magical city, Daly's paintings
will evoke many an ``Oh, I remember that building!'' Again the
story is spare; a little boy wants to join his crotchety
grandfather's commedia del-l'arte street theater troupe and
succeeds in scoring a small acting triumph as a rooster. But here
the illustrations, exquisitely drawn and illuminated with Venetian
light, carry the story farther than words can.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
