<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0689 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-COBTOWN-NYTSF     12-03 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-COBTOWN-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 A COBTOWN CHRISTMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the Diaries of Lucky Hart
</P>
<P>
   By Julia Van Nutt, illustrated by Robert Van Nutt.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday, $15.99. (Ages 5 and up) &QL; 
 &UR; ----- &QL; 
 &UR; GOOD WILL TOWARD COBTOWN, 1845 &QL; 
 &UR; By CYNTHIA ZARIN &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Only Scrooge could resist this elaborately packaged plum pudding
of a picture book. It purports to be an 1845 diary written by one
Lucky Hart (there's also a character called Fliberty Jibbert),
which details the exciting revels and events that lead up to
Christmas Day in the little hamlet of Cobtown. Will the gift Lucky
has ordered from Ploomajiggy for her Mama arrive in time? Will the
townspeople discover the identity of the lost blind man who keeps
on muttering about ``nine donkeys''? Will the dog with the hurt paw
-- bound up by Lucky's Aunt Heddy, who keeps a wild pig as a pet --
find a good home? Luckily for the reader, Lucky herself, who's all
set to sing for the whole town on Christmas (if the busted organ is
fixed), is funny and dear. ``There are other things I'd rather do
than memorize the new hymn,'' she confides to her diary, and then
supplies a list, which includes ``eating Christmas cookies'' and
``baking more Christmas cookies (I ate all the first ones).'' A
rustic Mrs. Beeton, Lucky also supplies a recipe for Snow Cream
(``be sure to use only clean snow'') and an illustrated lesson in
how to make pomander balls.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hearty, happy tale, but in addition to its helpings of
cheer (and despite occasional lapses into just-folks corn) its
gentler theme is that things can be tricky: people do get lost; the
church organ sometimes fails; cloves can break, Lucky notes, when
you make pomanders. The lesson of unpredictability -- that things
don't always work out as planned -- is perhaps as good as any to
take into Christmas; in Cobtown it's in the company of patience,
hope, perseverance and good will toward creatures great and small
that festivities abound. The good fare and the dollhouse
illustrations, all lighted by Christmas firelight, are just right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
