<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ARCHITECTURE-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHITECTURE
</HEADLINE>
  By MARTIN FILLER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICAN PAINTED HOUSES: Basotho Dwellings of Southern Africa. By
Gary N. van Wyk. (Abrams, $39.95.) Every few generations, Western
architects wake up to the fact that our civilization's habitual
fear of strong color and bold pattern on the exteriors of buildings
causes us to lose out on a powerful form of architectural
expression. Fortunately, no such inhibitions restrict the Basotho
women of Lesotho. After each rainy season they redecorate the outer
walls of their single-story mud-brick houses with pulsating
polychrome designs of such potent graphic impact that the tradition
constitutes one of the continuing glories of African culture.
</P>
<P>
   Gary N. van Wyk, a South African artist and art historian,
places these remarkable schemes -- votive symbols invoking tribal
peace, agricultural plenty and divine protection -- fully within
the complex social order of the Basotho people. In these vibrant
patterns, at once contemporary and timeless, Western eyes will find
reflections of the painted architecture of the German
Expressionists, as well as the art of Klee, Matisse and Malevich.
Yet such affinities are more correctly seen as evidence of the
first world's expanded visual horizons in this century. For where
would modernism have been without the reinvigoration it found in
Africa's vital art, inextricably enmeshed in its makers' experience
of everyday life?
</P>
<P>
   NOTRE-DAME DE PARIS. By Alain Erlande-Brandenburg. Photographs
by Caroline Rose. Translated by John Goodman. (Abrams, $75.) With
everything else to see and do in Paris, visitors often pay little
close attention to the city's majestic early Gothic centerpiece,
the Cathedral of Our Lady of Paris, more familiarly known as Notre
Dame. Yet this sumptuous volume, written by the French medievalist
Alain Erlande-Brandenburg and illustrated with photographs by
Caroline Rose, reminds us that this iconic structure bears as much
close scrutiny as a more viscerally compelling cathedral, Notre
Dame de Chartres.
</P>
<P>
   The construction of Notre Dame -- begun shortly after 1160 under
the direction of the highly ambitious peasant-born Bishop Maurice
de Sully -- was not just an act of religious devotion but also an
assertion of the primacy of Paris above all other French dioceses.
To make that more evident, the sanctuary was designed to be taller
than any preceding church, with the nave rising to 108 feet. That
impressive feat of engineering was made possible by the first true
flying buttresses, those deceptively delicate-looking exterior
supports that keep the towering walls of the nave and apse from
collapsing beneath the weight of so much load-bearing masonry.
</P>
<P>
   The author documents Notre Dame's lengthy construction process
as well as depredations the building suffered during the French
Revolution and in the 19th century. It is debatable who did more
harm. Was it the iconoclastic revolutionaries who vandalized images
of royal authority like the sculptural Gallery of Kings above the
main portals? Or were the worse culprits the architects
Jean-Baptiste Lassus and Eugene Viollet-le-Duc, whose fanciful,
historically misconceived ``restorations'' of 1844-64 did a
different kind of violence to the intentions of the original
builders?
</P>
<P>
   BUILDING THE GEORGIAN CITY. By James Ayres. (Paul Mellon Center
for Studies in British Art/Yale University, $65.) The classical
proportions and aristocratic aura of Britain's urban architecture
of the 18th and early 19th centuries mask the fact that the
period's construction techniques took full advantage of the new
materials and manufacturing methods of the dawning Industrial
Revolution. This absorbing survey by James Ayres, director of the
John Judkyn Memorial near Bath, delves instructively into the
ingenious technologies that Georgian carpenters, masons, glaziers,
plumbers and other master craftsmen devised, taking the world's
first industrialized nation from medieval means of construction and
into the modern age. Many of the architectural and interior design
amenities we now take for granted first became prevalent during the
reigns of the four Georges, when Britain's growing prosperity,
artisanal know-how and mass production allowed great numbers of
consumers to enjoy such domestic pleasures as window glass,
wallpaper, paint and ceramic tile.
</P>
<P>
   Ayres unearths many forgotten originators and entrepreneurs,
none more fascinating than the matriarchy of the two Eleanor
Coades. The older Coade's eponymous invention, Coade stone, was a
terra-cotta-like compound that withstood the cold, damp British
climate as effectively as natural masonry and could be molded into
architectural details of every description. Her namesake daughter
and successor brilliantly exploited the design and marketing of the
versatile substance but took its secret recipe to her grave, and
the family company closed in 1840.
</P>
<P>
   CAST-IRON ARCHITECTURE IN AMERICA: The Significance of James
Bogardus. By Margot Gayle and Carol Gayle. (Norton, $39.50.) In the
annals of architectural loss, innumerable landmark buildings have
been demolished, but how many have been stolen? The latter was the
bizarre fate of one of the earliest milestones of modernism, the
Laing Stores of 1849 in New York, designed by the mechanical
engineer and inventor James Bogardus. Though this four-story
structure near City Hall employed conventional wood and brick
framing, Bogardus's ingenious wraparound curtain-wall facade of
modular cast-iron panels was as innovative (if not as celebrated)
as London's iron-and-glass Crystal Palace, completed two years
later.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan's inexorable march northward, and decades of benign
neglect, helped this modestly scaled but extraordinarily
significant relic survive intact until 1971. Its facade was then
carefully disassembled for re-erection elsewhere, proving the
``portability'' its designer expounded as a benefit of his new
construction system. Alas, those easily movable metal parts proved
all too tempting to thieves, who in 1974 and 1977 made off with the
components and presumably sold them for scrap.
</P>
<P>
   This long-awaited book, the first ever on Bogardus, is the
culmination of the lifework of Margot Gayle, the 90-year-old
doyenne of the cast-iron preservation movement -- written with her
daughter Carol Gayle, who teaches history at Lake Forest College in
Illinois. Their thorough study is likely to remain the definitive
work on the enterprising inventor whose seminal architectural
concept helped set the stage for the astounding advances in
construction during the century after his death in 1874.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-ARCHITECTURE-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: death in 1874.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSES OF McKIM, MEAD &AMP; WHITE. By Samuel G. White.
Photographs by Jonathan Wallen. (Rizzoli/The Museums at Stony
Brook, $70.) America's leading Establishment architectural practice
at the turn of the century, the New York-based collaboration of
Charles Follen McKim, William Rutherford Mead and Stanford White,
was an unusual hybrid of the corporate, the social and the
artistic. Their large office could do everything from train
stations and clubs to commercial buildings and churches. But it was
in domestic design that the virtuoso talents of White, a
self-conscious esthete and usual partner-in-charge of house
commissions, were at their most dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   A great-grandson of Stanford White and himself a New York
architect, Samuel G. White selects more than 30 of McKim, Mead &AMP;
White's extant houses, about a tenth of those built and a third of
those that survive. He offers a fond but perceptive portrait of a
team that gave their patrons -- fellow patricians -- exactly what
they wanted. Against a backdrop of privilege that Edith Wharton
would recognize, the author picks up on the seismic shift in
attitudes toward wealth and status that divided the firm's houses
into two distinct phases.
</P>
<P>
   As the Gilded Age grew more unabashedly ostentatious, McKim,
Mead &AMP; White's upper-crust clientele rejected the democratic image
inherent in the firm's porch-and-gable Shingle Style designs and
prompted the imperial classicism and pretentious historicism of its
later palatial schemes. Jonathan Wallen's excellent color
photographs confirm that a chill hand gradually fell over White's
vivid sense of color, texture, light and shadow. The telling
contrast between two of his mansions in Newport, R.I. -- the
tawny-shingled Ochre Point of 1882-84 and the white
terra-cotta-clad Rosecliff of 1897-1902, modeled after the Grand
Trianon -- is not so much a matter of material or money (both were
very costly ``cottages'') as one of spirit.
</P>
<P>
   GREENE &AMP; GREENE: Masterworks. By Bruce Smith. Photographs by
Alexander Vertikoff. (Archetype/Chronicle, $40.) The architect
brothers who took the Arts and Crafts movement in America to
unsurpassed heights of refinement -- Charles Sumner Greene
(1868-1957) and Henry Mather Greene (1870-1954) -- were in several
respects the equals of their greatest contemporary, the similarly
long-lived Frank Lloyd Wright. The Greenes' reverence for the
classical culture of Japan, belief in the complete integration of
architecture and interior design, disdain for historical styles and
profound understanding of natural materials were all values they
held in common with their more famous colleague. Regrettably, the
fraternal partners did not share Wright's indomitable resilience or
genius for late-life transformation.
</P>
<P>
   All three men went into a precipitous professional decline by
the outbreak of World War I, when the Arts and Crafts style fell
out of fashion, but only Wright's fortunes ultimately revived. The
Greenes, who worked in the idyllic Los Angeles suburb of Pasadena,
where they built most of their houses, dissolved their joint
practice in 1922 and struggled on separately until the Depression
finally ended their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, despite the beauty of Alexander Vertikoff's color
photographs of the Greenes' sophisticated bungalows, their autumnal
tonalities also project a certain poignancy. In his intelligent
text, Bruce Smith, a specialist in Arts and Crafts design, recounts
the personal histories of the architects' enlightened upper-class
clients. Their wealth and taste afforded them houses that whispered
luxury through humble materials handled like precious treasure and
set off by details of breathtaking inventiveness and exquisite
artistry. Small wonder that Greene &AMP; Greene's masterpiece, the
Gamble house of 1908 in Pasadena, is now almost as beloved by the
American public as Wright's Fallingwater.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEWALK CRITIC: Lewis Mumford's Writings on New York. Edited by
Robert Wojtowicz. (Princeton Architectural Press, $27.50.) So
convinced was Lewis Mumford of his polymathic talents -- as a
philosopher, sociologist, literary critic, religious theorist,
biographer, art historian, poet, playwright and watercolorist --
that he tended to play down the one role for which he is now most
justly remembered: architecture critic. Mumford, who died in 1990
at the age of 94, had long been urged to issue an anthology of his
essays that appeared in The New Yorker from 1931 to 1963 under the
heading ``The Sky Line.'' But he resisted doing so because of his
growing anxiety that his best-known specialty would overshadow the
larger reputation he cherished as an interdisciplinary savant.
</P>
<P>
   This collection of Mumford's 1930s articles on New York,
selected by Robert Wojtowicz, a professor of art history at Old
Dominion University in Virginia and the author's literary executor,
belies any hesitation in exposing these topical reviews to the more
demanding standards of history. Mumford, an incomparable analyst of
urban design and planning, was at his best evaluating the public
housing that stood among the proudest accomplishments of the New
Deal decade. Discussing an award-winning luxury apartment house
erected by a real-estate heir at 120 East End Ave. in Manhattan,
the outspoken critic compared it in terms of light and air with new
low-cost, union-sponsored housing on the Lower East Side, dryly
noting that ``Mr. Vincent Astor's standards would not do for the
Amalgamated Clothing Workers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-ARCHITECTURE-3RDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: Amalgamated Clothing Workers.''
</P>
<P>
   THE ARCHITECTURE OF ADDITIONS: Design and Regulation. By Paul
Spencer Byard. (Norton, $40.) The civic-minded New York architect
and lawyer Paul Spencer Byard brings hard-won insights from his
dual professions into sharp focus in this superlative overview of
the issues inherent in designing new buildings in concert with
older ones. With concision and clarity that laymen will appreciate,
Byard covers virtually every scenario likely to be faced by
practitioners, patrons and preservationists, including adding on to
landmarks, retaining the character of historic districts and
dealing with the tricky notion of architectural ``context.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair-minded and soundly informed, Byard judges each scheme
(ranging from St. Peter's Basilica in Rome to Sir Norman Foster's
Law Faculty building at Cambridge University, completed last year)
with keen understanding of the realities that affect extensions to
individual structures and expansion of building ensembles. Though
receptive to a wide spectrum of stylistic solutions, he is always
on the side of design values that promote a more humane public
environment. The author's pithy evaluations (accompanied by
unusually informative illustrations and easy-to-read plans) make
for provocative reading. His memorable coinage for saving only the
fronts of historic buildings is ``facadomy.''
</P>
<P>
   A FIELD GUIDE TO CONTEMPORARY AMERICAN ARCHITECTURE. By Carole
Rifkind. (Dutton, $45.) Even those who think they know all about
architecture in the United States since World War II will find
Carole Rifkind's bracingly idiosyncratic and admirably accessible
new survey an eye-opening experience. Although Rifkind, the author
of ``A Field Guide to American Architecture'' (1980), includes
built work by acknowledged masters of the past six decades, this is
no usual-suspects lineup. With complete self-confidence and blithe
disregard for the accepted canon, she casts a far more inclusive
eye over the man-made landscape than most current critics and comes
up with a number of structures seen in no other recent compendium.
There is something irresistible about a book that highlights
Langdon &AMP; Wilson's replica Roman villa for the Getty Museum of
1970-74 in Malibu, Calif., but ignores Richard Meier's overblown,
billion-dollar Getty Center of 1984-97 in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Rifkind resurrects several once-admired buildings of
considerable merit, including Paul Rudolph's moody, inward-turning
Tuskegee Chapel of 1968-69 in Alabama and the playful, villagelike
Kresge College of 1972-74 at the University of California, Santa
Cruz, by Charles W. Moore and William Turnbull. With her
unconditional love for architecture in all its forms, she refuses
to overlook a particular style or movement on purely esthetic
grounds or merely because it has become unfashionable. Thus, if
readers will be astonished by some of her more deservedly obscure
examples, few will doubt her passion or immense skill in digesting
and summarizing the most perplexing half-century in American
architectural history.
</P>
<P>
   FRANK O. GEHRY: Guggenheim Museum Bilbao. By Coosje van Bruggen.
(Abrams/Guggenheim Museum, $55.) No other building of the 1990's
has received (or merited) the universal praise that welcomed Frank
Gehry's Guggenheim Museum Bilbao in Spain's Basque country when it
opened late last year. Indeed, several critics have already placed
this stunningly unconventional structure among the greatest of all
20th-century buildings. So startlingly animated are Gehry's
voluptuous, organic forms that analogies to the natural world are
required to describe them. But it remains an open question whether
the titanium-clad art gallery more closely resembles a gigantic
silver blossom unfolding in a gritty industrial landscape or a
colossal aquatic creature writhing and gleaming on the banks of the
Nervion River.
</P>
<P>
   This handsomely illustrated account, written by Coosje van
Bruggen (wife and collaborator of the artist Claes Oldenburg, and a
longtime friend of Gehry's), recounts the execution of this
historic commission. It also celebrates the most successful attempt
yet by Thomas Krens, director of the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum
in New York, to turn his institution into a worldwide franchise.
Though hiring the already-acclaimed Gehry, 62 when the project
began in 1991, did not amount to the discovery of an unknown
architect, Krens was canny enough to realize that the architect had
yet to do his finest work. The Guggenheim Museum Bilbao is not only
Gehry's masterpiece but also a delicious rebuke to the
short-sighted West Coast museum patrons who earlier rejected the
Santa Monica-based architect because they feared his maverick
esthetic and were apprehensive about being deemed provincial if
they chose a Californian to design their buildings. Like Frank
Lloyd Wright's original Guggenheim, Gehry's Basque branch is its
own most stupendous work of art.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Martin Filler writes about architecture for House Beautiful, The
New York Review of Books and The New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
