<HEADER>
A0693 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ARTBOOKS-1000     12-03 2249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ARTBOOKS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTBOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN RUSSELL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FROM VAN EYCK TO BRUEGEL: Early Netherlandish Painting in the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. Edited by Maryan W. Ainsworth and Keith
Christiansen. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/Abrams, $75.) If there
were a first prize in this column for beauty of statement and
probity of elucidation, this catalogue would run away with it. The
exhibition it describes is not a loan show. It has no catchpenny
title. Everything pictured in it belongs to the Metropolitan
Museum. Quite a few of the works come tagged as ``Workshop of,''
``Style of,'' ``Copy after,'' ``Follower of'' or ``Attributed to.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is this show so crowded? Why do people come away so
palpably awed and enriched? It is because early Netherlandish
painting is, apart from everything else, a school of truth. Its
truth is perennial, moreover. Its people are our people. Its vision
is our own. Its way of summing things up is still remarkably close
to ours, though the society with which we have to deal is so
different.
</P>
<P>
   The goldsmith whom Petrus Christus painted in his shop in 1449
could be the master craftsman whose shop we would love to walk
into. The ``Man in Prayer'' (workshop of Robert Campin) is a man
whom we would entrust with our troubles. As for Pieter Bruegel the
Elder's ``Harvesters,'' we can only echo the catalogue entry: ``No
more satisfying image of a wheat field, the labor of harvesting or
the atmosphere of late summer has ever been painted.'' And all
this, without a hint of puff or evasion! The show runs through Jan.
3, 1999, after which the paintings will be redistributed in the
parts of the museum (including the Cloisters) where they are
normally found.
</P>
<P>
   DELACROIX. By Barthelemy Jobert. (Princeton University, $65.)
DELACROIX: The Late Work. By Arlette Serullaz, Vincent Pomarede,
Joseph J. Rishel, Lee Johnson, Louis-Antoine Prat and David Liot.
(Thames and Hudson, $65). There is not, and quite probably there
never will be, a definitive book about Eugene Delacroix, the great
French painter who was born just 200 years ago. There is simply too
much of him, and his work was too extensive and too various, and
there was in his nature a sovereign aloofness that remains intact.
</P>
<P>
   It was not that he hid from our view. His output as a painter
has been covered in a six-volume critical catalogue by Lee Johnson,
published from 1981 to 1989, that will not soon be superseded. The
900 pages of his diary can be read over and over again. So can his
letters, though they are overdue for a more complete edition. He
had wonderful friends and wonderful admirers, along with one or two
enemies, so the word of mouth is abundant. As recently as 1989
Maurice Serullaz crowned a lifetime of work on Delacroix with a
biography that is as shapely as accessible.
</P>
<P>
   But every generation has its take on Delacroix, and the newest
entrant is Barthelemy Jobert, who teaches art history at the
Sorbonne. His is the view of a civilized and highly informed
Parisian who has had comprehensive access to Delacroix: his
illustrations include many minor but telling examples of work on
paper from the Louvre, and he has managed to give the reader an
idea of Delacroix's major decorative achievements in Parisian
public buildings that are not normally open to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   His book is thoughtful, well paced and generous with insights
that (as Delacroix would have wished) stop just short of intimacy.
Those who come new to the subject could not have a better guide in
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delacroix: The Late Work'' is the title of an exhibition that
can be seen in Philadelphia till Jan. 3. As its title suggests, it
begins when Delacroix was turning 50 and had only another 13 years
to live. This means that readers of the catalogue will not find the
famous ``Liberty Leading the People'' of 1830, or ``The Death of
Sardanapalus'' or ``Women of Algiers in Their Apartment.'' But this
does not mean that Delacroix in the 1850's and early 60's was
quietly shutting up shop. On the contrary. There are moments in the
show when his ambition peaked and every motif was attacked with an
unprecedented ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   This was the case with ``Lion Hunt.'' Delacroix had always been
obsessed by the lion as predator and, no less, by the lion as prey.
In the climactic period of 1855 and thereabouts, he gave symphonic
outlet to the theme of the lion being attacked by a group of men.
</P>
<P>
   This was not an unequal combat, and quite often some of the men
got the worst of it. As it was quite some time since he had been in
Africa he didn't at all mind setting the lion hunt in a landscape
not far from Paris. And if he had studied some of the lions quite
recently in the Jardin des Plantes in Paris, he didn't mind that,
either. What mattered was the frenzy of the imagined struggle,
which he was very well able to simulate. And if a dealer asked,
``Couldn't you just give us another one?'' he generally complied.
</P>
<P>
   The masterpiece of this period was the enormous ``Lion Hunt'' of
1855. It measured 102 by 141 inches, and he gave it all he had.
Lions, horses and men erupt in a tumult of savagery. It is a
picture that scared people at the Salon in Paris. (``The critics
completely missed the mark,'' Delacroix said.)
</P>
<P>
   At the museum in Bordeaux, whither it was sent forthwith, it
rhymed very well with a painting of the same subject by Rubens. It
was a favorite with two rather unlikely painters, Odilon Redon and
the landscapist Charles-Francois Daubigny; both copied it. But in
1870 it was partly destroyed by fire. What survived is missing a
wide strip of canvas, 34 inches wide, at the top of the painting.
It may now look like a wounded giant, but it still inspires pity,
terror and awe.
</P>
<P>
   The catalogue has quite other things to show -- flower
paintings, in which Delacroix delighted in his mid-50's; subject
pictures powered by Shakespeare, Byron and the New Testament; and
four very large decorative panels (normally in Sao Paulo) on the
theme of ``The Four Seasons.'' Delacroix in these panels was
attentive not so much to the weatherman as to the opportunity to
paint ``Orpheus and Eurydice,'' ``Diana and Actaeon,'' ``Bacchus
and Ariadne'' and ``Juno and Aeolus.'' They were not quite finished
when he died in August 1863. But how he enjoyed doing them, and how
good they look in this very handsome catalogue!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-ARTBOOKS-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: handsome catalogue!) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SCHOLAR AND HIS STUDY: Ownership and Experience in
Renaissance Italy. By Dora Thornton. (Yale University, $50.) This
is not an ``art book,'' though many amazing works of art can be
found in it. It is about the role in the Italian Renaissance of the
``studiolo'' -- a private place set aside for study and allotted to
one person only. The owner would eventually be judged by what that
study looked like, and by what came out of it.
</P>
<P>
   It could be rather grand, as it was when St. Augustine or St.
Jerome were portrayed by Botticelli or Ghirlandaio. Or it could be
a tumbledown affair like the one portrayed in this book by Lorenzo
Lotto. It could be a workplace, a think place or a place of prayer.
It could even be all three together.
</P>
<P>
   But, in any case, every study had to have a desk, even if it was
only a simple table supported by walnut trestles. (The up-market
version looked like a Ferris wheel, and was operated by a kind of
treadmill, bringing shelf after shelf within reach.) Whatever it
was, it had to have a place for books, and it had to have all the
apparatus for writing. These instruments could be complex and
beautiful, or they could have been bought for pennies. Among visual
aids, rock crystal lenses ranked high. Inkwells could be miracles
of contrivance. Others came paired with a container for the sand
that was needed to dry the ink. A steel hand mirror was sometimes
used for reading, placed to focus light on the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Musical instruments were welcome in the study, as were
instruments for the pursuit of geometry or the casting of
horoscopes. Showing off was bad form, but there were ways of
establishing oneself as a person of taste. There were Florentine
humanists who even invited their friends to dance in their studies,
to music laid on for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   If this consistently entertaining book sounds to be a world away
from the mainline monograph on Renaissance art, it isn't. On every
page we are drawn into the society in which great art was made,
nowhere more so than we see Albrecht Durer's plan and elevation
(studio included) of the house in which he stayed in Venice.
</P>
<P>
   MARK ROTHKO: The Works on Canvas. A Catalogue Raisonne. By David
Anfam. (Yale University, $125.) Quietly, and almost without our
knowing, we are close to the age of the 1,000-page art book.
Christmas is the time to let these mammoths loose. But ``Mark
Rothko'' is a book for all seasons, and in spite of its size and
weight, it looks right and feels right. Somewhere in this volume
you can find just about everything you will want to know about what
Rothko painted between 1924 and his death in 1970. In all, 854
paintings are catalogued, and David Anfam follows up clue after
clue that may or may not yield a new truth. If Rothko was
interested in 1960 in the movies of Michelangelo Antonioni, there
is a still from ``L'Avventura'' on the relevant page.
</P>
<P>
   And the paintings? They look gorgeous, as everyone knows. But
even on these hefty pages many of them look like miniatures.
Something of the ruminatory spread of the originals is lost in such
cases. And instead of the poignant hesitation that marks so many of
Rothko's paintings, these tiny images come toward us with every
problem solved (or smoothed away). But this is a noble book, and a
bargain in today's terms.
</P>
<P>
   GOYA AND THE DUCHESS OF ALBA. By Susann Waldmann. (Prestel,
$25.) BOTTICELLI: Images of Love and Spring. By Frank Zollner.
(Prestel, $25.) As is borne out by these new volumes in Prestel's
``Pegasus Series,'' small mercies can be great blessings. The books
have great subjects -- some of the most famous images in all
European art -- and they have something new to say about them.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Botticelli: Images of Love and Spring,'' Frank Zollner, a
professor of art history in Leipzig, comes straight out and says,
``The best known paintings are the least understood.'' It is his
contention that what we have always known as Botticelli's ``Birth
of Venus'' is in reality a portrayal of the arrival of the goddess
of love on Cyprus. ``Thus far,'' he goes on, ``few details of the
picture have been interpreted either coherently or convincingly.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a pleasure to hear him put his case -- and all the more so
since the Pegasus Series volumes are a delight to have and to hold,
with their tall narrow format, their stalwart binding, their fine
paper and their ingenious choice of accessory illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Goya and the Duchess of Alba,'' Susann Waldmann wastes some
of her time (and ours) with a rubbishy novel by Lion Feuchtwanger
about Goya. But that is soon forgotten as we scrutinize Goya's
great portraits of the 13th Duchess of Alba -- the most attractive
woman of her day in Europe -- and go on to look at the highly
libidinous drawings Goya made while staying (so it is thought) at
one of her country houses. As to that, Waldmann allows the two of
them to keep their privacy. But most readers of her narrative will
decide that the jury is still out, or perhaps was never convened.
In any case, these two books would make delicious presents.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY OF MODERN ART: Painting, Sculpture, Architecture,
Photograph. By H. H. Arnason and Marla F. Prather. (Abrams, $75.)
This is the third occasion on which H. H. Arnason's ``History of
Modern Art'' has been mulled over, revised and (in this case) very
substantially enlarged. It still stands in awe before Piero della
Francesca and Jan van Eyck before taking the plunge. But thereafter
it pursues a remarkably steady, levelheaded and ecumenical course
until it ends with Mark Tansey, Raymond Pettibon, Tony Oursler and
Jeff Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Marla F. Prather, the ``revising editor'' here, is curator of
20th-century art at the National Gallery of Art in Washington. As a
curator, she has star quality. As editor, she has clearly rethought
and comprehensively updated the entire ``History of Modern Art''
and the chapter on Cubism -- for which she was personally
responsible -- has both crispness and cogency. The individual
summaries of living artists are fuller and more evidently
fair-minded than is usual in books of this sort. With close on
1,500 color plates and plenty of space for short but never flabby
biographies, this book makes an ideal introduction to a hugely
complicated subject.
</P>
<P>
   Readers should note a shaft of wit, which is exceptional in
art-book publishing. The images on both the front and the back of
the jacket are made with bedclothes long subject to heavy use. On
the front is ``Blanket,'' pieced together by Sonya Delaunay with
scraps of material after the birth of her son in 1911. On the back
is Robert Rauschenberg's famous ``Bed,'' hung up and painted over
in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   John Russell writes frequently about art and culture for The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
