<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0694 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-COOKING-1000&AMP;     12-03 2275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-COOKING-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOKING
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM GRIMES 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the other arts, cooking goes through stylistic phases.
Baroque curlicues give way to a clean classical line, which
eventually sharpens the appetite for adornment and fascinating
complications. At the moment, after several years of tricky fusion
cooking by high-strung superchefs, a purifying wind seems to be
blowing across the culinary landscape. A new simplicity is in the
air, and it can be seen in the latest crop of cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Batali's SIMPLE ITALIAN FOOD: Recipes From My Two Villages
(Clarkson Potter, $30) makes the less-is-more case persuasively.
The first of the two villages in question is Borgo Capanne, on the
border between Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna, where Batali spent
several years cooking in a mountainside trattoria and developing a
passion for straightforward, robust cooking. The second is
Greenwich Village, where he runs two enormously popular
restaurants, Po and Babbo. ``Simple Italian Food'' offers the best
of both these worlds.
</P>
<P>
   In true Italian fashion, Batali blends rigor and insouciance. He
describes his food as ``Italian in sensibility, but made of local
ingredients -- some never used in classical Italian cooking.'' He
likes big flavors. He dislikes fuss and bother. If he can get away
with using three ingredients, he won't tack on a fourth. This
pared-down, workmanlike approach to Italian food -- viewers of
Batali's shows on the Food Network, ``Molto Mario'' and
``Mediterranean Mario,'' know him as the Bob Vila of chefs -- makes
``Simple Italian Food'' immensely appealing and endlessly useful.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that Batali lavishes attention on bruschetta,
that humblest of dishes. It can be a bore, nothing more than
chopped tomatoes and basil on a slice of grilled garlic bread, but
Batali comes up with a smooth, spicy topping of cannellini beans,
red pepper flakes, garlic and basil that's ridiculously easy to
make and almost impossible to stop eating.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it goes throughout the book. A warm terrine of
sausage, bell peppers, polenta and mozzarella could hardly be more
satisfying, and, as Batali suggests, it's the kind of dish that
cooks can sneak little surprises into, like Gaeta olives or bits of
fresh thyme. In another recipe, figs take a flying leap into the
sublime when they are stuffed with Gorgonzola and walnuts, then
baked until the cheese begins to bubble and the sugary liquid in
the figs oozes out, creating a sweet crust, the perfect
counterpoint to a paper-thin wrapping of prosciutto. No tricks
here, just brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO COOK EVERYTHING: Simple Recipes for Great Food
(Macmillan, $25) is a title with some swagger to it, but Mark
Bittman, a cookbook writer who contributes the Minimalist column to
the Dining section of The New York Times, delivers the goods. The
book, which runs to nearly 1,000 pages and contains about 1,500
recipes, strides the world of food in seven-league boots. The
familiar American classics are here, usually brought up to date
with new ingredients or techniques, but the book is a multicultural
feast, embracing ethnic foods that have become as American as apple
pie. A recipe for kimchi rubs shoulders with a recipe for kosher
dill pickles. Plain rice pilaf is followed by an international
pilaf delegation: pilaf with Indian spices, a Mediterranean-style
pilaf with wine and tomatoes, Mexican rice and a Caribbean-inspired
coconut rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Cook Everything'' is a one-volume encyclopedia, with
clearly presented information on cooking equipment and basic
techniques, valuable mini-essays on the ins and outs of basic
ingredients and illustrations showing how to shape a baguette, cut
a chicken into pieces or peel and segment an orange. At the same
time, the book has a point of view. ``Anyone can cook, and most
everyone should,'' Bittman writes in his introduction. He hates
fast food. He hates the very idea of ``gourmet'' food. His mission
is to preach the gospel of everyday cooking -- a gift, he writes,
``to which all humans are entitled.''
</P>
<P>
   By definition, ``How to Cook Everything'' is not flashy. There
is no way to put a glamorous spin on cabbage braised with onions or
a sandwich of sauteed chicken breast and spinach. Even the more
exotic offerings, like pheasant stewed with dried fruits and
vinegar
</P>
<P>
   or grilled squab Vietnamese-style, follow Bittman's quick and
easy approach. One of the book's most attractive features is its
pink-tinted boxes offering helpful hints or variations on basic
recipes, with titles like ``Twenty-six Vegetable Dishes That Will
Make Converts'' and ``Twelve Ideas for Filling Omelets.'' This is a
cookbook whose pages are destined to become stuck together from
constant use.
</P>
<P>
   The gospel of simplicity finds a genuine prophet in Christopher
Kimball, author of THE YELLOW FARMHOUSE COOKBOOK (Little, Brown,
$27.95). The book is as much about a vanishing way of life as it is
about food, and Kimball, the editor of Cook's Illustrated magazine
and the author of the aptly titled ``Cook's Bible,'' devotes a good
many pages to conjuring up the plain country pleasures of his life
in a small town in Vermont, where he and his wife do, in fact,
dwell in a yellow farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Readers will probably have different tolerance levels for
Kimball's heartfelt effusions and colorful country anecdotes. The
verb ``hunker'' shows up a lot. No one actually sits by the cracker
barrel, whittling and emitting the occasional ``Uh-yup,'' but it's
a close call. Tractors loom large as a cultural totem. You feel
certain that Kimball voted for Fred Tuttle.
</P>
<P>
   As Kimball repeats on several occasions, ``The Yellow Farmhouse
Cookbook'' is a country cookbook. It has recipes for macaroni and
cheese, noodle casserole, baked beans, ``cheap biscuits'' and
skillet potatoes. The list is a little deceptive because the author
has done some subtle modernizing, lightening and reworking some of
the heavier old recipes and throwing in a little wiggle here and
there, while remaining true to the farmhouse spirit. The recipes
are solid. The meatloaf is firm, juicy and flavorful. The master
recipe for baked beans (``the one I bring to the annual ox roast or
to potluck suppers around town'') comes out thick and pungent, just
sweet enough to make the herbs and spices count for something.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-ARCHITECTURE-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: for something.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What sets ``The Yellow Farmhouse Cookbook'' apart, however, is
Kimball's experimental streak. His baked bean recipe comes with two
charts, one showing how the beans turn out when subjected to eight
different cooking methods, another showing what happens when nine
different kinds of beans are cooked with or without a presoaking.
Even when he doesn't print a chart, Kimball usually clues the
reader in on his efforts to find, say, the perfect filling for a
lemon meringue pie. The charts and commentary on kitchen equipment
are easily worth the price of the book, even if it means spending a
few hours too many around the cider press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simplicity'' may not be the first word that comes to mind in
connection with Le Bernardin, the renowned, very expensive
Manhattan seafood restaurant, but it applies. Rare is the recipe
title in LE BERNARDIN COOKBOOK: Four-Star Simplicity (Doubleday,
$35) that's longer than six words. Sole with artichokes and pink
peppercorns. Pistou vegetable soup with mussels. Roast cod nicoise.
Spiced skate in sage broth. Recipe after recipe reflects the severe
philosophy that Gilbert Le Coze and his sister, Maguy Le Coze,
brought to Le Bernardin in Paris and later New York.
</P>
<P>
   The book is a work interrupted. Gilbert Le Coze had been working
on it for years when he died suddenly in 1994 at the age of 48,
leaving his sister to complete the cookbook and carry on with the
restaurant. She has written a touching introduction about their
childhood in Brittany, where they helped run the family hotel, and
of their struggles to establish Le Bernardin. Eric Ripert, who took
over the kitchen without missing a beat, has added many of his own
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Great restaurants do not easily produce great cookbooks. The
food at Le Bernardin is deceptively simple. It is subtle and
difficult to pull off unless the chef has access to the freshest
seafood and cooks with a very fine hand. There is nothing to hide
behind. The roast monkfish on a bed of bacon and savoy cabbage
clearly demonstrates that all it takes is one good idea to make a
dish sing. Gilbert Le Coze, an untrained, idiosyncratic chef, saw
that the smoke and salt in slab bacon and the earthy crunch of
cabbage would work beautifully with the meaty flesh of monkfish.
The dish is one of the restaurant's signatures. The home chef will
probably wonder what all the fuss is about. The poached bass with a
fragrant, tangy nage (an herb-infused broth), perked up with fresh
ginger, coriander and scallions, makes a pleasing spa dish, but
again, it all depends on the bass. The recipes work. Any home cook
can manage them. But for some kinds of cooking, you have to go to
the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, sometimes you don't. Against all rational
prediction, DESSERTS BY PIERRE HERME (Little, Brown, $35), by
Pierre Herme and the American cookbook writer Dorie Greenspan,
manages to translate the work of France's most celebrated pastry
chef onto the printed page and make it accessible to home cooks of
only average ability. Herme, not yet 40, is already a legend. The
son of a pastry chef, he apprenticed as a teen-ager with Gaston
Lenotre, went on to assume command of the pastry kitchen at Fauchon
in Paris and at 35 shifted operations to Laduree, Paris's oldest
pastry shop and tea salon. He is the only pastry chef to be
decorated as a Chevalier of Arts and Letters.
</P>
<P>
   How to explain, then, the perfectly simple lemon loaf cake? An
8-year-old child could make it. In fact, an 8-year-old child could
teach a 5-year-old child to make it, and both of them would kill to
eat it. The loaf is springy and moist, aglow with tart lemon flavor
and the richness of creme fraiche.
</P>
<P>
   The book abounds in easy-to-make pleasers like the lemon cake,
some of them with unexpected twists, like the coriander in the
coconut loaf cake or the apple tea that infuses a creme brulee.
Herme has a silly side too -- evident in his Rice Krispies treats
(the main ingredients are caramelized Rice Krispies and Nestle's
Crunch).
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the book includes a full lineup of showstoppers, like
the Chocolate Dome, a triple-threat chocolate dessert in which two
layers of chocolate cake are buried under an avalanche of chocolate
mousse, then smothered with a shiny chocolate glaze. For dieters, a
visit to the Dome will be a shameless joy ride through the very
heart of Sin City. Home hobbyists will find it a thrilling
architectural project, requiring patience but no great skill. The
instructions in the book are a model of clarity and precision, and
when Greenspan asserts in her introduction that ``none of the
recipes is beyond the capabilities of an average home baker,'' she
means it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elegant simplicity,'' Paula Wolfert writes, is the common bond
that unites the disparate recipes in her MEDITERRANEAN GRAINS AND
GREENS: A Book of Savory, Sun-Drenched Recipes (HarperCollins,
$27.50), a strenuously researched work that can be seen as a
travelogue, a culinary swashbuckler -- or the world's most
unbeatable collection of stories on the theme ``What I Did on My
Summer Vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfert, the author of ``The Cooking of the Eastern
Mediterranean'' and ``Paula Wolfert's World of Food,'' is the
foremost practitioner of extreme cookbook writing. Her endless
search for the old ways of cooking, and the old wisdom that goes
along with them, takes her across deserts, up twisting mountain
trails and into a thousand and one home kitchens from Spain to
Morocco to Turkey. If it involves grain or greens and it's in the
Mediterranean, Wolfert has been there and got the complete story.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the recipes really are simple. Polenta slices topped
with caramelized onions and grated Asiago cheese make a flavorful
first course, and who knew that a spicy paste of beet greens and
Swiss chard could achieve such heft and density? It's billed as a
dip, but it throws real weight around, and Wolfert's clever recipe
for seven-day preserved lemon means that you don't have to wait the
usual six weeks to try it out.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfert's insistence on absolute authenticity doesn't always
work in the reader's favor. Again and again, recipes seem to
include one ingredient that requires a quick trip to Tunis or
Istanbul. The description of Black Sea corn bread approaches
self-parody. Seeking to reproduce the recipe, which she encountered
in Turkey, Wolfert tried sweet corn from a local market. No good.
She tried toasted dried corn ordered by mail from Pennsylvania.
Ditto. She huddled with Zarela Martinez, the owner of the
restaurant Zarela in Manhattan, and hit on chacales, a dried corn
from Mexico. Closer, but still no good. ``All I can do is suggest
that, if you visit the fabulous Black Sea coast of Turkey, you stop
at the restaurant Kerasus in Giresun and try it for yourself,''
Wolfert writes.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion noted. That seems simple enough
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   William Grimes is a reporter for the Dining section of The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
