<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-GOTHIC-1000&AMP;A     12-03 2027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-GOTHIC-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE GOTHIC NOVELS BY CHARLES BROCKDEN BROWN
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIELAND: OR, THE TRANSFORMATION.
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR MERVYN: OR, MEMOIRS OF THE YEAR 1793.
</P>
<P>
   EDGAR HUNTLY: OR, MEMOIRS OF A SLEEP-WALKER.
</P>
<P>
   914 pp. New York: The Library of America. $35. &QL; 
 &UR; SOMETHING WICKED THIS WAY COMES &QL; 
 &UR; By CALEB CRAIN &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``As I am you despise me,'' Charles Brockden Brown wrote to a
friend and ex-roommate on New Year's Day 1798. ``How can I remove
the burthen of your scorn but by transforming myself into a new
being? . . . I shall die, as I have lived, a victim of perverse &AMP;
incurable habits.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's friends were used to his high-strung self-reproaches.
The playwright William Dunlap called them ``mysterious &AMP;
unintelligible.'' Another friend, Dr. Elihu Hubbard Smith, heard
them so often he lost patience. ``What, my friend, is the meaning
of all this?'' Smith once demanded of Brown. ``If you meant that we
should understand you, why were you not explicit?'' But it does not
pay to be explicit -- not even to your friends -- when you are
trying to get away with something. Brown was trying to get away
with writing novels. And in the American Gothic style that he would
pioneer, an air of mysterious criminality was a boon.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Brockden Brown was born to a family of Philadelphia
Quakers in 1771. Modern literary critics harp on the ``Brockden,''
probably because three names sound grander than two, and because,
at cocktail parties, it helps to distinguish him from Snoopy's
friend. But Brown himself may not have been so fond of his middle
name. He got it from his great-uncle Charles Brockden, whom
Benjamin Franklin once described as ``an eminent Scrivener or
Conveyancer.'' The original Charles Brockden was a paralegal --
like Melville's Bartleby, though not as lowly. Brockden researched
property titles and copied legal documents. Brown's father, too,
worked as a conveyancer, after he had failed as a merchant. The
family gave young Charles B. Brown an education so that he could
become something better -- a lawyer proper. But inadvertently, that
education introduced him to the writings of Jean-Jacques Rousseau
and Samuel Richardson, who sowed in Brown a wish to use words even
more freely and imperiously than lawyers do.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of the critic Leslie Fiedler, Brown became ``the
inventor of the American writer.'' Brown was the first to live a
myth that is still familiar, despite the Federalist-era particulars
of his case. A young man with delicate health (consumption) and a
strangely overkeen conscience (see the self-reproaches above)
shirks a responsible career (law) to run off to New York City,
where he camps out in the apartments of his radical friends
(deists, vegetarians and anarchists) and risks his life (during a
yellow fever epidemic) for no very good reason. After years of
unemployed vagrancy, when everyone has given up on him, he writes
masterly novels that earn him little money. He then gives up on
art, marries, takes a steady job, and dies in relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, a Library of America edition compacts into one
volume a career that spanned decades. But to publish three of
Brown's novels at once approximates the pace at which he wrote
them. In 1798, the year he burst forth, Brown wrote two and a half
novels. By 1801, when he gave up fiction, he had written seven (one
has been lost), as well as novel fragments and short stories.
</P>
<P>
   In 1846, the transcendentalist Margaret Fuller called Brown one
of ``the dark masters,'' because it was Brown's genius to descend,
precipitously, into the twisty maze of a lonely mind that was
trying to think its way back to the light. Fuller also noted that
Brown was something of a feminist, since he ``usually placed this
thinking royal mind in the body of a woman.'' Brown's ``Alcuin''
imagined a gender-neutral utopia and a critique of marriage based
on William Godwin's anarchist philosophy. Unfortunately, this
Library of America edition omits ``Alcuin,'' as well as Brown's
most woman-centered novel, ``Ormond,'' whose heroine not only
resists but stabs to death her would-be seducer, just moments
before her girlfriend breaks down the door to save her. But the
reader does get to meet Clara Wieland, the fierce protagonist of
Brown's first published novel. As Kevin Williamson, the
scriptwriter of ``Scream,'' could tell you, as a rule horror
heroines should be sturdy. If you think a character is braver than
you are, it is easier to let your guard down and sympathize with
her fear. Appropriately, the Clara of ``Wieland'' is strong, and
she protects her boundaries. She lives alone, rather than with her
brother's family, because she is ``an economist of pleasure.'' To
danger she is ``habitually indifferent.'' The first time the
Wieland family hear a voice they can't explain (they learn, much
later, it's a ventriloquist's), her brother Theodore feels dread,
but Clara feels only ``a thrilling and not unpleasing solemnity.''
Clara obeys another law of horror scripts, too: she is so out of
touch with her feelings that she has no idea whom she can trust --
and therefore, neither do we. Love, in Clara's narrowed eyes, is
``a passion that will never rank me in the number of its
eulogists.'' She also has the obligatory traumatic past: one night
while praying, her father spontaneously combusted.
</P>
<P>
   Clara is thoroughly modern. Ventriloquists, however, are no
longer scary, which makes it hard to read ``Wieland'' today with
the terror it deserves. When Clara addresses the villain Carwin, a
young man who knows how to throw his voice, as ``O most fatal and
potent of mankind,'' 20th-century grown-ups may giggle. For an
analogous modern threat, you would have to imagine someone who
knows your credit card numbers, has broken into your E-mail account
and has pocketed your cell phone. In the late 18th century,
selfhood was not digitized, and the human voice had the burden of
representing political agency, sexual reputation and financial
integrity. You were only as good as your word, and words were
supposed to give order to the world. It makes sense that an
18th-century set of words, the Constitution, should have balanced
power so exquisitely as not to have toppled in 200 years. Corrupted
by Godwin and Rousseau, Brown was experimenting with words that
failed to give order, or words that called up the disorder of
violent feelings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-GOTHIC-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: violent feelings) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Clara unmasks Carwin, she shrieks that ``he is able to
speak where he is not.'' She could be accusing her villainous
author and the suspect potential of his art. If voices can be split
from their subjects, if stories can be made up, then it becomes
impossible to know any social fact for sure. And so, in obedience
to another rule of the horror genre, Clara blames the wrong person.
Carwin the ventriloquist is no mastermind killer. He is just a
piece of news: in the future, the media will be unreliable,
striving for sensation rather than accuracy. Carwin is a geek. The
real monster is someone else, whom this new contingency pushes over
the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's writing can be clunky, almost as if he wants to call
attention to the inadequacy of words to experience. For example,
when Clara hears two voices in her closet debating whether to shoot
or strangle her, she explains that ``flight instantly suggested
itself as most eligible in circumstances so perilous.'' A sentence
like that is meant to take a little too long to read. It's the
literary equivalent of the movie actor pausing to tie his shoes
while the audience screams and the spree killer raises his ax.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ventriloquism, the peril in ``Arthur Mervyn'' is
accessible to modern readers -- eerily so. A plague of yellow fever
has descended on Philadelphia, poisoning society with distrust and
fear, just as young Arthur arrives in the city to find his fortune.
Arthur hires himself out as a scrivener, but in a plot twist that
hints at Brown's distaste for the family business, the man Arthur
copies for turns out to be a forger -- as well as an impostor,
adulterer, thief and murderer. In an odd congruence, Arthur's
panics, vigilance about secrets, imprudent idealizations and
doubtful moral choices foreshadow uncannily the modern experiences
of gay men who came to the metropolis in search of community, only
to find an epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur Mervyn'' may have the messiest plot that the Library of
America has ever published. In Part 1, Chapter 23, for example,
Arthur discovers in his master's attic something that ``furnished
matter which my curiosity devoured with unspeakable eagerness,''
but it is apparently too awful to share with the reader, who is
hurried on to the next shock, a house of prostitution. Brown does
not unravel his mysteries so much as distract you with new ones.
Brown's first biographer complained of ``this perpetual intrusion
of novelty to explain a novelty.'' However, these disruptions in
Brown's style -- the ``ambiguities, abruptnesses and dark
transitions,'' as he called them -- are Gothic effects. They are
designed to unnerve and compel. Brown's plots have loose ends, but
so do most nightmares. (The narrative logic of David Lynch's ``Lost
Highway'' was not exactly airtight, either.) When Brown writes that
all the men in the Mervyn family die before the age of 21, it may
irk a close reader that Brown ends his novel, happy marriage and
all, without either firing or unloading this Chekhovian rifle. But
an omen would not be quite so frightening if you knew for sure it
would come true.
</P>
<P>
   There is a similar logic of distraction and dislocation at work
in ``Edgar Huntly.'' The book starts as a whodunit. Edgar wants to
know who killed his friend Waldegrave. He spies on a man named
Clithero, who has the guilty habit of digging up and reburying a
box while he sleepwalks. Soon Edgar is chasing Clithero through a
jagged and confusing limestone landscape in Pennsylvania, then
sleepwalking himself, then slaughtering cougars, then slaughtering
Native Americans -- and we never find out who killed Waldegrave.
Brown's fugue feels genuine, nonetheless. There is nothing aimless
about Edgar's path from mourning to obsession to violence. It may
have been the path of Brown's own mind, as he tried to mourn his
friend Elihu Hubbard Smith. A sort of junior Ben Franklin, Smith
had provided the intellectual spark that ignited Brown's fit of
creativity. He supported Brown through his fallow years,
spiritually and financially, but then died of yellow fever halfway
through the writing of ``Arthur Mervyn.'' Like Waldegrave in
``Edgar Huntly,'' Smith left behind a cache of letters full of his
troubling, radical ideas. In Federalist America, that was not an
easy legacy to inherit, and Brown, like Edgar Huntly, survived it
by making a violent break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edgar Huntly'' was Brown's last Gothic novel. One of his
brothers suggested that readers disliked his books' gloom. Since
Brown was impatient to earn a living as a writer, he decided that
this was ``a sufficient reason for dropping the doleful tone and
assuming a cheerful one.'' Unintentionally, Brown's cheerful tone
was even more gruesome, and he soon dropped fiction altogether. He
should have persisted in gloom, which would eventually earn a
commercial reward that outran the avarice of his most flagitious
villains. Though he did not realize it, during his brief, doleful
career Brown succeeded in infecting America with his perverse and
incurable taste. The nation has been horrified ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Photo: Portrait of Charles Brockden Brown by James Sharples, a
detail from the jacket design of ``Charles Brockden Brown: Three
Gothic Novels.'' (Worcester Art Museum)
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Caleb Crain has written for Lingua Franca and American Literary
History. He is writing a book on early American friendships.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
