<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-EDITORS-CHOICE-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST BOOKS OF 1998
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best books of 1998, chosen by the eight editors of the Book
Review from 25 initial nominees, are three novels, two collections
of stories, three biographies, a scientific tour d'horizon and two
books about slaughter -- one concerning diplomacy to end it in the
Balkans and another asking why it happened and no one tried to stop
it in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance it might seem the editors are habit-bound. There
were also 11 books on the 1997 list, by four women and seven men --
and this year's 11 are by four women and seven men. Last year,
however, six of the writers had appeared on these lists previously.
This year only two are repeaters, a biographer of Victor Hugo and a
Canadian fiction writer making the list for the sixth time in 15
years. And one of the books here is its author's first -- a fairly
rare occurrence. All the fiction writers are North Americans; the
nonfiction authors are three Americans and three Britons.
</P>
<P>
   There is no history in the lot. That is unusual. But the
biographies contain a great deal of it, our reviewer called one
novel a personalizing of history, and the volume of science is a
biological history recounting four billion years. One biographer
has a passion for his subject's warts and poetry, but the two
others exhibit tendencies that may signal a sea change in our
mores: the life of a robber baron is eminently evenhanded and does
not try to incite mobs against him, and the life of a painter does
not peek once into the artist's bedroom. What is going on? Do these
writers not know this is the year of the Starr report?
</P>
<P>
   The boss's 1997 decree that editors' discussions must be civil
held this year, with a vengeance: everyone found flattering things
to say about every book nominated. The result was that the boss
expressed surprise that the majority did not make the cut when we
voted. Is that remark the first sound of the crumbling of civility?
Sweeter than a nightingale's song it was.
</P>
<P>
   Certain types of books, like letters and diaries, are not
eligible for nomination. It was not a remarkable year for them in
any case, although last month did see publication of ``I Will Bear
Witness,'' the disturbing diary of Victor Klemperer, a Jewish-born
German academician during the Nazi years.
</P>
<P>
   The best books are chosen from among those reviewed here since
last year's Holiday Books issue, and the summaries below are
generally drawn from the reviews. They are not included among
Notable Books of 1998, the list of which begins on page 65.
</P>
<P>
   BIRDS OF AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   Stories.
</P>
<P>
   By Lorrie Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   The two epigraphs of Lorrie Moore's third volume of short
stories are taken from poems on birds -- one by Amy Clampitt
questioning whether their songs mean anything and another by
Charlie Smith musing that grief cannot be translated into any
comprehensible language. Moore bypasses translating emotions. She
uses her fluid, colloquial sentences and her mordant wit to pry the
feelings of her characters loose inside the readers, where they
resist articulation and make us sense the depth of the predicaments
that most of her protagonists, usually women, fail to extricate
themselves from. The story is Moore's natural scale, and the best
in this collection, especially the last three, are stellar
performances. They all concern cancer -- the whole book is a
probing of mortality -- but even the most overpowering of them, the
already famous ``People Like That Are the Only People Here,'' has a
kind of steady hilarity amid its sublime darkness. Moore, like
Samuel Beckett, sees that nothing is funnier than unhappiness. Her
precise observation of characters' horror, or suffering, is often
delivered in prose that extorts laughter, and the mirth is a jolt
when it bursts out. Here is a measure of her mastery: in a reverie,
a mother discovers that despair over her baby's cancer has deprived
her of once formidable gifts of expression, and her search for
words to define her grief becomes a satire of Moore's own writing.
Now that is confidence, and it is fully justified.
</P>
<P>
   CLOUDSPLITTER
</P>
<P>
   By Russell Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Harper Flamingo.
</P>
<P>
   How do you survive upbringing by a fanatical prophet? You don't.
That is the story in Russell Banks's huge novel about the
abolitionist John Brown, whose 1859 raid at Harpers Ferry was one
of the fuses that detonated the Civil War. Banks seems to take his
cue from the assertion by some modern historians that history is
not an account of what happened but of what people think happened.
This domestic drama is told early in this century, nearly 50 years
after Harpers Ferry, by Brown's son Owen, a spiritual tag-along to
his father. Slowly, deliberately -- the storytelling often assumes
the leisure of timelessness -- Owen draws a magnificent picture of
the older Brown as an unmoved mover, a man of giant ambitions whose
biblical learning makes him eerily worldly; his absolute
righteousness is a religious mystery, not a neurosis, but a mystery
that still brings madness and death to his children and pain to
some escaped slaves for whom he is ready to kill if need be. Next
to him Owen appears emptier page by page; he knows he died with his
father on the scaffold. Banks's analysis is moral, not
psychological. The result is that the closer John Brown gets, the
more he too appears a ruin -- drawn by Piranesi, to be sure --
scorched and gutted by the purity of his vision. Fittingly, Banks
brings the whole world to witness Brown's fate: revolutions, the
fall of empires, the grandeur of the earth; indeed, the American
landscape is virtually a character, heralded by the book's title,
the name of a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE
</P>
<P>
   A Natural History of the First
</P>
<P>
   Four Billion Years of Life on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Fortey.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   At last a book that puts dinosaurs in their place -- and it
turns out to be a niche. Dinomania has nearly blinded the public to
the reality of evolution. But Richard Fortey, a British
paleontologist with an extensive range of humane learning and a
gift for arresting language, gives a coherent account of the
biological history of earth for four billion years, surprisingly
the first popular but authoritative one written by a professional.
This is no boring slog, but an adventure -- one comes away with a
reverence for the courage of the students of fossils -- in which we
meet weird creatures like rats as big as bears, dragonflies as big
as people, carnivorous kangaroos, poisonous sea octopods and
shell-crushing clams. Fortey does not present evolution as warfare,
but at times the development of species does look like an arms
race. In his words the evolution of whales from land animals is as
dramatic as some paleontological expeditions he describes. He
decries the mutation of natural history museums into entertainment
palaces, but his book has plenty of entertainment in the form of
digressions, literary excursions and surprising analogies -- enough
to irritate some readers. However, it is a survey of the facts of
life that reliably summarizes state-of-the-art knowledge from many
sciences, and it is written for readers with no science. It will
help them understand the specialized and often technical books on
evolution that make headlines but leave most people wondering why.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK--EDITORS-CHOICE-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: wondering why.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE LOVE OF A GOOD WOMAN
</P>
<P>
   Stories.
</P>
<P>
   By Alice Munro.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Munro is, in Virginia Woolf's phrase, one of the few
writers ``for grown-up people.'' Retrospection has always been
important in her work, but never has she been quite this autumnal,
acting as the mediator between the way people lived around 1960,
when all but one of these eight stories begin, and the way we live
now. She has an uncanny ability to make a reader realize that
people really think differently in different eras and that morals
may shift more quickly than customs. The price can be, as she puts
it in a story about a woman who leaves her family to be with her
new lover, a pain she will have to get used to until it is ``only
the past she's grieving for and not any possible present.'' Her
stories were always long, and now they grow longer. The title story
-- an extraordinary accomplishment even by Munro's soaring
standards -- is really a novella. Also, her conclusions have become
ever more open, without being inconclusive. A woman who thinks she
knows a quiet man's secret about a drowning death suddenly sees
that she faces ``an entirely different possibility'' from the one
that had grounded her until now -- her life will harden into a form
unimagined before. The large, enigmatic quality of this ending is
reflected in the other stories; they never end where we expect them
to and never take a turn without pain. They are like life, but
trying to detect their shifts in time or point of view is as
difficult as trying to remember where a change came in one's own
life that put one in another world altogether.
</P>
<P>
   THE POISONWOOD BIBLE
</P>
<P>
   By Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   Harper Flamingo.
</P>
<P>
   Zeal is mere termite food in Barbara Kingsolver's novel about a
white American clergyman's religious mission to the Congo in 1959.
At least ostensibly, this is Nathan Price's story. But it is told
by his wife, Orleanna, recollecting years later on an island in
Georgia, and her daughters, writing in Africa -- an epistolary
novel from places so remote the letters might have been sent to sea
in bottles. The picture of Price is merciless; Kingsolver implies
that his story is only the one men always tell. There is a load of
political message here, but ultimately this is a novel of
character; the women discover themselves as they lose faith in
Price and find another one, each according to her kind. The tone of
Orleanna's reminiscences is ironic, and Kingsolver's use of her
unconscious dissembling to reveal her pain is masterly; the mother
confides in Ruth May, her baby, the catalyst for breaking up the
family, and there is wisdom in every sentence. Rachel, the first
daughter, is the brainless soul of American materialism. A younger
sister, Adah, is hemiplegic, limping and nearly speechless, but a
verbal gymnast whose wit sets fire to her diary and lights up the
true nature of anyone she notices. Her twin, Leah, is the
conscience of the novel, always measuring the distance she has to
go before she is worthy of Africa. Perhaps the greatest character
is collective, the Congolese, whose perfect adaptation to the
harshness of their lives amid drought, hunger, pests and diseases
is simply beautiful. Their rejection of American salvation feels
triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   PRESTON FALLS
</P>
<P>
   By David Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   Boomers go bust in this scary novel, the whole generation of
them. Doug Willis is a New York public relations executive, and his
wife, Jean, a successful designer; they live in Westchester County
and own an old getaway house upstate. He is a maelstrom of male
vanity whose obsessive irony has left him with little but a
withering reflexive consciousness and the cynicism he hopes will
prevent him from going missing in the middle of life. Jean's form
of denial is keeping up an illusion of normality no matter what
happens; she is no wiser than he is, but she is nicer. She's also
nicer than their two children. When Willis takes two months off to
work on the old house, a family fight on the first weekend lands
him in jail, and the lawyer who springs him turns out to be a drug
trafficker who brings Willis into the trade. Briefly the dope is a
whiff of youth, but then Willis, in a panic about what he is doing,
flees the country life without telling Jean where he's going. From
there till the end of the novel the suspense about his fate is
brilliantly maintained. David Gates has a superb reporter's
precision, an analyst's ear, a teen-ager's glee in exposing
deception and a moralist's eye that is as unforgiving as Evelyn
Waugh's. Here the entire culture is deception, and as these
characters betray themselves ever deeper into it, the very
possibility of trust, of reliable understanding, is worn away. A
reader ends up wary of looking at the book again once he's finished
-- because anything could happen and whatever does is likely to be
irremediable.
</P>
<P>
   TITAN
</P>
<P>
   The Life of John D. Rockefeller, Sr.
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Chernow.
</P>
<P>
   Random House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, John D., we hardly knew ye.'' Sorry. It is not that Ron
Chernow unearths so much new information about John D. Rockefeller
in this biography, but his dispassionate portrait places the man in
so rich a context that we understand how he gathered more economic
power into his hands than anyone before or since, and, to a large
extent, we know why he did it. As we recognize the intelligence,
courage and vision of the man, his rapacity and cunning become more
alarming, not less. Chernow catches the early Rockefeller better
than anyone has -- the quick-witted young man who had developed by
the time he was 30 all the principles and techniques of his
business life. With mischievous humor Chernow points out that his
analysis of the American economy was Marxist, and he chose to solve
its problems with monopoly. The Government finally broke the
monopoly, but Rockefeller's organization of Standard Oil has been
the model of global business ever since, and the company's reach
and power taught the Government the vulnerability of the economy to
manipulation and the need for regulation. Finally, we see that
underlying all his achievements and philanthropies was a deep
religious commitment that was shared by his wife. It shaped them,
their family and, through the philanthropies, many religious,
educational and social institutions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK--EDITORS-CHOICE-3RDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: institutions.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TO END A WAR
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   Random House.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomacy is the grungiest job, if one judges from Richard
Holbrooke's account of the negotiations he led in 1995 to end years
of war in Bosnia. But it must be satisfying, because this
enthralling book is also a heartfelt call to America to use its
power when societies break down and to become a steady global force
resisting human rights abuses everywhere. It is filled with
anecdotes and sharp pictures of the wily Balkan leaders Holbrooke
had to deal with, as well as with shrewd and seldom flattering
analyses of the personalities and motivations of timid American and
NATO military commanders. Foreign diplomats who complain that
Holbrooke is a bulldozer in the polite corridors of international
politics may be right, but few could complain that he is gutless.
His re-creations of battles over principle and tactics with Western
generals and State Department and White House officials are
dramatic, and his description of a rudderless Administration during
the early days of his efforts is astonishingly candid, and
convincing. It is telling that the decision to use heavy air
strikes to bring the Serbs to the bargaining table was not a
careful calculation but an act of desperation. His combativeness
may offend the pinstripe set, but it is wonderfully refreshing on
the page; it is a very rare book on diplomacy that makes you feel
you were in the midst of it, and excited to be there.
</P>
<P>
   THE UNKNOWN MATISSE
</P>
<P>
   A Life of Henri Matisse:
</P>
<P>
   The Early Years, 1869-1908.
</P>
<P>
   By Hilary Spurling.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   Can this be a biography? It says next to nothing about Matisse's
sex life. More than half the population has lived its adult life
thinking biography means sex, but here if there's a mistress, well,
she's glimpsed in our passing among canvases, but we look at them,
not her. In fact, it is a smashing good biography, this first
volume taking us up to the painter's 40th year -- Matisse before he
was Matisse. Hilary Spurling's role is advocate, and she is a
formidable one. Her heroic research pays off; her sense of the time
and place, of Matisse's family and friends and competitors, of the
old teachers and Young Turks in the French art world, is admirable.
We are swept into all-night arguments among aspiring artists about
what art is, and into their dreams and prospects. We even fear for
Matisse -- will he ever find his style? The tentativeness of his
career is pointed up by the deaths or despair of contemporaries who
were his equals in art and by his failure into middle age to gain a
public. A painter's development is both an intimate and an open
transaction, and Spurling makes us feel its peril. By the end of
this volume, although Matisse is still largely unknown as an
artist, it is clear that having nothing to lose is increasingly a
spur to his creativity, and one begins to sense that the next door
he opens may be the last he has to.
</P>
<P>
   VICTOR HUGO
</P>
<P>
   By Graham Robb.
</P>
<P>
   W. W. Norton &AMP; Company.
</P>
<P>
   What a life! By the time he was 30, Victor Hugo had witnessed
Napoleon's Iberian campaigns and seen his fall; his poetry had made
him the lion of Paris, and his drama had touched off street
battles. He was elected to the French Academy and the Senate before
he started a steady march to the left that made him a political
force in the revolutionary period from 1848 to 1851, and he became
a national hero when, in exile, he led opposition to Napoleon III
for two decades. When he died in 1885, at 83, his funeral drew two
million people. His huge body of work in every genre has saturated
the French language with his expression. Even in life he
disappeared in a cloud of myths he created -- tribune of the
republic, the arch-romantic, the lifelong womanizer. Graham Robb
penetrates the myths and exposes the hidden impulses and hurts that
gave rise to them, and he has deep sympathy for the women, many of
them victims, who flocked around Hugo. His enthusiasm for Hugo's
writing is infectious, and we share his annoyance that there is no
good modern English translation of any of it. He tells us to put
down his book and read ``Les Miserables.'' Read both. Hugo lifts
spirits. Robb will open your mind and heart. His is the best
biography of Hugo in English and probably the best single-volume
one in any language.
</P>
<P>
   WE WISH TO INFORM YOU THAT
</P>
<P>
   TOMORROW WE WILL BE KILLED
</P>
<P>
   WITH OUR FAMILIES
</P>
<P>
   Stories From Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   By Philip Gourevitch.
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 the Government of Rwanda called on everyone in the Hutu
majority of the country to murder everyone in the Tutsi minority.
In 100 days 800,000 people were killed, most of them individually
cut down with knives. The daily killing rate exceeded that of the
Nazi Holocaust, and the deed was done mostly not by trained cadres
but by neighbors, co-workers, even family members. In the years
since, Philip Gourevitch, a New Yorker writer, has talked to
survivors, witnesses and participants to discover the origins and
personal motives for this collective crime. His grim book -- it is
his first -- lays a burden on the world's conscience. This
genocidal crime now has faces, names, personal psychologies. As we
encounter people involved in the massacre, we cannot pull back from
looking into their souls, and our own. As the title -- taken from a
letter by seven Christian pastors to their religious leader --
indicates, there were warnings. Those given to international
agencies, especially the United Nations, make dismal reading. And
American policy, which encouraged the United Nations to stay out of
internal conflicts, is sickening in retrospect. The history of
Belgian, French and British racism in colonial times bears on the
massacres too. Gourevitch withholds judgments, but his restraint
gives his book a subtle, subterranean power.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
