<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0697 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-GARDENING-100     12-03 2078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-GARDENING-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING 
 BY VERLYN KLINKENBORG
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judging from the pile of gardening books at my feet, this is the
season, or so publishers believe, when gardeners throw off the
petty restraints of practicality -- considerations like time, money
and space -- and unstay their imaginations. A gardener is always
trying to steep himself in the moment and to read the year ahead as
well. But the snowdrops are still very distant this month, too far
away to anticipate, and the midwinter moment is dark and
uninspiring. So instead of pretending to find salvation in seed
catalogues, instead of staring at the iced-over brush pile that
will neither compost nor burn, instead of refining the pencil
scratchings that pass for garden plans, why not open a book and
transport yourself to a softer hardiness zone, where gardens are as
extensive as the mind and labor is as cheap as thought?
</P>
<P>
   Some garden writers let you smell the earth in their prose.
Their paragraphs are damp at the knees from weeding. But if you're
going to set aside practicality, for now at least, you should do it
with an air about you. Take the tone from Beverley Nichols, whose
MERRY HALL, first published in 1951 and reissued this year by the
redoubtable Timber Press ($24.95), is the very model of gardening
insouciance. Nichols, an Englishman who wrote at least once about
everything and died in 1983 at 85, is nearly the Bertie Wooster of
gardening, and I say nearly only because some would consider it an
insult to be called the Bertie Wooster of anything. But about
Wooster, the creation of P. G. Wodehouse and the employer of
Jeeves, there was a carefree quality that resulted from the fact of
employing Jeeves and that sometimes chafed against it. The same is
true of Nichols, who purchased a small estate -- Merry Hall --
complete with a brilliant gardener named Oldfield, who was haunted
by memories of his previous employers. Nichols is a master of
hyperbolic understatement, an invaluable asset in the English
garden. ``I once owned a house with a 999 years lease,'' he writes,
``and it gave me an unbearable sense of being a sort of weekend
guest; it hardly seemed worthwhile planting the hyacinths.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a season of books that defy the reader to ignore the
labor that went into the gardens they depict, which is a thing no
actual human can do. Nature happens but gardens don't, and the
pleasure of large illustrated garden books is greatly increased if
you can adopt a Bourbon indifference to the matter of labor and
gaze over your demesne, like Louis XIV while Versailles was still a
construction site, without noticing the little people at work upon
it. And, of course, the invariable convention of large illustrated
garden books is to show completely uninhabited gardens, as if the
camera were king and everyone had suddenly ducked out of its regal
path. Three very different but worthwhile examples of this genre
are THE AGNELLI GARDENS AT VILLAR PEROSA: Two Centuries of a Family
Retreat (Abrams, $75), by Marella Agnelli; GARDEN ORNAMENT: Five
Hundred Years of History and Practice (Thames and Hudson, $29.95),
by George Plumptre; and AMERICAN DESIGNED LANDSCAPES: A
Photographic Interpretation (Spacemaker Press, $49.95), by Alan
Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Villar Perosa lies north of Turin and has belonged for nearly a
century and a half to the family that founded Fiat. ``The Agnelli
Gardens at Villar Perosa'' portrays both gardens and family, and it
is surprisingly effective at creating in the reader a sense of the
esthetic power of this place. I say surprising because at first the
photographs are more than a little irritating -- purposely blurred,
grainy, almost out of register. What succeeds in this book is not
the photographs per se but their cumulative arrangement, enfolding
the reader, by the end, in the grandness of these 25 Italian acres,
which are punctuated by hornbeams and at least one remarkable
araucaria.
</P>
<P>
   Grandness is the solitary note in Plumptre's ``Garden
Ornament,'' published in England several years ago and just
reissued in this country in paperback. By garden, Plumptre means
Vaux-le-Vicomte or Hadrian's Villa at Tivoli, and by ornament he
means a colossal, artfully concealed cruciform canal with a stone
Pomona oxidizing somewhere near. Luckily, he also means urns,
seats, pergolas and gates -- the sort of things a mortal might try
to incorporate in a garden plan. This book is a useful and visually
instructive history of architecture and ornament in gardens that
are the horticultural equivalent of the tower of Babel.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking of these three books is ``American Designed
Landscapes.'' Above all, it's a reminder of how powerful
black-and-white photography can be, even of gardens, and how well
it captures rhythmic effects in the landscape. This book contains
suites of photographs of places like Biltmore, Dumbarton Oaks,
Solana, Naumkeag and the Blue Ridge Parkway. The boundary between
garden and landscape is not a clear one, and Ward exploits the
ambiguity, especially in his photos of the Blue Ridge Parkway,
where a ribbon of asphalt gives the illusion that the surrounding
hills were laid in place solely to accentuate the beauty of the
highway's curves. These are eloquent photographs, and they are
excelled this season only by the work of Lynn Geesaman, a wonderful
photographer who has learned to use a ghostly saturation in her
black-and-white pictures of European gardens and landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Geesaman has just published her first book, called POETICS OF
PLACE (Umbrage Editions, $45), which is not to be missed by
gardeners or photographers. From such celestial terraces it is just
a short descent into the realm of gardens where one's personal
labor might actually be exploited from time to time, where you
might be required to tie up a wayward spray of this or disentangle
a stem of the other. No heavy lifting or spading yet, for this is
still a realm, as it was for Adam and Eve, demanding ``no more toil
/
</P>
<P>
   Of their sweet Gardening labour than suffic'd /
</P>
<P>
   To recommend cool Zephyr.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK--GARDENING-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: cool Zephyr.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On this shelf I would place ARTS AND CRAFTS GARDENS (Rizzoli,
$35), by Wendy Hitchmough, and REFLECTING NATURE: Garden Designs
From Wild Landscapes (Timber Press, $39.95), by Jerome and Seth
Malitz. The subject of ``Arts and Crafts Gardens'' is the several
late-19th- and early-20th-century gardeners, designers and
architects -- notably Gertrude Jekyll, William Robinson, Sir Edward
Lutyens and Philip Webb -- who, in places like Munstead Wood, Great
Tangley Manor and Hidcote, laid a new foundation under the English
and American sense of what a garden might do. There are passages in
these gardens that suggest intimacy -- domesticity, even -- but
horticultural opulence is what strikes the reader here, rather than
an imperial expanse of space, as at Tivoli, or a merely regal
profusion of statuary and squirting water, as at Versailles. This
is the kind of book in which you can simply luxuriate if you like
but which will also cause you to begin taking notes or to scratch
emendations into your garden plan.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of ``Reflecting Nature,'' an extended photo
essay, with text, by a father-and-son team from Colorado. The
conceit here -- and it is a good one -- is to show garden scenes
from unaided nature, like a seaweed pool in Acadia National Park or
a stand of aspen in Rocky Mountain National Park. In this beautiful
book, gardening is as much a trick of the eye -- a matter of
framing the composition -- as it is of design, construction, plant
selection and husbandry. ``Reflecting Nature'' is a study in visual
literacy for the experienced and inexperienced, the diligent and
the lazy alike.
</P>
<P>
   Nature -- or rather naturalness -- is also the dominant concern
in Penelope Hobhouse's NATURAL PLANTING (Holt, $45) and Ann
Lovejoy's NATURALISTIC GARDENING: Reflecting the Planting Patterns
of Nature (Sasquatch Books, $21.95). These books presume that
readers will get dirt under all their nails and perhaps sore backs
from working with garden forks. The emphasis in both these fine
books is the same: to help create gardens with a natural feel,
where the idea of ``natural'' pays homage to Jekyll and Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Any work by Hobhouse, a recent recipient of the Victoria Medal
of Honor from the Royal Horticultural Society, leads naturally to a
mention of works by two extraordinary plantsmen who also received
that medal: MY GARDEN IN AUTUMN AND WINTER (Timber Press, $24.95),
by E. A. Bowles -- a facsimile of the 1915 edition -- and CUTTINGS
FROM MY GARDEN NOTEBOOKS (Sagapress, $39.95), by Graham Stuart
Thomas. These are the kinds of books in which the ordinary gardener
peers over the horizon, so to speak, and begins to glimpse what it
means to devote one's being to plants. Few of us have friends of
whom we can speak as knowingly or affectionately as Bowles speaks
of crocuses. As for Thomas, he reminds you that there is no pursuit
where emotion and intellect are quite so entwined as gardening. I
can't avoid recommending the 1997 reprint of Thomas's TREES IN THE
LANDSCAPE (Sagapress, $35). There, the meaning of a lordly eye,
with dominion over all it sees, is perfectly demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   From naturalness it is a mere step to wildness, and that is the
subject of Philip Keenan's WILD ORCHIDS ACROSS NORTH AMERICA: A
Botanical Travelogue (Timber Press, $39.95). This is a fascinating
book, both as a study of wild orchids and as a study of enthusiasm
itself. The author has traveled all over this continent in search
of wild orchids, to which he devotes a gaze that is unwavering.
This book is likely to make mildly skeptical readers feel as though
they had been born with no eyes, and no passion either.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other fine books this season, of course,
including Patrick Taylor's MAKING GARDENS (Timber, $29.95) and
Jennifer Potter's SECRET GARDENS (Trafalgar Square, $29.95), but I
want to close with gardening in literature, as represented by two
fine anthologies: Jamaica Kincaid's MY FAVORITE PLANT: Writers and
Gardeners on the Plants They Love (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $18)
and Jane Garmey's WRITER IN THE GARDEN (forthcoming from Algonquin,
$18.95). But the work I have particularly in mind is Henry
Mitchell's ON GARDENING (Houghton Mifflin, $24).
</P>
<P>
   ``On Gardening'' is the final collection of Mitchell's gardening
essays, which were published in The Washington Post until he died
in 1993. (The first two collections are called ``The Essential
Earthman'' and ``One Man's Garden.'') Every gardener has a folly,
an imponderable affection, and the prose of Henry Mitchell is mine,
if loving prose this well made is foolish at all. Some writers
spend their whole lives searching for subjects, and some writers,
like Mitchell, make of one subject a whole life, though to call
gardening one subject is a little unfair. The literature of
gardening is filled with towering figures -- towering and, at
times, a little austere, a little too ready to sack the countryside
and frighten the peasants. But whatever Mitchell knew about plants
and gardens -- and he knew plenty -- he had to bring to bear in the
columns of a newspaper and in a small backyard garden in
Washington. He alludes to this garden in a remarkable variety of
tones. Some days it was everything a reasonable man could expect in
life -- a place where plants would grow. Some days it was nothing
but a hot catwalk and a dry brick patch. Even at its worst, it was
better, in Mitchell's opinion, than trying to garden in England's
miserable climate. To him, gray clashes with everything.
</P>
<P>
   It's always tempting to quote Mitchell, but once you start it's
hard to know where to stop. He is the gardener for all of us who
know better but do worse, and a quotation from him on that topic
will bring us full circle. ``Hyacinths,'' he wrote in a December
column, ``should be planted in October, in friable, rich, well-dug
earth that crumbles easily when rubbed in the fist. So sue me.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Verlyn Klinkenborg writes editorials for The Times. He is the
author of ``Making Hay'' and ``The Last Fine Time.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
