<HEADER>
A0698 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-FICTI     12-03 6824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-FICTION&AMP;POETRY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTABLE FICTION &AMP; POETRY OF 1998
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This list has been selected from books reviewed since the
Holiday Books issue of December 1997. It is meant to suggest some
of the high points in this year's fiction and poetry. The books are
arranged alphabetically under genre headings. The complete reviews
of these books may be found at The New York Times on the Web:
www.nytimes.com/books.
</P>
<P>
   FICTION &AMP; POETRY
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT A BOY. By Nick Hornby. (Riverhead, $22.95.) A funny,
intelligent, generous novel in which an incompetent man and an
impossible youth learn to depend on each other.
</P>
<P>
   ALIENS OF AFFECTION. By Padgett Powell. (Holt, $22.50.) A
collection of stories about characters who reject the bland
conformity of contemporary life.
</P>
<P>
   THE ALL-TRUE TRAVELS AND ADVENTURES OF LIDIE NEWTON. By Jane
Smiley. (Knopf, $26.) A historical novel of both action and ideas,
whose heroine, a determined abolitionist, sets out to subvert
slavery in person before the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   AN AMERICAN KILLING. By Mary-Ann Tirone Smith. (Marian
Wood/Holt, $23.) In the author's fifth novel, a Washington
true-crime writer investigates the death of her lover and discovers
the modern face of evil.
</P>
<P>
   AND BOTH SHALL ROW: A Novella and Stories. By Beth Lordan.
(Picador USA, $21.) A collection, in an assured and distinctive
voice, about relentlessly unglamorous characters whose experiences
go beyond words and cannot be named, though Lordan is able to
describe them.
</P>
<P>
   THE ANTELOPE WIFE. By Louise Erdrich. (Harper Flamingo, $24.)
Multiple intertwined narratives and similar family relations shape
this novel of bliss and bale among American Indians on the big
bleak prairie.
</P>
<P>
   THE ARCHIVIST. By Martha Cooley. (Little, Brown, $22.95.)
Engagement with historic evil (the Holocaust) and rejection or
avoidance of the past are the poles of this absorbing first novel.
</P>
<P>
   ARK BABY. By Liz Jensen. (Overlook, $24.95.) The author's
disorderly second novel satirically examines Darwinism, progress
and the notion of scientific certainty through 150 years of
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ARMADILLO. By William Boyd. (Knopf, $24.) Everything goes wrong
for the hero of Boyd's latest novel, an Englishman of Gypsy descent
who discovers zemblanity (the opposite of serendipity) in today's
multicultural London hustle.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOBIOGRAPHY OF RED: A Novel in Verse. By Anne Carson. (Knopf,
$23.) A compulsively readable hybrid work by a scholar and poet who
reimagines a lost Greek poem into a destructive love affair between
Hercules and an American boy who is also (somehow) a winged red
monster.
</P>
<P>
   bad chemistry. By Gary Krist. (Random House, $24.) Featuring a
headless body, inflammable dogs, a 14-year-old sleuthing
techno-nerd and Beatrix Potter, this first novel is as much a
meditation on the power of secrets as it is a detective story.
</P>
<P>
   BARNEY POLAN'S GAME: A Novel of the 1951 College Basketball
Scandals. By Charley Rosen. (Seven Stories, $23.95.) Barney, a
sports columnist for The Brooklyn Sentinel, is an old-fashioned
guy, a would-be novelist whose misfortune is excessive proximity to
his material when the corruptions of the gray 1950's arrive.
</P>
<P>
   BARNEY'S VERSION. By Mordecai Richler. (Knopf, $25.) Like much
of Richler's fiction, this novel seeks to evaluate Jewishness,
Canadianhood and the struggle for personal integrity; but this time
it's told by a hero whose memory is failing, making the moral task
all the harder.
</P>
<P>
   BECH AT BAY: A Quasi-Novel. By John Updike. (Knopf, $23.) The
third, quite possibly the last, of Updike's Bech satires, starring,
since 1970, the Jewish anti-Updike who incarnated aspects of the
literary scenery when the real Updike was still liable to being
written off as a provincial WASP.
</P>
<P>
   BERTRAM COPE'S YEAR. By Henry Blake Fuller. (Turtle Point,
paper, $14.95.) Written and self-published by a Chicago novelist
nearly 80 years ago, this elegant satirical novel deals with lots
of illicit sex without saying anything naughty.
</P>
<P>
   BIG GIRLS DON'T CRY. By Fay Weldon. (Atlantic Monthly, $24.)
With her usual sly wit, the author uses the history of a feminist
publishing house to ponder if the women's movement was worth all
the bother.
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHDAY LETTERS. By Ted Hughes. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $20.)
A collection of poems by Sylvia Plath's widower, who himself died
this year, but not before giving his side of their tempestuous
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   THE BLACK FLOWER: A Novel of the Civil War. By Howard Bahr.
(Owl/Holt, paper, $12.) The malignity of war is captured with
post-Vietnam graphic ferocity in this novel about a group of
Mississippi soldiers who are much worse than decimated in an
assault on a Federal line.
</P>
<P>
   BLINDNESS. By Jose Saramago. (Harcourt Brace, $22.) A novel by
this year's Nobel laureate in literature, written in polyphonic
paragraphs; in it, a plague of contagious blindness is harrowing
far beyond its allegorical function of inability or unwillingness
to see.
</P>
<P>
   BLIZZARD OF ONE: Poems. By Mark Strand. (Knopf, $21.) A
distinguished contemporary sets the purity of his language against
an essentially godless, Wallace Stevensish universe that returns
our examination with a blank stare.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE LIGHT. By Walter Mosley. (Little, Brown, $24.) The author
abandons Easy Rawlins in favor of a quasi-science-fictional
meditation about race relations.
</P>
<P>
   BODY PARTS: Stories. By Jere Hoar. (University Press of
Mississippi, $26.) Mythologies and manners of the 20th-century
American South, by a keen and fearless observer -- brave enough to
live in Faulkner's Oxford and cheeky enough to create an entirely
new Snopes.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOY. By Naeem Murr. (Houghton Mifflin, $22.) A man seeks out
his abandoned illegitimate son and has the bad luck to find him in
this dark, intelligent novel that evokes the damage scared people
can do either by accident or by design.
</P>
<P>
   BRAIN STORM. By Richard Dooling. (Random House, $25.) A tightly
packed thriller whose hero, a lawyer who justifiably hates his
loathsome client, becomes sexually involved with a reductive brain
researcher who can explain anything away.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget jones's diary. By Helen Fielding. (Viking, $22.95.)
Though this novel's hilarious British heroine ruthlessly monitors
her incoming calories (most from alcohol), she still knows the
anguish of dateless Saturdays and unwaxed legs.
</P>
<P>
   BRINGING OUT THE DEAD. By Joe Connelly. (Knopf, $23.) A first
novel about a paramedic who is driven to despair by the devastation
he witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   CARTESIAN SONATA: And Other Novellas. By William H. Gass.
(Knopf, $24.) The philosopher-novelist continues his challenge to
conventional fictional forms.
</P>
<P>
   CAVEDWELLER. By Dorothy Allison. (Dutton, $24.95.) A
rock-and-roll singer returns home to Georgia and the children she
abandoned, in the second novel by the author of ``Bastard Out of
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATION. By Harry Crews. (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23.) In his
16th novel, Crews ponders the effect of a voluptuous teen-ager
named Too Much on a retirees' trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   CHARMING BILLY. By Alice McDermott. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$22.) A life distorted by a lie, and by the expectations of others,
is the matter of this eloquent, unsettling novel, set among
Irish-Americans in New York; the winner of a National Book Award in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   CITIES OF THE PLAIN: Volume 3, ``The Border Trilogy.'' By Cormac
McCarthy. (Knopf, $24.) The concluding volume of the current cowboy
saga by this stubborn, long-winded, fascinating writer (many of his
characters are like that too).
</P>
<P>
   THE COAST OF GOOD INTENTIONS: Stories. By Michael Byers.
(Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, paper, $12.) Gently resigned stories,
melancholy and hopeful at once, about loss and accommodation in the
lives of very different kinds of people.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-FICTION&AMP;POETRY-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: kinds of people.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COLLECTED FICTIONS. By Jorge Luis Borges. (Viking, $40.) The
first complete English version of all the fictional work of the
father of magic realism in a single voice, that of Andrew Hurley, a
professor of English at the University of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   CORDELIA UNDERWOOD: Or the Marvelous Beginnings of the Moosepath
League. By Van Reid. (Viking, $24.95.) An amiable and richly
inhabited first novel, re-creating Maine in the summer of 1896,
when people were cheerier, wild animals tamer and villains more
innocuous than now.
</P>
<P>
   CUPID AND DIANA. By Christina Bartolomeo. (Scribner, $22.) A wry
and provoking novel, set in Washington, in which, for a change,
it's the women (including the narrator) who are into cheating,
infidelity and the sacrifice of love to business.
</P>
<P>
   DAMASCUS GATE. By Robert Stone. (Houghton Mifflin, $26.) A
pyrophoric mix of extreme religious persuasions explodes in the
face of Stone's skeptical hero in Jerusalem's Old City.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH IN SUMMER. By William Trevor. (Viking, $23.95.) The child
of a man who has never known love is abducted by a woman who longs
for love with something like madness in this novel by an author
expert in malformations of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   THE DOWER HOUSE. By Annabel Davis-Goff. (St. Martin's, $22.95.)
Snobbery, need, coldness, inertia and purposelessness intersect in
this frankly old-fashioned novel about the Anglo-Irish aristocracy,
living on leftovers in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   DREAMER. By Charles Johnson. (Scribner, $23.) A novel that
illuminates the life and work of Martin Luther King Jr. by
exploring the soul of an ordinary man who is King's physical
double.
</P>
<P>
   DUSK. By F. Sionil Jose. (Modern Library, paper, $12.95.) A
microhistorical novel in which the author, focusing on the trials
of a single family, educates the reader in Philippine history and
in how the people of that country see themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ENDURING LOVE. By Ian McEwan. (Nan A. Talese/Doubleday, $23.95.)
Another eerie novel by the author of ``The Cement Garden''; this
time the tour de force involves a science writer who is the victim,
or beneficiary, of a homoerotic religious obsession he has done
nothing to deserve.
</P>
<P>
   THE ENGRAFTED WORD: Poems. By Karl Kirchwey. (Marian Wood/Holt,
cloth, $23; Owl/Holt, paper, $13.) Typically steeped in myth,
history and literature (without neglecting doses of sensuality),
these poems propose that the transformative word of poetry can save
souls.
</P>
<P>
   EUCALYPTUS. By Murray Bail. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $23.) A
magic novel from Australia, in which a homesteader's daughter must
marry, fairy tale fashion, the first suitor who can correctly
identify every eucalyptus species; a wandering storyteller breaks
the rule.
</P>
<P>
   EVENING. By Susan Minot. (Knopf, $23.) An elegant, assured novel
that tells the story of a woman's life in two narratives: one as
she remembers her life, one as she passes from it.
</P>
<P>
   THE EVERLASTING STORY OF NORY. By Nicholson Baker. (Random
House, $22.) The novelist turns his magnifier on the mentation of a
9-year-old girl protagonist; the details, and the comedy they
yield, are sharp and clear.
</P>
<P>
   THE EVOLUTION OF JANE. By Cathleen Schine. (Houghton Mifflin,
$24.) A woman named Jane and the elements of evolution are both
shrewdly rendered in a novel that unconventionally uses large
principles to illuminate a particular life.
</P>
<P>
   THE FARMING OF BONES. By Edwidge Danticat. (Soho, $23.) A
sobering novel by a Haitian-American, set in Hispaniola in 1937
during a bloody eruption of the endless hostility between Haiti and
its neighbor, the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   THE FARM SHE WAS. By Ann Mohin. (Bridge Works, $22.95.) A novel
about farm life that is a celebration of sounds and sensations.
</P>
<P>
   FINAL VINYL DAYS: And Other Stories. By Jill McCorkle.
(Algonquin, $18.95.) Exasperating characters treated with knowing
humor are the marks of this collection of stories.
</P>
<P>
   FLYING LEAP: Stories. By Judy Budnitz. (Picador USA, $20.) A
first collection, by a 26-year-old cartoonist for The Village
Voice; her narratives are bold enough to posit a man in a dog suit
who is able to pass, or a high school pep squad that immolates
itself out of sheer enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Freedomland. By Richard Price. (Broadway, $25.) In an almost
obsessively realistic novel that echoes the Susan Smith case,
long-simmering racial tensions erupt in a New Jersey city after a
dazed and bleeding white woman claims her 4-year-old son was
abducted by a black carjacker.
</P>
<P>
   GAIN. By Richard Powers. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25.) An
erudite, penetrating novel that deals with the evolution of
American industry and commercial practice over two centuries, and
with one of its casualties, a woman who (rightly or wrongly) blames
chemicals for her cancer.
</P>
<P>
   GERTRUDE OF STONY ISLAND AVENUE. By James Purdy. (Morrow,
$19.95.) In Purdy's 16th novel, a woman researches the life of her
late daughter, a sexually flamboyant artist.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING IT IN THE HEAD: Stories. By Mike McCormack. (Holt, $23.)
An Irish writer's first collection; funny, fantastical tales that
trample inventively on the toes of sanctimonious news media,
provincial pride and the 20th century itself.
</P>
<P>
   GHOST TOWN. By Robert Coover. (Holt, $24.) The master of
hypertext flings cinematic cliches into the fever-dream narration
of a nameless cowpoke's misadventures as he bears his solitude
through a terrain of dry rocks and dead things.
</P>
<P>
   THE GIANT, O'BRIEN. By Hilary Mantel. (Marian Wood/
</P>
<P>
   Holt, $22.) An early mad scientist meets a late, unviable,
enormous Irish spinner of tales in a novel that grants the future
to the scientist but the heart to the bard.
</P>
<P>
   THE GIRL IN THE FLAMMABLE SKIRT: Stories. By Aimee Bender.
(Doubleday, $21.95.) Confused, libidinous young women who aren't
sure what they want or how to get it are frequent in the population
of this insouciant first collection.
</P>
<P>
   GLORIE. By Caryn James. (Zoland, $24.) A novel, by the chief
television critic of The Times, that investigates character and the
fear of loss through its widowed octogenarian protagonist's
struggle to avoid selling her home.
</P>
<P>
   GOD IS MY BROKER: A Monk-Tycoon Reveals the 7 Laws of Spiritual
and Financial Growth. By Brother Ty with Christopher Buckley and
John Tierney. (Random House, $20.) A fictional sendup of self-help,
by two experienced senduppers.
</P>
<P>
   GOING FAST: Poems. By Frederick Seidel. (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $22.) With an eye on the millennium, Seidel aims his
astute, ironic wit at targets like nuclear testing, technocracy and
vanished pleasures; but he still loves New York.
</P>
<P>
   GRAND CENTRAL WINTER: Stories From the Street. By Lee Stringer.
(Seven Stories, $21.95.) Narratives of the down-and-out, by a
writer whose career began when he found a pencil in a crawl space
under Grand Central Terminal, where he was living at the time; his
first book.
</P>
<P>
   Groundwork. by Robert Welch. (Blackstaff/Dufour, paper, $19.95.)
The essence of the Irish experience, distilled into a masterly
family saga encompassing four centuries and 22 characters; a
kinship chart is thoughtfully provided.
</P>
<P>
   THE HALF-LIFE OF HAPPINESS. By John Casey. (Knopf, $25.) This
spacious novel's hypersensitive and often uncharitable narrator
analyzes the failure of her parents' marriage as her mother falls
in love with another woman and her father grows becalmed in the
everyday.
</P>
<P>
   THE HANDSOME SAILOR. By Larry Duberstein. (Permanent Press,
$25.) Herman Melville is the hero of this novel, which summons in
lyrical detail the Victorian New York he lived in after his
commercial and critical failure as a writer. There are love
affairs, but not with a sailor.
</P>
<P>
   THE HEALING. By Gayl Jones. (Beacon, $23.) A wry and funny novel
in which violence and paranoia are banished by a kind of faith that
is happy with illogic and depends (like analysis) on free
association toward insight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-FICTION&AMP;POETRY-3RDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: toward insight.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY'S CHAIR. By Michael Palin. (Thomas Dunne/St. Martin's,
$23.95.) Written by a former member of Monty Python's Flying
Circus, this novel tells the story of a sweet-tempered, prudish
postal worker who suddenly goes batty.
</P>
<P>
   Horace Afoot. By Frederick Reuss. (MacMurray &AMP; Beck, $25.) The
hero of this debut novel lives as a modern-day ascetic in a town
called Oblivion and, in middle age, makes his first tentative stabs
at human connection.
</P>
<P>
   HOURMASTER. By Christophe Bataille. (New Directions, $17.95.) A
French novelist's fable without a moral, in which 218 clocks drown
out the hiss of nothingness in an isolated seaside castle.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOURS. By Michael Cunningham. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$22.) A delicate, subtle, perhaps eerie novel with three parallel
stories: one that echoes Virginia Woolf's ``Mrs. Dalloway,'' one
involving Woolf herself and one about an American woman who reads
``Mrs. Dalloway.''
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSE GUN. By Nadine Gordimer. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$24.) An elegantly conceived political novel of physical violence
and spiritual turmoil that assault a liberal white family in
post-apartheid South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSE OF SLEEP. By Jonathan Coe. (Knopf, $24.) A witty,
intricate novel (Coe's second) whose four chief characters live in
engaging, unpredictable communion with dreams.
</P>
<P>
   HULLABALOO IN THE GUAVA ORCHARD. By Kiran Desai. (Atlantic
Monthly, $22.) Chaos -- perhaps intended to stand for the larger
chaos of India itself -- is the prevailing mode in this lively,
imaginative novel about a cracked youth who becomes an object of
worship in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ICY SPARKS. By Gwyn Hyman Rubio. (Viking, $24.95.) Icy, the
hyperarticulate heroine of this first novel, struggles with her
personal handicaps (she's an orphan with Tourette's syndrome) in a
world that's in no hurry to help her out.
</P>
<P>
   IDENTITY. By Milan Kundera. (HarperCollins, $23.) The naive hero
sends anonymous love letters to his lover, setting off events that
illuminate their psychological obsessions and miscommunication.
</P>
<P>
   I KNOW THIS MUCH IS TRUE. by Wally Lamb. (Regan
Books/HarperCollins, $27.50.) This novel's protagonist, who has
already suffered life's most devastating losses, must somehow rally
to care for his equally bereft schizophrenic brother.
</P>
<P>
   I MARRIED A COMMUNIST. By Philip Roth. (Houghton Mifflin, $26.)
A tender, harsh, witty novel whose title refers to a bitter,
hostile book written by the female half of a ruined marriage (sound
familiar?), and whose principal action, recalled in the present,
takes place in the dire focus of the age of McCarthyism.
</P>
<P>
   IN ANOTHER PLACE, NOT HERE. By Dionne Brand. (Grove, $24.) A
first novel, passionately attentive to nuance, that explores the
transit between the Caribbean and North America through a love
affair between two women.
</P>
<P>
   INGRATITUDE. By Ying Chen. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $20.) This
author's third novel, short, resolute and tightly strung, is
narrated from the grave by a woman who killed herself in order to
make her mother suffer (and to make a point about women in
traditional Chinese culture).
</P>
<P>
   THE INLAND ICE: And Other Stories. By Eilis Ni Dhuibhne.
(Blackstaff/Dufour, paper, $16.95.) Fiction, graced with
head-versus-heart knowingness, about people on whom Ireland imposes
timid choices and straitened lives.
</P>
<P>
   AN INSTANCE OF THE FINGERPOST. By Iain Pears. (Riverhead, $27.)
This intricate literary thriller, elaborately plotted and
superlatively researched, casts real Restoration figures in a
mystery about the murder of an Oxford don (and a much greater crime
to which it is adjoined).
</P>
<P>
   THE IRON TRACK. By Aharon Appelfeld. (Schocken, $21.) Tracing
for some 40 years the vanished outposts of Jewish life in central
Europe, Appelfeld's narrator and protagonist compresses big themes
of revenge, recovery and the weight of history into this short
Israeli novel.
</P>
<P>
   JACK MAGGS. By Peter Carey. (Knopf, $24.) A sly, enticing,
sophisticated sort of paranovel, in which the characters are
fun-house images of real and imaginary people in the life and work
of Dickens, especially those associated with ``Great
Expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   KAATERSKILL FALLS. By Allegra Goodman. (Dial, $23.95.) Little
actually happens in this first novel, but the author discovers form
and sensibility in the small excitements and grand rhythms of life
in an Orthodox Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   KALIMANTAAN. By C. S. Godshalk. (Marian Wood/Holt, $25.) A
formidably imaginative first novel in which a man's idealized love
for his dead mother powers British imperialism in Borneo.
</P>
<P>
   KAROO. By Steve Tesich. (Harcourt Brace, $24.) A Hollywood
script doctor destroys another man's great film to further a
personal agenda in this posthumous novel by the screenwriter of
``Breaking Away.''
</P>
<P>
   THE KNIFE THROWER: And Other Stories. By Steven Millhauser.
(Crown, $22.) Stories whose characters -- dreamers, artists,
illusionists -- all run to excess as the author explores our
responses to the products and projections of our own minds.
</P>
<P>
   THE LADIES FROM ST. PETERSBURG: Three Novellas. By Nina
Berberova. (New Directions, $19.95.) A posthumous collection,
characterized by lucid prose, deft characterization and an
unromantic gaze at the author's Russian homeland.
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST KING OF SCOTLAND. By Giles Foden. (Knopf, $25.) The
nonhero of this ambitious first novel is a Scottish doctor whose
consciousness of his moral mediocrity doesn't enable him to
separate himself from his employer, the Ugandan dictator Idi Amin.
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST RESORT. By Alison Lurie. (Holt, $22.) The place the
world ends in this sparkling, smart novel is Key West, where a
number of exemplary type characters have to stop and wait for
whatever they are running from to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   LEAVING EARTH. By Helen Humphreys. (Metropolitan/Holt, $22.) A
novel, by a Canadian poet, in which two women try to set a record
for endurance flying; as the days mount, the real world recedes
from the view of the world aloft.
</P>
<P>
   LEONARDO'S HORSE. By R. M. Berry. (FC2 Press, paper, $13.95.)
Leonardo da Vinci is cast as a failure, a great prodigy of little
accomplishment, in a novel-within-this-novel (the fictitious
author, an academic, isn't doing so well himself).
</P>
<P>
   LIKE NEVER BEFORE. By Ehud Havazelet. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$23.) Tense, unpredictable short stories about two Jewish
generations; their principal themes include the unforgivingness of
time and the wasting of love.
</P>
<P>
   THE LONG FALLING. By Keith Ridgway. (Houghton Mifflin, $22.) An
Irish writer's first novel, which turns the quite understandable
murder of a truly horrible husband into a meditation over whether
taking another's life is ever justifiable.
</P>
<P>
   LOST IN TRANSLATION. By Nicole Mones. (Delacorte, $23.95.) An
American bigot's daughter becomes entranced with Chinese culture
and Chinese men in a first novel that inspects two great cultures
and their invincible convictions of superiority to each other.
</P>
<P>
   LOST LAKE: Stories. By Mark Slouka. (Knopf, $21.) Beautiful and
mysterious fiction with a dreamlike sense of life in death and
death in life, set in a summer community in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   A LOVER'S ALMANAC. By Maureen Howard. (Viking, $24.95.) Taking
as her model the ``Old Farmer's Almanac,'' the novelist plumbs the
shallows of millennial irrationality as she follows two young
members of Generation X into the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-FICTION&AMP;POETRY-4THTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: year 2000.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Loves that bind. by Julian Rios. (Knopf, $24.) In this
epistolary novel first published in Spain, the narrator dreamily
chronicles a slew of past sexual encounters in a series of letters
to his (current) beloved, for whom he is searching in London.
Beloved's response is not recorded.
</P>
<P>
   MACKEREL BY MOONLIGHT. By William F. Weld. (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$23.) A political novel and a suspense novel (same novel) by the
former Governor of Massachusetts that profits by formidable skill
in deft and devious storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   A MAN IN FULL. By Tom Wolfe. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $28.95.)
Righteous stuffing of everything known about Atlanta into a huge,
audacious comic novel that exposes Old South values to a new world
in which they are hopelessly vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   MAN OR MANGO? A Lament. By Lucy Ellmann. (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $22.) A rambling rant, sometimes very funny, about love and
loneliness; its heroine is a grumpy hermit named Eloise.
</P>
<P>
   Master Georgie. By Beryl Bainbridge. (Carroll &AMP; Graf, $21.) With
her characteristic deft mix of deadpan humor and nightmarish
horror, Bainbridge's novel centers on a sequence of upsetting
photographs -- some of them showing the newly deceased.
</P>
<P>
   MENDEL'S DWARF. By Simon Mawer. (Harmony, $23.) Moral,
historical and philosophical considerations about genetics pervade
this thematically ambitious novel whose hero is a dwarf and a
distant relative of Gregor Mendel, the monk who founded genetics.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING WOMEN AND OTHERS: Stories. By June Spence. (Riverhead,
$21.95.) Evocative short stories in most of which women (sometimes
men) seem mired in perpetual states of transition: recent divorce,
recovery from crackup, boring jobs; the author's first collection.
</P>
<P>
   MISTLER'S EXIT. By Louis Begley. (Knopf, $22.) Falsification of
the self, a theme that runs through Begley's earlier novels, peaks
out in a rich and powerful protagonist whose terminal cancer does
not move him to separate his truth from his lies.
</P>
<P>
   THE MOORING OF STARTING OUT: The First Five Books of Poetry. By
John Ashbery. (Ecco, $25.) This collection of the poet's work from
1956 to 1972 demonstrates Ashbery's tireless effort to remain
poetically fresh.
</P>
<P>
   THE MOURNERS' BENCH. By Susan Dodd. (Morrow, $24.) A novel in
which two working-class sisters in the South and a male teacher
from Yankeeland assume tragic configurations, from which the
survivors are able to escape by humor, irony and real interest in
what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   MY HEART LAID BARE. By Joyce Carol Oates. (William
Abrahams/Dutton, $26.95.) A certain vanity of soul, a belief in a
special American national destiny, makes this novel's inhabitants
easy marks for greed, racism and the workings of a cosmic con
artist with a resemblance to Satan.
</P>
<P>
   NIGHT TRAIN. By Martin Amis. (Harmony, $20.) Amis's ninth novel
is a tightly constructed, darkly romantic police procedural about a
suicide; it defers to genre conventions while probing deeply into
questions of human motivation.
</P>
<P>
   NOBODY'S GIRL. By An- tonya Nelson. (Scribner, $22.) A tartly
phrased novel of moral and social isolation whose heroine,
self-exiled in one of New Mexico's empty quarters, has broken off
connections after her mother's death.
</P>
<P>
   No Lease on life. by Lynne Tillman. (Harcourt Brace, $21.) The
novelist recounts 24 hours in the life of her tough, intelligent
heroine, whose roiling anger may ultimately prove no match for the
auditory and olfactory indignities of a single New York block.
</P>
<P>
   NOSFERATU. By Jim Shepard. (Knopf, $22.) This novel, whose hero
sees himself as a vampire lover of sorts, imaginatively
reconstructs the amorous and creative lives of the director F. W.
Murnau.
</P>
<P>
   THE notebooks of don rigoberto. By Mario Vargas Llosa. (Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux, $23.) An amazing variety of sexual conduct courses
through the gorgeous prose of this master's latest novel. But aha!
Perhaps it's all on some interior level of fictional fantasy. Well,
it pleases the characters.
</P>
<P>
   AN OCTAVE ABOVE THUNDER: New and Selected Poems. By Carol Muske.
(Penguin, paper, $16.95.) Work culled from over two decades of
writing by a poet who invites readers to peer over her shoulder and
see how she's doing.
</P>
<P>
   THE ONE FACING US. By Ronit Matalon. (Metropolitan/Holt, $25.) A
haunting first novel from Israel that collects history rather than
synthesizing it; unearthed in fragments (photographs, letters,
anecdotes, scraps), it resists becoming any one kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE OCCASION OF MY LAST AFTERNOON. By Kaye Gibbons. (Putnam,
$22.95.) This novel is told as the recollections of an elderly
Southern woman about the years surrounding the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   OYSTER. By Janette Turner Hospital. (Norton, $25.95.) A
half-surreal novel set in a dreamscape Australia, populated by
frontiersmen and cultists whose consciousness, warped by extreme
conditions, ignites a combustive disaster.
</P>
<P>
   PARADISE. By Toni Morrison. (Knopf, $25.) A characteristically
ambitious, troubling, complicated novel set in a small black utopia
whose ineluctable encounter with the ``real'' world has both tragic
and regenerative consequences.
</P>
<P>
   PARK CITY: New and Selected Stories. By Ann Beattie. (Knopf,
$25.) Three dozen fine stories, warm and cool at once, from 25
years of writing about men and women for whom domestic rupture
occurs quietly, ordinarily and inevitably.
</P>
<P>
   A PATCHWORK PLANET. By Anne Tyler. (Knopf, $24.) Tyler's 14th
novel concerns a 29-year-old underachiever, estranged from his
family and subject to terrible attacks of clarity.
</P>
<P>
   PLAIN AND NORMAL. By James Wilcox. (Little, Brown, $24.) The
nebbishy, well-meaning hero of this gravely farcical novel is newly
divorced, newly out of the closet and newly conscious that his
every move is misconstrued by somebody.
</P>
<P>
   the priest fainted. by Catherine Temma Davidson. (John
Macrae/Holt, $23.) Call it hubris, but the young heroine of this
first novel, who is spending a year in Greece, views her new life
as part of a continuum that began with Athena &AMP; Company.
</P>
<P>
   QUARANTINE. By Jim Crace. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $23.)
Expanding on the accounts of the Gospels, this novel by a wizard at
rendering other times and cultures reinterprets Jesus' 40-day fast
in the wilderness at the beginning of His mission.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-FICTION&AMP;POETRY-5THTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: of His mission.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REMOTE FEED. By David Gilbert. (Scribner, $22.) This debut story
collection, whose characters are exemplars of familiar types yet
absurdly individual, includes a hostess who makes her guests tread
on hot coals, the Donner Party revisited as a Hollywood feature
film and a dazzling appearance by a sea cucumber.
</P>
<P>
   RESERVATION ROAD. By John Burnham Schwartz. (Knopf, $24.) A
painful, spare novel that explores lives altered and grief
transmuted to revenge by the hit-and-run death of a 10-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   THE RINGS OF SATURN. By W. G. Sebald. (New Directions, $23.95.)
This self-confident hybrid of fiction, travel, biography, myth and
memoir traipses through time and space to visit everyone the author
cares about, whether living, dead or imaginary.
</P>
<P>
   RIVEN ROCK. By T. Coraghessan Boyle. (Viking, $24.95.) A rich
madman lives cloistered away from women for 20 years because he
both loves and hates them far too much in this purplish novel
starring some real early-20th-century Americans.
</P>
<P>
   RIVER ANGEL. By A. Manette Ansay. (Morrow, $24.) An eloquent
novel that sets the rotten behavior of bored teen-agers against the
domain of spiritual belief, represented here by a possible miracle
that seems both awesome and trivial.
</P>
<P>
   THE ROAD HOME. By Jim Harrison. (Atlantic Monthly, $25.) A
graceful novel, mindfully and multiply narrated by some of those
concerned, about three generations of a part-Sioux family and their
links to one another and the natural world.
</P>
<P>
   ROXANNA SLADE. By Reynolds Price. (Scribner, $25.) A woman in
her 90's passes judgments on the century and concludes that life
itself is ``an adequate blessing'' in this novel by a writer more
receptive to grace than is usual in these times.
</P>
<P>
   RULES OF THE WILD. By Francesca Marciano. (Pantheon, $23.) An
impressive first novel whose heroine, a European come to Kenya for
salvation, encounters instead a poisonous love affair and an
incestuous community of competitive expatriates.
</P>
<P>
   THE RUM DIARY: The Long Lost Novel. By Hunter S. Thompson.
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $24.) Before he became the master of gonzo,
Thompson wrote this novel about a New York journalist adventuring
in Puerto Rico; no drugs but lots of sex and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   SALT WATER. By Charles Simmons. (Chronicle, $19.95.) A delicate,
elegiac, regretful novel, by a former editor of this Book Review,
in which boy meets girl and dad steals girl on an island off New
England in the last enchanted summer of 1963.
</P>
<P>
   SALVATION AND OTHER DISASTERS: Short Stories. By Josip
Novakovich. (Graywolf, paper, $12.95.) Investigations, by a
Croatian-born writer, of public deception, private honesty and
self-betrayal against a backdrop of Balkan wars.
</P>
<P>
   A SCIENTIFIC ROMANCE. By Ronald Wright. (Picador USA, $23.) A
skillful, thoughtful fantasy of the postmillennium whose hero,
traveling in H. G. Wells's very own time machine, discovers a
Thames flowing through steaming everglades and harboring crocodiles
in A.D. 2500.
</P>
<P>
   SELECTED POEMS. By Harvey Shapiro. (Wesleyan
University/University Press of New England, paper, $12.95.) Fresh,
informal, metrically traditional work that balances life and
experience in two countries, of which one is New York City and the
other is Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   SHROUD OF THE GNOMES: Poems. By James Tate. (Ecco, $23.) Beneath
a nearly impenetrable modern surface, tried-and-true pieties:
peace, happiness, human connection and the pleasures of pure
ordinariness are possible after pain.
</P>
<P>
   SINGING INTO THE PIANO. By Ted Mooney. (Knopf, $25.) Sex is the
ultimate transaction in this novel about American-Mexican
relations.
</P>
<P>
   THE SKY, THE STARS, THE WILDERNESS. By Rick Bass. (Houghton
Mifflin, $23.) Three novellas of diverse character that offer an
unsentimental but ecstatic portrayal of the physical world.
</P>
<P>
   THE SMITHSONIAN INSTITUTION. By Gore Vidal. (Random House, $23.)
In his 23d novel, Vidal offers a larky and thought-provoking
excursion through American history.
</P>
<P>
   SOLIBO MAGNIFICENT. By Patrick Chamoiseau. (Pantheon, $23.)
Published in French in 1988, this novel concerns a storyteller
whose death from strangulation by words is an emblem of French in
conflict with Creole and of the author's will to pick up where the
Caribbean oral tradition left off.
</P>
<P>
   SPENDING: A Utopian Divertimento. By Mary Gordon. (Scribner,
$24.) A best-of-all-worlds fantasy novel in which a painter, a
middle-aged woman, faces a choice between worldly comfort
(including sex and money) and the artistic struggle, and manages to
have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   THE SPRINGS OF AFFECTION: Stories of Dublin. By Maeve Brennan.
(Houghton Mifflin, $24.) A posthumous collection about the strength
and weakness of insularity, the small joys and unrealized dreams of
a single corner of Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   starting out in the evening. By Brian Morton. (Crown, $25.) The
forcefully ordered life of an aging, out-of-print novelist is
suddenly ruptured when he finds himself the subject of a sensitive
young woman's master's thesis.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER AT GAGLOW. By Esther Freud. (Ecco, $23.95.) A shrewd,
absorbing novel about a family whose notions of ``home'' change as
their relations with the onetime family estate in Germany alter.
</P>
<P>
   THE TALE OF THE 1002ND NIGHT. By Joseph Roth. (St. Martin's,
$23.95.) The last novel (1939) of the intellectual journalist
Joseph Roth imposes a fairy tale on Hapsburg Vienna and its zesty
combination of artistic and philosophical achievement with
corruption and fancy dress.
</P>
<P>
   TALES FROM OVID. By Ted Hughes. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25.)
The mellifluities of the Roman poet subjected to the rough
sensibilities of the late English poet's often dark and stormy
Yorkshire.
</P>
<P>
   T. C. BOYLE STORIES: The Collected Stories of T. Coraghessan
Boyle. (Viking, $35.) Sixty-eight stories in almost 700 flashy,
inventive pages of stylistic and moral acrobatics; some of the
later stories show more empathy and less black comedy than the
earlier ones.
</P>
<P>
   THIRST. By Ken Kalfus. (Milkweed, $16.) Short stories, mostly
brief and jarring fantasies, concerned with structures and
considerations usually identified with magic realists from other
countries; one character, for example, wakes up in one life every
time he falls asleep in the other.
</P>
<P>
   THIS IS MY DAUGHTER. By Roxana Robinson. (Random House, $25.) A
story of innocence lost, and not by children only; the distress of
a child of divorce is matched by the incomprehension, guilt, rage
and shame of the adults themselves.
</P>
<P>
   THIS SIDE OF BRIGHTNESS. By Colum McCann. (Metropolitan/Holt,
$23.) A painful, disturbing novel in which three generations of a
troubled family decline from constructing the New York subway
system to inhabiting its dark tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO RED. By Daniel Woodrell. (Marian Wood/Holt, $20.) With
storytelling that is vivid, funny and full of bad attitude, this
country-noir novel describes a wanderer who gets caught up with a
prostitute, her resentful daughter and her hairdresser son.
</P>
<P>
   TOMCAT IN LOVE. By Tim O'Brien. (Broadway, $26.) A comic novel
about the romantic failures of a Vietnam veteran.
</P>
<P>
   The Treatment. By Daniel Menaker. (Knopf, $23.) Aimless,
dateless and motherless, the hero of this novel thinks he's got
problems -- until he lies on the couch of the last surviving
Freudian.
</P>
<P>
   TWO CITIES. By John Edgar Wideman. (Houghton Mifflin, $24.) A
novel of love under the pressure of urban warfare in Pittsburgh and
Philadelphia, where love may grow beside despair, and hopelessness
must be accepted but hope need not be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   TWO GUYS FROM VERONA: A Novel of Suburbia. By James Kaplan.
(Atlantic Monthly, $25.) A slightly futuristic account, set in
1999-2000, of the enduring friendship of two men whose lives
diverged after high school; one is a model businessman, the other
the town slacker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-FICTION&AMP;POETRY-6THTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: town slacker.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE ULTIMATE INTIMACY. By Ivan Klima. (Grove, $25.) The Czech
novelist explores issues of trust, forgiveness and love in this
novel about a pastor who has an extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   VAIN EMPIRES: Poems. By William Logan. (Penguin, paper, $14.95.)
A brilliant, cheerless performance whose prevailing spirit is an
atmosphere of anger, sadness and disgust; many poems are
meditations on mankind's historical enterprises, earthly, spiritual
or intellectual.
</P>
<P>
   VAST EMOTIONS AND IMPERFECT THOUGHTS. By Rubem Fonseca. (Ecco,
$24.) An engaging Brazilian novel whose hero, a movie director, is
uncomfortably close to a murder and ungovernably obsessed with
Isaac Babel's fiction.
</P>
<P>
   THE VENTRILOQUIST'S TALE. By Pauline Melville. (Bloomsbury
USA/St. Martin's, $23.95.) A gleeful fiction that plays the
spirit-filled world of South American Indians against the
rationalist world of exploiting, ``civilizing'' Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   VISITORS. By Anita Brookner. (Random House, $23.) In a novel
largely unobscured by the excess baggage of plot, Brookner
illuminates the private dignity of a 70-year-old widow as she
struggles to survive the exquisite alienation of old age.
</P>
<P>
   NOTABLE-3
</P>
<P>
   THE VOYAGE OF THE NARWHAL. By Andrea Barrett. (Norton, $24.95.)
A British naturalist turns a search for Franklin's disappeared
Arctic expedition of 1845-47 into a voyage of self-discovery in a
historical adventure novel.
</P>
<P>
   THE WALL. By John Marks. (Riverhead, $24.95.) The first novel by
a correspondent for U.S. News &AMP; World Report describes Germany
after the fall of the Berlin wall in the form of a gripping spy
story.
</P>
<P>
   THE WAY I FOUND HER. By Rose Tremain. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$25.) A subtle, complex novel that captures, in the voice of a
13-year-old English boy, the reflections of a precocious
intelligence on the verge of adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   WELCOME TO THE WORLD, BABY GIRL! By Fannie Flagg. (Random House,
$25.95.) The author of ``Fried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop
Cafe'' follows a television anchorwoman who abandons New York for
her hometown in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE SHE WENT: Stories. By Kate Walbert. (Sarabande, $19.95.)
In linked stories, a mother and daughter travel the world in search
of fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   WHITE BOYS: Stories. By Reginald McKnight. (Holt, $23.) A
collection of stories about members of the black middle class,
reflecting the complexities of racial interactions.
</P>
<P>
   A WIDOW FOR ONE YEAR. By John Irving. (Random House, $27.95.) A
large, entertaining novel with four main characters, all writers,
and lots of sexual farce and occasional brutality.
</P>
<P>
   A WORKING GIRL CAN'T WIN: And Other Poems. By Deborah Garrison.
(Random House, $15.) Lyrics that form a kind of whole, with stories
at their centers, written around the axes of work and love, small
frustrations and larger losses.
</P>
<P>
   A WORLD AWAY. By Stewart O'Nan. (Holt, $23.) Domestic
hostilities in a Long Island family proceed under a thin camouflage
of brilliantly realized World War II period detail in this grim
novel by a proven master of grimness.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
