<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-CHILDRENS-BOOKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTABLE CHILDREN'S BOOKS OF 1998
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This list has been selected from books reviewed since the
Holiday Books issue of December 1997. It is meant to suggest some
of the high points in this year's children's books. The books are
arranged alphabetically under genre headings. The complete reviews
of these books may be found at The New York Times on the Web:
www.nytimes.com/books.
</P>
<P>
   HOLES. By Louis Sachar. (Frances Foster Books/Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $16.) (Ages 12 and up) In this comic novel of suspense and
imagination, which won a National Book Award this year, Stanley
Yelnats has been sent to a Texas juvenile correctional facility and
is set to digging holes. Nothing is quite what it seems.
</P>
<P>
   HURRY, HURRY, MARY DEAR. By N. M. Bodecker. Illustrated by Erik
Blegvad. (Margaret K. McElderry, $16.) (Ages 7 and up) A witty
verse about autumn chores has been illustrated with amusing detail
and in the subtle colors of New England as the leaves fall and the
skies darken.
</P>
<P>
   I LOST MY BEAR. Written and illustrated by Jules Feiffer.
(Morrow, $16.) (Ages 3 and up) A serious, and all too familiar,
psychodrama told in comic style and complete with hysteria and
satisfying resolution.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK-ALIKES. By Joan Steiner. Photographed by Thomas Lindley.
(Little, Brown, $12.95.) (Ages 3 and up) In the Universe of Stray
Stuff there is order and imagination and great wit. Eleven dioramas
made from hundreds of everyday objects require and reward close
study.
</P>
<P>
   NO PRETTY PICTURES: A Child of War. By Anita Lobel.
(Greenwillow, $16.) (Ages 10 and up) The unsentimental and deeply
moving story of this popular illustrator's childhood in World War
II, moving through the concentration camps to recovery and
adolescence in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   PETE'S A PIZZA. Written and illustrated by William Steig.
(Michael di Capua/
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $13.95.) (All ages) A wonderful treatment for
cranky children: roll 'em out, dust 'em off and turn 'em into
pretend pizza. Deliciously funny.
</P>
<P>
   SQUIDS WILL BE SQUIDS: Fresh Morals, Beastly Fables. By Jon
Scieszka. Illustrated by Lane Smith. (Viking, $17.99.) (Ages 8 and
up) Behind the irreverence and wise-guy tone, beyond the dark and
stylish illustrations, these modern fables, giving human foibles to
other creatures, have some shrewd observations.
</P>
<P>
   THIS LAND IS YOUR LAND. Words and music by Woody Guthrie.
Illustrated by Kathy Jakobsen. (Little, Brown, $15.95.) (All ages)
A miniature panoramic setting of all of the verses of the song
everyone thinks everybody knows, filled with details from Guthrie's
life. Sing along.
</P>
<P>
   VICTOR: A Novel Based on the Life of the Savage of Aveyron. By
Mordicai Gerstein. (Frances Foster Books/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$17.) (Ages 12 and up) In telling the true story of the feral child
found in the south of France in 1800 and the boy's life in Paris,
the author addresses the question of what civilization is all
about.
</P>
<P>
   WHIRLIGIG. By Paul Fleischman. (Holt, $16.95.) (Ages 12 and up)
Brent's journey to the four corners of the United States, to plant
the whirligigs he has made to honor a girl he accidentally killed,
is complex and beautifully told.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
