</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-MYSTERIES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTABLE MYSTERIES OF 1998
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This list has been selected from books reviewed since the
Holiday Books issue of December 1997. It is meant to suggest some
of the high points in this year's mysteries. The books are arranged
alphabetically under genre headings. The complete reviews of these
books may be found t The New York Times on the Web:
www.nytimes.com/books.
</P>
<P>
   BACKFLASH. By Richard Stark. (Mysterious Press/Warner, $20.)
This dazzling crime caper (written by Donald E. Westlake in noir
humor) follows the misadventures of a crack team of con men and
killers who have worked out an ingenious scheme to rob a riverboat
casino sailing up the Hudson River to Albany.
</P>
<P>
   THE BALLAD OF FRANKIE SILVER. By Sharyn McCrumb. (Dutton,
$23.95.) A case of 19th-century frontier justice and the modern-day
execution of a killer are interwoven in this Appalachian mountain
tale of love, loyalty and murder.
</P>
<P>
   BEYOND RECALL. By Robert Goddard. (Holt, $25.) The elegant arc
of this generational mystery takes the English narrator from a
guilty confrontation with the childhood friend he abandoned, when a
murder drove their families apart, to the exhumation of an old
crime and unresolved issues of greed, betrayal and revenge.
</P>
<P>
   BLIND DESCENT. By Nevada Barr. (Putnam, $22.95.) On a
hair-raising mission into a ``monster man-eating cave'' in Carlsbad
Caverns, a National Park Service ranger discovers that a member of
her rescue team is a killer.
</P>
<P>
   EVERYBODY DIES. By Lawrence Block. (Morrow, $25.) Matt Scudder
finds some metaphysical questions to ponder when his gangster buddy
Mick Ballou, the bloodthirsty but engaging owner of the last great
Irish saloon in Hell's Kitchen, involves him in a brutal gang war.
</P>
<P>
   FEVER SEASON. By Barbara Hambly. (Bantam, $23.95.) Set against
the appalling spectacle of the yellow fever epidemic of 1834, the
mystery of the freed slaves who are vanishing from New Orleans
proves a dangerous puzzle for Benjamin January, a surgeon who takes
the reader through the worst of the city's pestilential death
houses.
</P>
<P>
   NIGHT DOGS. By Kent Anderson. (Bantam, $22.95.) A street cop in
Portland, Ore., works himself into a hellish state of mind as he
pounds his wretched beat in 1975, reliving his own nightmares as a
Green Beret in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ON BEULAH HEIGHT. By Reginald Hill. (Delacorte, $22.95.) Part
murder mystery, part meditation on the love and loss of children,
this tragic story sends detectives Dalziel and Pascoe into a
Yorkshire village where a little girl's disappearance brings fresh
grief to the parents of three other children who went missing 15
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   SUNSET LIMITED. By James Lee Burke. (Doubleday, $24.95.) The
murky waters of the Louisiana bayou breed lurid crimes and
revolting villains, prompting the Cajun detective David Robicheaux
to brood about the fate of local characters like Cool Breeze, a
luckless soul who ``tried to stay out of trouble but wouldn't
nobody let him.''
</P>
<P>
   WINGS OF FIRE. By Charles Todd. (Thomas Dunne/St. Martin's,
$23.95.) The wild scenery and dark legends of the Cornish
countryside provide the moody atmosphere for a Scotland Yard
detective's investigation into the suicide of a beloved poet.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
