<HEADER>
A0702 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-SCIEN     12-03 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NOTABLE-SCIENCE-FICTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTABLE SCIENCE FICTION OF 1998
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This list has been selected from books reviewed since the
Holiday Books issue of December 1997. It is meant to suggest some
of the high points in this year's science fiction. The books are
arranged alphabetically under genre headings. The complete reviews
of these books may be found at The New York Times on the Web:
www.nytimes.com/books.
</P>
<P>
   ANTARCTICA. By Kim Stanley Robinson. (Spectra/
</P>
<P>
   Bantam, $24.95). Robinson is at the top of his form in this
near-future novel about the men and women who fall in love with the
ice-bound continent and fight over its development. Like John
McPhee, Robinson finds drama and poetry in the raw facts of
geography and geology.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOM. By Wil McCarthy. (Del Rey, $23.95). A journalist named
John Strasheim finds himself on a journey to the heart of a
``technogenic'' organism that threatens to eat the solar system.
Life's determination to survive, no matter what the consequences,
is the theme of this rousing yet thoughtful adventure story.
</P>
<P>
   THE CHILDREN STAR. By Joan Slonczewski. (Tor/Tom Doherty,
$24.95). Are our conventional notions of intelligent life too
narrow? To the well-meaning human colonists on the planet
Prokaryon, the answer is a matter of life and death. The author, a
biology professor with a strong feminist bent, has written a puzzle
story that begins slowly but moves toward a climax filled with
intellectual and emotional fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   CIRCUIT OF HEAVEN. By Dennis Danvers. (Eos/Avon, $14.) ``Romeo
and Juliet in Cyberspace'' might be the subtitle of this moving
love story, in which technological barriers threaten to separate an
appealing pair of ``star-cross'd lovers'' as painfully as the more
traditional barriers of class and clan.
</P>
<P>
   MOCKINGBIRD. By Sean Stewart. (Ace, $21.95). As in his previous
``Resurrection Man,'' Stewart writes about magic as if it were an
everyday occurrence, with its own rules and reasons. Antoinette
Beau-champ is an actuary with a sense of humor, an indispensable
survival trait for the daughter of a witch who inherits powers she
cannot control -- without a little help from her friends.
</P>
<P>
   THIS ALIEN SHORE. By C. S. Friedman. (DAW, $23.95). Traveling
faster than light warps the mind yet allows humans to fill the
galaxy with new kinds of societies that tap the long-buried
potential of the genome. Jamisia, a young girl on the run from
interstellar plotters, turns out to be a key player in this
breathlessly plotted, emotionally savvy space opera.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
