<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0703 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PHOTOGRAPHY-1     12-03 2203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PHOTOGRAPHY-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHY
</HEADLINE>
  By ANDY GRUNDBERG 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This season's bounty of photography books has an international
flavor in both subject matter and source. Volumes surveying places
far and near -- Algeria, India, Jerusalem, South Africa, New York
City -- abound. That's par for the course, though; what's
interesting is that American trade publishers are increasingly
relying on offshore imprints for their titles. Art houses like
Editions du Seuil in Paris, Phaidon in London and Scalo and Edition
Stemmle in Zurich are the source of many of the most beautiful and
interesting books this year, but you often have to look carefully
to tell. The trend has a downside: for all the virtues of the
photographs, the texts in these books can be stiffly translated and
negligible in terms of scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   As for American specialized publishers, Arena Editions, now in
its second year, continues to take chances with a volume on the
emerging photo artist Vik Muniz, and Distributed Art Publishers
adds to its publishing record a new and different Lee Friedlander
book. Fans of more classic modern photography have to be content
with the recycled images of some of their favorites -- books on the
work of Margaret Bourke-White, Henri Cartier-Bresson, Man Ray and
W. Eugene Smith are new this year but not especially novel. The
nominees for the most interesting faded reputations to be brought
back to light are Ellen Auerbach and Lottie Jacobi, two Bauhaus-era
women whose careers are more interesting than the books devoted to
them. Landscape photography also takes a new turn that is less
skeptical than in recent years. But the expanding universe of
photography books is a great deal larger than this suggests, as
readers will discover soon enough on their holiday bookstore
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN MUSICIANS: Photographs. By Lee Friedlander. Preface by
Joel Dorn. (D.A.P., $49.95.) If the sight of Tammy Wynette wearing
a red dress and standing all alone in a thick green wood spells
</P>
<P>
   D-I-V-O-R-C-E to you, or if an image of Aretha Franklin belting
out a song with her eyes pinched shut spells R-E-S-P-E-C-T, this
new collection of Lee Friedlander's photographs will prove to have
charms beyond the usual appeal of his artful, snapshot-indebted
style. Chalk it up to our cultural nostalgia for the 1960's and
70's, or to the photographer's obvious affection for the people who
make American music unique, but the book's more than 500 pictures,
in color and black and white, have an irresistible appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Musicians'' breaks a mold established by a dozen or
so previous Friedlander books. It consists largely of pictures the
artist made in the course of commercial assignments for record
companies, not as part of a purely personal artistic effort. As a
book it has a commercial appeal as well. The design, by Katy
Homans, puts as many as 10 pictures on the page and forgoes the
conventional and pretentious coffee-table look in favor of a
practical, lap-size square format. The result conveys a new and
exciting understanding of Friedlander, one of our most important
contemporary photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look here for any pictures of Yo-Yo Ma or Kiri Te Kanawa,
or of Jimi Hendrix or Jerry Garcia. Friedlander's idea of
indigenous American music extends only as far as bluegrass, rhythm
and blues, country and western, gospel, and jazz in all its
variations. Still, the cast of characters is beyond reproach: Eddie
Arnold, Count Basie, Solomon Burke, Ray Charles, Miles Davis,
Coleman Hawkins, Billie Holiday, Hank Jones, Wilson Pickett and a
hundred-odd others. The portraits are arranged by musical genre,
the thickest section being devoted to jazz, which -- no surprise --
is Friedlander's favorite. His fondness for jazz (and for a son who
plays jazz cello) also explains a lot about his photographs, which
often are rhythmically and tonally complex in composition.
</P>
<P>
   Vik Muniz: Seeing Is Believing. (Arena Editions, $65.) Vik Muniz
is arguably this year's hottest photo artist, and this elegant
survey of his work of the past 10 years offers evidence that he is
no flash in the pan. The earliest pictures in the book, from a
series called ``The Best of Life,'' are exemplary of his witty,
conceptual approach: Muniz began by making drawings from memory of
famous historical images, including Alfred Eisenstaedt's V-J Day
embrace, Eddie Adams's picture of a Vietcong suspect being shot at
point blank range and NASA's picture of an astronaut walking on the
moon. These fractured but evocative renditions were then
photographed and converted to halftones, giving them the same
qualities (if not the same features) as the originals. In other
series, Muniz's prodigious drawing skills are highlighted:
landscapes after Corot done with thread, portraits of Jamaican
children made from sugar, a remake of Harold Edgerton's milk-drop
photograph drawn in Bosco syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Muniz, who also draws with dirt and sculpts with wire, is heir
to the rebellious, conceptual tradition of older artists like
William Wegman and Robert Cumming, and like them he works to
confuse the existing boundaries between art mediums, converting
photographs into drawings and drawings back into photographs. His
labor-intensive procedures are aligned with much recent art, like
the installations of Ann Hamilton. Unfortunately, the
transformation of his work into reproductions in a book takes away
some of its sting; photographs of drawings, when reproduced, look
like drawings unless you are told otherwise. Still, the
reproductions and essays suffice to explain Muniz's intentions and
his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   JULIA MARGARET CAMERON'S WOMEN. By Sylvia Wolf. (Yale
University, $49.95.) This is the book that Julia Margaret Cameron,
the premier photographer of the Victorian era, has long deserved.
Not only are the 63 full-page plates well chosen and superbly
printed, but the texts -- which include contributions by Stephanie
Lipscomb, Debra N. Mancoff and Phyllis Rose -- place Cameron's work
in arresting contexts. Wolf, a curator at the Art Institute of
Chicago who organized the exhibition on which this book is based
(appearing through Jan. 10 in Chicago, it opens on Jan. 27 at the
Museum of Modern Art), justifies the concentration on women by
arguing that these pictures, much more than Cameron's well-known
portraits of men, constitute her greatest achievement. In separate
essays Rose considers Cameron's penchant for basing her personae on
tragic figures; Mancoff relates the importance of Arthurian legend
to Cameron and to Victorian artists in general, and Lipscomb
provides information about how Cameron sold her pictures as art --
and for how much.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-PHOTOGRAPHY-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: for how much.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the pictures: Mary Hillier, a maid, cast as a
regal Madonna; May Prinsep, the photographer's niece, staying at
Cameron's estate on the Isle of Wight, posing as the condemned
Beatrice Cenci; Julia Jackson, another niece, portrayed as herself;
and the wonderful Alice Liddell, at 20, taking no prisoners as the
goddess Pomona. Each is a jewel of surprisingly provocative
expression. All that keeps this from being a definitive work is the
absence of Cameron's cast of heroic Victorian males, but here they
seem irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ALBERT RENGER-PATZSCH: Photographer of Objectivity. Edited by
Ann and Jurgen Wilde and Thomas Weski. Introductory text by Thomas
Janzen. (MIT, $60.) Originally published in Germany by Schirmer
Mosel, this collection of 113 black-and-white images from the
1920's to the 60's makes clear just what the movement called New
Objectivity (Neue Sachlichkeit) in photography was all about.
Renger-Patzsch, who was the movement's leading practitioner,
embraced modern industrialism with all his heart, photographing
trains, machines, quarries and slag heaps with the same admiring
precision that he applied to cathedrals, snow-covered landscapes
and medieval castles. Besides epitomizing the hopes of Weimar-era
Germany for a rational, ordered existence, Renger-Patzsch also
provided a stylistic model for Bernd and Hilla Becher, postwar
artists whose photographs portray the decline and fall of the very
industrial order he glorified. To see his picture ``Katharina Mine
in Essen, 1956,'' with its blank sky and exact attention to
structure, is to see the Bechers' work in embryonic form --
suggesting that objectivity, new or old, is not a dead issue in
contemporary photography.
</P>
<P>
   RIVER OF COLOUR: The India of Raghubir Singh. (Phaidon, $49.95.)
It is a rare year that does not bring us another book of Raghubir
Singh's color photographs of India, usually in the form of a
specific precinct of that country's varied geography -- Calcutta,
Rajasthan, Kashmir, Bombay. But here, in a lush coffee-table book
guaranteed not to fit a standard bookshelf, is both a summary and
the essence of Singh's photographic record of his native land.
Relying on the ability of modern color film to convey bold color
and extremes of light and shadow, he fashions a stirring
celebration of life amid extremes of heat, poverty, overcrowding
and desolation. At their best his pictures are filled with
narrative incident and visual surprise, in a manner that is based
in the decisive-moment approach of Henri Cartier-Bresson but that
also is indebted to the more radical framing of Garry Winogrand. Of
all of Singh's books to date, this is the most essential and
stirring.
</P>
<P>
   HUTTERITE: A World of Grace. By Kristin Capp. Texts by Kristin
Capp, Sieglinde Geisel and Rod Slemmons. (Edition Stemmle. $75.) In
1994, at the age of 30, Kristin Capp ventured into a Hutterite
community in eastern Washington State and began a series of
pictures that describe a group of farm people living at one remove
from the culture that she, and we, take for granted. Today's
Hutterites, like the Amish and Mennonites, are descended from
16th-century Anabaptists and, as Capp's pictures show, they retain
many of their ``old ways,'' like making their own clothes and
farming their land communally. But Capp also shows a fair share of
new ways, including Hutterite big rigs and gleaming food-processing
equipment. All of this would add up only to a good National
Geographic article were it not for the tender and mysterious
quality of Capp's square black-and-white portraits of young
Hutterite women, which suggest the existence of an interior
complexity within their beautifully plain exteriors.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE PHOTOGRAPHERS: What They Saw. By John Loengard.
(Bulfinch/Little, Brown. $35.) Ever wonder how Life photographers
like Alfred Eisenstaedt, Carl Mydans, George Silk, Co Rentmeester
and John Olson managed to make those memorable photographs that
remain lodged in the popular imagination 25 to 50 years after the
fact? John Loengard, himself a Life veteran, has done us all a
service by interviewing 43 of Life's best-known photojournalists
(and including a CBS interview with himself) about the how, who,
what, where and when of their most famous pictures. Some of the
stories are deliciously wicked -- Gordon Parks telling how Roy
Stryker of the Farm Security Administration photo project needled
him into taking his most famous picture -- and some are run of the
mill, but all are fascinating footnotes to the still images that
once had more of an impact than television or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   HART ISLAND. By Melinda Hunt and Joel Sternfeld. (Scalo. $45.)
DISARMING THE PRAIRIE. By Terry Evans. Introductory essay by Tony
Hiss. (Johns Hopkins University. Cloth, $55; paper, $29.95.) Both
of these slim, earnest books attempt something important: to
relocate landscape photography from its recent role as a critic of
human presence in nature toward a more balanced viewpoint that sees
mankind as part of nature. Both books focus on territory where
nature seems to be in the ascendant and man on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Hart Island,'' which was photographed by Joel
Sternfeld in conjunction with an art project by Melinda Hunt, the
territory is the traditional potter's field of New York City, which
for more than a century has held the graves of the indigent and
friendless. It has served other purposes as well, including housing
delinquent children and recovering drug addicts, but judging from
Sternfeld's pictures it retains a wild, untamable demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the prairie of Terry Evans's book is the former site
of the Joliet Army Arsenal in Illinois, where TNT and other
munitions were made in bunkerlike buildings since World War II.
Although the now-abandoned buildings remain, as they do on Hart
Island, they are being reclaimed by the forces of nature. In both
books, the visible signs of decay are given pride of place, lending
an elegiac air to what otherwise might seem purely documentary
images.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Andy Grundberg, a critic who has written extensively on
photography and art, is teaching art history at Dartmouth College
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
