<HEADER>
A0704 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-GOUT-1000&AMP;ADD     12-03 1529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-GOUT-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 GOUT
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Patrician Malady.
</P>
<P>
   By Roy Porter and G. S. Rousseau.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 393 pp. New Haven: Yale Press. $35.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; BIGFOOT &QL; 
 &UR; By CLAUDE RAWSON &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Things you should know about gout: One in a hundred white males
are at risk. Women seldom get it before menopause. Executives are
more likely to get it than blue-collar workers. In 1952 it was
unknown in Asia, in the tropics and among blacks, but it is now
common in Japan and spreading in the third world, Roy Porter and G.
S. Rousseau tell us in ``Gout.'' Like many illnesses, gout has a
cultural history and an image. The image is of dyspeptic
aristocrats, port-swilling neurasthenics, Dickensian fireside
tipplers -- a ``patrician malady'' or ``monarch's disease'' (the
Emperor Charles V and several kings were victims), or else quaintly
``olde worlde.'' But it is modern and democratic, or at least
meritocratic or upwardly mobile, a disease open to the talents.
</P>
<P>
   Like consumption, gout has sometimes been regarded as a badge of
genius, so much so that the uncertainly diagnosed diseases of great
writers (Coleridge, Tennyson, Carlyle, Darwin) were automatically
assumed, by themselves and others, to be gout. Unlike consumption,
gout doesn't evoke the frail pallor of the ailing artist, a Keats
or a D. H. Lawrence. Often unromantically sited in the big toe,
gout is gross, not refined. The 18th-century physician George
Cheyne specifically said it was a disease for well-fed and hearty
types. Sensitive or refined persons suffered from ``nervous''
disorders instead. If genius nevertheless claims gout, the fact may
go back to ``patrician'' pretensions: geniuses like to think they
are spiritual aristocrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gout comes from Latin gutta, ``drop'' (French goutte), and
describes a flow ``of matter from the body's vitals to the
extremities.'' It was known in ancient Egypt, Greece, and Rome
(where it spread under the Empire and was associated with luxury
and decadence). It was often identified with rheumatoid arthritis.
The two were uncoupled, but not definitively, in the 17th century,
by the English physician Thomas Sydenham. It was also associated
with sexual virility, a macho martyrdom (``those who have nothing
to do with women'' were thought to be exempt), though Greek
physicians and others opined that when luxury reached a certain
point, even eunuchs and premenopausal women were at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise, and abstinence from wine and sex, were thought to
prevent it. Cures included bleeding and purgatives, as well as a
repellent diet of ``easily digested food.'' Sea voyages were
recommended because seasickness made one vomit. It was said that
the swollen-footed Oedipus (among other heroes of Greek story) was
a sufferer. But Freud, our greatest Oedipal thinker, seems to have
mentioned gout only once, in another connection, evidently thinking
that gout was sometimes just gout.
</P>
<P>
   There was a snobbery of gout. The great 18th-century arbiter of
social caste, the Earl of Chesterfield, announced that rheumatism
was for hackney coachmen but ``gout is the distemper of a
gentleman.'' Gout was even thought to be hereditary. It ``ran in
good families.'' It is one of the illnesses that, at certain
moments in history, acquire cultural glamour, while rheumatism, its
Cinderella cousin, never made it as a fashionable disease. If you
believe Jane Austen, giddy romantic girls would sooner fall in love
with a consumptive scoundrel than a good man with mild rheumatic
symptoms. Sydenham, himself a victim of gout, liked to think he
shared it with ``kings, princes, generals, admirals,
philosophers.'' It had class, as well as a classless grace or
predemocratic cachet.
</P>
<P>
   Sydenham and others also thought gout a medical blessing,
protecting victims from more serious diseases by acting as an
``overflow pipe, Nature's means of evacuating poisons.'' One author
said it was an antidote to ``murdering Maladies'' and dangerous
fevers. It was incurable but not fatal, and sufferers tended to be
long-lived. During plagues, war and famine, the gout-ridden were a
disproportionately small minority among fatal casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Gout has an 18th-century aura. Bewigged grandees boastfully
nursed their big toes. Men of letters -- Voltaire, the novelist
Smollett, the poet Cowper -- and the scientist Sir Joseph Banks
were victims. Some were fat, like Dr. Johnson, others thin, like
Horace Walpole. They wishfully consoled themselves that the gout
would protect them from other diseases, but Walpole also developed
rheumatism. Johnson concluded that gout ``is only a dog that drives
the wolf away and eats the Sheep himself,'' and insisted on having
his gout ``evicted.'' His friends thought he ``died of repelled
Gout.'' Benjamin Franklin debated whether gout was his friend or
his enemy. The best advice was thought to be to hold on to your
gout, and make sure it stayed in the foot. This did not help Edward
Gibbon, whose gout didn't protect him from a hydrocele, or swollen
testicle, the size of a melon, which went septic after surgery and
killed him. The worst fate was imagined by Swift, as usual: ``As if
the gout should seize the head, /
</P>
<P>
   Doctors pronounce the patient dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1679, the Dutch scientist Anton van Leeuwenhoek observed that
the chalky deposits of a gouty relative were crystalline. This
discovery was not followed up. It was only in 1848 that the English
physician Alfred Garrod identified the crystals with uric acid, of
which gout was a ``defective'' excretion. Gout thus differed from
other rheumatic disorders, which, he said, showed no sign of uric
acid. In 1892, Alexander Haig argued that uric acid was a cause of
both illnesses, defining rheumatism as affecting ``a large number
of joints'' and gout ``one particular joint.'' But then, the
authors say, Haig thought ``all diseases were caused by excess uric
acid!'' Unlike Garrod, Haig held that gout was not hereditary.
There continued to be to-ing and fro-ing on that issue, to which
this book seems not to suggest a clear resolution. But it assures
us we now know gout's chemistry and have drugs to control it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-GOUT-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: control it.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gout has always been associated with high living. Its growth in
the 18th century seems to have been due to increasing affluence,
exposing more people to protein-rich diets. In 1703, the Methuen
Treaty with Portugal brought large quantities of port into Britain,
and the use of lead in wine casks was thought to be an additional
risk. But Porter and Rousseau think there was also a ``gout wave''
factor, which made doctors attribute undiagnosed symptoms to gout,
as they did to hysteria in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, gout became a cultural icon. It made you
interesting. Not being a killer disease, like the plague or
consumption or cancer or AIDS, it never came to be seen as
tragically emblematic of its time. It belongs instead with
``hysteria,'' ``neurasthenia,'' ``neurosis,'' differing oddly from
these lesser aura-conferring maladies in its gross physical
visibility. I doubt if there was any other period in which social
distinction and moral complacency could be derived from a
grotesquely enlarged toe. If anyone still believes in the myth of
an Age of Reason, this should lay it to rest.
</P>
<P>
   This book is as much a cultural as a medical history. The
authors take up the ancient analogy between the body natural and
the body public, noting that gout was thought of ``as a
constitutional disease.'' The pull of the pun seems more evident
here than the tang of truth, but medical denials that gout was
hereditary were apparently regarded as a leveling challenge to the
British Constitution. ``As the constitutional diseases are often
hereditary,'' the Scotsman William Grant said in 1779, ``so the
hereditary diseases are always constitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other illnesses, gout was often described as a war within
the body. War language was full of gout insults. A royalist writer
in the English Civil War referred to ``a Gouty Army of Cut-throats
(called by some Saints).'' One writer complained that ``Old Bishop
Gout, that lordly proud disease, /
</P>
<P>
   took my fat body for his diocese.'' An exuberant literature of
swelling, excess, bodily effluvia, jovial fatness and exploding
decrepitude grew up around gout images. There was a visual
tradition to match, especially rich in phallic grotesqueries
mushrooming out of a large gouty foot. Painters and cartoonists
have thrived on gout, from Hogarth to the present, and are well
represented in the illustrations. This abundant, generous, somewhat
repetitious and disorganized book is very good reading
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Claude Rawson is the Maynard Mack Professor of English at Yale.
His latest books are ``Satire and Sentiment, 1660-1830'' and, with
H. B. Nisbet, Volume 4 of ``The Cambridge History of Literary
Criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
</TEXT>
