<HEADER>
A0705 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-STRANGE-1000&AMP;     12-03 1595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-STRANGE-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 STRANGE AND SECRET PEOPLES
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fairies and Victorian Consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   By Carole G. Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 272 pp. New York: Oxford Press. $29.95.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; O.K., SO DON'T CLAP &QL; 
 &UR; By JAMES R. KINCAID &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   DO you believe in fairies? I don't know about you, but I am not
prepared to give that question the time of day. If it's a matter of
saving Tinker Bell in the play, I'll clap; but a scholarly book,
equipped with citations, up-to-the-minute jargon and a thesis to
ride ought to spare us. Carole G. Silver's ``Strange and Secret
Peoples'' does not, it is true, insist that we ourselves hold what
she calls ``the fairy-faith''; but it wants us to believe that this
faith gripped the Victorians, or most of them, and not just
fisherfolk and crackpot rural antiquarians either.
</P>
<P>
   We are expected to embrace the proposition that the revival of
fairy lore during the 19th century was not simply decorative, but a
haunting of the imagination and spirit of the time that drained
large measures of the nation's capacity to ``believe.'' The
Victorians were not just charmed or fascinated or willing to put up
with elf dogma; they swallowed it whole, most of them. Silver wants
us to believe they believed. The problem is that what she brings
forth as evidence counts only for those who are already true
believers: it's all Bigfoot tracks and circles in the cornfields.
</P>
<P>
   I am not persuaded that most Victorians took it for granted that
there were flitting things among them, invisible or hiding in the
leaves, things like elves, sylphs, banshees, undines, bogles,
brownies, cluricanes, pixies and Ihiannon-shees. I think only a few
bedazzled people -- cuckoos, fakes, half-wits and loonies --
imagined any such thing. I am sure the Victorians liked having
access to the sentimental and horrifying possibilities of fairy
lore; they found the figurative language useful. We still do. My
own father-in-law, for instance, is best described as a troll in
his fondness for lurking under bridges, his warts and his
willingness to eat about anything. But that doesn't mean he is a
troll in any literal way, I expect.
</P>
<P>
   The annoying issue of belief aside, this is an entertaining and
informative study of Victorian culture, seen through the colorful
lore of those fairies who are ugly, vicious and murderous. Silver
has no interest in flower-folk and cute stuff generally; she wants
to get at such hard-nosed issues as Victorian racism, colonialism,
patriarchal oppression and class anxieties. She needs the nastier
fairies for that.
</P>
<P>
   Silver is a relentlessly enthusiastic and thorough scholar (she
teaches English atYeshiva University), and she has found many
references to fairies in libraries and at conferences. She has
found so many that she has taught herself to believe that they were
everywhere, that Victorians thought of little else, that every
Victorian was as interested by fairies as she. After all,
everywhere she went in her focused research there were fairies, and
it is an easy matter to forget how many minutes there were in a
century occupying how many millions of Victorian minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Victorian study of fairy lore acts as an excellent
reflection of both the dominant ideas and the concealed anxieties
of the era,'' she says. Her zeal gets the better of her: Victorian
``social and cultural concerns'' are ``perhaps shown elsewhere, but
never in such sharp relief.'' Not only is an examination of
Victorian fairy-study a way to get at the culture; it is the very
best. Want an example? Victorian fears about an increase in the
number of changelings (defective infants swapped by the fairies for
good ones) ``came to be located in the nexus of Victorian anxieties
about difference, race and class.'' This is new historicism run
amok. I might as well say that American interest in ``The X-Files''
or ``Teletubbies'' exists at the very marrow of all our really big
anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   Still, once we get past the hyperbolic claims and the
evangelical zeal, ``Strange and Secret Peoples'' provides some of
the most original reading on the subject we have. Silver's spirited
and clever analysis of the Victorian fairy revival shows how it
found strength in literature, in the growing development of
folklore and cultural anthropology, in Darwinism, in the discourse
of ``otherness'' generated by new ideas of race and in the need to
find some narrative, even a cruel and anarchic one, that would
offer relief from the mechanistic and empty story the Victorian
industrial world seemed to be telling. She gives very lucid
summaries of the development of a specifically nationalistic fairy
world and of the competing, unfailingly ingenious accounts of where
fairy stories came from: remnants of tales about an aboriginal
pygmy race or about Druids hiding underground from Roman and
Christian persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Most of her special-topics chapters are very rewarding and a
blessed break from the special pleading. Halfway through the
chapter on changelings, she stops trying to convince us that
Victorians were, every last one of them, ``obsessed'' with
changelings, stops citing Weekly World News stories (``The
Tipperary Horror: Michael Cleary, Convinced Wife Is a Fairy
Changeling, Burns Her Alive'') as if they constituted evidence and
gets to sober and smart analysis. Changelings, she suggests, embody
ideas of savagery, of ``lower races,'' and, sadly, form a shadow
folk explanation for childhood diseases that resisted explanation
and cure: spina bifida, cystic fibrosis, cerebral palsy and failure
to thrive. Silver movingly shows how the horror of little deaths
might find outlets in the alien and strange, not as explanation but
as a way of giving some form to the inexpressible.
</P>
<P>
   When Silver is content to demonstrate how figures like these
merely reflect ``sociocultural signs of British racism and
xenophobia,'' she is terrific. The discussion of powerful fairy
brides (swan maidens) in legend and popular culture is convincingly
linked to cultural fears of female sexual power and to attitudes
about divorce, suffrage and women's rights generally. Even finer is
the discussion of dwarf-goblin figures as displays of social
Darwinism in its crudest forms. Silver touches on well-known
literary figures from Mr. Hyde to Wells's Morlocks to show how the
dwarf embodied imperialist racism and a variety of disguised forms
of fascinated horror.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-STRANGE-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: fascinated horror.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Victorians were fond of the lore of the terrible woman --
the sidhe, lamia, vampire or Ihiannon-shee. In these stories, the
face of evil was female and that evil was aggressive and violent.
The extraordinary violence could be excused by the claim that it
was, after all, lore: it was ``permitted to be 'crude' because it
was authentic.'' Silver is just as acute and surprising in dealing
with the decline in fairy popularity. It became too cutesy, she
says, too settled in the nursery (largely because of Lewis Carroll
and J. M. Barrie, neither of whom are her favorites). Also, fairies
became too much the subject of crude positivism, attempts to
``prove'' their existence by, for instance, photographing them. The
famous Cottingley photographs of 1917 hurt serious fairy thinking
by the very intensity of the media glare and the dubious stamp of
``authenticity'' awarded to the photos by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle.
It wasn't so much that the butterfly cut-outs in the photos are
fakes as that fairies can hardly thrive if they need ocular proof,
Silver says. Once fairy lore was an aid to cultural survival; now
it was a media circus, alive in our time only in ravings about
aliens and U.F.O.'s coming here with their rectal probes. Quite a
falling-off from tales of sidhes leading unwary travelers into
bogs.
</P>
<P>
   My recommendation is to blot out all the talk about belief,
which is much like enjoying the choir and snoozing through the
sermon. This clever and entertaining book need not only be
appreciated by the true believers. And anyhow, some beliefs (not
many) may be nourishing. I have heard that only 92 percent of
Americans believe professional wrestling is fixed. That leaves 8
percent who must hold fast to the belief that pro wrestling is
straight-from-the-shoulder authentic. Many wrestling believers,
clearly, live in Minnesota; but not all. Eight percent of the
population amounts to, let's say, 20 million people. That's a fair
number; and if we can't say that the wrestling-faith has quite yet
``gripped the imagination'' of our culture and exists as the nexus
of our darkest and most perplexing anxieties, we can say that the
faith is ``growing'' (why not?) and that it will soon become our
very heart. Wrestlers are not the same as fairies, perhaps, but I
think there is a considerable overlap in the charm exerted by both
and in the quality of faith required. If that's true, there's hope
for the fairy-faith. Honest wrestlers and fairies haunt my dreams
and yours too. I don't just suspect that; I believe it. And that
belief is about to sweep the nation.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   James R. Kincaid, the Aerol Arnold Professor of English at the
University of Southern California, is the author of ``Annoying the
Victorians'' and ``Erotic Innocence: The Culture of Child
Molesting.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
