<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0721 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAIWAN-ELECTION-1204-     12-03 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ELECTION-1204-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAIWAN'S TUMULTUOUS DEMOCRATS SEEK PATH TO AVOID STRONG ARM OF
CHINA
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 725 words.
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    NOTE: The name 'Fredrick' in bottom of story is CQ.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ This rough-and-tumble democracy has drawn
millions of Taiwanese into a furious 10-day election campaign
revolving around the unspoken issue of how to avoid mainland
China's smothering embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Multi-colored campaign flags festoon every street. Trucks blare
music and rhetoric day and night. Staccato blasts of firecrackers
signal a candidate's arrival to yet another neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Fist-fights break out. Newspapers bemoan ``vote-buying''
estimated at $50 a voter or more.
</P>
<P>
   And doctors, teachers, old folks, laborers -- people of all ages
and pursuits -- walk away from giant political rallies hoarse and
exhilarated from participating in one of the world's most exuberant
democracies.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the Taiwanese will go to the polls on Saturday(Dec.
5) to decide the makeup of the 225-member national legislature, as
well as elect mayors and city council members in their two biggest
cities.
</P>
<P>
   But voters also are defining a course for this demi-nation that
will have world ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Taiwan there is only one issue: Taiwan's national
identity,'' said John Hsieh, political science professor at
National Chengchi University.
</P>
<P>
   This issue has crystallized in the Taipei mayoral race and
expanded the contest far beyond the bounds of traffic jams and
urban renewal. Its outcome is expected to thrust either the ruling
Nationalist Party or the upstart Progressive Party into the
forefront of Taiwan's presidential election in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is sharp: Nationalists support a status quo
looking toward reunification with China if it becomes more
democratic, while the Progressive Party was founded on a call for
eventual Taiwanese independence.
</P>
<P>
   The contest between Nationalist candidate Ma Ying-jeou, 48, and
the Progressives' incumbent Mayor Chen Shui-bian, 47, is the race
most tracked by Beijing's communist leaders, who as recently as
last week threatened to respond with armed force to any steps
toward Taiwanese independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think certainly they (in mainland China) are very much
worried about Mr. Chen's popularity in Taiwan,'' Deputy Foreign
Minister David Lee said in an interview with the Cox News Service.
``They are very worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a Nationalist, predicted that a failure to win re-election
would be a major setback for Mayor Chen's Progressives, who remain
a minority party on this island of 21 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Overcome in civil war by Chinese communists, the Nationalists
fled here from the mainland in 1949, setting up a dictatorship they
contended was China's real government. The United States withdrew
recognition from Taiwan in 1979 in favor of the communist
government on the mainland, and now Taiwan exists in a nether-world
of lively ``unofficial relations'' with
</P>
<P>
   America that include Washington-approved weapons sales.
</P>
<P>
   It took almost four decades for the Nationalists to finally
relax their grip on Taiwanese politics, giving some voice to more
than two-thirds of the population made up of Malay -descended
Taiwanese natives and other islanders whose families lived here
more than four centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Voters with deep Taiwanese roots such as Chen Di-chou, a wiry
61-year-old, charge the Nationalists are still ``mainlanders'' at
heart. He stood cheering for hours at a Progressive Party rally
last weekend that drew an estimated 100,000 raucous supporters to a
muddy soccer stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an election in Taipei, but the ideology is national,''
said the retired accountant. Over blasts of music and shouts, he
said he is sure the Nationalist candidate Ma ``won't care about
Taiwan'' but will do the bidding of mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   Fears run as strong on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to have war between the two nations across the
strait, said Chao Ching Lo, 35, a cabbie who had plastered
pro-Nationalist flags and stickers on his yellow taxi. ``If
mainland China ever gives up its communist leaders, then we can
reunite.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither side wants to yield the prosperity and democracy setting
this West Virginia-sized island apart from the mainland that looms
only 100 miles away. Yet each side fears the other may lose both.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election will be an important indication of whether a
true opposition party has emerged in Taiwan,'' said longtime
China-watcher Steven Goldstein, professor of government at Smith
College. ``You can't have a solid democratic system unless you have
an opposition party with enough strength to 'throw the rascals out'
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A fickle turn of democracy has left Taiwan's Nationalists
fearful of losing power. The heirs of Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek
are even accused of being tools of the mainland communists he so
bitterly resisted.
</P>
<P>
   The iron-fisted Chiang, father of the Nationalists and as
autocratic as his mainland communist foe Mao Tse-tung, did not
countenance democracy from the time he took over Taiwan until his
death in 1975. His son Chiang Ching-kuo eventually introduced a
more relaxed atmosphere, and under growing demands for political
rights lifted emergency rule in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy exploded, culminating in a multi-party presidential
election in 1996. The Nationalists have kept control of the
legislature and presidency, but barely.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists at times sound worried about the democracy they
unleashed. ``It is awesome. If you have this too heatedly
conducted, then there is the fear that it might lead to something
like anarchy,'' said Fredrick Chien, speaker of the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every (election) time in the last 10 years I had that fear,''
Chien said. ``But when the voting day comes, people line up, the
voting percentage is very high, and after casting votes, they just
go home or go out to play.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
