<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0723 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-ELECTION-$A     12-03 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-ELECTION-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOULD-BE COUP LEADER POISED TO WIN PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION IN
VENEZUELA
 &HT;    With VENEZUELA-BOX-$ADV05.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Dec. 5 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ His critics paint him as a cross between a terrorist and
the devil, someone who opposes trade, supports rebellion, and
hasn't been able to get a U.S. visa since he came close to toppling
his country's democratic government in 1992 with a would-be coup.
</P>
<P>
   Yet retired Lt. Col. Hugo Chavez, a controversial but
charismatic populist, is the front-runner in Sunday's(Dec. 6)
much-anticipated presidential election in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``El Comandante,'' he's won widespread appeal by vowing
to shake up the state oil industry, which he says has failed to
benefit the poorest in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venezuela is a big supplier of oil so the United States is
frightened of this left-leaning candidate who brings a lot of
uncertainty to the country's future,'' said Larry Birns, head of
the Council on Hemispheric Affairs, a Washington, D.C., think tank.
</P>
<P>
   His allure lies in pledges to fight corruption and dissolve
congress in order to create a ``new democracy'' that would improve
the lots of rich and poor alike.
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez, 44, also has hinted that he might introduce price
controls, stop payments on Venezuela's foreign debt, and use more
protectionist policies to close the country's borders to most
trade.
</P>
<P>
   This has provoked uneasiness among those in the middle and upper
classes, who fear he might impose a dictatorship and roll back
free-market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Chavez has some so concerned that current President
Rafael Caldera's army chief recently implied that the armed forces
might even try to block Chavez's ascent to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   With so much uncertainty, the candidates have asked the
Atlanta-based Carter Center to monitor the election, which could
prove to be a turning point in the nation's 40 years of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with Cox News Service, former U.S.
President Jimmy Carter said Chavez had previously indicated that he
may not accept the election results unless he wins.
</P>
<P>
   But later, after a lengthy conversation with Carter, Chavez
apparently indicated that he will accept the election results, even
if he loses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy is in danger, at least in the opinion of many
Venezuelans, if the election is not successful,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter will head up a 26-person delegation to monitor the
elections, a team that will include former U.S. Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady and former Chilean President Patricio Aylwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Venezuelan people want, almost unanimously, dramatic
change in their government, and they want peaceful change,'' Carter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's leftist Patriotic Pole coalition, made up of 14 minor
parties, won a stunning victory in legislative and gubernatorial
elections on Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Now Chavez stands a good chance of being elected president,
riding high on a tide of discontent with traditional parties over
government corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls show Chavez with about 50 percent of the vote
and his closest challenger, Henrique Salas, 62, with 38 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Both have run independently, although the Yale-educated Salas is
believed to be more mainstream and is more favored by the business
community.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Venezuela's largest political party, Democratic
Action, decided to dump its candidate and support Salas in a final,
last-ditch move to keep Chavez from winning.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela's other main party, the Social Christian COPEI,
followed suit on Wednesday, dropping its candidate, former Miss
Universe Irene Saez, to back Salas.
</P>
<P>
   Saez, even though her popularity has plummeted in recent months,
plans to remain as an independent candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venezuelans have been going through bad economic times and are
demanding political change,'' said Jennifer McCoy, director of the
Carter Center's Latin American and Caribbean Program. ``The rise of
all these independent candidates is the manifestation of the
political change.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Chavez helped plot an attempted coup against former
President Carlos Andres Perez, claiming he was corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was impeached and removed from office a year later after
being found guilty of misusing public money.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Caldera pardoned Chavez, who has has spent the last
four years building grassroots support among the more than 70
percent of the country's population that are considered poor.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has not been so forgiving. It still deems
Chavez ``ineligible'' for a U.S. visa because of his role in the
failed coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
   With 23 million people and the largest oil reserves outside the
Middle East, Venezuela is the main supplier of oil to the U.S.
market and is Latin America's fourth-largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, many Venezuelans have accused the government of
frittering away their oil-rich country's vast wealth, hence the
dissatisfaction with traditional parties has grown.
</P>
<P>
   According to the United Nations, more than half the country's
wealth goes to the richest 20 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Adding fuel to the fire is an economy that's been hammered this
year by soaring inflation, a jumpy stock market, a sharply
overvalued currency, and oil prices that are at their lowest point
in years.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, especially those in the oil industry, are becoming
increasingly unnerved by the possibility of a Chavez win and some
have already fled the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst scenario is that anyone who has any resources will
get out of the country, turning Venezuela into a gigantic ghetto,''
said Jerry Haar, a Latin American expert at the University of
Miami's North-South Center. ``The business community and Chavez are
going to have to find a way to work together even if that community
doesn't support him.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez also has pledged to dismiss the president of the state
oil company Petroleos de Venezuela S.A., Luis Giusti, a
highly-regarded oil executive who helped open the nationalized oil
sector up to outside companies.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as Mobil Corp., Exxon Corp., Texaco Inc., and
Atlantic Richfield Co. recently returned to Venezuela for the first
time in decades under Venezuela's plan to double oil production
within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chavez has backed away from some of his earlier,
more-controversial threats including one to take dictatorial
powers.
</P>
<P>
   He's even lobbied the U.S. government for official recognition
and has, recently, pledged to improve ties with Washington if
elected despite being denied a U.S. visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chavez is certainly considered to be a radical, but he will
make concessions,'' Birns said. ``Everybody has to when they are
confronted by the realities of being a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
