<P>
   &UR; COUNTERFEITING IN THE DIGITAL AGE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FIVE COLOR SLIDES &QL; 
 &UR; (1,600 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By WILL HIVELY &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, U.S. government officials worried about
counterfeiters manufacturing money with photocopiers. Now desktop
digital printing has appeared on the counterfeiting horizon. At
least 25 million ink-jet printers have been sold worldwide, and
sales show signs of accelerating. In 1995 there weren't many $9,000
Tektronix printers in basements and dens. Today, color ink-jet
printers can be bought for under $100. Welcome to the Digital Age!
Will Hively, a contributing editor of Discover magazine, reports on
how counterfeiting has gotten easier _ and cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-FAKE-MONEY-SCIENCE-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WELL DRESSED? YES. COCAINE ADDICT? THAT TOO. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR SLIDE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,200 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By TONY DAJER &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   They came into the emergency room within days of each other.
Each patient was young, well dressed and employed. The first was a
44-year-old executive. While he'd stood shaving that morning, his
right arm had gone limp, and he suddenly couldn't speak.
Panic-stricken, his wife dialed 9-1-1. Three days later, a stocky
40-year-old woman, outfitted in the latest take-no-prisoners Wall
Street fashion, came howling into the emergency room. ``My chest,''
she screamed. Their malady? Cocaine addiction. ``In 1996, we
`imported' 240 tons of the stuff,'' reports Tony Dajer, who treated
the aforementioned patients. Dajer, formerly associate director of
the emergency room at New York Downtown Hospital, now lives in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-TREATING-COCAINE-ADDICTS-SCIENCE-NYTSF. Sent to
category codes ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EVOLVING BACKWARD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED DIAMOND &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The blind mole rat _ a fat, furry sausage of a rodent with tiny
legs and no eyes visible _ is helping evolutionary biologists
figure out how the human lost his tail. The long list of ancestral
traits that were lost or reduced in the course of human evolution
includes tails, body hair and the bony browridges over our eyes.
Snakes lost their legs, and whales lost most of their sense of
smell. Why would any animal cavalierly dispense with such hard-won
victories? What evolutionary force drove their loss? Jared Diamond,
a professor of physiology at UCLA Medical School and a member of
the National Academy of Sciences, reports.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-BACKWARD-EVOLUTION-SCIENCE-NYTSF. Sent to category
codes ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BREAKTHROUGH BRIEFS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER MAGAZINE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   _ What benefit did volunteers in one chemical engineer's
experiment get from being jabbed by 400 tiny needles?
</P>
<P>
   _ Has an anthropologist at the University of Illinois in
Urbana-Champaign founds the origins of gift-giving at a dig in
Kenya?
</P>
<P>
   _ What makes a sheet of paper flutter back and forth as it
falls, while a business card tumbles end over end?
</P>
<P>
