<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CODIS04-COX     12-03 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CODIS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sharing DNA evidence with other states solves cases faster, nabs
more criminals
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Server
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ DNA, the genetic material scientists call the building
block of life, is rapidly becoming the stumbling block of violent
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Major advances in the forensic analysis of DNA have culminated
in the linking of databases in about 20 states containing thousands
of DNA samples from criminals and criminal investigations, all
under the administration of the FBI. Georgia, an early participant,
was one of the first states to get results.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Georgia section of the Combined DNA Index System, or
CODIS, went on line, investigators in four cities have been handed
incontrovertible evidence linking separate rape cases. DNA matches,
made using small amounts of blood or other body fluids from victims
or crime scenes and compared with samples from suspects, have taken
on the virtual certainty of fingerprints in court.
</P>
<P>
   More important, authorities say, as the CODIS database grows and
expands to more states, it will allow the tracking of transient
serial killers and rapists, traditionally the toughest criminals to
catch.
</P>
<P>
   Behind CODIS is an equally significant development in DNA
forensics pioneered at the GBI Crime Lab in Decatur.
</P>
<P>
   George Herrin, who was the DNA Section manager at the lab and is
now a deputy director, said analysts last fall switched to a new,
much quicker and less demanding testing method, the Short Tandem
Repeat, or STR, system.
</P>
<P>
   The GBI was the first crime lab in the country to switch
entirely to STR, which has two enormous advantages over older
systems, Herrin said. A much smaller sample is required for
complete matching and analysis, and the analysis itself requires
only a few weeks instead of six to seven months. The change has
helped the GBI make a dent in backlogged cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``When STR came on line in November (1997), we had about 50
cases backed up,'' Herrin said. ``That's down to about 25 now. We
can analyze about 60 cases a month now, depending on how often our
people have to go to court. We get about 65 to 70 new cases every
month.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer database, he said, immediately identified two rapes
in Atlanta as the work of one man; tied two rapes in Macon to
another man; two in Valdosta to one offender; and two in Gwinnett
to one man.
</P>
<P>
   CODIS, even more than the GBI's massive Automated Fingerprint
Identification System, will be a major factor in bridging the lack
of information exchange between distant law enforcement agencies,
which has allowed serial killers and sex offenders to escape
detection by simply moving on. There is still no method in sight
for linking the various state AFIS systems.
</P>
<P>
   When Georgia was approved to join the national DNA network, GBI
CODIS administrator Ted Staples said, he spent three hours
uploading Georgia's roughly 2,500 sex offender samples and another
1,000 unidentified samples from crime scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The following week, I was in an FBI software class in Virginia
when some agents came in and got me and said we had matches at the
national level, which of course was very exciting,'' Staples said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the matches concerned a suspect already convicted in
several rapes in Florida and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The other, he said, was a match between a semen stain that
helped to convict a man in a Tatnall County break-in and rape and a
blood sample collected by Broward County, Fla., authorities at a
breaking-and-entering scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't earth-shattering,'' Staples said, ``but it's good
to know the system is working.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, the DNA analysis of every convicted sex offender in
Georgia is entered into the state's CODIS database every week, and
loaded into the national database every month or so.
</P>
<P>
   The GBI is limited now, by legislation of its own design, to
entering the profiles of sex offenders. ``When we asked for the
legislation, we figured that was all we could handle,'' Herrin
said.
</P>
<P>
   But during the next legislative session, he said, the agency
will ask for the funds and new laws to allow the entry of DNA
profiles from all assaults, which will automatically take in
homicides, and home invasion burglaries. Corrections authorities
estimate that would add another 3,500 samples a year to the crime
lab.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's CODIS efforts are also impeded by current state law
mandating that all DNA taken from convicted offenders be in the
form of blood samples, which requires qualified personnel to take,
Herrin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alabama is having a lot of success with getting the samples
through simple mouth swabs,'' Herrin said, a technique that
requires no special qualification. He said the GBI plans to ask to
be permitted to take DNA samples by whatever proper means
investigators think best.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
