<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0785 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV06-C     12-03 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE PINOCHET PINCH
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Nov. 6.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What would have happened if Augusto Pinochet had
chosen to have his back surgery done in New York instead of London?
How would President Clinton have fielded a request from the Spanish
court that wants the former Chilean dictator to face charges of
murder, torture and genocide?
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the waffling tones heard from top U.S. diplomats, the
general would have been allowed to board the next flight home to
Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   When the authorities in London privately asked for American help
in making a call in the Spanish case, the State Department
announced that ``we will declassify and make public as much
information as possible,'' in line with U.S. laws and national
security interests.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a ``clarification.'' The commitment, it seems, is
merely to ``review'' any papers at hand that may shed light on
abuses during Pinochet's nasty rule.
</P>
<P>
   Prior statements said Chile should ``wrestle with'' justice for
Pinochet on its own. But as a ``senator for life,'' he enjoys
immunity from prosecution _ his reward for having handed over power
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's vivid compassion for the
victims of the Nazi Holocaust apparently does not extend to
Pinochet's prey. Albright allows that ``significant respect''
should be afforded to Chile's demand that the charges be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it's not at all easy to sort out the competing
interests. As Britain's Economist has noted: ``Plenty of dictators
have enjoyed comfortable retirements, no matter what bloody deeds
they committed or ordered while in power. They had little to fear
from judges or lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if Adolf Hitler had been found hiding in, say, Bolivia, a
decade after World War II, the international community would
promptly have had him seized, tried and executed. But what if Henry
Kissinger were arrested by a prosecutor in, say, Bolivia, and
charged with the deaths of thousands of innocent Cambodians while
he served in the U.S. government during the Vietnam War? How many
nanoseconds would it take the Bolivians to accede to an Albright
protest?
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton and Albright believe that the Pinochet case rests
on shaky ground, they might favor the creation of a permanent
international criminal court that would deal with all such matters
under defined legal rules.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, nearly every democratic government supports the
formation of this tribunal, save the United States. Last July, at a
conclave in Rome, the administration spurned a treaty to set up the
court, aligning itself with the likes of Iraq and Cuba on a
120-to-7 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Over five weeks, however, U.S. negotiators did succeed in
greatly watering down the text they finally rejected. What they
wanted (but, of course, could not get) was a guarantee that no
American citizen would ever be charged with a war crime. They saw
North Carolina's Sen. Jesse Helms as having a fit if a U.S. soldier
were to become a prosecutorial target.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, such a thing in this world as right and
wrong, whether or not Clinton and Albright have the guts to stand
up to the likes of Helms or to the Chilean government.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
