<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-THEFT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mail theft, `washed' checks emptying coffers of Florida
businesses
 &HT;    By Matt Mossman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Four small businesses in Delray Beach
and Boca Raton have been victimized by a mail theft and
check-washing scheme that's robbed them of $19,473.85, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police in both cities are investigating 15 check alterations
reported since Oct. 12. In March, federal authorities arrested 23
people in South Florida for similar crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents highlight two dangers: mail theft that could
affect anyone who sends checks from home, an office or street
mailboxes; and check washing, a literal type of money laundering
that's difficult to detect.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: thieves ``wash'' the stolen checks in a
timed process using household chemicals, erasing all handwriting.
Then they re-write the checks for any dollar amount. Thirteen of
the washed checks were used at an Office Max in Boca Raton,
according to police reports.
</P>
<P>
   Office Max spokesman Michael Weisbarth said the store's
check-cashing policy requires clerks to inspect two pieces of
identification, one with a photo; to get a phone number for the
buyer; and to make sure the signature on the check matches the name
printed in the top-left corner. Also, the bank account is checked
for fraud through a computerized system.
</P>
<P>
   The checks were stolen from mail collection boxes outside of
post offices in Boca Raton or Delray Beach, according to police
reports. Postal Investigator Rafael Rivera confirmed thefts at two
Delray Beach post offices, but said postal investigators have no
knowledge of any check-washing schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Boca Raton and Delray Beach detectives said they were
investigating the cases themselves. Boca Raton Detective Barry
Zeeuw said he may ask the postal service to help.
</P>
<P>
   The common thread in all four cases is that the victims were
small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   They're ideal targets because they tend to be small enough to
handwrite their checks _ rather than print them by computer _ but
busy enough to overlook a few forged checks, Delray Beach Officer
Vinny Mintus said.
</P>
<P>
   He took a report of six forgeries on a Delray Beach dentist
office's account after a bookkeeper there noticed the washed
checks. That office lost $9,140, according to a police report.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not for an alert bookkeeper, some of these things go by the
wayside,'' Mintus said.
</P>
<P>
   The other victims were a painting contractor, a doll accessory
shop and a clothing store.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Breckenridge, a postal service spokesman in Atlanta,
recommends that all mail containing checks be dropped off inside
the post office.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to be more alert about strangers in the
neighborhood messing with the mail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cecile Sasso, a postal service spokeswoman in West Palm Beach,
said there have been ``one or two'' mail thefts in the city in the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
