</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-DEATH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Large number of child deaths were preventable, report says
 &HT;    By William Cooper Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ More than 75 percent of the child deaths
studied by Palm Beach County's multi-agency review team were
preventable, according to a report released this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Child Fatality Review and Prevention Project analyzed 25
local deaths that have occurred since January and found that 19 may
have been prevented if people had taken better precautions. If
parents had provided better supervision or youngsters had learned
to swim, for example, children may not have died, project members
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this shows we have our work cut out for us,'' said Dr.
Jean Malecki, the project's chairwoman and the county's health
department director.
</P>
<P>
   Causes of homicides involving children were not studied because
they are still under police investigation. The number of deaths
since January were not available, but state figures show anywhere
from five to 15 children have died of abuse in the county annually.
</P>
<P>
   The local group made prevention a priority rather than targeting
child abuse cases. That approach caused State Attorney Barry
Krischer and other law enforcement officials to abandon the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were concerned that the group might be reluctant to
report any suspected abuse problems from their investigation to
authorities. But during the research for their report, project
staff members found such a case and reported the family to the
Department of Children and Families.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Bennett, the Health Care District's chief executive
officer, said results from the report suggest that some nonprofit
and governmental agencies will have to rethink their prevention
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the county's drowning prevention effort has been
on having homeowners enclose pools to keep kids out. But the report
showed that drownings did not happen in pools and that there is a
need to start teaching children to swim, Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Cobb, the project's director, said the two in-line skating
deaths indicate a need for laws to make skaters wear helmets.
Currently, Florida law only requires kids to wear helmets when
riding bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   Research also found that a child died in the front seat of a car
crash when the air bag deployed, Cobb said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a rash of similar child deaths nationwide caused by
air bags prompted federal officials to issue warnings about the
risks to children. The auto industry responded by installing
switches to disable air bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not endorsing every car be given a switch that turns off
the air bag,'' Cobb said. ``We think people need to be educated
about who should not sit in the front seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
