</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-INSURANCE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overhaul planned for state insurance policy
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state insurance plan that pays for the
health care of more than 100,000 retired public school employees is
about to go belly up, according to a legislative report released
recently.
</P>
<P>
   A joint House committee says it will take a major overhaul and
major bucks to keep the Teachers Retirement System's TRS-Care
program afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, insolvency is scheduled for September 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state could pay the initial deficit of $64-plus million,
but this would only be a temporary solution,'' says the report from
a special joint House committee. ``Due to the increasing number of
retirees, the system is projected to need more than $2 billion to
be solvent by fiscal year 2008.''
</P>
<P>
   TRS-Care was created by lawmakers in 1985 to plug a major gap in
health-care coverage for retired public school employees, most of
whom are not covered by the Medicare programs that most Americans
rely on later in life.
</P>
<P>
   Of Texas' 1,043 school districts, only about 20 contribute to
Social Security for employees. Without Social Security
contributions, retirees are not eligible for Medicare coverage. The
Austin Independent School District is among the few that provides
Social Security coverage for employees.
</P>
<P>
   About the only option not on the table for bailing out TRS-Care
is maintaining the status quo _ a system based on state funds,
limited contributions from public school employees and premiums
from retirees, the committee decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the policy issue facing the state is to offer
catastrophic care only or build an affordable system of health care
with the current systems provided,'' the committee concluded.
</P>
<P>
   House Public Education Chairman Paul Sadler, who co-chaired the
special panel that looked at TRS-Care, said not finding a solution
is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the retired teachers out there, we have no choice. We have
to address it,'' said Sadler, who, like many lawmakers, has now
found a new place to spend part of the state's projected $3
billion-$6 billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   It's an expenditure Sadler did not see coming,
</P>
<P>
   ``I was floored,'' he said. ``I had no idea the teachers were
not eligible for Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   But James Moore of Amarillo, chairman of the Teachers Retirement
System board that oversees TRS-Care, said everyone could have seen
this coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that claims would outstrip the money over a period of
time,'' he said. ``Legislators began inquiring about it two years
ago, but it was not a high priority because it had some years
remaining before the funds were expended.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, insolvency in sight, Simms is convinced TRS-Care will be a
top priority when lawmakers convene next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't doubt for a moment that it will be reworked,'' he
said. ``What avenue they will use, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms is confident the fix will be in before the money runs out.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, TRS-Care serves 101,853 retirees and 17,252
dependents. The number of participants has tripled since the
program was created. Claims also have skyrocketed, from $62 million
in the first full year to $211 million in 1997. Contributions to
the plan have not kept pace with the increase in claims, putting
the plan on course for fiscal meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current setup, the state contributes a half-percent of
the statewide school district payroll. Full-time employees
contribute a quarter percent of their salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees pay premiums based on the type of coverage they choose,
ranging from a low-end payment for catastrophic coverage that
carries a $4,500 deductible to a comprehensive plan that carries a
$240 deductible and monthly premiums ranging from $47 to $142.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, it would cost school districts almost
$2 billion a year to get all employees into the Social Security
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely critical,'' Annette Cootes, spokeswoman for
the Texas State Teachers Association, said of TRS-Care. ``For many
of them, you are talking life and death.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee laid out several ``alternative funding
scenarios,'' including increased contributions from the state,
active employees and/or retirees; and setting up a permanent fund
to support the program.
</P>
<P>
   TSTA Vice President Donna Haschke said any solution that dips
into the pockets of teachers or retirees is not really a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think teachers already take too many hits to their paycheck
as it is,'' she said. ``This is a major concern for us and we
certainly think our retired teachers, after working so hard for the
students, should be able to count on TRS-Care in their golden
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Texas Professional Educators is counting on
lawmakers to head off insolvency. ATPE wants to scrap TRS-Care in
favor of a combined system of health insurance coverage for active
educators and retirees, perhaps in conjunction with similar
programs for state employees.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McLamore, the group's director of governmental affairs,
said a close look at health insurance for educators is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are asking people on fixed incomes to pay more and more
for health coverage in their sunset years,'' he said, noting
increased premiums. ``It is time to take a look at the system as a
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
