<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREX04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Erxleben losses another battle in court
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Attorneys for Austin Forex International Inc.
chief executive Russell Erxleben were unsuccessful recently in
their battle to keep correspondence between attorneys and Erxleben
privileged.
</P>
<P>
   The former University of Texas football star, through his
attorneys, had tried to keep from turning over legal records
requested by the temporary receiver for Austin Forex, the foreign
currency trading company that closed Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   One of Erxleben's attorneys argued before state District Judge
Paul Davis that Erxleben and Austin Forex had entered into an
agreement in February for several law firms to represent him and
Austin Forex regarding an investigation by the Texas State
Securities board. The board put the company into receivership days
after it closed.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Steve Orr said that under agreement the communications
between Austin Forex and its attorneys should be considered
privileged and remain confidential.
</P>
<P>
   However, after a three-hour hearing, Davis ordered the law firms
to turn over the corporate legal records to receiver Janet
Mortenson and ruled that Mortenson could continue to decide what
documents she should release to state and federal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing Orr sought to keep private a critical letter
written by Roy Mouer, a former state securities commissioner hired
as a special counsel to Austin Forex. Orr argued that Erxleben had
not waived his personal attorney-client privilege and that Mouer's
letter should be considered confidential. The letter was the
subject of a Nov. 19 story in the American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was part of the evidence presented at a Nov. 18
federal bankruptcy court hearing, in which a federal bankruptcy
judge ruled against Erxleben's attempts to put Austin Forex and its
affiliate, International Foreign Exchange Corp. into Chapter 11
bankruptcy court protection.
</P>
<P>
   In the two-page letter, Mouer urges Erxleben to stop misleading
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruiting new investors to satisfy old investors while the
problem grows bigger and bigger is the essence of a classic Ponzi
or pyramid scheme. It is fraudulent beyond any doubt, and may very
well subject you to both civil and criminal liability,'' Mouer
wrote in the June 22 letter.
</P>
<P>
   Erxleben and his attorneys have denied any wrongdoing, saying
the company had trading losses and money was lost because of the
actions of unidentified third parties. Erxleben has claimed through
his attorney that he never saw the letter from Mouer.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Mortenson testified Wednesday that she had handed over
Mouer's letter and other legal records to a federal grand jury and
the U.S. Attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   After silently reading the letter, Judge Davis ruled that it
could not be considered privileged correspondence, especially since
it was already entered as evidence in a federal bankruptcy court
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hunter, an assistant State Attorney General, questioned why
Erxleben hired attorneys in late February to jointly represent him
and Austin Forex. Seven months later the company closed, leaving an
estimated 600 investors to wonder what had happened to the $40
million to $60 million they had given Austin Forex to invest in
foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously early in the game they thought there was a (legal)
problem,'' Hunter said after Wednesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The Feb. 24 agreement was signed by Erxleben as president of
Austin Forex and attorneys at four law firms in Austin and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Separately Wednesday, Davis ordered Erxleben to turn over by
Dec. 11 a list of the tangible assets of Austin Forex International
and its affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   The state district judge also granted a motion by the receiver
to put into the same receivership two other entities affiliated
with Austin Forex _ Austin Forex International L.L.C. and Ausforex
International L.L.C. Another Austin Forex affiliate, International
Foreign Exchange Corp., was already part of the receivership.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators wanted the other entities in the receivership
because there was evidence that money flowed freely between them,
Hunter testified.
</P>
<P>
   In its lawsuit that put Austin Forex into receivership, state
securities investigators say at least one instance shows that $5.28
million of Austin Forex investor checks were deposited into an
account of Austin Forex International L.L.C. Later, $4.46 million
of the funds were wired to an International Foreign Exchange Corp.
account.
</P>
<P>
   Erxleben's attorneys did not object to the move to put the
assets of the two companies under the control of the temporary
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
