<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNEAKER-CASH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't dunk those sneakers in the trash _ they could be worth
cash
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ That old pair of basketball shoes that's been
sitting at the back of your closet for 10 years may fetch some
extra cash just in time for holiday spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are not aware they are of collector value,'' said
Chuck Vander Hoek who, with partner Andrew Drasiewski, will set up
shop at the Holiday Inn South this weekend. The pair will pay up to
$400 for some styles of Nike and Adidas basketball shoes from the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``One gentleman brought in a pair of Nike North Carolinas in
baby blue and white, a first-edition Air Jordan that he got as a
birthday gift from his wife,'' said Vander Hoek. ``He got $400.''
</P>
<P>
   The shoes are resold in Japan, where early Nike and Adidas
basketball shoes are status symbols among teen-agers and young
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Small Earth Inc., Vander Hoek's company, sells the shoes to
Japanese businesses at double the price. By the time they're sold
in Japan, the price doubles again. (If you're counting, that's
$1,600 for a pair of used sneakers.)
</P>
<P>
   Some Japanese buyers pay even more _ up to tens of thousands of
dollars for rare promotional colors, such as the 1985
black-and-gold Air Jordans.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Hoek has found Midwest cities like Dayton to be the best
markets for purchasing the shoes ``because basketball is big
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Miami Valley, he's on the lookout for Nike's Dunk and
Terminator styles in Ohio State University colors.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Hoek and his partner, who own vintage clothing stores in
Michigan, stumbled into the shoe business about three years ago
when Japanese buyers began asking for the old athletic shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Though he'll consider larger sizes, Vander Hoek is primarily
looking for shoes in men's sizes 8 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Before you head for the closet or attic, know that most of the
shoes purchased bring $30 to $50 and many will have no value at
all. However, the original shoebox will increase a collectible
shoe's value by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And control the urge to clean up that pair of golden oldies
before taking them to the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worse thing someone can do is try to improve the
condition,'' Vander Hoek said. ``I've seen more people hurt the
value than help it. Anytime you alter the original vintage
condition, it does affect the value.''
</P>
<P>
   One Milwaukee woman, whose ex-husband left a pair of shoes
behind when he moved out, saw Vander Hoek's ad and swapped the
shoes for $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked her if she was going to split the money with her
ex,'' Vander Hoek chuckled. ``She said she was going to use it to
take a trip to Chicago and she'd mail him a postcard.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-FEET04-COX     12-03 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-FEET04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH: Patient is footloose and almost pain-free
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For more than seven years, Rick Waits, 47, watched his
world shrink. Struggling with a painful foot condition, he could no
longer play golf or even take weekend strolls with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Although he didn't complain, the couple realized that his
problem was getting worse over time, limiting their activities and
creating a sedentary lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   But after having an experimental treatment that uses shock waves
to mend minor bone and tendon problems, Waits is walking again,
able to play golf and, most importantly, take weekend strolls with
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not completely well; I've probably got about a third of
the pain left,'' he said. ``But the beauty of it now is all I have
to do is get off my feet for 15 or 30 minutes and I start to get
relief. That was never the case before.''
</P>
<P>
   The treatment that turned Waits' life around and healed his heel
involves a machine called an OssaTron, which uses high-energy shock
waves to blast away calcifications and re-tear injured tendons in
heel spurs and tennis elbows. By doing this, doctors can dissipate
old scars and cause tendons to heal correctly, thus alleviating
pain.
</P>
<P>
   The technique, called extracorporeal shock wave therapy, has
been around since the mid-1980s, when it was first used to
disintegrate kidney stones. Researchers suspected that the process
had a number of orthopedic applications as well.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Atlanta is one of five cities in the United States
conducting clinical trials of the machine's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three months, Georgia Baptist Medical Center has
been testing the machine for the treatment of heel spurs, and soon
the hospital will be evaluating the machine's effectiveness with
tennis elbow.
</P>
<P>
   And that's good news for the state's weekend warriors. Serious
injuries, often from spurts of sports and exercise, aggravate and
sometimes cause bone and joint conditions suffered by one in four
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a real solution to a lot of people's problems,''
said Dr. John A. Ogden, director of Georgia Baptist Hospital's
orthopedic division. Most doctors can now only offer basically
three types of treatment: anti-inflammatory drugs, devices such as
splints or casts, and physical therapy or surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But drugs don't fix the ailment, they merely mask the symptoms.
Devices and therapy often don't alleviate the pain. Surgery
requires more time healing and is more expensive _ costing between
$2,500 and $3,000 per procedure.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the shock wave procedure is done on an outpatient
basis and is expected to cost about $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Anice Pearson, 62, of Peachtree City said she was still sore
about a week after the procedure, but it didn't hurt at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel it hitting against my heel, but nothing beyond
that,'' said Pearson, who had suffered from foot problems for at
least two years. Pearson had already tried ultrasound and
cortisone, but they did nothing to ease the pain. Pearson decided
to seek treatment after the ailment stopped her from walking
</P>
<P>
   and playing golf. ``And I didn't want to take any more pain
pills,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors told her _ like all patients _ that it will take about
two weeks before she feels better.
</P>
<P>
   Waits said the procedure took about 45 minutes. Local anesthesia
was used, with the machine's arm placed against the heel. Waits
then received 1,500 jolts to the injured area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The treatment was intense, but not scary,'' he said. ``I
wouldn't say it was a totally pain-free experience,
</P>
<P>
   but it was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other options, such as a cast and physical therapy, Waits
said he actually felt better the same day. A few weeks after the
treatment, he played golf. Ogden
</P>
<P>
   said the hospital has used the machine on about 30 patients. By
the end of one to two months, about 80 percent of the patients
showed marked improvement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The machine _ like any shock wave device _ works by sending an
electrical impulse to an electrode submerged within a brass or
steel ellipsoid lens immersed in water. When a charge of up to
30,000 volts is fired, a small amount of water is vaporized and a
shock wave results. The wave then ricochets from the
</P>
<P>
   side of the lens and reconverges at a focal point aimed at the
injured tendon.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment risks are relatively low. Ogden said, however,
physicians need to take special care when treating the elbow
because it's so close to the shoulder and sensitive lung tissue.
The OssaTron was developed in Switzerland and is distributed in the
United States by a Marietta company, HealthTronics.
</P>
<P>
   Besides treating heel spurs and tennis elbow, HealthTronics' Roy
Brown said, the machine is also being evaluated for its ability to
correct fractures that fail to heal or heal badly. It is also
scheduled to be tested for fixing loose hip prostheses.
</P>
<P>
   And applications might not be limited to humans. The machine and
technique are showing promising results in curing lame horses,
Brown said. In the United States, clinical trials for veterinarian
use should start within the year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Waits is thrilled he was able to participate in the new
therapy. For years, he said he was frustrated with the pain and the
slow erosion of his quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally got help because my wife said, 'You're too young and
life's too short' to be so debilitated,'' Waits said. ``She was
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
