<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-ROLES04-COX     12-03 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-ROLES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going home for the holidays can reap stressful harvest
 &HT;    WITH HOLIDAY-ROLES-TIPS, PHOTOS, ILLUSTRATION
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Truth is, you can go home again. Question is, do you
really want to?
</P>
<P>
   Fed up with her mother's ``terrible cooking,'' Christine Ronn,
41, a mother of three from suburban Atlanta, decided a few years
ago that phoning home would be easier on her stomach, not to
mention her nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get nauseous just seeing the Toledo city limits sign,''
says Ronn. ``At some point as you get older, it's just not worth it
_ unless you get off on going nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   For millions, going home for the holidays has become an arduous,
stress-filled ordeal in which grown men and women unconsciously
revert to childish roles, elderly parents bark orders like tyrants,
and somebody else _ anybody but you _ makes all the decisions,
including when, where and what to eat, when to open gifts, how to
decorate the tree or even whether it's OK to leave for a while
without hurting anyone's feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday stress, brought on in part by such visits, is one reason
America's suicide rate starts rising in January from a low in
December. And why January is the busiest month for therapists.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Wheeler, an Atlanta psychologist, says her patients
can't seem to wait to get holiday hell stories off their chests.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are confrontations over tinsel or icicles on the tree,
or turkey with corn bread or roasted chestnuts. People worry, 'Are
my gifts good enough? Did I spend enough money? Is Aunt Sara gonna
be as horrible as last year? Is Dad gonna get drunk?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It can all make you feel empty, depressed, alienated. It's now
a tradition to feel guilty for not feeling happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta stockbroker Pierce Hammond, 54, is a case in point. He's
trekked to Mobile, Ala., for longer than he can remember to spend
the holidays with his wife's folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's chaotic, is what it is,'' says Hammond. ``God,
everybody's there. All my wife's sisters and brothers and their
kids, a whole bunch of people floating around. It's kind of a haze.
I'm ready to leave when it's done, even before.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, then grins: ``But I'm supposed to say it's great,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes we are, say the headshrinkers. And, when the reality
doesn't measure up to the ``supposed to,'' stress snowballs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rick Winer, a Roswell, Ga., psychiatrist, says his patients
often are full of guilt in January.
</P>
<P>
   We've been programmed to think we should head home for
Thanksgiving, Hanukkah, Christmas or New Year's, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're under pressure not to offend anyone, which you can do
simply in your decision about who to stay with,'' says Winer. ``And
it's supposed to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, heading home is healthful, even relaxing, Winer
says. ``In some instances, you don't have to think because
everything's scheduled.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, difficulties loom. ``With your parents, there's always
that feeling, `Do I need to let them know where I'm going and when
I'll get back?''' Winer says. ``Parents will assert their authority
more: `You are under my roof, you are under my rules.'''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Roper Organization at the University of
Connecticut, most Americans say they look forward to going home to
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet going home for the holidays is one of the most stressful
events of the year. Senior analyst David Wilber says polls show 49
percent of adults who visit their parents report significant
stress.
</P>
<P>
   Adults report stress over being treated like kids, over how to
trim the tree and how much to spend on gifts, the trip itself _
even lingering sibling rivalries. ``Who got the biggest raise? Who
has the best car? The best house? It's like comparing curriculum
vitae,'' Wilber says.
</P>
<P>
   Ronn decided home for the holidays was where her ``real house''
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be my mom and dad were the big kahunas,'' she says.
But holidays in Marietta turn out to be just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food is better. In Toledo, the sexiest thing we had to eat
was beef stew. Mom's idea of cooking was to get a can of vegetables
and boil them until they are so limp they scream to get out of the
water,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother is the queen of criticism. I'll be damned if I'm
going to fall back into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Celente, head of the Trends Research Institute in
Rhinebeck, N.Y., says it's not just bad cooking and carping that
dampen a visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most of us, it's no longer over the river and through the
woods. It's over the road to hell or to a hellish airport or
freeway,'' says Celente. ``And for those who still head out, it's a
hassle they'd rather avoid, even if they don't want to admit it.
...
</P>
<P>
   ``People are burned out. It's an hour to the airport, then
getting tangled up in a sea of people and confusion, then going
halfway across the country, then coming back really knowing why you
live so far away.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, we go. About 45 percent of us will head to faraway
relatives, according to the American Automobile Association. The
numbers may be even higher in metro Atlanta, where fully 42 percent
of the people aren't native Georgians.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Thompson, 22, a salesman for Pugmire Izusu in Marietta,
is weighing whether to drive home to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, it's comforting,'' he says. ``I think I like it
because nothing ever changes. They try to fix my plate. They tell
me to wear my coat.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bramham, 51, an executive at CNN, enjoys his family visits
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a change, and in a lot of ways, it's really nice,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom always reverts,'' he laughs. ``I had asthma as a child,
and she always says, 'Put on a sweater, you'll get cold. Close the
window.' Her favorite comment is 'Now listen to your mother.' We
still have a great time, and I still look forward to the
holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses and adds, ``But I'm really, really thankful for Jan.
2.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
