<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-ROLES-TIPS04-     12-03 0190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-ROLES-TIPS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tips on coping with stress from family visits during the
holidays
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   _ Temper your expectations. The notion of the ``perfect''
reunion can set you up for frustration and depression.
</P>
<P>
   _ Call a friend if the family setting becomes unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take heed of alcohol consumption. It may seem relaxing in the
short term, but its physiological effect can compound stress and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   _ Set comfortable limits. Determine how involved and
accommodating your plans should be well in advance, and make your
limits known to others involved.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reach out to those with whom you have healthy, nurturing
relationships. Get together with friends if a family setting is not
feasible.
</P>
<P>
   _ Change gift-giving procedures. Consider putting a limit of one
gift per person.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``When Holidays Are Hell: A Guide to Surviving Family
Gatherings'' by Mariana Caplan (Ingram Book Co., $7.95); and
Patricia Wheeler, an Atlanta psychotherapist.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XMAS-MUSIC-GIFTS04-CO     12-03 2733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XMAS-MUSIC-GIFTS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Musical selections for great holiday gifts
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Holiday Songs and Lullabies'' Shawn Colvin
(Columbia)
</P>
<P>
   This stocking stuffer is an understated seasonal offering,
recorded last summer while Colvin was pregnant with her first
child, Caledonia. Nimbly dodging a potential case of the cutes, the
acoustic-flavored package meanders gracefully from ``Love Came Down
at Christmas,'' ``Silent Night'' and a ballad from ``Merry
Christmas, Charlie Brown'' to traditional lullabies such ``All the
Pretty Li'l Horses'' and ``The Christ Child's Lullaby.''
</P>
<P>
   Conjured up in part by Maurice Sendak's illustrations from
``Lullabies and Night Songs,'' which Colvin loved as a child, and
by her impending motherhood, ``Holiday Songs and Lullabies'' stands
as an elegant counterpoint to all the plummy and overstuffed
yuletide schmaltz of the season. It also offers a serene and lovely
soundtrack by which children of all ages may sleep and, perchance,
dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kings of African Music'' Various artists (Music Club)
</P>
<P>
   Your friend (or you) is intrigued by the excitement of African
music but overwhelmed by the sheer volume of choices available.
There is, after all, a whole musical continent to explore, and
without a native and/or knowledgeable guide it's easy to get lost.
``Kings of African Music,'' a budget-priced compilation mixing
contemporary African hit-makers with the legendary pioneers of the
music might well be the best gateway on the market.
</P>
<P>
   By including songs by such African music legends as Franco and
Thomas Mapfumo, artists as important to the evolution of worldbeat
as the better-known King Sunny Ade and Fela Kuti, the collection
provides an enlightening historical context for the more
contemporary selections. The newer material, by modern artists such
as Youssou N'Dour and Baaba Maal, resonates with tradition but
expresses itself in considerably more contemporary terms. Both
approaches meld to create an educational overview of the music's
possibilities, but most listeners will be having too much fun to
care as the music's inherent rhythmic wonders hit the body first,
leaving the mind to fend for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the names will be new to fledgling fans of the music but
some, such as Kanda Bongo Man, whose percolating rhythms glow with
sheer pleasure, blues man Ali Farka Toure, known as the John Lee
Hooker of Africa, and the irrepressible Papa Wemba, will soon
become familiar as listeners search out their recordings. The 13
tracks obviously don't cover all aspects of African music, but they
do get you through the door of a brave, new musical world you can
spend the rest of your life enjoyably exploring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live on Two Legs'' Pearl Jam (Epic)
</P>
<P>
   The equation is pretty cut-and-dried: Capable live band plus
thick song catalog equals great concert album. Pearl Jam adds up
its strengths remarkably well, though, on its first (authorized)
live album, ``Live on Two Legs.'' Recorded on two legs of this
year's ``Yield'' tour, this 16-track, 72-minute collection picks
rather evenly between P.J.'s five studio albums. Starting with the
ferocious ``Corduroy'' and climaxing with a crunching version of
Neil Young's ``(expletive) Up,'' the order of the day here is
aggressive hard rock, the kind people forgot Eddie Vedder and Co.
could manhandle so well. Chest-beaters like ``Go,'' ``Do the
Evolution'' and ``MFC'' find the Seattle boys strutting their stuff
with thoroughly satisfying bravado.
</P>
<P>
   Except for ``Evenflow'' and ``Black,'' the band lets its
overplayed first album rest, choosing instead to dust off such
``Vs.'' classics as ``Daughter'' and ``Elderly Woman Behind the
Counter in a Small Town'' while adding fuel to the fire of the
``Yield'' track ``Given To Fly.'' One thing this album makes clear
is that the band's two ``experimental'' albums, ``Vitalogy'' and
``No Code,'' did offer some rather straightforward crowd-pleasers.
``Nothingman,'' ``Hail Hail'' and ``Red Mosquito'' all make this
collection complete for Pearl Jam diehards and doubters alike.
</P>
<P>
   Paired with Metallica's ``Garage Inc.,'' also released 1 1/2
weeks ago, ``Live on Two Legs'' provides a sort of catharsis for
'80s hard-rock fans who were supposed to feel guilty because they
once paid to see Van Halen. It also allows younger fans a chance to
claim a great rock band for themselves. Go ahead and try to tell a
P.J. fan this stuff is passe(accent). Chances are, they won't hear
you anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wide Open Spaces'' Dixie Chicks (Mercury)
</P>
<P>
   The freshest breeze to blow through Nashville in the past year
comes in the form of a platinum-tressed trio from Texas (two from
Dallas, one from Lubbock, if you're counting). Sister
instrumentalists Martie Seidel and Emily Erwin, along with vocalist
Natalie Maines, were playing the Broken Spoke within recent memory;
the last time they came to town, they had graduated to the Erwin
Center. As for their debut major-label album, it has pole-vaulted
past the platinum level, with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   None of which would matter if the music therein weren't so
fresh, vibrant and engaging. The Chicks are a ray of light in the
gloom of commercial sludge and pre-processed dross that represents
so much of Music City's cynical output. If Nashville is smart, it
will stand out of the way and let these Texas girls inject some
unalloyed delight back into country music.
</P>
<P>
   From the sexy, self-assured opener, ``I Can Love You Better,''
to the back-porch breakdown of Bonnie Raitt's ``Give It Up or Let
Me Go,'' which closes the album, the Dixie Chicks give blondage a
good name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy Boy's Greatest Beats, Vol. 1-4'' Various artists (Tommy
Boy) ``The Perfect Beats, Vol. 1-4'' Various artists (Timber!/Tommy
Boy)
</P>
<P>
   New York's famed hip-hop and dance label Tommy Boy Records came
up with two stocking-stuffer CD packages _ for extra-large
stockings, that is _ which are surprisingly fun, if not thoroughly
enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greatest Beats'' and ``The Perfect Beats'' are both four-disc
box sets that are also conveniently available in single-disc
format. The cornerstone track in both sets is Afrika Bambaataa's
``Planet Rock,'' but each takes a wildly divergent turn from there.
``Greatest Beats'' is basically a greatest-hits package from the
label's roster, including everything from Naughty by Nature and De
La Soul (yeah!) to RuPaul and Information Society (boo!). ``The
Perfect Beats'' is a compilation of vintage dance tracks pulled
together from various other labels, most of which have since folded
or been long forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Meant for DJs and hardcore electronic music fans, ``The Perfect
Beats'' may seem a little over the top to casual listeners.
Subtitled ``New York Electro Hip-Hop + Underground Classics
1980-1985,'' it's really the geek's bible to this sort of music.
Many of the tracks featured on ``Perfect Beats'' are terribly hard
to find, which is great _ if you were looking for them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the names heard on ``Perfect Beats'' are Planet Patrol,
Jonzun Crew, Peech Boys, Yello, B Beat Girls, Shannon, Jellybean,
Jay Novell, Dominatrix and many more you'd be hard-pressed to know
anything about. More mainstream tracks by Kraftwerk (``Trans Europe
Express''), New Order (``Confusion''), Chaka Khan (``My Love Is
Alive''), Yaz (``Don't Go'') and Level 42 (``Starchild'') serve as
North Stars to help the listeners find their way. For campy, quirky
and classic dance music, though, this collection is hard to beat.
Single-disc shoppers may want to check out volumes 1 and 3 for the
best samplings.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Boy's other collection, ``Greatest Beats,'' is mostly
hip-hop with a few odds and ends that probably shouldn't have even
been thrown in. It's among the first hip-hop box sets out there, as
few labels and artists have amassed or own complete catalogs. Tommy
Boy's discs include everything from pre-heyday tracks by Afrika
Bambaataa and G.L.O.B.E. to recent hits by Coolio and Apache. The
best tracks, though, are the ones in between, including De La
Soul's ``Me, Myself and I,'' Naughty by Nature's ``O.P.P.,'' Queen
Latifah and Monie Love's ``Ladies First,'' Stetsasonic's ``Talkin'
All That Jazz'' and House of Pain's ``Shamrocks and Shenanigans.''
Again, anyone wanting just one or two discs should choose volumes 1
and 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Forgotten Angel'' Clyde McPhatter (32 R&AMP;B)
</P>
<P>
   Few singers, past or present, ever achieved such sublime
transcendency with their vocal acrobatics as the late Clyde
McPhatter, the sweetly soaring voice that transformed R&AMP;B hits like
``A Lover's Question,'' ``Money Honey'' and ``Treasure of Love''
into timeless classics. McPhatter's voice, pure and piercing, was a
natural wonder but the singer improved upon nature, perfecting his
instrument until it was capable of sending delicious shivers up the
spine with just a twist of a phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Neville, a kindred vocal spirit and stone cold McPhatter
fan, co-produced this collection and provides a heartfelt
testimonial in the liner notes, stating ``as singers go, on a scale
of 1 to 10, he was a 15.'' If that's not endorsement enough,
consider that McPhatter's replacements in his first hit groups were
Jackie Wilson and Ben E. King, certifiable vocal virtuosos in their
own right. The perfectly titled ``The Forgotten Angel'' offers
three dozen McPhatter songs on two discs and each is a treasure.
The heartbreakingly sincere love ballads are too perfect for words,
while other songs, such as the salacious mambo ``Honey Love,''
originally banned from Memphis jukeboxes more because of its
suggestive rhythms than its lyrics, provide a more physical
expression of his romantic nature. All the songs benefit from
McPhatter's supporting cast, whether it's the vocal textures of The
Drifters or the funky sax work of Texas legend King Curtis, but the
stunning vocal gymnastics carry the show. And it's a real live
show, via a selection of live performances from the Apollo Theater,
featuring the venue's crack house band, that concludes the
collection and proves McPhatter could also rock with primal R&AMP;B
energy when he wasn't soaring with angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teatro'' Willie Nelson (Island Records) ``Me and the Drummer''
Willie Nelson (Luck Records) ``VH-1 Storytellers'' Willie Nelson
(with Johnny Cash) (Columbia Records)
</P>
<P>
   Or, a crash course on Why Willie Still Matters. ``Teatro,'' an
atmospheric follow-up to his acoustic-flavored ``Spirit'' album,
teams Willie with producer Daniel Lanois and uber-harmonizer
Emmylou Harris. From jazzy Django Reinhardt instrumentals to
atmospheric nouvelle versions of Nelson classics such as ``Three
Days'' and ``Darkness on the Face of the Earth,'' ``Teatro''
reveals Nelson's adventurous imagination is running on all
cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and the Drummer,'' on Willie's independent label named
after his Western movie set, reincarnates one of Nelson's classic
bar band lineups, dubbed the Offenders. The group offers a low-key
but intense honky-tonk set that includes ``I Let My Mind Wander,''
``You Wouldn't Cross the Street To Say Goodbye,'' ``No Tomorrow in
Sight '' and more. It's whiskey-drinking music par excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Robert E. Lee and Stonewall Jackson sitting around a
campfire swapping war stories and you have some idea of the
comfortable and classic flavor of ``VH-1 Storytellers,'' a live
recording taken from the television show of the same name. It ain't
much on the surface, just Nelson and Johnny Cash and two guitars.
Some songs, some stories _ but what songs: ``Ring of Fire,''
``Family Bible,'' ``I Still Miss Someone,'' ``Funny How Time Slips
Away.'' You don't get much closer to a pure distillation of country
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Progress &AMP; in Motion'' Taj Mahal (Columbia/Legacy)
</P>
<P>
   International blues man Taj Mahal's music is so endlessly and
aggressively eclectic that even a three-disc retrospective only
scratches the surface of his musical incarnations. But ``In
Progress &AMP; In Motion'' does an excellent job of covering the basics
while also providing 15 never-before-available recordings for Taj
Mahal fans who think they've heard it all.
</P>
<P>
   The compilation offers three tunes, including ``Fishin' Blues,''
from his ``Austin City Limits'' performance, a half-dozen songs
(including a rambunctious live take on ``Sweet Home Chicago'') in
collaboration with the sassy Pointer Sisters and even a few
exceedingly rare tracks from ``The Rolling Stones Rock and Roll
Circus'' television special. Throw in a live number with Boz Scaggs
and Elvin Bishop and add a couple of tunes, including a sizzling
``Statesboro Blues,'' from his first band, the Rising Sons, a group
also featuring Ry Cooder, and you've got a first-class collection
of Taj Mahal rarities, complete with star-studded accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   But Taj is at his most effective and evocative without guest
stars to get in the way, and the compilation supplies literally
dozens of enjoyable examples of his ability to personalize the
music in his own image. Such classics as ``Take a Giant Step,''
``Going Up to the Country '' and ``Dust My Broom'' allow the singer
to creatively reconfigure traditional style material while
remaining true to its original intent. It's the artist at his
easy-rolling, storytelling best, and few artists are more
comfortable to curl up with on a holiday night than Taj.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sing It!'' Marcia Ball, Irma Thomas, Tracy Nelson (Rounder)
</P>
<P>
   Three distaff veterans _ Austin keyboardist Marcia Ball, New
Orleans soul diva Irma Thomas and blues belter Tracy Nelson _ unite
for an all-star ``girl group'' like they don't hardly make any
more. Taking turns at center stage (and uniting triumphantly,
especially on the rousing title track), each woman stamps out her
own turf while aiding and abetting her partners. Friends for years,
while constantly crossing paths on the Crawfish Circuit of clubs
and festivals, Ball, Thomas and Nelson know how to play to one
another's strengths and, moreover, how to cajole great performances
out of one another.
</P>
<P>
   This is rib-sticking stuff, backed by a cast of musicians from
Memphis and Louisiana. The songs range from the syncopated ``I Want
To Do Everything for You'' to a wailing update of Bobby ``Blue''
Bland's ``Yield Not to Temptation'' and the soaring ballad
``Shouldn't I Love Him,'' and all over the musical terrain of the
South. But the best line on the album may be an ad-lib by Ball,
who, toward the conclusion of ``Love Maker'' (as in, ``I'm a love
maker, not a home maker . . .''), says, ``You say, what are you
makin' for supper? And I say _ reservations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Blues in Bebop'' Kenny Dorham (Savoy)
</P>
<P>
   The late trumpet legend Kenny Dorham is, along with native sons
Teddy Wilson, Oscar Moore and Gene Ramey, Austin's most direct and
significant connection to jazz history. Dorham, who began playing
trumpet in high school in Austin, was a legitimate jazz genius _
and that's not just hometown pride talking. He replaced Miles Davis
in Charlie Parker's band, was a co-founder of the legendary Jazz
Messengers and recorded classic tunes with everyone from John
Coltrane and Max Roach to Thelonius Monk and Sonny Rollins, to name
only a few.
</P>
<P>
   But Dorham's career was cut short by kidney disease, and he died
decades before his time, leaving a legacy of work whose quality was
enormous but whose quantity was limited. ``Blues in Bebop,'' taken
from a 10-year period ending in 1956, showcases Dorham's early work
in excellent fashion, reprising his recordings, many still
difficult to obtain, with Parker, Bud Powell, Billy Eckstine, Milt
Jackson and others in chronological order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blues in Bebop'' is not necessarily the pinnacle of Dorham's
jazz creativity _ his Blue Note albums from the years following are
uniformly superlative _ but the collection is nevertheless filled
with moments of miraculous music-making. That's not too surprising
considering the phenomenal musicians on the sessions, but the
freshness and vitality of the music is consistently amazing.
``Blues in Bebop,'' eminently accessible to both neophyte and
veteran jazz fans, offers gift-givers a perfect opportunity to fly
the flag of Austin music while paying tribute to a world-class
talent and elevating the artistic and enjoyment level of the CD
collection of its recipient.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
