<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good news, Texas; you can strike stupidest law from books
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The folks at Texas A&AMP;M have done their best at
wiping out boll weevils and grubs. They've made headway against
fire ants and web worms. But only now can they confirm an outright
bio-eradication.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough was announced to a bonfire rally last week, not
by an entomologist but by a tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Football player Dan Campbell said he was glad to attend a school
where ``men like women and women like men.'' Scientists no doubt
are catching planes this week to find out how A&AMP;M has cured
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation is a stunner, and certainly a relief. Whatever
A&AMP;M has done it must share with lawmakers in Austin. With
homosexuality cured, as its first item of business, the 76th Texas
Legislature can revoke Texas' stupidest law.
</P>
<P>
   Is the cure for homosexuality a serum? If so, vials can be
rushed to the University of Texas. Some took the Aggie's comments
to imply that UT is sorely blighted. Campbell and A&AMP;M officials
have apologized to all offended by the comments, but wait.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we know you can take a sampling of 34,000 average
collegians, do whatever A&AMP;M did with them, and have every one march
straight, well ...
</P>
<P>
   That means we don't need Texas' sodomy law.
</P>
<P>
   Court dockets spared?
</P>
<P>
   That means two Houston men shouldn't have to go on trial for
touching each other in ways outlawed by the state.
</P>
<P>
   That means a Houston lawman wouldn't have to testify exactly how
not-OK the touching was, there among consenting adults.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Texas Supreme Court and the U.S. Supreme Court
wouldn't have to sit down to review the touching, as opponents of
this ridiculous law want to force the justices to do.
</P>
<P>
   Our courts and our police ought to deal with crimes that have
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is one of 19 states with anti-sodomy laws. There's one
fewer as of last week. The Georgia Supreme Court struck down that
state's law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot think of any other activity that reasonable persons
would rank as more private and more deserving of protection from
governmental interference than consensual, private, adult sexual
activity,'' said Georgia's chief justice. The Georgia case, but the
way, did not involve homosexual conduct. It involved a male and a
female. Texas is one of five states whose anti-sodomy laws apply
only to homosexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Their privacy obliterated
</P>
<P>
   What were John Lawrence and Tyrone Garner doing in Lawrence's
Houston apartment the night of Sept. 17? None of Texas' business.
</P>
<P>
   A Harris County deputy responding on an unrelated matter entered
the unlocked apartment and saw what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   Showing uncommon courage, these two men decided to face the
music and then step out into the national light challenging the
law.
</P>
<P>
   They pleaded no contest, were fined $125 each by a justice of
the peace, and then filed their appeal. Good luck to them.
</P>
<P>
   No one should have to face this. Texas lawmakers should see to
it. They should stand up for the right of privacy. But they won't.
Some will be spineless. Some will be beholden to pious forces that
put them there.
</P>
<P>
   A serum for homosexuality? Don't be ridiculous. It's not a
disease spread through the air.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of life's mysteries. It bothers many sensibilities.
Many would like to wish it didn't exist or that advisories of
righteous damnation would make us all the same.
</P>
<P>
   People's emotions can no more be controlled by vaccine than by
nonsensical laws.
</P>
<P>
   Dare we run a dragnet at A&AMP;M to check on who's pairing up with
whom? Of course not. It's none of our business. However, I imagine
a census would surprise.
</P>
<P>
   John Young's column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail
address: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com. He is opinion page editor at
the Waco Tribune-Herald in Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
