<HEADER>
A0799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRITIC-BASHING04-COX     12-03 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRITIC-BASHING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When good critics say bad things
 &HT;    By Michael Corcoran
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The job of music critic has long been a
thankless task, but in recent months it's become an increasingly
dangerous gig as well, as artists are fighting back in more direct
arenas than the letters page.
</P>
<P>
   Last week after a show in New York City, for instance, Spin
editor Craig Marks was roughed up by Marilyn Manson's bodyguards,
allegedly under orders from the schlock-rocker, who looked on as
Marks was lifted by his neck, pinned to the wall and dropped like
an '80s hair band after a label purge.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you get for disrespecting me,'' Manson said,
according to a report Marks filed with New York police. It seems
Manson was miffed that Spin, noting the chart-plummeting of the
recent ``Mechanical Animals'' LP, changed its plans to put the man
with the plastic ``Barbarella'' breasts on the cover of the January
issue in some sort of ``Artist of the Year'' salute. Knowing that
his career has the shelf life of a carton of milk, Manson
apparently felt he had nothing to lose with an assault on the
editor, and could maybe even gain fans amongst the legion of
freelancers to whom Spin rarely returns phone calls or letters.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the hip-hop Spin-off magazine Blaze, meanwhile, editor
Jesse Washington said he was beat up last week by four men,
including rapper Derek ``D-Dot'' Angellettie, who was angered
because Blaze was planning to unmask his identity as the phantom
``Madd Rapper'' in an upcoming issue. Washington is the same music
scribe who claims to have had a pistol pointed at him by Wyclef
Jean of the Fugees about three months ago after hearing that Blaze
planned to run a negative review of a Jean-produced LP by Canibus.
Then there was the incident in England during the summer when
Tricky and one of his men pummeled a British critic who had panned
the last Tricky snore-fest ``Angels With Dirty Faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting closer to home we have A.J. Vallejo writing a letter to
the Austin Chronicle after a writer unmercifully slagged the new
``Storyville'' LP and saying, basically, that if the critic had
written that kind of review about Vallejo, he'd be chugging his
free beers through a straw for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   The hunters are becoming the hunted, but what's most shocking
about this recent turn of events is that it hasn't been happening
all along. Every musician worth anything has, at one time or
another, probably wanted to play ``Wipeout'' with their fists on
some smart-mouth critic's cranium, but the most violent kind of
reaction critics could expect in the good ol' days was an
eight-page fax from Don Henley's manager. After a year of hearing
how Ronnie Dunn of Brooks &AMP; Dunn was going to tear me up if our
paths crossed, the worst he did when that day happened was to tell
me that those that can't do, criticize (``and those that can't
criticize write for the Dallas Morning News'' I offered as a
punchline). In these times, though, members of the crit clique are
starting to see stars if they don't give records more than a
couple. This new era of intimidation makes me glad I live in the
laid-back metropolis of Austin, where the worst fate that can
befall a critic is to see a truly boring act's manager guarding the
exit when you're ready to leave two songs into the set.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I've taken a couple of half-smacks in the course of my work,
but it was always from fans who didn't like what I wrote about
bands like KISS and Motley Crue, not musicians or their goons. I
also had a guy take a swing at me during a Pantera show in Dallas a
few years back, but he was just basically punching everyone who
didn't look like him (burr-head, sideburns, Doc Martens, tattoos,
animal blood dripping from his chin) and I happened to stroll by in
my Dockers and golf shirt. (I've never been a fan of security
guards quite as much as when they physically removed the thug that
night, using his face to feel their way through the poles and
railings of the darkened amphitheater).
</P>
<P>
   I've been choosed off at clubs a few times by band members who
didn't like what I wrote, but they invariably called the next day
with a wordhangover and an apology. The thing is, I'm a big guy
with tattoos and even though I've had to file a restraining order
against an ex-girlfriend, who wants to run the risk of losing a
fight with ``Corky''? Let's face it, you lose a fight with a
music/gossip columnist and your friends will show up carrying a
pillow with a gun on top, urging you to go into the next room and
do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't say that I miss Joe Mac's Whistle Stop in Dallas'
``Thin Blue Line'' country _ that would be like pining for a bad
LSD trip _ but it's great to remember the monument to seedy kitsch
that closed in '93 from the distance provided by Homer Henderson's
new compilation ``Greatest Flops &AMP; Golden Filler,'' which just came
out on Honey Records. With his warped country songs ``Pickin' Up
Beer Cans On the Highway'' and ``Lee Harvey Was a Friend of Mine''
always playing on the jukebox, Henderson was the musical spirit
(along with slashabilly cohort Tex Edwards) of the ``five-star
toilet tavern.'' Homer lived in Austin in '96, helping start the
Nortons and doing his one-man-band at the Continental on occasion,
but his failure to catch on here (except via a cover of ``Lee
Harvey'' by the Asylum Street Spankers) says a lot about Austin's
avoidance of true sickoid culture in favor of nimble jambabies.
</P>
<P>
   Ample proof that Austin is moving closer to ``Tinseltown,
Texas'' and away from ``Live Music Capital of the World'' as a
slogan came Saturday night at Stubb's when Won Santo Condo's mix of
classic rock vocals and alternative aggression was being met with
stares from a crowd that came to see headliner Soulhat. Suddenly,
actor Matthew McConaughey, still apparently celebrating the
Longhorns victory over A&AMP;M 36 hours earlier (in the shirt he wore
at the game), started dancing with abandon in front of the band, so
the audience finally started moving closer and getting involved in
the set. There's your cure for clubland complacency: movie stars
dancing like the Funky Chicken with an inner ear infection.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
