<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENYBOPPER-MUSIC04-C     12-03 1707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENYBOPPER-MUSIC04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Back to the bubble gum bands
 &HT;    WITH TEENYSIDE
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Caitlin Greene doesn't know how accurately she
puts it when I ask her how the Backstreet Boys compare to '80s teen
sensations New Kids on the Block and Debbie Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't listen to classic rock,'' the goldilocked 12-year-old
says with a huff, trying her best to ignore me as she turns another
poster in the wall rack at Camelot Music in Highland Mall. Flip,
there's one of the Backstreet Boys. She pauses, and examines. Flip,
then comes the Spice Girls. Flip, Hanson. Flip, the Backstreet Boys
again. Sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that one,'' she says, pointing to her favorite
Backstreet Boy and showing a little more interest now that we're on
her turf, talking again about her group. Not knowing which of the
Boys she points to, and not knowing their names anyway, I teasingly
tell her that Zac is my favorite one, but I also like Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zac and Taylor are in Hanson!'' she throttles at me, raising
her head and clenching her teeth like she literally wants to bite
my head off.
</P>
<P>
   Flip, the Spice Girls. Flip, Korn. Flip, Brandy. Flip,
conversation over.
</P>
<P>
   You're out of touch. You try to keep up, but as quick as the
flip of a poster, the names and the songs change while the smiles
and the gimmicks stay pretty much the same. Oh sure, it was easy
enough _ 1 1/2 years ago when the Spice Girls and Hanson hit the
scene all by themselves, cashing in on the teeny-bopper music
market that was dormant for most of the dreary '90s. But the
Backstreet Boys are in now, and so is 'N Sync, 98, All Saints and
many more, which may mean Hanson and the Spice Girls are out. Or
not. Nobody knows for sure because, well, kids have a tendency to
change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that teeny-bopper music is back with a
vengeance. The Recording Industry Association of America estimates
that teen-geared acts now account for 10 percent of all pop albums
sold in the country. That's up from a fraction of a percent in the
early '90s, and it doesn't include the plethora of major acts with
teen crossover appeal, including Alanis Morissette, Mariah Carey
and the Beastie Boys. Not since the early and mid-'80s have so many
pre- and early-teen fans (roughly ages 9-14) been buying and asking
for records, er, CDs.
</P>
<P>
   A scan of the Billboard charts last week found kiddie acts all
over the place. On the album chart, the Backstreet Boys were at No.
10 while fellow Orlando, Fla.-reared boy group 'N Sync had not one
but two albums ranked even higher. (That explains why the
Backstreeters, who used to share management companies with 'N Sync,
are seeking new representation. Jealousy perhaps?). Meanwhile, on
the singles chart, upstart hunk act 98 was in the Top 10 along with
Brandy's younger
</P>
<P>
   prote(accent)ge(accent), Monica. Girlie acts All Saints and
Britney Spears also had Top 40 singles.
</P>
<P>
   See, what happened was in the late '80s and early '90s, grunge
became the thing, then punk. Disenchanted rock bands dressed in
jeans and T-shirts and singing about how much the world sucks had
zero appeal to most happy, carefree youngsters, particularly girls.
But record companies were so excited about finding the next Nirvana
or Green Day, that they didn't seem to notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame it on the New Kids on the Block,'' said Matthew
Rettenmund, editor of Pop Star! magazine, a pinup publication that
started up this year on the shoulders of the teen pop movement.
``The New Kids saturated the concept of the boy band. When they
finally burned out, boy groups and teen acts in general were very
passe(accent). Nobody (with a record company) wanted to sign
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, record companies just can't seem to get enough of them.
Michael Jackson's new, Sony-operated label MJJ Music is launching a
hunky boy group called No Authority. The similarly named and
manicured No Mercy is being heavily touted by Arista Records, which
is already knee-deep in teen mania with Monica. And Mercury
Records, which can be thanked for kicking off this trend with
Hanson, is getting back in the ring with the newly signed Boyzone _
already a hit in Europe, where the Backstreet Boys and many other
teen acts were first launched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious we were leaving the kids out,'' Mercury Records
artist-and-repertoire executive and Hanson champion Steve Greenberg
told me this spring. ``Record companies have hit stagnant times,
and they're seeing teen acts as a way out.''
</P>
<P>
   You can almost feel the rejuvenation when you walk into the
mall. Where once it seemed the mall record shops would permanently
close _ and many did, including Musiclands nationwide _ things are
hopping once again. Kids are there, taking soda and ice cream
breaks in the food court between trips to the magazine racks at B.
Dalton Bookseller, the whoopee cushion aisle at Spencer Gifts and,
of course, the CD bins at Camelot or Sam Goody.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great year for us,'' said Mario Sifuentes,
assistant manager at Camelot in Highland Mall. ``We've got people
asking for everything Backstreet Boys- or Hanson-related: T-shirts,
buttons, key chains.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those sure signs of teen mania, stores are once
again stocked with posters, pinup magazines, stickers and home
videos. There are plenty of new twists on the phenomenon, too. Some
of the groups have online fan clubs. Some also have CD-ROMs with
pictures and quizzes and lots of other fun stuff. An Austin-based
computer software company called Girl Games Inc. is even selling a
CD-ROM called Digital Diva that lets girls create their own teen
magazine at home, so they can cut and paste pictures of themselves
alongside those of the Backstreet Boys or Brandy or whoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they'll have any trouble coming up with a
Christmas list this year,'' said Nancy Molina, who has three kids,
two of them _ a boy and a girl _ at ripe teeny-bopper ages. ``She
likes the Spice Girls. He hates them. It never ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Girls are the backbone of the teeny-bopper music industry. Girls
buy all the posters, the pinups and the CD singles. Girls are the
ones whose smiles and sighs make it all bearable.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because they mature faster than the boys, but young
ladies worship boy bands when boys their age don't even look at the
girl groups. You don't see too many boys drooling over the Spice
Girls, for instance, and you certainly don't see many that are into
the Backstreet Boys or 'N Sync. Girls, however, are into both sides
of the teen phenomena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Younger girls like to pretend that they're older than they
are,'' said Pop Star's Rettenmund. ``Along with that, comes the
idea that they want to be married to the Backstreet Boy of their
choice, and they want to be strong and independent and glamorous
like the Spice Girls or Brandy. It's really quite sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Boys are different. Boys are cool. Boys don't cry. Somewhere
around the age of 10 or so, boys usually begin shunning fluffy
music for a completely new breed of, ahem, crap. They want tough.
They want rough. They want the kind of music that goes with their
new set of muscles and speaks to their inner-most fists. Like video
games where you can rip people's heads off.
</P>
<P>
   Parents may fear such aggressions, but at least it's not
directed toward them (that comes later). In my preteen days, an
obsession with the schlocky, makeup-wearing rock band Kiss led to a
fanaticism for all things heavy metal. Like older girls who thought
the Spice Girls movie was kid stuff, I lost my interest in Kiss
around age 9 when I saw their TV movie, ``Kiss Meets the Phantom.''
That led me to Twisted Sister. And Mtley Cr e. And Iron Maiden.
And, though I now wonder if I didn't just make them up in my head,
Keel.
</P>
<P>
   Proof that the music industry has once again picked up on teen
selling power, as well as a sure sign that the younger generation
is more spoiled than we were, boys nowadays have two musics to
choose from to meet the demands of their hardening images: metal
(still) and rap. In the former category, Marilyn Manson leads the
pack. There's also Korn, Limp Bizkit and Rob Zombie. As far as
rappers go, everyone from Puff Daddy to the members of Wu-Tang Clan
to Jay-Z have earned an early-teen, mostly male following, despite
the parental advisory warnings on the covers of their CDs. Most of
the metal CDs also have these stickers, or at least should have
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever!'' said 14-year-old Frederick Hearn, when presented
with the idea that he shouldn't be shopping for CDs with parental
warnings. He was looking at Korn's CDs. ``It's just cool music, and
I like it. I don't need anybody telling me what I can or can't
buy.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed as put off as the girl with the Backstreet Boys
posters.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, judging from the reactions Hearn and other teens gave me,
we should just let the kids be. We shouldn't tell them about the
New Kids on the Block or Kiss, or David Cassidy and Alice Cooper,
or whoever the yin-and-yang teen acts were from our childhoods, the
ones that wound up being as substantive as cotton candy. We grew
up, and the acts grew old. They'll grow up, and Lord willing, the
Backstreet Boys and Marilyn Manson will grow old, too. There's no
need to spoil the party in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the difference now is that teen mania may be a
permanent fixture in the pop music world, more so than it has ever
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be teen-agers,'' said Mercury Records' Steve
Greenberg. ``Trends come and go, but I think record companies now
know there always has to be something out there to give to the
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   As sure as the gleaming white smiles on the Backstreet Boys, as
perfectly crafted as the haircuts on those 'N Sync guys, as
carefree as the choruses in all the Hanson songs, young music fans
have united and left us adults out in the cold. We could always try
to warm up to the stuff, but it's doubtful that will do us any
good, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped listening to the Spice Girls,'' said Page
McAllister, 13. Her reason for exiting Spice World? ``My mom
started listening to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, it hurts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
