<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0802 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENYSIDE04-COX     12-03 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENYSIDE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Major stars among minor fans
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   THE HUNKS
</P>
<P>
   Backstreet Boys
</P>
<P>
   Five all-American boys between the ages of 18 and 26, A.J.,
Brian, Kevin, Howie and Nick met about four years ago at various TV
and Disney World auditions in Orlando, Fla. After some two years of
massive overseas success, the Boys finally stormed U.S. shores this
year with the single ``Everybody (Backstreet's Back)'' and its
``Thriller''-like music video that, well, you have to see to
believe. ``All I Have To Give'' is their latest single, and lead
throb Nick just put out his book, ``The Heart and Soul of Nick
Carter.'' No doubt, it's a page-turner.
</P>
<P>
   Danger factor: Nick, nicknamed Chaos, has a tendency to break
into Journey's ``Open Arms.'' Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync
</P>
<P>
   Formed almost two years ago in Orlando, Fla., by members Justin
Timberlake and JC Chasez, who were part of the new ``Mickey Mouse
Club'' cast, the five 17- to 26-year-olds were managed by Justin's
mom until the Backstreet Boys' guru team took over and launched
them in Germany. They hit it big in the United States a couple of
months ago with the single ``I Want You Back'' and are currently
all over the Top 10 charts. Did you know the letters in 'N Sync are
taken from the last letters in each member's first name? Hmmm. The
boys have a new Christmas CD out, a TV special airing on the Disney
Channel on Saturday and a concert at the Bronco Bowl in Dallas on
Dec. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Danger factor: Chris, the oldest, has earrings, dreads and
facial hair. Justin, the youngest, admits in the group's press kit,
``I'm a real party animal.''
</P>
<P>
   98(degrees)
</P>
<P>
   Signed to Motown, which has produced a few lasting teeny-bopper
acts (Jackson 5, Boyz II Men), this smiling quartet is the latest
entry in hunkdom. Hit singles include ``Invisible Man'' and
``Because of You,'' from their album ``98 &AMP; Rising,'' as well as
``True to Your Heart,'' a pairing with Stevie Wonder for the
``Mulan'' soundtrack. There's really nothing else interesting here.
</P>
<P>
   Danger factor: Jeff has tattoos. One tattoo reads, ``98.'' Lucky
for him, tattoo removal is cheaper than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson
</P>
<P>
   Still hanging in there, despite some calls that their 15 minutes
were ticking, the three Oklahoma brothers were discovered in Austin
at the South by Southwest Conference and debuted early last year
with the album ``Middle of Nowhere'' and the single ``MMMBop.'' In
addition to a recent ``early years'' compilation (``Three Car
Garage''), a Christmas CD (``Snowed In'') and a concert album
(``Live From Albertane'') the Hanson Inc. machine has turned out
not one but two home videos. Cha-ching.
</P>
<P>
   Danger factor: Isaac is almost old enough to buy cigarettes.
Hunks on the horizon: No Authority, No Mercy, Boyzone, 5ive.
</P>
<P>
   THE GIRLS
</P>
<P>
   Brandy
</P>
<P>
   Her big-screen debut in ``I Still Know What You Did Last
Summer'' was a stinker, but Brandy still knows what she did four
years ago to become a superstar: sing. The 19-year-old's sophomore
album, ``Never Say Never,'' and her hit duet with Monica, ``The Boy
Is Mine,'' have made her a lasting favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Danger factor: ``Sassy'' is Brandy's middle name. Don't get
sassy with me, young lady.
</P>
<P>
   All Saints
</P>
<P>
   A cheap imitation of the Spice Girls, right down to their London
home base, questionable ages and multi-ethnic look (hey, it beats
the Ozzie and Harriet quota of the boy groups), All Saints hasn't
exploded in America the way it has in Europe. Save your sighs of
relief, though, because the group is still trying.
</P>
<P>
   Danger factor: The quartet recently auctioned off its knickers
on a London radio show.
</P>
<P>
   LeAnn Rimes
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Blue, along with her frequent onstage cohort Bryan White,
has brought teen mania to country music. Having recently endured
her parents' divorce and a decision to live in Texas instead of
Nashville, though, the 16-year-old is growing up fast.
</P>
<P>
   Danger factor: She just played a runaway on her favorite soap,
``Days of Our Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Spice Girls
</P>
<P>
   Downed by pregnancy, marriage and other pesky adult things, the
Girls may be out for the count. Ginger/Geri's departure certainly
didn't help, and rumored attempts to replace her sound like Power
Ranger maneuvering. The question now is whether they can stretch
out their appeal to growing/older crowds, la Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   Danger factor: Yes, that was a baby popping out through Scary's
wedding dress recently.
</P>
<P>
   Girls on the horizon: Monica, Britney Spears, Mya, Jennifer Love
Hewitt (she's big in Japan), Cleopatra.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMONS: Marilyn Manson, Korn, Rob Zombie Remember when?: New
Kids on the Block, Debbie Gibson, Tiffany, Bay City Rollers, The
Osmonds, Boyz II Men, New Edition, David Cassidy, Jackson 5, Davy
Jones, Fabian, Pat Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
