<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0803 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREATING-COCAINE-ADDI     12-03 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATING-COCAINE-ADDICTS-SCIENCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL DRESSED? YES. COCAINE ADDICT? THAT TOO.  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: One color slide is available by mail (or overnight
delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) at no extra
charge to purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want
the art when you order the article.)  
 &HT;    
 By TONY DAJER 
 c.1998 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   They came in within days of each other. Each patient was young,
well dressed and employed. The malady they shared was simple, in a
sense, but not straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a 44-year-old executive. While he'd stood shaving
that morning, his right arm had gone limp, and he suddenly couldn't
speak. Panic-stricken, his wife dialed 911.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Woods, can you understand me?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   He nodded. ``Yuh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Squeeze my hands.'' His right hand gripped my fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bad,'' I said. ``Does it feel stronger than it did a
little while ago?''
</P>
<P>
   Again, he strained to speak. ``Yuh.'' Then he shook his head,
sad and disgusted at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Woods,'' I continued, ``I need to ask you some questions.
Have you ever used cocaine?''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible for a 44-year-old to have a stroke, but with no
history of hypertension or smoking, it's decidedly unusual. Unless
cocaine is involved. Mr. Woods's head trembled a bit, then he
looked me in the eye. ``Uh, hm,'' he muttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``When was the last time?'' I asked. ``Th-this m-morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, his wife walked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning?'' she cried. ``John ... you said you were
clean!''
</P>
<P>
   She turned to me. ``He did the program and said he was clean.
For six months.'' She spun back to face him. ``Oh, God, you
promised.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Woods felt duped, but she is by no means alone. Doctors,
especially we emergency room doctors, pride ourselves on squeezing
the truth out of rocks. But I work in New York City; it's boom time
here, and drugs chase money.
</P>
<P>
   Cocaine was such an emblem of the go-go '80s that in 1985 the
United States reported 5.7 million users. In the dozen years since,
that number has dropped by more than two-thirds, but ominous signs
of a comeback are in the wind. In 1996 we ``imported'' 240 tons of
the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   My emergency room cares for half a dozen young professionals a
day who rush in with all the symptoms of a panic attack. But
cocaine can trigger an identical sense of choking doom. We always
ask, and they always deny. And then I meet a Mr. Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for him, it looked as if his stroke would be transient,
as happens when the body's own system dissolves the clot in a brain
artery before permanent damage is done.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, a stocky 40-year-old woman, outfitted in the
latest take-no-prisoners Wall Street fashion, came howling into the
emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   ``My chest,'' she screamed.
</P>
<P>
   The medics filled us in on what had happened. ``She's at her
office. Suddenly clutches her chest and keels over. She has no
heart problems, and as far as they know, doesn't smoke, drink, or
do drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sims was out of control. It took six ER staff members to
undress her, start an iv and run an electrocardiogram, a recording
of the heart's electrical activity. A heart attack in a woman her
age _ with no other risk factors _ would be very unusual. Her ECG
wasn't giving us a clear answer, and there are many conditions that
can cause severe chest pain.
</P>
<P>
   My partner that day, Susan Woo, parked herself at the bedside
and shouted above the din, ``Ms. Sims, do you use cocaine?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No! No!'' her patient shouted back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very important. You may be having a heart attack. To
treat you properly, we must know anything that might put you at
risk. Have you used cocaine recently?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No! I told you. No! Oh, God, the pain. Make it stop. Please!''
</P>
<P>
   Susan ordered high doses of nitroglycerin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm treating her as if it's real,'' she said, shaking her
head. ``Beats me, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should a healthy, young, nonsmoking woman have a heart
attack?
</P>
<P>
   Cocaine, as everyone knows, is a stimulant. It achieves its
euphoric effects by prolonging chemical interactions in the tiny
gaps between nerves, or neurons, in the brain. The drug is
especially seductive because it heightens the response of the same
neurons that allow us to experience sensual pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   But while cocaine is best known for its mental effects, the
blood vessels take the hardest beating. Fill your system with
cocaine and you might as well drip acid in your arteries. Susan
found me a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember Ms. Sims?'' she smiled ruefully. ``She ruled in for a
heart attack. It was real. And her drug screen was positive for _
guess what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yup.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Megan. Blond, plump and 22, she looked like a
rosy-cheeked poster girl for the Dutch Dairy Farmers' Guild. She
sat on a chair, eyes darting about and chest heaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Megan Sutherland?'' I asked, reading off the chart. ``What's
the matter?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I-can't-breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any chest pain?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's squeezing, like a tight _ Oh, Jesus, I can't breathe _
band around my ribs.''
</P>
<P>
   After a quick exam, my concern grew. She was on the pill and had
recently had an abortion _ two predisposing factors for a pulmonary
embolus, a blood clot to the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you're sure,'' I repeated for the fifth time, ``no
drugs?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Marijuana. Over a year ago. Am I going to be OK?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' I soothed. ``But I need to take blood from your
wrist artery and see how well your lungs are getting air.''
</P>
<P>
   Megan's blood gas, the measure of oxygen and carbon dioxide in
arterial blood, was borderline normal, as was her chest X-ray.
Still, not all pulmonary emboli show up on these tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen.'' All kidding and sympathy drained from my voice.
``I'm about to send you for some very expensive, invasive, and
possibly dangerous tests. Please tell me if you use cocaine.''
</P>
<P>
   Megan eyed the distance between us. ``A couple of lines. This
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many?'' I pressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Couple more after I got to work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And then your heart started racing? And your chest got
tight?''
</P>
<P>
   She looked at me and nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your symptoms are due to the cocaine,'' I said. ``They'll wear
off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But what about my insurance? I just started this job. What if
they find out?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The information is confidential. But you've got to promise me
one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' she sighed, expecting the usual ``just say no''
lecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ever, ever lie to a doctor again.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tony Dajer, formerly associate director of the emergency room
at New York Downtown Hospital, now lives in Paris.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
