that 98 percent of all phony bills that get passed fail to
reproduce key security features-no watermark, no security thread,
no color-shifting ink in the lower right corner. Usually the
counterfeiters don't even try. And such uncraftsmanlike
nonchalance, he says, highlights the most important reason these
bills get passed: ``The American public is not paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   That puts a heavy burden on police to take up the slack. In the
good old days Secret Service agents could handle the challenge,
because counterfeiters belonged to an identifiable breed. They
spent many hours making plates, ran off huge numbers of fake
hundreds, fifties, or twenties to cover their considerable time and
expense, and then had to pass all those bills without raising
suspicions. Inevitably they left a trail-purchasing or gaining
inside access to specialized equipment; recruiting others to help
pass the bills; or selling trunkloads of bogus cash at a discount
to criminals. The Secret Service could catch those guys with
standard gumshoe work.
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays, desktop counterfeiters don't need a bill-passing
network. Instead they print cash as needed. And they certainly
don't need specialized equipment. As Lynch knows all too well, at
least 25 million ink-jet printers have been sold worldwide, and
sales show signs of accelerating. ``The nightmare,'' he says, ``is
when the system changes from 500 counterfeit printers passing
$100,000 each to 100,000 passing $500 each. We can't be everywhere.
We can't be in everybody's basement and den.''
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare is happening now. In 1995 there weren't many
$9,000 Tektronix printers in basements and dens. Today, color
ink-jet printers can be bought for under $100. What's more, there
are stand-alone scanners that don't need a computer; they plug
right into an ink-jet or laser printer. Hook them together, and you
have a color copier-all for as little as $200, compared with
$40,000 in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   If there's no stopping the digital revolution, why shouldn't
policing go digital, too? Indeed, several manufacturers of color
copiers have installed chips that recognize the world's major
currency notes and block attempts to copy them. Unfortunately, such
a chip might raise costs. Another suggestion is to modify printers
to add a unique, covert mark to every piece of paper, allowing
counterfeits to be traced to particular machines. The Secret
Service is looking into all these possibilities and more. ``The
technical issue,'' Lynch says, ``is really the linchpin.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Engraving and Printing is also eyeing new
technical fixes. Many promising countermeasures have already been
adopted in other countries. Australia, for example, is spearheading
a push to plastic money. Printing on plastic allows designers to
add translucent effects to foil counterfeiting. And plastic would
make a suitable base for holograms.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. currency experts are following those experiments with keen
interest. ``There are advantages but also disadvantages in security
with plastics,'' Ferguson says. ``We're years away from making that
decision.'' Tests show that the bureau's huge, high-speed intaglio
presses can print money on plastic stock. But then, so can ink-jet
printers.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. Over its long history, counterfeiting has
continually leapfrogged preventive measures, behaving like certain
diseases-like the flu, say. Yet all epidemics eventually run their
course. New variants spread explosively at first, but finally new
defenses kick in and the rate of infection levels off.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the idea is to deter the new breed of counterfeiters
with enough technical barriers and currency changes to restore
equilibrium. Yet the printing techniques used for both
counterfeiting and genuine currency are mutating faster than ever.
</P>
<P>
   As Ferguson says, ``It's a very interesting period.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Will Hively is a contributing editor of Discover magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
