A0811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEAK-INTL-ACQUISITION     12-03 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEAK-INTL-ACQUISITION04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peak International CEO Brook fired
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin's Peak International Ltd. fired its chief
executive recently, two weeks after reporting that it was the
target of a possible acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Brook had been promoted to CEO in September after
serving as president and chief operating officer since 1995. He
joined the company in 1991. Jerry Mo, Peak's chief financial
officer, was named acting CEO. Mo joined Peak in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to comment on reasons for Brooks'
termination, citing possible litigation between the company and
Brook.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage, we felt it would beneficial to terminate his
contract,'' Mo said. ``There will be a search (for a new CEO).''
</P>
<P>
   Brook could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mo said he will be on the list of candidates for the position.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Peak fell $1.25 in Nasdaq trading Wednesday to $9.50 a
share. The share price is up from its 52-week low of $6.25 on Sept.
25, but is still below the 52-week high of $25.87 1/2 reached March
30.
</P>
<P>
   Peak manufactures products to store, transport and handle
semiconductors and electronic devices. Its products dominate its
business with a 35 percent to 40 percent share of the market.
Customers include Texas Instruments Inc. and Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Peak told shareholders it had received interest from
a possible buyer. Mo declined to name the company or reveal details
of a possible acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Peak, like many companies that service the semiconductor
industry, has been hit hard this year by a worldwide slump in
semiconductor sales. Sales for Peak's second quarter ended Oct. 31
dropped 15 percent to $15.3 million from $18 million in the second
quarter a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings per share fell to 23 cents from 37 cents per diluted
share from a year before.
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Kumar, an analyst at Piper Jaffray who follows the
company, said that despite the slump, the offer made to buy the
company undervalued Peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see the fundamentals getting much worse,'' for next
year, Kumar said. ``I think (the offer) doesn't reflect the true
value of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to identify the company proposing to buy Peak, but
said the offer was below the company's market value. Peak's market
capitalization on Wednesday was $128.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar said the acquisition offer caused friction between Brook
and Chairman T.L. Li, who has a majority voting share on the
company's board. Kumar said Brook was opposed to the deal and may
not leave the company quietly. ``It's my take that he was
instrumental in building the company,'' Kumar said. If legal action
is taken, the analyst said, ``this is gonna be like a soap opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Peak's corporate offices are located in Austin and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
