<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT1204-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Friday, December 4, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-ROLES _ Why we fall into old, often juvenile roles when
we visit Mom and Dad. Or, if we ARE Mom or Dad, we might lapse into
old, not-always-optimal parenting habits. Lots of anecdotes from
people whose holiday travels aren't always so merry, shrinks, et.
al. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH ILLUSTRATION,
PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/HOLIDAY-ROLES-TIPS _ Tips for dealing with visits. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SNEAKERS-CASH _ DAYTON, Ohio _ That old pair of basketball shoes
that's been sitting at the back of your closet for 10 years may
fetch some extra cash just in time for holiday spending. (Moss,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ When you move, you break things, no matter what
the signs say on the big moving vans. The little boys in our family
didn't care about the Spode plates their mother grieved for, but
they are plenty put out because a whole box of Christmas ornaments
crashed. (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   PAJAMAS-WARNING _ Loose-fitting T-shirts could be fire traps for
children, warns the Consumer Product Safety Commission. (Hill,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-FEET _ For more than seven years, Rick Waits, 47, watched
his world shrink. Struggling with a painful foot condition, he
could no longer play golf or even take weekend strolls with his
wife. And although he didn't complain, the couple realized his
problem was getting worse over time, limiting their activities and
creating a chronic, sedentary lifestyle. But after having an
experimental treatment that uses shock waves to mend minor bone and
tendon problems, he is walking again; able to play golf and, most
importantly, take weekend strolls with his wife. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TV-HOUDINI _ Review of ``Houdini,'' new biopic coming Sunday on
TNT. Other reviews have not been kind. (Jubera, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   XMAS-MUSIC-GIFTS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Short reviews of music being
released for the holiday season. (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CRITIC-BASHING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The job of music critic has
long been a thankless task, but in recent months it's become an
increasingly dangerous gig as well, as artists are fighting back in
more direct arenas than the letters page. (Corcoran, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEENYBOPPER-MUSIC _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Teeny-bopper music is back
with a vengeance. The Recording Industry Association of America
estimates that teen-geared acts now account for 10 percent of all
pop albums sold in the country. That's up from a fraction of a
percent in the early '90s, and it doesn't include the plethora of
major acts with teen crossover appeal, including Alanis Morissette,
Mariah Carey and the Beastie Boys. Not since the early and mid-'80s
have so many pre- and early-teen fans (roughly ages 9-14) been
buying and asking for records, er, CDs. (Riemenschneider, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/TEENYSIDE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Short profiles of hot teen stars.
(Riemenschneider, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-INHERITORS _ Review of ``The Inheritors,'' an Austrian
film. The plot: Seven peasants unexpectedly inherit the farm on
which they work after the farmer dies. The neighboring farmers view
this as a breach of the rigid class structure in rural 19th-century
Austria and try to destroy the ``One-Seventh Farmers.'' (Murray,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-GADJO _ ``Gadjo Dilo,'' the third in a trio of
Gypsy-themed movies by filmmaker Tony Gatlif. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
