EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Dec. 3, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-SCHOOLS (San Francisco) _ Charter schools, touted as the
``magic bullet'' to improve public education in California, are
less accountable than other public schools and offer no evidence
that students are faring better academically, according to a
sweeping two-year study released Thursday. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-DECISIONS (San Francisco) _ Sometimes the worst career
decision you can make doesn't feel like a decision at all. You're
either deciding one thing when you should be focused on a broader
or more important issue, or you lull yourself into a false sense of
security when you should be doing something to protect yourself or
your job. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FURBY-PHENOM (San Francisco) _ Are you parent enough to stand up
to a Furby? This Christmas shopping season, adults are lining up
outside shopping malls at 3 a.m., pushing, shoving _ and, according
to one news report, biting _ in hopes of buying one of these small,
Gremlin-like interactive toys. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   FURBY-AUTOPSY (San Francisco) _ If you're planning to wait in
line all night at your local retailer for a Furby, you might as
well have some idea of what you're in for. We dissected a Furby
that reached an untimely end at the hands of an irate San Francisco
Examiner business writer to find out what makes it tick. By MATT
BEER.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-FURBY-CRAZE (Houston) _ Attention, shoppers: Furby has
left the building. And no, we don't know when he'll be back. But if
price is no object _ if, say, the idea of spending $300 or more for
a $30 talking hairball won't make you fear you've taken leave of
your senses _ you may be in luck. By JEANNIE KEVER.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-CATNIP (Undated) _ You've browsed the gift catalogs for
the superrich, scanned Martha Stewart's seasonal entertainment
guides, sneered at the neighbor's go-for-broke decorating scheme.
You think you've seen it all. You're wrong. A company has
introduced catnip-scented wrapping paper. By JEANNIE KEVER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-NICKELODEON (Undated) _ Empowered by rocketing ratings and a
hit movie spin-off, Nickelodeon is teaming up with the Children's
Television Workshop to launch Noggin, the first 24-hour kids'
``thinking channel.'' Besides being offered on standard cable,
Noggin will be both a digital network and an on-line site. By BRUCE
WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   LUCINDA-MUSIC-PROFILE (Houston) _ In the title track of Lucinda
Williams' latest album, ``Car Wheels on a Gravel Road,'' a little
girl looks out of the rear window as a car pulls away, ``little bit
of dirt, mixed with tears ...'' Williams has said she was trying to
tell a story in the song. Only later did she realize that it was
the story of her own childhood. Forty years down the road, Williams
is still staring out the rear window. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS-THEATER-REVIEW (Houston) _ They're no angels, the Devil's
Island convicts who make up the title trio in Sam and Bella
Spewack's ``My Three Angels.'' Alfred and Jules are killers, while
Joseph is merely a fraud, forger and all-around crook. Ah, but
there were mitigating factors in the murders. By EVERETT EVANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DREXLER (San Francisco) _ After a 15-year NBA career that
included a world championship, 10 All-Star Game selections and the
honor of being chosen as one of the 50 greatest players of all
time, Clyde Drexler had a pretty clear notion what he wanted to do
in retirement: ``I'd be on about the 10th green right now, heading
out the back nine, trying to shoot a 72,'' he said. By JORGE L.
ORTIZ.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-YOUNG-NORTON (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ Ken Norton Jr., in the
wake of the gruesome injury to teammate Bryant Young, is beginning
to sound like a man who is losing his taste for the violent world
of professional football. By BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-YOUNG-INJURY (San Francisco) _ Bryant Young's freakish
double-bone snap was the result of a few normal events on the
football field that combined to create a one-in-a-million injury.
The injury is rare among all athletes, including football players.
By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Ellen DeGeneres and partner Anne
Heche say they're tired of anti-gay prejudice in Hollywood and
they've decided to move to either San Francisco or Ojai. Ojai,
what's that? A sport played in Miami? Ellen, we want you. Move to
San Francisco. Who else can beat Willie Brown? By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCE-CHARLES (San Francisco) _ As Prince Charles celebrated
his 50th birthday last month, I felt he deserved a word of thanks.
One of the most important roles of any prince is to be a great
romantic hero, and, over the years, Prince Charles has seldom let
me down. By DIANA RATHBONE.
</P>
