<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A three-ring impeachment circus
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The House impeachment hearings are vacillating between farce and
slow-motion attempted coup.
</P>
<P>
   For farce, there was the Judiciary Committee's vote to expand
its inquiry into fund-raising for the Clinton re-election _ on the
day when Federal Elections Commission auditors recommended record
paybacks from both the Clinton and the Dole campaigns for similar
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   As coup, the same party-line vote to expand the impeachment
scope enlists the committee in the ceaseless effort of Clinton's
political opponents _ for which read, mainly, Clinton-haters _
first to find any excuse to undo the president's election and, when
that failed, then to unravel his re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's dip into campaign funding continues the
one-sided political show trials the GOP has been staging for two
years in a series of congressional hearings. It would be one thing
if the investigations were aimed at reforming the corrupting
influence of outsized special-interest money and the grubbing for
it that begrime our politics, but the GOP leadership has made it
emphatically plain it wants no part of changing the system, which
bankrolls Republicans far more generously than Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the game has been to use Democratic excesses _ more
egregious than Republican ones in '96 but not different in kind _
as merely a means to partisan ends. Now the impeachment panel, too,
is putting its shoulder to that mired wheel, in hopes of getting
the tumbrel rolling toward the guillotine again.
</P>
<P>
   And all this atop the Red Queen parody of jurisprudence that
marked the committee's Starr-struck thralldom to the report and the
testimony of the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has produced no corroborative evidence or
questioned any key witnesses itself. It has heard no rebuttal
witnesses. Its majority is apparently prepared to vote for
impeachment solely on the word of prosecutor Kenneth Starr and on
his at-points tendentious reading of the record _ and never mind
that Starr himself has his information second-hand from assistants.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans pretend special outrage that in response to the
81 loaded questions they asked him, Clinton dared to continue
dodging and weaving, defending himself especially against a
possible post-presidency indictment for perjury. Like Starr, the
majority reads Clinton's failure to confess as an obstruction of
justice. Any Soviet court would have understood.
</P>
<P>
   With House Speaker Newt Gingrich fading from command like
yesterday's bugle call and Speaker-designate Robert Livingston
apparently reluctant to have his fingerprints either on impeachment
or its failure, the Judiciary Committee increasingly looks panicky,
unfocused, disorganized and daily more at the mercy of its
anti-Clinton ultras.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Henry Hyde is presiding over one after another
on-camera meltdown as committee members _ when they bother to show
up, that is _ trade insults, hurl accusations at one another and
act out in ways that would exasperate a kindergarten teacher. What
we have here is impeachment as the Jerry Springer show. Without the
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0926 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-CO     12-03 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Baseball shows its ugliness again
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Dec. 6, 1998.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and the New York Yankees
did their things this past summer and fall, they gave back to the
game of baseball a soul that has been lacking for some years.
Several weeks later, baseball showed that soul was only temporary;
that it's still a giant, nasty business not beyond the rawest of
moves to reach its goals.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem only minor that baseball took away the 2000 All-Star
game from South Florida and awarded it to Atlanta. But beneath it
lies something that should concern any city with a major league
team, or one hoping to get one.
</P>
<P>
   It's about a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Millionaire owners, awash in the flush of network and cable TV
money, rarely reach into their pockets to pay for their own
facilities. Some steal out of town in the middle of the night
(Baltimore Colts, Cleveland Browns) to relocate their franchises to
cities hungry enough for a team to mortgage their treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   Others take the issues to the voters and, in efforts to convince
a wary electorate, use creative threats to reach their goals. Among
those was the recently concluded issue in Denver, where the Super
Bowl champion Broncos of the NFL sought a new stadium to replace
the one that is sold out week after week after week.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign to gain public favor for a new stadium, it
became ``news'' that if the stadium issue was not approved, a
wealthy Houston businessman was interested in buying the team and
moving it to Houston, which recently lost its team to Nashville _
or is it Memphis?
</P>
<P>
   I always thought it a ruse. The fact that the Broncos had just
won the Super Bowl and were undefeated at the time of the vote on
Nov. 6 played the more significant role in getting overwhelming
voter approval.
</P>
<P>
   In South Florida, where the Marlins won a World Series
championship in 1997, then auctioned off its players the following
year _ thereby creating one of the worst teams in baseball history
_ existing owner Wayne Huizenga knew he could not get the public to
spend for yet another stadium. He already had gone to the public
treasury to build a new arena for his NHL team, while a short hop
down the road, another wealthy owner, Micky Arison of the NBA's
Miami Heat, did the same with a basketball arena being constructed
in downtown Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga said he was selling the Marlins because he didn't think
he could get a new stadium built. He was right. Over a period of
testy negotiations, Huizenga reached an understanding with
commodities broker John W. Henry for sale of the team for $158
million. (There are some who still doubt that Huizenga actually
will complete the deal.) Henry, of course, says he, like Huizenga,
needs a new stadium, most of it with public money, so he can have
some left to buy better players _ and pay them $10 million a year
to maybe hit .275.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the millennium year 2000 All-Star game,
awarded in 1995 to South Florida. Without warning, Major League
Baseball last week yanked the game from South Florida, explaining
that it had to do with the uncertainty of the franchise ownership
and the fact that baseball likes to reward cities with new
stadiums, Atlanta among them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no such condition was put down when the game
originally was awarded to South Florida, and the entire argument
seems a bit balmy when you realize the 1999 All-Star game is being
played in Boston's Fenway Park, built three-quarters of a century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   What's behind this is pressure by baseball and its owners to get
the people of South Florida to again pass the hat for millionaires.
When a new stadium is built, baseball told South Florida, they'll
get an All-Star game there as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Sports, even down at the collegiate level, has become a cold,
ruthless business. Baseball just reneged on about $45 million worth
of All-Star business to a community that is now expected to
genuflect and respond to the fictional ``Field of Dreams'' request:
``Build it and we will come.''
</P>
<P>
   On that basis, I doubt there will be an All-Star game in South
Florida in the next millennium, either.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
