<HEADER>
A1064 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRINCE-CHARLES-HNS &LR;      12-03 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCE-CHARLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIL TO THE PRINCE OF WALES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DIANA RATHBONE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As Prince Charles celebrated his 50th birthday
last month, I felt he deserved a word of thanks. One of the most
important roles of any prince is to be a great romantic hero, and,
over the years, Prince Charles has seldom let me down.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have dreamt, watching his Cinderella-like wedding,
that he was secretly harboring an illicit passion for Camilla
Parker Bowles, wife of an erstwhile commander of his mother's
household cavalry, who was sitting right there in the middle of the
congregation? Or that this frumpy doyenne of the hunting, shooting
and fishing set would turn out to be such a great romantic heroine?
</P>
<P>
   And yet, there she is, a wrinkled Anna Karenina in Wellington
boots, a gray-haired Madame Bovary, defiantly sacrificing the
British monarchy to the throes of her passion, giving renewed hope
that there really is sex and romance after 50, and that it is not
reserved for men only.
</P>
<P>
   People may disapprove; the consensus among my friends seems to
be that ``Camilla shouldn't have done it,'' that she deserves all
the misery and social ostracism she has received. Whereas it seems
to me that, just like Madame Bovary, she had no choice _ she had to
do it. Otherwise, she would have betrayed the essence of life
itself.
</P>
<P>
   My second cousin once removed, Basil Rathbone, played the cruel
and cold-hearted Karenin to Greta Garbo's Anna in an early movie of
the novel. He has my father's mouth, which I too have inherited,
leaving me to watch, outraged, as Karenin coldly bent to kiss his
passionate wife. How could those lips have touched Anna's, lips
that are, after all, my own, and not find one ounce of arousal? No
wonder she fell in love with Vronsky.
</P>
<P>
   When Princess Diana was alive, I could not help admiring her
Titanic battle with Camilla for Prince Charles, even though it was
hard to understand how such an eccentric, mild and thoroughly
unlikely looking man could inspire such strong passions. And now,
frozen in death, Diana remains the perfect arch-rival. Much as I
loved her for making mincemeat of the stuffy royal family,
ruthlessly using to her own advantage what my sister would call a
bunch of North American psych-babble, Diana was, I believe, at
heart, a Machiavellian figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell has no fury like a woman scorned,'' nor yet like the
vengeful Diana, intent on stealing the throne to punish her spouse
for his wayward passions. She reminds me of the goddess Fricka in
Wagner's ``Die Walkurie,'' whose job it was to uphold the legal
straitjacket of marriage in the face of Wotan, her straying
husband.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Queen Elizabeth is, of course, in trouble on all fronts.
Hopelessly outclassed by the devious and beautiful Diana, in death
even more so than in life, the queen must also be, I should
imagine, thoroughly, deeply and venomously jealous of Camilla. I
suspect that, not unlike the wise but pinched Dowager Duchess of
Tintagel in Edith Wharton's ``The Buccaneers,'' her steely
disapproval of her wayward son has less to do with any harm he is
causing to the monarchy than with the fact that, like the dowager,
she has never once allowed herself to abandon duty for the passion
of romance.
</P>
<P>
   I think it is this need to follow one's heart, especially in the
image-conscious `90s, that explains Jane Austen's sudden
popularity. She may not have understood the glories of elopement,
passion and illicit sex _ there is always some woman in her novels
that does this, but she is flighty and silly and the man a no-good
will-o'-the-wisp _ but she is nevertheless a fervent advocate for
romantic love. All her heroines manage to subvert the neurotic and
mercenary mating dance surrounding them, marrying instead
delicious, goose-bump handsome men, escaping the fury of the
squawking matchmakers and fortune hunters scuttling all around.
</P>
<P>
   And so my secret hope is that Camilla and Charles will elope to
John o' Groats (the British version of Reno and the quickie
marriage), returning radiant and triumphant to what will certainly
be an interesting moral and constitutional pickle for the
Archbishop of Canterbury; that Diana's son William will ascend the
throne, enshrining his mother's wounded beauty in our collective
memory, and that the queen will finally get bored with her
passionless life and have a wild affair with a uniformed and
handsome member of the horse guards, meeting secretly in her
beloved, straw-filled stables, providing living proof to senior
citizens everywhere that life isn't over till it's over.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, thank you, Prince Charles, for fulfilling my
dreams. Please don't stop, and I wish you a very happy birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1246EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN04-COX     12-03 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good news, Texas; you can strike stupidest law from books
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The folks at Texas A&AMP;M have done their best at
wiping out boll weevils and grubs. They've made headway against
fire ants and web worms. But only now can they confirm an outright
bio-eradication.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough was announced to a bonfire rally last week, not
by an entomologist but by a tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Football player Dan Campbell said he was glad to attend a school
where ``men like women and women like men.'' Scientists no doubt
are catching planes this week to find out how A&AMP;M has cured
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation is a stunner, and certainly a relief. Whatever
A&AMP;M has done it must share with lawmakers in Austin. With
homosexuality cured, as its first item of business, the 76th Texas
Legislature can revoke Texas' stupidest law.
</P>
<P>
   Is the cure for homosexuality a serum? If so, vials can be
rushed to the University of Texas. Some took the Aggie's comments
to imply that UT is sorely blighted. Campbell and A&AMP;M officials
have apologized to all offended by the comments, but wait.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we know you can take a sampling of 34,000 average
collegians, do whatever A&AMP;M did with them, and have every one march
straight, well ...
</P>
<P>
   That means we don't need Texas' sodomy law.
</P>
<P>
   Court dockets spared?
</P>
<P>
   That means two Houston men shouldn't have to go on trial for
touching each other in ways outlawed by the state.
</P>
<P>
   That means a Houston lawman wouldn't have to testify exactly how
not-OK the touching was, there among consenting adults.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Texas Supreme Court and the U.S. Supreme Court
wouldn't have to sit down to review the touching, as opponents of
this ridiculous law want to force the justices to do.
</P>
<P>
   Our courts and our police ought to deal with crimes that have
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is one of 19 states with anti-sodomy laws. There's one
fewer as of last week. The Georgia Supreme Court struck down that
state's law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot think of any other activity that reasonable persons
would rank as more private and more deserving of protection from
governmental interference than consensual, private, adult sexual
activity,'' said Georgia's chief justice. The Georgia case, but the
way, did not involve homosexual conduct. It involved a male and a
female. Texas is one of five states whose anti-sodomy laws apply
only to homosexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Their privacy obliterated
</P>
<P>
   What were John Lawrence and Tyrone Garner doing in Lawrence's
Houston apartment the night of Sept. 17? None of Texas' business.
</P>
<P>
   A Harris County deputy responding on an unrelated matter entered
the unlocked apartment and saw what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   Showing uncommon courage, these two men decided to face the
music and then step out into the national light challenging the
law.
</P>
<P>
   They pleaded no contest, were fined $125 each by a justice of
the peace, and then filed their appeal. Good luck to them.
</P>
<P>
   No one should have to face this. Texas lawmakers should see to
it. They should stand up for the right of privacy. But they won't.
Some will be spineless. Some will be beholden to pious forces that
put them there.
</P>
<P>
   A serum for homosexuality? Don't be ridiculous. It's not a
disease spread through the air.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of life's mysteries. It bothers many sensibilities.
Many would like to wish it didn't exist or that advisories of
righteous damnation would make us all the same.
</P>
<P>
   People's emotions can no more be controlled by vaccine than by
nonsensical laws.
</P>
<P>
   Dare we run a dragnet at A&AMP;M to check on who's pairing up with
whom? Of course not. It's none of our business. However, I imagine
a census would surprise.
</P>
<P>
   John Young's column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail
address: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com. He is opinion page editor at
the Waco Tribune-Herald in Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1246EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
