<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMNESTY-HUMAN-RIGHTS-     12-03 1654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMNESTY-HUMAN-RIGHTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HUMAN RIGHTS, AMERICA, THE PILLAR OF DEMOCRACY, MUST PRACTICE
WHAT IT PREACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.) 
 &HT;    
 By PIERRE SANE  
 c.1998 Emerge  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; __ NOTE: Amnesty International, the world's premier
human-rights organization and recipient of the 1977 Nobel Peace
Prize, is sponsoring a yearlong campaign to spotlight human-rights
violations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The group has monitored U.S. abuses since the 1960s, but the
1999 campaign is Amnesty's first effort to focus worldwide
attention on these violations. Its priorities are police brutality,
prison conditions, the death penalty and the treatment of asylum
seekers.
</P>
<P>
   It also wants the United States to ratify without reservation
certain international treaties, including the Convention on the
Rights of the Child, and to better monitor U.S. foreign weapons
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Sane, the London-based secretary-general, is primary
spokesman for the group, which has 1 million members, 300,000 of
them in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sane, a native of Dakar, Senegal, has pursued doctoral studies
at Carleton University in Ottawa, Canada and holds an M.S. in
public administration and public policy from the London School of
Economics. He joined Amnesty International in 1988, and became
secretary-general in 1992. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   .................................
</P>
<P>
   What Amnesty International has documented in our research, and
this is over the years _ since the first 17 reports that we have
issued _ are a number of violations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Because the United States prides itself on being the land of
liberty and the land of democracy, people believe bad things may be
happening but only as isolated incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Our concern now is that there is a deterioration of the
human-rights condition. The United States has the highest
incarceration rate in the world, 1.7 million prisoners, including
79,624 women. And those numbers have really rocketed since the
'80s. The death penalty is used more and more frequently, with less
and less mercy. Juvenile offenders are executed. Mentally ill
people are executed.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions in the prisons are deteriorating. We find cells that
have vermin. Overcrowding is leading to violence of inmates on
inmates, and guards failing to protect inmates from violence, as
well as violence by the guards _ physical assaults, sexual assaults
on women. The use of technology such as stun guns and pepper spray
is on the increase.
</P>
<P>
   And complacency, coupled with the legitimate concern of the
population for safety and the spread of drug use, is manipulated by
politicians. All of this is further eroding human-rights protection
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   During 1999, the members of Amnesty International will be
engaging in an awareness-raising campaign. We want other
governments and intergovernmental bodies to fulfill their
obligations to the American people. We want other governments to
challenge the U.S. government to put its house in order.
</P>
<P>
   When I meet Mexico's secretary of foreign affairs, I'll say:
``When you visit the United States and meet with your counterpart,
you should raise your concerns regarding the deteriorating
human-rights condition in the United States.'' Our members also
will be writing letters, expressiong concerns and targeting
Congress, state governors and police chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, I think people would agree that the United
States uses double standards. In the Middle East, people will often
discuss the way the United States deals with Israel, on the one
hand, and Iraq, on the other, in terms of the implementation of
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   In western Europe, people find it shocking that the United
States is the only Western industrialized country that continues to
use the death penalty, especially against juvenile offenders and
mentally impaired people.
</P>
<P>
   In many countries of Asia, there is a resistance to human rights
because they perceive that the United States is instrumentalizing
human rights for other purposes, not necessarily out of real
concern for the well-being of the Chinese people, or the Malaysian
people.
</P>
<P>
   They say, ``Why should the United States have concerns regarding
the treatment of prisoners in China when its own prisoners in the
United States are treated in this way?'' They believe it's totally
hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. image internationally is also changing through the life
experiences of asylum seekers who, fleeing persecution, come to
what they believe is the land of freedom and find themselves locked
up in jail. For many in America, the promise of equal rights for
all is still a fake promise.
</P>
<P>
   When asylum seekers came from Russia and Communist states, they
were welcome because the United States was using it to show the
superiority of the country, with people fleeing dictatorships.
</P>
<P>
   Now the same people are fleeing the same dictatorships, but they
are coming from Latin America, Africa and Asia. They are seeking
asylum for exactly the same reasons that led people from eastern
Europe to seek asylum. Instead of being protected and granted the
level of protection to which they are entitled under international
law, they are treated like criminals. And this is because they are
black, Hispanic or Asian.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics in Amnesty International's report show that you are
more likely to face the death penalty for crimes in which the
victim is white. The black population, compared to its total
percentage, is overrepresented on death row. And I have visited
death row in Texas and Pennsylvania _ there is no millionaire on
death row.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, those who end up on death row, in large part, had
totally inadequate legal representation. People are fighting for
their lives but they don't have the means to have adequate legal
representation, and they end up being sentenced to death. So from
poverty and being black, you are at risk in America.
</P>
<P>
   We believe that the best way to eliminate racism and poverty is
to ensure the full respect for all human rights. The Universal
Declaration of Human Rights contains the set of rights that are
guaranteed to everyone, and which governments have an obligation to
meet. Human rights are a way to preserve peace and ensure justice,
and also a way to help heal nations and improve the interaction
among members of just societies.
</P>
<P>
   When the U.S. Congress admonishes Turkey, Colombia, Cuba and
other nations, it does so on the basis of international
human-rights law. When the State Department publishes annual
reports on human rights around the world, they are based on
international treaties.
</P>
<P>
   International human-rights law IS the United States of America.
It's the United States that chaired the committee that drafted the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights in 1948. It's the United
States that took the lead in establishing the International
Tribunal at Nuremberg. So the United States has been the lead actor
in the development of international law.
</P>
<P>
   It's very difficult to develop standards when the United States
opposes them and uses its influence to twist the arms of many of
its allies. As a result, these treaties are developed by consensus
and, once developed, they are used by the United States as a
yardstick against which to judge others.
</P>
<P>
   The United States cannot be above the law. The Convention on the
Rights of the Child prohibits explicitly the execution of juvenile
offenders, defined as young persons under 18. Those children
require special protection, and when they commit a crime, the
convention reads that they should not be executed. When the United
States does that, it is in breach of the convention. Since 1990
only six countries have executed juveniles: Iran, Saudi Arabia,
Yemen, Pakistan, Nigeria and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I met a woman from Chicago who gave testimony for
Amnesty's report about being shackled in leg irons when transported
from prison to the hospital to give birth. And she was shackled
during labor for seven and a half hours.
</P>
<P>
   I can't understand the logic of the system that shackles women
while they are giving birth. I can understand that some prisoners
may be dangerous and you need to protect others and protect the
prisoners from harming themselves. But a woman who is giving birth
cannot be thinking about trying to escape or harm herself. Why
should she be contained in shackles? Women give birth in prison
every year.
</P>
<P>
   Among Amnesty's recommendations is to increase police
accountability by ensuring that we have effective methods of
oversight. Another is to develop and enforce standards for the
treatment of prisoners. We need to ban the use of stun belts and do
serious research into the use of pepper spray. There's no reason to
jail asylum seekers; these are not criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, we want to abolish the death penalty, but in the
meantime, we think that juveniles should not be executed. Mentally
impaired people should not be executed, and resources should be
provided for legal aid for the impotent. People fighting for their
lives in the courts have the worst legal conditions; that is
totally unfair.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This commentary is adapted from an interview conducted by
Marcia Davis, senior editor at Emerge magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1252EST &QL; 
