<HEADLINE>
TALKING TOY MAY NOT BE THE IDEAL GIFT FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With FURBY-AUTOPSY)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This holiday shopping season, adults are lining
up outside shopping malls at 3 a.m., pushing and shoving in hopes
of buying a small, Gremlin-like interactive toy known as the Furby.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Internet sites have been created to pay homage to
the Furby, offering the speaking creature at more than double the
$34.99 list price.
</P>
<P>
   And a black market of early-buying brokers has sprung up,
offering overpriced Furbys through word of mouth and Internet chat
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're lighting up our switchboard, that's for sure,'' said
Mark Cloud, operations manager at the FAO Schwartz toy store in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud said the store was avoiding the unruly lines of
angst-ridden parents by keeping a waiting list. Furbys are doled
out as they come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can put you on the list,'' Cloud said. ``But you wouldn't
see a Furby until sometime in late January.''
</P>
<P>
   The Furby is an owlish, long-eared, plush toy, filled with
switches, sensors and computer chips, hailing from somewhere up in
the clouds, according to the instruction manual. When filled with
four AA batteries, its eyes open, it lets out a sigh, and then
begins yammering in ``Furbish,'' a nonsensical language in which
``may-may'' means ``love.''
</P>
<P>
   Put Furby in the dark and it goes to sleep _ after a bit of
snoring. It bobs up and down to music. It asks for food. It burps.
It laughs when it's tickled. It can play a rudimentary form of hide
and seek. It also integrates, over time, English phrases into its
vocabulary, simulating learning.
</P>
<P>
   All the hype has made the Furby the hottest toy of the season,
much like the Tickle Me Elmos and Power Rangers of seasons past.
</P>
<P>
   Yet experts question whether all the hype is a good thing for
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents think buying a material object, like a Furby, is going
to somehow put their kids ahead of the game,'' said Elizabeth
Lloyd-Mayer, a child development psychoanalyst who teaches at the
University of California at Berkeley and the University of
California at San Francisco Medical Center. ``It's a very
unfortunate reading of what kids really need.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark I. Levy, an assistant clinical professor and chairman
of the San Francisco Foundation for Psychoanalysis, said the Furby
fever was a result of two modern-day family ailments he encounters
again and again in his practice: guilt and neediness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of parents are enormously guilty about their
kids, for a variety of reasons,'' Levy said. ``Single parents are
invariably working, and couples in general are spending more time
out of the home, at their jobs or whatever. It creates a tremendous
sense in them that they're abandoning their children.''
</P>
<P>
   That guilt, Levy said, isn't unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children do feel abandoned,'' he said. ``They are left with
other caregivers, and they feel like they're no longer any sort of
a priority with the adults in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   These parents, Levy said, use the holidays as an attempt to set
things right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's makeup time, big time,'' said Levy, who compared the
parents who splurge on holidays to the ``weekend dad syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Needy children need time, not stuff,'' he said.
``Unfortunately, for most parents, time can be the most difficult
thing they can give.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, where there are Furbys there will be buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the coolest toy ever,'' said Rick Washburn, who works at
the Charles Schwab brokerage house in San Francisco. ``Totally
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn said that he, together with two co-workers, bought five
Furbys when they hit the shelves in October, selling two of the
$34.99 toys later for $180 on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned my lesson two years ago, when Tickle Me Elmo came
out,'' Washburn said. ``I totally misjudged how popular it would
be. Come Christmas Day, I was the daddy without the toy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
