<SLUG> BC-FURBY-AUTOPSY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FURBY, INSIDE AND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you are planning to wait in line all night to
buy a Furby, you might as well have some idea of what you are in
for. We dissected a Furby to find out what makes it tick.
</P>
<P>
   Name: Unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Race: Furby, electronic toy.
</P>
<P>
   Height: Approximately 6 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Weight: About 1 pound.
</P>
<P>
   DOB: Unknown, but sometime after the February 1998 American
International Toy Fair in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Next of kin: Inventor Dave Hampton, a 46-year-old programmer who
lives in an undisclosed Western national park, where he uses a gas
generator to run his computer.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy technique: Generally accepted Furby autopsy procedure,
as described in the Furby Autopsy Web site (www.phobe.com/furby).
</P>
<P>
   Exterior: No apparent signs of trauma. Large Furby face is
owl-like in nature, apparently resembles owls seen by inventor
Hampton near his home. The Furby is covered by a loose fur skin,
which is 100 percent polyester according to a manufacturer's tag.
Cutting a plastic loop under the tail frees up the skin, which can
then be pulled off over the top of Furby's head. Underneath the
polyester is a hard, black plastic exoskeleton, attached by a
number of small Phillips screws.
</P>
<P>
   Musculature: A series of cams, springs and levers, working off a
single motor, drive the Furby's motion. Manipulating the gears
indicates that they account for the toy's rocking back and forth on
its base, opening and shutting its eyes, waving its ears and moving
its beak.
</P>
<P>
   Brain: There are three unidentified microprocessor chips on a
circuit board which rests underneath the motor and gears. One chip
is wired directly to the Furby's side-mounted microphone,
apparently enabling Furby to respond to noise.
</P>
<P>
   The main processor probably contains the code that enables the
toy to put together about 800 phrases from a 200 word ``Furbish''
vocabulary. According to the instruction manual, Furby will begin
using English words over time, simulating a learning process. Two
computer daughter boards, with smaller custom processors, are
present.
</P>
<P>
   Organs: The Furby's interior contains an array of microswitches
and sensors that allow it to interact with its owner. There is also
an infrared send/receive sensor array in the forehead, that can
send data to another Furby, enabling them to begin talking in
unison. Switches on the head, front and back let Furby respond to
petting. A motion switch on its computer board lets the Furby
respond with a ``whoa!'' when it's picked up. In the base is room
of four AA batteries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
