<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SAY CHEAP OIL WILL SOON BE A MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oil prices are so low these days that Americans buy gas-guzzling
sport utility vehicles with impunity and ditch wood stoves they
once installed to save energy. Meanwhile, the oil industry feels
the pain, as Exxon plans to buy Mobil to cut costs _ and an
estimated 9,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But enjoy the oil glut now, because Earth's conventional crude
oil reserves are almost half gone, according to several energy
analysts. Sometime early in the next century, they predict oil
output will begin to decline, ushering in an age of rising fuel
prices and, possibly, political tension.
</P>
<P>
   Already, global oil consumption far outstrips discovery of new
oil fields, and countries such as the US and Canada are past their
peak output. Meanwhile, OPEC nations, whose embargo on sales to the
US caused drastic price hikes in the 1970s, are seizing a bigger
share of the oil market again, potentially increasing their ability
to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There always will be more oil to be found, but it's not going
to make up the difference of what is being extracted,'' warns James
J. MacKenzie of the World Resources Institute, a Washington think
tank, who expects the oil decline to begin between 2010 and 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts say that MacKenzie is too gloomy, but even they
agree that consumers worldwide are enjoying a rare bubble that has
to pop eventually. The collapse of Asian economies last year
reduced global demand for oil, while OPEC has been unable to limit
its members' output, flooding the world with oil.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, average gas prices in the US dipped below $1 a
gallon last month, lower in inflation-adjusted terms than in 1973,
when the OPEC oil embargo started what became known as the Energy
Crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are short term circumstances because of the problems in
Asia and some warm weather and a complete failure by OPEC members
to be able to do anything about it,'' said Henry Jacoby, an energy
economist at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   The US Energy Information Administration anticipates a 60
percent increase in world oil prices by 2007 as the Asian economies
recover and today's artificially low prices disappear.
</P>
<P>
   But the notion of an end to cheap oil is largely lost on
American consumers for the moment as US energy demand, and oil
imports, approach 1973 levels. Almost half of US oil consumption
fuels our vehicles, which have been getting lower fuel efficiency
as pickup trucks and sport utility vehicles surge in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite mounting concern that carbon dioxide from burning
fossil fuels may be warming the planet, there is no end in sight to
growing demand. The Energy Information Administration forecasts
that carbon dioxide releases from US energy use will be 47 percent
above 1990 levels by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are scared witless about trying to reduce oil
demand or even trying to control it. They'd rather go to war than
do that,'' said MacKenzie, author of the book ``Car Trouble,''
which calls for alternative vehicle fuels.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, doomsday forecasters have been predicting that oil
would run out for decades, only to be proven wrong by new
discoveries or improved oil recovery technologies. Today, oil
companies say that proven oil reserves are sufficient to last for
decades, not counting oil-laced sands and other unconventional
sources that could be tapped at a higher cost.
</P>
<P>
   But two longtime oil industry geologists sent shock waves
through the industry earlier this year when they predicted that
worldwide oil production would reach its peak within 10 years as
humans depleted the most easily accessible oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   Colin J. Campbell and Jean H. Laherrere, both 40-year oil
industry veterans with Petroconsultants of Geneva, estimate that
humans have consumed 800 billion barrels of oil so far, leaving
perhaps 1 billion barrels still in the ground. With demand rising
more than 2 percent a year, they predicted that oil companies would
pass the 50 percent depletion mark in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   As the oil supply shrinks, they said, prices will rise, and OPEC
nations such as Saudi Arabia and other Middle Eastern states could
control 50 percent of the world's oil business, giving them greater
power to increase prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is not running out of oil _ at least not yet. What
our society does face, and soon, is the end of the abundant and
cheap oil on which all our industrial nations depend,'' wrote
Campbell and Laherrere in the magazine Scientific American in
March.
</P>
<P>
   The pair called for rapid development of energy alternatives
such as nuclear power, renewable energy and conservation to ``help
postpone the inevitable decline of conventional oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts saw Campbell and Laherrere's article as the
latest version of ``The Poverty of Power'' and other books that
have wrongly foreseen the end of big oil. Critics said they had
overlooked new technology that allows oil companies to drill in
places such as the rough seas off Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colin Campbell is fostering a fraud on the public,'' said
MIT's Jacoby. ``He is looking at the wrong numbers. He is not
taking account . . . of all these resources out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Campbell and Laherrere are wrong, however, consumers
have reason to worry that oil prices will rise in the years to come
from such factors as government efforts to cut fossil fuel
emissions and the reduced competition that comes when the nation's
largest oil company merges with the second largest.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the two energy consultants are right, they argue, ``the
next oil crunch will not be so temporary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
