<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY IS TOPS IN BUYING BIG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes big stocks trading text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has your mutual fund gotten big?
</P>
<P>
   We don't necessarily mean the the size of the fund. We're
talking about the size of the stocks it owns.
</P>
<P>
   Big has been beautiful in the stock market for years. Big
stocks, particularly those that dominate the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index, continue to run circles around the rest of the market.
</P>
<P>
   We've written about how some funds at Fidelity Investments have
bulked up on big stocks like General Electric, Microsoft, and
Intel. But we lacked a good tool to closely measure individual
funds and compare them to competitors across town and around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Problem solved.
</P>
<P>
   We just got our hands on a computer software program called
Overlap, which can measure mutual funds against one another and
calculate the degree to which their equity investments overlap.
Using the Vanguard Index 500 fund as a proxy for the S&AMP;P 500 index,
we ran virtually every growth mutual fund of any size in Boston
through the process.
</P>
<P>
   The actively managed local fund with the greatest similarity to
the Vanguard 500 Index fund: Fidelity Magellan, with a 54 percent
overlap. The next six locally run funds of any size, ranked by
percentage overall, were also Fidelity funds.
</P>
<P>
   We knew a number of Fidelity funds would be high on the list.
The surprise: the degree to which Fidelity funds dominated.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven different Fidelity funds showed an overlap of at
least 40 percent. We could find only one local fund not run by
Fidelity that cracked the 40 percent barrier. The giant Putnam Fund
for Growth and Income weighed in at 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   We also measured the overlap in the world's 20 largest mutual
funds. Magellan and Fidelity Growth &AMP; Income, with a 46 percent
overlap, ran first and second on that list.
</P>
<P>
   Why bother measuring funds for their resemblance to the S&AMP;P 500?
Funds that bulk up on high-flying big stocks tend to come under
scrutiny by analysts who wonder whether managers are drifting away
from their stated investment style to chase bigger returns.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst cases, some fund managers are accused of being
closet indexers. Or are they just doing what investors pay for:
finding stocks that are going to appreciate the most?
</P>
<P>
   Most Boston-based mutual fund companies field a roster of
actively managed stock funds with overlaps ranging from 20 percent
to 40 percent, according to our calculations. Often small stock or
micro-cap funds generated lower overlap figures.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Financial Services, Pioneer Group, Scudder Kemper
Investments' Scudder funds, and State Street Research and
Management each had only one sizable fund with an S&AMP;P 500 overlap
of 30 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what managers are getting paid for; they should be
making investments they think can outperform the competition, which
is the S&AMP;P 500,'' said Kevin Parke, chief equity officer at MFS.
</P>
<P>
   We heard similar comments from David Eisenberg, chief equity
strategist at John Hancock Funds.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity isn't talking to us these days, but the last time we
chatted with funds chief Robert Pozen he made several points about
big stocks. He said there was no big-stock mandate issued from
above, that fund managers were making their own decisions, and, in
every case, big-stock buyers were well within the limits of their
funds' investment rules.
</P>
<P>
   Other Fidelity watchers tend to agree. ``Even at (Magellan's) 54
percent, that still leaves you a lot of leg room,'' said James
Lowell, editor of the Fidelity Investor newsletter. ``It's a very
prudent way to invest.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Fidelity's big-stock investing has been concentrated
among the very largest of the S&AMP;P 500 stocks. Fidelity is the
largest institutional investor in six of the 10 largest S&AMP;P 500
stocks and tops in each of the four biggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those stocks have been driving the S&AMP;P for the last couple
of years and the (performance) concentration is getting higher, why
not own them?'' said William Dougherty of Boston-based fund tracker
Kanon Bloch Carre.
</P>
<P>
   One other rationale: Many of Fidelity's funds are so big they
have to own lots of the largest, most liquid stocks available.
</P>
<P>
   A word about Overlap. Created by Bill Chennault, a Kansas City,
Kan., college administrator, it provides lots of information but is
not perfect. Data about specific funds is limited to the percentage
of assets that overlap and can be slightly dated. Most of the
Overlap information about local funds was based on portfolio data
from the spring and summer, but went back to January in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   Overlap was really created for avid investors and financial
planners to determine whether funds in a portfolio own too much of
the same things and mask a lack of diversification.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BIG BOYS &QL; 
(! used as column separator) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Actively managed local mutual funds with the largest percentage
investment overlap with the Vanguard 500 Index. &QL; 
Fund ! Portfolio date(1) ! Pct. overlap &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Magellan ! March ! 54  &QL; 
Fidelity Blue Chip Growth ! January ! 48  &QL; 
Fidelity Growth &AMP; Income ! January ! 46  &QL; 
Fidelity Fund ! June ! 45  &QL; 
Fidelity Adv Growth &AMP; Income ! May ! 45  &QL; 
Fidelity Equity-Income II ! May ! 43  &QL; 
Fidelity Large Cap Stock ! April ! 41  &QL; 
Putnam Fund for Growth &AMP; Income ! April ! 41  &QL; 
Fidelity Adv Equity Growth ! May ! 37  &QL; 
Hancock Independent Growth ! June ! 36  &QL; 
Fidelity Growth Co. ! May ! 36  &QL; 
Fidelity Equity Income I ! January ! 35  &QL; 
Fidelity Dividend Growth ! January ! 34  &QL; 
Pioneer Fund ! June ! 32  &QL; 
Scudder Large Co. Growth ! June ! 32  &QL; 
