<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' BATES STILL GETS NOWHERE FAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If speed alone equaled success, Shawn Bates might be
dominating the NHL today with his piston-like legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed kills,'' the 23-year-old center/wing likes to say. ``If
I can use it at the right time, it will only benefit me.''
</P>
<P>
   So went the brief conversation between Bates and Bruins coach
Pat Burns at the Bruins' practice rink outside of Boston Wednesday.
Burns talked. Bates listened. The conversation moved from
ice-filled rink to open, greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your speed's worth a million bucks,'' Burns told the former
Boston University standout after practice. ``But it's like the
farmer with the tractor out in the fields. Out there alone with no
one around him, he looks just fine. But take that tractor out on
Route 93 at 7:30 in the morning ... now that's a different story
altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Bates was doing a fine job in Providence, where he
was leading the Baby B's in scoring (12-8_20 in 15 games), but now
it's time for him to show that he can apply his speed and finesse
north of Providence. It's time to get his game in gear and make
certain the clutch doesn't slip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to use my legs and I've got to be smart about when
I'm using them,'' said Bates, who is expected to play on a line
with Anson Carter and Steve Heinze Saturday night when the Penguins
visit the FleetCenter. ``What it comes down to, I guess, is
one-on-one battles. Whether I'm forechecking, backchecking,
whatever _ I've got to beat their guy to the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns wanted to roll Bates out with Carter and Heinze Tuesday
night during the 1-1 tie with the Canucks, but the flu kept Bates
from playing what would have been his third game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really like to give Batesie a good shot,'' said Burns,
whose lineup always is in need of offensive enhancements, viable
options for a No. 2 scoring line behind Jason Allison-Sergei
Samsonov-Dmitri Khristich. ``He's got NHL speed, no question, and
he's also got a heck of a shot. Speed's the key, though. He flies
around out there in the drills, and then when the game comes, he
seems to get lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates earned a shot at the big time last September, his first
training camp out of BU, when he impressed the coaching staff with
his speed and his determination to dig along the boards and in the
corners. A couple of weeks into the season, his game dipped, his
legs stopped moving, and on Nov. 14, 1997, he was standing in
Providence with his big-time dream about to turn into a minor
league morass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down there and didn't have a solid year, so that didn't
help me,'' he recalled. ``That caused me to do a lot of thinking
over the summer, and I came in determined to go all out again.''
</P>
<P>
   Right thought. Wrong outcome. Midway through training camp, he
was dished back to the minors. But on Nov. 14 _ exactly one year
after his demotion last season _ he was summoned again to Boston,
with Burns immdediately reminding him to keep those legs moving
because there are only so many invitations to the dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can go out there and be a pain in everyone's neck, it
will get me in the lineup, I think,'' said Bates, who was crowned
the club's fastest skater in Sunday's skills competition,
completing one lap around the rink in 13.619 seconds. ``And show up
here every day ready to go, show in practice that you really
care.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same kind of prodding Burns applies to
sensation-in-waiting Joe Thornton. A year plus removed from junior
hockey, Thornton's game moves along in fits and starts. One night
he appears on the brink of getting it all together, his Berlitz
course of the boards finally making sense. The next night,
suddenly, everything's Greek to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're two opposites,'' said Burns. ``Batesie realizes he
has to do something, so he starts skating and does the wrong thing.
Away from the puck, he panics. Then there's Joe, who realizes he's
got to do something, but he just stops ... just stops and looks.
They're getting it, but they've got to keep at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
