<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1150 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUG-TREATMENT-BOS &LR;      12-03 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-TREATMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-EPILEPSY PILL SHOWS PROMISE IN ADDICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UPTON, N.Y. _ A small white pill, available as antiepilepsy
medicine in 60 countries but banned in the United States, might
help control cravings for cocaine, heroin, amphetamines, and even
cigarettes, according to several scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many drug treatments, the scientists say, the pill _ at
least in tests with animals _ does not seem to be addictive, nor
does it produce the withdrawal pains of other treatments.
</P>
<P>
   But the scientists emphasized that the pill is no magic bullet.
It has not been tested on humans, who often respond to experimental
drugs differently from animals.
</P>
<P>
   If human trials prove successful, a patient must want to quit
the addiction, the scientists said. Even then, most patients would
need to supplement the pill with drug counseling to prevent a
relapse.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery, announced Wednesday by scientists at the
Brookhaven National Laboratory in Upton, Long Island, is generating
more excitement among drug researchers than any medical news in
years.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Leshner, director of the National Institute on Drug Abuse,
which funds 85 percent of the world's research on addiction, called
the finding ``exciting and dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Most antinarcotic medicines work, at best, against one drug.
Methadone, for example, blocks the craving for heroin, but only
heroin. The significance of the Brookhaven study, Leshner said, is
that it uncovers and suggests a way to attack a ``common essence of
addiction.'' Many drug abusers are addicted to more than one
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Conan Korentsky, professor of pharmacology at Boston
University's School of Medicine, who has worked on drug treatments
for 50 years, has replicated some of Brookhaven's results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the drugs that have come up'' to treat addiction, he
said, the pill tested here, known as gamma-vinyl GABA, or GVG, and
sold under the name Vigabatrin, ``looks very interesting, more
interesting than the others.''
</P>
<P>
   GVG works by blocking sharp increases in the levels of dopamine,
a chemical in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have dopamine,'' said Stephen Dewey, chief author of a
paper that details the Brookhaven experiment. It was published
Wednesday in the scientific journal Synapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the `feel-good' neuro-transmitter . . . the thing that
lets us feel pleasure after a good meal or a fun movie,'' Dewey
said.
</P>
<P>
   When pushed to extremely high levels, dopamine induces euphoria,
a high that, at first, makes a person want to experience it again
and again, until the desire becomes a craving beyond control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like most, if not all, drugs of addiction raise
dopamine levels,'' Dewey said. ``The evidence certainly suggests
that's what makes them addictive.''
</P>
<P>
   In their experiments, Dewey and his Brookhaven colleagues got
several rats and primates addicted to cocaine or nicotine, then
gave them GVG. Brain scans found that GVG reduced their dopamine
levels. The animals' behavior indicated that GVG also diminished _
and, at higher dosages, eliminated _ their craving for the
addictive substances.
</P>
<P>
   The results with nicotine were published Wednesday. The results
with cocaine appeared in Synapse in August. At the time,
Vigabatrin, one drug company's brand name for GVG, was under review
as an antiepilepsy treatment by the US Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   However, in October, the FDA rejected the drug on the grounds
that it constricts peripheral vision in some users.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey noted that the dose of GVG needed to treat addiction is
much smaller than the amount needed for epilepsy. Where Vigabatrin
is prescribed for epilepsy, its users, mainly children, take 2 to 4
grams a day. To eliminate the craving for nicotine, Dewey
estimates, an adult would have to take only 200 milligrams a day _
1/10 to 1/20 as much.
</P>
<P>
   Quelling the need for cocaine would take 2 to 3 grams. However,
Dewey noted, the balance of risks and benefits, which the FDA
calculates in assessing a drug, might be different if it were the
only drug that suppressed cocaine addiction, as opposed to one of
many drugs that controlled epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Brookhaven has applied to the FDA for permission to conduct
limited human trials of GVG, which could begin early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey, meanwhile, is conducting further tests to see the effects
of GVG on alcohol and, soon after that, heroin.
</P>
<P>
   All of GVG's enthusiasts emphasize that even if the medicine
works in humans as well as in animals, it will not herald the end
of drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Volkow, head of Brookhaven's addiction-research department,
said: ``I do not think we will be able to cure addicts by giving
them a pill and saying, `OK, you're on your own.' ''
</P>
<P>
   By controlling dopamine levels, GVG blocks the high that a drug
produces. But if people want to get high, they will stop taking the
pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pill will help us integrate an addict into society, so it
increases the likelihood that he stops taking drugs,'' Volkow said.
``But beyond that, it depends on your alternatives in life. If you
take someone off cocaine but offer no alternatives and there's not
enough to engage him, he'll fall back on drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stress is the most important variable on whether you take
drugs,'' she continued. ``Stress causes biochemical changes, which
rewire pathways that make a drug more pleasurable. So you cannot
dissect biochemistry from sociology. . . . The environment produces
changes in the biochemistry of the brain that make it more
susceptible to drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Korentsky agrees. ``In people who want help, a little added
crutch may be all they need and this pill may give them that
crutch,'' he said. ``This will probably help people get off, and
maybe stay off, drugs. But we're not going to get rid of drug
abuse. . . . It's sort of like sex. If we had a war on sex, we'd
lose it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
