<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT-1204-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for FRIDAY, DECEMBER 3,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ Coverage if House Judiciary Committee
holds a hearing Thursday with FBI Director Louis Freeh and
prosecutor Charles LaBella. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Trying to outline an agenda for the
106th Congress of cutting taxes, fixing schools and preserving
Social Security, Republican leaders of the House and Senate could
not avoid the I-word Thursday. ``Is there a question other than on
impeachment that we could maybe (answer)?'' wondered Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott as reporters asked repeatedly about
coming developments in the congressional investigation of President
Clinton. ``No,'' replied a voice from the journalistic horde
crowded into Lott's Senate office. ``Nuts!'' laughed House
Speaker-elect Robert Livingston, who clearly indicated that he
would like the thorny issue settled before he officially replaces
Newt Gingrich when the new Congress convenes Jan. 6. (Dart, Cox
News Service 450).
</P>
<P>
   POLMONEY _ WASHINGTON _ The Federal Election Commission prepared
Thursday to reject its staff's recommendation that 1996
presidential candidates Bill Clinton and Bob Dole repay millions of
dollars in federal matching funds. The formal vote will be next
Wednesday or Thursday, but a daylong debate made it clear that
there are enough votes to block approval of the finding that Dole
and Clinton used party-paid TV ads to evade spending limits. The
impending decision illustrates the weaknesses of the current system
of policing campaign finance. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   LIVESTOCK-WASTE _ WASHINGTON _ More than 30 states _ including
Texas and North Carolina _ fail to prevent pollution from large
livestock and poultry operations, a new report says. The waste from
these ``animal factories'' fouls drinking water and threatens
public health, says the Natural Resources Defense Council, who
released the report Thursday. Livestock operators say the report
lacks scientific evidence and is just another attempt by
environmental groups to scare the public. (Moscoso, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Continuing spot coverage of the
Microsoft antitrust trial. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT _ ATLANTA _ U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
delivered the Rosalynn Carter Distinguished Lecture in Public
Policy at Emory University on Thursday. (Brice, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ANDREWS, N.C. _ FBI task force press briefing on the
search for Eric Rudolph. (Harmon, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUS-TEXAS-CONSTITUTION _ AUSTIN, Texas _A proposed new Texas
Constitution to be unveiled Friday by top lawmakers includes a
provision lengthening terms of office for legislators. The framers
want four-year terms for House members and six years for senators.
All lawmakers, however, would face term limits. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   AUS-BUSH-ISRAEL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush talks to
reporters about his trip to Israel at a morning briefing. (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   CODIS _ DNA, the genetic fingerprint that scientists call the
building block of life, is rapidly becoming the stumbling block of
the violent criminal. Major advances in the forensic analysis of
DNA are culminating with in the linkage of 40 now-separate state
databases containing thousands of DNA samples from known criminals
and criminal investigations, all under the administration of the
FBI. It's the Combined DNA Index System. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-INSURANCE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The state insurance plan
that pays for the health care of more than 100,000 retired public
school employees is about to go belly up, according to a
legislative report. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ELECTION-1204 _ TAIPEI, Taiwan _ This rough-and-tumble
democracy has drawn millions of Taiwanese into a furious 10-day
election campaign revolving around the unspoken issue of how to
avoid mainland China's smothering embrace. Multi-colored campaign
flags festoon every street. Trucks blare music and rhetoric day and
night. Staccato blasts of firecrackers signal a candidate's arrival
to yet another neighborhood. Fist-fights break out. Newspapers
bemoan ``vote-buying'' estimated at $50 a voter or more. And
doctors, teachers, old folks, laborers -- people of all ages and
pursuits -- walk away from giant political rallies hoarse and
exhilarated from participating in one of the world's most exuberant
democracies. Officially, the Taiwanese will go to the polls on
Saturday(Dec. 5) to decide the makeup of the 225-member national
legislature, as well as elect mayors and city council members in
their two biggest cities. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Resending for those who need it.
</P>
