<HEADER>
A1163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS &LR;      12-03 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_NEW STUDY CORRECTS OSTEOPOROSIS THEORIES  
 _HEART INSTRUMENT CUTS HOSPITAL ADMISSIONS  
 _SEIZURES DRUG EASES DAMAGE, PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 New study corrects osteoporosis theories
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to medical dogma, white women over age 50 are at
highest risk of bone-thinning osteoporosis and resulting fractures.
That's what the National Osteoporosis Foundation said last month in
its first-ever guidelines for recognizing, treating, and preventing
a disease that costs $14 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Not so. In fact, white women rank fourth among major US ethnic
groups on tests of marked bone loss, with more than 50 percent
having serious weakening of bone structure, according to results
from the largest study undertaken on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-American women are at highest risk, with 65 percent of
menopausal women having low bone density, followed by native
American women at 59 percent. African-Americans, who had long been
thought to be at low risk, ranked fifth. But still, 38 percent of
them have weakened bones if they are past menopause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your ethnicity does not protect you against osteoporosis,''
Dr. Ethel Siris of Columbia University said Wednesday in San
Francisco, where she presented the findings at an osteoporosis
meeting. ``This was a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, half of all post-menopausal American women have serious
bone disease. Those with actual osteoporosis _ the stage of bone
loss associated with imminent risk of fracture _ make up 7.2
percent of all women.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier notions about the risk of bone loss, Siris said, were
based on doctors' impressions that minority women don't suffer
fractures as often as whites. But this may be due to the greater
numbers of whites in physician practices, coupled with their
generally better access to care.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the first to assess bone loss among large numbers
of women from various ethnic groups. The results are based on
48,000 women with an average age of 65, but the study will
encompass at least 250,000 subjects. All will be followed for five
years to see how many suffer fractures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purpose is to increase awareness,'' Siris said. ``Primary
physicians are waiting for women to have a fracture before
evaluating them for osteoporosis. That's like waiting for someone
to have a stroke before taking their blood pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The study is funded by Merck &AMP; Co., which makes a leading
osteoporosis drug, but Siris said the investigators ``are not in
the business of selling drugs.'' The main message, she said, is
that doctors should screen older women for bone loss, using tests
costing $50 to $120 that Medicare began covering in July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Heart instrument cuts hospital admissions
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A super-electrocardiogram invented at New England Medical Center
can help doctors decide when it's safe to send a patient with chest
pain home, or admit him to a regular medical ward for observation
rather than to a coronary care unit.
</P>
<P>
   The innovation, reported in the current issue of Annals of
Internal Medicine, consists of software that extracts data from a
regular ECG and calculates the probability that a patient is having
a heart attack or serious shortage of blood to the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Tested in a study of nearly 11,000 patients with possible heart
attacks in 10 US hospitals, the instrument reduced unnecessary
hospital admissions from six to 100 percent, depending on the
institution. It reduced needless coronary care unit admissions from
16 to 50 percent. It did not result in any patient being sent home
or refused admission who really was suffering a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone is really sick or really well, you don't need a
probability calculation to tell you what to do,'' said Joni
Beshansky, one of the study authors. ``It's in the gray area where
you need guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   The device is used routinely at New England Medical Center and
some other hospitals, and the Food and Drug Administration has
recently approved its wider use. The researchers say it could
prevent 204,000 hospital admissions a year and 112,000 coronary
care unit admissions, for a total savings of $728 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Seizures drug eases damage, pain
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A drug called gabapentin, approved in 1994 for seizures, reduces
the pain of two hard-to-treat conditions: the nerve damage that
afflicts nearly half of all diabetics and the pain that persists in
up to 15 percent of people after a bout of shingles.
</P>
<P>
   Two studies in the current Journal of the American Medical
Association showed gabapentin reduced pain in such patients and
improved their ability to sleep and carry out daily activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
