<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, DEMOCRATS PROVOKE IMPEACHMENT BACKLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two weeks ago it appeared that the impeachment of President
Clinton had reached a dead end. Republicans, spooked by the midterm
election results and the consequent departure of House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, had all but given up. Democrats, emboldened by same,
offered up draft resolutions of ``censure.'' Talk of a deal was in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   Today it appears that the House of Representatives will vote in
the affirmative on one article of impeachment regarding
presidential perjury. House GOP head-counters now believe they have
a seven-vote majority to pass just such a measure. They are
increasingly adamant that a vote of the full House on this matter
occur before the end of the legislative session. And there are
equally adamant that there be no deal for censure.
</P>
<P>
   Three things changed the political dynamic. First, Democrats
seriously overplayed their hand when they turned Kenneth Starr's
testimony before the House Judiciary Committee into a 12-hour
inquisition into the independent counsel's professional conduct.
That performance, wrote National Journal editor Michael Kelly,
``was contemptible, really loathsome in its cynicism and in its
naked disdain for the evidence and for the law. From the opening
sneers of Mr. Lowell to the closing insults of Mr. Kendall, the
Democratic side made clear their absolute unconcern with anything
approaching a desire to discern the truth. All they cared about was
trashing Starr on television.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The treatment of Starr by the Democratic members,'' Kelly
continued, ``was striking for its relentless ugliness. Some members
were ugly and bombastic (Reps. Wexler and Nadler), some were ugly
and snide (Rep. Frank), some were ugly and incoherent (Rep.
Waters). But all were ugly.'' Kelly's view was widely shared by
congressional Republicans. More important, the ferocity of the
Democratic assault generated a huge backlash of support for Starr
from the GOP's core constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Second, incoming House Speaker Robert Livingston was disgusted
by the Democratic assault on Starr and acutely aware of the
reaction to it at the grass roots. Shortly thereafter, he let it be
known publicly and privately that censure was not really an option
and that he expected the House to vote either up or down on the
question of impeachment. Livingston also made it plain that he had
full confidence in the House Judiciary Committee's chairman, Henry
Hyde, and that he would support whatever Hyde decided was right.
</P>
<P>
   Third _ and this was the kicker _ President Clinton's
``responses'' to 81 questions submitted by the House Judiciary
Committee were released by the White House on the Friday after
Thanksgiving. The questions were designed to establish what lawyers
in appellate cases call a ``fixed set of facts.'' Clinton's answers
to these questions stunned GOP lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just that Clinton yielded not one inch of legal
ground. It wasn't just that Clinton continued to maintain that he
suffered from a new form of mental incapacity known as convenient
amnesia. It wasn't just that Clinton did nothing to hide his utter
contempt for the House Judiciary Committee's inquiry. What was so
astonishing to GOP members was the tone of the president's replies.
``It was like the Tom Wolfe book (``A Man in Full'') with the
workout specialist at the bank,'' said one Republican consultant.
``Clinton gave them the `unidigital salute.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The president's answers to the committee's questions were
quickly characterized by The New York Times as ``lies about
lying.'' That phrase caught on like wildfire up on Capitol Hill,
and by Tuesday of this week it was clear that the mood of the
members had changed. Republicans who were thought to be leaning
toward some sort of censure arrangement were now back in the
impeachment-for-perjury camp. To the surprise of the GOP
leadership, the head count even included three Democrats. Four or
five other Democrats were considered ``possible'' votes for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   By overplaying their hands and underestimating Speaker
Livingston, Democrats and President Clinton have all but guaranteed
a vote in the House on impeachment. It appears likely that the full
House will vote, by a slim majority, to impeach the president on
one count of perjury. The Senate will then take the House's action
under advisement. And there, the issue will die.
</P>
<P>
   This is probably the best possible result. Those who favor
allowing Clinton to remain in office will be satisfied. Those who
favor his impeachment will also be (at least partially) satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing Clinton out of office was never really an option. The
votes in the Senate were never there. A House vote of impeachment
for perjury would nevertheless stand as an indelible rebuke for
conduct unbecoming of an officer of the United States government.
It is a rebuke that President Clinton fully deserves. It would
haunt him through history.
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
