<SLUG> BC-CAREER-DECISIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH OUT FOR `INVISIBLE DECISIONS' IN CAREER MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sometimes the worst career decision you can make
doesn't feel like a decision at all. You're either deciding one
thing when you should be focused on a broader or more important
issue, or you lull yourself into a false sense of security when you
should be doing something to protect yourself or your job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call these `invisible decisions,''' said Ralph L. Keeney,
co-author with John S. Hammond and Howard Raiffa of ``Smart
Choices: A Practical Guide to Making Better Decisions.'' ``The
person doesn't realize they can create a choice situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeney said decisions often are triggered by specific events,
such as tragedies, layoffs or children reaching a certain age. He
added, though, that people often don't take the time to evaluate
their current situations at work and determine whether they can
make improvements.
</P>
<P>
   He said job hunters in particular often make three common
mistakes:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``They work on the wrong decision at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   People spend too much time in job interviews evaluating whether
the job sounds right for them, Keeney said. ``What they should be
thinking of is, `What should I be doing to get the offer?''' After
you know that the company wants you, you're in a stronger
bargaining position to try to make the job right.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not being clear about what skills they have and what they want
out of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I have to offer the employer? What do I hope to
experience? What's the scope of responsibility I will have?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Accepting the jobs that others have created.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeney said that sometimes people are better off thinking about
what in particular they want out of a job, then approaching
companies with that as a proposal. ``The key often is thinking of
the objectives of the employer.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeney said people who might otherwise be good at making
decisions can make mistakes because they are identifying the wrong
problems. Are you planning to move when all you really need is to
remodel your home? Is your commute really too long or does an
inflexible work schedule force you into a lot of traffic? Is your
salary too low or are you spending too much?
</P>
<P>
   To make sure that doesn't happen, he suggests people list all
the objectives they can think of that will be involved in a
particular decision. Then they should ask why that objective is
important, which may lead them to even more objectives. Then they
should ask how those objectives can be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Keeney said, if one of your objectives is a shorter
commute, that might lead you look for work closer to home. But if
you ask yourself why the shorter commute is important, the real
objective might be that you want more time to spend with your
children.
</P>
<P>
   How do you find more time to spend with your children? Maybe
with a company that encourages telecommuting or has flexible hours
or offers a condensed workweek or has on-site child care. If all
those things will meet your real objective, Keeney explained, then
you have a wider range of job options than if you simply look for
work closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't put restraints on your job search, you can later
reject anything that you don't like,'' he said. ``You can always
reject offers that you have, but you can't accept offers that you
didn't get.''
</P>
<P>
   Another mistake people often make is with ``anchoring,'' when
your mind gives too much importance to the first information it
receives, said Keeney, who is a professor of management and
engineering at the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   In their book, the authors give this example: ``How would you
answer these two questions?
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the population of Turkey greater than 35 million?
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your best estimate of Turkey's population?''
</P>
<P>
   When the authors posed similar questions to other groups, but
substituted ``100 million'' for ``35 million'' in the first
question, the typical answer to the second question shot up by many
millions.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason Keeney suggested both that you think about
your objectives before discussing them with friends and advisers,
and that you don't tell those people too much about your own
beliefs before they get a chance to give advice. If you don't cloud
their thinking, they might present alternatives that you hadn't
thought of.
</P>
<P>
   Once you decide what your objectives are, Keeney said it was
crucial to put them in writing so that all the elements of each
alternative are in front of you. You can then weigh the advantages
and potential consequences of each, and determine which elements
are the most important.
</P>
<P>
   He said it helped to cross off aspects that you consider ``even
swaps,'' so that you can boil the decision down to the major
differences. If you have two potential jobs that offer the same
salary, then you can cross ``salary'' off the list as a
consideration. But Keeney said you also should do that for
different elements you consider to be of equal value.
</P>
<P>
   People also need to understand how crucial the invisible
decisions are, Keeney said. If, for example, they procrastinate on
building their skills and ignore the waves of layoffs around them,
they are setting themselves up to be victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only control you have on your life is your
decision-making,'' he said. ``The rest just happens to you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
