<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OUTLOOK MUCH HEALTHIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Think of it as a glass figurine shattered in
a free fall. Little by little, you start piecing it back together.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Patriots' situation.
</P>
<P>
   Because 15 regular players have missed games and three others
have played injured, it is taking a while to piece the team back
together.
</P>
<P>
   When wide receiver Terry Glenn returned two weeks ago, the
change was dramatic because of the multitude of options quarterback
Drew Bledsoe suddenly had available. Now there's a good chance Troy
Brown will return after missing six games with a severe ankle
sprain.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is the big-play weapon, not to mention the NFL's top punt
returner (14.3-yard average).
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of his return, the team terminated the contract
of receiver Henry Ellard Wednesday and activated cornerback Kato
Serwanga off the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Things also are looking up on defense.
</P>
<P>
   End Willie McGinest has been in for only four plays in the last
six games. In the last five, the Patriots have sacked the
quarterback twice, putting excess responsibility on the secondary,
which allowed a ton of yardage.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest, suffering from a chronic groin pull, is inching his
way back into the lineup. While he was expected to miss the rest of
the season, he's showing signs that he may return much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even Sunday against the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was able to do some things in the warmups this morning,''
said defensive line coach Ray Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing everything I can can to get back out there and help
us win some games,'' said McGinest. ``I can't wait to be able to go
full strength. I'm tying to do some things out there in practice
this week, and we'll see how it responds. It's feeling better, but
this early in the week, it's hard for me say whether I can play or
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big game. It's against Pittsburgh, and I'd love to be
able to get back in there,'' added McGinest, who had 1 1/2 sacks
and eight tackles in the Patriots' 7-6 playoff loss at Pittsburgh
Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest would be a welcome addition against Kordell Stewart,
especially when the Steelers quarterback tries to escape to the
outside. McGinest's presence also would improve the pass rush
because he usually draws special attention, which opens up the rush
for the inside guys like Henry Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long haul for Brown, who first injured the ankle
Oct. 19 against the Jets after catching four passes for 41 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew threw me a pass out in the flat, and I caught it and
tried to turn with it,'' recalled Brown. ``When I turned, I didn't
put it away. I thought it was going to be a fumble, so I threw it
over my shoulder and I went to get it and the guy rolled over my
ankle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was bad, but it's been six weeks Monday, and the
report I got originally was that it was going to be six weeks
before I even ran again. I think I've taken big strides in a short
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown hadn't been hurt since he missed the Super Bowl two years
ago after a double-hernia operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm look foward to coming back out there,'' he said. ``It's
going to be a good, tough game in Pittsburgh. Their secondary is
playing well over there. Going up against Carnell Lake is a great
task. He's a great corner. He plays the inside guys in the nickel
package. That's gonna be tough coming off an injury, but I think
I've prepared myself well for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has been like an extra coach on the sidelines during his
convalescence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to offer tips during the game,'' he said. ``You see
them do certain things, and sometimes it gets a little repetitious
with the route running. I just tell (the receivers) to change it up
a bit. When I'm in there, I'm thinking of things to do to get open,
and when I'm on the sidelines, I'll say, `Coach, maybe you should
try doing this or that because he's overplaying this way or that
way.'''
</P>
<P>
   He knows that not everyone has the knack of getting open the way
he does. That's why Bledsoe said at his press conference Wednesday
that he felt it would be a major boost for the Patriots to have
Brown ready for Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different guys run routes different,'' said Brown. ``We've had
to move some guys who run outside and run them inside, so they
weren't used to playing inside. I've tried to help them out a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   He's assuming nothing but has been pushing the trainers and
coaches to let him play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been out this long,'' said Brown. ``It's tough. The
last two weeks, they've had a lot of fun, so you want to be a part
of that. When they go on road trips and leave you behind, that's
disappointing. But now I know I'll be back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
