<HEADER>
A1172 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STADIUM-SUPPORT-BOS &LR;      12-03 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-SUPPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARTFORD'S STADIUM QUARTERBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ When Robert Fiondella looks up from his desk
on the 12th floor of the Phoenix Home Life Mutual Insurance Co.,
the site of the proposed new stadium for the New England Patriots
is right outside the window. It is just past the proposed $1
billion Adriaen's Landing development that he has spent years
promoting.
</P>
<P>
   One can easily imagine the glimmering, distinctive shape of The
Phoenix _ the name of the building _ broadcast to the nation during
televised National Football League games. Such incidental marketing
is one reason Fiondella has been so enthusiastic about bringing
sports events to Hartford and central Connecticut for years.
</P>
<P>
   What began four years ago as a campaign to increase the name
recognition of his company has blended with his leadership role in
revitalizing the city. And now Fiondella, chairman of the Greater
Hartford Chamber of Commerce, wants the New England Patriots to
help him do both.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really view the Patriots being a part of Adriaen's Landing
as the catalyst for revitalizing the whole region and, to a lesser
extent, the whole state,'' Fiondella said during a recent
interview. ``I have always had an interest and involvement in
sports and in urban renewal, and, a few years ago, Hartford was at
the point where it needed a business person to try to help deal
with that challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if you look at cities that have gained teams,
that has been a real source of revitalization in all ways,
including economic,'' said Fiondella, a lawyer and a former town
councilman and redevelopment official in his lifelong hometown of
Bristol. ``And if you look at cities that have lost teams, they
have regretted losing them.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how the public will benefit from Connecticut
taxpayers' financing of the new stadium _ an investment of at least
$375 million, one of the most lucrative deals ever offered an NFL
owner _ Fiondella says he disagrees with studies that show sports
stadiums do little to attract new business or create jobs. He cites
few figures to support his view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the issue of the stadium is a lot like the issue of
advertising,'' Fiondella said. ``How do you demonstrate that
branding and name recognition results in profits? It's pretty hard.
But it's pretty clear that if you don't have it, you know that
impact is.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiondella has worked long hours for years with other businessmen
and with state and local government officials to support the
Adriaen's Landing development, which includes a convention center,
a hotel, stores, and residences. In May, and quite in secret, the
planning began to include the Patriots, shortly after Jonathan
Kraft, the son of owner Robert Kraft, reviewed the redevelopment
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Robert Kraft has met Governor John Rowland in the
Phoenix Home Life boardroom, which also overlooks the stadium site,
as they negotiated the proposed deal. Fiondella personally guided
NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue around the site during a subsequent
meeting. And, this week, politicians and businessmen sat around the
big table in the boardroom talking excitedly about the proposed
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company and a CEO who have not just given lip
service to the idea that bringing sports to Hartford is good for
Hartford,'' said Boston sports lawyer Robert Caporale, who has
helped governments and franchise owners negotiate sports deals.
``They have written checks to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, realizing that Phoenix Home Life's market
position was ``as a large company, but not the largest'' Fiondella
began attracting and sponsoring a number of sports events. It
started with women's basketball at the University of Connecticut.
About the time the company put up $5,000 of the $20,000 it cost to
broadcast the games on public television, the women won the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Fiondella also helped bring the Special Olympics to Connecticut
along with a franchise of the women's American Basketball League
and the American Tennis Professionals Tour World Doubles
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sports is a great medium for reaching people at all
levels and for bringing people in a community together. It evokes
pride, particularly if it is done well,'' Fiondella said.
``Whenever we had an opportunity to focus on name recognition, if
we could also stimulate activity in the city, then we would do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Patriots are an even bigger and better use of sports to
market the town, Fiondella reasons. But many doubt that the massive
expenditure of public finances will make that much difference,
beyond some people around town feeling better about calling
Hartford home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publicly financed stadiums essentially have almost no
anticipated revenue,'' said Andrew Zimbalist, an economics
professor at Smith College and coauthor of a Brookings Institution
study, ``Sports, Jobs &AMP; Taxes: the Economic Impact of Sports Teams
and Stadiums.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimbalist has been contacted by Connecticut legislators who want
him to testify during hearings before the General Assembly on the
stadium proposal set for Wednesday. The study includes a number of
reports from cities nationwide concluding that the financial
payback from publicly financed stadiums is minimal, and the public
subsidies almost always exceed the incremental tax revenues and
other financial benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subsidized sports facilities do not exist because they are
financially valuable assets in their own right,'' Zimbalist and his
coauthor, Roger G. Noll, a senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution, wrote. ``They exist, instead, because most cities have
decided that a subsidized team is better than no team at all, and
because scarcity in the number of teams give owners the advantage
in bargaining with cities.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar study of the impact of new stadiums in California on
other businesses, written by University of California at Berkeley
professor Jack Sylvan, found that sales-tax data from 1972 to 1995
showed no increase in business clearly related to the construction
of any stadium in seven California cities.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the studies, Fiondella said: ``I never read
them. I think I know a little bit more about job creation than the
people who do those studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fairly significant investment,'' Fiondella says of the
$375 million in proposed public financing, which he said has
substantial support in the General Assembly. ``But I think that
what's less important to one person may be more important to
someone else. For us, causing the Patriots to come here is
significantly more important than it may have been for
Massachusetts to keep them. And that's the way business goes, and
that is the way life goes.''
</P>
<P>
   He also rejects, with a shrug and a smile, criticisms of some in
the sports business industry that Hartford's lucrative offer to the
Patriots has merely driven up the costs for all other cities intent
on securing NFL teams or other professional sports franchises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, quite honestly, those very same cities that are
complaining about it didn't seem to complain about moving factories
out of the Northeast, with fairly significant incentives,'' he
said. ``I mean, the economy is competitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
