</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCINDA-MUSIC-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCINDA WILLIAMS KEEPS MOVIN' ON DOWN THE ROAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In the title track of Lucinda Williams' latest album,
``Car Wheels on a Gravel Road,'' a little girl looks out of the
rear window as a car pulls away, ``little bit of dirt, mixed with
tears ...''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has said she was trying to tell a story in the song.
Only later did she realize that it was the story of her own
childhood as she moved constantly with her father and siblings from
town to town around the South.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years down the road, Williams is still staring out the
rear window.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll always have one foot out the door,'' she said in
an unmistakable Gulf Coast drawl. ``It's just my nature. I'm just
kinda restless, you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not necessarily a bad thing. I like to explore
different places. I never had kids or anything, so I've always been
able to go where I want to go. I've gotten used to that freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Williams will explore the Aerial Theater at Bayou
Place in Houston, where she'll perform with her band. Jim
Lauderdale opens the show, which marks Williams' first Houston
appearance since ``Car Wheels'' was released in July.
</P>
<P>
   Despite limited commercial airplay, the album has sold a
respectable 300,000 copies to become far and away the best-selling
release of Williams' career. It's also a strong contender for album
of the year in various critics' polls, having drawn rave reviews in
Rolling Stone, Spin and many major newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things where now that you've gotten there,
what does it mean?'' Williams said of her rising national profile.
``I've got mixed feelings about the whole thing, because I don't
really want to be a big star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to finally be making a living as a musician. But
there's a lot of other stuff that you can potentially get into that
I've seen other people do, and I just don't want to go there. The
whole idea of fame is an illusionary thing. I'm still doing the
same things I used to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 45, was born in Lake Charles, La. By the time she was
4, she'd already passed through Baton Rouge, La., Vicksburg, Miss.
and Jackson, Miss. Her father, distinguished poet Miller Williams
(he spoke at President Clinton's second inauguration), kept
switching universities in search of a tenured position.
</P>
<P>
   After her parents divorced, Miller Williams received custody of
Lucinda and her younger brother and sister. The family moved on
through Mobile, Ala., Atlanta, Santiago, Chile, Mexico City and New
Orleans before the poet settled in at the University of Arkansas in
1971.
</P>
<P>
   Lucinda briefly attended college in Little Rock but dropped out
after a year to take a job performing in a folk bar in New Orleans.
From the first, her music was a mix of traditional country,
acoustic blues and '60s folk-rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always managed to kind of drift in and out of different
groups of people,'' she said. ``I was always able to play in
country honky-tonks or folk bars or biker bars. I opened for Ted
Nugent one time at Liberty Hall. It didn't occur to me that I was a
`folk' singer.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Williams landed in Austin. But she quickly realized she
felt more at home in Houston's acoustic singer-songwriter scene
than with Austin's cosmic cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bunch of people were just getting started at the same time I
was,'' she said. ``Nanci Griffith, Eric Taylor, Vince Bell, Lyle
Lovett, Robert Earl Keen. And, of course, Townes (Van Zandt) would
come in all the time to play. It was a really healthy breeding
ground for songwriters. That whole scene nurtured me quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Leatherwood, longtime owner of the Anderson Fair folk club,
said Williams stood out for her talent, although she lacked the
career focus of some of the other emerging young songwriters
playing his club.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really one of the sweetest people I've ever known,''
Leatherwood said. ``Lucinda always struck me as someone who, if
things went right for her, could achieve success. But I never knew
if she was going to get her life together enough to really get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   During the time she lived in Houston, Williams was managed by
her boyfriend, Clyde Woodward. The couple moved to Los Angeles to
pursue her career. After they split up, Woodward moved back to
Austin, where he died of liver failure.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' relationship with Woodward has inspired a number of
her best songs, including ``Lake Charles'' from ``Car Wheels on a
Gravel Road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel particularly special about `Lake Charles,' because that
was a real difficult thing that I went through,'' she said. ``Some
of his ashes were scattered over Lake Charles _ off the bridge
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Williams found a home in the
roots-rock/alternative country scene developing around the
Blasters, Los Lobos, Dwight Yoakam, the Desert Rose Band and
others. Her self-titled 1988 album for the British Rough Trade
label (two previous albums for the Folkways label had received
limited distribution) brought her an international audience
seemingly overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``After virtual anonymity, all of a sudden, boom!, people had
discovered me,'' Williams said. ``Before that, I was just singing
in the little bars and doing my little thing. I got noted by the
media.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Williams released another critically acclaimed album,
``Sweet Old World,'' on the Chameleon label, which promptly went
out of business. Around the same time, after another brief stay in
Austin, she moved to Nashville, where she currently lives with her
bassist boyfriend, Richard Price.
</P>
<P>
   When she started work on ``Car Wheels,'' Williams was signed to
Rick Rubin's American label. She began work on the recording in
Austin with her longtime musical collaborator, Gurf Morlix. She
then re-cut the basic tracks in Nashville with Twang Trust
producers Steve Earle and Ray Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams still wasn't satisfied, so she headed to L.A. for
additional overdubs co-produced by former E-Street keyboardist Roy
Bittan. When American Records bogged down renegotiating its
major-label distribution deal, Mercury bought the rights to the
album in April and released it in July.
</P>
<P>
   Given the arduous recording process, it's a miracle that ``Car
Wheels'' didn't come out sounding terribly overcooked. Instead,
every track has something extra _ from the lead guitar playing by
Buddy Miller, Charlie Sexton and Johnny Lee Schell to the harmony
vocals by Lauderdale, Morlix and Emmylou Harris _ that takes it to
another dimension.
</P>
<P>
   But basically, it all comes back to the songs: ``Car Wheels on a
Gravel Road'' is the strongest collection of new material released
this year by an American singer-songwriter. With a lifetime of
rambling behind her, Lucinda Williams has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she's already getting antsy to move on. After six
years in Nashville, where she lives with bassist boyfriend Richard
Price, she's dreaming of a new life in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six years is about my limit,'' she said with a laugh. ``I
think I'm always looking for that community feeling, that
camaraderie thing, that we all had back then. It's hard to find. I
can't tell if that's what's changed, or if I've changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's that some folks are just born to run.
</P>
<P>
   Like the song says, ``Cotton fields stretching miles and
miles/Hank's voice on the radio/Telephone poles, trees and wires
fly on by/Car wheels on a gravel road...'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
