<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASE TAKE NOTE OF THESE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN   SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picked-up pieces while pondering the spirit of Ben Drieth....
</P>
<P>
   --Pete Carroll simply has to do something about his sideline
comportment. The constant cheering makes him look like Potsie Weber
and Ralph Malph from ``Happy Days,'' and it's not dignified to be
getting tackled by your assistant coaches after a luck-laced,
last-second victory. The sight of Pete rolling on the ground was
mildly reminiscent of a prone Jeff Van Gundy holding on to Alonzo
Mourning's leg during a basketbrawl.
</P>
<P>
   --The Red Sox are banking on the All-Star Game to protect them
from season ticket drop-off in the wake of this dismal,
embarrassing, and passive offseason. Will Clark? Now that everyone
else is gone, why not bring back Jack Clark? He could probably use
the money. Hope Jose Offerman can play first base.
</P>
<P>
   --One last time: The Red Sox never had any intention of signing
Mo Vaughn. If you want to keep a guy, do you tell him to go get
market value, then come back with something slightly less? Don't be
duped by the PR spin. And know that Mo's animosity will forever be
aimed at Dan Duquette, not John Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   --Glad to see that Connecticut resident Ralph Nader has spoken
to his fellow citizens. Old Laughing Boy characterized the Kraft
stadium giveaway as ``the worst kind of corporate welfare,'' but
thus far, the Connecticut Yahoos aren't listening. Desperate to be
``big league'' at any cost, the legislators are expected to approve
the Love Canal Stadium bill in the middle of the month. I still say
the Pats aren't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   --How Did We Miss This Dept.?: Nine days after Pete Schourek
toed the rubber instead of Pedro Martinez against the Cleveland
Indians _ a decision which was equated with Joe McCarthy's decision
to start Denny Galehouse in the 1948 playoff game _ Mr. Galehouse
died from complications caused by heart disease in Doylestown,
Ohio. Ever a gentleman, Galehouse was the surprise starter and
loser of the first playoff game in American League history. He
never won another game in the big leagues and was a scout with the
Padres for 18 years before his death.
</P>
<P>
   --If you have a son or daughter who digs sports and is between
the ages of 10 and 14, see ``The Waterboy.'' Jimmy Johnson and Bill
Cowher make cameos, and Henry Winkler's assistant coach might
remind you of Fred Smerlas.
</P>
<P>
   --Vaughn rearranged his schedule to come back from Anaheim to
appear at Team Harmony at the FleetCenter Dec. 15 (his 31st
birthday). He'll be honored at the fifth annual event to promote
diversity and harmony among today's youth. More than 12,000 New
England young people are scheduled to attend.
</P>
<P>
   --Mike Greenwell is thinking of coming out of retirement and
signing with the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   --Is Press Corner Kraft still feeling good about replacing
Curtis Martin with Robert Edwards?
</P>
<P>
   --In defense of Roger Clemens's last four years (40-39) in
Boston: In '93, he was 4-1 with a 1.55 ERA before a groin pull
plagued him and he had his worst year ever (11-14). In '94, he was
9-7 with a 2.85 ERA, and batters hit .204 against him, lowest in
the majors. He also finished second in the AL in strikeouts. In
'95, he was 10-5. The Sox scored three runs or fewer in 10 of his
starts but still went 16-7 in his starts and won the AL East. In
'96, he went 10-13 with a 3.63 ERA, the seventh-best ERA in the
league. He led the league in strikeouts and allowed a .237 average,
second lowest in the league. The Sox scored three or fewer runs in
15 of his starts, and Heathcliff Slocumb blew seven leads for
Clemens in the first half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   --Is there a better NHL coach than Pat Burns?
</P>
<P>
   --Wondering what ever happened to Sam Jankovich? He's been named
interim athletic director at Cal State-Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   --How many Big East wins for Boston College's ``Get Shorty''
basketball team? One? Two? This could be Holy Cross's best chance
for a rare victory over the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   --The Patriot cheerleader swimsuit calendar somehow doesn't
sound like Myra's idea.
</P>
<P>
   --Best wishes to Mike Barnicle for a speedy recovery from heart
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
