A1177 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANGELS-THEATER-REVIEW     12-03 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELS-THEATER-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANGELS' IS AFFABLE RENDITION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're no angels, the Devil's Island convicts who make up the
title trio in Sam and Bella Spewack's ``My Three Angels.'' Alfred
and Jules are killers, while Joseph is merely a fraud, forger and
all-around crook.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but there were mitigating factors in the murders. And Joseph
always has viewed his criminal career as a sort of fairy tale,
subject to his own storytelling fancy.
</P>
<P>
   These three shopworn angels reveal hearts of gold when they come
to the assistance of a put-upon shopkeeper and his family on
Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   No masterpiece, ``My Three Angels'' nonetheless generates mild
entertainment in Main Street Theater's uneven but affable
rendition.
</P>
<P>
   The 1953 Broadway comedy (filmed as ``We're No Angels'') was
written by the husband and wife writing team best remembered for
``Boy Meets Girl,'' a comedy spoofing 1930s Hollywood, and for the
book of the classic Cole Porter musical ``Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in sweltering French Guiana on a Christmas Eve early in this
century, ``Angels'' sets up the situation in the opening scene.
Felix is a good-hearted merchant who failed in France and now is
struggling to succeed with a general store in the French colony. As
his practical wife, Emilie, reminds him, Felix is too generous and
trusting _ giving away merchandise, letting his customers get away
with owing but never paying.
</P>
<P>
   As the play opens, Felix is preparing for a visit from his
cousin Henri, the bane of Felix's existence, who drove him out of
his business in France. Apparently, Henri has designs on Felix's
business in the colony _ and also wants to put a stop to the
budding romance between Felix's pretty daughter Marie Louise and
his (Henri's) son Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the angels, on shore in the colony (from Devil's Island,
just off the coast) to work as free labor for the respectable
class. During a break from repairing Felix's roof, the trio
ventures downstairs just in time to see Marie Louise faint upon
reading a telegram indicating that her plans to marry Paul are to
be thwarted. The trio come to the girl's aid and, after helping her
parents with other matters, they are invited to spend Christmas Eve
with the family.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of the trouble-making cousin, the stage is set
for the angels to save Felix and his business while ridding the
world of the miserably greedy visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angels'' is decent, second-tier work of its era. The offbeat
plot (with its unusual notions about when it's appropriate to get
away with murder) is bolstered by modest helpings of whimsical or
ironic humor and doses of pardonable sentiment. The play also
evinces the inevitable flaws of its type: Some passages are
needlessly talky and prolonged, while others are merely weak or
pointless.
</P>
<P>
   Director Steve Garfinkel has overseen a production as uneven as
the material. Some scenes are right on target, while others are too
overstated; still others lag or lack energy. What MST's production
always has in common with the script, however, is a good-humored
affability.
</P>
<P>
   The three cons here are amiable but variable in dramatic impact.
Charles Charpiot takes a natural relish in his role as Joseph, the
resourcefully larcenous rogue who proves especially useful to
Felix. Joe Hudson sometimes scores with a quiet wistfulness as
Jules, the philosophical member of the trio. Maurice Tuttle has
moments of energy and humor as Alfred, the most impulsive one _
though as with the others, his line readings don't always ring
true.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Masterson is aptly cast as Felix _ decent, ineffectual,
flummoxed and in need of rescue. Theo Lane Moffet is ideal as his
wife, Emilie _ fussy, pragmatic, worried yet ever-loving. In many
ways, this is the play's most believable role and in Moffet's
portrayal it becomes the emotional center of the play _ though you
may wish Moffet were more central to the action, as she was in
MST's delightful ``Good Housekeeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Pfister makes a substantial villain of Henri _ so bossy,
insulting and obnoxious to everyone that you will not mind at all
when the angels find a neat way of dispatching him. Good riddance!
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Haag is the quintessence of ingenue as Marie Louise _
fresh, fetching, eager and girlishly romantic. Garfinkel has
directed her to overdo things a bit, though, especially in her
breathless line readings of the first act. Ty Mayberry (subbing for
Mark Pickell at Saturday's performance) did crisp and capable work
as the villain's son Paul, temporarily a love interest for Marie
Louise, but too determinedly following in his nasty dad's footsteps
to retain her love for long. Theatergoers can decide for themselves
whether the punishment meted out by the angels fits Paul's crime.
</P>
<P>
   MST's ``My Three Angels'' is a pleasant, unspectacular revival
of a pleasant, unspectacular play. It's for theatergoers who, like
the playwrights when they penned this, are in a benevolent and
forgiving mood. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
