<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1179 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIUS-AUTO-AZR &LR;      12-03 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIUS-AUTO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRIC CAR A REAL GAS  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The little Toyota Prius hardly seemed worth a second
glance, parked at the curb with a dozen sleek and exotic examples
of electric cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   But ordinary as it may appear, there's a critical difference
between Prius and the other electric vehicles being demonstrated
Wednesday in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Prius is an electric vehicle that never needs to be recharged.
Range is not an issue. Nor is battery replacement.
</P>
<P>
   This is the world's first mass-produced car with hybrid power _
part gasoline engine and part electric motor _ providing the
benefits of low emissions and high gas mileage in a real-world
vehicle that can be driven anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   It's the closest thing so far to an all-purpose electric
vehicle, maybe lacking the purity of a battery-powered car, but
possibly the type of clean, efficient vehicle we'll all be driving
someday. And without ever having to plug it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of this is that you don't have to change your
lifestyle at all to accommodate an electric vehicle,'' said Jeremy
Barnes, Toyota's product safety and environment administrator.
``You can drive it as fast and as far as you want without worrying
about recharging.''
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's technological brainchild is one of about a dozen
electric vehicles on display or being demonstrated at the North
American Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Conference, an
international cadre of automakers, small companies, researchers and
electric utility companies being held at Phoenix Civic Plaza.
(NOTE: THROUGH SATURDAY DEC.5)
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by California's clean-air mandates and growing public
impatience with the brown clouds that hang over urban areas,
including Phoenix, electric-powered and other alternative-fueled
vehicles are under intense development efforts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The sleek form of the General Motors EV1 is a familiar sight in
the Phoenix area, with about 100 of them being leased, not nearly
as many as hoped for, but still seen as a toehold in public
acceptance of electric cars.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the conference participants were sampling electric
vehicles from various manufacturers, including the EV1, Nissan's
Altra station wagon, Ford's electric Ranger pickup and
DaimlerChrysler's EPIC van, as well as a small, short-range
``neighborhood vehicle'' from Bombardier, a Canadian small-vehicle
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   As well-developed as these vehicles may be, they still have the
well-known bugaboo of electric cars and trucks _ the short driving
range between lengthy rechargings, making them impractical for
anything but urban commutes and errands.
</P>
<P>
   The Prius is a different sort of vehicle, one that seems hardly
different from a conventional gasoline-powered car. But it gets
about 67 miles per gallon, Toyota says, in mixed urban and highway
driving while sending only a tiny amount of pollutants out the
tailpipe.
</P>
<P>
   The hybrid works through a complex electronic and mechanical
system that varies the power to the front wheels between a small
gasoline engine and an electric motor.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.5-liter gas engine serves to recharge 40 small
nickel-metal hydride batteries that drive the 40-horsepower
electric motor, and it provides extra power for acceleration and
cruising at highway speeds.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-horsepower gasoline engine stops running completely when
the car is stopped, instead of idling in traffic, a major source of
pollution in rush-hour conditions. When the car is stopped, it's
completely quiet, just like a regular electric car, though the gas
engine will kick over at times to recharge the batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said the batteries never have to be replaced for the
lifetime of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it operates:
</P>
<P>
   - When pulling away from a stop or under light acceleration,
only the electric motor is doing the work, with the gas engine shut
off.
</P>
<P>
   - In normal driving, the gas engine turns on and off, with power
split between providing power for a generator to recharge the
batteries and run the electric motor.
</P>
<P>
   - Under full acceleration, both the electric motor and the gas
engine share the load.
</P>
<P>
   - In highway cruising, the gas engine takes over, supplemented
by electric power.
</P>
<P>
   - In deceleration, the batteries are recharged as the electric
motor doubles as another generator.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said that although the Prius is a subcompact vehicle with
a small engine, there's no reason why hybrid cars couldn't be built
with V-6 or even V-8 engines, getting the same performance as
today's cars with much better fuel economy and far fewer
emissions. &QL; 
In Japan, the Prius is already being used regularly by the public,
and Toyota plans to bring them into this country in early 2000,
priced in the low $20,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, Prius feels only marginally different from a
regular gasoline vehicle. Acceleration is brisk, an attribute of
the electric motor. A video display on the dashboard monitors the
various functions of the engine, motor and generator.
</P>
<P>
   That Prius can be driven anywhere was demonstrated recently when
``Road and Track'' magazine drove a Prius from Los Angeles to
Florida without a single recharge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to baby this thing,'' Barnes said, referring to
how electric-car drivers have to drive and accelerate slowly to get
the longest range between recharging.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't run the batteries down, and the only recharging you
have to do is at the gas pump.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
