<HEADLINE>
HOTTEST TOY IN TOWN: FURBY FLIES OFF SHELVES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEANNIE KEVER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Attention, shoppers: Furby has left the building.
</P>
<P>
   And no, we don't know when he'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   But if price is no object _ if, say, the idea of spending $300
or more for a $30 talking hairball won't make you fear you've taken
leave of your senses _ you may be in luck.
</P>
<P>
   Houston stores receiving shipments of the toys don't hold on to
them for long. And store employees say there's no way to predict
when the next shipment might arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get them when we get them,'' said Shanlanda Holman, a
customer service representative at the Toys R Us in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   And then they'll fly off the shelves again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three cases (before Thanksgiving), and they probably
went in 30 minutes,'' Holman reported. ``And the only reason it
took 30 minutes was people didn't know we had them.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like Tickle Me Elmo and the Cabbage Patch Kids before it,
Furby has become a phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   And Houston's entrepreneurs are watching.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Ortiz, a 39-year-old papermill worker in Galena Park,
stumbled upon a dozen Furbys obscured by other toys at a Kmart
several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He bought all 12, spending about $360.
</P>
<P>
   He gave one to a girlfriend and placed a classified ad offering
the rest at $550. Each.
</P>
<P>
   The first day, he said, he sold one for $500 and a second for
$400.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz's ad was one of 18 offering Furbys for sale in Tuesday's
Houston Chronicle, with prices ranging from $200 to $800.
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer to take their chances and pay retail,
finding Furby may be frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   At the Target on San Felipe, it is telephone operator Sophie
Capelo's misfortune to deliver the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the calls,'' she said. ``We don't have any (Furbys).
Even before the store opens, they're calling me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wal-Mart in Tomball, Texas, north of Houston, got a shipment
on Friday, as after-Thanksgiving shoppers swarmed into the store,
operator Lorene LaRoche said. The booty was rationed _ one per
customer _ but still sold out almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The story was the same everywhere Furby was to be found.
</P>
<P>
   A manager at the Kay-Bee Toy &AMP; Hobby Shop in Baybrook Mall in
Houston arrived at work at 4:30 a.m. Friday to find people already
lined up for the 180 Furbys he had in stock.
</P>
<P>
   He handed out numbers, and all 180 were spoken for by the time
the store opened, according to the manager, who declined to give
his name.
</P>
<P>
   Why Furby?
</P>
<P>
   The Kay-Bee manager speculated that the toy's fortunes took off
after it was included in a cache of hot holiday toys on a ``Good
Morning America'' segment a month or so ago.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone on the show fussed over Furby, he said, and another
chapter in hot-toy history began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
