A1184 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-WARM-BOS &LR;      12-03 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-WARM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON IS HERE _ WINTER IS NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some years early-season skiing is a snap. Last year, for
instance, the big snows that swept down from the north around
Thanksgiving set up one of the best early skiing seasons in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Other years are ... well ... like this one.
</P>
<P>
   It's about that narrow strip of white snow running river-width
through the brown woods.
</P>
<P>
   Or about the fact that, without a frozen base underneath the
surface, there's no protective buffer between ski bottom and
submerged object _ rock, stump, petrified squirrel fossil,
whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Early-season skiing takes the kind of imagination required to
appreciate Shakespeare's ``Othello'' acted without costumes or
stage sets. Keep telling yourself you're in Cyprus and the Turkish
navy just got sunk in a hell-howling tempest (really bad storm).
</P>
<P>
   Just tell yourself it is winter and we really are in the midst
of another ski season.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, by all records, was a freak. The snow that piled in
with arctic air meeting the moist Atlantic air created a wondrous
2-foot storm in ski country and something that almost never happens
with such storms _ enough snow down in Boston to inspire Bostonians
to go skiing.
</P>
<P>
   This year, says John Diller from Sugarloaf, which is usually
buried in the natural stuff for most of the season, the big storm
hasn't hit yet. Still, Thanksgiving was tolerable because of a foot
of wet snow that fell over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind that really packed in well,'' said Diller,
adding that a few of the good natural trails such as Double Bitter
and Sluice were open throughout the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, warm weather has damaged the weekend snow that most
higher elevations were blessed with for the first big weekend of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, eight ski areas are open with limited terrain, which
generally means limited ticket prices as well. Molley Mahaer Kerr
of the Vermont Ski Areas Association said that while bookings for
later in the season are up over last year, early season is still
usually marginal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really for the hardcore,'' she said. ``This year has been
more typical, whereas last year was an anomaly. It would be great
if we had a storm like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Thanksgiving dump brought a wave of skiers to the
slopes. As that storm packed in, it became base for more natural
and manmade snow, setting up an early season that skiers are still
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing,'' said Jon Buell, who has already skied twice
at Killington this year. ``Last Thanksgiving we left the rock skis
on the car and used our good stuff. But not this year. You're not
going to be that lucky two years in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Killington's open terrain was crowded last weekend, and
the crowds, says Kerr, are likely to increase into the Christmas
holidays, which is the traditional time the season fully opens. But
in the meantime, there are some warm days to fight through, like
last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out in the slush,'' said Buell Tuesday, ``but when you
ski this time of year _ and there were boards out _ you kind of
know what you're getting into, literally. It is what it is _ not
the best skiing we're going to see this year. At least I hope
not.''
</P>
<P>
   As most areas open, what natural snow has fallen is augmented
with snowmaking, but that requires a consistent string of cold
nights. Even so, the look of winter that many skiers prefer is not
available in most ski areas this week.
</P>
<P>
   When Ben Monte bought new shaped skies at the Boston ski show
two weeks ago, the first thing he wanted to do was try them out.
``I've been reading about shaped skis, and everyone talks about
them. But my girlfriend is a big skier, and she said I'd wreck
them. So here I am on the same old skis I had last year. I even got
them used. I suppose the real winter snow will be here by
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   The point? Back to those submerged objects under the thin cover.
When the skier or boarder does hit them, the plastic on the bottom
of the ski can get damaged. The answer is a pair of old skis,
usually known affectionately as ``rock skis.''
</P>
<P>
   Another drawback to early-season skiing, aside from aesthetics,
is safety. Without a blanket of snow in the woods, around trees,
signs, and lift towers, there is less buffering effect than snow
provides in mid-winter conditions. However, while most ski
patrollers believe the conditions are harsher in early-season
skiing, the evidence of danger is only anecdotal, especially since
the number of skiers is relativley small, and dominated by those
with advanced skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it only makes sense,'' said a Loon patrolman, ``that if
there's less snow around off the trails and everywhere on the
mountain, that the hard surfaces are closer to the skiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Diller, ``any day now, we're going to get that big
storm we're wating for, and suddenly everyone will want to come
skiing. It happens every year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
