<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Memories come rolling back
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (''Dreamsville'' is an occasional feature in which readers share
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Hall Hutchinson, age not disclosed, of Tucson, Ariz.,
takes us roaring down memory lane on in-line skates. Here's her
story:
</P>
<P>
   ``While filling out the form to rent the in-line skates, I
hesitated at the 'age' blank. Was it really necessary to record the
number that labeled me a senior citizen? I had to admit that on
paper the number did not look age-appropriate to the activity. But
then, was there a correct age?
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity was just too good to pass up: Six high school
girlfriends reunited more than 40 years after graduation for a
weekend in a Mission Beach house in San Diego that was surrounded
by smooth, wide, curving sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Dorothy had brought along her in-line skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``While some of us were eager to join her in this activity,
others hesitated. Excuses were forth-coming: hadn't skated since
high school ... a bad knee ... fear of injury ... in-line skates
were not the same as roller skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excitement mounted as, one by one, we tried on Dorothy's
knee-pads, skates and wrist-guards, and with her gentle coaching,
each decided to take a tentative turn close to the security of a
wall. It helped that some of us had learned to ski, as the stopping
motion felt similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we began to share our socks with the skater-of-the-moment
to achieve the proper fit, and to squabble like children over whose
turn it was, we knew we were ready to roll. Each of us was
committed to renting skating equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question about my enthusiasm. Some five decades later the
soles of my feet can still feel the satisfying click-click-click of
racing full speed over the sidewalks of my Midwestern childhood
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The streets, sidewalks and empty lots in the neighborhood were
our playground. Shaded by a canopy of stately elm trees, the
neighbor kids rollerskated, jumped rope, played hopscotch and rode
bikes all summer long. More ambitious projects were organized by
the bigger kids: carnivals, theatrical productions, dog shows and
parades. Their little brothers and sisters were willing lackeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``At twilight we'd gather under the elms to play 'I Will Draw
the Frying Pan,' 'Red Light/Green Light' or 'Ghosts.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But any summer day would find me on my skates, the skate key
dangling on a grubby cotton string around my neck, scabs on my
knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``My most daring feat on roller skates was regularly performed
at the steep hill that led down to the next street at the end of
our block. Lickety-split, my friends and I would roar down the hill
and stop ourselves at the bottom with a quick jerk to the left.
We'd slam with a resounding bang into a conveniently located garage
door. The door, much to the owner's displeasure, was permanently
dirtied with a row of child-sized handprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, some 50 years later, I gleefully suited up with knee-pads
and wrist guards, buckled up the rented skates and followed
Dorothy, my friend since fourth grade, down the alley to the wide,
smooth pavement where we could really take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turning her head, she grinned at me and said, 'We're 8 years
old.'
</P>
<P>
   ``'Absolutely,' I agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the number I'd been searching for.''
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, mail it to ``Dreamsville,'' c/o
Joe Murray, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915. If your story is
printed, you'll receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
