<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: A working theory of road rage
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I got zapped by somebody's BMW horn the other day for,
apparently, having committed an egregious civility. I had paused to
let a marooned driver take a left in front of me. This, to
paraphrase Churchill, is an insult up with which a BMW driver will
not put. What the heck's the use buying a luxury car if you can't
drive over someone whenever you want?
</P>
<P>
   This is a city that prides itself on its deeply rooted Southern
courtesy. All very true, too, until you put many Atlantans behind a
wheel and on the road, where they instantly turn into mad dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe tailgating is the result of all those years of watching
Southern stock car racing on television. My definition of a true
tailgater is someone who won't get off your rear bumper even if you
speed up.
</P>
<P>
   I always follow the old rule of leaving a car length of space
for each 10 miles of speed. If you're going 60, that means six car
lengths. In this city, it means only three or four cars will zip
laughing into the open space.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is a city famed for constructing freeways that solve
nothing. Cars became popular because they gave people freedom.
Remember the Sunday family drive? Now cars limit freedom. I guess
that's why everyone's so cranky.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
