<HEADLINE>
BABY, DON'T THROW BATH OUT WITH THE TUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dumbest remodeling mistake I ever made was eliminating our
bath tub.
</P>
<P>
   Especially now, in these cold, damp winter days, I miss a long
hot soak in a tub.
</P>
<P>
   I removed the tub to gain room for a roll-in handicapped shower
in the adjoining bathroom, and have regretted ever since not
finding or making the space for at least one tub in our home.
</P>
<P>
   In the two-flat where I grew up, eight of us _ three generations
_ shared a big ol' lion's-foot bath tub. Not at the same time,
except in my early years when my twin sister and I were
rub-a-dub-dubbed in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   There was no shower, save for the gravity-fed one out back in
the garage, fed by a hot water tank under the roof and used only on
hot summer evenings when we would run bare-butt naked back across
the yard to the house.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the year, we took Saturday night baths. And with that
many people in line, there were definite rules against
lollygagging. Especially since that also was the location of our
single toilet.
</P>
<P>
   A home with more than one bathroom was a luxury dreamed of, and
one that I and all of my siblings realized. And long, hot soaks in
a tub have always seemed to me the most luxurious of indulgences.
</P>
<P>
   To be done right, a bath should follow a relatively short,
cleansing shower ... the kind many of us do in our daily routines.
Showers, for the most part, leave you with a kind of slam-bam sense
of something missing.
</P>
<P>
   And our missing tub offered best what I miss most: that
unhurried and deliciously guilty indulgence in self-gratification.
When I announced: ``I'm going to take a bath,'' the family knew
that I would disappear for about the same amount of time as when
I'd say: ``I'm just going down to McLendon Hardware for a couple
things.''
</P>
<P>
   But a bath was infinitely more rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   A bath, when done correctly, is a protocol in pampering. Your
biggest and fluffiest bath towel is set out. A fresh bar of soap is
at hand. And a bath oil of choice is administered to the torrent of
hot water.
</P>
<P>
   And regardless of what image you project in real life _ whether
you slop hogs, apply hot-tar roofs, teach school or drive a desk _
you are allowed to add bubbles to your bath.
</P>
<P>
   There are other things that add to the soft ambience of bathing.
While some so-called relaxation bathers will sneak in a paperback
mystery or maybe a Reader's Digest, true Zen bathers prefer a
minimum of light. Or, at best, a few carefully placed candles.
</P>
<P>
   Beverages are best left outside. Glasses pose a danger as well
as a diversion from true relaxation. So too, snacks are verboten in
the bath. A bath is an indulgence that works from the outside in,
and should not be compromised by soggy sandwiches or crumbs in your
bath bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   A good bath must be HOT! This is best accomplished by slowly
lowering your tired body into the tub when it's half full. Once
your body has adjusted to the warmth, you then may increase the
flow of hot water along with your tolerance of same. (Warning:
Don't tell your cardiologist, because really hot baths reportedly
pose certain cardiovascular dangers. Then again, so does really hot
sex. And any combination of hot baths and the latter indulgence
must be done prudently and semi-moderately. Especially if there are
lighted candles nearby.)
</P>
<P>
   A good bath also requires a full tub. It helps if you hold a
wash cloth on the overflow with your foot, thereby allowing the
water level to reach your nose while you are in the
fullest-possible reclining position. This also facilitates your
imitating a crocodile or, if you will, a hippo, while you are at
periscope depth.
</P>
<P>
   The wash cloth or a bath sponge may be used, along with the
fresh bar of soap, to gently massage your body and remove the old
skin cells softened to a greater extent than in any shower.
</P>
<P>
   While they are not necessary, and might even interfere with the
total relaxation, bath toys are left to individual bathers'
discretion. Splashing about, especially when you are alone in the
tub, might create undue curiosity in passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   Music might help your bath relaxation. A battery-powered radio
or CD player is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   As your body adjusts to the water temperature, you might
occasionally add hot/hotter water, until your skin is a rosy pink
and your fingertips begin to show prunish wrinkles. That might be a
good time for a final crocodile imitation, followed by your best
``Aphrodite (or, Neptune) Rising From the Sea'' pose.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the vent fan going, the ambient moisture will fog up
your bathroom mirror sufficiently for secret messages. Inscriptions
in fogged-up mirrors will reappear briefly when the next person
takes a shower or bath.
</P>
<P>
   If you are unsure what message to leave, you can always write:
``Burma-Shave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
