<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASURES OF THE PAGE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glimpses of unspoiled nature, visions of high style, strolls
down memory lane, portraits of passion, advice on getting control.
Each one an idea of the way gardening should be, they are all found
in this year's best garden books. If you're buying gift books,
think hard before you make a match. After all, you're pairing
someone up with a vision of their ideal world. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Photography &AMP; Illustration &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Botanical Footwear of Dennis Kyte,'' by Dennis Kyte
(Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang, $30). These amusing watercolors of
fabulous footwear, all fashioned from flowers and fruit, are based
on the premise that a shoe inspires the imagination and thus
demands to be created from far more interesting material than
leather. For the shoe fetishist on your gift list. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Photography &AMP; Illustration &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Botanical Footwear of Dennis Kyte,'' by Dennis Kyte
(Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang, $30). These amusing watercolors of
fabulous footwear, all fashioned from flowers and fruit, are based
on the premise that a shoe inspires the imagination and thus
demands to be created from far more interesting material than
leather. For the shoe fetishist on your gift list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth On Her Hands: The American Woman in Her Garden,'' by
Starr Ockenga (Clarkson Potter, $55). Most of the American women in
Ockenga's word and photo portraits are, like Martha's Vineyard's
Polly Hill, elderly doyennes with ample acreage, means, and free
time, who chose to devote these assets to gardening _ with awesome
results. Ockenga treats them as respectfully as artists, weighing
in with a retrospective of their lifes' work, which is what these
women are.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Tuscan Paradise,'' by Marina Schinz (Stewart, Tabori &AMP;
Chang, $35). A Swiss photographer, Schinz traveled widely to
capture the world's most beautiful gardens in ``Visions of
Paradise,'' her 1985 classic. This time she's discovered heaven on
earth in a single, 10-acre Tuscan villa owned by two spirited,
quirky Roman friends, Matteo and Frederico. Over a three-year
period she explores every corner of their two courtyard-linked
homes and the surrounding 10 acres of hilly gardens and olive
groves. The melding of indoor and outdoor living, of fresh flowers
and Etruscan antiques, of fugitive and eternal beauty make this the
year's most evocative house and garden book. There is much to learn
here. Superbly printed in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gardens of the Wine Country,'' by Molly Chappellet with
Richard Tracy (Chronicle Books, $40). Napa Valley is the Tuscany of
America, and these estates are its villas. Longtime resident
Chappellet has gained access to 40 of its most opulent private
gardens to banish winter blues and start you planning that
California trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reflecting Nature: Garden Designs from Wild Landscapes,'' by
Jerome Malitz and Seth Malitz (Timber Press, $39.95). This
father-son team looks at how private gardens can adapt ideas from
wilderness landscapes. They focus on both natural and artificially
created waterfalls, alpine rock gardens, wetlands and meadows, as
well as 10 Japanese gardens that elegantly suggest nature. For the
naturalistic gardener or landscaper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Essays &AMP; Memoirs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Mitchell on Gardening,'' (Houghton Mifflin, $24). ``I
well know I have neither the time nor the energy nor even the
desire to have a garden that people admire,'' wrote the
iconoclastic Washington Post garden columnist, who died in 1993.
Yes, he was getting tired in this last collection of essays, but
Mitchell remained dedicated to the pursuit of subjective, piercing
beauty and indifferent to merely putting on a good show. Mitchell
wrote as he gardened. Pursuing contrarian enthusiasms for obscure
roses or finicky camellias that he happened to fall in love with,
rather than enforcing rules of taste or even giving particularly
helpful advice, he reminds us here that gardening can be a passion,
instead of an exercise in organic decorating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merry Hall,'' by Beverley Nichols (Timber Press, $24.95). This
reissued 1952 memoir by the late British garden writer creates an
entertaining period piece with cantankerous gardeners, ditzy floral
designers, and disastrous flower shows that reads like P.G.
Wodehouse. It is the first in a trilogy about the author's efforts
to rehabilitate an old house and garden in a sleepy English
village. The second, ``Laughter on the Stairs,'' was also reissued
this year. The third, ``Sunlight on the Lawn,'' will be reprinted
next spring. Hilarious for gardeners who adore Masterpiece Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich Harvest,'' by Don Hastings (Longstreet, $20). Hastings
has a wholesome, almost reverent way of telling stories ranging
from working on his family's Georgia seed farm as a child to
developing agricultural projects in Egypt, the Philippines, and
Chile as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gardening Life,'' by Lee May (Longstreet, $22). A collection
of favorite newspaper columns by a noted journalist and the Atlanta
Journal's first black editorial writer who decided one day he had
had enough of writing about murder and mayhem and wanted to focus
on ``feeling good about life as I aged.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gardens as Sanctuaries. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Inviting Garden: Gardening for the Senses, Mind and
Spirit,'' by Allen Lacy (Henry Holt, $40). ``Gardening is not a
hobby, and only a non-gardener would describe it as such,'' writes
Allen Lacy in the best-written garden book of the year. A professor
of philosophy, Lacy has, in fact, long used gardening as the
vehicle for his intellectual inquiries into the nature of
existence. In these essays accompanied by enlightening photographs,
he deconstructs the meaning of gardening as a source of renewal,
sensual pleasure, and ultimately of connection to time and place
and the larger world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Magic Land: Designing Your Own Enchanted Garden,'' by
Julie Moir Messervy (Macmillan, $19.95). This sensitive and
imaginative book can help homeowners draw on the deepest levels of
their psyches to create healing landscapes full of personal
meaning. Using design philosophies from feng shui to Egyptian
symmetry, this Wellesley landscape designer shows how to translate
emotions into garden designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rustic Retreats: A Build-It-Yourself Guide,'' by David and
Jeanie Stiles (Storey Books, $19.95). First it was gazebos. Now an
increasing number of people are building little sleep-away
bungalows, even in the corner of their own back yards. Here's how
to add habitable nooks and hideouts to yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gardens of the Spirit: Creating Your Own Sacred Spaces,'' by
Roni Jay (Sterling, $19.95). This book borrows from many traditions
to create garden plans for a build-it-yourself Japanese Zen garden,
a Taoist garden, a teahouse, a fruit- and rose-filled Islamic
garden, an English knot garden, and an Italian Renaissance garden
with gravel walkways, a central pool and stone statue fountain,
tunnel arbors, and flower beds. A delight for the dreamer and the
skilled gardener or someone working with a professional landscape
architect, but too ambitious for the casual amateur. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instruction &AMP; Advice &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a Garden: Reliable Techniques, Outstanding Plants, and
Honest Advice,'' by Rita Buchanan, illustrations by Steve Buchanan
(Houghton Mifflin, $35). Connecticut-based Rita Buchanan's talents
as both a veteran gardening editor and writer are present in this
reassuring book that takes the beginner by the hand and explains
everything she really needs to know, and nothing she doesn't.
Combining warmth and efficiency, each word and illustration is
well-chosen so you absorb a lot of information without feeling
overwhelmed, or even realizing how much ground you've covered.
Potentially intimidating subjects such as raising seedlings indoors
and pruning shrubs, as well as fun stuff like the new tropical pot
plants, are gently explained, and everything in it works for our
climate. A jewel.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Garden Style,'' by Bunny Williams (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $35).
A noted New York interior designer, Bunny Williams brings haute
interior design to the out-of-doors in this book devoted to style,
nuance, and ornmentation. Everything you ever wanted to know about
using concrete fragments, finials, posts, pedestals, obelisks, and
pots. Williams is also the owner of the New York garden ornament
emporium Treillage, and gardens in Connecticut, too. A lush idea
book for refined tastes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
