<HEADER>
A1204 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      12-03 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RECOMMITMENT TO `JUST THE FACTS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a year of credibility-sapping scandals _ from Mike
Barnicle's, Patricia Smith's, and Stephen Glass's mingling of fact
and fiction to CNN's report alleging US use of nerve gas in the
Vietnam War _ the journalism business now seems very eager to
redevote itself publicly to Sergeant Joe Friday's ``just the
facts'' credo. (Perhaps just in time, too. A stunning 66 percent of
the respondents to a recent Media Studies Center survey believe
journalists often or sometimes ``make up stories and pass them off
as real.'')
</P>
<P>
   In September, journalists, photographers, and writers gathered
at the Poynter Institute for Media Studies in St. Petersburg, Fla.,
to debate the issue of fact versus fiction. ``The Poynter thing was
to streamline the mortification, to say we have a code,'' says
Boston University journalism professor and co-editor of the
``Literary Journalism'' anthology, Mark Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, the influential Committee of Concerned
Journalists recently sent out a survey to 200 randomly selected
journalists asking them about ``altering reality,'' explains
committee vice chair Tom Rosenstiel. (A typical question is whether
it's OK to clean up someone's grammar in a quote.)
</P>
<P>
   Although the results are incomplete, Rosenstiel says the
response is running about 4-1 ``against all alteration. . . .
People don't always necessarily agree on the details (but) on the
broader question, there's almost no serious support for inventing
things in non-fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee is teaming up with Poynter to produce what could
become a definitive document on journalistic standards. Currently
an early draft, the report is expected to address a range of
questions including: how to handle slang and ungrammatical quotes;
reconstructing scenes that were not witnessed firsthand; reading
back quotes to sources to verify accuracy; creating composite
characters; using devices like slow motion or dramatic music to
enhance television news reports; and employing computer technology
to alter photographs.
</P>
<P>
   From all indications, the final version will look askance at any
whiff of fancy and will counsel strict adherence to two core
principles. Do not report things that did not happen and do not
deceive listeners, viewers, or readers.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, ``Do we have to move the line (for standards of
truth) or do we have to take a big black marker and redraw it?''
says Poynter Institute senior scholar Roy Peter Clark. The loudly
professed intent is to toe the line all the more respectfully.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Author Philip Nobile's crusade to convince media outlets to
acknowledge that the late Alex Haley played fast and loose with the
facts in ``Roots'' now focuses on a 26-year-old New York Times
article. Nobile is not the only doubting voice in the chorus:
Harvard's Henry Louis Gates Jr., who co-edited the Norton Anthology
of African American Literature, recently told the Globe that ``
`Roots' is a work of the imagination rather than strict historical
scholarship.'' But Nobile has failed miserably in his efforts to
get Haley's 1977 Pulitzer Prize rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is waging war over a 1972 article tracing Haley's
genealogy _ titled ``My Furthest-Back Person _ `The African' ''_
that the ``Roots'' author wrote for the Times's Sunday magazine. On
Oct. 16, Nobile wrote Times executive editor Joseph Lelyveld asking
why _ even at this late date _ the paper ``does not publicly
disown'' the Haley magazine article. ``The New York Times,'' he
stated, ``finds itself in the dubious ethical position of refusing
to admit a hoax.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether Lelyveld had responded to his request, Nobile
said: ``Shockingly, not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who says a newspaper's demise has to deprive the community of an
editorial voice? When the evening Chattanooga Free Press
(circulation 40,119) and the morning Chattanooga Times (circulation
41,229) merge Jan. 5, several dozen out of more than 500 staffers
will lose their jobs. But the Free Press's conservative-leaning
op-ed/editorial page and the Times's more liberal opinion section
will be kept intact and published on facing pages, thus maintaining
a two-newspaper ideological war in a one-newspaper town.
</P>
<P>
   According to Walter Hussman, who will be publisher of the merged
paper, one major issue has already been resolved. ``The more
conservative Free Press editor said he'd like to move to the right
side,'' of the two-page layout, he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Different scandal, same messenger.
</P>
<P>
   Poll result: 58 percent of the public believes the presidential
scandal does not merit the amount of press coverage it has
received. (Source: a Media Studies Center survey in October about
the Clinton/Lewinsky story.).
</P>
<P>
   Poll result: 53 percent of the public believes the presidential
scandal does not merit the amount of press coverage it has
received. (Source: A June 1974 Gallup survey _ taken more than a
year after Capitol Hill hearings began _ asking whether journalists
were too obsessed with Watergate.)
</P>
</TEXT>
