<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     12-03 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... refined tastes.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Gardening From Scratch: How to Turn Your Empty Lot Into a
Living Garden,'' by Ann Lovejoy (Macmillan, $19.95). This is a
crash course for the new homeowner who needs to landscape ``from
scratch.'' Lovejoy first gardened in Massachusetts and now writes
and gardens on Bainbridge Island, in Washington. It takes into
account the reader's time, energy level, and budget, but does make
the design process seem complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Way to Garden: A Hands-On Primer for Every Season,'' by
Margaret Roach (Clarkson Potter, $30). Roach is garden editor of
Martha Stewart Living magazine and this book shares the same high
level of photography and design. She divides the year into a
gardener's calendar of six two-month segments beginning with
``Conception'' (January and February) and ending with ``Death and
Afterlife'' (November and December).
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Greenthumb Plows Ahead: Five Steps to the Drop-Dead
Garden of Your Dreams,'' by Cassandra Danz, (Crown, $25). Some
people wince at Danz (alias Mrs. Greenthumb) and her jokiness, but
I find her shtick a welcomed antidote to garden snobbery. Danz
shares good humor and good advice with the harried homeowner on a
quarter-acre lot, not the wanna-be lady of the manor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solviva: How to Grow $500,000 on One Acre &AMP; Peace on Earth;
Learning the Art of Living, with Solar-Dynamic, Bio-Benign
Design,'' by Anna Edey (Trailblazer Press, $35). Visionary Anna
Edey tells the story of her model experimental farm on Martha's
Vineyard, where she has raised organic vegetables, laying chickens,
sheep, and angora rabbits for the last 15 years using solar energy
and other nonpolluting technologies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perennials &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Well-Tended Perennial Garden: Planting and Pruning
Techniques,'' by Tracy DiSabato-Aust (Timber Press, Portland,
$29.95). This is the book of the year for anyone who gardens with
perennials. While most books focus on initial design and planting,
this details ongoing maintenance and particularly pruning for
specific types of perennials, a subject never before so thoroughly
covered. DiSabato-Aust tells which perennials are better
deadheaded, disbudded, thinned, pinched, or cut back to extend
flowering periods, with explanations of each technique. She even
tells how to renovate an overgrown garden without throwing
everything out. Her own garden-tested recipe for great soil, her
surprising list of the truly low-maintenance perennials, and her
tips on getting the most from each make this book a time-saving
road map to perennial success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perennial All Stars: The 150 Best Perennials for
Great-Looking, Trouble-Free Gardens,'' by Jeff Cox (Rodale Press,
$29.95). Get this book for beginners overwhelmed by the vast
variety of perennials available. I admire the bold specificity of
Cox's choices. Here's a man willing to pick the best day lily, the
best hosta, the best daffodil. Brave indeed. And mostly right. His
selections, such as Ingewersen's Variety cranesbill, Marshall's
Delight bee balm, David summer phlox, Lord Baltimore hibiscus, Alma
Potschke New England aster, and Ceasar's Brother Siberian iris,
match my own hard-earned experience as to the best ``doers'' in
each category. Well illustrated and easy to use, this book will
help readers pick winners next February when flipping through those
plant catalogs that rhapsodize about everything they sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Plantfinder's Guide to Tender Perennials,'' by Ian Cooke
(Timber Press, $34.95). Gardeners looking for something totally
different will be fascinated by the gorgeous and unfamiliar plants
in this well-photographed and designed directory of tropicals for
the outdoor garden. The new trend toward perennials that aren't
hardy in our zone may sound silly, but they do offer stunning
colors and exuberant foliage. Best of all, they make summer seem
longer, hitting full stride from August through October, when most
other plants have wound down. Instructions on overwintering are
included, but plants described as borderline hardy for the British
author are definitely not hardy for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gardener's Guide to Growing Daylilies,'' by Diana Grenfell
(Timber Press, $29,95). Day lily fans, and they are legion, will be
glad for this update on the new and remarkable cultivars. The color
photographs make all look as glittering and tempting as
sugar-crusted bonbons. But are they hardy here? Written by an
English gardener (with a chapter on day lilies in North America by
a Virginia gardener), this book doesn't say. Place your confidence
in cultivars that go dormant in the winter and approach varieties
labeled semi-evergreen or evergreen with caution. With day lilies,
it pays to buy from a local specialist such as Bob Seawright in
Carlisle or Tranquil Lake in Rehoboth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herbs in Bloom: A Guide to Growing Herbs as Ornamental
Plants,'' by Jo Ann Gardner (Timber Press, $34.95). No worry about
hardiness here. The author stumbled on the idea of using herbs as
ornamental perennials when they proved the only things she planted
that survived her first winter on her Canadian farm on remote Cape
Breton Island. In a friendly but straightforward manner Gardner
details propagation methods, site and soil selection for her 80
favorite flowering herbs. Good for northern New England gardeners. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reference Shelf &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Taylor's Guide to Growing North America's Favorite Plants,''
by Barbara Ellis (Houghton Mifflin, $35). Here is an encyclopedia
containing the most commonly grown perennials, bulbs, annuals,
vines, flowering shrubs and trees, in a single easy-to-read volume.
Especially helpful are the groupings by use with, for instance, one
heading for fragrant viburnums and another for viburnums with
four-season interest. Sidebars on topics such as tea herbs and
perennial tulips help make this hefty volume fun to explore.
</P>
<P>
   ``100 Orchids for the American Gardener,'' by Elvin McDonald
(Smith &AMP; Hawken Series, published by Workman, $17.95). Orchids are
the ultimate houseplant. This is the first orchid book to show the
whole plant, pot, foliage, and blooms, with outstanding photos by
Steven McDonald accompanied by his father's precise growing
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bird Gardening Book: The Complete Guide to Creating a
Bird-Friendly Habitat in Your Backyard,'' by Donald and Lillian
Stokes (Little, Brown, $12.95). Through the tips they outline here,
the Stokeses have transformed their own Carlisle yard from a wild
and tangled but effective bird santuary into a showpiece garden
equally attractive to birds and humans. This is by far the best of
several new books with a user-friendly pictorial format for bird
lovers who garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brooklyn Botanic Garden Gardener's Desk Reference,''
edited by Janet Marinelli (Henry Holt, $40). A well-done,
all-in-one reference that is part how-to guide and part
horticultural encyclopedia. It lists public gardens and plant
societies but also includes entertaining horticultural trivia such
as biographies of 50 great figures in garden history, seven of whom
lived in Massachusetts. Ecological issues are well-covered in four
chapters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tropical Look: An Encyclopedia of Dramatic Landscape
Plants,'' by Robert Lee Riffle (Timber Press. $49.95). It's
margarita time! If you're looking for a banana that can bounce back
from zero-degree temperatures or plants that merely look tropical,
this book has them, along with 400 color photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rose Garden Series: Shrub Roses; Tea Roses; Old-Fashioned
Roses; Climbing Roses,'' by Elvin McDonald (Smithmark, four books,
$12.95 each). Each of these four small but beautifully illustrated
books zeros in on a different category of rose, making them ideally
personal yet inexpensive gift books for true rose-lovers, who are
apt to have strong preferences. (For instance, fans of
old-fashioned roses often disdain tea roses.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Trees of the Central Hardwood Forests of North America: An
Identification and Cultivation Guide,'' by Donald J. Leopold,
William C. McComb, and Robert N. Muller (Timber Press, $49.95). Our
trees lose their leaves in the fall, but that's not true in most of
the country. Since the end of the last ice age, southeastern New
England has been part of what scientists call the Central Hardwood
Forests, a broad band of deciduous trees that are bordered on both
the north and south by evergreen forests. This scholarly manual
explains the different forest communities found locally and
describes the 188 native species that make up this diverse ecology,
with the goal of encouraging the conservation of this ecosystem and
the use of native trees in the landscape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
