<HEADER>
A1214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUPLES-WORK-2TAKES-A     12-03 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUPLES-WORK-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARRIAGES THAT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's been only a few times in their 30-year partnership that
Dr. Barbara Ann Payne Rockett has had to put Dr. Francis Xavier
Rockett in his place, publicly. And one of those occasions was
during a marathon operation on a 21-year-old woman with a brain
tumor. Six or seven hours into the surgery, Dr. Francis Rockett
turned to his wife and cosurgeon and said, ``Barbara, pay
attention!''
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Barbara Rockett turned to her husband and said, ``If you
keep that up, I'm leaving you!''
</P>
<P>
   But instead of a stunned silence (a la the TV show ``ER''),
everyone in the operating room at Newton-Wellesley Hospital _
nurses, anesthesiologists, attending surgeons _ burst out laughing.
They had just seen the Drs. Rockett at possibly their worst public
moment and they knew the husband and wife surgical team would
survive it.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed they have. Married 40 years, the Rocketts have
flourished doing what many couples today say they could never do:
work together and stay married. And along the way, they have raised
five children (two of whom are also doctors), and have won numerous
awards for their work in medicine and the community at large.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say the Rocketts, whose relationship seems as
comfortable and well-worn as the furnishings in their office, don't
have their differences. There are times, Francis Rockett
acknowledges, when he gets curt and moody, such as when he snapped
at his wife in the operating room. But there are consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get curt, I'll get my toast burned the next morning,'' he
says, with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after decades of being a rare breed, the Rocketts find
themselves joined by a growing phalanx of younger husband-and-wife
teams who have discovered the Rocketts' secret: being married to
your partner may be the best way to raise children and still work
full time in a job you love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you it's a growing phenomenon and that's because a
lot of women have figured out that it's one of the ways to
establish equity right from the beginning,'' says Fran Rogers, CEO
of Work/Family Directions, a national consulting firm in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we know from the research is that men and women often
enter marriage as equals in the workplace, but when children come,
the woman backs off and the man moves forward. But if you're doing
something together, you have a better chance of establishing an
equal relationship at home and with the business,'' Rogers says.
</P>
<P>
   The number of husbands and wives working together is also
growing, family business specialists say, because more people are
leaving corporate life and starting at-home businesses, and many
spouses are doing it together. According to the US Bureau of Labor
Statistics, the number of people working in home-based businesses
has doubled since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But so much togetherness carries a strong undercurrent of risk.
``If you have a lousy marriage, it's not going to work,'' Rogers
warns. ``You have to have a strong marriage going into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers should know. Ten years ago, after founding Work/Family
Directions in 1983, Rogers brought her husband, a labor economist,
into the business as her partner. And very early on, Rogers and her
husband, Charles, &UR;  &LR; learned that too much togetherness can suffocate
a marriage, particularly when both partners are strong-willed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is kind of an organized person who keeps notes from
week to week, and while I remember the important things, I don't
necessarily write things down or follow through the way he does,''
Rogers says. ``So when we tried to do things together it was too
much of a strain. Keep in mind that the honesty you're going to get
from a spouse is very different from what you're going to get from
an employee, so when he first joined the company, I have to say it
was a shock to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers says she and her husband solved that problem by
separating their roles. ``My husband, who has more of a research
and academic background, runs the consulting side of the business,
and I manage the service side of the business,'' Fran Rogers says.
``And we talk a lot. Communication is key; you can't let this stuff
build up.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Rogerses have long since figured out how to make their
differences work for them, Vera and John Diaz-Freitas, married
Brazilian immigrants who run a small jewelry store in downtown
Framingham, are still grappling with that issue.
</P>
<P>
   John Freitas, 32, a tall &UR;  &LR; man who laughs a lot, is the more
easygoing of the pair. Vera Diaz, also 32, a petite dark-haired
woman with a passion for life, is more high-strung. And there are
times, John Freitas says, when they will disagree over how to
handle a customer who, say, wants to return some jewelry and get
his money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's more aggressive on business matters,'' Freitas says.
``I'm more inclined to let things go.''
</P>
<P>
   When they do argue on the job, Vera Freitas says, it's very hard
for her to keep working in the same room with her husband. ``When
you have a disagreement, you don't want to see that person again
for a few hours,'' she says candidly. ``So sometimes I grab my
handbag and I go out and have a Starbucks coffee and then I'm fine
when I come back.''
</P>
<P>
   But underneath their flare-ups, the Diaz-Freitases say, lies a
strong current of mutual admiration and respect. A year after the
couple married in 1991 _ they met at a Brazilian Baptist church in
Framingham _ Vera decided to open the jewelry store, a risky
venture by any measure, and John supported her by continuing to
work in his cleaning business. Now that their jewelry business has
taken off, John has joined her in the store.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
