<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The newly elected Senate and House
leadership of both parties is oddly unrepresentative of the country
at large. The top leaders come from states with small populations.
Among the Democrats there is some regional diversity, but the
Republicans are largely southerners. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1400EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUPLES-WORK-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     12-03 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUPLES-WORK-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... in the store.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``She is the one who did all the work; she has all the credit
for it,'' John says of his wife. ``She really knows where to buy
and when to buy. She has a gift for business.''
</P>
<P>
   Vera, interviewed from Brazil, where she is on a business trip,
hasn't heard what her husband said about her. But when told, she
instinctively returns the compliment. ``I couldn't do it without
him,'' she says. ``He doesn't feel that if I'm growing, he has to
put me down. He likes to see me grow. It's really amazing the way
he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Such mutual generosity is not unique to the Diaz-Freitases
marriage. It is present in the 40-year marriage of the Rocketts,
who repeatedly sing each other's praise during a brief interview in
their Newton-Wellesley office. When asked what makes their
relationship tick, Francis Rockett, a genial, white-haired man who
could easily play Santa Claus without makeup or pillow, replies,
``We recognize we're a team. I bask in the glory of what she has
accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is obvious in the easy, laughter-filled rapport between
Mary Ann Thompson and Charles Rose, principals in their own
architectural firm in Harvard Square. Both 38 and dressed stylishly
in black as they greet a visitor in their office high above the
square, they laugh at each other's jokes and finish each other's
sentences as they explain how their philosophy of working together
fits with the way they are trying to run their marriage and raise
two young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thread that runs through our lives and our practice is the
thread of collaboration,'' says Mary Ann Thompson, who like her
husband is a graduate of Princeton and Harvard Graduate School of
Design. ``We have a shared goal _ to create an incredible project.
So we don't get competitive about who has the best idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The same thread runs through the marriage of Ed and Shelley
Rainen, who have worked together in the field of title law for
almost 20 years, while raising two children and making sure that
Shelley went back to earn her undergraduate degree and then her law
degree, at night. (She had dropped out of college to support Ed,
who was then in law school).
</P>
<P>
   ``Shelley worked full time the whole way through,'' her husband
says proudly. ``And she finished law school in three-and-a-half
years as opposed to four.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Rainen, ,45, who works as an equal alongside her husband
in their two-partner firm in Government Center, puts her finger on
it halfway through lunch at the Parker House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not threatened by me,'' she says, and he finishes the
thought: ``I want her to succeed,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, they fight. ``Just last night, we had an argument in
the car on the way home,'' Ed Rainen says casually. Rainen, 47,
hates to talk about work once he locks the door to the couple's
Center Plaza law office. But the other night, when the Rainens were
driving home from a late meeting around 10 p.m., Shelley Rainen
started in on a troublesome business matter that had come up that
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the opposing view and when she continued to argue with
me, I said I didn't want to talk about it anymore,'' he recalls.
``All of a sudden I was the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Rainen nods, sagely keeping quiet, and her husband
continues: ``Maybe it's the Mars and Venus thing. I tend to work
significantly later than Shelley _ for me to walk in the door
before 9 p.m. is a miracle _ and when I get out of the office, I
don't want to think or talk about work and sometimes Shelley
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Chan and Anne Mock, who are building an innovative
architectural practice a few blocks down the street from Thompson
and Rose, ran into the same roadblock when they first started
working together two years ago. And that gender gap was exacerbated
by the fact that their office was initially located in their
Cambridge home.
</P>
<P>
   There were blueprints all over the kitchen table and living room
floor, and the constant disarray drove Annie Mock, as everyone
calls her, crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a small space; it was really bad,'' recalls Mock,
a serious, competent-looking woman with a rosebud mouth. ``We
realized very quickly we needed a separate office.''
</P>
<P>
   Their new office, in a stately yellow Victorian a few blocks
from Harvard Square, has made a big difference. And their
workstyle, they say, gives them a flexibility that many of their
friends don't have. When Annie Mock, for instance, leaves work
every day at 1 p.m. to pick up their newly adopted 2-year-old
daughter from a nearby day-care center and bring her home, she
doesn't get any resentful stares from coworkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see that with our own friends who have high-powered jobs:
how difficult it is for them to get the flexiblity they need for
home and family,'' says Mock, 40, &UR;  &LR; who met her husband at the
Harvard Graduate School of Design. ``We have more flexibility.
There's a cost to it, of course; we have to worry about making a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are other costs. Chris Chan acknowledges that he still
occasionally gets exasperated by his partner's need to chew over
work-related problems after hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes think it works best to compartmentalize this
stuff,'' Chan says. Mock immediately disagrees: ``I don't think so.
I certainly can't compartmentalize!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he says. ``With Annie, stuff is always oozing out all
over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   And then they laugh and exchange affectionate, knowing grins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
