<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 ELLEN DeGENERES FOR MAYOR  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ellen DeGeneres and partner Anne Heche say
they're tired of anti-gay prejudice in Hollywood and they've
decided to move to either San Francisco or Ojai.
</P>
<P>
   Ojai, what's that? A sport played in Miami? Ellen, we want you.
Move to San Francisco. Who else can beat the city's mayor, Willie
Brown?
</P>
<P>
   I was the first to write ``Run, Willie, run'' back in early
1995. Do I regret it. I've been waiting for a bus ever since.
</P>
<P>
   I was a king-maker. Now I can be a queen-maker, pardon the
expression.
</P>
<P>
   Run, Ellen, run.
</P>
<P>
   We need a real comedian as mayor, a kind one, not an amateur
like Brown who laughs at his own mean jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Polls say Supervisor Tom Ammiano, who is gay and a comedian by
trade, could be a viable candidate for mayor. If Ammiano has a
chance, imagine the popularity of a comedian, a household first
name, who spent much of 1997 coming out on national television.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Ammiano says he's not running. ``It's scary,'' he told
me when I asked him about that poll. ``The world is flat.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Mayor Brown has gone flat.
</P>
<P>
   What would Ellen do about San Francisco's problems once she
takes office with Anne by her side? You can bet she wouldn't say
she'd fix the Municipal Railway's problems in 100 days.
</P>
<P>
   It took longer than that to promote her coming-out episode.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say there are advantages to having a real Hollywood
star running the city, instead of a wannabe who's always running
off to Los Angeles and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The homeless problem: Easy. They can be extras. The work pays
scale, and beats three years of Willie Brown pretending the
homeless don't exist.
</P>
<P>
   The housing shortage: Everyone can just hang around Ellen's
house, the way all those useless supporting characters did on her
TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Muni: On TV, Ellen ran a bookstore. She can give everyone who's
waiting for the train a book and a cup of coffee. Big ones.
</P>
<P>
   Being dictator: Heck, no, not her. On ABC, she only wanted to be
herself, not Mao or Napoleon.
</P>
<P>
   Sartorial splendor: None. No dress codes from Ellen. It'll be
come out as you are.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to figure out the rest of the Ellen program _ as hard
as it was to figure out the ``Ellen'' program when it began as
``These Friends of Mine.''
</P>
<P>
   At least it won't involve those friends of Willie's.
</P>
<P>
   Does Ellen have big developers as friends, or run a steamroller
of a political machine? No way. From what I read in the gossip
columns, she can't even get a producer to do lunch.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, we eat lunch, and do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen used to live and perform here. She shouldn't worry about
residency requirements, or whether she can go on tour while running
for office. Willie Brown is always on some trip.
</P>
<P>
   It's about time we had a gay mayor. It'd be a twofer. We'd get
Anne Heche as first partner.
</P>
<P>
   Heche stars in the remake of ``Psycho,'' playing the Janet Leigh
role. After looking at that picture of Frank Jordan, it'll be nice
to have a pro doing shower scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen and Anne can even take showers together. This is San
Francisco, and we won't put parental warnings on them the way ABC
did on Ellen's show.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco may be a theme park, but it's for adults. It's not
about to be bought by Disney.
</P>
<P>
   There are all kinds of good reasons to move to San Francisco
from L.A., besides becoming mayor and having a show that can't be
canceled for four years.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has better restaurants than L.A. And you don't
have to drive as far to get to them. Mayors don't have to figure
out where to park, either. They get squadrons of police motorcycles
as escorts.
</P>
<P>
   In L.A., the police only draw fire.
</P>
<P>
   San Franciscans love Hollywood stars who move here, and
immediately take them into their hearts and fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   San Franciscans don't stalk or gawk. It isn't cool. Instead,
they studiously pretend not to see celebrities until their backs
are turned.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen and Anne can even get married, and the local papers won't
cover the event. That's how cool we are.
</P>
<P>
   San Franciscans don't care if Ellen and Anne hold hands and
smooch as they walk around town. In fact, we hope they do. We won't
look. Honest.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I'm not Dick Morris, thank God, but here's the way I see
Ellen's campaign. Call it lavender triangulation.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the triangle, she wins the gay and lesbian votes.
She's an icon. It's a gimme. On the second side, she wins the
women's vote. She had Linda Ellerbee on the legendary last episode
of ``Ellen.'' There's the women's vote right there.
</P>
<P>
   On the hypotenuse of the triangle, she wins the
celebrity-worshiper vote. Brown tries too hard to be a celebrity.
And he may have had a lot of women on his arm, but definitely not
Anne Heche.
</P>
<P>
   Gays, women and celebrity worshipers add up to more voters than
Willie Brown can turn out no matter what he does with the registrar
of voters, when special polling places are opened, or how early and
often the dead vote.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, Ellen, any comedian can run this town.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
