<HEADER>
A1228 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-REMNICK-2TAKE     12-03 1529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-REMNICK-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW YORKER'S BOYISH WONDER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Includes editors box)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``My father was a dentist,'' David Remnick explains,
``and he got lots of magazines. One of them was The New Yorker. I
remember reading it, initially, like anybody else, because it had
these cartoons. . . . then, slowly, slowly, you get the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   A good 25 years later, as the magazine's editor, the 40-year-old
Remnick not only gets the idea of what makes The New Yorker what it
is, he gets to define it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it my dream job?'' Remnick asks of the post he's held since
Aug. 1. ``No. Am I liking it? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   He's only the fifth editor in the publication's 73-year history,
putting him in a line of succession that comprises two certified
magazine legends (Harold Ross and William Shawn), a man widely
regarded as the finest book editor in postwar US publishing (Robert
Gottlieb), and the once and future empress of buzz (Tina Brown).
</P>
<P>
   This is heady company to be in, and editing The New Yorker may
be the most coveted job in print journalism and, from the sheer
weight of all that covetousness, the most onerous.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation about dozens of possible successors when
Brown made the surprise announcement in July that she'd be leaving
to start up her own magazine. But the one who got the job was
Remnick, a dark horse unity candidate commonly regarded as the only
contender who might combine the best of Brown's innovations with a
feel for the magazine's fabled sense of tradition. ``There's joy in
Mudville,'' senior editor Hendrik Hertzberg told The Washington
Post the day Remnick's selection was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Remnick joined The New Yorker as a staff writer in 1992. One of
Brown's first hires, he almost immediately emerged as her era's
biggest star (after Brown herself, of course). On the day his
selection was announced, she called him ``the key member of my
dream team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Storybook 101: Boy meets magazine; magazine gets boy; boy
gets magazine. There was even a juicy subplot: New Yorker owner S.
I. Newhouse Jr. had briefly tapped an outsider, Slate editor
Michael Kinsley, only to rescind the offer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Brown's calm legatee
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker had long been America's most revered
general-interest magazine. Brown made it the most talked about: for
better, the 200,000 new readers she brought to it would argue _ for
worse, traditionalists, and the magazine's balance sheet, would
counter. Remnick has no trouble with being Brown's legatee. ``What
she did was she revived (The New Yorker) by intelligently getting
rid of the `cannots': You can't have photographs, you can't have
color, you can't do this, you can't do that. It took a kind of
rebellious spirit, like Tina's, to say, `Well, why not try to do
it?' . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I agree with every single decision she made? No. And no
one here agrees with every single decision I make. But I think she
played a great role here, without having to deify it.''
</P>
<P>
   What changes Remnick has made since taking over have been
incremental. New York magazine's David Denby has come aboard as a
film critic, and The Village Voice's Peter Schjeldahl as art
critic. The Shouts &AMP; Murmurs page has been moved from the back of
the magazine to the middle. The New York Times's Elizabeth Kolbert
will be writing a column on city politics. More generally, the
magazine's Brownian motion has grown visibly less agitated (there
have been, as yet, no articles about dominatrixes under the new
regime).
</P>
<P>
   In person as in print, where Brown was a cool whirl of activity,
Remnick suggests a penetrating stability. He has sleepy eyes and a
boyish air. He talks in unhurried, even tones that aren't so much
soft-spoken as calm-spoken. The whole package _ eyes, air, speech _
works to allay the otherwise-disconcerting effect of the liveliness
of his intelligence, like putting a 45-rpm record in a 33-rpm
sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
360-degree curiosity
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An agile mind married to an almost-rabbinical equanimity: It's a
good combination in an editor. Nor does it hurt to have an
almost-360-degree curiosity. As a staff writer, Remnick was a
one-man table of contents, equally comfortable writing about Amish
drug dealers and warring Shakespeare scholars, Boris Yeltsin and
Michael Jordan. A. J. Liebling, one of Ross's greatest hires, once
wrote of his boss, ``Many aspects of life entranced him
imprecisely.'' When this remark is quoted to Remnick, he roars with
laughter. ``My first and foremost fault as a writer was an
imprecision of obsession,'' he declares.
</P>
<P>
   That's a very good line and a very good thing in his new line.
On the other hand, Remnick has never previously held an editing job
(his high school paper excepted), and he's finding out what it
means to have to use different editorial muscles. ``Writing is
singular. You're thinking about your piece, your next interview,''
he explains. ``Editing is the opposite. You are trying to help
someone else do their best work. One enterprise is nobly selfish,
and the other'' _ he breaks into a grin _ ``is ignobly unselfish.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem facing Remnick is rather less substantial. Even
Brown's harshest critics had to concede that the former editor of
Vanity Fair _ the executive with the most famous fashion allowance
in publishing _ was in synch with an important part of New Yorker
tradition: the magazine's being the epitome, in Remnick's nice
phrase, of a certain ``Manhattan champagne fizz.'' In attire,
anyway, her successor is more Sam Adams than Veuve Clicquot.
Remnick might be Eustace Tilley, the magazine's dandified mascot,
in an anti-universe: Tilley's monocle, top hat, and cravat would be
as unthinkable on Remnick as his earth tones, open-necked shirts,
and rolled-up sleeves would be on Tilley.
</P>
<P>
   There's a divergence in attitude, as well. A side effect of The
New Yorker's special place in magazine culture has been a certain
institutional arrogance. The late Brendan Gill titled his
best-selling memoir of the magazine, ``Here at The New Yorker'';
the implicit subtitle was ``Out There All the Rest of You.'' It's
hard to detect much New Yorker affectation about Remnick. He has an
easy modesty and relaxed, slouchy manner born of absolute
confidence (why dress for success when you're already so
successful?). Solicitousness and a shrug come naturally to someone
who not only knows how good he is, but knows everyone else does,
too.
</P>
<P>
   An international reputation earned during four years as Moscow
correspondent for The Washington Post, four books published in five
years (the first of which, ``Lenin's Tomb,'' won both a Pulitzer
Prize and George Polk Award), 100 New Yorker bylines in six years:
Even if Si Newhouse fired him tomorrow, Remnick knows his family
wouldn't starve. For one thing, his wife, Esther B. Fein, earns a
good salary as a New York Times reporter. (Remnick and Fein have
two sons, Alexander and Noah, and live on Manhattan's Upper West
Side.) For another, he can always go back to his first love,
writing and reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Remnick started at the Post as an intern on its Style section.
He briefly worked the night police beat, then spent three years as
a sportswriter before returning to Style for another three. He
wasn't quite 30 and was a rising star at one of the country's best
papers. But in 1988 came the move that took him to a wholly new
level.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of artwork adorns the walls of Remnick's large but
far-from-imposing office: family pictures, sports photographs, book
jackets. Surprisingly enough, only one is a New Yorker cartoon. A
beggar holding a tin cup wears a sign that says, ``Expert on
Russia.'' ``It seems appropriate,'' Remnick says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The luck of Moscow
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After going to Moscow, Remnick's career would never be the same.
``That was an accident _ a happy, happy accident,'' he sighs. ``I
put my name in for Moscow because I just thought it would change my
life and it sounded thrilling, and I wanted both things to happen:
change and thrills. I was too young to be in the office all day _ I
thought. I had no reasonable sense that I'd get sent, because they
don't send feature writers off to revolutions. . . . And I got
preposterously lucky _ and I mean preposterously lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   His Moscow days led to ``Lenin's Tomb'' and Remnick's third
book, ``Resurrection: The Struggle for a New Russia,'' and they
even crop up in his second book, ``The Devil Problem and Other True
Stories,'' a collection of magazine pieces that includes a
memorable profile of Alexander Solzhenitsyn and a moving tribute to
Joseph Brodsky. But Remnick wrote his latest book, ``King of the
World: Muhammad Ali and the Rise of an American Hero,'' as a
conscious departure from what he jokingly calls ``all these baggy
Russian books.''
</P>
<P>
   The former heavyweight champion might seem an odd choice for
someone who for some time now has had his pick of assignments. But
Remnick's passion for Ali predates even those adolescent visits to
his father's waiting room to see what William Steig or Charles
Addams had been up to that week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
