<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1230 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-ICE-BOS &LR;      12-03 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HEROIC TALE OF MEN ON THE ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE ICE MASTER 
By James Houston 
McLelland &AMP; Stewart, 372 pp., $29.99 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   North America holds no area more romantic, more unknown, more
mysterious than the icy waters off Baffin Island, just south of the
Arctic Circle. In the 1870s those waters, so cold, so uncharted, so
forbidding, were inhabited by whales _ and, it strains credulity
still, by small bands of hardy men from New England and
Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   The men, determined to harvest the whale's oil for lights and
its bone for ladies' corsets, were of a different breed _
independent, to be sure; adventurous, of course; foolhardy,
probably. They were also smart and tough and crooked and mean and
inspiring and courageous.
</P>
<P>
   James Houston's ``The Ice Master'' is a tale of captains
courageous, and of boat steerers, coopers, sailmakers, carpenters,
stewards, cooks, and ship's boys. Together they sailed the great
whaling ships and together, when the big freezes came and the snows
blew, they planted tiny, isolated whaling camps on the ice. Their
lives were all but unknown to their contemporaries, and all but
unknown to us.
</P>
<P>
   This volume is a novel, a gazetteer, a field guide, a
reminiscence, and a morality tale. But it is also a lengthy
statement about a life that has disappeared and a breed of man that
has vanished. Think of it as a tribute that cries: Lest we forget.
</P>
<P>
   Houston hasn't. His name provokes no nods of recognition in New
England, where the waters are cold but not frigid, but he is
something of a folk hero in Canada, where the ice defies man's
humble strength and noblest intentions. A half-century ago he
ventured into the Arctic on a sketching trip and returned with a
cache of folk crafts that introduced the term ``Eskimo art'' to the
urban centers of Canada and the United States. For years he lived
in the North, learning the folkways and life rhythms of the Inuit,
as the native people of the region today are called.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has sketched a credible portrait of a world unimaginable,
where agile mammals with primitive tools battle ancient mammals
with terrifying instincts. His rendering of life on Arctic-bound
ships and at Arctic hunting camps is unforgiving and unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   The story is punctuated with a remarkable set of characters and
episodes, classic elements of the literature of the mariner.
Mutiny. Mutineers in leg irons or stuffed into wooden barrels.
Flights of snow geese. Men in sealskin mitts and boots and
caribou-skin pants and parkas. Feasts of seal kidney stew.
Explosions of gunpowder shattering the spring ice.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way there are shards of colorful mariner talk and
flashes of graceful writing: ``At night, Finn lay on the bed in his
cabin, eyes open, staring through the dark, imagining that he and
his anxious crew were holding old Lancer afloat with their stomach
muscles.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a gripping group portrait of men on ice. They
lived on provisions of salt beef and pork, molasses, salt mackerel
and cod, coffee, tea, vinegar, dried corn meal, pickles, and beans.
They knew that the rancid whale oil that soaked their hulls also
helped keep their ships afloat. They scrubbed each other down with
pig-bristle brushes and horse-tar soap. They believed whistling
aboard ship brought bad luck, but whistling on shore brought good
luck. They handled dental problems by inserting a patient's head in
a wooden vise and twisting the stricken teeth out with pliers.
</P>
<P>
   These were not toffs and dandies. They lived with native people,
hunted with them, slept with them, respected them. When they
departed for warmer climates (and for the paymaster), they missed
them. These men were a little salty, a little lusty, but they were
not without sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   The climax is gripping, terrifying, and masterfully drawn, as
the crippled Sea Horse limped home from the Arctic only to be
battered and broken apart off Montauk Point:
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge wave caught Sea Horse on the starboard quarter, lifted
her, and thrust her hard on top of Blackfish Rock, and the hatch
cover, with men still clinging to it, was hurled into the water.
The ship stopped with a grinding, tearing jolt and hung there
shuddering, her bottom ripped wide open. Sea Horse was defenseless
against the power of the next incoming wave. This wall of water,
when it struck her, broke Sea Horse's spine.''
</P>
<P>
   This life is gone now. Fortunately, it is not forgotten.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1403EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
