<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1232 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-REMNICK-2ND &LR;  &UR;      12-03 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-REMNICK-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... that week.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Ali was this great hero of mine as a kid,'' Remnick explains.
``He was thrilling the way rock 'n' roll is thrilling. At that
time, for me, it was Bob Dylan, Muhammad Ali _ and it just doesn't
go away (I saw Dylan two weeks ago at the Garden, looking not bad,
by the way, with Joni Mitchell). And Ali kept evolving: beginning
first with shtick and athletics, then evolving into something with,
well, greater dimensions: a religious dimension, a racial
dimension, a political dimension. . . . He's just so interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ali's youthful admirer
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was more than keeping faith with a youthful admiration that
moved Remnick to write about Ali. It was also journalistic
instinct: the sheer richness of the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the fact that the Ali story in the '60s has the
classic proportions of the conventional novel. The main character
changes over time and is faced with improbable odds and difficult
decisions _ it's like right out of the handbook. You have secondary
characters who both reflect the main character and (are themselves)
of enormous interest: Sonny Liston and Floyd Patterson. Then you
have interesting times. And you have tertiary characters like
Malcolm X, (fight manager) Cus D'Amato, (sportswriters) Jimmy
Cannon and Bob Lipsyte, the Beatles. It's a gift, a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Remnick saw Ali's 1976 title defense against Ken Norton at
Yankee Stadium, sitting in a $25 seat that was closer to Queens
than it was to the ring. That was the only time, though. ``I wasn't
even allowed to go to closed-circuit things,'' Remnick laughs. He
adds that his parents ``didn't mind that I loved Muhammad Ali but
they weren't ready to shell out 25 bucks so I could go to a
theater'' to see a fight.
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey native, Remnick was born in Hackensack, grew up in
Hillsdale, and went to college at Princeton. If it was in a
dentist's waiting room that Remnick first encountered The New
Yorker, it was in a college seminar room that he truly fell under
its spell. Besides being one of the magazine's most celebrated
writers, John McPhee has long taught a course at Princeton on the
literature of fact. Remnick took it his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine that it must be like someone who has seen a lot of
movies, and has read a lot about this director and that director,
then gets a chance to spend a semester hearing Martin Scorsese talk
about acting and editing and actually making something into a
movie. . . . Princeton tuition cost a lot back then _ a lot _ but
getting to learn from McPhee was worth every penny.''
</P>
<P>
   The seed had been planted. ``Quite frankly, as much as I loved
The Washington Post, the thought of going to The New Yorker (which
seemed fairly impossible for a long time) was always there,''
Remnick says. And now, he's here, at the top, at The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I don't know how this thing will turn out,'' he says.
``I hope I might turn out to be good at it. It's early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never, ever in a million years have done this anywhere
else. I can't presume I would have been offered a job anywhere
else, but I also know I wouldn't have done it. I care immensely
about The New Yorker. I think its existence, its thriving, is
important not only to the 800,000 readers. But it's important to
have a weekly magazine that's on the search for the very best
fiction, poetry, narrative journalism, essays, criticism. Believe
me _ believe me _ I know there is good of all that elsewhere. But
as a single roof, this is a very unique place. I just care about
this place, I always have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEW YORKER NOTABLES
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
In its 73 years, The New Yorker has played host to a legendary
array of writing and editing talent. Here are New Yorker editor
David Remnick's comments on six of the magazine's best-known names,
himself included. &QL; 
 &QL; 
John Updike: Updike is our Ted Williams _ and, of course, I was
terrified about dealing with him (the whole notion of editing John
Updike is hilarious on the face of it). Yet it turns out he's more
game, more open to suggestions, than any 25-year-old freelancer. .
. . He's an incredible man.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A. J. Liebling: Liebling is probably my favorite, the big vibrating
guy with the belly, he's such a writer of joy.. . . The image of
him sitting in his office, laughing at his own lines as he pounded
away at the typewriter, jiggling with delight, is a kind of cream
soda _ a Cel-Ray tonic _ to think about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harold Ross: Too much is made of his lack of education. To have
produced this magazine he had to be a very clever guy and very
smart indeed. The famous story about him writing in the margin next
to a Moby-Dick reference, ``Who he: the man or the whale''? That's
shtick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
William Shawn: The stereotype of Shawn as someone Buddha-like and
soft-spoken to the point of inaudibility and simon-pure and the
rest? In fact, this was a guy who played jazz piano and had real
passions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tina Brown: Can I be very frank with you? I think this business
of ``Tina Brown, show-biz editor'' is baloney.. . . Circulation
(during Brown's tenure) went from 600,000 to 800,000. I don't think
the new 200,000 people signed on to get Show Biz magazine, to get
Photoplay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Remnick: People like Ross and Shawn, and probably Tina Brown,
have attached to them a 15-word thumbnail sketch. I don't know what
mysketch is at this point _ I don't know if I'm even worth having
one at this point.
</P>
</TEXT>
