<HEADLINE>
REMEMBER, TURKEYS ARE PEOPLE, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few days before Thanksgiving, emerging from Park Street Under
at dusk, I heard chanting: ``One, two, three, four! Don't eat
turkeys anymore!''
</P>
<P>
   The source was a knot of demonstrators standing near the T
entrance. Some of them were holding signs depicting the horrors of
turkey farming. One was handing out leaflets adorned with a drawing
of a turkey family _ tom, hen, chicks _ gathered around a dinner
table, and several ``Thankful Turkey Recipes,'' including one for
roasted tom tofu.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators were there to remind passersby that there are
those who look upon turkeys not as food, but as individuals in
their own right, entitled to live out their lives in peace and not
end up roasted on a dinner table. Their struggle _ the
demonstrators' struggle, that is _ is a noble one, but let's face
it, one that's pretty much uphill. The turkeys' struggle is even
grimmer, and, generally speaking, a losing one, especially during
the holiday season, when millions are slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   The brochure gave an address for ordering a vegan cookbook
published by Farm Sanctuary, a rescue organization that maintains
shelters for abused and neglected farm animals in New York and
California. Farm Sanctuary has an adopt-a-turkey program. For $15
you can sponsor a turkey. In return you receive a color photograph
of your turkey and an adoption card. Holly McNulty, who works at
the sanctuary in Watkins Glen, N.Y., said the adopt-a-turkey
program runs through the holiday season because so many people like
to give a turkey as a gift. I adopted one named Cosmos for my
husband. We await his, or her, photograph and adoption card,
eagerly. (If you'd like to adopt a turkey, call 888-776-6767.)
</P>
<P>
   The makers of Tofurky, a vegan turkey substitute (``A Delicious
Vegetarian Feast''), donate part of their profits to Farm
Sanctuary's program. I'm not a vegetarian, just one of those
hypocrites who would be a vegetarian if she ever had to kill
anything. The demonstrators had started me thinking about the mass
slaughter of turkeys, and frankly, I was getting a little queasy at
the prospect of eating one. I like tofu. I thought I'd try Tofurkey
on an experimental basis, before Thanksgiving. (My husband and I
took our mothers out to dinner on the big day, to the Mohegan Sun
casino, but that's another story.)
</P>
<P>
   I bought a small Tofurky roast ($19.95), thawed it, and cooked
it as directed, basting it in a mixture of orange juice, soy sauce,
and honey. I baked the accompanying six tempeh ``drummettes,''
which resembled drumstick-shaped Gardenburgers, and heated the
package of ``heavenly golden mushroom gravy.'' When the Tofurky
emerged from the oven it looked like something you might see in a
glass case at the Basketball Hall of Fame with a sign reading,
``Prototype basketball designed by James Naismith, 1891,'' a
battered, deflated spheroid object.
</P>
<P>
   It tasted only slightly better than it looked. The consistency
of the ``flesh'' was similar to turkey, but more rubbery. Actually,
it tasted like nothing much at all, certainly not tofu. The
stuffing wasn't bad, if a bit salty. But the ``heavenly'' gravy was
unspeakable. The drummettes tasted a little like Gardenburgers.
They were the best part by far.
</P>
<P>
   A vegetarian neighbor, Jim Levinson, obligingly sampled the
Tofurky. I wanted his opinion. He said it wasn't bad, exactly.
Would he want to eat it on Thanksgiving? ``I'd prefer a
Gardenburger,'' he said. Personally, I'd just as soon skip turkey
and Tofurky and move straight to dessert.
</P>
<P>
   As a tofu lover, I can't help thinking that Tofurky amounts to
cruelty to tofu. Maybe the president could be persuaded to
``pardon'' a Tofurkey next Thanksgiving, along with the turkey he
reprieves every year, and send them both to Farm Sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
