<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING WITH THE FEAR OF DYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend Christina was diagnosed with a precancerous throat
condition at 42. Six years later, in 1992, she was diagnosed and
treated for breast cancer. Five years later, in 1997, while she was
in Holland visiting her family, she became exhausted and feverish.
Rushed to a hospital emergency room, she was operated on for
ovarian cancer and later treated at Dana-Farber in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   She gave a sermon at our Unitarian-Universalist Church that
spring, speaking from the heart about the ``Euthanasia Passport''
she had obtained in the Netherlands, a document that gives anyone
with a fatal illness the right to decide at what point they wish to
end their suffering. She talked about what a comfort it was to know
she would be allowed to make that choice. Then, seemingly restored
to health, she went on with her life.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, however, she felt unusually tired once again. She
had a blood test and discovered her blood count had risen 12 points
above the normal range, a sign that the cancer was returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first response was total fear,'' she tells me as we sit
together over coffee. As members of the steering committee of the
Marblehead Cancer Prevention Project, we are colleagues as well as
friends. ``I felt I was coming totally unwrapped and although I had
no control over the cancer, it was not OK with me to have fear
rampant like this. But I couldn't just push it away. I had to come
to grips with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Christina decided to spend a week at Kripalu, a yoga center in
Western Massachusetts where a woman named Dayashakti was teaching a
method of entering deep within called ``Wave Work.'' The process is
designed to create a safe space for the integration of strong
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Christina found herself able to enter a deep state of
relaxation. With the support of a partner, she visualized healing
energy coming toward the cancer as waves of color swept across her
mind's eye and a sense of lightness flooded her body. ``The first
two days,'' she says, ``I had a very positive experience of
relaxing into my body in the most wonderful way.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, however, when she entered the same relaxed state,
she was invaded by an overwhelming sense of sadness. Did she really
have to go through this again? It seemed more than she could bear.
In her mind she asked the Universal Power for help.
</P>
<P>
   I'll let her tell the rest in her own words:
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, I saw myself on a high, overhanging ledge. I was in
a deep trance, and yet, though I was still aware of where I was and
what was happening, I knew somehow I had to get up and jump. I was
unsure whether I would be crushed when I landed or fall into a
feather bed. And then I dove into the abyss. But I didn't fall.
Instead, wrapped in what seemed to be a linen shroud _ like a piece
of candy twisted at both ends _ I was swirling in a cone of light
full of beautiful colors. I could sense that there were beings of
some sort at the top of the cone and I wanted them to pop me out of
the wrappings so I could go there. I wanted to join them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying out loud, `I'm dying. I'm dying,' but at one
point I laughed out loud. I felt so incredibly alive. I had no
sorrows, nothing weighing me down. And then I felt a pinch on my
left toe, pulling me back into my body, and I was back in the room,
laughing, feeling so free, so unbrittle. I remember saying to my
partner, `My God, dying is the most alive thing you can do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Christina is radiant, reexperiencing those sensations as she
describes them with a quiet confidence. I can feel the power of
that knowledge in her. The hair is standing up on the back of my
arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda,'' she continues, ``when I went to Kripalu I was
expecting simply to release the tension I was feeling and, instead,
I felt something flowing into my body, and it was pure ecstasy. I
had a visceral experience of dying and there was no negative, only
pure being, gentle and alive and very deeply felt. Oh, my God, we
worry so much about dying and it's the most alive thing we'll ever
do.''
</P>
<P>
   That evening at Kripalu, feeling calm and unafraid, Christina
checked her answering machine. The fact that she'd had a follow-up
blood test had slipped her mind until she heard her doctor's voice,
giving her the test results. In one week Christina's blood count
had shot up dramatically from 12 to 72 points above the normal
range.
</P>
<P>
   (To be continued.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's website is at www.shore.net(tilde)weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
