<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1245 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-03 1704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING KIDS CURB THE HOLIDAY `GIMMES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When her daughter was 3, Nina Senatore set to work to combat the
``Gimmes,'' that awful disease of childhood that runs rampant
around Christmas and Hanukkah.
</P>
<P>
   Early in December, Senatore would give Amanda scissors, glue,
cardboard, and toy catalogs and tell her to cut out pictures of
toys she liked and paste them on the cardboard. Another day, they
would go through her toys, discarding what was broken, outgrown, or
what Amanda wanted to give to charity. That served as a reference
point later on for Senatore, who could say with credibility,
``Remember how that crying doll broke really quickly?'' or ``Didn't
you say that toy was boring?''
</P>
<P>
   The trip to the toy store was next. This is typically headache
time, when the Gimmes are at their peak. But Amanda had a mission.
Armed with her cardboard cutouts, she would compare the real toy to
its picture and write-up, eliminating as she went along.
</P>
<P>
   What survived the cut would now be divided into two categories,
``toys you can create with'' and ``toys that are what they are.''
It didn't take her many years to catch on to her mother's bias or
to see the wisdom of it: Toys from the latter category get boring,
toys from the former are more fun for a longer time. Each year,
that list would grow while the other would shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Amanda is 12, the cardboard has evolved into notebooks
and she's graduated from toy to clothing catalogs (she circles the
item and folds the page instead of cutting and pasting), but the
pre-list scouting trip is no less instructive.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's picked up a lot of nuances about advertising at a young
age,'' says her mother, a developmental education specialist and
assistant professor at Simmons College.
</P>
<P>
   In an age of acquisition in which children are unwitting targets
of marketing campaigns that reach a frantic peak this time of year,
developing an analytical eye is not only an antidote to the Gimmes
but arguably a survival skill for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are not born with the Gimmes,'' says educator and
child developmentalist Judith T. Wagner. ``They only turn into
materialistic creatures with the help of grown-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   The more-is-better inculcation typically begins when a child is
2 or 3, when there's a literal pile for her under the tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overwhelming,'' says Senatore. ``Even if there's a
wonderful, creative toy in that pile, there are too many toys to
appreciate any one.'' The inescapable message even to a toddler is
that there is value in acquisition alone.
</P>
<P>
   It's never too late to start to limit quantity, even if a child
is older; in fact, the older a child, the more you can discuss it.
Keep it non-judgmental and impersonal: ``I've heard about some
families where they agree to a limit on the number of presents each
person gets. I'm wondering about the pros and cons of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Child psychologist Roni Leiderman tells parents not to take
literally every request your child makes for this or that toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time she says, `I want this,' it's instinctive; she
sees something and can't control the impulse to say she wants it,''
says Leiderman, who is director of the Family Center at Nova
Southeastern University in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute the word ``admire'' for ``want''; it reflects more
accurately what's in her mind. ``She's attracted to it but she
doesn't expect to get it any more than we expect to get everything
we see and like,'' says Leiderman.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking she's simply admiring the toy will also keep you from
accusing her of being a spoiled brat. When we respond negatively or
put her down _ ``That toy is a waste of money!'' ``How many toys
can one child have?'' _ we make matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has to justify herself,'' says Leiderman. The more
defensive she becomes, the more she convinces herself of her own
argument. Now she not only wants it, she can't live without it.
</P>
<P>
   Leiderman says that offering a sympathetic response _ ``I can
see why you want this!'' ``That does look exciting!'' _ enables a
child to move on because you validate rather than belittle her.
</P>
<P>
   For the times when this doesn't work, try granting your child
her wish in fantasy: ``It would be fun to play with this''; turn
catalog shopping into a learning experience: ``Let's cut out all
the toys with wheels''; or defuse the situation by buying time: ``I
can see how much you like it. Why don't you add this to your list
and decide about it later?'' This also works when a child is
unhappy: ``I can see you're sad not to get that toy. You must be
very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gimmes are not fueled only by quantity. We also need to pay
attention to the kind of play a toy encourages and the values it
represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many of these toys come with hidden messages that push
grown-up ideas on little kids,'' says Wagner, who is director of
the Broadoaks Children's School, the lab school of Whittier College
in California. ``Without realizing it, we buy into, in fact, we pay
for retailers to dictate values to our children.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing for Mom to paint her preschooler's nails while
she does her own; that's part pretending but it's also part
bonding. To buy a preschooler a cosmetic, nail, or hairstyling kit
(there's one on the market this season called Miss Glamour) sends a
different message entirely. ``It tells a little girl, `This
(concept) is for you,' and encourages her to embrace behaviors
she's too young for,'' says Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Because children under 7 typically can't make the cognitive leap
to think about how an ad or catalog write-up was made to appeal to
them, early childhood educator Diane Levin tells parents to
deconstruct ads.
</P>
<P>
   She suggests asking a series of questions: I wonder how they
made that toy do that? If we had that toy, do you think it would
work that way? What else could you do with it besides play with it
the way they're showing? I've never seen kids look that happy
playing with a toy, have you?
</P>
<P>
   Also don't be afraid to restate your values, says Levin, a
professor at Wheelock College: ```It looks like all this action
figure does is fight and you know I don't like violence. Is there
anything else you could do with it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Although Amanda came to value creative toys, almost every year
one or two trendy toys would make it to her final wish list, and
almost every year Senatore and her husband, John, would pick the
least offensive to put under the tree. ``Parents need to be
sensitive to kids' needs to fit in,'' Senatore says.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other strategies to fight the Gimmes:
</P>
<P>
   _Involve children in giving to charity. One Hanukkah gift Levin
and her husband give their son every year is a certificate:
``Tonight, your present is a gift to the charity of your choice.''
They typically offer him a list to choose from, like Oxfam or World
Wildlife Fund. Now a teenager, Eli is likely to add some of his own
money to the donation.
</P>
<P>
   _Create family rituals. ``The greatest gift is time spent as a
family,'' says Wagner. When her children were growing up, there
would always be a family game under the tree. Christmas afternoon
would be devoted to playing it together. ``That's what the kids
remember most about our Christmases,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   _Create gifts that encourage creativity. Last year, Wagner gave
her step-grandchildren, ages 13, 8, and 6, discarded bolts from a
fabric store, $10 worth of strong tape, and yards of frilly organza
she bought on sale. They spent the afternoon making a house, a
road, and costumes. Levin encourages what she calls Shoe Box Gifts,
which is a collection of small items organized around a play theme
(office, restaurant, rescue) and placed in a decorated shoe box.
Office, for instance, might include a message pad, receipt book,
labels, ink pad, stamps.
</P>
<P>
   By combining strategies, Senatore says it's not only possible to
immunize children to the holiday Gimmes but to turn them into
thoughtful consumers all year long. She knew that had happened with
Amanda the day her daughter looked at a picture of a doll in a
catalog and said she doubted it could really fit on the toy horse
the way it was pictured.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUGGESTIONS FOR PARENTS &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, TRUCE (Teachers Resisting Unhealthy
Children's Entertainment) has published a list of Toys for Healthy
and Creative Play and Toys to Avoid. Here is a sampling of toys on
their lists for 1998:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Watch out for toys that: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Hook infants and toddlers on TV, computers, and older
children's issues, for instance: Talking Teletubbies by Playskool,
Microsoft Actimates Interactive Barney by Microsoft, or Barbie
Shapes at the Ballet (Golden Books).
</P>
<P>
   _Transform traditional creative play materials into overly
structured play, for instance: Playdough Doh-Bot by Playskool,
Godzilla Sound Bytes Puppet by Resaurus, Scala Lego Series by Lego.
</P>
<P>
   _Focus girls on teenage issues: Spice Girl dolls by Galoob,
Barbie and Friends Conference Phone by Mattell.
</P>
<P>
   _Entice boys in antisocial behavior: X-Files Fight the Future
Series by McFarland Toys, World Wrestling Federation Goldust and
Marlena by Jakks Pacific, Kiss Psycho Circus Ultra Action Figures
by McFarland.
</P>
<P>
   _Promote violence: Nerf Sports Turbo Spiked Football by Kenner,
Predator Bike Helmet by Variflex.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Go out of your way to find toys that:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Encourage social skills: Imagination Transportation by Creative
Art Activities, Classic Sport Set by R.A.M. Sports, the Very Busy
Baker by ALEX.
</P>
<P>
   _Encourage physical skills: Toobers and Zots by Hands-on, Brio
Builder System by Brio, Hoppity Ball by Small World Toys.
</P>
<P>
   _Develop thinking skills: Max Discovers Shapes and Colors by
International Playthings, Goodnight Moon Memory Game by Briarpatch,
Paint Center by Koosh Creative.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
