<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-RATES (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The central banks of the 11
European countries that are adopting a common currency next month
unexpectedly cut interest rates to combat what the president of the
German bank calls a ``clouded'' economic outlook. The reductions
reflect growing concern among central banks that the global economy
may be heading for recession next year. In this country, the Fed
has lowered rates three times within two months. Earlier in the
day, Germany reported that its economy grew 0.9 percent in the
third quarter from the prior three months and 2.8 percent from a
year earlier, powered by industrial output, a pace economists say
probably cannot be maintained. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-ASSESS (Washington) _ Was it an accident that the
European countries cut rates on the day that German Finance
Minister Lafontaine is in Washington to meet with Treasury
Secretary Rubin and company? This was the very action that
President Clinton had called for in October, drawing a skeptical
response from Europeans. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-DEAL (Undated) _ A look at how the the Exxon-Mobil deal
was put together. A reconstruction. By Allen R. Myerson. (1500
words)
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-LOBBY (Undated) _ In the short run at least, the lobbying
presence of Exxon and Mobil in Washington is expected to increase
as a result of the merger, not decline. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:45 p.m., the industrial average was
down 115 points. Elsewhere, prices declined 1.9 percent in Tokyo
and 0.1 percent in Hong Kong. They rose 2.3 percent in Frankfurt
and 1.2 percent in London. They fell 6.8 in Brazil and 1.5 percent
in Mexico. On the American debt market, the long bond was unchanged
at midday, with the yield at 5.02 percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL-SALES (Undated) _ Discount retailers and specialty
clothing chains report higher same-store sales for November, but
department stores saw slower results as the holiday shopping season
began. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ Developments at the Microsoft
antitrust trial. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ General Motors and Ford wrap up November
sales today, and the final data are expected to show that light
trucks took 51 percent of the market for the first time. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Japan's economy shrank in the year's third
quarter, marking the fourth consecutive quarterly contraction _ the
first time that has happened. It fell 0.7 percent from the previous
quarter, or at a 2.6 percent annual rate, as shriveling corporate
profits led companies to slash investment spending. By Sheryl
WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CHIPS (Tokyo) _ Raising the stakes in the race to develop
the next generation of computer memory chips, Toshiba and Fujitsu
announce an innovative joint venture that is expected to allow both
companies to reduce costs and development time. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
