   FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ The Federal Election Commission to
decide today whether to require the Clinton and Dole campaigns to
repay millions of dollars in federal matching funds for violating
campaign spending rules. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS (Washington) _ The vote count is under way in the
Teamster election. James. P. Hoffa is favored over Tom Leedham;
when the results will be announced is not certain. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WATER (Providence, R.I.) _ President unveils first new
regulations under a 2-year-old drinking water law, requiring cities
and towns to spend $1 billion yearly to filter cryptosporidium (a
toxic microbe) and other contaminants from water, and to ensure
that harmful byproducts of chlorination are not present in drinking
water. By John H. Cushman. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-CDC (Undated) _ After declining for many years, the
number of abortions has gone up slightly, according to data from
the Centers for Disease Control from 1995-96. The reasons for the
increase are unclear, some say it could be a decrease in popularity
of Norplant or a return to work of those receiving welfare. By
Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-INJECTION-TRIAL (St. Charles, Mo.) _ A man accused of
injecting his 11-month-old son with blood tainted with the AIDS
virus told the boy's mother shortly before he allegedly
administered the shot that the child was damaged and no longer
worth keeping, the child's mother told a court. The boy, now seven,
was not diagnosed with AIDS until four years later. Now in the
final stages of full blown AIDS, he requires around-the-clock care.
By Jo Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SURF (Half Moon Bay, Calif.) _ Surfers tackle the biggest
waves that come once a year. Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHRISTMAS-WINDOWS (New York) _ Expensive, over-the-top,
department store windows at Christmas time are a ritual as integral
to the season in New York City as overpriced chestnuts sold at
street vendors and snarls of traffic near Rockefeller Center. But
what amounts to a moment's thrill for those who pass by the windows
is the result of months and months of tedious, highly-guarded
planning among retailers, who are looking for much more than
general gawking from the world: they see the windows as a
competitive tool for increasing media attention and store traffic.
By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
