<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECT (Jakarta) _ The Habibe government announces
election dates, drawing protests from students, who also say there
has been some backsliding on the inquiry into the wealth of the
former president, Suharto, and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL (Dateline tk) _ Developments in the latest uncertainty
over the Wye peace plan. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Oslo) _ Diplomats from 60 countries meet to beef
up the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which
is about to take on its toughest job ever: monitoring Kosovo, the
rebellious ethnic-Albanian province in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHTS-REPORT (Washington) _ The largest U.S.-based human rights
group, Human Rights Watch, says the Clinton administration has
``large blind spots'' on human rights and is ``severely out of step
with most of the rest of the world'' on major issues. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast) _ Modest compromises are reported in
the stalled peace effort after intervention by the British and
Irish prime ministers. By James F. Clarity.
