<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS04-COX     12-03 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP LEADERS CAN'T AVOID THE I-WORD
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders of the House and Senate tried to
outline an agenda Thursday of cutting taxes, fixing schools and
saving Social Security, but could not avoid the I-word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a question other than on impeachment that we could
maybe (answer)?'' Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi
wondered as reporters asked repeatedly about developments in the
congressional investigation of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' replied a voice from the journalistic horde crowded into
Lott's Senate office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuts!'' laughed House Speaker-elect Robert Livingston of
Louisiana, who signaled he would like to see the issue settled
before he officially replaces Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia when
the new Congress convenes Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said it was premature to speculate on whether the GOP
leadership would allow a vote on censuring Clinton, an alternative
to impeachment that is supported by most Democrats and some
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining that he'd already been asked about censure ``about
40 times today,'' Livingston said, ``the fact is that I don't have
any idea what we're going to do until the Judiciary Committee
reports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I'd be perfectly happy'' if the battle drags into
the new Congress, Livingston admitted, but that's the likely timing
if the committee doesn't meet its schedule of voting by the end of
next week on an impeachment resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Lott sidestepped questions about a Senate trial of
Clinton should the House vote to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not making any plans or any preparation at this time,''
Lott said. While there is no constitutional mandate that the Senate
hold a trial, the leader said, ``it would be very hard not to'' if
the House voted for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in armchairs in front of a fireplace and a mantel
decorated for Christmas, the Republican leaders sought to steer the
subject to their long friendship and how it would help them achieve
``our common agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax cuts will be a top legislative priority, promised
Livingston, as will ``making sure our youngsters have good schools
to attend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And of course we did talk about the importance of preserving
Social Security so it will be there, not only for my 85-year-old
mother, bless her heart, in Pascagoula, Mississippi, but so it'll
be there for my grandson now, that's six months old,'' said Lott.
</P>
<P>
   But the questions kept coming back to possible votes on
impeachment _ which the leaders agreed would be the most
``weighty'' that members of Congress would cast during their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each member of Congress has the responsibility to search his
heart and his conscience and judge for himself the importance to
his constituents what his vote should be,'' said Livingston. ``And
I think for us to arbitrarily prejudge the conditions under which
he casts that vote is unfair at this point, because we really don't
know what the recommendations of the Judiciary Committee are going
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
