<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1310 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATAMERICAN-ELECTIONS     12-03 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATAMERICAN-ELECTIONS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LATIN AMERICA'S ELECTIONS, RUMBLINGS AGAINST THE STATUS QUO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.) 
 &HT;    
 By JORGE G. CASTANEDA  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Sunday's opposition primary elections in Argentina, and
this coming Sunday's presidential vote in Venezuela capture both
the potential victories awaiting, and the dilemmas befalling, Latin
America's left-of-center, anti-status quo, politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Between next week and the middle of the year 2000, countries as
varied as Venezuela, El Salvador, Argentina, Chile and Mexico will
hold presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the free-market tide submerged the
region in the mid- and late 1980s, candidates, coalitions and
parties from the left, or who question or openly criticize the
status quo, stand an excellent chance of winning according to polls
in all of these countries.
</P>
<P>
   While previous occasions did surface _ in Brazil in 1989, in
Mexico in 1994 _ the upcoming contests suggest that
anti-establishment candidates such as former military coup author
Hugo Chavez in Venezuela, the ex-FMLN guerrilla commander Facundo
Guardado in El Salvador, Socialist Party leader Ricardo Lagos in
Chile, Buenos Aires mayor and head of the anti-Menem alliance
Fernando de la Rua in Argentina and Cuauhtimoc Cardenas _ on the
progresisve left _ and Vicente Fox _ on the anti-authoritarian
right of center _ in Mexico all could be the presidents of their
respective countries two years from now.
</P>
<P>
   As they get closer to power, though, they are all being beckoned
by a traditional political temptation, which in their case could
prove either decisive for victory, or fatal. Because of the
benefits that fiscal stability have brought to Latin electorates
over the past few years, and thanks to the market-oriented programs
implemented by sitting governments, these candidates all have tried
to minimize their differences with incumbents on economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   The two contenders for the Alianza Opositora nomination in
Argentina _ De la Rua and defeated human-rights activist Graciela
Fernandez de Meijides _ both committed themselves to conserving
Menem's currency board and convertibilty-based monetary policy, as
well as privatizations and other reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas and Fox have also, in fact, resigned themselves to
leaving the Salinas and Zedillo economic reforms in place. Even
Guardado in El Salvador has stopped distancing himself from
right-wing Arena's fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, opposition candidates, or further left-of center
coalition leaders such as Lagos in Chile, are defining themselves
in non-economic policy terms: on cultural issues, anti-corruption
grounds, social matters and law enforcement and security themes.
</P>
<P>
   This seems wise apparently, since it assuages fears of
instability and radical change among highly conservative
electorates and elites. Only Chavez in Venezuela, and more
rhetorically than in substance, has emphasized his
anti-establishment credentials.
</P>
<P>
   There is a danger lurking here, however, and the Argentine
primaries underline it. Graciela Fernandez lost by a nearly
two-to-one margin. A possible explanation for her defeat, as well
as for the setbacks encountered by PAN and PRD opposition
candidates in governor's races in Mexico over the past year, may
lie in the consequences of being too insipid, too tame, too
``responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition and anti-status-quo candidates have to mobilize their
troops. Repeatedly claiming that the election makes scant
difference, since on many defining matters they'll perform like
incumbents, hardly qualifies as a highly mobilizing statement.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, Fernandez claimed that the main
difference between her and her opponent, and between the Alianza
and Menem and his successors, was that she possessed honesty and
integrity. The PRD and the PAN, in deed if not in word, are
essentially making the same claim in Mexico, since they either have
no economic, social or international program or it is
indistinguishable from the government's.
</P>
<P>
   The voters' response seems to be: In that case, we may prefer
proven and relatively competent crooks to honest, incomptetent
neophytes. In the Argentine case, if that is the platform De la Rua
runs on, he risks being overtaken on the left by the Peronist
candidate, Eduardo Duhalde, who can mobilize his troops simply on
the basis of historical loyalty and populist demagogy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is a slippery slope phenomenon at work. These
candidates start out excluding macro-economic policy from the field
of differences separating them from rivals. They can end up
including a great many more issues in the ``untouchable'' category.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, for example, while contenders such as Fox and
Cardenas have inevitably toned down their long-term economic policy
differences with the government _ limiting their split to
short-term matters such as the bank bailout or the 1999 budget _
they had emphasized their disagreement on matters such as
corruption. They would ensure greater accountability and
transparency, past, present and future.
</P>
<P>
   And unquestionably, the Cardenas and Fox administrations in
Mexico City and Guanajuato are far more honest than their
predecessors. But both leaders have been frustratingly tepid in
their investigations and prosecution of past corruption _ as if to
imply, why rock the boat before they reach the presidency? So the
country's past also becomes taboo as an electoral issue, other than
in purely rhetorical terms.
</P>
<P>
   The same has happened with Lagos in Chile regarding the Pinochet
affair. The Frei government, of which Lagos was a member until
recently and which is supported by the same coalition whose ticket
he will presumably run on in 1999, has found itself in a terribly
uncomfortable position after the ex-dictator's arrest in London.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, rank-and-file Socialists and Christian
Democrats cannot but applaud the arrest and possible extradition to
Spain. On the other, this attitude infuriates the right, the
military and part of the business community, jeopardizing Lagos'
chances of attaining power next year.
</P>
<P>
   Too sensitive to past experience, and too savvy to believe
naively in the strength of Chile's reborn democracy, Lagos waffles,
but would prefer to remove the Pinochet issue from the 1999
electroal agenda. He may be right, but how many issues would soon
be left on the agenda?
</P>
<P>
   The elections in Venezuela may provide a clue to how voters view
this phenomenon. Coronel Chavez has run on a stridently
anti-establishment platform. He may prove his colleagues in other
countries right, by losing the election because of his lack of
caution, or by returning to the moderate, cautious fold right after
his inauguration if he wins.
</P>
<P>
   Or conversely, he may demostrate that prudence is not the better
part of electoral valor, and show that other contenders may want to
pay more than lip service to the rumblings against the status quo
in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jorge G. Castaneda, Latin America's leading political
scientist, is the author of the best-selling ``Companero: The Life
and Death of Che Guevara.'' Castaneda lives in New York and Mexico
City and teaches at New York University.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1446EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
