<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-REED-1204-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARENT OF LEXIS NEXIS EXPECTS LOWER 1998 PROFITS
 &HT;    Moving in both the International and Financial categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Profits for the parent company of Lexis Nexis will fall
short of 1998 projections because of lower demand for its
publishing products and a weakening worldwide economy, the company
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Elsevier PLC also attributed the shortfall to investments
it is making in its on-line information products, such as the
Dayton, Ohio-based Lexis Nexis. The division has experienced
slower-than-expected revenue growth because of increased
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that it's a very competitive sphere,'' said
Susanna Smart, a spokeswoman in Reed Elsevier's headquarters here.
``However, Lexis Nexis continues to develop and launch new
information products.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the investments in its online information business was the
purchase of Matthew Bender, a legal information service which is
being integrated into Lexis Nexis, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Anglo-Dutch company, which also publishes scientific,
business and legal magazines, said it expected pre-tax profits to
be US$1.27 billion, 6 percent below earlier expectations. Another
factor contributing to the decline is the strength of the British
pound, which erodes revenues because of the cost of converting the
currency, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The weakening global economy, particularly in Asia, is largely
to blame for the reduced demand for its travel-related publishing
products, Smart said. ``People are cutting back on their business
travel and that affects the demand for business publications,'' she
said. ``A new management team is in place, and we're refocusing the
products, but we don't expect a rapid rebound in the travel
publications business.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnings had also been diluted by a number of sales made during
the year, most notably the sales of IPC Magazines last January,
which publishes consumer magazines including TV Times, Loaded and
Marie Claire.
</P>
<P>
   The company also was hit in its trade show management business,
in part because many of the exhibitions take place on two-year
cycles and 1998 was an off-cycle year, Smart said. Reed Elsevier
manages 335 trade shows and other events in 25 countries --
including the Showbiz Expo, the National Hardware Show and National
Manufacturing Week in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company, a partnership of the London-based Reed
International PLC and Amsterdam-based Elsevier NV, has not
concluded its search for a single chairman and a sole chief
executive officer for Reed Elsevier. The company announced in
August that it was going to abandon its co-chairman structure but
said that neither Herman Bruggink or Nigel Stapleton -- the
company's co-chairmen -- were in line for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The search is well in hand,'' Smart said. ``We will make an
announcement when we have an announcement to make.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
