<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRA-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Sophocles' ``Electra,'' at
the Barrymore Theater. Reviewed by Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   POWELL-NOVELS (New York) _ Time for holiday shopping. Why not
first stop at a bookstore and give yourself a treat? This is a good
season to catch up on reading. It's also good for rambling around
the neighborhood of a writer many readers are only now beginning to
catch up with: the brilliant social satirist Dawn Powell. Her
glittering novels, especially those set in New York, offer a rare
opportunity to reflect on the dependence of cities and books for
mutual survival. Take home a stack. You'll thank me. By Herbert
Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   POOLROOMS (New York) _ The premise was simple enough. Now that I
am closer to my second childhood than to the first one, would I be
able to find any spaces as dark, dank and nurturing as the
poolrooms of my adolescence? It was in these vaguely disreputable
parlors, up stairways or below street level, that at the age of 15
I found refuge from the purposefulness of school, from dreams of
glory and fears of failure, and though I probably didn't realize
it, from the looming rituals of sex and courtship. Once you walked
into these places, you were immediately comforted by the notion
that your parents would not be happy if they knew you were there.
By Michael T. Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   FORSYTHE-DANCE (New York) _ William Forsythe, the American
choreographer who has been artistic director of the Frankfurt
Ballet in Germany since 1984, is a prodigious talent but no
prodigal son. He refuses to come home. But he does drop in
occasionally to create new work and restage old ones for major
American ballet companies. More rarely, he visits with his own
troupe, now officially billed as Ballett Frankfurt on its tours,
and shows off a more anarchic side of his highly organized
choreography. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
