<HEADER>
A1367 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-HNS &LR;      12-03 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA CHARTER SCHOOLS GET A CRITICAL GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Charter schools, touted as a way to improve
public education in California, are less accountable than other
public schools and offer no evidence that students are faring
better academically, according to a sweeping two-year study
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, ``Beyond the Rhetoric of Charter School Reform,'' has
broad implications for California, which enrolls more students in
charter schools than any state.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is an important laboratory to test the effects of
charter schools,'' said Amy Stuart Wells, the University of
California at Los Angeles education professor who led the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned that despite the hard work and dedication of
charter school operators, charter school reform, for the most part,
falls short of the broad and comprehensive claims made by many of
its proponents,'' Wells said. ``It's time to look at where this
reform is going. Is it headed toward vouchers? Toward revitalizing
public schools or privatizing them? Policymakers need to think
about what this means for the bigger system.''
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools are publicly funded but free from many state and
local regulations. Proponents say such schools offer parents more
choice, stricter student accountability and the freedom to
innovate. These innovations may then be picked up by educators in
traditional public schools, proponents say.
</P>
<P>
   The report, however, disputes the these contentions.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA researchers looked at 17 charter schools in 10
districts across the state. Researchers conducted more than 450
interviews with parents, teachers and educators.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes at a time when charter schools are heartily
endorsed by Democrats and Republicans. With 1,100 charter schools
in operation nationwide, President Clinton has called for 3,000
such schools by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   California has nearly 50,000 children in 130 charter schools.
The original charter law, adopted in early 1993, limited the number
of charter schools statewide to 100. The law was amended in May and
raised the cap to 250 charter schools for the 1998-99 school year
and 100 more per year after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond the Rhetoric of Charter School Reform'' had 15 major
findings. The highlights are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Charter schools in California are more likely to be held
accountable for how money is spent rather than how well students
are doing academically, partly because a defining purpose of
charter schools is non-academic in nature, making it hard to use
traditional testing.
</P>
<P>
   _ There is no clear understanding of who is supposed to hold
charter schools accountable, parents, district officials or elected
school board members.
</P>
<P>
   _ There are no mechanisms in place for charter schools and
regular public schools to learn from one another.
</P>
<P>
   _ While teachers at charter schools value the added freedom,
smaller classes and closer relationships with students and parents,
work loads are heavier than at other public schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charter schools have a far greater ability to shape who
enrolls than most public schools. The requirement that charter
schools reflect the ethnic makeup of the district has not been
enforced, with whites overrepresented and Hispanics
underrepresented.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charter schools are not evenly funded and receive less money
than other public schools. The level of funding depends largely on
the political savvy of the charter school directors, who lobby the
district and outside benefactors for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to survive, charter schools have to raise private
resources,'' Wells said, noting that charter schools are not
eligible for many state categorical programs, like money to
maintain buildings and other non-academic costs. ``That pushes the
system toward privatization. It's a bigger trend in public
education that's accelerated in this context.''
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA researchers did not study for-profit charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA report serves as a reality check for those who follow
attempts to overhaul education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advocates of charter schools have set themselves up for
criticism because they over-attribute problems to the public school
system and underestimate the difficulty of setting up good new
schools,'' said Stanford University education professor David
Tyack, who has written extensively on the topic. ``Creating a good
new school is very hard work, like creating a small business.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tyack believes the charter school concept is promising.
``To ask people to think about what kind of school they want and
then hand them a charter and say go do it ... well, that's good.
People who are dissatisfied with what's out there might be able to
make a charter school really pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Noguera, an education professor at the University of
California at Berkeley and an adviser to the UCLA researchers,
hopes charter schools will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this sense that small is beautiful and by breaking off
from the district, and all the politics, you can focus on the
education,'' Noguera said. ``What happens, though, is politics
emerge on a smaller scale in these charter schools.''
</P>
<P>
   To make charter schools function better, the authors of the
report make a number of suggestions, including: Establishing a
variety of tests to measure achievement of specific goals; lobbying
districts or states to facilitate interaction between charter and
public schools; making sure charter schools have less _ not more _
authority over who is enrolled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
