<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1394 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVESTOCK-WASTE-TX12-     12-03 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVESTOCK-WASTE-TX12-04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPORT SAYS STATES NOT CURBING ANIMAL WASTE POLLUTION
 &HT;    555 words
 &HT;    Robbin(cq)
 &HT;    TEXAS EDITORS: Note Texas angle
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- At least 30 states -- including Texas -- are
failing to curb pollution from large livestock and poultry
operations, a new report says.
</P>
<P>
   The waste from these ``animal factories'' fouls drinking water
and threatens public health, according to the Natural Resources
Defense Council, an environmental group who released the report
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most states have few regulations and do little to enforce what
laws might be on the books,'' said Robbin Marks, one of the authors
of the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result is unchecked pollution leading to contaminated well
water, fish kills, sickness from toxic gases in the air and
plummeting property values for neighboring landowners,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Livestock industry representatives say the report lacks
scientific evidence and is packed with old information.
</P>
<P>
   ``'If this (the report) was food, it would have salmonella,''
said Steve Cohen, spokesman for the National Pork Producers
Council.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Cohen said many states have regulations that are
more strict than the national standards. He also said pork
producers are not against regulation. For example, the industry
supports recent efforts by the Environmental Protection Agency and
the U.S. Department of Agriculture to regulate large farms, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, however, say much more needs to be done.
The report details specific environmental problems in 30 states.
</P>
<P>
   One of those states, Texas, suffers significant river pollution
from dairy factory farm operations, the report says. Waste from
dairies in Erath County in Central Texas has significantly degraded
the Bosque River and the creeks of the Upper Bosque, the report
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Bosque River is the major tributary to Lake Waco, the source
of the city of Waco's drinking water. Waco has regularly found a
parasite from animal waste in samples from the lake, the report
says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the report states that expanding swine and cattle
operations are potential threats in Texas. In particular, the
report is critical of the state's design standards for large
feeding operations that allow clay liners for the lagoons where
millions of gallons of animal waste are stored. The liners can
crack after long droughts, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, groundwater contamination near animal
factories is increasing, posing a potentially serious drinking
water problem for nearby residents, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the report states that 88 percent of North Carolina
hog farms had at least one water-quality violation, but the state
has been unwilling to take enforcement action against the majority
of them.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of dissatisfaction with the state permitting system,
North Carolina implemented a two-year moratorium on new and
expanding hog farms, but hog production continues to grow because
of loopholes in the law, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about the environmental impact of the nation's 1.4
billion tons of animal waste has escalated as livestock and poultry
farms have become larger and more concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to address the problem, the EPA and the Agriculture
Department released a draft strategy earlier this year to further
regulate the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy would require an estimated 15,000 to 20,000 of the
largest livestock operations to have plans that detail how the
owner will collect and store manure and how the waste might be
applied to fields as fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
   Owners would have to keep detailed records and test their soil
regularly to ensure no excess buildup of nutrients that could
potentially pollute nearby waterways.
</P>
<P>
   Under current federal laws, large livestock farms are prohibited
from discharging waste directly into rivers and streams, but the
rules do not prevent waste from being washed off farmland by rain.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy also includes encouraging tens of thousands of
smaller farms and animal feeding operations to voluntarily adopt
similar plans. The goal is to have all feeding operations on board
by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA and the Department of Agriculture are conducting public
hearings nationwide to get feedback before finalizing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
