<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1402 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MITCH-AFTERMATH-HNS &LR;      12-03 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCH-AFTERMATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    HONDURANS START LONG CLIMB BACK TO LIVES THEY ONCE HAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO SULA, Honduras _ After weeks of digging, Jose Luis
Duron and his wife finally can see the floor of the two-room house
that was once their proudest possession.
</P>
<P>
   Duron has been shoveling mud from the sitting room, hurling it
over the roofless house's front wall into the shaded yard. His
wife, Josefa, has been scraping away in the small bedroom, using a
jagged piece of plastic torn from a bucket to scoop the mud into
balls and toss them out of the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had just finished remodeling their home in late
October. A few days later, floodwaters driven by Hurricane Mitch
carried away the house's new tin roof and deposited about 7 feet of
sewage-laced mud inside the structure.
</P>
<P>
   Duron, 53, and his wife have cleared the mud from about half of
the house's concrete floor, but up to 3 feet of dirt covers the
rest. Weeks of more work lie ahead. ``We have no choice. We have
nowhere else to live,'' he says with a sad smile as he takes a
break from the labor. ``We have to make this place right again.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a month after Mitch tripped ashore on the northern
coast of Honduras and kicked its way across Central America, the
poor have started the long climb back to the lives they once led.
Government officials say the storm killed at least 9,000 people in
the region, most of them in Honduras, and that hundreds of
thousands remain homeless.
</P>
<P>
   For the many who lost loved ones, homes and jobs to the storm,
rebuilding will be defined by economic circumstances and political
systems that have been less than benevolent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to rebuild what you had,'' says Efrain Diaz, a
Honduran agricultural economist who works on development issues for
the United Nations. ``The question is, how to go about it. There
are still a lot of uncertainties.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere, perhaps, are things more uncertain than in the gutted
riverside neighborhoods of Chamelecon, a sprawling working-class
section of the industrial city of San Pedro Sula on Honduras'
northern coast. Scores of houses were swept away when a levee on
the nearby Chamelecon River collapsed, and hundreds of other homes
were flooded to the rafters
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Central America, Mitch killed far more people and
wreaked more lasting damage. But in Chamelecon, the struggle back
undoubtedly will prove as tough as anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   International aid is pouring into the region. But people in
Chamelecon share the belief of many of Central America's poor that
the help will somehow remain in the hands of the rich or powerful,
siphoned away through corruption or passed out in return for
political support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to sound resentful about the help,'' says Mauro
Pineda, 58, whose house was chest-deep in muddy water. ``But it
never reaches to the poor. If the government asks for something, it
is for the rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Weeks after the Chamelecon River returned to its banks, the
area's streets remain clogged with mounds of fetid mud and pools of
filthy water.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people made homeless by the flooding still sleep in
makeshift shelters in schools and gymnasiums. Others crowd into
relatives' houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all living on top of each other,'' says Catalina Reyes,
whose family of six occupies a 5-foot-by-5-foot piece of classroom
marked off by desks, old boxes and hanging clothes. ``There is no
privacy, everyone is sick, and we don't know what the future
holds.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people return each day to the riverbank to scrounge for
remnants of their lives. &UR;  &LR; They dig in the earth like archaeologists
to recover buried mattresses and other possessions. They wash
clothes and bathe at the still-functioning water spigots where
their kitchens formerly stood. They cook over open fires and sit
talking under trees that once shaded their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Young men swim in the muddy Chamelecon River, apparently
unconcerned about reports of disease being carried in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no help, no nothing,'' says Raquel Sarmiento, a
28-year-old mother of four whose flooded home was spared the total
destruction suffered by houses one street closer to the river.
``Each family has to make their own effort to get out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamelecon was built piecemeal over the past 30 years, expanding
with the arrival of each wave of newcomers from other parts of
Honduras, people who hoped to find steady work in the factories of
San Pedro Sula. But the jobs were too few and too lowly paid to
lift most from poverty. Today, Chamelecon's neighborhoods are rife
with crime and youth gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Situated where the Chamelecon River enters San Pedro and at the
foot of a low mountain range, the area has a long experience with
floods.
</P>
<P>
   After the city government built a levee along the Chamelecon
River, the floods became less severe and less frequent _ until
Mitch arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's heavy rains, which at their height poured down at
the rate of 4 inches an hour, began to inundate the neighborhoods
along the levee on Oct. 26, residents say.
</P>
<P>
   Families started evacuating their homes when the waters reached
thigh-deep, so few people were in their houses when the levee gave
way the night of Oct. 30. Mitch killed only two people in
Chamelecon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened here was bitter, but those who were prudent got
their things out,'' says Humberto Lara, 46, who managed to rescue
some of his family's belongings from their flooded home before the
levee collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost a lot of things, but that is secondary,'' Lara
says. ``We have our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   With storm-scuttled classes set to resume in January, those
taking refuge in schoolhouses here and around Honduras will have to
new places to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   San Pedro Sula officials hope to move the homeless into five
``megashelters'' that will hold as many as 5,000 people each.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the officials plan to use loans from international
lenders to relocate families from the hardest hit neighborhoods to
what they call a flood-proof area on the outskirts of the city. The
development's tiny houses, which will be hooked to city water,
sewage and electricity, will cost about $2,000 each, says Roberto
Larios, an industrialist who serves as San Pedro Sula's mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's practically a gift,'' the mayor says of the planned
homes, which residents will pay for over 20 years. ``And it's on
land where there is not the slightest risk of flooding.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Chamelecon, where unemployment runs high and a good job
doing piece work in garment factories pays about $35 a week, many
worry they will never be able to afford the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are rich, so it seems like a great deal to them,''
Salvador Plateros, 39, an unemployed father of five, says of the
city's relocation scheme. ``But if somebody doesn't have the money
to buy a lot, what are they supposed to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Most people worry about the long-term economic effects of the
storm. Although many in Chamelecon work in the foreign-owned
clothing factories that have sprung up throughout San Pedro Sula,
the competition for those jobs is expected to become fierce in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Chiquita Brands International plans to lay off many of the 7,300
workers it employs on storm-ravaged banana plantations and packing
sheds in the countryside surrounding San Pedro Sula.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here already have relatives working in Houston, Los
Angeles and other U.S. cities. Slipping illegally through Mexico
and into the United States remains a powerful attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without money you are nothing, and we have no money,'' says
17-year-old Humberto Lara Mejia, who was caught trying to slip
across Mexico's southern border earlier this year. ``Many people
are saying they are going to migrate now.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
