A1426 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-YOUNG-NORTON-HNS &LR;      12-03 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-YOUNG-NORTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG'S INJURY HOVERS OVER THE 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE ADAMS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Ken Norton Jr., in the wake of the
gruesome injury to San Francisco 49ers teammate Bryant Young, is
beginning to sound like a man who is losing his taste for the
violent world of professional football.
</P>
<P>
   It was an accidental blow from Norton's helmet in a frenzied
fourth-quarter collision that broke the two bones in Young's lower
right leg. Young is out for the year and recovering from surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Norton, a linebacker known for his hustle and his hitting, was
somber and subdued Wednesday as he talked about Young's injury in
the 49ers' 31-7 win over the New York Giants on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we all know is possible,'' Norton said. ``When
it happens to someone you know, someone you're real close to,
somebody you've been in a lot of battles with and you really care
about, it makes you wonder if it's all really worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, say coaches, saying Norton will be emotionally
ready when the 49ers play the Carolina Panthers on Sunday in
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to allow him some mourning time,'' defensive
coordinator John Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Steve Mariucci said Norton would be fine with a
little time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny came to work today, and he had a good day,'' Mariucci
said. ``Nobody said it was going to be easy for Kenny. He's got to
know it's not his fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall referred to Norton's father, Ken Sr., a former
heavyweight boxing champion, in expressing his confidence that
Norton would bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made out of big-time stuff,'' Marshall said. ``Kenny's
got that same grit.''
</P>
<P>
   In earlier interviews Norton has said he wasn't sure if he had
caused the injury. By Wednesday he knew without a doubt that he
struck Young's leg when he came crashing in at the end of a play as
Young tackled Giants quarterback Kent Graham. ``I was in on the
play,'' Norton said. ``I'm the guy who hit him, obviously, and it's
hard to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he believed he would be ready to play on Sunday, Norton
said, ``It's hard to really focus right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, one of the best defensive tackles in the NFL, is out for
the season. He had surgery on Monday, in which a titanium rod was
inserted in his right tibia. Both the tibia and fibula were cleanly
broken, about halfway between the knee and ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci said Young had further minor surgery Tuesday night to
reduce swelling.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci said the team's orthopedic surgeon was confident that
Young could play next year.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci said Young was doing fine, but would be kept in the
hospital a few more days _ possibly until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bored silly right now,'' Mariucci said. ``He's not the
kind of guy who can sit around and watch `Oprah' and `Jerry
Springer.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Norton also had talked to Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to be doing OK,'' Norton said. ``His spirits are
decent.''
</P>
<P>
   The same cannot be said of Norton.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I'm not doing too well,'' he said.
``I'm feeling lousy.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton said that no one blamed him for the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I'm really putting on myself,'' he said.
``We're taught to hit people, we're taught to jump on people. This
was just a freak situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's injury has been hard for many players to deal with
because of its severity. Feelings have also run strong because
Young is highly respected and well-liked by his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can feel bad and we can grieve for B.Y.,'' Mariucci said.
``We can go through all those emotions. But when it comes time to
play football, that's our job.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the team faced the task of replacing Young. Marshall
said the two leading contenders were Gabe Wilkins and Shane Bonham.
Marshall hedged on naming a starter for Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know exactly who the ball-buster is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins, who signed as a $20 million free agent from the Green
Bay Packers in the offseason, has seen limited action at defensive
end in the past four games. He injured a knee in last year's Super
Bowl, had surgery and missed the first eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Bonham came to the 49ers from the Detroit Lions, where he
started two games in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mariucci and Marshall said Wilkins, Bonham and Junior
Bryant, who has been starting next to Young all year, would
alternate at the two tackle spots. Also in the mix is Brenston
Buckner, who has missed the last two games with a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear the coaches are looking to Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this as an opportunity for him to show us what he's
got,'' Mariucci said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
