<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
. 
The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
PSYCHO-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ By some logic, Gus Van Sant's almost
shot-for-shot remake of Alfred Hitchcock's ``Psycho'' should be
welcomed by fans and cineastes everywhere. It's both a radical
formal notion and as faithful a tribute to a master filmmaker as
could be imagined. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
EXHIBIT-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Paul Schrader penned the words ``You
talking to me?'' uttered by a really frightening Robert DeNiro in
1976's ``Taxi Driver.'' Schrader's been talking to us ever since
and LACMA is putting up a two-weekend exhitibition of this auteur's
personal style of filmmaking. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
VOICE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Actress Jane Horrocks, who can belt
with the best of them, is the best reason to see ``Little Voice,''
a wildly uneven movie about a sheltered, fragile young woman who
won't speak but can sing up a storm. 2{ stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
GUTHRIE-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Billy Bragg and Woody Guthrie are
linked by musical tradition and a belief in the power of one voice.
On the acclaimed ``Mermaid Avenue'' (Elektra), Bragg teamed up with
rootsy Chicago rockers Wilco in Dublin for a collection that puts
new music to never-before-released lyrics by Guthrie. By Fred
Shuster. 
. 
SHARPS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ The consolidation of Seagram-owned
PolyGram and the Universal Music Group (UMG) could eliminate as
many as 3,000 jobs, and has employees at Geffen, A&AMP;M, Mercury and
other imprints preparing for the worst. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ If you're a Pearl Jam fan, you'll just
have to own ``Live on Two Legs,''career-spanning package that
ignores ``Jeremy'' but adds nods to old tour partner Neil Young _ a
verse of ``Rockin' in the Free World'' inside ``Daughter'' and a
cover of a Young tune that boasts an unprintable title. 3 Stars. By
Fred Shuster. 
. 
ZORRO-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ ``The Mask of Zorro'' was the best pure
popcorn movie of the summer. Call it retro fun, which is no
surprise because Steven Spielberg, who loves adventure films, had a
hand in making it. By Rob Lowman. 
. 

