<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMIZING HOLIDAY TRAVEL WOES  
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business travelers can be especially un-jolly this time of year.
Airports and planes are full of people who don't travel very often.
While these are perfectly nice people, they don't know the tricks
of travel. Many of them don't use the technological toys --
laptops, cell phones, pagers -- that business travelers take for
granted. To help lessen the travel trauma, here are ways to cut
down on the hassles of holiday travel.
</P>
<P>
   Book early for bargain fares. If you don't book early, you are
not going to be able to find either an inexpensive flight or a
flight that's convenient. If you have to book a flight on short
notice during this season, be prepared to pay full fare. Flights
are usually overbooked, and someone is going to get bumped. The
full-fare passengers are more likely to be the bumper rather than
the bumpee. If you have to pay full fare, consider using your
frequent flyer miles to upgrade to first or business class.
BizTravel has a service called BizMiles that keeps track of your
points on both the airlines and hotel plans.
</P>
<P>
   Use the Web to check on your flight before leaving home. Most of
the airlines post flight information on their Web sites. Even with
a confirmation that the flight is leaving on time, you still need
to get to the airport early. The admonition to arrive two hours
before the flight is not to be taken lightly during heavy travel
periods. The earlier you check in, the less likely you are to get
bumped from a flight. Also, holiday travelers have lots of luggage.
Both curbside check-in and the ticket counter will have long lines,
so it will take twice as long to check in.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be an unwritten law of travel that all connecting
flights must be at the farthest point from your arriving gate. It
won't cut down on the run, but getting an idea of the layout of the
airport can at least let you plan your mad dash more efficiently.
QuickAid has links to the layouts and services of all the major
airports.
</P>
<P>
   The usual advice is to travel light and never check your bags.
It slows down your exit from the airport if you have to wait for
your luggage. But during holiday travel, do the opposite. Take only
the essentials (delicate electronics, any medication, and
toiletries) on the plane. Infrequent fliers don't seem to know what
can and cannot fit under the seat and in the overhead compartment.
You'll spend a lot of time waiting for too many of them to accept
that the bag they brought on board is too big and needs to be
checked.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure batteries on all electronic gadgets are charged in
case you need to demonstrate to security personnel that they are
what they appear to be. Each airport seems to have its own rules.
Major American airports that are international hubs, like Los
Angeles and New York's Kennedy, tend to be stricter about checking
electronic equipment. For the rest, it is an even bet that you will
be asked to turn on your laptop after going through the security
check. The last time it happened to me, in Indianapolis, I had a
dead battery and had to go into a nearby office to plug it in. I
nearly missed my flight.
</P>
<P>
   Once through security, turn off all the gadgets, especially
pagers, that emit either infrared or radio waves before boarding
the plane. The jury is still out on what effect these devices have
on sensitive equipment aboard the plane, but why take a chance?
</P>
<P>
   Take public transportation into the city. It's not just airport
traffic that piles up during the holiday season, Most of the
highways to the airport are also the fastest way to major malls.
Avoid the stress of sitting behind the wheel of your rental car
stuck in a traffic jam. If you must drive, check road conditions at
RWA Direct's road conditions Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Get to the hotel very early or very late. Checkout in most
hotels is noon, but most will tell you that check-in is after 3
p.m. If you arrive early, before 8 a.m., you're likely to get a
room that wasn't occupied the night before. Also, the check-in
lines will be non-existent -- everybody's checking out. Arriving
late, after 5 p.m., gets you a nice clean room and no check-in
line. You can find out the hotel's check-in and check-out policy on
its Web site. Many hotels are now starting to accept e-mail at the
front desk. If yours doesn't, it will surely have a fax machine,
and you can use your computer to fax them your arrival time. I once
did this from a plane that circled Boston for three hours, using
the AirFone.
</P>
<P>
   If you are planning to take a client out to dinner, make a
reservation before you leave home, since restaurants can be busy
this time of year. You can use the Internet to find a good
restaurant. Check any of the city guide sites or Internet phone
books like Switchboard.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to confirm your returning flight. A couple of hours
before you leave for the airport, check to make sure your flight is
on time and has not been canceled. You might try one of the pager
notification services like the one offered by Travelocity.
</P>
<P>
   Be patient with your fellow travelers. It's only a couple of
days a year that you have to deal with the overload. Relax. This
too shall pass and you can go back to dealing with the problem of
talkative seatmates.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
