<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTTOM-CYBERTIMES-LAW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS ON THE BOTTOM TAKE AIM AT THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  By CARL S. KAPLAN 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the time of year when thoughts turn to ... salary
bonuses. That is, if you are a lawyer at one of the nation's top
law firms.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are a few Web sites where young, overworked lawyers --
known as associates -- can go to trade the latest news and rumors
about end-of-year bonuses and salary pay scales. There is also
plenty of gossip about law firm culture, hiring possibilities and
the grind of making it at a competitive firm.
</P>
<P>
   The creator of a bulletin board ``club'' on Yahoo called ''
Greedy Associates,'' whose screen name is ``nowhitenoise,'' wrote
in a ``Founder's Message'' that the club is ``designed to give the
whiny overprivileged lawyers at the nation's most prestigious law
firms a place to discuss such pressing matters as whether or not
this $20,000 bonus is really going to pan out.''
</P>
<P>
   The club has grown to 125 members since it was founded in
September. According to access statistics on the site, 37 members
logged on Wednesday morning, and 219 non-members visited. Messages
on the site can be viewed by anyone, but only members may post
comments. Membership is free.
</P>
<P>
   The unvarnished notes, written anonymously by people with screen
names like ``DebitBoyz,'' ``Body_Count_Rising,'' ``NYCglamourgirl''
and ``happylawyer,'' can be childish, supportive, informative or
scandalous. They give a glimpse of what is on the minds of young
lawyers who toil late into the night on a dry legal memo or the
sixth draft of a motion concerning a business dispute between
toothpaste companies.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, ``jmkm'' described himself in a message on the board
as a ``greedy associate-to-be,'' indicating that he is probably a
law student. He noted that while an $87,000 starting salary at the
top San Francisco law firms was ``a ridiculous amount of money,''
it still trailed behind the $95,000 starting salary in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next day, a ``Greedy Associates'' member replied to
the message with a combination of self-pride and self-pity: ``JMKM,
I take it you mean that $87,000 is a ridiculously high amount of
money. When you are expected to work ridiculously long hours, pay
ridiculously high rents and service ridiculously high debts, I can
assure you that $87,000 will seem ridiculously low.''
</P>
<P>
   A young lawyer out of law school can make around $100,000 at a
major New York City firm during his first year of employment,
</P>
<P>
   according to the New York Law Journal, a newspaper that tracks
salaries and bonuses at the top firms in New York and that first
reported on the Greedy Associates sites. The figure includes a
routine annual bonus of several thousand dollars. But this year,
some firms are offering additional ``boom year'' bonuses'' of
$10,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Another ``Greedy Associates'' discussion group, unaffiliated
with the Yahoo club, is located on a message board site called
``Inside the Web.'' It, too, hosts an exchange of gossip about
salaries and bonuses, along with other topics. Members include
``DeathbyLoans,'' ``MoMoney,'' SnobbyNewYorkloser'' and
``overworked_skadden_fool,'' a likely reference to the powerhouse
New York-based law firm Skadden Arps Slate Meagher &AMP; Flom.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, correspondents discussed whether a law student was
better off taking a job at Simpson Thacher &AMP; Bartlett or Skadden
Arps (both have their good points, the members said). Others
tackled the question of which town on Long Island was a commuter's
paradise. One member touted Long Beach, with its yuppie-friendly
bars and boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   Law students who are eyeing their first stint of real legal work
at firms during summer break now have their own place to gossip.
Earlier this month a new Yahoo club was formed, ``Greedy Summer
Associates.'' Founded by someone named ``Perks4US,'' the groupswaps
information on the size of summer associate offices at various
firms, the number of weekends off and the types of free sports
tickets offered by management.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Henning, a senior vice president and general counsel at
Hildebrandt, a law firm management consultant, said associates
already have ``a pretty good network'' of information about pay
scales thanks to articles in trade magazines, headhunter calls and
chats with colleagues. The ``greedy associates'' sites add to the
mix, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Henning questioned the validity of the information on the
sites, given the notorious inaccuracy of anonymous postings on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firms aren't going to be buffaloed by associate demands, even
though it is a seller's market for associate talent,'' he said.
``The best impact of these sites would be to stimulate the powers
that be at the firms to do a reliable survey,'' one that is not
based on Internet gossip, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the sites' latent function as a pressure-valve for law
firm drones, Henning said gossip has always gone on in coffee rooms
and bars every Friday night after work. ``The Net just makes it
more available,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http:)
</P>
<P>
   _ Yahoo ``Greedy Associates'':
//clubs.yahoo.com/clubs/greedyassociates?s
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Carl S. Kaplan, a New York-based lawyer and journalist, was a
business reporter for New York Newsday.)
</P>
