</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LITTLE VOICE' FALLS A LITTLE SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 { Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With her moptop haircut and prodigious nose,
actress Jane Horrocks bears more than a passing resemblance to a
``Hard Days Night'' era Ringo Starr _ except for the singing voice.
Horrocks doesn't need a little help from her friends. She can
imitate them. From a brassy Shirley Bassey to a quivering Judy
Garland, Horrocks can capture every legendary inflection, right
down to the smallest hand gesture and facial expression.
</P>
<P>
   Horrocks is the best reason to see ``Little Voice,'' a wildly
uneven movie about a sheltered, fragile young woman who won't speak
but can sing up a storm. The film was adapted from an English play,
``The Rise and Fall of Little Voice,'' and, my guess is, it worked
much better as a live stage show than it does as a movie. But
Horrocks' presence, along with a devilish supporting turn from
Michael Caine and a soundtrack full of marvelous standards, ensures
more than a few entertaining moments.
</P>
<P>
   Horrocks plays LV (or Little Voice), a young woman who lives in
the dark attic of her father's once thriving record shop. Dad is
dead now, and LV has never quite recovered from that. She plays
albums from his record collection night and day, developing an
uncanny ability to sing along with the likes of Bassey, Garland,
Marilyn Monroe and Marlene Dietrich.
</P>
<P>
   LV may never talk, but her obnoxious mother, Mari (Brenda
Blethyn), more than fills the sound void. Ever on the prowl, Mari
has her sights set on a low-life talent promoter with the wonderful
name of Ray Say (Caine). Obliging and convivial (at least on the
surface), Ray is convinced that he could have made it big if only
he had caught one lucky break. When he overhears LV singing ``Over
the Rainbow,'' Ray realizes he has found his meal ticket.
</P>
<P>
   One problem: LV doesn't want to perform in public. For her,
singing is a private therapy, a way to cope with her tortured
relationship with her spiteful mother. The ties between mother and
daughter should be ripe for exploration, but writer-director Mark
Herman's script doesn't delve into the subject until it's much too
late.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he didn't reign in Blethyn's over-the-top
performance _ she comes off as a cross between Eliza Doolittle and
any dunce from the royal family _ doesn't help matters much,
either. Neither does a rather pointless subplot involving Ewan
McGregor as LV's pigeon-loving suitor.
</P>
<P>
   Horrocks' nuanced performance almost makes up for all these
shortcomings, though. Having originated the character on stage, she
knows LV inside and out and delivers a rollicking revue once Little
Voice takes to the stage. Caine is equally enjoyable, particularly
in a quiet scene where he convinces LV to go public with her
talents. It's an indelible reminder of a talent too often hidden
through the years by poor choices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1546EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1496 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PSYCHO-MOVIE-LADN     12-03 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHO-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PSYCHO:' IN THE FOOTSTEPS OF THE MASTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ By some logic, Gus Van Sant's almost shot-for-shot
remake of Alfred Hitchcock's ``Psycho'' should be welcomed by fans
and cineastes everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   It's both a radical formal notion and as faithful a tribute to a
master filmmaker as could be imagined by a director whose highly
personal films have made him a critics' favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a sense of outrage surrounding the new ``Psycho.''
The very idea of remaking Hitchcock's 1960, black-and-white
masterpiece in color smacks of tasteless exploitation to some.
That's understandable, because of all Hitchcock's great films,
``Psycho'' is the best known and most influential.
</P>
<P>
   The original slasher thriller remains a watershed of pioneering
technique, and even though it's tame by subsequent standards, the
film broke oodles of Hollywood taboos regarding the presentation of
sex, violence and deviant psychology at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, it's an iconic piece of American pop culture that
stands apart from its numerous, non-Hitchcock-involved sequels and
knockoffs.
</P>
<P>
   All of which Van Sant is eminently aware of.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to improve the film in any way,'' the
famously low-key, easygoing filmmaker says. ``We're trying to
actually popularize a film that people don't watch. The people that
would be offended by this whole idea are probably not in our
audience; they know the original and are very happy watching the
original.''
</P>
<P>
   Those would be people like genre specialist John Carpenter, who
has repeatedly put homages to Hitchcock and other classic
filmmakers in his horror films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot figure that one out,'' Carpenter, whose movies
include the ``Psycho''-inspired ``Halloween'' and a remake of ``The
Thing,'' says, wincing, about the new ``Psycho.'' ``I don't get
that. Somebody's going to have to explain that to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Sant tries again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that we're making the film for are people that
would never go see the original because it's antiquated,'' says the
director, who had his first mass-market hit with the Oscar-winning
``Good Will Hunting'' within the past year. ``It's a very general
audience type of reason, but it's a very strong reason.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, it appears that Van Sant tried to make the best new
``Psycho'' that he could (we can only speculate, though, since he
also refused to screen the film for critics before today's
commercial release). Besides adding color and stereo sound, Van
Sant has incorporated elements from Joseph Stefano's original
``Psycho'' script that Hitchcock had to cut for the censors or _ as
in the case of an elaborate helicopter shot _ for which he did not
have the technology to film properly at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Stefano was also brought in as an accuracy consultant and to
update a few plot points. For example, Marion Crane, the famous
shower victim played by Janet Leigh in the original and Anne Heche
in the remake, now steals $400,000 from her boss instead of 1960's
less-of-a-motive-after-inflation $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also hired were the world-renowned Australian cinematographer
Christopher Doyle (``Chungking Express'') and such admired actors
as Julianne Moore (``Boogie Nights''), William H. Macy
(``Pleasantville'') and Viggo Mortensen (``A Perfect Murder,''
itself a remake of Hitchcock's ``Dial M for Murder'').
</P>
<P>
   But the most important hire, of course, was the actor who would
portray Norman Bates. Anthony Perkins' jittery performance as the
homicidal mama's boy is easily the best-known madman in movie
history. But instead of going for an actor with a proven ability to
project neurotic creepiness, Van Sant opted for Vince Vaughn, the
robust, 6-foot-5 party animal from ``Swingers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince has a mysterious quality, and he also has a very
friendly quality, which I thought was good for Norman,'' Van Sant
says. ``And, like Anne, he seemed very excited about doing it,
which was a very big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Well aware that his every move would be compared with an icon's,
Vaughn did his best to walk the thin line between respectfulness
and making the character his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just based my work on the material, which is where the first
performance came from,'' Vaughn says. ``I watched Hitchcock's film
before we started this one, and certain things I did do are exactly
like the original. But there are other times when I said `No, I'm
going off in this head space.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you just don't get a fair shot out of the gate with
it, and I understand why, because people liked the first one,''
Vaughn admits. ``I just think that people should be open to the
fact that music is constantly replayed, plays are restaged many
times over, and works are meant to be explored and reinterpreted.
It's 40 years later, and it's time for that to happen with
`Psycho.'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Van Sant first dreamed up the idea eight years ago _
and off the top of his head at that. On the strength of ``Drugstore
Cowboy,'' his first independent hit, the Oregon-based director was
making the obligatory rounds of meetings with semi-interested
Hollywood studio executives.
</P>
<P>
   The suits at Universal didn't care for the project he wanted to
make next _ a pseudo-Shakespearean tale of narcoleptic teen-age
hustlers that would become ``My Own Private Idaho'' _ so they asked
him if there was anything in the studio's vast archive he'd like to
remake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, the remake process is to find an obscure movie _
like `Death Takes a Holiday,' I suppose _ and change it into `Meet
Joe Black,''' Van Sant says. ``But my feeling was that the whole
reason to remake a film was because it did something that was good.
I didn't really see why remakes had this practice of changing the
language of the filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I said, `Instead of trying to hide it's a remake, why not
pick something great like ``Psycho''?' They weren't real excited by
the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   But after ``Good Will Hunting'' grossed upward of $130 million
and won two Oscars, Universal, well, agreed to do anything Van Sant
wanted. So he not only set about making as perfect an update of
``Psycho'' as possible but made it like Hitchcock did whenever
possible, sticking to an eight-week shooting schedule and keeping
the production cost _ an estimated $25 million _ in the same,
relatively low-budget ballpark as the $800,000 original.
</P>
<P>
   Expect some changes, though, like a few different cuts in the
sacred shower scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that I've done something that not only supports what
Janet Leigh did, because I love her performance in the original,
but also makes it interesting enough for the audience who's seen
that to appreciate what I've done differently,'' says Heche, who
proudly adds that she did her own screaming.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the inevitable changes, Stefano was amazed by how
closely the production followed the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that there were some lines that I wanted to change
that Gus didn't want to change, as well as lines that the actors
didn't want changed,'' says Stefano, whose adaptation of Robert
Bloch's source novel was only his second screenplay. ``So, far from
happily being there to protect my sacred work, I was the one who
was pushing the most for changes. I read something I've written 10
minutes ago, and I'm already into rewriting it; imagine what I
thought I could do with something I'd written almost 40 years
ago!''
</P>
<P>
   Stefano reports enjoying the rare opportunity of seeing a new
group of actors reinterpreting his lines. And at least one other
partial observer, Hitchcock's daughter Pat Hitchcock, has given the
project her blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very flattering to my father that Gus wanted to
do it this way,'' she says. ``I can understand the naysayers' point
of view, but everybody should be allowed to express themselves in
any way they want to. If you want to remake a picture like
`Psycho,' then more power to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Other customers remain tougher to sell, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're talented people involved in this movie, and I think
they'll make an interesting one,'' says Janet Leigh's daughter,
actress Jamie Lee Curtis (Leigh refuses to comment on the project).
``They're never going to make a better movie, though, that's for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Sant says that was never the intention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original will always be the original,'' he says. ``Our
restaging shouldn't upset people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1547EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
