<HEADLINE>
TALKING TO SCHRADER FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``You talking to me? You talking to me? There's
nobody here, so you must be talking to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976's ``Taxi Driver'' was molded into unsettling cinema
by Martin Scorsese, screenwriter and director Paul Schrader has
been talking to us. First, it was through Robert DeNiro's character
as a loose-cannon, night-shift cabbie who's infatuated with a
12-year-old prostitute, played by Jodie Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in 1980, Schrader let Richard Gere's male prostitute
character do his bidding in another story of a loner, only this
time one with Gucci style and cool charm that draws him into the
company of well-appointed women looking for a good time in the city
of fallen angels.
</P>
<P>
   The co-existence of alienation and humanity in the metropolitan
rat race is a theme he's come back to frequently _ from 1992's
``Light Sleeper,'' with Willem Dafoe as a drug courier living on
the razor's edge in New York, to 1997's ``Touch,'' about a young
man with healing powers that make him vulnerable to exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   Starting tonight with the screening of ``Taxi Driver'' and
``Light Sleeper,'' audiences can realize Schrader's rather bleak
cinematic style and see his evolution from writer to
writer-director to director of other authors' works. The program
begins at 7:30 p.m. at Los Angeles County Museum of Art's Bing
Theatre. ``American Gigolo'' and ``Touch'' screen on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The program continues Dec. 11 with ``Mishima'' and ``The Comfort
of Strangers,'' and concludes Dec. 12 with the L.A. premiere of
``Affliction,'' based on the novel ``The Sweet Hereafter'' by
Russell Banks. Schrader will introduce his newest film, which opens
later this month. All shows begin at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   EVENING WITH GREGORY PECK: Disney studio's restoration of David
O. Selznick's western-love story ``Duel in the Sun'' was given the
thumbs-up by co-star Gregory Peck, who said seeing the picture gave
him a new appreciation for his co-star and friend Jennifer Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invited her to join me tonight,'' the charming and rugged
Peck, now 82, revealed, ``but she's a shrinking violet. She told
me, `I wouldn't know what to say in front of all those people'.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Duel in the Sun,'' Jones plays a mixed-heritage daughter
who goes to live with a Texas family after her own father is hanged
for killing his wife and her lover. There, she encounters the
hostility of the ranch's patriarch, played by Lionel Barrymore, and
the affection of the motherly Lillian Gish and her two sons, the
lawyerly Joseph Cotten and the free-spirited ladies' man Peck.
</P>
<P>
   The actor maintains a close friendship with Jones, with whom he
was paired again in Fox's ``The Man in the Gray Flannel Suit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to call her tonight and tell her,'' Peck said, after
applauding the preservation effort done by Walt Disney Library
Restoration, the Museum of Modern Art and the Library of Congress.
This new version of the 1946 picture includes the original
10-minute ``Roadshow Overture,'' the three-minute ``Popular
Overture'' and the ``Roadshow Exit Music'' written by Dimitri
Tiomkin.
</P>
<P>
   Bits by Butterfly McQueen as the family's talkative house
servant and Walter Huston playing a hellfire preacher sprinkle some
hearty humor into this overtly sexual production that critics
dubbed ``Lust in the Dust.'' The censors let it go, but
conservative groups were outraged when it debuted and more editing
was needed to satisfy them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about playing a fiend (albeit, a likable one) against
type, Peck let everyone in on a secret. Playing the bad apple in
only his fifth motion picture was easier than it looked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in La Jolla, I had a cousin named Stretch. He was a
Lothario. I was just playing my cousin.''
</P>
<P>
   FIRST FOR ACADEMY BOARD: Oscar winner Kathy Bates has been
elected to the motion picture academy's Board of Governors, filling
the seat left empty by the late Roddy McDowall.
</P>
<P>
   Bates, who won an Academy Award in 1990 for ``Misery,'' joins
governors Gregory Peck and Karl Malden, making this the first time
that three Oscar-winning actors have served together, according to
academy spokeswoman Leslie Unger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primary Colors,'' ``The Waterboy,'' ``Titanic'' and ``Fried
Green Tomatoes'' are among Bates' screen credits.
</P>
<P>
   McDowall died of cancer at age 70 on Oct. 3 in Studio City.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the academy's 13 branches is represented on the board by
three governors.
</P>
<P>
   PICKING ARTISTS' BRAINS: Documentarians come at art from
opposite directions in this month's Contemporary Documentary series
Tuesday, hosted by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelangelo, Restored,'' produced by Perry Wolff and Severine
Bourlet de la Vallee, examines the painstaking, 13-year effort to
restore the great Michelangelo's paintings in the Sistine Chapel,
arguably the world's most famous frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder where creative people get their ideas? In the second
film, ``Inspirations,'' seven artists describe their own creative
process and how they communicate their ideas. Produced by Michael
Apted and Jody Patton, ``Inspirations'' interviews musician David
Bowie, painter Roy Lichtenstein, architect Tadao Ando,
choreographer Edouard Lock, dancer Louise Lecavalier, sculptor Nora
Naranjo-Morse and glass artist Dale Chihuly.
</P>
<P>
   This free event is at the James Bridges Theater on the northeast
corner of the UCLA campus. Parking is available for $5 in Lot 3,
next to the theater. For information, call (310) 206-3456.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
