<SLUG> BC-SHARPS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPARING FOR THE WORST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; These are sad times in the music industry, and
the new Cher album has nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The depressing mood at the major labels has little to do with
music and everything to do with business.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation of Seagram-owned PolyGram and the Universal
Music Group (UMG) into one company could result in the elimination
of as many as 3,000 jobs. Rank and file employees at Geffen, A&AMP;M,
Mercury and other imprints are preparing for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing's ever certain in the music business. A quick look at
the albums chart confirms that. Acts that were selling millions a
year ago are hanging on by their teeth today.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, executives who may be forced out during this massive
reorganization will have hefty severance packages to fall back on.
Staff in the publicity and promotions departments, however, won't
be as lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The way things are expected to work, Geffen, A&AMP;M and Interscope
will be folded into the Interscope Music Group based in Los
Angeles. MCA will remain as is, while New York-based Universal
Records will include Motown and Def Jam. Island and Mercury also
would be merged and based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The changes should start next month with the first round of
firings expected the second week of January.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the loss of jobs, Geffen's historic string of offices
in the 9100 block of Sunset will be put on the block, sources say.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Spector Productions operated there in the '60s and '70s,
before Lookout/Frontline Management moved in. That's where David
Geffen co-managed Joni Mitchell; Jackson Browne; Neil Young; and
Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Later, those little bungalow offices were home to the Asylum
label (the Eagles, Tom Waits, Mitchell, Linda Ronstadt and Browne).
</P>
<P>
   The Strip just won't be the same when Starbucks moves in.
</P>
<P>
   HOOKER AS PIONEER RECIPIENT: Delta bluesman John Lee Hooker will
receive the lifetime achievement award at the Rhythm &AMP; Blues
Foundation's 10th annual Pioneer Awards on Feb. 25 at Sony Studios
in Culver City.
</P>
<P>
   Smokey Robinson will host the event, in which 1999 Pioneer
honorees include soul greats such as the late Johnny Adams, Mickey
Baker, Brenda Holloway, Barbara Lewis, Barbara Lynn, Garnet Mimms,
Johnny Moore, Bill Pinkney, Joe Simon, Charlie Thomas and Dee Dee
Warwick.
</P>
<P>
   Ashford &AMP; Simpson and David Porter/Isaac Hayes will be
recognized as songwriters, while Patti LaBelle &AMP; the Bluebelles and
the Manhattans will be honored in the vocal groups category.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, part of Grammy week each year, will bestow
$260,000 to the honorees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1549EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1504 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUTHRIE-MUSIC-LADN     12-03 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUTHRIE-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GUTHRIE TO BRAGG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Although separated by 50 years and an ocean,
Billy Bragg and Woody Guthrie are linked by musical tradition and a
belief in the power of one voice.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, British troubadour Bragg hit upon the heady mix of
the Clash's fiery energy and Guthrie's political fervor, managing
to avoid the ``angry folkie'' tag due to his command of pop music.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie, born into dust-bowl poverty, roamed far and wide during
the Depression and afterward, writing such classic anthems as
``This Land Is Your Land'' while chronicling social struggle and
the resiliency of the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Since both artists belong to the same singer-songwriter
heritage, it seemed like a natural for Bragg to cover Guthrie.
Instead, something more creative took place.
</P>
<P>
   On the acclaimed ``Mermaid Avenue'' (Elektra), Bragg teamed up
with rootsy Chicago rockers Wilco in Dublin for a collection that
puts new music to never-before-released lyrics by Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   The lyrics, mostly penned at Guthrie's Coney Island home in the
late '40s and early '50s, were fitted with tunes composed by Bragg
and Wilco's Jeff Tweedy and Jay Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although some of these lyrics are over 50 years old, they
don't sound dated at all,'' Bragg said recently. ``This is not a
tribute album but a genuine collaboration between contemporary
artists and the man who in many respects is the original
singer-songwriter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragg and his band the Blokes appear tonight at the House of
Blues in West Hollywood. Slide guitarist Corey Harris opens.
</P>
<P>
   Since the June release of ``Mermaid Avenue,'' Guthrie's widow,
Nora, has unearthed more Guthrie material at the Woody Guthrie
Archives in New York. It was her idea to invite Bragg to work on
the original treasure trove in spring 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a spirit to these songs that matches Billy's outlook
and intensity,'' she said. ``Billy has a way of getting a message
across without being pompous, the same way Woody did.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragg put the idea of a collaboration to Wilco in London two
years ago. The following summer, both acts were on the bill at the
Fleadh Festival in New York where they met with Nora, ``and from
there on it was a done deal,'' Bragg recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Bragg and Wilco met in Chicago to demo the material, and the
ensemble soon decamped to Dublin fwpossibility of another Guthrie
record with Wilco and a tour featuring both Bragg and Wilco next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out promoting the album, and as a result a group of
people have taken a closer look at Woody,'' he said. ``I have a
strange inkling that this might be Woody's time. People may at last
be ready to reassess his contribution to popular music and
recognize him as the first true singer-songwriter.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1550EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1507 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZORRO-VIDEO-LADN     12-03 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZORRO-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ZORRO' SLASHINGLY GOOD FUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``The Truman
Show'' grabbed the critical acclaim, ``There's Something About
Mary'' packed in the comedy lovers, and ``Deep Impact'' and
``Armageddon'' cranked up the decibel level, the best pure popcorn
movie of the summer was ``The Mask of Zorro'' (Sony), which hit
video stores this week.
</P>
<P>
   Call it retro fun, which is no surprise because Steven
Spielberg, who loves adventure films, had a hand in making it.
Starring Oscar winner Anthony Hopkins as the aging swordmaster Don
Diego de la Vega and Antonio Banderas as his rash young pupil who
eventually dons the mask to fight for the rights of the oppressed
peasants, ``Zorro'' combines an old-fashioned swashbuckling quality
with a modern, hip sensibility. And what helps give it the latter
is the stunning addition of Catherine Zeta-Jones as Elena, de la
Vega's long-lost daughter. The scenes in which she dances and duels
with Banderas smolder _ in a PG-13 sort of way, of course.
</P>
<P>
   With her fiery beauty and strong screen presence, Zeta-Jones is
likely destined for stardom. She was literally cast for the film
when Spielberg saw her in a television movie about the Titanic.
Next up for her is the thriller ``Entrapment,'' with Sean Connery,
that is set for next summer.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Zorro'' pits good vs. evil in an easily definable way,
``The Negotiator'' (Warner) blurs the edges. The thriller pits one
hostage negotiator (Samuel L. Jackson) who has been framed for
stealing from the police disability fund and takes a room full of
people hostage to prove his innocence against another high-profile
negotiator (Kevin Spacey). The film becomes a cat-and-mouse game
between two wily opponents set against the intrigue of who the real
villains are. (This is complicated by those cops who are angry at
Jackson's character because they think he's guilty.)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the action scenes are a bit overblown, and the end is a
bit too tightly wrapped, but where the script falters, the acting
fills in. And it's a treat to watch Jackson and Spacey, who are
both at the top of their game, command the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sliding Doors'' (Paramount) offers its take on a question that
most of us us ask every day: ``What if?'' In this case, it shows us
how Helen's life would be different if she had caught a London
subway train instead of just missing it. In one of the two
alternating futures intercut throughout the film, Helen (Gwyneth
Paltrow) makes the train and meets a handsome fellow (John Hannah),
who offers the possibility of a new job and fresh love. In the
other future, Helen misses the train and returns home to her dull
job and a live-in boyfriend (John Lynch) who is cheating on her.
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow, like the film, is charming in either parallel future.
``Sliding Doors'' is a light confection that will fall flat under
too much examination, but nevertheless is entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   DVD WATCH: Twentieth Century Fox recently joined the DVD
revolution with the release of its first eight titles. Considering
Fox's great catalog of film, there are some curious choices here
for film bluffs, though perhaps not for marketing people.
</P>
<P>
   You'll get no argument here with the selections of Jan De Bont's
``Speed,'' ``Predator,'' starring Arnold Schwarzenegger, and
``Young Frankenstein.'' The first two are terrific action pictures
with spectacular special effects that look great, especially in the
wide-screen format option.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Brooks' black-and-white ``Young Frankenstein,'' starring
Gene Wilder as the doctor and Peter Boyle as the monster may not
the have the special effects of the other two _ except the
ever-changing hump of the hunchback Igor (the late Marty Feldman)
and whatever weird stuff he does with his eyes _ but the bonus
features of Brooks' commentary and a feature of outtakes/bloopers
makes this a fun DVD choice.
</P>
<P>
   The other five titles _ ``Marked for Death,'' ``Home Alone 3,''
``Porky's'' ``Hope Floats'' and ``Jingle All the Way'' _ are
dubious picks to lead off Fox's foray into DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Clark's teen comedy ``Porky's'' is admittedly funny for all
of us with adolescence senses of humor, and ``Hope,'' starring
Sandra Bullock, and ``Jingle,'' with Schwarzenegger, have their
moments. ``Home'' and ``Marked'' have marginal entertainment value
at best, but none of them is crying out to be the first on DVD. No
doubt ``Jingle'' was chosen because of the holidays, and ``Hope''
for it romance, but a Steven Seagal film (``Marked'') and the worst
of the ``Home Alone'' series? Come on.
</P>
<P>
   endit &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
