<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBOTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBOTS SHOW OFF THEIR SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROLWING  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANDLER, Ariz. - Max and Lisa, two workers at a new Chandler
company, lift and haul heavy boxes, flawlessly repeat boring tasks
and work in hazardous environments without complaints.
</P>
<P>
   And they'll do it all for eight straight years without taking a
coffee break, getting a raise or a headache.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't superhuman. They are robots.
</P>
<P>
   The two are among many robots at a new 28,000 square-foot plant
tucked away among the miles of semiconductor companies in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Motoman Inc. of Dayton, Ohio, recently opened the shop to cater
to the semiconductor industry worldwide. It will sell, support and
teach people how to control the robots. Also, engineers will
customize existing robots for customers like Intel, Motorola,
SpeedFam International and others.
</P>
<P>
   Just sitting in the floor of the cavernous building, the robots
seem underwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of our robots look like C-3P0,'' said Don Adkins, general
manager of Motoman's supermechatronics group.
</P>
<P>
   But after firing up their motors, creating an eerie humming
noise, the powerful hunks of metal come to life _ rapidly moving
heavy boxes, flipping around windshield-size plates of glass held
on by suction cups. They can really dance.
</P>
<P>
   The robots come in two basic designs. One is fairly small and is
designed to pick up an item and move it from one place to another
in a straight line. Such devices tend to cost in the low $20,000
range.
</P>
<P>
   The other is like a mechanical arm, with six joints that mirror
the movement of a shoulder, elbow, forearm, wrist and hand. The
``wrist'' part has a couple of joints for full-range of motion.
</P>
<P>
   These robots, which include Lisa and Max, range from about 2.5
feet tall to 6 feet tall and cost up to $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   And they can do a slew of tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as your hand, you can pick up a cup or you can
sew. You can teach it to do very simple things or you can teach it
to do complex assembly,'' said Jim Brinegar, Motoman's customer
satisfaction supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Crafty programmers taught Max and Lisa to work together to show
off their skills during trade shows.
</P>
<P>
   Max will lift up a pallet and Lisa will promptly draw a picture
of herself. They also can goof off _ when programmed to do so, the
two will play take away with a pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lisa always wins, she always wins,'' Adkins said.
</P>
<P>
   On the more practical side, robots play a critical role in the
semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   Even people wearing clean suits, like those folks dancing around
in the Intel commercials, pose a risk of contaminating the highly
sensitive silicon wafers used to make chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically taboo to handle wafers,'' said Darren McDougal,
international field operations manager for SpeedFam International
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   SpeedFam, which neighbors Motoman in Chandler, uses robots in
most of the polishing equipment that it makes for the semiconductor
industry.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, robots are extremely clean and have a greatly
reduced chance of tainting the chips.
</P>
<P>
   Some have only one particulate, which can be a speck of dust,
moisture or anything else, per cubic foot, while an operating room
has 1,000 particulates per cubic foot.
</P>
<P>
   And talk about tidy, some robots will even wash their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanical arms will take a wafer from one kind of chemical
solution and dip its hands in highly purified water before touching
another chemical bath.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, robots will do much more. They will use laser
optics and specialized cameras to ``see'' and sophisticated
microprocessors to ``think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting to surface right now. We have some very
sophisticated vision guided applications out there and some
rudimentary artificial intelligence systems,'' Adkins said.
</P>
<P>
   There will soon be a day when a robot will see a part and
decided if it's good or bad. It will know if a product is assembled
right and if not, what adjustments are needed.
</P>
<P>
   But Adkins doubts there will be a day when robots will put us
all out of work, comparing it to the fear people felt when the
automobile first threatened to replace the buggy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robots allow you to be able to do mundane jobs and do it
better, faster and correct,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rebecca Rolwing can be reached at rebecca.rolwing(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
