<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT THEATER NOTES ON STAGE AND OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three weeks after dismissing the artistic staff of ``Elaborate
Lives: The Legend of Aida,'' producers at Disney have reportedly
selected a new creative team. The newcomers are expected to make
big changes in the troubled musical.
</P>
<P>
   A senior production executive who spoke only on condition of
anonymity said this week that Robert Falls, artistic director of
the Goodman Theater in Chicago, would replace Robert Jess Roth as
director, and Bob Crowley would take over the set and costume
designs. For choreography, the producers have tapped Wayne Cilento,
who won a Tony for ``Tommy'' in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Katz will stay on as the lighting designer. The music by
Elton John and lyrics by Tim Rice will remain, as will the book by
Linda Woolverton. Disney declined to comment on its plans for
``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has poured more than $10 million into the show,
which had a rough tryout this fall in Atlanta. It was dogged by
jokes about its cartoonish look and its central set piece, a giant
mechanical pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   The new choices suggest a shift of focus from the glitzy
spectacle exemplified by ``Beauty and the Beast,'' which Roth
directed, toward the more high-minded charms of ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   Falls, for example, has never directed a Broadway musical but
has been hailed for his surreal, cerebral take on Arthur Miller's
``Death of a Salesman,'' which will open on Broadway in February.
Crowley is also hot, with his lushly elegant scenic design for last
summer's ``Twelfth Night'' at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   But the new team will also face high expectations and tough
decisions. Will Falls, for example, add the same artistic gravitas
to ``Aida'' that the director Julie Taymor did to ``The Lion
King''? Will Crowley keep the show's finicky and expensive pyramid
in the mix?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's something quite deep and wonderful there,''
Falls said. ``I think it's a serious work _ certainly entertaining,
but also a love story set against an epic landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   The new team is expected to begin work on the show in New York
after Falls completes the transfer of ``Salesman'' to Broadway
</P>
<P>
   The target date for a Broadway run has been pushed back a year,
to the spring of 2000. A scheduled out-of-town run is likely next
fall, probably in Chicago. And a new title, possibly shorter, is an
option. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several other shows are also facing changes.
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway, Wendy Makkena will be bowing out of ``Side Man,''
probably next month. The reason is a happy one: she's pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Her replacement in the role of the narrator's mother is expected
to be named soon. Producers are said to be looking at two familiar
faces: Edie Falco, who originated the role last year, and Angelica
Torn, who plays Patsy, the flirty waitress in the show, and has
filled in for Ms. Makkena several times.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, at the white-trash thriller ``Killer Joe,'' Amanda
Plummer, who plays a semi-demented stepmother, and Scott Glenn, who
is the show's lecherous gun for hire, are to leave on Jan. 17. The
producer, Darren Lee Cole, said he hoped to recast by next week.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Off Broadway shows are having unexpected delays. At
New York Theater Workshop, the actress Jenny Bacon broke her foot
onstage on Saturday night during a performance of Paul Rudnick's
``Most Fabulous Story Ever Told.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw her fall, but she just bounced up,'' Rudnick said.
``She was amazing. She got all her laughs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bacon performed another show before a doctor diagnosed a
serious fracture and prescribed a knee-high cast. Kathryn Meisle
has taken over Ms. Bacon's role, but the show's opening has been
delayed until Dec. 14.
</P>
<P>
   And at the Vineyard Theater, Tristine Skyler has been replaced
by Amelia Campbell in ``Mercy,'' Laura Cahill's play about four
young New Yorkers. That set back the show's opening until Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the Vineyard, Betty Buckley, who recently completed a
run as Rose in Paper Mill Playhouse's ``Gypsy,'' in New Jersey, is
signing on to ``The Eros Trilogy,'' the new Nicky Silver play,
which begins performances on Jan. 21. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The theater world and the animal kingdom lost one of their own
on Sunday when Zingaro, a longtime performer and the namesake of
Company Zingaro, the French equestrian theater troupe, died after
surgery for colic at a veternarian hospital in New Jersey. The
horse was 17, or about 60 in human years.
</P>
<P>
   Zingaro, a towering black stallion whose name means gypsy,
became ill in mid-October during the company's recent run in
Battery Park City, said Bartabas, the company's artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically he was a monster, very powerful,'' Bartabas said.
``But he was very kind, and like an actor, he had a lot of
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Zingaro began acting when he was a foal, making his debut in
1983 in the show ``Cabaret Equus'' in Paris. He always worked
without a rider.
</P>
<P>
   While the recent show, ``Eclipse,'' received tepid reviews,
Zingaro had a knack for upstaging his human counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Dunning of The New York Times called Bartabas'
choreography anemic, but she said Zingaro ``settles into a recline
so slowly that one can see every rippling strand of muscle down the
length of his body.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartabas said Zingaro had no immediate family (``He didn't have
time''), adding: ``He was the foundation of this company, and its
memory.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ The deal is done to move ``This Is Our Youth'' by Kenneth
Lonergan to the Minetta Lane Theater on Jan. 8, after it finishes
its run at Second Stage on Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   _ Corin Redgrave will perform an adaptation of ``De Profundis''
by Oscar Wilde on Monday at the Century Center for the Performing
Arts, 111 East 15th Street. The material should be familiar to
Redgrave, a scion of the Redgrave acting clan; this fall he
finished a run in Plymouth, England, in the title role of ``Gross
Indecency: The Three Trials of Oscar Wilde'' by Moises Kaufman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1619EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      12-03 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCAPISM: THE STORY OF HOUDINI 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Erich Weiss was lucky to have been born in a more innocent time.
Before the turn of the century, he transformed himself into Harry
Houdini and never had the secrets of his famous escapes revealed on
the tacky, magicians-reveal-all television specials so popular now.
</P>
<P>
   When he was manacled and submerged underwater in a giant milk
can, or suspended upside down in a straitjacket over a city street,
the audience held its breath until he set himself free.
</P>
<P>
   As the TNT film ``Houdini'' makes clear, engaging the crowd with
his showman's patter and evoking the specter of his death were
essential parts of Houdini's magic.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who think of him as only a great escape artist may be
surprised to find how strongly Houdini was rooted in vaudeville,
and this uninspired film works best when focusing on the theatrical
aspects of his career. He stumbles before being sealed in the milk
can, every time he does that trick; the stumble heightens the
audience's concern.
</P>
<P>
   But when it addresses his private life, the film becomes wildly
erratic. There is a whirlwind romance and long-lived marriage to a
woman named Bess; that tritely written part of the story is
salvaged by Stacy Edwards' warm, graceful performance.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the film veers from the pedestrian (overblown
dialogue in shouting arguments with his jealous brother) to the
actively bad (Houdini is a tormented soul because his beloved
mother never kissed him).
</P>
<P>
   The film is awkwardly structured as a series of flashbacks,
constantly returning to 1936 and a seance, broadcast live on radio,
in which Bess tries to contact her husband 10 years after his
death.
</P>
<P>
   His early years are handled in the perfunctory style of most
made-for-television biographies. He works in a New York sweatshop;
he meets and quickly marries Bess, an aspiring singer who becomes
his onstage assistant; he is seen doing one of his earliest tricks,
stuffing a hunk of thread and a pile of needles in his mouth and
pulling out a long chain of threaded needles.
</P>
<P>
   George Segal, as the vaudeville impresario Martin Beck, turns up
with a laughably thick German accent but good advice. He tells
Houdini to do stunts so dangerous he'll be dead if they fail.
</P>
<P>
   The film recreates several of his best tricks, and though there
is no question he will escape whatever water-filled chamber he is
tossed into, there are tantalizing hints and revelations about how
he pulled off those feats. The secrets were merely part of it,
though.
</P>
<P>
   With a neurotic need to push himself into ever-more-dangerous
stunts, Houdini was truly death-defying. As Bess explains, ``Few,
even if they knew his secrets, would have the courage or ability to
attempt them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Houdini's theatrics are still so entertaining,
for they keep a viewer going through the many dull patches here. As
Houdini, Johnathon Schaech is wooden, and improves only as the
character ages, acquiring wild, grizzled hair and a fanatical look
in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the script falls apart along with the character. When he
goes on a crusade to expose fake spiritualists who have promised to
connect him to his dead mother, no trick can save the movie from
its cheap psychologizing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime's Intimate Portrait biography series may be the
puffiest of a uniformly puffy genre. But with Saturday's profile of
Gloria Steinem, its 100th episode, the series has finally come up
with a program worth celebrating. Though no less glowing than the
typical installment, this one is more substantial, taking its tone
from the tough-minded, clear-sighted, always articulate Ms.
Steinem.
</P>
<P>
   (Sure, it's easy to call her Ms. now, but only because she once
crusaded for a term as neutral as, making no distinction between
married and unmarried women.)
</P>
<P>
   This richly detailed program takes her from childhood (complete
with family photographs) to a sad girlhood caring for her
emotionally unstable mother, to the years of founding Ms. magazine
and traveling around the country giving feminism a glamorous face.
</P>
<P>
   The feminist Dorothy Pittman Hughes, who often spoke with her on
lecture tours, recalls that while Ms. Steinem famously attracted
attention with her miniskirt and flowing hair, ``Once she got that
attention she just really used it.''
</P>
<P>
   The profile includes vibrant interviews with Ms. Steinem,
friends like Marlo Thomas, and Blair Chotzinoff, the man she was
once engaged to marry and who remains endearingly smitten. Above
all, it is packed with reminders of how much has changed in the 30
years she has been on the public stage.
</P>
<P>
   Just out of college, en route to study in India, Ms. Steinem had
an abortion in London; it cost $500, half her scholarship money. As
she says here about her decision not to marry, ``Looking at the
world, I didn't see very many women who were married and mothers
and free, and were their own selves.'' If you see more of that
today, it is because she helped make it happen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUDINI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TNT, Sunday at 8. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Pen Densham. Produced by Triology
Entertainment Group. Richard Barton Lewis, Pen Densham and John
Watson, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Johnathon Schaech (Harry Houdini), Stacy Edwards (Bess
Houdini), Paul Sorvino (Blackburn), Rhea Perlman (Esther), George
Segal (Beck), David Warner (Sir A.C. Doyle), Mark Ruffalo (Theo),
Grace Zabriskie (Mother), Ron Perlman (Booking Agent), Karl Makinen
(Jim Collins), Judy Geeson (Lady Doyle) and Emile Hirsch (Young
Houdini). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
