<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN PLANS `EFFETS DE NEIGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Riding on the success of its 1997 blockbuster, ``Monet and the
Mediterranean,'' the Brooklyn Museum of Art announced this week
that it would be the final stop for ``Impressionists in Winter:
Effets de Neige,'' an exhibition of winter scenes by masters like
Monet, Sisley, Pissaro, Renoir, Caillebotte and Gauguin, artists
more readily known for their lush warm-weather landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   The show will open in Brooklyn on May 27. It originated at the
Phillips Collection in Washington, where it will remain through
Jan. 3, and it will be at the Fine Arts Museum in San Francisco
from Jan. 30 through May 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impressionists in Winter'' has been a big success so far,
attracting more than a thousand people a day. ``We're obviously
delighted that this will have a New York audience,'' said Jay
Gates, director of the Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   While it may seem odd to show scenes of winter in late spring,
the chance to generate the kind of record-breaking attendance the
Brooklyn Museum had for ``Monet in the Mediterranean'' (more than
250,000 saw it) was irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, curators there are joking that the advertisement for the
show should read ``Chill Out at the Brooklyn Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold L. Lehman, director of the museum, said the season should
not make a difference. ``This is exactly the kind of exhibition for
us to have here,'' he said. ``It's a show with a particular point
of view, not a survey, and brings together for the first time many
really gorgeous paintings.''
</P>
<P>
   Included will be Monet's ``Red Cape'' (1871), a snow scene that
shows the artist's wife, Camille, through a window, and
Caillebotte's ``View of Rooftops (Snow)'' (1878), a wintery Paris
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three museums will have a slightly different
selection of paintings, because some lenders do not want their
works to travel. Elizabeth W. Easton, curator of European paintings
at the Brooklyn Museum, who is organizing the exhibition there,
said she hoped it would include 50 to 60 paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show ranges from the early years of Impressionism, when
artists like Monet and Pissaro were painting the same scenes side
by side,'' she said, ``to later works, including Monet's series of
ice flows on the Seine, which were a metaphor for mourning the
death of his wife in 1879.''
</P>
<P>
   Timed tickets will be required for the show, which runs through
Aug. 29. They go on sale on Tuesday by telephone at (877) 946-8379
and on the Internet at www.2btech.com/winter/. Tickets may also be
purchased at the museum, beginning on Jan. 2. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christie's sale of Old Master drawings in New York on Jan. 28
will include a selection of important works by artists like
Barocci, Rubens, Goya and Lorenzo di Credi.
</P>
<P>
   In past years such high-quality offerings would have been
reserved for the London sales, but the market has been shifting to
New York. As the number of important buyers here has grown, the
auction house has decided to send its best offerings across the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The sale will include a collection of 40 drawings formed by the
Banque Nationale de Paris. Like the British Rail Pension Fund in
London, the bank began buying works of art in 1989 as an
investment, intending to keep them for only 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Its collection, mainly from the Florentine and Roman Mannerist
schools, includes ``The Life of Taddeo Zuccaro'' (circa 1590),
drawn by his brother Federico Zuccaro and made up of 20 drawings
that tell the life of an artist. The series is estimated to sell
for $2 million to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the sale is Barocci's ``Madonna del Popolo,'' which is
being sold by a family trust set up by David Tunick, the New York
art dealer. It was among the highlights of Christie's landmark 1987
London sale of drawings from the Dukes of Devonshire at Chatsworth,
when a $2.8 million bid made it the highest-priced drawing in the
sale. Christie's now estimates it will sell for $1.9 million to
$2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Barocci drawing is a study for an altarpiece commissioned by
the Confraternita dei Laici di Santa Maria della Misericordia for a
1576 chapel in Arezzo. It now hangs in the Uffizi.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no Barocci pictures in America,'' said Francois
Borne, who runs Christie's Old Master drawings department in New
York and London. ``So I hope a museum here will buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the sale is a newly rediscovered drawing by Lorenzo di
Credi, ``Drapery Study,'' which comes from an unidentified European
collection. ``The collectors didn't know what it was,'' Borne said.
``When we saw it, we made the attribution.'' Christie's estimates
it will bring $300,000 to $500,000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Constance Wolf, who has been associate director of public
programs at the Whitney Museum of American Art for seven and a half
years, has resigned to become director of the Jewish Museum in San
Francisco. She is the fourth top curator at the Whitney to resign
since Maxwell L. Anderson became the museum's director in
September.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year-old Jewish Museum, which does not have its own
collection but exhibits and has an education program, is planning a
major expansion. An old power plant adjacent to the San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art is to be renovated into a 60,000-square-foot
museum, with construction scheduled for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The architect is Daniel Liebskind, a native of Poland who is
completing an extension to the Jewish Museum in Berlin and has been
chosen to build a modern addition for the Victoria and Albert
Museum in London. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because ``From van Eyck to Bruegel: Early Netherlandish Painting
in the Metropolitan Museum of Art'' has attracted close to 200,000
visitors since it opened Sept. 22, the show has been extended
through Jan. 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
