<SLUG> BC-FBN-YOUNG-INJURY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG LIKELY TO HEAL FULLY FROM RARE INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bryant Young's freakish double-bone snap was the
result of a few normal events on the football field that combined
to create a one-in-a-million injury.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, athletic trainers and coaches who have seen the
videotape of the injury Monday night said the conspiracy of
circumstances included:
</P>
<P>
   _ The pressure of Young's 291 pounds pushing down on his right
leg at the end of the play.
</P>
<P>
   _ His cleated foot that dug into the soggy turf at Candlestick
Park and held his lower leg like a vice.
</P>
<P>
   _ A crushing blow at mid-shin, where the shock was absorbed
directly by the two lower leg bones, breaking both the fibula and
the larger tibia.
</P>
<P>
   The injury is rare among all athletes, including football
players. Doctors say they occasionally see the double-bone breaks
of the lower leg among downhill skiers and motorcyclists.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Young, sports medicine specialists say, is
that the bones are cleanly broken and likely to heal fully, though
not necessarily as fast as doctors for the San Francisco 49ers
hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a football injury,'' said Dr. James Garrick,
director of the Center for Sports Medicine at St. Francis Medical
Center. ``First of all, you don't see that many fractures in
football. That's because it's the joints (at the knee and ankle)
that usually give. You have to get hit just exactly right.''
</P>
<P>
   According to statistics kept by the National Collegiate Athletic
Association, lower leg injuries of all types are fairly uncommon,
at least in college football.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA tracks football injuries at 100 Division I, II and III
schools. Of 1,795 injuries in games last year, 21 percent were knee
injuries, 18 percent were ankle injuries and 14 percent were
shoulder injuries. Lower leg injuries comprised just 4 percent of
the injuries, and the survey's director said most were bone
bruises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee and ankle are joints, and every time the players
move, they're using them as a pivot point,'' said Dr. Randall Dick,
the NCAA's senior assistant director of sports sciences, who
oversees the survey. ``The shoulder is used in blocking and
tackling. It's a point of contact that's going to be at risk on
every play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lower leg is not a joint so it can't be twisted or
sprained. The only thing that can happen is that it can be bruised
or broken. That's what happened. It's not really as much in play as
the joints are.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick said the only way the tibia or fibula could be snapped is
if the bones are held tightly in place, and exposed to extreme
force. In this case, the force came from teammate and linebacker
Ken Norton Jr.'s helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically you've got two hard things hitting each other,''
Dick said. ``The helmet is going into the shin bone. If the shin
bone is held firm _ if the guy is planted _ really it's just like a
baseball going through a window. One is harder than the other. The
window is static, the baseball is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the arms, the lower legs are one of the few areas on a
football player's body not protected by pads. Trainers said they
have rarely if ever seen football players wear shin pads, like
those worn by soccer players.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got a 300-pound mass rolling up on you, there's
not much you can do,'' said Dr. Cindy Chang, a physician for
several university teams. ``I don't think there's any type of brace
that could prevent that type of injury. Basically it is a traumatic
injury that happens in the game of football.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Young's cleats _ which provided critical traction on
a soggy field Monday night _ may have also helped lock his leg in
place just as Norton crashed into him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting to see if his cleats were very long,''
said Joe Callan, who coached high school football in San Francisco
for 26 years. ``Clearly he planted so hard that his foot stuck in
the ground. There was nowhere for his leg to go but to break.''
</P>
<P>
   Callan said the California Interscholastic Federation limited
the length of cleats a decade ago to help high school football
players avoid injuries, especially knee injuries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doctors see several encouraging signs for Young: He apparently
suffered no ligament damage, and his parallel bone breaks are
clean. If the bones had shattered into several pieces, they would
have been slower to heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the nice things about bone is that it heals
completely,'' said Dr. Gordon Matheson, director of sports medicine
for the Stanford University athletic department. ``When it comes to
ligaments and other soft tissues, they heal by scarring. Bones heal
by completely replacing with normal bone material. There's not a
different kind of scar tissue ... the tissue is exactly the same.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garrick said the team doctors' prediction that Young's
recovery would take eight or nine months sounds overly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tibial fractures are notoriously slow to heal,'' Garrick said.
``It's a big bone, and it doesn't have a great blood supply in the
center of it. That usually slows the healing down.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrick said Young should ease into his recovery: ``He's in a
business that puts an incredible amount of demand on his leg _ it's
not like you and me walking from the parking lot to our offices. If
you want to make a full recovery, you've got to be well-healed and
ideally fully rehabilitated before you even think about playing
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
