u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     12-03 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, Dec. 4. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey (E-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com); Phone:
(888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CITIBANK (Undated) _ Eager to do lucrative business with
Raul Salinas de Gortari, a brother of Mexico's former President,
executives at Citibank ignored some of their own basic safeguards
against the laundering of illicit funds, congressional
investigators have found. By Tim Golden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Podujevo, Serbia) _ Though there is little combat
in Kosovo, ethnic Albanian rebels are spreading their influence to
places they had not operated until NATO threats made the Serbian
Government withdraw many police and army units. Expanding the area
they control without having to fight for it allows the rebels to
undercut American efforts to reach a negotiated settlement to the
war. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Raising his public profile,
Representative Robert L. Livingston, the incoming Speaker, said
Thursday he would prefer to see the House finish impeachment
proceedings this year, but refused to indicate whether he would
allow House consideration of an alternate proposal to censure
President Clinton. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS (Washington) _ As House Republicans push toward a
vote to impeach President Clinton, not only is public sentiment
overwhelmingly against them, but so are many prominent Republicans
across the country. A look at the divisions among Republicans over
impeachment and the reasons for them. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-RATES (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The central banks of the 11
European countries that are adopting a common currency next month
unexpectedly cut interest rates to combat what the president of the
German bank calls a ``clouded'' economic outlook. The reductions
reflect growing concern among central banks that the global economy
may be heading for recession next year. In this country, the Fed
has lowered rates three times within two months. By Edmund L.
Andrews. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-ASSESS (Washington) _ Three months ago, Alan Greenspan,
the Federal Reserve chairman, warned that the United States `'could
not remain an oasis of prosperity unaffected by a world that is
experiencing greatly increased stress.'' It has taken a while, but
Europe has come to the same conclusion. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ENCRYPTION-EXPORTS (Undated) _ Clinton administration officials
said Thursday they had persuaded other leading countries to impose
strict new export controls on computer data-scrambling products
under the guise of arms control. At a meeting in Vienna, 33 nations
that have signed an agreement limiting arms exports agreed to
impose controls on the most powerful data-scrambling technologies,
including, for the first time, mass-market software. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS  &LR; (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-NORTHWESTERN (Chicago) _ Northwestern University's football
program has equalled its basketball program, with a gambling
scandal of its own. Four former football players were indicted
Thursday on charges of playing to lose games so they could win
bets. By Bill Dedman. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
