<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARE HIGH-TECH EXECUTIVES COOL, OR JUST COLD?
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Saturday, Dec. 5.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the giant TV screen at the Microsoft antitrust
trial Wednesday, chairman Bill Gates was shown denying knowledge of
a potentially devastating lawsuit by Sun Microsystems Inc. _ even
though he'd written that Sun's Java programming language ``scares
the hell out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, a Sun executive took the stand to downplay and chuckle at
e-mail and other evidence that Sun employees wanted to use Java as
``a way to attack the evil empire'' of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The double-speak at the trial exposes the underbelly of an
industry whose executives cultivate a super-cool, super-casual
image. Even as they publicly seek partnerships to create the next
``killer app,'' privately the executives are at their keyboards,
tapping away at strategies to wipe out each other's latest
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may wear jeans and T-shirts,'' said William Kovacic, a
visiting law professor at George Washington University in
Washington. ``But they've got knives in their belts, guns under
their shirts and brass knuckles on their fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   Collaboration and competition are intertwined in the emerging
high-tech industry. Microsoft, for example, may dominate 90 percent
of the operating-system market, but it still must work with
independent software developers if it wants them to write programs
to run on new products.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer Co. may compete with Microsoft by selling its own
operating system, Mac OS, but it has to team up with the software
giant to market popular software such as a Mac Microsoft Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real convergence,'' said Frederic H. Dickson,
director of research at Branch, Cabell &AMP; Co., a Richmond, Va.-based
brokerage firm. ``No one knows what the final solution will look
like, ...not the chip-makers, software developers or the hardware
guys. So they've got to collaborate.''
</P>
<P>
   As the trial has revealed, however, these collaborations don't
always stay friendly. In 1994, for example, Netscape Communications
Corp.'s co-founder James Clark e-mailed a Microsoft official, ``We
want to make this company a success, but not at Microsoft's
expense. We'd like to work with you.''
</P>
<P>
   But by 1996, the relationship had soured, according to America
Online Inc. executives, who traded e-mails about a Gates offer:
``Gates delivered an uncharacteristically blunt query: 'How much do
we have to pay you to screw Netscape? This is your lucky day.'''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in recent years, AOL, Netscape and Sun each have played
footsie with Microsoft, teaming up on projects ranging from AOL's
use of Microsoft's Internet browser to talk that Microsoft might
invest in Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this month, the trio sprung news of their own collaboration:
AOL announced a $4.3-billion deal to buy Netscape that includes a
three-year agreement under which Sun will market Netscape's
business software. The alliance is considered the greatest threat
yet to Microsoft's operating monopoly, as well as to corner the
booming e-commerce business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it looks like everybody against Microsoft, `` said
Robert Litan, a Brookings Institution scholar and former Justice
Department official. ``But there's still a lot of jockeying going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most surprising in this world of former nerds is the
crude language that conjures up images of gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   Apple senior executive Avadis Tevanian Jr., testifying in
November at the antitrust trial about perceived threats by
Microsoft to force Apple to abandon its Quicktime software to play
back video clips, described a lunchtime exchange between a Sun
executive and a Microsoft official.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you asking us to kill playback? Are you asking us to knife
the baby?'' asked the incredulous Sun executive. ``Yes,'' the
Microsoft official responded. ``We want you to knife the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Business scholars say these colorful exchanges, in conversations
and e-mail messages, also indicate that industry leaders may not be
as savvy as they pretend to be.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1995, for example, AOL and Netscape wanted to unite
against mighty Microsoft. AOL Chairman Steve Case referred to the
Redmond, Wash., software giant company as ``the common enemy,'' and
agreed with Netscape co-founder Marc Andreesen's assessment that
both companies should ``resist the Beast from Redmond that wants to
see us both dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Netscape wasn't able to strike a deal with AOL to exclude
Microsoft, even though Case clearly was sympathetic to their
position. In the end, AOL decided to include Microsoft's Internet
browser on its site.
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry likes to paint itself as the omnipresence of
genius where you've got boy wonders becoming billionaires,'' said
Kovacic. ``But we're seeing that some of these people have no more
insight than the guy selling mufflers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some financial analysts fear the public airing of the industry's
dirty laundry will make executives wary that future partners will
disclose private negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not completely stifle innovation,'' said John J.
Puricelli, an analyst with A.G. Edwards, a St. Louis-based
brokerage house. ``But it could slow it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
