<HEADLINE>
COLLECTIBLES AND BIG BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This time of year in video lends itself to boxed sets,
commemorative editions and other collectibles. It also brings on
some big books.
</P>
<P>
   Two large, specialized volumes from Visible Ink Press go along
with the 1999 edition of ``Video Hound's Golden Movie Retriever,''
with reviews of 23,000 films. ``Video Hound's World Cinema'' covers
800 foreign films, and, for those to whom a film's size matters,
``Video Hound's Epics: Giants of the Big Screen'' assesses 200
representives of the colossal from ``Doctor Zhivago'' to ``Samson
and Delilah.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatter still, ``Movies Unlimited 1999 Video Catalog,'' from the
mail order company in Philadelphia, lists 40,000 titles of all
kinds, both film and television. ``The Hound,'' as it's called in
video circles, is a guide.
</P>
<P>
   Movies Unlimited sells videos and must compete with Internet
services like Amazon.com. Irv Slifkin, a Movies Unlimited
spokesman, said that while the company was about to put its catalog
on line, it still sells 100,000 catalogs a year (information:
800-523-0823).
</P>
<P>
   Paper or Web, Slifkin and other dealers confirm some trends
relevant to the gift-giving season. First, the studios are issuing
more commemorative re-releases of famous films, some in wide-screen
versions with extras added.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``Chinatown,'' ``The Exorcist,'' ``American
Graffiti,'' ``Animal House'' and ``The Searchers'' are available in
new editions.
</P>
<P>
   Second, some major discontinued titles, most of them off the
market for years, have been reissued. Among the most requested,
Slifkin said, are Mel Brooks' ``The Producers,'' with Zero Mostel
and Gene Wilder; ``The Night Stalker,'' the television movie with
Darren McGavin; Sam Peckinpah's ``Straw Dogs,'' with Dustin
Hoffman; Ernest B. Schoedsack's ``Mighty Joe Young'' (in
anticipation of the release of the remake), Peckinpah's ``Cross of
Iron,'' and Morton Da Costa's ``The Music Man,'' with Robert
Preston and Shirley Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In one swoop, Anchor Bay has brought back four of ``the
discontinued'' as a set, all of them Hitchcocks: ``Notorious''
(1946), with Ingrid Bergman, Cary Grant and Claude Rains; ``The
Paradine Case'' (1948), with Gregory Peck, Alida Valli and Charles
Laughton; ``Rebecca'' (1940), with Laurence Olivier, Joan Fontaine
and Judith Anderson, and ``Spellbound'' (1945), with Bergman and
Peck.
</P>
<P>
   Also in a slipcase are three noir films by Akira Kurosawa, who
died in September. ``High and Low'' (1962), about a businessman
(Toshiro Mifune) who raises ransom money to rescue the kidnapped
son of his chauffeur, is back on video after a long period out of
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bad Sleep Well'' (1960) also stars Mifune, confronting
corruption as he maneuvers the corporate ladder. The third film of
the set, ``Stray Dog'' (1949), about a detective (Mifune again)
tracking his stolen gun and a killer through postwar Tokyo, is
classic noir.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the best set of the year, ``Les Vampires,'' Louis
Feuillade's 1915 silent classic about a gang of diabolical
criminals who terrorize the Parisian bourgeoisie, has never been
available. Irma Vep is up to her neck in evil, and the car chases
never exceed 30 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Recent Releases
</P>
<P>
   The Parent Trap
</P>
<P>
   In a remake of the 1961 Hayley Mills hit, twin sisters separated
at birth are reunited at a summer camp, in this case 11{ years
later. Alternating British and American accents, Lindsay Lohan
plays both girls with gusto.
</P>
<P>
   Having managed a no-fault divorce with no custody problems,
their parents (Natasha Richardson and Dennis Quaid) went their
separate ways with one offspring apiece. Dad is a Napa Valley wine
grower and Mom designs bridal gowns in London.
</P>
<P>
   Neither parent realizes it when the girls switch places, and
both seem ripe for a reunion in a lavish, super-cute film that,
Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, invites one to ``suspend
disbelief and enjoy the story's good cheer.''
</P>
<P>
   1998. Disney. $22.99. 127 minutes. Closed captioned. PG. Release
date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Six Days, Seven Nights
</P>
<P>
   No sooner does the New York fashion editor Robin Monroe (Anne
Heche) land in the South Pacific for a getaway with her sappy
boyfriend (David Schwimmer) than she's called away for a picture
shoot. With no other choice of transportation, she boards a clanky
puddle jumper piloted by the raffish Quinn Harris (Harrison Ford).
</P>
<P>
   During a thunderstorm the plane goes down and the two are
stranded on an uncharted speck of an island. Fortunately, they have
come fully outfitted to get a well-equipped workout while evading
pirates and still look great in an ``escapist romance for the
Treadmill Generation'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Touchstone. $107.37. 111 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mendel
</P>
<P>
   His parents try to shield him from the experience, but
9-year-old Mendel Trotzig (Thomas Jungling Sorensen) is aware of
his family's suffering during the Holocaust. Resettled in Norway,
the Trotzigs find themselves in a cool Christian land where Mendel
grows from a guarded boy into a daredevil whose reckless behavior
covers his fears.
</P>
<P>
   But the Holocaust lives on in his dreams and taints his
perceptions in a film whose ``anecdotes and images are so vivid
that you can feel the boy changing and toughening with each new
experience'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. First Run Features. $79.95. 85 minutes. Norwegian with
English subtitles. No rating. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sour Grapes
</P>
<P>
   In his first feature film, Larry David, the co-creator of
``Seinfeld'' sticks closely to a series formula. Two cousins, Evan
(Steven Weber) and Richie (Craig Bierko), go to Atlantic City,
where Richie wins a slot-machine jackpot with two quarters borrowed
from Evan.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately the bickering starts between the two, with warfare
spreading throughout the family the way crazy escalation did on the
show. ``David's strong comic voice here is at least as conspicuous
as his film's visual flatness, and it's the former quality that
counts'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $100.96. 91 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Studios increasingly price their biggest films to sell on home
video. Many people, however, still prefer to rent. Here are some
low-priced best sellers that are doubling as best renters.
</P>
<P>
   ARMAGEDDON. Rallying around the flag, a rowdy bunch of oil
drillers led by Harry S. Stamper (Bruce Willis) ride a couple of
space shuttles out to an incoming meteor the size of Texas. 1998.
Touchstone. $26.99. 150 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   GODZILLA. The lizard that wrecks New York is so large he can
barely fit on screen, inspires wooden dialogue from pop-eyed
observers and picks Madison Square Garden to have its 200 babies.
1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $22.95. 138 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL SOLDIERS. Advanced computer chips normally used in
weaponry wind up in G.I. Joe-style toys that talk like the Dirty
Dozen and are led by the flat-topped platoon leader Chip Hazard
(Tommy Lee Jones). Universal. $22.99. 99 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   PAULIE. A tart-tongued parrot bounces cross-country in hopes of
locating the little girl who once owned him. 1998. Universal.
$22.99. 91 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
</P>
<P>
   THE X-FILES. Having devastated early man 37,000 years ago,
aliens turn up in weird holes in the ground, which draws agents
Mulder (David Duchovny) and Scully (Gillian Anderson) to Texas and
points radically beyond. 1998. Fox. $22.98. 145 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13.
</P>
</TEXT>
