<HEADER>
A1668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     12-03 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUG'S WORD: YADANYAFOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Dialogue and voices have always played a critical
role in animated movies, and that has never been more true than in
today's enormously competitive market. Consider this unforgettable
line from ``A Bug's Life,'' which has set box office records in its
opening weekend. As Tuck says so notably to Roll, ``Yadanyafoo!''
</P>
<P>
   How's that? Mike McShane, the actor who did the voices for this
pair of pill bug acrobats, repeated, in his peculiar barking tone,
``You know, Yadanyafoooo!''
</P>
<P>
   Even in this crowded season, ``A Bug's Life,'' produced by Pixar
for the Walt Disney Co., rocketed out of the starting blocks over
the Thanksgiving holiday. It earned $46 million over the long
weekend, the most ever for the time period.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has been applauded for its animation techniques,
created on computers, and its endearing story of how a group of
circus bugs help deliver an ant colony from the menace of a gang of
grasshoppers.
</P>
<P>
   But for the filmmakers, the voices were critical to the movie's
off-center humor. Some well-known actors, like Julia Louis-Dreyfus,
Dave Foley, Phyllis Diller and Kevin Spacey, played main
characters, but many lesser-known actors played important parts and
shaped their characters by ad-libbing to get the dialogue just
right _ even when the dialogue comes from no known language family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very, very proud of our voices, but it's something we
really work at,'' said John Lasseter, the director of the film.
``We look at lots and lots of actors and what we'll do is take a
performance from a movie and just take the audio and put it against
some drawings. When you take away the visual of an actor, what do
you have? Some people are not as good as you thought.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a process that also allows for serendipity. Take Heimlich,
the rotund performing caterpillar. In the animation process, Pixar
first develops a sketched-out version of the movie using
storyboards; animators frequently provide the voices just to test
out the plot twists and dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ranft, the head of Pixar's storyboard department, said that
one of the animators suggested that the caterpillar would sound
funny if he had a German accent. Almost instantly, Ranft said, he
started blurting out Heimlich's lines with a heavy accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just popped out of my mouth,'' Ranft said. ``Ohhhh, I et
too much. Oh, my schtomach!''
</P>
<P>
   Once Pixar began work on the real movie, a number of actors
auditioned for Heimlich's voice, but Lasseter said he was not
satisfied, so he ended up making a tape that was half Ranft's voice
and half a professional actor's. He played the tape for his wife,
he said, and she giggled every time Ranft did a line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him the part the next day,'' Lasseter said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuck and Roll, acrobatic brothers, evolved enormously after
McShane was chosen as their voice and began to transform them into
cheerful performers almost completely oblivious to what was
happening around them, reflected in their ability to chatter with
great sincerity but no discernible meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice started out as Hungarian and we all agreed on that,
but then it rapidly devolved into gobbledy-gooseky,'' McShane said.
``It was nonsense, but there was a beginning and an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of their interaction involves the older brother, Tuck,
scolding his sibling nonsensically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuck is older by a few milliseconds, we decided, and he's the
bossy one,'' McShane said. He added that he was aided by his
training in improvisational comedy, in which he had to do entire
scenes talking gibberish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't plan on the dialogue turning into gibberish, but
when we played around with it that's who those guys were,'' McShane
said. ``They're performing bugs, after all.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood generally believes you're supposed to laugh over the
holidays, or at the least enjoy some light entertainment. And who
better to deliver such a pleasant frisson than Chris Columbus
(left), the director of ticklish fare like ``Mrs. Doubtfire'' and
``Home Alone''?
</P>
<P>
   Think again. Columbus' offering for the season is ``Stepmom,''
an adult drama that stars Ed Harris, Julia Roberts and Susan
Sarandon, and opens on Christmas Day. Columbia Pictures, which has
had a decidedly mediocre year, is placing great hopes on this $50
million picture. But be forewarned, keep some Kleenex handy _ a lot
of Kleenex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepmom'' is reminiscent of ``Terms of Endearment,'' but
without loopy characters like Jack Nicholson and Shirley MacLaine
and their antics. It is an earnest examination of how a divorced
couple, Harris and Ms. Sarandon, and their children come to terms
with the father's girlfriend, then wife, played by Ms. Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   The story, which does have some decidedly comic touches, follows
their emotional journey from one wrenching moment of truth to
another and then goes into emotional overdrive when Jackie, the
mother, discovers she has cancer.
</P>
<P>
   She has to come to terms with the role the stepmother will play
in the lives of her children, while Ms. Roberts' character, Isabel,
who has said she never wanted children, has to make her peace with
the fact that she will always play second fiddle to Jackie in the
minds of her stepchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus ends the film with a dedication to his mother, Irene
Columbus, who died of cancer several years ago. He said he first
saw the script, initially titled ``Goodnight Moon'' and written by
Gigi Levangie, a couple of months after his mother died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `I don't want to go there.' It was too hard, so I
passed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later the script went through some rewriting by Ron Bass, and
Columbus saw it again. This time, he said, he was more prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to work out my own personal demons and this seemed like
a way to do it,'' he said, adding, ``It's not necessarily a
goodbye, but certainly this is a picture I made for my mother. It's
about loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbus, who started as a screenwriter (``Young Sherlock
Holmes,'' ``Heartbreak Hotel'' and ``Gremlins'') said he did a
great deal of rewriting of ``Stepmom.'' But he said the writing
became unusually collaborative, with the main actors all
contributing enormously to shaping the dialogue in some important
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, an unusual proposal scene, in which Harris uses a
piece of thread tied around Ms. Roberts' finger in asking her to
marry him, came from Harris and Ms. Roberts, Columbus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed had gone to this wedding for the weekend during rehearsals,
and he just came back with this speech scrawled on about 10
cocktail napkins,'' Columbus said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Few movies could be more different than ``Saving Private Ryan''
and ``There's Something About Mary,'' but both demonstrate why this
has been such an unusual year in the movie business. Supposed niche
films have tended to do best, with the greatest financial successes
enjoyed by films made on more moderate budgets rather than
blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   According to Exhibitor Relations, which collects box office
data, total domestic box office receipts are likely to set a record
this year, with slightly more than $7 billion expected, up from
$6.36 billion last year, the old record.
</P>
<P>
   The total for the first 11 months of the year stood at $6.35
billion, up 9 percent from the same period last year. Foreign
receipts are likely to come in at about the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean it has been the most profitable year.
``Godzilla,'' which cost upward of $200 million to produce and
market, earned just $136 million domestically. Even ``Armageddon,''
the year's leader with $202 million in domestic revenues, may not
be hugely profitable because it also cost some $200 million to
produce and distribute. There has not been, in short, anything like
the hugely profitable ``Titanic'' or ``Lost World'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several less expensive films did make a profit. ``Saving
Private Ryan'' cost about $65 million to produce and has earned
$190 million, while ``There's Something About Mary,'' starring
Cameron Diaz, cost some $25 million and has taken in $172 million.
Similar profitable surprises have been ``Dr. Dolittle,'' ``Rush
Hour'' and ``The Water Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's healthier when it's spread around on a lot of smaller
movies rather than focused on one or two movies,'' said Terry
Press, the head of marketing for Dreamworks, which produced
``Saving Private Ryan.'' ``It's only when the nasty head of
profitability rises up that you have the problem because most
movies still cost too much to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dergarabebian, the president of Exhibitor Relations, said:
``This is good for the audience, even if profits for the industry
are down. There are a lot of good films, a lot of crowd pleasers,
not just one or two. These are movies for the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
