<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1677 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DREXLER-HNS &LR;      12-03 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DREXLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH DREXLER, HOUSTON MAY NOT HAVE A PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JORGE L. ORTIZ  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After a 15-year NBA career that included a world
championship, 10 All-Star Game selections and the honor of being
chosen as one of the 50 greatest players of all time, Clyde Drexler
had a pretty clear notion what he wanted to do in retirement:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be on about the 10th green right now, heading out the back
nine, trying to shoot a 72.''
</P>
<P>
   The dreams of relaxed accomplishment on the links were
interrupted when his alma mater came calling. The University of
Houston Cougars, who went a combined 20-36 in the last two years,
desperately needed a savior.
</P>
<P>
   In glided Drexler, taking over the program with nary a coaching
day in his resume.
</P>
<P>
   The results so far have been stunning, and they go far beyond
the 3-2 mark the Cougars bring into Thursday night's game against
the University of California at Berkeley (2-1) in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   After inspiring nothing but apathy for years, Houston has sold
out the 8,479-seat Hofheinz Pavilion for the season, including 24
new luxury boxes (at $15,000 per season for three years).
</P>
<P>
   Though still predicted to finish at the bottom of the Conference
USA standings, the Cougars and their charismatic coach are suddenly
the object of countless newspaper stories. And one of the nation's
top junior college players, George Gervin Jr., better known as Gee,
decided the once-moribund program was just the place for him after
Drexler came on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much of an impact as I expected Clyde to have, as much of a
positive as I knew he would be for us, there's no way I saw it
coming,'' Houston athletic director Chet Gladchuk told the Houston
Chronicle. ``I'm still amazed at what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly the result of Drexler's desire to give back to the
school from where his career took off. He even has a couple of his
old Phi Slamma Jamma cohorts on staff, assistant coach Reid Gettys
and strength and conditioning coach Michael Young. Another former
Cougars (and Rockets) teammate, Hakeem Olajuwon, has bought one of
the luxury boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program was in dire straits,'' said Drexler, who signed a
four-year deal for a total of $1.2 million, a fraction of his
yearly salary as a player. ``It was a nationally recognized
program, and to have it not remain respectable was tough to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Skepticism ran rampant last March when Houston tabbed Drexler,
and there's no certainty he'll make the transition to the bench as
easily as his contemporary Larry Bird did with the Pacers. But just
like Bird, Drexler commands instant respect from the players
because of his Hall of Fame credentials.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he's even had to tell them not to be too awed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first they're almost afraid to play in front of you because
they don't want to look stupid,'' said Drexler, 36. ``So you have
to get them to relax and play their game.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports history is littered with names of star players who failed
as coaches or managers. The physical abilities that made them so
successful mean nothing on the bench, and the competitive spirit
that drove them only augments the frustration of losing.
</P>
<P>
   Handing a downtrodden program _ one that also lost its top two
players from last year's 9-20 squad _ to a neophyte coach who knew
nothing but success as a player would seem ill-advised.
</P>
<P>
   However, Young, a journeyman player as a pro, believes his good
friend is up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clyde will know what he can reasonably expect from his guys,''
Young said. ``He's not going to demand or expect more than his
players can deliver, but they are expected to deliver as much as
they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Drexler is taking his return to school quite literally. He
intends to sign up for a couple of courses next spring to start
making up the 30-40 credits he said he still needs to complete his
degree in education. As the coach, Drexler figures he should set an
example.
</P>
<P>
   ``By finishing what I started, I can make a statement,'' he
said. ``I want the kids to know not going to school is not an
option.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
