<HEADER>
A1776 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-BERRY-BOS &LR;      12-03 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-BERRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WINTER, THERE'S BEAUTY IN THE BERRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roses still bloomed recently, the small pink blossoms of ``The
Fairy,'' an occasional perfect yellow rose on the ``Golden
Showers'' climber, and not long ago three deep pink, scented
beauties on the ``Zephirine Drouhin.''
</P>
<P>
   Those last were quickly snapped off by my wife and brought
inside, adorning our living room from a vase. I hate to cut
flowers, but those were doomed, for cold was coming, as this is not
really a time for roses. What is it that, post-foliage, is the
bee's knees?
</P>
<P>
   Why, it's the berries.
</P>
<P>
   The berries of autumn are botanically and ornamentally the fruit
of summer. They provide interest from fall through, in some cases,
late winter and early spring. They look lovely in the landscape;
they are fetching in interior arrangements. Many attract birds.
</P>
<P>
   We have a lot of autumn berries, though for the most part I did
not plan it that way.
</P>
<P>
   I certainly did not plan to have berries on our Euonymus
fortunei ``Emerald Surprise'' for the very good reason that I did
not plant our four. They were here when we moved in nearly 10 years
ago. But I am glad to have them. They form very hardy evergreen
shrubs and even vine up, and help hide, a chain-link fence. Amid
the green and creamy white leaves nestle quarter-inch, pale orange
berries emerging from fleshy whitish casings. I like them, but I
wouldn't call them beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   For beautiful, you cannot deny beautyberry. I have two, both
sporting the most incredible electric, metallic purple berries,
about three-sixteenths of an inch in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   One is Callicarpa japonica, and the other is supposed to be
Callicarpa dichotoma, which is reported to be smaller but in this
case seems to be bigger, leading me to suspect it is really
Callicarpa americana. Anyway, they are roughly the same, one being
three feet high and four feet wide and absolutely festooned with
clusters of berries, the other a good seven feet high by three feet
wide, and not as well-berried. They are next to each other and draw
the eye from across the garden.
</P>
<P>
   The other excellent show we have comes from several
cotoneasters, about which I also am confused. (I hereby resolve,
firmly, to compile a detailed, accurate, thorough plant list this
winter, and I shall not misplace it!)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, to help tie our long, shallow roadside bed together, I
spotted four Cotoneaster apiculatus, known as cranberry cotoneaster
for the color and size of the berries, at intervals along the bed.
These are now thick with berries on branches 18 inches high and
spreading horizontally like fish bones.
</P>
<P>
   I confess that I had intended these four-foot-wide plants to be
Cotoneaster adpressus, which I don't think would have worked as
well, then decided I really had gotten praecox, but now believe
these to be apiculatus. I vaguely recall a mixup at the nursery,
but since I didn't jot things down at the time, the facts have
dissolved into the ether of my mind. On the other hand, I do have
an apiculatus out back, and it does not seem to be of similar
habit, that one being smaller and more contorted. There is another
cotoneaster by the pool, spreading six feet and sprawling onto a
concrete walkway. Its red berries are sort of lost in burgundy
leaves, and I have not bothered to identify this plant.
</P>
<P>
   I know just what the holly is that finally is sporting some
berries this year. It is Ilex meserveae ``China Girl'' and has been
pollinated by an adjacent ``Blue Prince.'' These are out back in
the Lucy Garden. Lucy is our 120-pound Newfoundland dog, and that
should explain some of the difficulty growing things in her special
plot. Shade and maple roots explain the other difficulties. The
``China Girl'' is now two feet high and two feet wide and has
glowing, reddish pink berries about three-eighths inch in diameter.
Eventually, it and the male will fill the small area off the deck
in front of some sunroom windows. It will make a nice winter
accent, the berries amid glossy, deep green leaves, perhaps dusted
with snow.
</P>
<P>
   Another choice plant is Euonymus alata ``Compacta,'' winged
euonymus or burning bush. As it drops its flaming red foliage, its
quarter-inch berries, red with orange tones, become apparent. They
hang singly from four-sided branches, the ``sides'' formed by corky
ridges. The ``Compacta'' is the right one for a house lot like
ours. We have two at the head of the driveway. butting against
peonies.
</P>
<P>
   A not-so-choice plant is Rosa multiflora, which sports orangy
berries, about three-eighths of an inch in diameter. These have
spread across our back hill, and one I let go next to an otherwise
civilized planting has become a seven-foot-high, 10-foot-wide,
sprawling fountain of prickly horror. Still, they provide cover for
birds, and it is lovely to see a bright red male cardinal bouncing
up and down on a cane.
</P>
<P>
   There are other berries.
</P>
<P>
   Lily of the valley, Convallaria majalis, still has a few
three-eighths-inch pale red berries sticking up on stalks maybe
eight inches high.
</P>
<P>
   Two yews, Taxus x media ``Hicksii,'' have fleshy, translucent
red berry cones. Ours are six feet high and four feet wide. They
grow upright and are almost architectural. The berries are about
the size of a pea, open at one end, with a naked seed visible
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Other ``berries'' are found on some sprawling junipers out back.
These are blue and not really berries, of course, but then neither
are the yews. But I include them as berries anyway, as I do the
rose hips on the now naked canes of the climbing rose ``Golden
Showers.'' The hips now are green and tomatoey red/orange, one to
one-and-a-half inches in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Until recent cold nights put an end to it, there still were
occasional blooms, reminding us that summer flowers bring fall
showers of berries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
