<HEADER>
A1778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      12-03 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEL-LO? IT'S A JUNGLE OUT THERE, IN CASE NO ONE TOLD YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Bug's Life  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Dave Foley, Kevin Spacey, Julia
Louis-Dreyfus, Hayden Panettiere, Phyllis Diller, Madeline Kahn,
others &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Lasseter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 94 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Though considerably outnumbered, some bully-boy grasshoppers
intimidate a hard-pressed colony of ants into providing food. One
eager beaver of an ant named Flik comes up with a mechanized seed
gatherer but, after innocently causing havoc, gets sent away to
keep him from causing further trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Still determined to help his fellows, Flik meets a troupe of
insect entertainers who maintain they can knock 'em dead. Flik
brings them back to the colony, where it is hoped that is exactly
what they will do to the grasshoppers.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, though, the bugs were referring to their
prowess as performers, not their combat skills. The grasshoppers,
who party hard Mexican style, aren't impressed. But young Flik and
his new friends lead the ants to a revelation: There are a lot more
of them than there are of the other guys.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE The grasshoppers send the ants scurrying, but the
scuffling is cartoon style. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE This is a computer-animated film by Pixar, which made
``Toy Story.'' The film follows ``Antz,'' the first ant epic of the
season, but this adventure is lighter and more geared to small
children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 They will be thoroughly involved with the movie, and
there is nothing that should upset them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-8 Just right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-11 Younger children in this group will be caught up. Many
of the older ones will have moved on.
</P>
<P>
   The Rugrats Movie &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of E.G. Daily, Tim Curry, Christine Cavanaugh,
Kath Soucie, Tara Charendoff, Cheryl Chase, others &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Norton Virgien and Igor Kovalyov &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Scarcely out of the Lipschitz Maternity Arts Building, the
aggressively self-involved newborn Dylan Preston (Dil) Pickles has
the Rugrats (his siblings and their neighborhood pals from the
Nickelodeon show) in an uproar. So when it's suggested that he be
returned to the baby store, no one objects strenuously.
</P>
<P>
   With Grandpa asleep at his baby-sitting post (he slept through
Pearl Harbor, Dil's mother notes later), the Rugrats start out in a
talking wagon called Reptar. One swift mishap later and everybody
winds up in a mattress truck that crashes in the forest. The media
descend. A rumor circulates that the children have been shipped to
Tokyo in a crate. There's a drooling wolf and a group of creepy
baboons from the Banana Brothers Circus, who hijack a train and
crack it up in the same stretch of wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   The lost little ones trod on gamely, do much soul searching and
look for somebody, anybody, in a wizard's pointed hat who will
grant them their wish to go home. Parents search, as does Angelica,
the Pickles' cranky older sister, who's dragged through the
underbrush by an ardent bloodhound.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Dad Pickles, a part-time inventor who can burst into
tears faster than the tots, joins the hunt in his homemade plane,
which resembles a pterodactyl. It's left to the bloodhound to take
on the wolf.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE There is plenty of rough and tumble but nothing too
scary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE In keeping with other animated films, this one employs
some big names _ Beck, Jakob Dylan, Patti Smith, Laurie Anderson _
to chime in on some snappy tunes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 This is a busy and talkative movie with some ruminative
passages here and there. Very little ones won't keep up with the
finer points, but that may not matter much, given the appeal of the
characters and story. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-8 They'll love it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-11 Rugrats fans will be solidly locked into the action
and repartee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP Hey, these are the Rugrats. Many teen-agers will
still be interested (and not a few adults).
</P>
<P>
   Babe: Pig in the City &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Magda Szubanski, James Cromwell, Mary Stein, Mickey Rooney, with
the voices of E.G. Daily, Danny Mann, Glenne Headly, Steven Wright,
James Cosmo, Ralph Ross, others &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by George Miller &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   With Farmer Hoggett (Cromwell) in traction after a fall down a
well, the suits from the bank show up to repossess the family
spread. Since Babe the pig is remembered for his sheepherding feats
in the hit forerunner of this sequel, Mrs. Hoggett (Ms. Szubanski)
figures he might be a pretty good draw in the big city.
</P>
<P>
   Having inadvertently caused Hoggett's accident, Babe, sweet soul
that he is, wants to do anything he can to make it up to the other
animals. But on arrival in the big town (a visually arresting but
huge and threatening amalgam of New York, Los Angeles and other
cities), a drug-sniffing dog targets Babe, which lands Mrs. Hoggett
in custody and leaves the pig on his own in a weird neighborhood
that resembles Venice.
</P>
<P>
   There he takes up residence in the Flealands Hotel, which teems
with dogs, cats and monkeys all keeping a low profile lest they be
turned in by the animal-hating opera lover across the canal. In
relatively short order, Babe plays harmonica for a chimpanzee
minstrel show, is anointed leader of the animals by a pit bull whom
he saves from drowning and organizes a revenue-generating disco at
the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But the opera lover blows the whistle, and the animals are
rounded up by a police squad not that concerned by possible
brutality charges. That sets up the day to be saved by Mrs.
Hoggett, who has her case dismissed and, tethered to a long elastic
cord, bounces about scattering the city's elite.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Various incidents _ Hoggett's accident, the pit bull's
near drowning, a duck caught in a shooting gallery, the rounding up
of the animals by the police _ have a violent connotation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 ``You can't soft-pedal, especially with kids,'' Miller,
the director, says in the production notes. The film has an
unusually dark side for a G-rated film, which may disturb some very
young children. But much will just pass over their heads. That
said, they will enjoy the animals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-8 Most children this age should understand the film and
not be too taken aback by the unsunnier turns of events. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-11 By this age, the film's content and tone shouldn't be
a problem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP Chris Noonan's ``Babe'' charmed many adults. This
film won't, and it has limited appeal for teen-agers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
