<HEADER>
A1783 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-GADJO04-COX     12-03 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-GADJO04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A glimpse of things on society's fringes
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Gadjo Dilo,'' the title of the third installment in Tony
Gatlif's Gypsy-themed trilogy, translates as ``crazy outsider.''
Which is precisely how a young Parisian named Stephane (Romain
Duris) strikes the Gypsy community he joins in snowy Romania.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane is on a mission _ to find the mysterious Gypsy singer
whose voice once entranced his late father. While traipsing through
the wintry countryside, playing his father's tape to anyone who'll
listen, Stephane encounters an elderly Gypsy named Izador (Izador
Serban). He's very friendly. And very, very drunk. Izador
``adopts'' Stephane and soon the ``crazy outsider'' is living the
Gypsy life, which, as presented here, offers lots of music, dance
and vodka.
</P>
<P>
   However, the darker side of being a Gypsy is also portrayed. To
the rest of the world, these colorful wanderers are the ``crazy
outsiders,'' not to be trusted or welcomed (in fact, the Gypsies
were right there with the Jews on Hitler's hit list.) Near the end,
Stephane experiences firsthand how a misunderstanding mixed with
bigotry can become combustible.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is an engaging patchwork that's often more effective
as an anthropological tract than a full-fledged narrative. Scenes
seem self-contained and barely interconnected. The closest the
picture comes to a cohesive plot is the growing attraction between
Stephane and the sultry Sabina (Rona Hartner.) She's the tribe's
designated ``scarlet woman'' _ it has something to do with running
off to Belgium with an inappropriate companion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, once you accept Gatlif's hang-loose style, the material's
intrinsic interest takes hold. We become privy to everything from
the community's celebrations and traditions to its colorful curses
(the subtitles are definitely NC-17.) Most of all, we get a glimpse
of the Gypsies' ancient and inviolate isolation _ an isolation
that's made them targets, true, but has also made them survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gadjo Dilo''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Romain Duris. Directed by Tony Gatlif. Not rated, but
there are sexual situations and NC-17-rated subtitles. 1 hour, 37
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: For those with a little gypsy in their soul.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
