<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-INHERITORS04-C     12-03 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-INHERITORS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nothing idyllic about this life down on the farm
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Inheritors'' starts with one murder and ends with another.
In between, it's occasionally a stirring tale of peasants finding
their self-worth. It's also a mystery. And a sex comedy. What it
isn't is a consistent piece of filmmaking. Though engaging and
well-acted, it never quite seems to figure out its own tone.
</P>
<P>
   The first murder is of a tightfisted farmer named Hillinger. His
passing isn't mourned in the surrounding countryside, least of all
by his long-suffering farmhands. These virtual slaves suffer one
last bit of abuse, as the farmer, in his will, takes pains to
belittle each of them _ much to the delight of the other wealthy
farmers, who assume the dead man's property is now up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Not so. Instead, Hillinger bequeaths it to his seven workers,
with a clause that explains this seemingly generous gesture: ``I
hope they beat each other to death when they fight for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the peasants unite, led by the strong, sexual Emmy
(Sophie Rois) and the cheerful orphan Lukas (Simon Schwarz). Though
the local gentry sneer at them as ``one-seventh farmers,''
ownership turns out to be transformative. First they find the
courage to oust their former foreman (Tilo Pruckner), who tries to
maintain steely control. And when his share of the farm must be
bought out, his former underlings work doubly hard to raise the
funds. (They're secretly helped by other farm workers, inspired by
this vicarious taste of freedom.)
</P>
<P>
   In its middle section, ``The Inheritors'' is full of sweet
moments of newly discovered liberty. The workers have to adjust to
this awkward new concept of ``free time,'' and some of them even
summon the nerve to sit in the front pews of the church, like the
other landowners. But as the established farmers, led by the
glowering Danninger (Ulrich Wildgruber), plot to wrest the land
away from them, the film takes increasingly melodramatic turns. The
ending plays out with a bleakness that seems unrelated to the bulk
of the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Inheritors''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Simon Schwarz, Sophie Rois. Written and directed by
Stefan Ruzowitzky. In German with English subtitles. Unrated, but
contains nudity, sexuality and violence. 1 hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An interesting tale of farm life that goes in too
many directions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
