<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-MONICA-1204-C     12-03 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MONICA-1204-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRITISH TV TO PAY LEWINSKY FOR INTERVIEW
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (e) Entertainment
categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Monica Lewinsky has agreed to tell all to Britons in
early January in a paid-for-TV appearance to be broadcast on an
independent station based in London.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal signed in California late Wednesday night, the former
White House intern embroiled in a sex scandal with President
Clinton agreed to be paid 400,000 pounds -- about US$670,000 -- for
a one-hour, no-holds-barred interview on Britain's Channel 4.
</P>
<P>
   The station announced the deal Thursday and said the interview
will be conducted in the United States sometime in the next few
weeks by Jon Snow, a widely known interviewer in Britain. It is
expected to be aired early next year.
</P>
<P>
   David Lloyd, the station's head of news, current affairs and
business, expressed triumph in announcing the deal after a month of
trans-Atlantic negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real coup for Channel 4,'' Lloyd said. ``Jon Snow is
one of the most respected broadcast journalists in Britain, and his
questions to Monica Lewinsky will be both tough and fair.''
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with the negotiations confirmed the amount to
be paid Lewinsky, who required the station to keep the financial
details secret.
</P>
<P>
   By paying Lewinsky, Channel 4 officials said they believe they
will be assured of her cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say what you like about the journalism of it, but it
does give us a certain amount of freedom,'' said spokesman Martin
Stott. ``As far as we're concerned, there are no editorial limits
to what we can ask her. And Monica Lewinsky has placed no limits on
where we can go with this conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   The station, which purchased worldwide rights to the interview,
intends to recoup much, if not all, of what it pays Lewinsky by
selling the special to TV markets around the world. Even though the
Monica story has been covered in the British media with inescapable
and sometimes tawdry thoroughness, Channel 4 officials are
convinced the topic remains a rich mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective this is a commercial deal,'' Stott said.
``Our initial conversations with broadcasters around the world lead
us to believe that there is a massive amount of interest in Monica
Lewinsky with her telling the story in her own words to the
camera.''
</P>
<P>
   The source familiar with the negotiations said Lewinsky had to
get clearance from Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr before she
could agree to the interview. Her immunity agreement included a
no-talk provision.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast in Britain will follow an interview conducted by a
U.S. network, reportedly ABC featuring Barbara Walters, to be
broadcast in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Channel 4 interview will be produced by Mentorn Barraclough
Carey, the large independent production company behind a searing
three-part series titled ``The Clintons -- A Marriage of Power.''
</P>
<P>
   With her and her family's legal bills and other debts related to
the Clinton affair well in excess of $2 million, Lewinsky and her
representatives have been actively marketing her story to British
broadcasters, who think nothing about paying for such an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Her appearance on an American network would be for free, because
major U.S. networks don't pay for interviews. The Lewinsky camp has
been fielding interview offers for some time, including ones from
Oprah Winfrey and Roseanne Barr, but both foundered.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1733EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     12-03 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: housekeeper (Maslin). 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``HAPPINESS,''  &LR; starring Jane Adams, Dylan Baker, Philip
Seymour Hoffman and Lara Flynn Boyle. Directed by Todd Solondz (not
rated; 135 minutes). In a much bigger film than his ``Welcome to
the Doll House,'' this audacious, deadpan filmmaker explores
loneliness in his murderously funny fashion. Outrageous touches _
none more so than its title _ come easily to ``Happiness,'' and so
do the dark secrets that would surely have brought it an NC-17
rating. No point in cataloging this film's perverse details: What
emerges most clearly is a ruthless yet tender portrait of suburban
characters seeking romance, captured with enough acid precision to
make this a ``Bob and Carol and Ted and Alice'' for totally
dysfunctional times. Ms. Adams plays the dartboard in a
three-sister family with hilarious tremulousness. Baker's gutsy
portrayal of a bland-seeming pederast who is also a respected
doctor and a loving father is impossible to forget (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``HOME FRIES,''  &LR; starring Drew Barrymore. Directed by Dean
Parisot (PG-13, 105 minutes). An absurdist satire of sex, sibling
rivalry, Oedipal ties, homicidal jealousy, fast food and
helicopters in the American heartland, ``Home Fries'' isn't funny
enough in its particulars to make you break up laughing, but at
least it tries for a sophistication beyond the typical gross-out
Hollywood comedy. Most of the humor comes from the collision of
caricatures that suggest refugees from ``Tobacco Road,'' reinvented
for a '90s version of the classic '70s sitcom ``Mary Hartman, Mary
Hartman.'' Ms. Barrymore, who is winsome throughout, plays a very
pregnant server at a burger outlet who falls in love with the
stepson of her recently deceased married lover (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``LIFE IS BEAUTIFUL,''  &LR; directed by and starring Roberto
Benigni (PG-13, 122 minutes). Italy's most antic funnyman dares to
find humor and tenderness in the midst of the Holocaust, and his
risk pays off. This Cannes prize winner is as stubbornly
entertaining as its central character, a Jewish waiter named Guido
who jokes his way through the nightmare for the sake of his loved
ones. Daring also to combine an opening hour of romance and pranks
with a more somber second act, Benigni avoids all traces of the
maudlin and effectively creates a situation in which comedy is
courage. In this unpretentious, enormously likable film, he shines
as a father whose fibs and hilarious buffoonery know no bounds, and
no fear (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``MEET JOE BLACK,''  &LR; starring Brad Pitt, Anthony Hopkins and
Claire Forlani. Directed by Martin Brest (PG-13, 170 minutes).
Hopkins zestily plays a noble tycoon in this otherwise somnolent,
emotion-free, nearly three-hour (!) weepie. And Pitt appears
blankly as Death with blond highlights, serving as a kind of
personal afterlife trainer to the tycoon, whose number is up. Ms.
Forlani plays the big man's beautiful daughter in a story based on
``Death Takes a Holiday.'' In a suffocatingly lavish film that
cries out for a trip to the cutting room, virtually every character
is allowed to overstay his or her welcome, with Pitt especially
diminished by the watching-paint-dry pace. The story drags on so
slowly that there's room for a subplot about party planning, and
several scenes establish how much Death loves peanut butter
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``PLEASANTVILLE,''  &LR; starring Tobey Maguire, Reese Witherspoon,
Joan Allen, William Macy, Don Knotts, J.T. Walsh and Jeff Daniels.
Written and directed by Gary Ross (PG-13, 116 minutes). This
cleverly executed fantasy, with a back-to-the-future trip into the
small-town, squeaky-clean paradise of a 1950s television show,
tends toward the black and white, visually and otherwise. The
missionary zeal with which teen-agers from the 1990s try to awaken
benighted '50s types from their slumber is an attitude that wears
thin. But in the meantime there are witty tricks integrating color
into black-and-white images, and nice little touches abound. The
cast is poignant and amusing, with Ms. Allen especially touching as
a pre-feminist housewife who's the prime recipient of '90s
hindsight (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``VERY BAD THINGS,''  &LR; starring Jon Favreau, Christian Slater,
Cameron Diaz and Daniel Stern. Directed by Peter Berg (R, 100
minutes). A film that means to make the most of black-humored
misanthropy had better be funnier than this mirthless exercise in
witlessness and sadistic humor. Five dull middle-class buddies
accidentally kill a prostitute while at a bachelor party in Las
Vegas, and that's only the beginning of the fun. While it's
possible to share the screenplay's eagerness to see these
unappetizing guys wind up dead, the direction reveals so little
point of view that it doesn't much matter who lives or dies. Ms.
Diaz, so cleverly funny in ``There's Something About Mary,'' plays
a wedding-obsessed ninny this time (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``WAKING NED DEVINE,''  &LR; starring Ian Bannen, David Kelly and
Fionnula Flanagan. Directed by Kirk Jones (PG, 91 minutes).
Delightful shenanigans greet the news of a winning lottery ticket
in a tiny Irish village. Especially after the winner turns out to
be dead. Bannen and Kelly are wonderfully funny as two old coots
who concoct a plot to claim the winnings, and who unite the town's
cast of hearty characters in the process. Jones' prize-winning
career directing television commercials means that everyone here is
an amusing eccentric with colorful quirks, and that the
septuagenarian stars' naked motorcycle-riding scenes are played for
all they're worth. This comedy doesn't have the tart edge of ``The
Full Monty,'' but it knows how to coax laughs from making a
spectacle of elderly gentlemen in the buff (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE WATERBOY,''  &LR; starring Adam Sandler, Kathy Bates and
Fairuza Balk. Directed by Frank Coraci (PG-13, 91 minutes). The
team behind ``The Wedding Singer'' looks like honorary Farrelly
brothers with a comedy that, like ``There's Something About Mary,''
is both cheerfully outlandish and genuinely endearing. Sandler
plays an amazing 31-year-old freshman who morphs from
water-distribution engineer to sports hero, and he succeeds in
doing to football whatever he did to golf in ``Happy Gilmore.''
There's a lot more innocence to his happy-idiot antics here than
there is in many a film made specifically for children. Ms. Bates
is a great hoot as the waterboy's overprotective mama, perfectly in
tune with the film's sneaky sense of fun (Maslin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
