<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARKANSAS-PIES06-COX     12-03 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARKANSAS-PIES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 6
 &HT;    Arkansas baker has a gift for pie _ and fans all across America
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DE VALLS BLUFF, Ark._ You've heard of gardeners who talk to
their plants? Mary Thomas talks to her pies.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, the undisputed pie queen of eastern Arkansas, runs the
Family Pie Shop, an out-of-the-way bakery in this blink-and-miss-it
town between Memphis and Little Rock. She works long hours alone,
which probably explains why she talks to herself and, on occasion,
converses with the pastry.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of nights before Thanksgiving, she opened the oven door
and glared at half a dozen egg custard pies that weren't baking
fast enough to suit her. ``Get done now,'' she instructed them as
if they were children dragging their feet getting ready for school.
``Y'all are holding up the traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, she returned to her flour-dusted countertop. There
were crusts to roll, custards to mix, sweet potatoes to peel _
dozens of holiday orders to fill. This time of year, people will go
over the river and through the woods to get their hands on a good
pie.
</P>
<P>
   Pie has always been one of this country's favorite desserts,
derived from the English but by now as American as you-know-what.
Southern cooks have put a distinctive exclamation point on this
tradition. When you think about the pies associated with this
region _ bourbon pecan pie, Mississippi mud pie, buttermilk lemon
chess pie, to name a few _ you'd have to admit that Southerners
have a weakness for desserts that talk loud and smile big. We like
the last course to have personality.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders are amused by our tendency to go over the top when it
comes to pies. Jane and Michael Stern, the New England couple who
wrote the book on road food, know exactly where to go when they
crave a wedge of something seriously sweet. As they put it, ``We
have eaten Key lime pies in Florida and wild blackberry pies in
Oregon, blueberry pies in Maine and sour cream raisin pies in Iowa,
but the place we like eating pies the best is the South, where love
of sweets (is) a regional obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why people who have never before been to Arkansas know
to stop by Thomas' bakery. Some years back, the Sterns were driving
down U.S. 70, across the flat, chocolatey soil of the Delta, when
they happened upon the Family Pie Shop. They listed it in one of
their guidebooks, and salivating travelers haven't stopped
detouring off I-40.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is whipping meringue when the screen door flies open and
in walks a couple headed from Houston to Indianapolis for
Thanksgiving. ``We just love to eat,'' say Morton and Marie Large
(no wisecracks, please) as they shovel into a chocolate cream pie.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the screen door whaps again and Terry
Presley of Huntsville, Texas, appears with a cooler and an order
for three pies and six fried pies. She's doing research of a sort.
``I pride myself on my pies,'' she says. ``I mean, I never use a
frozen pie shell, because if you aren't going to make a crust,
what's the point? You're just making pudding. I'm here because my
brother told me that this place makes a better coconut pie than I
do. I told him, `Thanks a lot _ how do I get there?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonder anyone finds the place. The bakery is behind
Thomas' modest brick home, in a cinderblock building that used to
be her husband's workshop. The only clue that it's a business is
``PIE SHOP'' spray-painted on the wall in uneven letters, looking
less like a sign than a polite act of graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, there's a cramped dining room with three stools, two
card tables and a church calendar. The kitchen, on the other side
of a pass-through window, has a plastic garbage can full of sugar
and a battered black stove that looks like it ought to be in a
living-history museum. Thomas bought it used from a school
cafeteria 20 years ago; it keeps the room so warm that her glasses
keep sliding down her nose, making her look like she's always
raising her eyebrows over something. When she's busy, puttering
around the concrete floor and muttering to herself, every available
surface seems to be covered by pies in various stages of assembly.
The biggest sellers are coconut cream, sweet potato and Karo-nut,
the term she and many other Arkansans use for pecan pie (as if
there were a tree that produced nuts and syrup).
</P>
<P>
   Thomas grew up in a sharecropping family of 13 children and has
been cooking for a living most of her 64 years. She worked for
decades at Craig's, a barbecue joint across the street from her
house, where she became well-known for her pies. In 1977, she and
her husband, a cook on Mississippi River paddlewheelers, opened the
bakery. He died five years later, and she has run the business
since then by herself, with help from her daughter, Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   The two of them have something of a road-food roadblock going on
U.S. 70. Joyce and her husband now manage Craig's, selling mama's
pies and referring customers across the road to the bakery. Mama,
of course, just happens to know a good place for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   One of their best customers, not surprisingly, was a certain
governor. ``I've seen Bill Clinton out there in front of Craig's a
hundred times,'' Thomas says. ``He'd sit in his limousine and send
one of his people in.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of her customers, though, are not just passing through.
They're local people who are just as busy, in their way, as a
governor or a traveler who has to make Memphis by nightfall. Thomas
knows who pays her bills. ``I make pies for ladies who work in
factories and don't have time to make pies,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But there's at least one working lady in town she doesn't make
pies for: herself. Thomas will nibble at peach cobbler, but she
never much liked pie. She'd rather eat cake.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, did she fashion a career out of making other people's
pies?
</P>
<P>
   She breaks into a grin and runs her thumbs across her
fingertips. ``Money, money, money,'' she says. When you grow up
sharecropping, what you want out of life more than anything else is
a piece of the pie _ and she doesn't mean sweet potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
