<HEADER>
A1798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARKANSAS-PIES-RECIPES     12-03 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARKANSAS-PIES-RECIPES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 6
 &HT;    Pie lovers, check out these regional favorites
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asking Mary Thomas for a recipe is like pumping a three-star
general for information about troop strength. Her lips are zipped.
One time, she remembers, a Memphis reporter drove over to De Valls
Bluff, Ark., on an apparent mission to reveal the secrets of the
Family Pie Shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her she could keep asking slick questions all day long,
but I wasn't going to be tricked,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And she still isn't talking. The only secret we learned was that
she uses shortening, not butter, in her indescribably flaky crust.
Fortunately, other pie makers are more forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Burnt Sugar (Butterscotch) Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 1 hour Baking time: 10
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Irene Wassell, food editor of the Arkansas Democrat-Gazette,
grew up in a family of dedicated pie eaters where it wasn't
uncommon for the six of them to polish off three pies in one
sitting. This recipe, from her book ``Best of Irene Wassell,'' is a
Depression-era pie that her mother made when chocolate and coconut
weren't always
</P>
<P>
   plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 3/4 cup plus
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons granulated sugar, divided use
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk, divided use
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 (9-inch) pie crust, baked
</P>
<P>
   Place egg yolks in a small bowl, and the whites in the small
bowl of an electric mixer; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy skillet, heat 1/2 cup sugar until it melts and is a
light caramel color. Slowly pour about 1 cup of the milk into the
melted sugar. The sugar may crystallize; stir and continue heating
until the sugar dissolves.
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy saucepan, combine remaining 1 cup milk, 3/4 cup
sugar, the cornstarch and salt. Stir until cornstarch dissolves.
Add caramelized sugar and cook over medium heat, stirring, until
mixture thickens.
</P>
<P>
   Dip a few spoonfuls of the thickened mixture, one spoonful at a
time, into the egg yolks and mix well. Stir egg yolk mixture into
thickened mixture. Cook slowly 3 to 4 minutes more. Remove from
heat and add butter and vanilla; stir until butter melts. Pour into
baked pie crust.
</P>
<P>
   Beat egg whites until soft peaks form. Add the remaining 2
tablespoons sugar and beat until stiff peaks form. Spread evenly on
top of pie filling and bake at 350 degrees until golden brown,
about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cool before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 361 calories, 6 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 36), 52 grams carbohydrates, 96
milligrams cholesterol, 243 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Miracle Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Baking time: 60
minutes
</P>
<P>
   There are two reasons for the name. First, it's one of those
crustless pies that miraculously forms its own shell while baking.
Second, it's one of those recipes, such as Scripture Cake, in which
each ingredient can be found in a Bible verse. (Except for vanilla
extract, which apparently does not appear in the Good Book.) From
the Georgia Agriculture Department cookbook ``The Best of Georgia
Farms.''
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Jeremiah 6:20
</P>
<P>
   (granulated sugar)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Genesis 18:8 (butter)
</P>
<P>
   4 Deuteronomy 22:6 (eggs)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup 2 Kings 7:18
</P>
<P>
   (all-purpose flour)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Hebrew 5:13 (milk)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Genesis 43:11 (coconut)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Matthew 5:13 (salt)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon 2 Kings 23:15 (baking powder)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Put all ingredients into a blender.
Blend thoroughly. Pour into a 10-inch pie plate that has been
greased and floured. Bake for 60 minutes. A crust will form on the
bottom, with pie filling in the center and a coconut topping above.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 240 calories, 6 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 31), 36 grams carbohydrates, 115 milligrams
cholesterol, 184 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Skillet Pecan Fudge Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings Preparation time: 25-30 minutes Cooking time:
40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The South's most famous pie has to be pecan. Some chefs try to
make it less cloyingly sweet by using darker syrups or cutting down
on the syrup altogether. Other chefs take the opposite tack and
pile on the yummy stuff. Tim Patridge, director of the food and
beverage program at Morris Brown College, falls into the second
group with this family recipe, which he remembers from his Georgia
childhood. And, please, no chopped-up nuts. ``I use pecan halves,
not those chopped-up things that get caught in your teeth,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   1 favorite recipe for double-crust pie pastry (do not divide)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound chocolate fudge, store bought or made according to
your favorite recipe (broken into 1/2-inch square chunks)
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups dark cane syrup
</P>
<P>
   Cast iron skillet (preferably 10 inches across and
</P>
<P>
   2 inches deep)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Roll out pie crust 1/4 inch thick
and line iron skillet with it. Crimp edges in decorative pattern.
Place pecan halves and chocolate fudge pieces into skillet.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, cream the butter and sugar. Add beaten eggs to
sugar mixture. Sift cornstarch and salt into mixture. Stir in
vanilla. Blend in syrup and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Pour over pecans and chocolate in skillet. Bake for about 40
minutes until set and crust is golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 656 calories, 7 grams protein, 45 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 62), 64 grams carbohydrates, 105
milligrams cholesterol, 241 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
