<P>
   SHUTTLE LAUNCH
</P>
<P>
   PBP-SHUTTLE (DEVELOPING) _ CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Two seconds.
That's how close NASA came to launching shuttle Endeavour Thursday
morning. NASA hoped to try again early today (FRIDAY) to launch
Endeavour after a last-minute cockpit alarm caused launch
controllers to scrub a pre-dawn lift-off Thursday, space agency
officials said. Endeavour's mission is to rendezvous with an
unmanned Russian power station that is already in orbit to begin
construction of the $60 billion International Space Station. Launch
Director Ralph Roe stopped the countdown as time ran out on a
narrow 10-minute window in which the shuttle must launch each day
or miss the Russian Zarya by miles. ``We missed the performance
window by between one and two seconds,'' Roe told a news
conference. (Pounds, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   DDN-COX-CURRIE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Nancy Currie's try to get into
space was scrubbed early Thursday and is now scheduled for 3:36
a.m. on Friday. Tim reports on what happened and the preparation
for Friday. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
