<HEADER>
A1822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ESPY-NYT &LR;      12-03 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ESPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE ESPY VERDICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Dec. 3:
</P>
<P>
   Former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy's acquittal by a jury on
corruption charges was not unexpected. The criminal case brought by
independent counsel Donald Smaltz was based on Espy's acceptance of
sports tickets, plane trips and luggage from food companies that he
regulated. But the value of the gifts totaled about $35,000, and
there was no evidence that Espy had made decisions favorable to the
companies because of the gratuities he received.
</P>
<P>
   Federal statutes that prohibit government officials from
accepting gifts do not require the showing of any quid pro quo. But
Espy argued that the gifts came from longtime personal friends,
which is allowed under the gratuities law. The tangle of
circumstances and the seemingly incidental value of some of the
favors worked against the prosecution. Indeed, the defense was so
confident in its position that it called no witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict does not mean that investigating Espy's conduct was
not proper and necessary or that he should not have been forced out
of office. But the trial's outcome does call into question how well
Smaltz conducted the investigation, which has cost $17 million over
four years. While he has achieved multiple convictions and $11.5
million in fines and penalties, they mostly involve those who gave
the gratuities. This case will probably be used by critics of the
Independent Counsel Act to justify changes to the act to limit the
time and cost of such investigations. Such reforms will have to be
fully debated by Congress, balanced against the need to maintain a
way to hold high-ranking officials accountable for their conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Espy, who was forced to resign from the Cabinet in 1994, brought
these troubles on himself when he apparently adopted the attitude
that he could ignore the federal gratuities law. Before joining the
Clinton administration he spent six years in the House, where gifts
and favors from special interests flowed freely. Carol Browner, the
head of the Environmental Protection Agency, testified at the trial
that Espy said he thought the ethics code that applies to the
executive branch was ``a bunch of junk.'' Others in the
administration find themselves under similar legal scrutiny because
they also seem to believe that the law did not apply to them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1741EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN04-COX     12-03 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    They'll take tree lights now, memories later
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you move, you break things, no matter what the signs say on
the big moving vans.
</P>
<P>
   The little boys in our family didn't care about the Spode
plates, for which their mother grieved, but they are plenty put out
because a whole box of Christmas ornaments crashed. They came to
the country on Thanksgiving hoping to trudge through woods, which
we now have in short supply, and spot a Christmas tree. But what is
a tree without Christmas pretties?
</P>
<P>
   Their mother very practically mentioned popcorn and cranberry
chains, but I could see in their young faces the shine of silver
and gold and red and green glass ornaments and chains of lights.
Their mother at their age held out for Christmas lights that
bubbled and twirled. Now I looked at the boys and decided I didn't
care if I had any kind of light on Sweet Apple's tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go to the basement and look for stuff,'' I suggested.
</P>
<P>
   And they went with alacrity. It was dusty, and many an old angel
was stained and warped. But they touched everything I hauled out of
the ornament box with a kind of reverence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you giving us this?'' the little one whispered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have all the lights and all the glass ornaments except
. . .'' I faltered. There is a red bird with a woozy tail that has
always been on my tree. ``Except,'' I said, ``the very old ones. I
want to keep the ones that people gave me or my children made when
they were your size.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a deal, they said. The ones I cling to aren't the
spectacular ones, of course. They're homemade and saggy with age.
An owl we've had for years, a frowzy dwarf with a Christmas wreath
over his shoulder, little felt animals made by children's hands.
There is a tiny music box that never made music. The older one, who
can fix anything, puttered with it a moment and, lo and behold, it
tinkled out a Christmas
</P>
<P>
   carol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take it,'' I said. ``You deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   The old angel we bought at Kress's at 10th Street during World
War II surfaced, and I clutched it to my heart. It was a funny
Christmas, that old one, with people we loved fighting overseas,
and rationing, and not many Christmas doodads in the stores. The
angel wasn't a grand one, a sort of token angel glued to a paper
cone, which would fit over the topmost branch of the tree. But we
thought she was lovely, and she has been on every Christmas tree
we've had since, getting more ragged and dusty as the years have
gone by.
</P>
<P>
   The little boys were interested in the candleholders that pinch
on tree branches like clothespins. Could they have them?
</P>
<P>
   Not this year, I said. Someday, when I have retired from the
Christmas tree fete and feel they are old enough to light the
little stubby candles safely. I held one in my hand and thought of
the old friends who pulled them out of their attics and sent them
to me when they learned that I was going to live in a log cabin. We
have a custom of lighting the candles with a bucket of water nearby
_ and only for the duration of one verse of ``Silent Night.''
</P>
<P>
   There was an angel with a broken arm and a Santa backed up to a
black stove. They were gifts from our neighbors when I fell off a
ladder and went through Christmas with my arm in a sling. The Santa
was my husband's, a reminder that he kept the fires going in the
chilly cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Everything reminded me of other years and other people, but the
little boys were content with strings of lights wound around rolls
of newspaper, with glass ornaments and a string of gold tinsel.
They said their thanks as they raced up the basement stairs, and I
called my thanks after them. It's good to have an excuse to sit in
the dusty basement and remember.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
