<SLUG> BC-PAJAMAS-WARNING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH: Tight-fitting sleepwear OK for kids, safety agency says
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sleeping in oversize T-shirts could create a firetrap for
children, the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission warns. But
snug-fitting cotton pajamas, previously considered dangerous,
should be OK.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, the agency advised the public that
flame-resistant pajamas were the only safe garments children should
wear to bed. However, those standards were relaxed this year, after
the commission decided that the way pajamas fit is more important
than the fabric they're made of.
</P>
<P>
   ``By fitting close to the skin, you don't have oxygen underneath
that feeds the fire,'' said Ken Giles, a commission spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, up to 300 children are burned by being near a flame _
a space heater, kitchen range or candle, for example _ while
wearing loose-fitting sleepers, the safety commission said. Hence
the warning about loose T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Flame-resistant fabrics, such as polyester, stop burning when
removed from a flame, prompting the agency's earlier warning about
fabric types. Cotton was one fabric the commission used to warn
against, because it can burn rapidly. But Giles said that is not
the case if the cotton garment is tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any burn injuries with snug-fitting cotton,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the new regulations, manufacturers have begun using
new tags on snug-fitting sleepers, indicating they meet federal
safety standards. Labels that say ``Not Intended for Sleepwear''
should still be followed, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
