<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-RACISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS LEADERS' DOCUMENT RIDICULES AUSTIN, TEXAS, AS BEING IN
DENIAL ABOUT ITS RACISM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ This Texas capital city, sometimes ridiculed for its
quirky liberalism, is actually in denial about its innate racism,
according to a remarkable document issued by the white mayor and
signed by 25 religious leaders of different races.
</P>
<P>
   ``White Austinites can no longer deny the reality of racist
laws, institutions, customs and conditioned reflexes,'' according
to the boldly worded ``Commitment to Racial Reconciliation''
drafted by local religious leaders representing a diverse spectrum
of faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be recognized that the continuing reality of racist
attitudes and practices still plagues our community in the present
and will curse our future unless we abandon them now,'' the
three-page statement continued.
</P>
<P>
   Signers of the statement, which was released this week, pledged
to ``repent and seek forgiveness for racist beliefs, attitudes and
behaviors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Sterling Lands, a black pastor at the Greater Calvary
Baptist Church and one framer of the statement, said racism must be
understood in terms of ``the superior group versus the perceived
inferior group'' while ``ignorance and greed is the driving
force.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the statement, written after Mayor Kirk Watson asked
religious leaders to help heal racial divisions, has been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it was ever intended to say that white people
hate black people or anything like that,'' Watson said. ``Instead,
I think it is a call that we need to recognize that there still is
racial prejudice and there is racism.''
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, an anti-affirmative action group blasted the
declaration as ``divisive and horribly misnamed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From reading this document, one would think we are currently
living in the 1950s where there was rampant and immoral government
enforced racial segregation,'' said Marc Levin, executive director
of the group, Campaign for a Color-Blind America.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, a 1998 graduate of the University of Texas, said the only
``overtly racist'' laws in Austin are those that impose racial
quotas in favor of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Mayor Lee Brown did not immediately respond when asked
if he had any comment on the Austin statement.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, the statement was variously praised as a breakthrough
or berated as ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great misconception that Austin is a liberal city ...
It's true a white person knows very little of what a minority
experiences in this red-neck Bubba land,'' commented one e-mail
signed ``me,'' after the Austin-American Statesman invited readers
to post comments on its Website.
</P>
<P>
   Another e-mail that closed with, &UR;  &LR; ``it'll all be sorted out when
we die anyway,'' expressed a commonly heard frustration: ``So,
what's the point? ... You live like a racist, you get labeled a
racist. You don't live like a racist, you get labeled a racist.''
</P>
<P>
   Negative reactions, in particular, are evidence that many whites
in the community do not see racism for what it is, said Larry
Bethune, the white pastor of the University Baptist Church. The
struggling church, a pioneer in fighting racial segregation during
the 1940s, made news earlier this year for welcoming openly gay
Baptists into its fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a history whose effects remain and one of the biggest
problems in dealing with that is the denial by many that such a
problem exists. I think that's been confirmed by a lot of the
reaction I've heard on talk shows and have seen on Web pages,''
Bethune said.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said Thursday he had no regrets about issuing the
document or seeking help from religious leaders on a such a touchy
subject rooted in morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I frankly think it is very difficult to lead on issues like
that when you're raised a white male in Texas. Let's face it,''
said Watson, an attorney and environmentalist who was elected mayor
just last year. He said he's intrigued that some people are
reacting to the statement by demanding measurable results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The religious community appreciates and understands you're not
going to get a measurable result. It addresses issues of hope and
forgiveness and those sorts of issues better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement points out that the city's racial segregation is
most obviously symbolized by Interstate 35, which divides the
disadvantaged east side where most blacks live from the western
half of town where more prosperous whites live. The document
focuses attention on white sins, drafters said, because it defines
racism as racial prejudice combined with power.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he decided to seek some form of reconciliation to
help heal wounds of racial discord from the 1997 city council
election.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he sought to ease bitter feelings still lingering after 80
Austin police and mostly black teen-agers clashed at a 1995
Valentine's Day party in east Austin. Police were cleared of
brutality allegations but Watson and others negotiated a settlement
with the party-goers. It included scholarships, job training and a
review of police training.
</P>
<P>
   Former City Councilman Eric Mitchell, who is black, was not
impressed by the statement of racial reconciliation. He called
Watson an ``insincere political opportunist'' Thursday on the local
``Sammy and Bob'' talk radio show, which specializes in redneck
schtick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying the context in which it is offered sort of damages
the dialogue,'' said Mitchell, who lost re-election to another
black candidate in the 1997 election.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell blamed his defeat on racism after earlier insulting his
opponent Willie Lewis with a racial epithet similar to calling
someone an ``Uncle Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is the only politician who signed the racial
reconciliation document, which many say was meant to be a statement
of spiritual leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who still says white leaders in the city wanted to
silence him for being too strong an advocate for his black
constituents, had also accused liberal environmentalists on the
city council of being racist. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
