<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ISRAEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AGAIN DOWNPLAYS PRESIDENTIAL AMBITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush said Thursday his recent
trip to the Middle East did not push his presidential ambitions one
way or the other and that he remained undecided on whether to seek
the Republican nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has sought to downplay talk about whether he would run for
president, but the three-day trip to Israel, followed by some
veiled criticism from Vice President Al Gore, has done nothing to
squelch the speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't decided yet,'' Bush said a day after returning to
Texas. ``Now is not the time to decide whether I will or will not
seek the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   The newly re-elected governor said he wants to enjoy the
holidays, finish his inauguration speech and prepare the
state-of-the-state address he will deliver to the Legislature next
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, I've got a job to do as governor of this
state,'' Bush told a news conference. ``My job is to get a
legislative agenda through.''
</P>
<P>
   He has said repeatedly he would not decide about running for the
presidency until sometime next year. He is widely viewed as the
leading Republican candidate, with some polls showing the eldest
son of former President George Bush defeating Gore _ the
presumptive Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   During the whirlwind tour, Bush and three other Republican
governors met with Israeli President Ezer Weizman, Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and top Israeli Cabinet ministers. Additionally,
he talked to opposition Labor leader Ehub Barak, and toured
Jerusalem's walled Old City.
</P>
<P>
   The governors also took a helicopter tour with Foreign Minister
Ariel Sharon, but they canceled a trip to a contested West Bank
Jewish settlement, reportedly after being advised to do so by the
U.S. Embassy. The settlements are a major issue of controversy in
effects to reach a lasting peace between the Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was organized by the National Jewish Coalition, a
Republican lobbying group whose views on the peace process are
similar to Netanyahu's conservative government. Bush said the group
tried to arrange a meeting with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
but Arafat was in the United States at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there to listen and learn, and I learned a lot. I
learned a lot about the history of Israel and the history of our
particular religion and the history of religions that are now the
dominant religions of the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He called the trip personal, offering no hint as to what his
policy on the Middle East would be should he become president.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this issue or any other issue related to Israel, the
appropriate time to develop and lay out a comprehensive foreign
policy will be when and if I decide to run for the presidency,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush doesn't yet consider himself a presidential
candidate, he was treated like one Wednesday by Gore, who
criticized the governor's and other Republicans' claims of being
``compassionate conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Compassion is more than a pretty word. There is a long road
between rhetoric and results,'' Gore said in a keynote address to
the Democratic Leadership Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gore is entitled to every opinion he wants to have,'' Bush
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What part does he object to _ the conservative part or the
compassionate part?'' Bush asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
