<HEADER>
A1849 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HOUDINI04-COX     12-03 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HOUDINI04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TNT's `Houdini' robs its subject of any magic
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Real magic would be if TNT turned ``Houdini'' into a movie worth
watching.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when Fox specials show us how a rabbit is pulled from
a hat, ``Houdini'' reveals how a network can take what looks like
an after-school special and turn it into prime-time entertainment.
It transforms the rich, spooky life of our most celebrated magician
into a simple-minded, simply ridiculous biography. It's the kind of
magic that makes viewers disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth be damned,'' Houdini narrates at the start, and
writer/director/executive producer Pen Densham (1996's ``Moll
Flanders'') takes his subject at his word. Despite clumsy nods to
Houdini's complex ego, his wife's complex alcoholism and the
magician's complex relationship with magic, ``Houdini'' is
satisfied with a paint-by-number portrait that, basically, tells us
Houdini had his faults.
</P>
<P>
   It's old-fashioned that way and even a little edgy _ if you're a
9-year-old looking to kill time before doing homework. The early
magic scenes _ a young Houdini pulling a thread and needles from
his mouth _ are indeed magical, enjoying the advantage of not
having to be real.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're not 9 _ say, you're 10 _ you might already assume
that Houdini, like the rest of us, wasn't perfect and hope for
something more.
</P>
<P>
   The movie alternates between a radio broadcast seance held by
the magician's widow (Stacy Edwards) in an effort to reach Houdini
in the great beyond and the unfolding of the magician's life. That
life is a classically inspiring rags-to-riches tale, and Johnathon
Schaech (``That Thing You Do'') as Houdini plays his part with all
the eager-beaver emoting of the lead in your high school play.
</P>
<P>
   Those early years, in which Ehrich Weiss (who adopted the stage
name Harry Houdini from a book he read) and his brother Theo (Mark
Ruffalo) begin a magic act in New York City, are full of such
time-honored slogans as ``Stay in school!'' and ``Take a chance!''
</P>
<P>
   Houdini ignores the first but holds tight to the second.
Struggling as an unmemorable magician, he gets his break in the
form of advice from an agent named Martin Beck, played as if born
for the role by George Segal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've seen everything. You have to jerk them out of their
seats,'' Beck tells Houdini, pushing him toward the kind of
death-defying illusions that would mark his career and end his
life.
</P>
<P>
   When Houdini follows this advice by becoming an escape artist, a
pleased Beck tells him afterward, ``See my lawyers tomorrow.
They'll give you a contract you won't get out of so easily.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the movie shows Houdini's rise and fall _ a rise to
international renown and a fall laid by his audience's
expectations, as well as Houdini's consuming crusade against
mediums who claim to talk to the dead.
</P>
<P>
   The movie never decides whether to enhance or debunk the
magician's self-created myth, so it ends up doing neither. By the
end, you just wish ``Houdini'' would make itself disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
