u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2TAKES-N     12-03 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 14: DEC. 6 AND 7 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNDAY 1:01 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (6-6) AT NEW YORK JETS (8-4)
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback John Kitna, who last week started in place of an
ineffective Warren Moon, guided Seattle to a thrilling
come-from-behind 20-18 victory over Tennessee. Don't look for those
types of heroics against the Jets. Before last week's start, Kitna
had started just two games in two years in Seattle. His head will
be spinning by the time he's finished looking at all the defensive
combinations that Jets defensive coordinator Bill Belichick will
throw his way. The Jets have hit their stride with a multiple
offense that features a rejuvenated Curtis Martin at running back
and two big weapons in receivers Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne
Chrebet. Johnson has a sore hamstring that could limit him in the
game. But it won't stop the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK 31-13.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO (7-5) AT CINCINNATI (2-10)
</P>
<P>
   By the time the game rolls around, the Bills will have had a
week to accept those two awful calls by the officials that led to
their loss to New England last Sunday. Having the opportunity to
beat up on a team like Cincinnati should take some of the sting
away. The Bengals got the practice week off to a rousing start.
Defensive back Tremaine Mack was sentenced to 365 days in jail for
driving under the influence of alcohol in October and is gone for
the season. Quarterback Neil O'Donnell has been inserted back into
the starting lineup, replacing a two-game experiment with Paul
Justin. Justin is back to No. 3, behind Jeff Blake. The Bengals are
in no shape to contend with the angry Bills. BUFFALO 23-10.
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (8-4) AT NEW ORLEANS (5-7)
</P>
<P>
   Dallas goes into this game without either of its starting
cornerbacks. Kevin Smith is out for 2-3 weeks with a back injury
and Deion Sanders has a fractured big toe on his left foot. Things
are so bad for the Cowboys battered secondary that they went out
and re-signed cornerback Larry Brown this week. Brown was Super
Bowl MVP for the Cowboys three years ago, left the team to sign a
free-agent contract (five years, $12.5 million) with Oakland in
1996 and was waived by the Raiders last year. Brown will earn
$76,000, plus a playoff bonus if the team makes it. The Cowboys,
23d in the league in pass defense, have given up 984 yards and nine
touchdowns passing in the last three games, so they can use any
help they can get. The Saints, still clinging to fading playoff
hopes, won't be able to beat Dallas. Coach Mike Ditka is talking
about playing rookies, a sure sign that they're waving the white
flag in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS 19-7.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (5-7) AT JACKSONVILLE (9-3)
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle Tony Boselli is listed as doubtful with a sprained
ankle. Boselli had trouble walking earlier in the week, so there's
a good chance he won't be pushing any Lion defenders around Sunday.
The bad news for Detroit is that Ben Coleman is a capable
replacement. Coleman replaced Boselli last year when he was out
four games with another ankle sprain. The Lions are coming off 10
days rest, after having beaten Pittsburgh with the help of that
botched overtime coin toss on Thanksgiving Day. But they'll be
hurting in the secondary, because free safety Mark Carrier is out
with a strained left foot. The Lions still have an outside chance
of making the playoffs, but the Jaguars will put a damper on their
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE 28-12.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (2-10) AT ATLANTA (10-2)
</P>
<P>
   Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler practiced this week for the
first time since spraining his ankle on Nov. 22 against the Bears
and expects to play against the Colts. The Falcons average 27.1
points a game when Chandler plays. Last week was the first time the
Falcons have won without Chandler at quarterback in the last two
years. Running back Jamal Anderson has been crucial, also.
Indianapolis running back Marshall Faulk has a chance to have 1,000
yards rushing and 1,000 yards receiving this season. He accounts
for 45.8 percent of the Colts net yards and he leads the league in
total yards from scrimmage (1,823). Faulk needs to average 54 yards
receiving in his last four games to reach the milestone. The
Falcons have already clinched a playoff berth, but don't expect
them to take it easy on the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA 33-20.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND (7-5) AT PITTSBURGH (7-5)
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe has been resting his broken right index finger this
week. He needed to. The Patriots have relied upon late touchdown
passes by Bledsoe to pull out victories in their last two games.
New England's rushing attack has averaged just 85 yards in the last
two games. The rookie running back Robert Edwards has been doing a
slow slide. In his first six games he rushed for 483 yards and six
touchdowns. In his last six games he has rushed for 222 yards and
one touchdown. Things don't get any easier against Pittsburgh,
which is No. 9 in the NFL against the run. Last year in the
playoffs, the Patriots shut down Jerome Bettis and dared
quarterback Kordell Stewart to beat them. Pittsburgh won, 7-6. Look
for the Patriots to deploy the same strategy. This time they'll
win.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND 25-17.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (5-7) AT WASHINGTON (3-9)
</P>
<P>
   Redskins president John Kent Cooke said he'll wait until after
the season to decide what to do about Coach Norv Turner and General
Manager Charlie Casserly, if he still owns the team by then. A
group of seven investors has bid $650 million, according to
published reports. If that group is successful, it's unlikely
they'll keep Turner, who is 29-46-1 in five years as Redskins
coach. Running back Terry Allen could return from a sprained ankle
that has sidelined him for four weeks. Unfortunately, it's not in
time to help Turner. In San Diego, Coach June Jones is trying to
get the word interim removed from his title. But the Chargers have
to win impressively in their last few games for that to happen.
Quarterback Craig Whelihan can still help Jones, but he has got to
do better than the five interceptions he threw against Denver last
week. The Chargers have scored 20 points just once this year and
the Redskins are 5-0 against San Diego all-time. San Diego won't
need much to change their history against the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO 19-7.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
