<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: DIEGO 19-7. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (8-3) AT CAROLINA (2-10)
</P>
<P>
   The loss of defensive tackle Bryant Young, who broke the tibia
and fibula against the Giants on Monday night, leaves a gaping hole
in the middle of the 49ers defense. A few of the players are still
shaken by the sight of Young breaking his leg. But San Francisco is
good at making adjustments and focusing on the task at hand. The
49ers are a game back of the Falcons in the NFC West and can't
afford to falter now. The Panthers were stunned by the Jets last
week and won't recover this week. Running back Fred Lane has been
suspended for making an obscene gesture to the fans at Giants
Stadium. His absence won't have any effect on the lowest-ranked
rushing offense in the NFL (72.2 yards a game). He'll be replaced
by Tshimanga Biakabutuka, the 1996 first-round pick, who has 50
yards and 14 carries this season.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO 38-10.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY 4:15 p.m. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK GIANTS (4-7) AT ARIZONA (6-6)
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have spent the week in the desert. Presumably, they
haven't been wandering around trying to find their offense, which
they left in San Francisco. New York failed on three scoring
opportunities inside the 49ers 25 yard line on Monday night. The
Cardinals are a reminder of just how far the Giants have fallen.
New York smashed Arizona, 34-7, earlier this year and have gone 1-4
since. Meanwhile, the Cardinals are talking about making a playoff
run. They have a one-game lead on Detroit, Tampa Bay and New
Orleans for the final NFC wild-card spot. The Cardinals signed
kicker Chris Jacke, the former Packer, to replace Joe Nedney who
tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his knee after a kickoff
against the Chiefs last week. Jacke has made 77.2 percent of his
field goals. The Giants will be left high and dry in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA 27-19.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY (5-7) AT DENVER (12-0)
</P>
<P>
   The last time these two teams played, the Chiefs lost their
composure on the Broncos' final touchdown drive and committed five
personal fouls. Linebacker Derrick Thomas drew a suspension for
yanking on the facemask of Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe. Chiefs
owner Lamar Hunt said the team had disgraced itself and the city.
This has always been a bitter rivalry. In the last four games the
two teams have played, Chiefs players have been fined, dismissed or
suspended. Don't expect things to have cooled down much in this
game. Add to that Denver's unblemished record and run for an
undefeated season and you've got a volatile mixture. The Chiefs
didn't have any answers last time and they don't have any this
time.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER 36-11.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (8-4) AT OAKLAND (7-5)
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders jumped out to a 7-3 record and now they've hit the
skids. This is a scary scenerio for the Raiders, because they can
remember 1995 when they got out to an 8-2 record and didn't win
another game. The signs of trouble are there. During halftime of
their loss to the Redskins last week some Raiders players were
tearing into each other. Quarterback Jeff George, who has been
plagued by a torn groin muscle much of the year, was moving stiffly
in the game last week and was yanked. He didn't complain. George
called it quits for the season Wednesday. The Dolphins will be
without right guard Kevin Donnalley (arthoscopic knee surgery). It
won't hurt. Miami is in the groove right now, tied with the Jets
for first place in the AFC East. They won't lose ground this week.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI 24-10.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (5-7) AT TENNESSEE (6-6)
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers have dim playoff hopes, while the light is flickering
on Ravens coach Ted Marchibroda's tenure in Baltimore. Tennessee is
in much better shape for this game than the Ravens, who will be
without receiver Michael Jackson (shoulder and foot injuries) and
Jermaine Lewis (sprained ankle). The Ravens had averaged just 14
points a game, until they broke out with 38 against Indianapolis
last week. They'll revert to their old form against the Oilers. In
the last meeting between the two teams, Oilers running back Eddie
George rushed for 121 yards and quarterback Steve McNair scored the
game's only touchdown on a 40-yard scramble in a 12-8 Tennessee
victory. The Oilers have the Raven's number.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 17-6.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT 8:20 P.M. GAME
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (3-9) AT MINNESOTA (11-1)
</P>
<P>
   As if things couldn't get any worst for the Bears, quarterback
Erik Kramer, who had been plagued by shoulder problems all year,
had surgery on his rotator cuff on Wednesday and is out for the
season. The rookie Moses Moreno will take over for Kramer. Moreno
started last week against Tampa Bay and was 18-of-41 for 153 yards
and one touchdown. But the Bears had only 69 yards rushing. The
Vikings aren't going to cry for Chicago. They have their own woes.
Running back Robert Smith is out 2-3 weeks with a sprained knee.
The bad news for Chicago is that his backup, Leroy Hoard, is just
as good. Hoard is third on the team in touchdowns with eight.
Against Dallas last week, the Vikings scored five TDs of 50 yards
or more all on drives under 3 minutes. The Bears are doomed.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA 45-9.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY 8:20 P.M. GAME
</P>
<P>
   GREEN BAY (8-4) AT TAMPA BAY (5-7)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's having to breathe the Vikings' fumes in the NFC
Central or maybe it's just the knowledge that he'll be able to
coach anywhere he wants at the end of the season, but Green Bay
Coach Mike Holmgren is getting punchy. How else to explain his
expletive-laced response to a heckler as he and the team were
leaving the field at the half of last week's game against
Philadelphia? Holmgren apologized Monday. The Packers had a
lackluster first half performance against the Eagles. Maybe that
was what irritated Holmgren. Well, the Bucs are just the tonic that
he and the Packers need. Tampa Bay will miss linebacker Hardy
Nickerson (viral infection of the heart) for this game more than
they did last week against the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN BAY 26-16.
</P>
</TEXT>
