<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN UNDER PRESSURE TO CUT INTEREST RATES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In theory, Britain will be standing alone when the
European nations that cut interest rates on Thursday band together
in a single currency, the euro, in 29 days. In reality, though, the
message from the rate cut on Thursday was that economic waves do
not stop at the Channel.
</P>
<P>
   First, the rate cut to 3 percent in Germany, France and most
other euro-zone countries was widely depicted by analysts here as
likely to increase pressure on the Bank of England to cut its
benchmark rates _ already twice the European average _ when its
monetary-policy committee members meet next week.
</P>
<P>
   And, second, the pressure will be to make the cut greater than
previously expected, in part to avoid strengthening the pound,
which would further damage Britain's battered exporters.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the first reaction to the rate cut on the London foreign
exchange market Thursday was to strengthen the pound against the
German mark _ precisely the market reaction that exporters fear,
because it makes their goods more expensive and increases
competition from cheaper imports.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange rate against the mark eased only when dealers
concluded that Britain's forecast rate cut _ initially expected to
be a quarter of a percentage point, would be a half-point instead,
bringing the Bank of England's benchmark repurchase rate down to
6.25 percent from 6.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That will leave the British rate more than twice as high as the
prevalent European rate when the euro is introduced on Jan. 1 in
electronic trading. At that time, British exporters say they will
be watching closely to see how the markets price the pound against
the euro _ the common currency of Britain's biggest trading area in
the European Single Market.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows whether the euro is going to be a strong or a
weak currency,'' one economist said. But Thursday's rate cuts were
likely to prevent the euro from ``going through the roof,'' as one
analyst put it.
</P>
<P>
   The British government says Britain's membership in the euro is
contingent on a referendum after the next election, which must take
place before May 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England's goal in setting interest rates is to
maintain inflation at 2.5 percent. But in recent months, as the
same threat of global slowdown that prompted Thursday's rate cut
swept over Britain, many industries blamed the bank for their
problems, saying the high interest rates designed to hold down
inflation also squeezed consumer and corporate credit, slowing the
economy at a time when it needed a boost. Since October, the bank
has lowered rates twice from a high of 7.5 percent amid widespread
forecasts of low growth, if not recession, in some industries.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with that, blue-chip companies have issued profit
warnings showing wider trouble, not just in Britain's depressed
manufacturing industry but increasingly in the service sector once
viewed as the nation's prime engine for growth. All that has
inspired calls from industrialists and economists for further rate
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Most telling, though, the Chartered Institute of Purchasing and
Supply's index _ a barometer of the service industry _ fell below
50, to 49.1, for the first time since the survey was created two
and a half years ago. A rating above 50 indicates an increase in
manufacturing; a number below that indicates a shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   And a separate survey by the Confederation of British Industry
employers' association said the volume of retail sales in November
was the lowest since March 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
