</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RELIGION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS HE WON'T PLAY GOD WITH PEOPLE'S RELIGIOUS BELIEFS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Gov. George W. Bush may or may not long to be president
of the United States, but there is one role he is sure he doesn't
want _ playing God with people's religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, a Methodist, walked the tightrope between politics
and religion Thursday on his return from a highly publicized trip
to Israel, which had renewed interest in his views about the road
to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``My faith tells me that acceptance of Jesus Christ as my savior
is my salvation, and I believe that,'' Bush replied to a question
about his religious beliefs at a Capitol news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, ``It's not the governor's role to decide who
goes to heaven. I believe that God decides who goes to heaven, not
George W. Bush,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a similar question five years ago, Bush said
people who do not accept Jesus Christ as their personal savior
cannot go to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The comments, which upset many Jews, were recently revived in
recent national media reports about the governor, who now is
considered the front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush runs for president, a decision which he insisted again
on Thursday is still up in the air, the support of Christian
fundamentalists, who share Bush's personal religious beliefs, could
be crucial in early Republican primaries.
</P>
<P>
   While the Texas governor was in Israel earlier this week,
Abraham Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League, a
major voice against anti-Semitism, said he expected Bush to clarify
his 1993 remarks.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Bush said he has ``shown people that I'm a tolerant
person. And my job as governor is to use my office to promote
dialogue and discussion and mutual understanding and mutual
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got great respect for the other religions of the world,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office said Bush planned to make similar
statements in a letter to Foxman on Thursday, but the governor
declined to release copies of the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who returned to Austin Wednesday afternoon after an 11-day
overseas trip, had a low-key response to criticism directed at him
by Vice President Al Gore, a potential presidential opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in remarks to the Democratic Leadership Council in
Washington on Wednesday, questioned the claims of Bush and other
Republicans who promise to govern with ``compassionate
conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Compassion' is more than a pretty word. There is a long road
between rhetoric and results,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was ``fully jet-lagged'' when he first heard of
Gore's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Then, borrowing a response from his spokeswoman, Karen Hughes,
the governor added, ``What part does he object to _ the
conservative part or the compassionate part?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would define ``compassionate conservatism,'' Bush
replied: ``Making sure every child can read, making sure that we
encourage faith-based organizations ... when it comes to helping
neighbors in need, making sure that our neighborhoods are safe,
making sure that the state of Texas recognizes that people from all
walks of life have got a shot at the Texas dream but, most
importantly, making sure that government is not the answer to
people's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's trip to Israel with three other Republican governors was
sponsored by the National Jewish Coalition, a Republican-oriented
lobby that backs the policies of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu. It followed a family vacation in Italy and a side trip
to Egypt, where the Texas governor had dinner with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he went to the Middle East to ``listen and learn.''
His meetings in Israel included sessions with Netanyahu, President
Ezer Weizman, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai and opposition party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   He also visited the strategic Golan Heights and, he said,
learned a lot about the security needs of ``our strong friend and
ally, Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the group tried unsuccessfully to meet with
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat, who was in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he saw ``wonderful business opportunities'' in Israel
for Texas business people. But he played down the implications of
his visit for a potential presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his round of dinners with presidents and other
high-level figures in the Middle East made him want to change his
own title, he replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me want to get on an exercise machine. I haven't
decided yet, and now is not the time to decide whether I will or
will not seek the presidency.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
