<P>
   &QL; 
IMPEACH (Washington) - Next week's planned vote on whether to
impeach President Clinton is considered so close that it may come
down to as few as 10 undecideds (Arizona's Rep. Jim Kolbe is one of
them) who are considered ``swing'' votes, leading Democrats have
told The Arizona Republic. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MURDERER-TEACHER (Tempe, Ariz.) - Arizona State University,
inundated by calls from angry parents, will not allow convicted
murderer James Hamm to teach criminal-justice classes. The
university apparently will honor his contract with the school, but
will reassign him to other duties, probably individual research.
DEVELOPING. By MARTIN VAN DER WERF. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ROBOT (Chandler, Ariz.) - One of the world's top robot makers has
opened a $50 million training plant for companies that use their
mechanical workers. By REBECCA ROLWING. Story moved in the ``F''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PRIUS-AUTO (Phoenix) - The little Toyota Prius hardly seemed worth
a second glance, parked at the curb with a dozen sleek and exotic
examples of electric cars and trucks. But ordinary as it may
appear, there's a critical difference between Prius and the other
electric vehicles being demonstrated Wednesday in downtown Phoenix.
This is the world's first mass-produced car with hybrid power _
part gasoline engine and part electric motor _ providing the
benefits of low emissions and high gas mileage in a real-world
vehicle that can be driven anywhere. With PHOTO. By BOB GOLFEN.
Story moved in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
