<SLUG> BC-FILM-SEPARATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LA SEPARATION' EXPLORES LOVE GONE STALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of recent French films deal with the disintegration of
romantic love in ways American movies don't:
</P>
<P>
   Benoit Jacquot's ``Seventh Heaven'' explores the power struggle
within a marriage with wry humor and delicate, almost
imperceptible, emotional shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Vincent's ``La Separation,'' made in 1994 but just
reaching U.S. art houses, takes a slice-of-life look at a
disintegrating bond and the pain and anger the split produces. It
has a brusque, raw urgency and sophisticated subtleness.
</P>
<P>
   And it features intense, fully dimensional performances by
Isabelle Huppert and Daniel Auteuil, who play Anne and Pierre, an
unmarried couple with a 15-month-old son named Loulou.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening scene, they seem content. Then they attend a
Roberto Rossellini film (and the irony that the film's star, Ingrid
Bergman, left her husband to marry Rossellini is not lost) and Anne
rebuffs Pierre's touch. This insignificant action signals the first
sign of trouble in their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   One night, Anne tells Pierre the truth: she's in love with
another man. After much pressing from Pierre, who pleads, ``What
did I do wrong?'' Anne impatiently tells him, ``Nothing specific.
Just a lot of little things.'' She finally tells him that her new
love ``listens to me, pays attention to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierre falls apart in the face of Anne's casual disinterest and
lashes out at her in a fury. He vows to take Loulou. He threatens
to kick her out. Calm turns to chaos and the pair bicker and
tensely reconcile, upping the ante until there's no place left to
turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Separation'' ultimately finds a quieter, if still tenuous,
resolution. Dan Franck's script asks some intriguing questions:
Does Anne embark on an affair to wake Pierre from his remoteness?
Can two people who have acted with desperation and cruelty resume
life again on a new, better level?
</P>
<P>
   These issues are explored simply and intimately, thanks to the
cast. Auteuil can be a chilly, almost repugnant, actor but he
brings a real agony to Pierre. His desperate appeals push Anne, who
is disgusted by him, further away. The bright, restless Huppert,
who has the tougher job because she must react to Auteuil's
explosive rages, conveys a crazy-making confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Though they exhaust us with their dramatics and their inability
to move beyond pain, they slowly let us see that they're more than
capable of finding a civilized peace and a new understanding that
will ease their heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   La Separation. Directed by Christian Vincent. Written by Dan
Franck. Cast: Isabelle Huppert, Daniel Auteuil. Phaedra Cinema. 88
minutes. Unrated with strong language. In French with English
subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
