<SLUG> BC-SWEETS-FOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOKIE RECIPES YIELD HOLIDAY TREATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For many, it wouldn't be Christmas without
Christmas cookies. ``Nothing represents the spirit of loving,
nurturing and giving more than a homemade cookie,'' notes Rose Levy
Beranbaum in her book ``Rose's Christmas Cookies,'' which has been
delighting holiday bakers for the last eight years. Besides coming
from the heart, cookies are sweet and comforting and associated
with many holiday memories. Among the 60 special recipes in
Beranbaum's collection are her favorites for celebrating this
enchanting time of year in style.
</P>
<P>
   To speed cookie-making chores this holiday season, you can
create dozens of different cookies _ drop, rolled, bar, ice box and
more _ from a basic butter cookie. Released just in time for
yuletide baking this year, ``One Dough Fifty Cookies'' by Leslie
Glover Pendleton (William Morrow; $13), will give you the master
dough and blueprint for producing more than four dozen cookie
choices with different textures, shapes and flavors in a short time
during the hectic holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most amazing part of this trick is that the cookies taste
and look completely different from each other,'' writes Pendleton,
a former food editor of Gourmet magazine. ``No one will suspect you
have taken a shortcut.'' Recipes in the book range from those
suitable for gifts and entertaining to variations kids will enjoy
at lunchtime. Tempting possibilities include recipes such as
Shattered Chocolate Balls, Chocolate Marzipan Pinwheels, Spiced
Peanut Currant Cookies, Orange Marmalade Walnut Pillows, Apricot
Stars and Malted Milk Buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Each batch of dough makes enough to prepare two different cookie
recipes or a double recipe of one cookie. If you don't have time to
make more than a single cookie recipe, freeze half of the dough to
use another time. You can also make plenty of the dough in advance
of baking day and store it, well-wrapped in layers of plastic wrap
and foil, in the refrigerator up to one week or in the freezer up
to three months.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the way you decide to go, be sure to allow time for
the dough to come to room temperature before mixing or forming.
There's no excuse for not turning the kitchen into a cookie
workshop with this easy concept.
</P>
<P>
   Another hot-off-the-press book to help satisfy this season's
cookie cravings is ``125 Cookies to Bake, Nibble and Savor'' by
Elinor Klivans (Broadway Books; $25). It's a gem and has a section
titled ``Especially for Holidays'' that contains such
yummy-sounding creations as Eggnog Bars; Gingerbread People; Sugar
Cookie Cutouts; Holiday Lebkuchen; and Orange, Cranberry and
Toasted Almond Bars, to name a few. But there's much more in this
volume that you'll want to try for festive celebrations and
gift-giving.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous recipes _ among them Chocolate Chubbies, Chocolate
Truffle Squares, New York Bakery Almond Raspberry Tall Bars,
Caramel Cashew Triangles and more _ made me want to run into the
kitchen and get baking.
</P>
<P>
   Klivans, a former pastry chef and author of two other dessert
cookbooks, said cookies are her family's legacy. Her childhood
centered around cookies, and before she was old enough to read a
recipe, she stood on a special stool so she could reach the counter
and help her mother pat out cookies. She carried a box of her mom's
cookies to every holiday party, and her dad's birthday ``cakes''
always consisted of platters of cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Klivans baked cookies (to serve with ice cream) for 12 years as
a pastry chef at a restaurant. ``Those years of cookie baking gave
me a chance to experiment with new ideas and try many of the
recipes that I had clipped and saved for years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She encourages everyone to make cookies, as they are the easiest
desserts to bake. Even a first-time baker or someone who isn't
familiar with baking can bake cookies because they are so simple,
she pointed out. Cookies are also ideal for baking, freezing and
mailing. ``Most cookies have the low moisture content required for
successful freezing, take up little space in the freezer, wrap
easily for freezer storage and defrost quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some bakers and pastry chefs, Klivans advocates freezing
cookies, as she can bake and freeze them when she has time. Be sure
to cool the cookies before wrapping, she advised. Careful packaging
is the key to keeping them at their best. ``Plain cookies,
brownies, bars, truffles, small tarts and individual cakes should
be individually wrapped in plastic wrap, then placed in a metal or
rigid plastic container and covered tightly. If cookies aren't
sticky, wrap several together or wrap cookies in pairs,'' she
suggested, adding that she also packs cookies in attractive metal
tins and freezes them, ready to deliver for gifts. The cookies
won't get frosty this way because the air isn't touching the
cookies or bars in the container, she added. Also, this kind of
packaging allows you to take out and defrost only what you need.
Figure that defrosting will require about 30 to 60 minutes _ and
only unwrap the cookies when they are completely thawed.
</P>
<P>
   Klivans, who lives in Camden, Maine, is currently in the midst
of baking 1,200 cookies (a dozen different kinds) for a holiday
cookie-sampling party for her book. In conjunction with this and
Christmas by the Sea in Camden, there is a cookie walk (at the same
time) to benefit the town library. Twenty volunteers are baking
three dozen each of 20 different cookies from the book. People in
the community can sample and then purchase a combination of their
favorite cookies to take home for $7 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Among Klivans favorites in the book are the Chocolate Truffle
Bars, Chocolate Chip Bars, Dark Chocolate Truffle Macaroon
Sandwiches, Pecan Cinnamon Twists, Cherry Orange Flaky Flats and
Morning Glory Tea Cakes.
</P>
<P>
   You probably have some cherished childhood or adult memories of
baking holiday cookies. I know I do _ and I'm including a couple of
my favorite recipes today along with several from the three books
mentioned above. Wherever you're a novice or pro at the cookie
game, these selections are bound to rate raves.
</P>
<P>
   You might find these renditions so good that you could eat the
entire recipe _ and that may necessitate making another batch.
Whatever you decide, happy holiday baking. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE CHUBBIES
</P>
<P>
   I've had versions of this half-brownie, half-cookie at bakeries
around the country. It's crisp on the outside, fudgy on the inside
and loaded with chocolate chips and pecans. It's my choice for
finest chubby.
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons (3/4 stick) unsalted butter, cut into 3 pieces
(see Note)
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces unsweetened chocolate, chopped (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups (9 ounces) semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup coarsely chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Position a rack in middle of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Line 2 baking sheets with parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Put butter and unsweetened chocolate in a large heatproof
container set over but not touching, a saucepan of barely simmering
water. Stir mixture over hot water until butter and chocolate are
melted and smooth. Remove from hot water and set aside to cool and
thicken slightly, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir flour, baking powder and salt together. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Put eggs, sugar and vanilla in a large bowl of an electric mixer
and mix on medium speed until fluffy and lightened in color, about
1 minute. On low speed add chocolate mixture, beating until mixed.
Add flour mixture and mix just until mixed and dough is smooth.
Stir in chocolate chips and pecans. Batter will be thick and hold
its shape when dropped onto a baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Place rounded tablespoons of dough 2 inches apart on prepared
baking sheets (you will have 2-inch mounds).
</P>
<P>
   Bake one sheet of cookies at a time in preheated 350-degree oven
about 10 minutes or until tops feel crusty when touched gently.
Reverse baking sheet after 5 minutes to ensure that cookies bake
evenly. Watch carefully at end of baking time. Bake second sheet of
cookies. Cool cookies on baking sheet 5 minutes, then transfer to a
wire rack to cool completely. Makes 24 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Cool melted chocolate and butter mixture until it thickens
slightly. This produces a thick batter that holds its shape and
makes a plump cookie, a generous 1/2-inch thick when baked.
</P>
<P>
   To freeze, place bottoms of 2 cookies together and wrap in
plastic wrap. Put wrapped cookies in a metal or plastic freezer
container and cover tightly. Label with date and contents. Freeze
up to 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, thaw wrapped cookies at room temperature. Serve within
3 days.
</P>
<P>
   From ``125 Cookies To Bake, Nibble and Savor'' by Elinor
Klivans, Broadway Books. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHORTBREAD ROUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Every Christmas, I look forward to the holiday cookies that my
friend Rosalee Glass bakes. Her cookie tins hold the classics that
I remember from my childhood _ nut cookies coated with powdered
sugar, chocolate-covered bars and these thick, buttery shortbread
rounds. Glass thinks she adapted her recipe from an out-of-print
edition of the ``Joy of Cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups plus 2 tablespoons unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound (2 sticks) cold unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup powdered sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Position oven racks in middle and lower middle of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Line 2 baking sheets with parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Sift flour, baking powder and salt together. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Put butter in a large bowl and beat with an electric mixer on
low speed 15 seconds. Add powdered sugar and beat on medium speed
until butter and sugar are blended together. Add vanilla. Decrease
speed to low and mix in flour mixture until dough looks smooth and
holds together.
</P>
<P>
   On a lightly floured surface with a lightly floured rolling pin,
roll dough out to 1/3-inch thickness. Using a round pastry cutter 2
inches in diameter, cut out circles and place on prepared baking
sheets about 1-inch apart. Gather together dough scraps, roll them
and cut out more circles.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven about 18 minutes or until
edges and bottoms of cookies are golden. Reverse baking sheets
after 10 minutes, front to back and top to bottom, to ensure
cookies bake evenly. Cool cookies on baking sheets 5 minutes, then
transfer to wire racks to cool completely. Makes 24 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Use cold butter so a firm dough forms. The first time I
prepared these cookies, I used very soft butter. Resulting dough
was so soft cookies spread over sheet and baked into one giant
wafer.
</P>
<P>
   Use a ruler to measure 1/3-inch thickness. Cookies actually
taste different, if they are rolled thinner; it's not a bad taste,
but not as good as Glass's cookies.
</P>
<P>
   To freeze, place bottoms of 2 cookies together and wrap in
plastic wrap. Put wrapped cookies in a metal or plastic freezer
container and cover tightly. Label with date and contents. Freeze
up to 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, thaw wrapped cookies at room temperature. Leftover
cookies can be covered with plastic wrap and stored at room
temperature up to 4 days.
</P>
<P>
   From ``125 Cookies To Bake, Nibble and Savor'' by Elinor
Klivans, Broadway Books. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
EGGNOG BARS
</P>
<P>
   At our house instead of drinking eggnog, we toast the holidays
with these Eggnog Bars. The cream cheese filling is just as velvety
as any liquid eggnog, while rum and a sprinkling of nutmeg add the
traditional touches.
</P>
<P>
   NUTMEG GRAHAM CRACKER CRUST:
</P>
<P>
   2 3/4 cups graham cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons (1 stick) unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   EGGNOG FILLING:
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces cream cheese, softened 3 to 4 hours at room
temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   l large egg, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg yolk, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark rum
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Position a rack in middle of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Line a 13x9x2-inch pan with heavy foil, letting foil extend over
ends of pan. Butter bottom and sides of foil.
</P>
<P>
   For Nutmeg Graham Cracker Crust, put graham cracker crumbs,
cinnamon and nutmeg in a large bowl and mix together. Add melted
butter and stir until crumbs are evenly moistened with butter.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer crumbs to prepared pan. Using your fingers, press
crumbs evenly over bottom and 1/2-inch up sides of foil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake crust in preheated 325-degree oven 8 minutes. Cool crust
while you make filling.
</P>
<P>
   For Eggnog Filling, put cream cheese in a large bowl of an
electric mixer. Mix on low speed until smooth, about 1 minute.
Blend in sugar and flour. Add egg and egg yolk and blend until
smooth. Stop mixer and scrape sides of bowl. Mix in vanilla, rum
and whipping cream.
</P>
<P>
   Pour filling into crumb crust. Sprinkle nutmeg evenly over top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven about 25 minutes, or until
filling looks set when you give pan a gentle shake.
</P>
<P>
   Cover pan loosely with paper towels and cool 1 hour at room
temperature. Discard paper towels and refrigerate 1 hour. Cover
with plastic wrap and chill thoroughly in refrigerator, at least 6
hours or overnight. Makes 12 bars.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: These bars taste rich, so I make them thinner than most
bars; they are about 3/4 inch thick. To sprinkle batter evenly with
ground nutmeg, grate a piece of whole nutmeg directly over top of
batter. A light coating of nutmeg equals 1/2 teaspoon nutmeg called
for in filling. To double recipe, use 2 pans and double
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   To freeze, use a spatula to slide each bar off foil. Wrap
individual bars in plastic wrap. Place in a metal or plastic
freezer container and cover tightly. Label with date and contents.
Freeze up to 1 month.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, thaw wrapped bars in refrigerator 5 hours overnight.
Store bars in refrigerator up to 5 days. Serve cold.
</P>
<P>
   From ``125 Cookies To Bake, Nibble and Savor'' by Elinor
Klivans, Broadway Books. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
UNCLE HOWIE'S EXTRAORDINARY BUTTERSCOTCH CHIP BARS
</P>
<P>
   It's an official tradition. Every time I write a new dessert
book, my Uncle Howie concocts a new variation of my mom's famous
Extraordinary Chocolate Chip Cake that appeared in ``Bake and
Freeze Desserts.'' In this version, Uncle Howie uses butterscotch
chips to change the texture from a cake to a dense, fudgy bar.
After telling me about the recipe, my uncle called to see if I had
baked it yet, but I hadn't. ``You haven't tried this? Make it right
away,'' he urged. I did and chalked up another success for my
uncle.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons (1 stick) cold unsalted butter, cut into 6 pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dairy sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (12 ounces) butterscotch chips
</P>
<P>
   Position oven rack in middle of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Butter a 13x9x2-inch baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Put flour and brown sugar in a large bowl of an electric mixer
and mix on low speed 15 seconds. Add butter and mix until butter
pieces are size of peas, about 1 minute. You will still see loose
flour. Mix in egg. Mixture will look dry. Rub any lumps out of
baking soda and gently mix into sour cream. Stir in sour cream
mixture and milk just until batter is evenly moistened. Stir in
butterscotch chips. Batter will be thick. Spread evenly in prepared
baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven about 50 minutes. To test for
doneness, gently press your fingers on top. Middle should feel
slightly soft and egdes firm. Insert a toothpick in center. When
toothpick comes out with a few crumbs clinging to it, bars are
done. Cool thoroughly in baking pan on a wire rack. Makes 16 to 20
bars.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: These bars have a firm butterscotch-fudge consistency, if
served cold. At room temperature they are soft and more like a
cake. If the bars bake just until a toothpick comes out sticky,
they have a moist, dense texture and deflate slightly as they cool.
If baked until a toothpick comes out with a few crumbs clinging to
it, they have a texture similar to that of a brownie.
</P>
<P>
   To freeze, cut either 2 to 3 large pieces or 16 to 20 individual
pieces. Slide a thin metal spatula under bars to loosen any sticky
butterscotch layer from bottom of pan, then remove from baking pan.
Wrap large pieces in plastic wrap, then in heavy foil. Wrap
individual bars in plastic wrap, place in a metal or plastic
freezer container and cover tightly. Label with date and contents.
Freeze up to 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, thaw wrapped bars in refrigerator. Unwrap and serve
cold or bring wrapped bars to room temperature about 1 hour before
serving. Leftover bars can be covered with plastic wrap and
refrigerated for up to 5 days.
</P>
<P>
   From ``125 Cookies to Bake, Nibble and Savor'' by Elinor
Klivans, Broadway Books. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE MASTER DOUGH
</P>
<P>
   This recipe provides enough dough to make two variations of
cookies. If you want to make one batch of cookies, freeze the
unused half of the Master Dough for another time.
</P>
<P>
   4 sticks (1 pound) unsalted butter, softened slightly
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt (use 3/4 teaspoon if using salted butter)
</P>
<P>
   3 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   4 3/4 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   When using a heavy-duty electric mixer fitted with a paddle
attachment:
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, cream together butter, sugar and salt. Add egg
yolks and vanilla and beat until smooth. Add flour gradually,
beating on low speed until incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   When using a food processor fitted with a steel blade and with a
bowl capacity of 11 cups or more:
</P>
<P>
   In food processor, blend flour, sugar, butter (cut into small
pieces) and salt until mixture is crumbly. Add yolks and vanilla.
Blend mixture, scraping bowl occasionally, until it forms a dough.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Do not allow butter to soften too much, as resulting dough
will also be soft and harder to work with. Margarine is not
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Use a common sense when mixing in additional ingredients. Coarse
ingredients will be chopped by blade in a food processor, and
should be stirred in by hand in a seperate bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Dough _ Fifty Cookies, Baking Favorite and Festive Cookies
in a Snap'' by Leslie Glover Pendleton, William Morrow. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE MARZIPAN PINWHEELS
</P>
<P>
   Marzipan is slightly sweeter than almond paste and will give the
chocolate part a crisper texture, but either can be used here.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 recipe Master Dough (recipe above)
</P>
<P>
   7 ounces (about 2/3 cup) marzipan OR almond paste, broken into
small pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon egg white
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   Measure 1/2 cup firmly packed Master Dough and transfer to a
bowl. Add marzipan, cocoa, egg white and almond extract. Beat with
an electric mixer on medium speed until smooth. This will take a
few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Roll remaining Master Dough out between 2 sheets of wax paper
into a rectangle measuring about 10x15 inches. Roll out chocolate
dough between 2 sheets of wax paper to same size.
</P>
<P>
   Remove top sheet of paper and invert chocolate dough onto plain
dough, pressing together lightly. Remove top sheet of paper and
starting with a long side, roll dough up tightly, jelly-roll
fashion, using paper to help. Continue to roll and compress log in
paper until it measures about 19 inches long.
</P>
<P>
   Chill 2 hours, or until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Using a sharp knife, slice log into 1/4-inch thick slices.
Arrange slices 1/2 inch apart on ungreased baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Bake cookies in preheated 350-degree oven 15 to 20 minutes, or
until pale golden. Transfer cookies to wire racks to cool. Makes
about 7 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Another way to form these doughs is to roll plain dough
into 2 rectangles, sandwich chocolate layer in between and cut
dough into sticks using a pizza wheel. Or try rolling logs in
chopped almonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Dough _ Fifty Cookies, Baking Favorite and Festive Cookies
in a Snap'' by Leslie Glover Pendleton, William Morrow. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE TOFFEE COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   These cookies are a Southern praline and a brownie all in one _
a marriage made in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 recipe Master Dough (recipe above)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Grease baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, beat together all ingredients with an electric
mixer on medium speed until thoroughly combined.
</P>
<P>
   Drop batter by rounded teaspoonfuls 2 inches apart onto prepared
baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Bake cookies in preheated 350-degree oven 12 to 14 minutes, or
until middles are set. Let cookies cool on sheets 1 minute.
Transfer cookies to wire racks to cool. Makes about 7 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Dough _ Fifty Cookies, Baking Favorite and Festive Cookies
in a Snap'' by Leslie Glover Pendleton, William Morrow. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FUDGE BROWNIE BARS
</P>
<P>
   A rich, fudgy layer of brownie sits atop a buttery cookie crust
to make this treat a sinfully scrumptuous indulgence. In order to
get neatly sliced bars, let them cool completely before cutting.
Remember, it is possible to have too much of a good thing, so cut
them small.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 recipe Master Dough (recipe above)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup lightly beaten egg whites
</P>
<P>
   Measure 1 cup Master Dough into a dry measuring cup, packing
level with rim. Press dough onto bottom of ungreased 9x13-inch
baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake crust in preheated 350-degree oven 10 to 12 minutes, or
until pale golden. Cool in pan on a wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   Set bowl of an electric mixer over a saucepan of simmering
water, add chocolate chips and stir until melted. Remove bowl from
heat and add remaining dough, sugar and egg whites. Beat together
with an electric mixer on medium speed until thoroughly combined.
Spread batter carefully over crust.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 28 to 33 minutes, or until a toothpick inserted in center
comes out with no crumbs adhering to it. Cool completely. Cut into
1 1/2-inch squares.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Dough _ Fifty Cookies, Baking Favorite and Festive Cookies
in a Snap'' by Leslie Glover Pendleton, William Morrow. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE-PECAN CHEWS
</P>
<P>
   These bring back fond childhood memories.
</P>
<P>
   1 can (14 ounces) sweetened condensed (NOT evaporated) milk
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces unsweetened chocolate
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 cups coarsely chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Line baking sheets with foil. Grease foil generously.
</P>
<P>
   In top of a double boiler, combine sweetened condensed milk and
chocolate. Place over boiling water on medium-high to high heat.
Cook until mixture thickens, about 6 minutes, stirring frequently.
Stir in salt and vanilla. Stir in pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Drop by teaspoonfuls, about 2 inches apart, on greased,
foil-lined baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven 12 to 14 minutes or until
edges begin to brown. Watch carefully to avoid burning. Cookies
will be very soft, but will become firm as they cool.
</P>
<P>
   Cool 5 minutes on baking sheets. Then carefully remove to racks
to cool completely. Makes about 48 (1 1/4-inch) cookies.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Cookies'' by Natalie Hartanov Haughton, HP Books. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE RASPBERRY STREUSEL CRUMB BARS
</P>
<P>
   The favorite combination of raspberry and chocolate is hard to
resist in these sensational bar cookies. They're a wonderful cookie
offering any time of year.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 stick (4 ounces) butter, cut into pieces, softened
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup seedless raspberry jam
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups semisweet chocolate chips (7 1/2 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   Crumb Topping
</P>
<P>
   To make shortbread base, in a food processor, combine flour and
sugar and process a few seconds until mixed. Add butter, cream and
vanilla and process until mixture holds together.
</P>
<P>
   Press evenly over bottom of a foil-lined 9x13-inch shallow
baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 12 to 15 minutes or until very
light golden.
</P>
<P>
   Place spoonfuls of jam on top of warm crust. Spread evenly with
a table knife. Sprinkle chocolate chips evenly over jam. Then top
with Crumb Topping, sprinkling evenly over all. Return pan to oven.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 18 to 20 minutes longer, or until crumb topping is golden.
Cool completely, then cut into 48 bar cookies. Makes 48 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   CRUMB TOPPING: In a food processor, combine 3/4 cup flour; 5 1/3
tablespoons butter, cut into pieces, softened; 1/3 cup sugar; 1
teaspoon vanilla and 1/2 cup chopped walnuts. Process with quick
on/off motions until mixture resembles coarse crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   From ``365 Great Chocolate Desserts'' by Natalie Haughton,
HarperCollins. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DAVID'S DREAMBARS
</P>
<P>
   This book would not be complete without a cookie or two from my
incomparable friend and associate David Shamah. This spectacular
contribution is not only delicious but easy to make.
</P>
<P>
   2 (3-ounce) bars bittersweet OR semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   2 (3-ounce) bars milk chocolate
</P>
<P>
   2 (3-ounce) bars white chocolate
</P>
<P>
   12 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cinnamon graham cracker crumbs (16 double cookies)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   3 cups pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   1 can (14 ounces) sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   Place 1 oven rack in middle of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Break chocolate into individual squares and cut each in half, or
chop chocolate into 1/2-inch pieces. Mix chocolate pieces together
and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a 10x15-inch jelly-roll pan in preheated
350-degree oven 5 to 10 minutes. Spread butter evenly over bottom
and sides of pan by tilting pan or using a pastry brush.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle cracker crumbs over butter mixing with a rubber spatula
to moisten. With fingers, press crumbs firmly and evenly onto
bottom and about 3/4 inch up sides of pan. Sprinkle coconut evenly
over crumbs. Reserve 1 scant cup pecan halves. Chop remaining
pecans medium-coarsely and sprinkle evenly over coconut. Scatter
chocolate pieces in an even layer over pecans. Slowly and evenly
pour condensed milk on top. Arrange reserved pecan halves, smooth
side up, in 5 long rows, starting 1 inch from each long edge and
spacing 1 1/2 inches apart.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 10 minutes. Remove pan from oven and, using an angled
spatula, press down nuts so they adhere to chocolate. Return pan to
oven and continue baking 20 to 30 minutes or just until milk
bubbling up between nuts in center of pan is pale golden. Do not
overbake or nuts and crust will be bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Cool completely in pan on a wire rack. Invert onto a large
cookie sheet and peel off foil. Reinvert onto a cutting surface and
cut cookie lengthwise into 5 strips (each about 2 inches wide,)
cutting in between rows of pecans, and then crosswise into 10
strips (about 1 1/2 inches wide.)
</P>
<P>
   Store in an airtight food container at room temperature or in
freezer. Will keep at least 2 weeks at room temperature, several
months frozen. Texture is best up to 5 days at room temperature or
frozen and thawed. Makes 50 bars.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Rose's Christmas Cookies'' by Rose Levy Beranbaum,
William Morrow. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MOM'S COCONUT KISSES
</P>
<P>
   This cookie is so easy to make, in fact, that it's ideal to make
with kids. No doubt they will think that these kisses look like
toasted snowballs.
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups freshly shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   1/2 of a 14-ounce can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   Place 2 oven racks in upper and lower thirds of oven.
</P>
<P>
   With an ice pick or nail and hammer, pierce 3 holes at one end
of coconut. Drain liquid and reserve, if desired, for another use.
</P>
<P>
   Bake coconut in preheated 400-degree oven until shell cracks,
about 20 minutes. Reduce oven temperature to 350 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap coconut with a towel to keep shell from flying about, and
use a hammer to crack open shell. Separate coconut meat from shell
and, using a small paring knife, peel dark outer shell from white
coconut meat. Discard outer skin.
</P>
<P>
   With a fine shredding disk of a food processor or hand shredder,
shred coconut meat. Do not grate coconut as shape of finished
cookie will be flatter.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, using a wooden spoon, mix all ingredients
together until well blended, but do not add all of condensed milk
until you check consistency. Mixture should be moist and hold
together. If necessary, add up to 2 extra tablespoons condensed
milk.
</P>
<P>
   Use a rounded cookie scoop, or a scant tablespoon and your
fingers, to form 1-inch mounds of mixture about 1 1/2 inches high.
Place about 1 1/2 inches apart on baking sheets lined with foil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 15 to 20 minutes or until most
of each cookies's surface is light golden. There will still be
white spots. For even baking, rotate cookie sheets from top to
bottom and front to back halfway through baking period.
</P>
<P>
   Use a small, angled metal spatula or pancake turner to transfer
cookies to wire racks to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Store in an airtight food container in refrigerator or freezer.
Will keep 2 months refrigerated or several months frozen. Makes 2
dozen cookies.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Rose's Christmas Cookies'' by Rose Levy Beranbaum,
William Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
