<HEADLINE>
MANDELA MEETS WITH FUGITIVE PRESIDENT OF ZIMBABWE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ In a move that outraged opposition
parties and baffled the police and foreign affairs officials,
President Nelson Mandela met quietly on Wednesday with the Rev.
Canaan Banana, the former president of Zimbabwe, who is a fugitive
after being convicted last week in Zimbabwe of sodomy and assault.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela did not advise the police or Interpol before the
meeting, which his office said Banana had requested.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's office said Zimbabwe had been advised of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Zimbabwe said his government was ``never
officially informed'' and would seek extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Banana, president from 1980 to 1987, was found
guilty on 11 counts of sodomy, attempted sodomy and indecent
assault in incidents that involved bodyguards, chefs and gardeners
at his official residence while he was in office.
</P>
<P>
   He fled, apparently to Botswana, before his court-appearance
date and an arrest warrant was issued. An Interpol official in
South Africa said Thursday that he believed Banana was trying to
reach Chile; he said he learned of Banana's presence here from news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's office gave no details of the meeting. A spokesman for
Mandela, Parks Mankahlana, called the meeting a sensitive matter
and said Mandela had met Banana ``in a private capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a very tight spot here,'' Mankahlana said. ``What is
illegal in Zimbabwe is not necessarily illegal in South Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   The South African laws against sodomy were struck down in
October by the Constitutional Court.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, George
Charamba, was quoted by Reuters as having pointed out that Banana
was also convicted of assault, which is a crime here.
</P>
<P>
   In its terse statement noting the meeting, Mandela's office
said: ``The principled stand of South Africa on matters pertaining
to the respect for independent judicial processes both in our
country and abroad, and for international law, remains unchanged.
The president's firm view is that justice should run its course.''
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Front called the meeting a ``political blunder,''
and the National Party accused Mandela of making ``a deliberate
decision to undermine the judicial system of a neighboring country
by aiding and abetting a person found guilty of a serious crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Zimbabwe and South Africa are strained over
the war in Congo and a contest of wills between Mandela and Mugabe
for moral leadership in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela flouts international opinion when it suits him. He
visits and maintains cordial relations with the Libyan leader, Col.
Moammar Gadhafi, and surprised his own foreign affairs department
three years ago by saying that South Africa would recognize China
instead of Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
