<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANNOUNCES NEW WATER-QUALITY STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., Wis., N.Y., Calif., Texas)  (lb) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ The Clinton administration on Thursday issued
standards for public water supplies intended to control previously
unregulated deadly microbes as well as cancer-causing compounds
that can result from chemicals disinfecting the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're escalating our attack on the invisible microbes that
sometimes creep into the water supply,'' President Clinton said in
a speech here overlooking the Narragansett Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations, the first water-quality standards to be issued
under the Safe Drinking Water Act of 1996, will cost local
water-treatment authorities an estimated $1 billion a year, adding
a few dollars a month to a typical household's water bills, the
Environmental Protection Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said that hundreds of thousands of illnesses from
bacterial pathogens would be avoided each year, potentially saving
hundreds of lives, and that the risks of bladder cancer and other
illnesses would also be reduced. The states have two to five years
to put the new rules into effect.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced the new rules here after touring a
nearby water-treatment plant. While it is somewhat unusual for
technical regulations like these to be announced by the president,
the White House has long recognized that keeping the nation's
drinking water clean is one of the most popular of environmental
causes. The law that requires the new rules passed both Houses of
Congress almost unanimously during the 104th Congress, the first to
be controlled by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental agency issued them after two years of
negotiations among environmental groups, local governments, and
other interested parties, and there is little controversy about
them.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new rules addresses contamination from microbes like
Cryptosporidium, an organism carried by animal wastes that causes
intestinal ailments when people drink contaminated water. The
illnesses, while often unreported, can become serious or even
fatal, especially in people whose immune systems are weakened by
the AIDS virus, by chemotherapy, or for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly publicized outbreak in Milwaukee five years ago,
thousands of people were hospitalized and several dozen died from
exposure to Cryptosporidium. Similar outbreaks elsewhere helped
propel Congress to rewrite the drinking-water laws.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new regulation, communities will have to upgrade their
water-filtration systems to remove more of the common bacteria,
viruses and protozoa that environmental scientists have called one
of the greatest remaining health problems in the nation's
drinking-water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The other rule is meant to correct a problem with the
traditional system of treating drinking water with chlorine to
disinfect it. While the disinfectants are effective in controlling
microorganisms, they react with natural organic substances in the
water to form byproducts that have been found to cause cancer in
laboratory animals.
</P>
<P>
   This regulation requires drinking-water systems to remove more
of the organic matter from water before disinfecting the water, and
sets stricter standards for the amounts of chlorine and
disinfectant byproducts that remain after treatment.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also disclosed details of grants of nearly
$800 million to communities across the nation to upgrade water
systems.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   About $47 million will go to New York state; California will
receive $87 million and Texas will get $62 million under the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Chafee of Rhode Island, the Republican chairman of the
Senate Environmental Committee, called the rules among the most
important to deal with drinking water in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proves, Mr. President, that divided government can produce
for the American people if we work together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were a few signs and chants calling for
impeachment in the crowd that lined Clinton's route and among those
who heard him speak, people were generally friendly toward him. The
audience at the historic fort, packed with schoolchildren, cheered
most loudly when he spoke of environmental causes as issues that
would dominate policy decisions for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The only allusion to his political travails among those
traveling with the president was a veiled one from Rep. Patrick
Kennedy, D-R.I. He called on Clinton to pursue an ``aggressive''
agenda for the next two years, saying, ``This nation cannot afford
a stagnant government.'' And Kennedy, who is likely to cast a vote
on impeachment before the year is out, said he would ``stand with
you and fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
