<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWANESE IDENTITY AT STAKE IN VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Fifteen million Taiwanese voters go to the polls
Saturday in an election that could shape both the future of
Taiwanese politics and the breakaway province's relations with
mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are all 225 seats in the national legislature, mayoral
posts in Taiwan's two biggest cities and city council slots. If the
ruling Kuomintang Party (KMT) regains the mayor's office in the
capital of Taipei and strengthens its slim majority in the
legislature, it will consolidate its 49-year hold on power and
continue its slow warming of relations with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But if the 10-year-old opposition Democratic Progressive Party
(DPP) keeps the Taipei mayorship and increases its seats in the
legislature, it would pose an increasing threat to KMT rule. It
would also signal growing pro-independence sentiment in a de-facto
nation that China has considered a ``renegade province'' ever since
anti-communist KMT officials set up a government in exile in Taipei
in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is the high drama of Taiwan's first direct presidential
elections in 1995, when an angry China fired missiles across the
Taiwan Strait and the United States sent aircraft carriers to the
area to cool tempers. But lacking such pyrotechnics, this election
campaign has been colorful.
</P>
<P>
   First came the release of a purported taped conversation between
the incumbent mayoral candidate in the southern port of Kaohsiung
and his alleged mistress. This week, a bloody brawl broke out
between a candidate from the Taiwan Independence Party and one from
the DPP, when the former accused the latter of being a lackey of
mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday, 10 people, including a Presbyterian minister,
were arrested on suspicion of buying votes with jugs of cooking oil
and $15 cash handouts in a mountain tribal community, and with
wristwatches for the disabled in suburban Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Bizarre gimmicks such as striptease, superhero costumes, and a
bicycle rally have dominated the campaign, and personalities have
overshadowed issues. Even restrained 75-year-old President Lee
Teng-hui joined in the carnival dressed on occasions as King
Arthur, a tribal chieftain, and a baseball team captain. In the
rural south, he donned a straw hat and rode a power tiller.
</P>
<P>
   But the raucous campaign also reveals the liveliness of Taiwan's
democracy _ one of the newest and freest in Asia _ and the first in
Chinese history. It has also proven, analysts say, that Beijing
cannot stifle democratic aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is proof that Taiwan is a true democratic society. We are
a very important window for promoting human rights and democracy in
the PRC (People's Republic of China),'' said Sisy Chen, former
spokeswoman for the DPP and president of the New Rising People
Foundation. ``It is impossible to push Taiwan back to PRC
authoritarianism.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic politics has become a main theme. Candidates have battled
to prove their ``Taiwanese-ness'' and loyalty to Taiwan over China,
underscoring the emergence of a uniquely Taiwanese identity in a
tiny island-state that has measured itself for half a century
against the behemoth of mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   The elections, therefore, carry significance not only for the
future of domestic politics, but also for the chances and desire
for a peaceful reunification of Taiwan and China _ perhaps under
the ``one country, two systems'' model adopted for capitalist Hong
Kong's return to Chinese rule.
</P>
<P>
   The marquee race has been for mayor of Taipei. The ruling
party's Ma Ying-jeou, a former justice minister and Harvard Law
School graduate, is challenging the charismatic incumbent Chen
Shui-bian, the star of the populist DPP who worked his way through
a Taiwanese law school and promotes his native ancestry against
Ma's mainland roots.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of people in Taiwan are considered native
Taiwanese, while 20 percent fled the mainland in 1949 or are
descended from those who did. Chen's camp adopted the slogan,
``Tawainese vote for Taiwanese.'' Ma can barely speak Taiwanese,
but President Lee _ a native Taiwanese himself _ defended his party
colleague this week, declaring, ``We are all new Taiwanese, whether
our ancestors came here 400 or 500 years ago, or 40 or 50 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Various polls show consistently that Taiwanese identity and
independence sentiment are ``defensive ideologies'' that people
adopt if they feel threatened.
</P>
<P>
   This past summer, for example, after President Clinton announced
in China that the United States does not favor Taiwan independence,
support in Taiwan for independence rose. But according to New
Rising People Foundation surveys, only about 30 percent of people
want a vote on independence under any circumstances. But 80 percent
would support a referendum if the United States and China were to
demand that Taiwan accept reunification under a ``one country, two
systems'' model.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sisy Chen, ``Everyone who wants to be mayor of
Taipei _ even a mainlander like Ma _ put a big emphasis on: `I love
Taiwan, I'm Taiwanese.' '' Beijing, she said, ``should pay more
attention to how Taiwanese identity has become a coherent ideology
in this election.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have complained, however, that ethnic and personality
politics have blotted out livelihood issues such as free
kindergarten and medical treatment for toddlers and pensions. ``Ma
and Chen are like stars. It's like, do you want to vote for Whitney
Houston or Celine Dion?'' Chen scoffed.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high in this tight race. If Chen wins, he will be
in a stronger position to run for president in 2000. If Ma wins, he
will wrest back a key foothold for the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Bau Tzong-ho, chairman of the political science department at
National Taiwan University, says the Taipei elections will set the
stage for party politics and establish new leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins will maintain a cautious course with Beijing. DPP
party leaders feel that they do not need to declare independence
because Taiwan is already separate from China. For the KMT, though,
Taiwan must wait for China to become more democratic before the two
sides can reunite as did Germany and East Germany did.
</P>
<P>
   Editorial assistant Liz Lau provided material for this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
