<HEADER>
A1935 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXASFORTS-TRAIL-960(     12-03 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASFORTS-TRAIL-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FORTS TRAIL WINDS DOWN BACK ROADS TO LONE STAR TURNING
POINTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MENARD, Texas _ The jagged ruins of Presidio San Luis de Las
Amarillas, originally built by the Spanish, are impressive, even as
they are battered by torrential rains. Although many people think
of the history of Texas as a narrative centered on American
settlers, Indian tribes and Bob Wills' music, Spain's was a
powerful presence, and these ruins serve as a reminder. In the
1930s, there was an attempt to restore the 18th-century fort to its
past glory, but the residents of Menard eventually built a golf
course around it instead.
</P>
<P>
   Now the grubby parking lot in front of the presidio lies
adjacent to the ninth tee of a 499-yard par-five. Though it may
seem incongruous to see a moss-covered old fort and a golf cart
side by side, that's just the way it is on the Texas Forts Trail.
You get a lot that you would expect _ and a lot more you wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   TALE OF THE TRAIL: Thirty years ago, the Texas Historical
Commission officially designated a 650-mile route through the west
central part of the state as a historical path to be known as the
Texas Forts Trail. The trail includes the Spanish presidio, eight
frontier forts of both the ruined and restored variety from the
19th century, and highlights of the communities that have sprung up
around them. It commemorates the legacy of cavalrymen and pioneers
who drew a line in the dust and offered to fight anyone who made
the mistake of trying to remove them.
</P>
<P>
   The trail is just one of 10 special ``heritage tourism'' routes
the THC hopes to bring to the public's attention over the next
several years; as a source for day- or week-long outings, it serves
as a reminder of not only the Lone Star State's military heritage
but also its quirky geographic beauties. The serpentine path twists
along tiny farm roads and past mighty lakes and leads to
fascinating museums, old-fashioned country stores and restaurants
that beckon with down-home comfort food.
</P>
<P>
   If highly fragrant road kill, slow-moving farm machinery
dominating one-lane roads and the occasional unnerving golf course
get thrown into the mix, well, think of it this way: The original
trailblazers had their obstacles to overcome, too.
</P>
<P>
   WAGONS HO!: The best way to begin a Texas Forts Trail jaunt is
to pick up the phone: Call the THC office in Austin and ask for the
handy brochure, which includes a map of 45 numbered points of
interest, as well as a well-written, concise history of each place.
The first stop on the map is Lake Fort Phantom Hill, just north of
Abilene; the last is Abilene State Park, just south of the same
city, marking the conclusion of a circuitous route along back roads
and one sole stretch of highway between Fort Worth and Abilene.
</P>
<P>
   Trail followers needn't feel they must travel by the numbers and
can, in fact, commence at any point along the way; adventurers from
Fort Worth-Dallas may want to kick off with Lake De Leon at No. 21,
because it is an easy drive west on I-20 before turning south on
Farm Road 2461.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the Forts Trail might be best enjoyed on a series of
two-day outings. At no point are travelers farther from Fort Worth
than a six-hour drive. If, however, you are determined to go
everywhere and see everything in one marathon jaunt, then four or
five full days are really required.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny roads and their inevitable delays are partly
responsible, but so is the fact that the Texas Forts Trail simply
includes lots of intriguing places.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER ROADSIDE ATTRACTION: Although different points along the
trail will appeal to different personalities, even an accidental
tourist will not want to miss these highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Fort Griffin (Point 5), 15 minutes past Albany, not only boasts
some of the most fascinating historical structures, but also serves
as home to the official Texas State Longhorn Herd. Steaks on the
hoof graze along the partially restored fort parade ground,
serenely interrupting their cud-chewing to smile for the camera. Be
warned: Lots of trail stops are in wild country, and it is always
advisable to be careful where you walk. But at Fort Griffin,
there's something to fear besides snakes: The longhorns' digestive
systems are obviously efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Belknap (Point 10) is more upscale than Griffin, and with
its sandstone buildings was reported to have been one of the
prettiest forts on the frontier. It is also somewhat more
predictable, though, lacking the cow equation. The views from
certain points in Possum Kingdom State Park (Point 14), though not
quite equal to those of Big Sur on the California coast, are
spectacular, and merit a stop or two.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   De Leon (Point 23) is a charming little place with streams,
bridges and fishermen's cottages that comes as a welcome respite
from its fairly dull surrounding countryside. On a recent visit,
some of the town's buildings were festooned with colorful art
hyping a peach and melon festival. This part of the trail also
encompasses Lake Leon and the Proctor Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   As the traveler moves along the trail past Comanche and its fine
old courthouse, the time and space between attractions lengthens,
providing a nice opportunity to muse about what you've seen and
what's to come. Where do some of these names come from, for
instance? Scalp Creek seems pretty obvious, but could early pioneer
literati have named the towns of Bronte and Desdemona? (Bronte was,
in fact, named for English author Charlotte. Desdemona, though, was
named for a founding father's daughter. We can only hope she wasn't
also the reason for her hometown's nicknames _ Hog Town and Hog
City.)
</P>
<P>
   Potential boredom can also be held at bay by studying the
quantity and variety of road kill. The narrower the roads, the more
plentiful the dead animals lying alongside them. A few deer, some
armadillos, a possum or two, and, apparently by legislative decree,
one squashed skunk each mile.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Lake Brownwood State Park (Point 28) looms, a site
almost as nice as its counterpart, Possum Kingdom. The town of
Brownwood, too, is a pleasant surprise, with a 1902 Romanesque
Revival jail and an especially inviting picnic area, complete with
waterfall, just on the east edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   After another longish stretch of nothing in particular, you'll
find yourself in the area around Brady (Point 29), site of
spectacular Indian battles. Your favorite memory, though, may be
the Lone Star Bar-B-Q on U.S. 87 South. Seven dollars will buy you
a plate piled with brisket, chicken, ribs, sausage, goat or pork
chops, all prepared in huge smokers outside the
unremarkable-looking restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be in Menard before your Lone Star meal is fully
digested. Presidio San Luis de Las Amarillas (Point 32) and its
companion golf course are followed in close order by Fort McKavitt
(Point 33), which at its peak in the 1870s contained 35 buildings
and which is now gradually being reconstructed.
</P>
<P>
   Some attractions along the way are considered so obvious they
aren't even listed among the trail's designated 45 stops. For
example, San Angelo's Fort Concho, built in 1867, is often
considered the state's unofficial fort showplace, and no wonder.
Every visit introduces something new and interesting among the 23
original and restored structures.
</P>
<P>
   The fort's infirmary is noteworthy; restored to an approximate
version of its original form (one interior staircase is now
straight rather than circular), the infirmary has an excellent
medicine-bottle exhibition. Equally illuminating, though far more
uncomfortable to look at, is the surgical saw that amputated
appendages of wounded troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Also unnumbered on the map but not to be missed are several
sites in Abilene's downtown area. The Grace Cultural Center
(housing the Abilene Fine Arts Museum and Children's Museum), the
Abilene Historical Museum and the old Paramount Theatre are all
worth a lingering look.
</P>
<P>
   MARKING THE SPORT: There's no denying that only diehard history
buffs will want to pause and gawk at all the historial markers
crammed along the historic trail, leaving dull stretches aplenty
for many of us. Most roads are narrow, and even moderate rainfall
renders them muddy. The countryside aromas often identify regional
crops _ peanuts around De Leon, decaying road kill near Menard.
</P>
<P>
   But just when you decide there surely are better trails to
travel, just as you're convinced the Comanche should have told the
white settlers they could ``have'' Texas and welcome to it, then
you turn a corner and there is the swell of Possum Kingdom Lake or
De Leon's painted downtown, or even the quiet dignity of a presidio
surrounded by a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   That's the moment it is possible to understand why so many men
and women were willing to fight, suffer and even die for the right
to make Texas their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the moment you realize that whoever at the Texas
Historical Commission mapped out the Texas Forts Trail knew exactly
what he or she was doing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Details: For a copy of the Texas Forts Trail brochure, contact
the Texas Historical Commission, Box 12276, Austin, TX 78711 or
call (512) 463-6100. The Texas Historical Commission Web site is
www.thc.state.tx.us.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
