<HEADLINE>
TURNER PRIZES TO INNOVATIVE ARTISTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The $33,000 Turner Prize was awarded in London this week to
painter  &UR; Chris Ofili &LR;  for a painting dotted with blobs of elephant
dung. The artist said he procures the material from the London Zoo.
``It is pretty straightforward,'' Ofili said. ``It comes out of the
elephant's arse, it dries up and is ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The prize is given every year to British artists younger than
50. Ofili's main competitors were sculptor  &UR; Cathy de Nonchaux &LR; , who
made female genitalia in suede, and video artists  &UR; Tacita &LR; 
 &UR; Dean &LR;  and  &UR; Sam Taylor-Wood &LR; . Dean's video showed Hungarian women in
a steam bath; Taylor-Wood shot a couple breaking up in a crowded
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man, thank God,'' Ofili said upon winning. ``Where's my
check?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONING THE GOP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Can a Republican be a rock 'n' roll fan?'' asks the latest
issue of the rock magazine Request. Essayist &UR; Geoffrey Himes &LR; ,
obviously a subjective Democrat, writes that members of the Grand
Old Party, particularly members of the right wing of that party,
clash ``with the integrationist, nonconformist, working-class and
sexually exultant tendencies of rock 'n' roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Himes deems all Republicans segregationists, saying that ``every
time a European American performer incorporates a  &UR; Bob &LR; 
 &UR; Dylan &LR; esque lyric or a Stratocaster guitar solo, they are resisting
the still-powerful pressures to keep black and white cultures
separate. ... Without this race-mixing, you wouldn't have rock 'n'
roll.'' He draws similar conclusions about class.
</P>
<P>
   He blames rock critics for failing to point out the political
messages in the music. ``We've done a pretty poor job of it if rock
'n' roll fans still think they can be conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Adding to this round of GOP-bashing (did the magazine
editors know about the election results before these issues went to
press?), the newest Penthouse includes a cartoon essay that
attempts to answer the question, ``Do Republicans make love?''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. The latest issue of George magazine, which apparently had
a pre-election deadline, says  &UR; Newt Gingrich  &LR; is the ninth most
powerful person in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOLIDAY GIFT GUIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From the Reliable Home Office catalog, the Caller TV device,
which enables the user who likes to watch more than he likes to
talk to see Caller ID information right on the TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   No more need to leave your chair to answer the phone, unless
it's a call you've been waiting for. It comes complete, at $129.95,
with a remote-control device that allows the user to look at a log
of calls in succession.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sharon Stone &LR;  addressed the United Nations on Tuesday for
World AIDS Day and talked about how she had sex in the backseat of
a car when she was a teenager. She was advocating safe sex and the
distribution of condoms.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Barbra Streisand  &LR; may give a New Year's Eve performance at
the turn of the millennium, reports the New York Daily News, and
might like to have &UR; Woody Allen &LR; 's Dixieland band as opening act.
The tabloid has also reported that  &UR; Sean Penn &LR; , who is starring in
Allen's next movie, is not getting along with the director and his
associate,  &UR; Jean Doumanian &LR; . Penn, who has repeatedly called in
sick, is reported to have been threatened by the filmmakers with a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Having read the headlines in Monday's San Francisco Chronicle,
 &UR; John Santibanes &LR;  thinks one story might explain the other:
``Mouseketeer Faces Trial for Stock Fraud'' and ``Scientists Report
`Fixing' Faulty Gene in Mice.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Der Speigel says  &UR; Placido Domingo &LR; ,  &UR; Luciano Pavarotti &LR;  and
 &UR; Jose Carreras &LR; , as well as  &UR; Montserrat Caballe &LR; , are about to be
fined for tax fraud.  &UR; Matthias Hoffman &LR; , the German agent for the
Three Tenors tour, is on trial in Germany for tax fraud.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``How many senators can give an extempore speech? In my
grandfather's time they ... took themselves seriously as tribunes
of the people, as voices for the unseen and unheard. Of course,
there were crooks then, too, but they at least had a Dickensian
sense of theater. They dressed up and spoke up. The Senate was the
best show in town. Now, displaced anchorpersons who never made it
in prime time toss their air-blown locks, or more sinister, their
bouffant wigs to the breeze from the air-conditioning that keeps
the television lights from overheating their thin blood. It's to
weep.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Gore Vidal in the latest Playboy.
</P>
</TEXT>
