<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BNK-AMERICA-WOMEN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former women execs at BankAmerica resign after its merger with
NationsBank
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Six of the 10 top ranked women executives at the old
BankAmerica have resigned since NationsBank, now part of the new
BankAmerica, announced in April that it would merge with the
California banking company.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Chronicle said Wednesday that women from the
old BankAmerica were being singled out for discrimination. The new
BankAmerica denied the charge. None of the women could be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Does Chief Executive Officer Hugh L. McColl's team discriminate
against women? ``I don't believe that's the case,'' said Lehman
Brothers analyst Diane Glossman.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco paper reported a former female BankAmerica
executive, who was not named, presented the newspaper with a
five-page memorandum claiming ``the entire generation of female
executives created during (the past 25 years) has been wiped out.''
</P>
<P>
   The two top-ranked women who resigned, Kathleen J. Burke, who
headed human resources, and Cheryl A. Sorokin, the corporate
secretary, were principal officers of the old BankAmerica. No women
are now part of the six-person management team that heads the new
BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   But only two male executives from the old BankAmerica are on the
new six-person team, and former NationsBank executives hold the
majority of other senior slots in the new company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the board of directors, which is the highest
management group in the company, (you see that) 4 of the 19
directors are women,'' said BankAmerica spokesman John Keane.
``That would place the new Bank of America fifth among the largest
50 companies in the nation with women on their boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Another BankAmerica spokesman, Richard Stilley, named several
women in top jobs at the new company, including Adelaide A. Sink,
president of the Florida bank.If that unit were independent,
Stilley said, it would be the 10th largest bank in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The four top women executives from the old BankAmerica who
stayed with the new company have been demoted, the San Francisco
paper said. That's an allegation ``I'm going to quarrel with,''
said Stilley.
</P>
<P>
   He maintained that the other female executives ``have good jobs
with a much larger company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The published reports used anonymous sources and generalized
about the management team in a very unfair fashion. Most of the
female executives cited in the report were offered very important
positions in the new company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
