<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-NOTEBOOK04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cable convention shows serious side
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Is this a cable TV industry trade show or a
carnival? It has been hard to tell.
</P>
<P>
   On the convention floor of the big industry get-together called
the Western Show, you can race cars in a big video game display,
watch the Radio City Hall Rockettes dance or shake hands of a Bill
Clinton look alike.
</P>
<P>
   It all looks like great fun _ and for the cable TV operators who
are the target of this carnival _ it is.
</P>
<P>
   But for the programmers who are hawking their shows, the
theatrics are a serious business. That's especially true this year,
with cable TV operators leery of adding new channels since they're
paying more for the ones already on their systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``These channels are too expensive,'' complained Lynne Bueing,
the vice president for programming at Los Angeles operator Falcon
Cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   Despite grumbling by both operators and programmers, the
industry still managed to have a good time and even poke fun at
itself during the three days of the Western Show which ends here
today.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it was hard to board an elevator without first
being brushed down for lint by some merry promoters of the E!
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a holdup,'' said Falcon general manager Terry
Eagleton, watching businessmen standing in front of the elevators
with their arms over their heads. She took the stairs instead and
there was a long line of people behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the giant cardboard statues of Rockette dancers
greeting attendees in several hotels. One woman who accidently
backed into one yelped and jumped five feet in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``My god, I thought she was alive,'' gasped a frightened Rosanne
Merckleson, a Control Data publicist. She soothed her jangled
nerves with a big helping of candy at the HBO channel booth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
