<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CABLE-SHOW04-COX     12-03 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-SHOW04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Operators, programmers square off
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Once upon a time, cable TV operators and
programmers were underdog comrades united in an epic struggle
against network television, which controlled 90 percent of all
viewership.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if the Western Show is any example, operators and
programmers are comrades no longer. Operators here at this big
industry trade show are openly complaining about the rising cost of
the channels they air, even threatening to yank some from their
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rising programming costs is one of the industry's most
volatile issues,'' says Robert Stengel, a principal of industry
consultant Continental Consulting Group. ``Operators used to pay
almost nothing for programming. Now it eats up 25 percent of their
revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is this struggle between operators and programmers more
evident than in Atlanta. Operators Cox Communications, based in
Atlanta, and MediaOne, with operations in the city, are strongly
resisting an effort by Turner Broadcasting to raise the price of
carrying its popular TNT channel by between 5 percent and 7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   None of the companies will talk publicly about the dispute, but
negotiations have become so heated that top Cox Communications
executives have threatened to pull TNT off some of its systems.
Turner Broadcasting executives dismiss the threat as a negotiating
ploy, saying TNT is well worth the rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   But other operators point out MediaOne recently cut struggling
channel Court TV from some of its systems. Channels are rarely
discontinued once started _ until now. Top executives of Turner
Broadcasting and Cox Communications met here at the Western Show _
which closes today _ to try and settle their differences. The
meeting reportedly resolved little, if anything.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the dispute between operators and programmers is
diverging interests and strategies.
</P>
<P>
   For programmers, the emphasis is on producing better and better
shows. They smell blood and opportunity as network television
viewership continues to decline, with much of the loss going to
cable.
</P>
<P>
   To attract more viewers, Turner Broadcasting, for example, spent
$100 million to buy the syndication rights of ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which owns ABC and ESPN, has paid hundreds of millions
for some key rights to NFL football games. It has passed part of
the cost to cable operators.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne and Cox Communications swallowed that increase but
neither are happy about it. They and other operators argue their
industry cannot afford rising programming costs right now.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is twofold. One, the top operators are spending
billions of dollars to build digital networks that can provide not
only television but telephone service and high-speed access to the
Internet. MediaOne alone has spent $5.5 billion so far on such
efforts in cities nationwide, including Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Second, many operators are trying to moderate price increases to
subscribers. Federal price regulation is scheduled to expire March
31 and operators don't want to do anything that would prompt
Congress to enact new restraints on their industry.
</P>
<P>
   Says Matt Bond, Tele-Communications Inc.'s executive vice
president for programming, ``Our programming costs are rising 10 to
15 percent a year while we're trying to hold rate increases to
subscribers to between 4 and 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't continue to do this,'' says Bond. ``At some
point we'll have to start trimming our channel lineup, eliminating
those that aren't worth the money.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
