<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-MEDICAID04-COX     12-03 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-MEDICAID04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medicaid change will help rural facilities
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia's Medicaid program has expanded its rules
governing physician assistants, paving the way for more medical
services in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Medical Assistance, which runs the
federal-state Medicaid program for more than 1 million low-income
Georgians, has decided to reimburse care by physician assistants in
what are designated ``remote sites,'' in medically underserved
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it will improve access to medical care in rural
areas,'' said Mark Trail, deputy commissioner at DMA.
</P>
<P>
   Trail cited the South Georgia town of Willacoochee, where a
medical clinic's closing in August was the subject of a
Journal-Constitution article.
</P>
<P>
   In closing the Willacoochee clinic, its operators blamed a
Medicaid policy that blocked payment for physician assistants' care
at a private clinic, other than those designated as a hospital
outpatient center or a ``rural health center.''
</P>
<P>
   About 30 percent of the clinic's patients were Medicaid
recipients. The closing left the community without medical
services, except for a single physician in his 70s, who is close to
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are having to travel out of town to see doctors,''
Jerome Crosby, a vice president of Peoples Bank in Willacoochee,
said Thursday. The clinic, he said, ``is a needed service, just
like water and sewer.''
</P>
<P>
   A former physician assistant at the clinic said he, along with a
doctor and another PA, plan to reopen the double-wide trailer
facility as soon as the Medicaid change takes effect. ``All we have
to do is get the go-ahead from Medicaid,'' said PA Bobby Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Access to health care has become a growing problem for many
rural communities. Some towns are threatened with losing their
hospital to financial problems. And if medical services dry up,
local jobs and industry are imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   In Willacoochee and such rural areas, PAs have helped fill a
medical void, though they can practice medicine only under the
supervision of a doctor. But while they must be available by phone
as a PA works, doctors generally don't have to be physically
present during those services.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Georgia Medicaid rules came under fire as too
restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Willacoochee clinic was receiving
Medicaid reimbursements for PAs because it was labeled a hospital
outpatient center. But the clinic lost that designation when a
local hospital decided to close it in March. Tucker and another PA,
Arlene Gottlieb, and their supervising doctor, Dr. Robert Bowman,
opted to keep the Willacoochee clinic open themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But in June, they were told the Medicaid payment would be cut
off, under a rule for private clinics that required a doctor to be
on the premises at all times. Bowman could only be present 10 hours
a week.
</P>
<P>
   DMA adhered to the policy despite Medicare, the federal
insurance program for the elderly, and private insurance paying for
services by PAs at the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Trail said the new rule on remote sites would require a
physician be physically present only 25 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven areas, including Willacoochee, are designated remote
sites. In order to qualify, a clinic has to be in a medically
underserved, nonurban area.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicaid policy change, though, could take two months to be
implemented. Glenda Yawn, manager of the Willacoochee senior
citizens center, said many seniors are now traveling 30 miles to
get medical care. But when the double-wide trailer reopens, Yawn
said, ``the whole town will be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
