</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAGOV-BUSINESS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes' priorities: Taxes, education, transit, training
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov.-elect Roy Barnes told members of the Georgia
Industry Association he wanted them ``to make money and pay taxes''
so he could educate Georgia students to be ``better employees for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Thursday to the prelegislative conference of the GIA at
Cobb Galleria, Barnes said improved education, including expanded
technical training, is among his top priorities as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``During this upcoming session, I will create a commission _
either by legislation or executive order _ that will review where
we are in education and ask some hard questions about what needs to
be changed or done,'' said Barnes, who plans to chair the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he intends to begin creating ``a seamless education
system'' that will allow high school students who plan to become
skilled tradesmen, rather than attend college, to take courses in
advanced technical schools while still attending high school.
</P>
<P>
   The technical school credits would count toward a high school
diploma, and the students would still be considered high school
students so they could compete in sports and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't complete this during this session, but we are going
to begin,'' said Barnes, who stressed Georgia's education system
must continue to improve from preschool to adult if it is going to
compete successfully in the national and world economies.
</P>
<P>
   Also high on his initiatives, said Barnes, is the establishment
of a regional transportation authority to deal with air quality and
transportation issues in metro Atlanta. This authority would be
empowered to coordinate transportation in the region, including the
possible building of a west-east commuter rail system along the
northern arc of I-285.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot overemphasize the importance of coming to some
agreement on what are the limits of growth (of metro Atlanta) and
what infrastructure is needed to support growth,'' said Barnes.
``We cannot afford to stop growing in Atlanta, but that is what is
going to happen if we don't come to a consensus about a
transportation and air quality policy in the metro region.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he also plans to propose a three-year moratorium on
the payment of unemployment taxes by employers because the fund is
currently overfunded.
</P>
<P>
   This would amount to about $1 billion in savings for companies,
which Barnes said they could use to expand business growth and
employment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
