A1986 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-COUNTDOWN-HNS     12-03 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-COUNTDOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA READIES ENDEAVOUR FOR SECOND LAUNCH ATTEMPT 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ NASA late Thursday readied the shuttle
Endeavour for a second launch attempt early Friday after a
momentary hydraulic problem prevented its six-member crew from
lifting off on a mission to begin orbital assembly of the new
international space station.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle was to launch well before dawn from NASA's Kennedy
Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's ground control teams early Thursday were forced to
postpone Endeavour's liftoff when they could not resolve the cause
of a brief drop in hydraulic pressure. The unusually brief
launching period expired before the problem was solved.
</P>
<P>
   The scrub broke a string of 18 missions in which the shuttle has
lifted off once the countdown had reached the point where a shuttle
crew had climbed aboard. The string dated back to November 1995.
The Endeavour was 19 seconds from blasting off.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty arose when the astronauts activated the shuttle's
hydraulic systems with five minutes left in a countdown that had a
3 minute, 42 second launch period. A momentary drop in pressure in
the system that steers the shuttle triggered an alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Launch and flight control teams at Kennedy and the Johnson Space
Center in Houston were unable to resolve the problem in time to
beat the clock. Flight controllers at Johnson, however, seemed
satisfied Endeavour was safe to fly but could not get their
colleagues in Florida to make a timely restart of the countdown
clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to launch with something we didn't
understand,'' said Ralph Roe, NASA's launch director at Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The launch period for Endeavour is precisely timed so the
shuttle and its 25,000-pound space station module can reach an
orbiting component launched by the Russians on Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Loaded in the shuttle's payload bay is the Unity module, a
33-foot long cylinder with a half-dozen docking ports that will
inter-connect a future U.S. laboratory module, airlock and power
generating gear.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian-built Zarya module, a much larger spacecraft
designed to provide propulsion, electrical power, guidance and
ground communications, awaits the shuttle crew's arrival in an
orbit just over 240 miles high.
</P>
<P>
   Once aloft, the Endeavour crew plans to rendezvous with Zarya.
Using the shuttle's robot arm and at least three long spacewalks,
they will then join the two components.
</P>
<P>
   The flight is scheduled for 12 days.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five launches are envisioned over the next six years to
fully assemble an orbital complex that will sprawl to the size of
two football fields placed side by side. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1854EST &QL; 
