<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADIAN-EXECUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WON'T BE SWAYED BY DIPLOMATIC PRESSURE TO GRANT 30-DAY STAY IN
EXECUTION OF CANADIAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
and JIM HENDERSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, returning from an 11-day
overseas trip and finding himself in the middle of an international
controversy, indicated Thursday that he will not be swayed by
diplomatic pressure to grant a 30-day stay to a Canadian national
scheduled to be executed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who
had requested the stay after meeting with Canadian officials, Bush
said he would take no action until he had received a recommendation
from the State Board of Pardons and Paroles concerning the case of
Joseph Stanley Faulder, who has been on death row for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has had sufficient time to review Mr. Faulder's
(clemency) petition in detail and should not require additional
time to examine the issues raised in the petition,'' he said in the
letter.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is the 1969 Vienna Convention on Consular Relations,
which states that foreign nationals, at the time of their arrest,
must be informed of their rights to contact their government.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder, who was convicted of the 1975 robbery-murder of an East
Texas woman, was never informed of that right and the Canadian
government did not learn of his conviction in Texas until 15 years
later. His lawyers last week filed their final appeal with the U.S.
Supreme Court, but Bush's office has become the focal point of a
diplomatic effort to spare Faulder.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy has asked Bush to lift
Faulder's death sentence and last week was joined in that effort by
United Nations Human Rights Commissioner Mary Robinson. Albright
then interceded with her request for a 30-day stay of execution and
offered to send State Department officials to Texas to brief the
governor on the implications of the Vienna treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I receive the board's recommendation, I assure you that
I will consider carefully those same issues when I review Mr.
Faulder's request,'' Bush said in his letter to Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Rodriguez, chairman of the parole board, said the panel
can consider the issue of consular notification in reviewing
Faulder's case, but he was noncommittal about the weight it would
carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will consider any and all issues that are brought to our
attention,'' he said. ``The most important thing I can say is we
will deliver our recommendation to the governor in a timely
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   While the board members are deliberating Faulder's fate in
secrecy, they are awaiting the outcome of a court battle over the
constitutionality and legality of their review procedures.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, state District Judge Paul Davis issued a temporary
restraining order against the board's practice of non-public
deliberations and voting. Ruling in a class action suit filed by
Faulder's attorneys, Davis said the parole board's actions are in
violation of the state constitution and the state Open Meetings
Act.
</P>
<P>
   The effect could be to force the board to hold a public meeting
to consider Faulder's case _ and the cases of all death row inmates
who petition for clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Morales immediately appealed to the Court
of Criminal Appeals, arguing that a judge in a civil case had no
jurisdiction in a criminal matter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gave no hint Thursday that he was inclined to stop
Faulder's execution and he suggested that he did not expect such a
recommendation from the parole board.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, the governor can't commute a death sentence
without a recommendation of the board, but he can grant one 30-day
reprieve on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like to me that if that option (reprieve) is
granted to me it makes any sense,'' he said. ``They (the parole
board) have had ample time to look at the issue already. It's not
as if the commutation request came at the last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's case raises the same Vienna Convention issues that the
state confronted when the Mexican government objected to the
execution of Irineo Montoya Tristan in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the courts, not the governor, should resolve any
constitutional issues involving international treaties and death
row inmates. He said the courts reviewed the consular notification
issue in the Montoya case and have also addressed it in the Faulder
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, I will uphold the laws of the state of Texas
regardless of the nationality of the person involved,'' he said.
``People can't just come into our state and cold-blood murder
somebody. That's unacceptable behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Bush came under pressure to commute the death
sentences of convicted murderers Karla Faye Tucker and Henry Lee
Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was executed in February, the first woman to be put to
death in Texas since 1863.
</P>
<P>
   Bush commuted Lucas' sentence to life in prison in June, saying
questions raised about his case convinced him to do so. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
