<HEADER>
A2005 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT04-COX-1STLE     12-03 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT04-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT CLAIMS IT BUILT A BETTER JAVA MOUSETRAP
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    Eds: Adds words ``an implementation of'' to 2nd graf.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is not a crime under the antitrust laws to take
a competitor's technology and make a better version, even if the
competitor's business from that technology drains away, Microsoft
Corp. argued in federal court Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft lawyer asserted that after an implementation of Sun
Microsystems Inc.'s Java programming language failed to deliver on
its claims, Microsoft improved the version it had licensed,
mightily impressing the trade press and the software development
community.
</P>
<P>
   In cross-examining James Gosling, Sun's chief scientist and
Java's creator, attorney Tom Burt presented an e-mail message that
Gosling sent his colleagues at Sun after attending a 1996 Java
conference at Microsoft's Redmond, Wash., campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The really scary thing at the meeting was how much effort
they're putting into it 12 months after they licensed it,'' Gosling
wrote, referring to the Microsoft-written code built into the
company's Internet Explorer browser, known as a Java virtual
machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, on the whole they were doing a respectable job,''
Gosling conceded on the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's claims that Java, which works with operating systems
other than its dominant Windows, was not viable seemed to
contradict videotaped testimony Wednesday from Bill Gates in which
the company's chairman said he viewed the technology as a
``threat'' to Windows' future.
</P>
<P>
   Although Burt had initially argued that Java posed a dire threat
to Microsoft's Windows franchise, he switched gears on Thursday to
portray Java as a flawed technology that had never met its promise.
To make his case, he cited Sun's once highly confidential documents
that described Java's inadequacy as a ``write once, run anywhere''
substitute for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   When Burt repeatedly asked Sun's Gosling about Java's
shortcomings, Gosling repeatedly replied that the ability to run
Java everywhere was a ``goal'' that Sun sought to attain as it
constantly upgraded its software.
</P>
<P>
   When U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is
presiding over the case without a jury, chided Burt for posing
``cumulative'' questions to Gosling, Burt said he was seeking to
prove that Java posed ``competition for the hearts and minds of
(software) developers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Achieving portability of code across computer platforms is
tough, but our goal is to make that as easy as possible,'' Gosling
noted.
</P>
<P>
   On the courthouse steps, Tod Nielsen, who heads Microsoft's
relations with the outside developers, argued that it was
technically impossible to write a software program that will run
without changes on a host of computer platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out the promises were bigger than the facts,''
Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to back up Burt, Nielsen contended that the Java
version it built from scratch for Windows is technically better
than Sun's original version.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of letting the cancer patient die, we have a cure, and
the cure is Windows,'' Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   During a break in the proceedings, Gosling, somewhat of a cult
figure in the Java development community, told a reporter that he
had bought his first suit, a fashionable model with blue stripes,
for his appearance in court as a government witness. On Monday,
before taking the stand, Gosling had sat unrecognized among the
spectators wearing a T-shirt, jeans, and sandals.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
