<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2020 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     12-03 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'90S GAME IS WIN NOW: GET ROCKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several days ago, Tom Hicks was in his private jet, somewhere
over Kentucky, headed west for the Texas motherland. By air phone,
he was talking about a pending emergency, which had nothing to do
with his flight. Or, for that matter, the state of pitching in
Arlington after the Randy Johnson rejection 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy told me we were second on his list, but he was torn
between a baseball and a family decision,'' said the Rangers owner.
``When he chose Arizona, he chose family. I can accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks then mentioned, ``Bud.'' No, not the long-neck variety,
but Bud as in Selig, commissioner of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's called an emergency meeting of the owners for Thursday
\Rin Chicago\S,'' said Hicks. ``We truly have an emergency in
baseball. The dividing line grows wider and wider between the teams
that can spend and the teams that can't spend. It's down to a mere
handful of us in both leagues who are now active in free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   That owners' meeting was yesterday. Selig's concern over the
haves and the have-nots is certainly legitimate, but there is no
known solution, outside of blowing up the players' union. But the
players' union owns all the dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, by the way, went as far as saying, ``I'd love to be a
part of baseball trying to find a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   But here's an owner who this week alone saw his salary offer of
$50 million turned down by Randy Johnson. And some 30 minutes after
his conversation with me, the Hicks air phone was ringing again.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was Doug Melvin, seeking permission from Hicks to
sign Rafael Palmeiro to a $45 million contract. The approval came
swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks is a ``player.'' The Rangers are ``players.'' When Hicks
purchased the team last January, this was predicted. Baseball life
as we've always known it in Arlington _ just doing enough, but
never pushing the bottom line _ changed instantly because of Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the sale of the team didn't happen two years earlier. If
so, we wouldn't now be having a
how-do-the-Rangers-get-Roger-Clemens debate. The Rocket-ship would
already be parked in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks is obviously sincere in his worry about the overall
welfare of baseball. There is and will continue to be a negative
impact on all 30 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if only the strong can survive and prosper, what's a
Tom Hicks going to do? And what does the local fandom want him to
do? The answer to both is go for the throat.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why in the same week Bud Selig is calling an emergency
meeting on the disparity between rich and poor teams, Hicks had
nearly $100 million in contract offers on the table to two players.
For at least 20, if not more, of the 30 teams, that would be
financial suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks and team president Tom Schieffer also became very touchy
this week over criticism of another ticket-price hike for fans.
Schieffer even asked some local writers to stop by his office,
where he tried to show a projected financial loss of up to $14
million for the Rangers in 1999. In Minnesota, Kansas City,
Pittsburgh and on and on, those teams simply stopped the spending,
and ordered payroll cuts. They have no hope of making payroll ends
meet by generating money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks knows he does, starting with a TV sports network he will
launch. Which is why his commitment to winning in Arlington doesn't
wane.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Hicks, the Rangers are on a fast track in the
free-agency market, although the current talent on the team still
will run out of rail before it can become a Yankees-type winner.
</P>
<P>
   This prompts some to think in small-brain baseball terms _ that
a rollback in priority is necessary. In other words, be docile,
build with the farm system, and wait a couple of years to see what
happens.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but go tell that to a loyal fandom just hit with the third
ticket-price increase in three years. Tell it to the TV and radio
sponsors being asked to pay top dollar. Tell it to that corporation
that will soon pay about $10 million a year for naming rights at
the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the 1970s, either in baseball or in Arlington. The
one and only objective is to work on the fly in pulling together
the three key elements to winning _ farm system, free agency and
trades. There are Doug Melvin's marching orders.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers, it's about winning now with an eye on the
future. But fewer concessions can actually be made to the future.
</P>
<P>
   Which, by the way, is why I'll flip-flop my initial opinion on
trading Pudge Rodriguez for Clemens. A very tough call, yes. But
Clemens makes the '99 team better, and also the 2000 team better.
</P>
<P>
   Hold your breath, Mr. Melvin, and do the deal. The price of
winning is excruciating, but only those who can and will pay the
price, do the winning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
