<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2031 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-WAC-REPORT-TEX     12-03 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WAC-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND FINALE FOR A FAILED EXPERIMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Western Athletic Conference preparing for its last
football game as a 16-team global conglomerate, it seemed logical
to play this one partly for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Brigham Young coach LaVell Edwards, whose team will play Air
Force in the third and final championship game tomorrow, praised
the short-lived expansion league as being innovative and open to
new concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played the first of these things back in '96, the idea
was evidently to find the two guys with the least amount of hair,''
said Edwards, whose coaching opponent then was Wyoming's Joe
Tiller, now at Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' he said, ``I see they've changed the format to
where they just picked the two oldest guys.''
</P>
<P>
   While flattered at this comparison, Air Force's Fisher DeBerry
quickly clarified the issue by saying, ``Well, I ain't as old as
/he'' is.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there seemed a sentiment that the Cougars and
Falcons _ the most nationally visible teams throughout much of the
league's history _ were the perfect duo for the last title game.
</P>
<P>
   And a certain nostalgic air this week carried an ironic twist:
The schools to whom the name ``WAC'' means the most are mostly
those who will form the Mountain West Conference next year.
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight teams remaining in next year's WAC, only two _
UT-El Paso and Hawaii _ were members at the start of the 1990s, and
only one (UTEP) can trace its membership back to the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Any tears shed about this over here in the Central time zone are
unlikely to be induced by nostalgia ... and will dry quickly as
soon as somebody comes up with a TV contract and a locked-in bowl
deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Edwards and DeBerry, who have spent 56 years either as
assistants or head coaches at their respective schools,
unquestionably represent the WAC at its best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a better way to end this,'' Edwards said,
``than with BYU and Air Force _ two schools that have meant a great
deal to this league over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   When Edwards arrived at BYU as an assistant in '62, the Cougars
were running the single wing with a famed tailback named Eldon
``The Phantom'' Fortie. When Edwards became the head coach 10 years
later, he ran an offense that featured the nation's leading rusher,
Pete Van Valkenburg.
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned to the pass ... creating a ``Quarterback
Factory'' (Gary Sheide, Gifford Nielsen, Marc Wilson, Jim McMahon,
Steve Young, Robbie Bosco, Ty Detmer, John Walsh, Steve Sarkisian)
and 25 years of highlight films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen this league grow over the years into something I
think we can all be proud of,'' said Edwards, who personally
distinguished the WAC by winning a national championship in 1984.
``It's grown into a very exciting conference _ we helped kick off
the Fiesta Bowl, and got the Holiday Bowl started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think certain people are meant to be in a place at a certain
time, and maybe Fisher and I are examples of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Following in the footsteps of Ken Hatfield, the man who hired
him as an assistant 19 years ago, DeBerry has improbably turned a
military institution with rigid academic standards into a national
presence. Further, he accomplished it with a presumed-extinct
wishbone that has blossomed into the multipronged spread option.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a member of the WAC has meant a great deal to us over
the years, and we are grateful for the experience,'' he said. ``I
would just like to think that we have given something back.''
</P>
<P>
   So, a failed experiment's grand finale is a perfect match: the
league's best passing team against the best rushing team, and a
clash of the two top defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled to be here,'' Edwards said, ``except for one
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the wishbone.'' \Ntagtop:Whit Canning, (817) 390-7760
Quick hit Souvenir ticket stub
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Karl Benson said a sellout crowd is expected at Sam
Boyd Stadium in Las Vegas for the WAC title game. This is due
partly to the fact that BYU brings a lot of fans and also that the
stadium capacity has been reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``When BYU played here two years ago, they brought about 20,000
and we had a record crowd over 42,000,'' Benson said. ``Some of the
seats have been removed since then, and current capacity is about
36,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both schools have sold their 10,000 allotment, and BYU's sales
are going about as they did in '96.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson also used the occasion to reflect wryly on the breakup of
the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have national exposure in a good time slot \Rnoon, Central
time\S on ABC, so this is a real plus,'' he said. ``Unfortunately,
neither the WAC nor the Mountain West will likely be able to
duplicate this in the near future. For one thing, neither will have
a championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the league's bowl situation has remained fuzzy throughout
the year, both teams in the title game have accepted the bids they
were offered: The Cougars will play Tulane in the Liberty Bowl on
Dec. 31, while the Falcons will be part of a Christmas doubleheader
(Aloha-Oahu) in Hawaii.
The Buzz
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that the Cougars are often a slow-starting team while
Air Force is fond of getting the early jump, BYU linebacker Rob
Morris said the problem has been solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about us,'' he said. ``We hired a guy to come over
to the dorm and blow a bugle every day at dawn.''...
</P>
<P>
   The presumably pass-happy WAC produced six 1,000-yard running
backs this year _ Mike Anderson (Utah), Jaime Kimbrough (Fresno
State), Ronney Jenkins (BYU), Marques Brigham (Wyoming), Basil
Mitchell (TCU) and Rodnick Phillips (SMU). But for the first time
in several years, there was nary a 1,000-yard receiver. ...
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii closed an 0-12 year with losses to Northwestern (47-21)
and Michigan (48-13), then fired coach Fred vonAppen, whose
three-year tenure produced a 5-31 slate. ...
</P>
<P>
   Wading through a brutal 12-game schedule without a break, SMU
came up 5-7. Included in the adventure were losses to Tulane
(11-0), Air Force (10-1), Arkansas (9-2), Wyoming (8-3) and
Colorado State (8-4). The other two losses _ to Rice and Ole Miss _
were in overtime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
