<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WARNS MIDEAST LEADERS ABOUT THREAT TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A week before President Clinton travels to Israel
and Palestinian territory, the Clinton administration is warning
both Israeli and Palestinian leaders not to set back a delicate
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The warning followed Yasser Arafat's declarations that he will
create an independent Palestinian state in May and Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's threat to stop troop withdrawals in
retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said they are alarmed by the increasing rhetoric by
both men, while still holding out hope that violence will subside
in the Mideast and peace talks will go on as planned during a
marathon session at Maryland's Wye Plantation in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wye River accords include a clear set of commitments which
both sides agreed to fulfill ... and implementation should proceede
without any new positions,'' White House spokesman David Leavy said
Thursday in a clear criticism of Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Leavy then criticized Arafat, saying ``We are against all
uniteral actions, incuding a unilateral declaration of statehood.''
</P>
<P>
   Other US officials said it is too early to know whether the fury
will calm and troop withdrawals will continue from the West Bank.
They said Israel will be put to the test as it completes the next
pullout before President Clinton visits the region.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's cabinet has said that Palestinians must vow not to
call for an independent state in the spring and must publicly say
that Israel never agreed to free Palestinian prisoners who attacked
Israelis. Otherwise, the West Bank withdrawals will cease.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in the Gaza Strip Thursday, Arafat said
Netanyahu's cabinet had violated its agreement with ``an attempt to
avoid honest and accurate implementation of what was agreed upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Nabil Shaath declared the Israeli
conditions ``null and void.''
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, in Israel, Netanyahu said ``lynch mobs''
incited by Palestinian leaders had imperiled the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The latest jolts to the peace process came after Wednesday's
fatal stabbing of an Arab man in Jerusalem and the beating of an
Israeli soldier near Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu shook up many supporters of the peace process with a
threat to stop troop withdrawals unless Arafat publicly abandons
his calls for an independent state next May.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu continued to play to his right wing Thursday, inviting
the tough-talking leader of the National Religious Party, Education
Minister Yitzhak Levy, a chance to join his inner circle of
national security advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Netanyahu called the beating of the Israeli
soldier ``organized, orchestrated, planned in advance and fomented
by the Palestinian Authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they were uneasy about the
escalating rhetoric by both Netanyahu and Arafat, who had spoken of
each others as partners in peace after the excruciating peace talks
with Clinton in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials said that they still pressuring both sides to
honor the promises they made in the Wye agreement. ``We're working
to get this thing done and we still think it's going to get done,''
said one of the officials. All officials requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   US envoy Dennis Ross is scheduled to fly to Israel over the
weekend to try to quell the controversy and prepare for Clinton's
Dec. 12-15 visit.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress who follow the Mideast said they are
concerned by the recurring violence but do not expect a significant
problem in the peace process before Clinton's visit. ``When the
Israel government has made a commitment, such as (withdrawing from)
Hebron, it's been a long and tortured and difficult proces, they
take pride in ultimately fulfilling their promises,'' said Senator
Jack Reed, a Rhode Island Democrat who has visited Israel twice
this year.
</P>
<P>
   While expressing concern about the latest violence in the
region, Reed said, ``If you collected all the front-page stories of
every paper in the country that said the peace process was falling
apart in the last few years, you could wallpaper a pretty
good-sized room.''
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, aides who monitor the Mideast were divided
about Netanyahu's comments. Many said that the prime minister is
trying to stave off criticism from his right wing, which accuses
him of caving in to Palestinians. One congressional aide who
follows the region called Netanyahu's linkage of Arafat's comments
and the West Bank surrender ``a very big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   At Americans for Peace Now, a Washington group that has often
criticized the Israeli government, spokesman Lewis Roth said, ``I
tend to think Netanyahu made a significant declaration.'' He added
that the Clinton administration ``is really just looking to get
through this presidential visit to the area with everything
intact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
