<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2036 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-03 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNREPRESENTATIVE LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) ,
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Except for the spectacular flameout of House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, both parties in the Senate and House decided
this week to stick next year with their present leaders despite
last term's stumbling and skimpy legislative history.
</P>
<P>
   There was enough political restlessness to produce minor changes
in the second leadership tier. But besides the addition of Bob
Livingston as the new speaker, the top posts remained firmly in the
hands of men who represented the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   This happened despite shock waves set off by November's
unexpectedly pro-Democratic election and the unseemly scramble to
resolve the uncontrolled political quarrel over impeachment with
some semblance of dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers choose their congressional leaders for reasons that
often have more to do with personalities and the exchange of favors
than with national stature or philosophical bent. But it does seem
odd that collectively the present leadership teams are so
geographically unrepresentative of the country at large.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority in both the Senate and House is led by
men with their roots in a single region, the South. Livingston is
from Louisiana, Majority Leader Richard Armey and GOP whip Tom
DeLay, from Texas, and conference chairman J.C. Watts, from
Oklahoma. In the Senate, Majority Leader Trent Lott is from
Mississippi, his deputy Don Nickles, from Oklahoma, and conference
chairman Connie Mack, from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leadership is more diverse, but, with some
exceptions, heavily representative of states with smaller
populations that have little in common with the urban Northeast and
West Coast. Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle is from South
Dakota, Whip Harry Reid, from Nevada, and conference chairman
Barbara Mikulski, from Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt is from Missouri,
Democratic Whip David Bonior, from Michigan, and caucus chairman
Martin Frost, from Texas. Bonior, the most liberal of the group, is
the key exception, coming from a bustling, northern midwestern
state, the eighth most populous in the country. Martin comes from
Dallas in the nation's second most populous state, and Mikulski,
from urban Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   California, the most populous state, is not represented in the
leadership of either party. Nor is New York, the third largest
state. Texas is overrepresented _ by two Republicans and one
Democrat. Oklahoma, with only 1.2 percent of the national
population, has a top GOP insider in both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana, about to have the next speaker, has only 1.6 percent
of the population and ranks 22nd in size among the states.
Mississippi, with the Senate majority leader, has even less _ 1
percent of the population, for a ranking of 31st.
</P>
<P>
   South Dakota's Daschle represents the tiniest constituency. His
state is 45th in size with only 0.3 percent of the population. His
deputy Reid comes from further west than the others, but Nevada
with 0.6 percent of the population is only the 38th largest state.
</P>
<P>
   Geographically, this is a small power circle indeed. Does the
shortage of regional and philosophical diversity at the top of the
Senate and House matter much? Actually, it does, but mostly in
subtle ways.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of both parties earn and keep their posts by
accommodating the often-competing needs of their colleagues. Lott,
Daschle and Gephardt are renowned for patient efforts to reconcile
differing interests and reach compromises that can move legislation
forward. Livingston has a reputation of being in that mold as well.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they come to these roles carrying their own biases and
backgrounds, which are bound to mark their thinking and their
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The three Texans, who come from safe districts, are the most
obvious about this, unafraid to take categorical positions at odds
with the majority of their own troops and the needs of the country.
Where they come out in backroom negotiations may differ from their
public postures, but their public postures can still have an
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Armey is the most insensitive, unafraid to look ignorant by
saying such things as he had been to Europe once, so he didn't have
to go abroad again.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how hard good politicians try, they can never be
totally objective. They are creatures of all the influences and
impulses that have affected their lives and their careers. How can
a man from Mississippi really understand the complicated economic
and cultural pressures of northern urban ghettos? How can a rural
state midwesterner ever fully comprehend metropolitan demands for
federal help for mass transit?
</P>
<P>
   The majority of these leaders are disturbingly alike.
</P>
<P>
   They get competing views from their staffs, their colleagues and
the public. And philosophically they are not identical. But in
their hearts and minds they are of a political piece.
</P>
<P>
   They are from the old, politically powerful America _ the South
and the small towns _ not from the future America _ the vast
technology-driven East-West Coast population explosion. Eventually,
we are likely to pay a price for that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
