<HEADLINE>
GENE VARIANT HASTENS EFEFCTS OF HIV, RESEARCHERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Aids-Mutate)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About one in eight Americans carries genes that would lead them
to develop AIDS more rapidly if they were infected with the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV), scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Other genes have been identified that protect against the
progession of AIDS, or even against HIV infection in the first
place, but this is the first time researchers have found a gene
that accelerates HIV disease.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of whites and 43 percent of African-Americans
carry the gene variant, called CCR5-P1. But it takes a double dose
of the gene to provide the AIDS-promoting effect, and from 7 to 13
percent of Americans have two such variants.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have two copies of CCR5-P1 develop AIDS, on average,
about two years earlier than those who don't, the researchers said.
The genetic trait may explain many AIDS cases that occur within the
first three or four years after infection; most AIDS does not
develop until after an individual has harbored HIV for 10 to 12
years.
</P>
<P>
   The gene variant was discovered by analyzing 2,400 individuals,
about 1,900 of whom had been infected with HIV for varying periods
of time and 500 who were uninfected.
</P>
<P>
   The new finding, reported in the current Science, is the latest
in a fast-evolving series of discoveries about what scientists call
``host'' factors _ characteristics of the infected individual that
determine the course of disease, for good or ill, rather than
traits of the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Host factors are important in virtually every disease, even the
most deadly. For instance, not everyone exposed to the bacterium
that causes plague dies from it, nor does everyone infected with
poliovirus become paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   The CCR5 gene is important in AIDS because it directs the
synthesis of a receptor protein that sits on the surface of immune
cells. The receptor's normal function is to link up with
immune-system signalling chemicals called chemokines that are
important in inflammation and healing.
</P>
<P>
   However, the AIDS virus uses CCR5 to gain entry into
macrophages, the first type of immune cell it infects in the body.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Carrington, a National Cancer Institute geneticist and
coauthor of the new report, said the newly discovered variant may
promote AIDS by increasing the number of CCR5 receptors on the
surface of macrophages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is that you end up with lots of CCR5 receptors, so
the virus has more gateways into the cell,'' Carrington said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Carrington said the new finding probably has no immediate
usefulness for HIV-infected patients _ for instance, in determining
which ones should be treated more aggressively because they carry
the AIDS-promoting gene _ because there are probably many ``host
factors'' involved in HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``HIV is a multigene disease,'' she said. ``What we're learning
about the genetics of HIV disease probably can be applied to other
infectious diseases, such as hepatitis C. We're further along in
understanding the genetics of HIV disease than we are with any
other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
