<HEADLINE>
COURT OK'S MASS. SETTLEMENT WITH TOBACCO COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A Superior Court judge has approved Massachusettts'
$7.6 billion, 25-year settlement with the tobacco industry,
rejecting requests by anti-smoking leaders who wanted more time for
public scrutiny of the complex deal.
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex Judge Martha Sosman said she was approving Attorney
General Scott Harshbarger's request to drop his suit against Big
Tobacco becausue the deal was in Massachusetts' ``best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's multibillion suit was set to begin in February. In
the case he filed three years ago, Harshbarger was seeking $2.3
billion plus penalities for the Medicaid costs incurred by
Massachusetts for smoking related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling is a critical first step toward bringing the first
visible benefits of the agreement to the people of Massachusetts in
the spring of 1999,'' Harshbarger said. The state is expected to
receive an initial $98 million payment next March from tobacco
industry funds.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 20, Harshbarger, who was under heavy pressure from the
public health community and anti-smoking activists to reject the
pact, announced he was giving up his suit and buying into the $206
billion settlement negotiated between a handful of attorneys
generals and Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the deal, both in Massacusetts and nationally, had
urged Harshbarger to press the state's case because they felt it
was the strongest suit filed by an attorney general and stood a
good chance of winning and inflicting significant damage to the
cigarette industry.
</P>
<P>
   But in her decision Thursday to accept Harshbarger's request to
dismiss the suit, Sosman said the deal exceeded the financial
remedies she would have had the power to grant the state if a jury
had found the companies liable.
</P>
<P>
   Sosman also said the settlement offers some public health
remedies, such as marketing restrictions on the industry, that the
court could not have imposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made it crystal clear that this settlement is in the best
interest of the people of Massachusetts and will provide tangible
benefits to our state, to our children and to the public health for
generations to come,'' Harshbarger said. ``I'm grateful that she
agreed that the terms of this deal exceed what we might have been
able to achieve through a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosman's decision to accept the consent decree clears the way
for the tobaccco money to pour into Massachusetts' state treasurer,
but also marks what undoubtedly will be a fierce debate over on
where the money will be spent.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger and tobacco control leaders vowed a battle to make
sure the money goes to anti-smoking and related public health
programs. Even Governor Paul Cellucci, who has supported plans to
raid the state's current $66 million tobacco control program, has
said he too wants the funds to only go to public health programs.
He said it would not be used to reduce taxes.
</P>
<P>
   After the first check in March, the state will get a $263
million payment in 2000; $284 million in 2001; $341 million in
2002; $344 million in 203; $287 million from 2004 through 2007; and
$323 million in 2008 and every year afterward.
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Lois Pines, who had asked the court to hold
hearings on the issue before granting the decree, said she was
disappointed over the decision, and that she believes Sosman had
made up her mind before Thursday. Pines said she plans to file a
taxpayers suit to pressure state officials to use the money only
for anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt there are issues that were not before the court, so I
filed my requests so that all the folks who were not party to the
settlement could be heard,'' Pines said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1933EST &QL; 
