<SLUG> BC-FOOD-STAMP-CARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK COURT CLEARS WAY FOR FOOD STAMP CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York's top court on Thursday cleared the way
for the state to dramatically alter the way public assistance is
delivered to recipients of welfare benefits and food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than paying for groceries with food coupons, recipients
will be provided with electronic swipe cards. And instead of going
to one of a handful of facilities where cash benefits are
disbursed, recipients will be able to use their card at thousands
of ATM machines.
</P>
<P>
   The state expects the change will save up to $2 million monthly
while decreasing fraud and increasing privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to a grocery store and swipe your card,'' said attorney
David M. Cherubin of Albany. ``You don't have to take out a food
coupon booklet and immediately identify yourself to everyone around
as a recipient of government benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``electronic benefit transfer system'' has been operating in
a few locations in New York and officials hoped to have the program
running statewide by last summer.
</P>
<P>
   However, two competing firms, Transactive Corp. and Check
Cashers Association of New York, claimed the state had not followed
proper bidding procedures. A lower court annulled the $125 million
Citicorp Services contract, but a midlevel panel overturned that
ruling in a decision upheld Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals ruled unanimously that the competing firms
lacked legal standing and therefore had no grounds to contest the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rule of law which extended standing to all and any taxpayers
to contest the manner in which state agencies award contracts might
seriously disrupt state operations,'' Judge George Bundy Smith
wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Albany attorney Hermes Fernandez, who represented Check Cashers,
said the ruling could have a dramatic impact on state contracting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have really restricted who can challenge state
contracts,'' Fernandez said. ``They have really restricted the
playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Madden, a spokesman for the state Office of Temporary and
Disability Assistance, said the program would begin early next year
on Staten Island and will gradually expand statewide. Madden said
the state hoped to have the entire state on the system by the
spring of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a win for the taxpayers and it is great for the
recipient population,'' Madden said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope the new system will eventually eliminate food
coupons, which are often stolen, lost or traded for drugs. They
also expect the new system to provide greater security; while
stolen food stamps can easily be used, a stolen swipe card is
useless unless the thief knows the secret personal identification
number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 1934EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
