u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COD-COLLAPSE-BOS &LR;      12-03 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COD-COLLAPSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND-LARGEST COD FISHERY IN RUIN, RESEARCHERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ New England's second-leading cod fishing ground has
collapsed from years of overfishing, according to a scientific
report released Thursday, forcing regulators to consider severe new
limits on cod landings that will hurt hundreds of fishing families
from Scituate to eastern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing regulators had hoped to avoid draconian measures to save
the cod in the Gulf of Maine, which includes near-shore waters of
northern Massachusetts, because so many small-boat fishermen rely
on the dwindling cod to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   But the report from the Multispecies Monitoring Committee, a
scientific panel that surveys groundfish, made it clear that delays
in tough action have brought the Gulf of Maine cod near ruin, with
record low fish populations and five times more fishing than the
scientists suggest for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few choices for the Gulf of Maine right now and
all of them are going to have an impact on people,'' said Eric
Smith, a member of the New England Fishery Management Council,
which must decide next week how to save the cod fishery. ``It's
very, very important to the communities of Maine and New Hampshire
and northern Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the Gulf of Maine fishing ground completes the
decimation of a fish species once so bountiful that Cape Cod was
named for it and Massachusetts legislators hung a sacred cod in
their halls. But, four years ago, the historically even more
abundant cod fishing ground on Georges Bank collapsed, forcing
closures and other restrictions that continue today.
</P>
<P>
   Depletion of the cod in the Gulf of Maine, which extends up to
200 miles offshore from Cape Cod to eastern Maine, followed the
Georges Bank closures as the bigger Georges Bank boats moved to the
Gulf of Maine and traditional Gulf of Maine fishermen increased
their efforts as cod prices increased.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, several environmental groups called on the Fishery
Management Council to bite the bullet and slash Gulf of Maine cod
fishing by 80 percent next year, arguing that though the cuts will
hurt fishermen, they could allow the fishing ground to recover
years from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story is tragic, but not a surprise,'' said Peter
Shelley, senior attorney at the Conservation Law Foundation in
Boston. He said the new limits on fishing ``will devastate the
coastal cod fishery, but there are no alternatives. The fishery
essentially must be closed.''
</P>
<P>
   But fishermen, increasingly hemmed in by restrictions on their
livelihood, called on regulators to consider the damage to fishing
communities if cod catches are deeply reduced. They said some of
the 214 small boat fishermen on Massachusetts' Cape Ann would be
forced to give up fishing altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would put Massachusetts fishermen from Scituate to the
New Hampshire border out of business for good,'' said Angela
Sanfilippo of the Gloucester (Mass.) Fishermen's Wives Association.
``To say that you can go catch everything else except cod is total
madness because cod is the permanent fish,'' meaning that cod are
the economic mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Fishery Management Council, which meets on Dec.
9 in Wakefield, Mass. to decide how to respond to the cod crisis,
had hoped that it wouldn't come to this. For two years, fisheries
biologists have warned that the cod population was sinking rapidly,
but regulators hoped modest restrictions, such as a 400 pound limit
on daily catch, would be enough.
</P>
<P>
   In August, faced with a roomful of angry fishermen, council
members decided to delay further cod fishing restrictions in hopes
that Thursday's Multispecies Monitoring Committee report would
contain good news.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the report showed that fishermen caught more than twice
the safe limit of Gulf of Maine cod this year, removing 82 percent
of the population from the sea. With sexually mature cod at record
lows, the committee recommended that next year's Gulf of Maine cod
limit should be as low as 782 tons for the year, compared to the
4,075 tons fishermen caught this year.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the council's problems, the report also saw signs of
renewed overfishing on Georges Bank where cod landings exceeded the
planned catch by more than 30 percent. As a result, the council may
have to impose more restrictions in addition to existing measures
such as the closing of 6,000 square miles to groundfishing.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists said Thursday that the best way to achieve the
cutbacks in the Gulf of Maine would be to close areas much like
Georges Bank. Many fishermen oppose that approach, since it also
closes areas to catching other groundfish such as haddock that
require the same types of nets.
</P>
<P>
   But Doug Hopkins, an attorney with the Environmental Defense
Fund as well as a member of the New England Fishery Management
Council, said the council had already tried the weaker measures
that fishermen preferred _ and they failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The council has run out of time and excuses to not take action
to protect the Gulf of Maine cod,'' said Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   However, Smith, a Connecticut state fishing regulator and
council member, said the council can't forget the fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gulf of Maine cod situation is dire, but it means the
council has to be very deliberate in how it weighs the overarching
conservation need relative to the impact it will have on society,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
