<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION SET IN INDONESIA BUT PROTESTS PERSIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The government announced a date for
national elections today, but any hope that this would be received
positively by student protesters was short lived.
</P>
<P>
   The government set June 7 for elections for a new House of
Representatives. It also said that on Aug. 29, four months earlier
than previously scheduled, it would convene the highest legislative
body, the People's Consultative Assembly, to elect a new president.
</P>
<P>
   But students who have been pressing President B.J. Habibie for
swifter democratic reforms continued their protests and blocked
Jakarta's main thoroughfare Thursday afternoon, demanding the
arrest of Suharto, the former President, on corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   Students have held protests throughout the capital almost daily
since a clash with soldiers and the police in central Jakarta
mid-November left 16 dead and scores injured. In addition to
Suharto's arrest, student demands include returning the army to its
barracks and an end to its role in political and economic affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
