<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EURO-NATIONS IN SURPRISE CUT OF SHORT-TERM RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eleven European nations unexpectedly cut short-term
interest rates Thursday, a coordinated attempt to spur their
economies and ward off the ill effects of the Asian and Latin
American financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   It was yet another sign that economic policy-makers and
investors still fear a global downturn. In the United States,
shares fell for the third time in four days amid concern that
Brazil is failing to take steps to avert a meltdown of South
America's largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 184 to close at 8879. The
index is now down 495 points, or 5.3 percent, from its Nov. 23 high
of 9374.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that US investors were reacting to developments in
Brazil rather than in Europe. Brazilian lawmakers rejected a tax
bill designed to help shrink the country's deficit, casting doubt
on whether the country will meet the requirements for gaining
international aid to prevent a recession.
</P>
<P>
   The European action gave investors an early look at how the
world will change with the arrival of the euro _ the new European
currency _ which debuts on January 1.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 nations that cut rates are the same ones that are
adopting the euro. In moving to a single currency, central banks in
each nation will transfer the authority to set interest rates to a
European Central Bank. Coordinated interest rate cuts, which are
now uncommon, will be the rule in the future, and the European
Central Bank could challenge the US Federal Reserve as the leading
player in world markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are clearly going to be two strong central banks, and
there's a lot of speculation about whether the Fed or the central
bank of Europe will be the stronger of the two,'' said John
Burgess, chief investment officer for bonds at Bankers Trust Global
Investment Management in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The rate cut Thursday was a surprise, though many analysts had
expected the European banks to cut interest rates later in December
or shortly after the euro begins trading in January.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the 11 European nations cut their key short-term interest
rate to 3 percent. The holdout was Italy, which cut its rate to 3.5
percent from 4 percent. Analysts said Italy was expected to bring
its rates in line with the other euro nations in the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Rates before the cuts had varied throughout the region, from
3.69 percent in Ireland to 3.2 percent in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 countries adopting the euro are Austria, Belgium,
Ireland, Italy, Finland, France, Germany, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Spain and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Setting a uniform interest rate is a necessary step to launching
the euro. In addition, banks have been under politcal pressure to
cut rates so that Europe's high unemployment rates do not rise
further. But some central banks, particularly Germany's Bundesbank,
had argued that economic conditions were not yet right to make the
move.
</P>
<P>
   The European banks cut an interest rate that is analogous to the
US Federal Reserve's federal funds rate, the rate that US banks
charge each other for overnight loans. Lenders usually raise or
lower other interest rates in tandem with the federal funds rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian flu has gotten to Europe as well, and the banks
needed to do this to escape recession,'' said Peter Cardillo, chief
strategist at Westfalia Investments in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Sinai, chief global economist at Primark Decision
Economics in Boston, predicted further interest rate cuts in Europe
and the United States because of a ``risky'' economic picture. ``I
think this is a general shift by central banks to lower rates
designed to promote growth, a major change from the religion of
fighting inflation that has characterized them for the past seven
or eight years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sinai said US stocks were falling because they had become
overvalued. Using price-to-earnings ratios he described as
``agressive,'' he calculated that the Dow Jones industrial average
was fairly valued in the range of 7800 to 9200. The midpoint of
that range is 8500, which is still below Thursday's close.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our notion: that we're in a correction of the equity
market,'' Sinai said. ``It won't be 20 percent, but it could be
sizeable, five to ten percent. It simply got too rich.''
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, central bank president Hans Tietmeyer said the rate
cut reflected the worsening outlook for European economies. ``The
coordinated rate cut could lead to a reduction in the current
pessimism and a reduction in financial market turbulence,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
