<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WATER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MAKES WATER-IMPROVEMENT LOANS AVAILABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ President Clinton Thursday shifted his focus
from battles in Washington to the safety of the nation's water
supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the water our children drink, Americans
cannot be too vigiliant,'' Clinton said in announcing nearly $800
million in new, low-interest loans to help states &UR;  &LR; upgrade their
water systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the sort of thing that we ought to be doing in America
_ tending to America's business, reaching across party lines,
looking into the future, thinking about our children. I think it is
a very important day,'' said Clinton, who shared the stage with
Republican US Senator John Chafee and several of the state's
leading Democratic politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came here to announce the release of $775 million in
low-interest loans to 50 states and US territories to help
communities upgrade their water systems. Massachusetts will get the
fourth largest loan, $28.7 million, which is less than only
California, Texas and New York.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Massachusetts will get more than $1 million in
grants from an additional $93.8 million the Environmental
Protection Agency is providing to states to help them monitor
drinking water quality, enforce standards, and provide technical
assistance to local communities.
</P>
<P>
   The new, tougher standards for drinking water, and the money
that goes with them, are an outgrowth of amendments passed in 1996
to the Safe Drinking Water Act. The new regulations are aimed at
protecting the nation's water supply against cryptosporidium, a
microscopic parasite, as well as other disease-causing microbes and
potentially harmful byproducts of the water treatment process.
</P>
<P>
   A cryptosporidium outbreak in Milwaukee in 1993 sickened 400,000
people, hospitalized more than 4,000 and caused more than 50 deaths
among people with weakened immune systems. Clinton said the new
standards are intended to ``ensure that no community ever has to
endure an outbreak like the one the people of Milwaukee suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Disinfectants used to treat such contaminants can combine with
natural organic material in water to create byproducts, some of
which cause cancer or birth defects in laboratory animals. The new
standards will require improved treatment practices in water
systems serving 140 million people nationwide, reducing exposure to
these byproducts by 25 percent, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The president seemed to bask in the friendly reception he found
in this seacoast city.
</P>
<P>
   After touring a water treatment plant, he stopped his motorcade,
got out and shook hands with some of the hundreds of people who
lined the streets. And after a speech in Fort Adams State Park, he
lingered long after the program had ended to shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   However, along his motorcade route, there were signs of the
problems that awaited his return. Scattered protesters hoisted
placards that read, ``Bill Clinton, Role Model for American
Youth?'' and ``B.Clinton, A Stain on American History.''
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, Clinton was in the company of friends. US
Representative Patrick Kennedy, a Democrat from Rhode Island,
introduced himself to the crowd as a ``staunch supporter'' of
Clinton. And in a comment filled with echoes of the White House
strategy in the current impeachment environment, Kennedy said:
``Mr. President, you've never backed down from a good fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to New England came as his administration is
suing the Massachusetts Water Resources Authority for the MWRA's
refusal to install a $180 million filtration system in its new $261
million treatment plant to be built in Marlborough. MWRA officials
dispute assertions federal law requires the filtration plant.
</P>
<P>
   The New England regional administrator for the Environmental
Protection Agency, John P. DeVillars, said, ``It's a sad irony that
on the day the president comes to New England to raise the
standards for America, the capital city of New England is almost
alone in the nation in failing to meet existing standards.''
</P>
<P>
   But Governor Paul Cellucci, whose administration plans to adopt
the rules Clinton announced as soon as possible, said DeVillars's
office ``is way off-base here. They want us to spend a lot of money
that will cause our ratepayers to pay more, and it's unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe reporter Peter Howe contributed to this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
