<HEADER>
A2084 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SANDERS-T     12-03 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SANDERS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Deion Sanders walked without a limp yesterday
and said ``not to count me out'' for the Cowboys' game Sunday
against the New Orleans Saints. To prepare for the possibility of
playing for the first time since Nov. 22 against Seattle, Sanders
plans to jog today to test his sprained left big toe.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, however, continued to conduct business as if
Sanders would not be able to return punts, if he should play. They
signed former Pro Bowl punt returner Tyrone Hughes yesterday,
watched him flawlessly catch kicks, then immediately tabbed him as
their punt returner for Sunday in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very comfortable with him back there,'' said special
teams coach Joe Avezzano, whose employers also made phone calls to
Mel Gray and Kelvin Martin about the club's punt-return duties.
``Our No. 1 priority is not to lose the game by making bad plays
bobbling the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, who made the Pro Bowl as a punt returner in 1993, will
earn roughly $19,000 a game. Several factors will determine how
many games he plays, including his own ability and how comfortable
Sanders feels when he is healthy again. Cowboys coach Chan Gailey
said Hughes might also return kickoffs, depending on how he works
out at the position today.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes will make his Cowboys debut against the team he had much
of his success with. While with the Saints from 1991-1996, Hughes
led the league in punt-return yards in 1993, and in kickoff return
yards from 1994-96. He holds the league record for most kickoff
return yards in a season (1,791) and most kickoff return yards in a
game (304).
</P>
<P>
   Because he has been strictly a returner, Hughes, 28, has found
it hard to stay on NFL rosters. A defensive back at Nebraska,
Hughes started just seven games at the position with the Saints,
and none with the Chicago Bears in 1997. The Bears released him
following last season, and the Baltimore Ravens released him in
training camp this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said yesterday that he had spent much of his time this
fall working out in the mornings, playing golf in the afternoons,
and playing with his daughter. He said the Cowboys called him last
night, and he hopped on a plane in time to take a physical and
participate in yesterday's workout.
</P>
<P>
   He fielded about 20 punts before watching the rest of the
practice from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get into the scout-team role, but they slid me
off to the side because they didn't want me to get hurt,'' Hughes
said. ``I wanted to be able to do something, you know, not feel
like I'm stealing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the New Orleans native said it'll be good to return to play
in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll have to get the tickets lined up again,'' he
said. ``I don't know how long they'll keep me. But I'm happy to be
here. With the \Rexpansion\S Cleveland thing coming up next year, I
just want to make a good impression.''
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith tried his luck fielding punts yesterday. The fun
didn't last long. After Smith fell awkwardly on his shoulder
following one kick, an uneasy-looking Chan Gailey whisked his star
running back off the field. Smith, by the way, would break a tie
with Marcus Allen for career rushing touchdowns with his next
score. Both have 123.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Hughes on the roster, the Cowboys waived
free-agent rookie linebacker Myron Smith, who has not played this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
