A2086 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLMONEY-12-04-COX     12-03 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLMONEY-12-04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEC MAJORITY SAYS TO LET CLINTON AND DOLE OFF THE HOOK
 &HT;    420&AMP;add
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- President Clinton and former Senate Majority
Leader Bob Dole shouldn't have to repay millions of taxpayer
dollars to the U.S. treasury, most members of the Federal Election
Commission agreed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC staff had concluded that the Democratic president and
his Republican challenger each broke the legal spending limit in
his 1996 presidential bid by arranging for his political party to
pay for TV ads that helped him. The career lawyers and accountants
recommended that Clinton be forced to repay $7 million and Dole to
repay $17.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the FEC regulations that Clinton and Dole were accused of
breaking are too ambiguous, said four of the six political
appointees who run the commission.
</P>
<P>
   One was Democrat Danny McDonald. Three others -- Republicans
David Mason and Lee Ann Elliott and Democrat Karl Sandstrom -- went
further and said the rules are so badly written that they should
not be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   During the commission's five hours of deliberation Thursday,
Mason described the rules as ``vague,'' and Sandstrom said the
standard was ``fuzzy.''
</P>
<P>
   Formal votes on pending motions to dismiss virtually all of the
findings will be conducted Wednesday or Thursday. It would take
only three members to block any repayment order.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all practical purposes, that would mean that spending
limits are dead,'' lamented Don Simon, general counsel to Common
Cause, a national anti-corruption group that endorsed the staff
report. ``The commissioners were appointed because it was thought
they would defend the interests of their own party, and on this
matter, they can join together and defend both.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheer size of the personal debts that such orders would load
on the shoulders of Clinton and Dole might have swayed the
commissioners against strict enforcement, said Trevor Potter, a
former chairman of the FEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``''The amounts were unprecedentedly large,'' Potter said.
``When the stakes are high, commissioners want to be on very firm
grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   In other probes of the 1996 campaigns:
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans announced they won't include campaign-finance
charges in their ongoing impeachment probe of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno is expected to announce by Dec. 7
whether a preliminary probe she conducted as a result of the FEC
staff report has convinced her to ask for an independent counsel to
conduct a criminal probe of Clinton and the Democrats. Dole isn't
covered by the independent counsel laws.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   If the commission eliminates every charge of excess advertising
and polling, the repayment demands would drop to about $70,000 for
Clinton and $1.2 million for Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Then the commission will discuss whether to eliminate or trim
those remaining repayment orders, Thomas said. After that, it will
decide whether to approve a separate recommendation by its staff
that Dole refund to news media and the Secret Service more than $1
million in overcharges for traveling with Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may decide to slice the apple several ways before we are
done,'' Thomas said. If any of the staff's recommendations survive,
the campaigns can appeal to the commission itself and then to the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Lyn Utrecht, a Washington attorney representing the Clinton
campaign, said, ``I think, ultimately, the commissioners will deal
with this in new regulations for the next election.''
</P>
<P>
   The process of adopting new regulations will begin later this
month, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, a former assistant to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., dominated Thursday's debate with repeated charges that
various FEC regulations were neither ``convincing nor
comprehensible'' or may include ``a constitutionally impermissible
standard for us to use at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff relied on ``vague standards'' and asked the commission
to apply ``a fuzzy standard,'' said Sandstrom, a new Democratic
member.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that some FEC rules are ``hardly clear,'' Thomas
told them the reason is that in the mid-1980s, he and the other two
Democrats who wanted rules with more clarity found out they
couldn't get the necessary fourth vote from any of the three
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming Thomas' explanation, Elliott described herself as one
of the Republican opponents who would not budge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have voted to put them in the regulations,''
Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
