u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOLIDAYS-CHELSEAHO     12-03 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOLIDAYS-CHELSEAHOTEL06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 6
 &HT;    From sweet to shabby, two hotels run gamut
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few blocks from the burgeoning gallery district of
West Chelsea, in Chelsea proper, are two hotels that are about as
similar as Sister Wendy and Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   One look at the lobby of the historic Chelsea Hotel, and you
know which one is Madonna. The Wendy of the pair is not really even
a hotel, but a nonprofit Catholic guest house.
</P>
<P>
   Known as The Leo House, it was established in 1899 by the St.
Raphael Society and has occupied this eight-story building since
1926. It has its own chapel and a priest on call, and many guests
are clerics. But The Leo House welcomes everybody, and numerous
academics, students and budget-conscious travelers (including art
curators) over the years have been pleased to find a clean, safe
place in New York that is well under $100 per night.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect glamour or frills. The lobby furniture looks like
granny's hand-me-downs, and the rooms meet minimum requirements. A
single bedroom is just that: one twin bed, a desk, chair and
television. (Remotes cost extra.) The bathroom _ be sure to request
one with a shower, unless you want to share _ is just big enough to
turn around in. At $68 a night, who's complaining?
</P>
<P>
   There are unexpected bonuses, however. The garden in the back is
a respite of green from city concrete. The $5, all-you-can-eat
breakfast buffet _ pancakes, French toast, oatmeal, muffins, fruit
_ is enough to fill you up for the better part of the day. And this
guest house exudes a sweetness of spirit unexpected in hard-edged
New York. That is a luxury you probably won't find even in the most
hospitable of the high-end hotels.
</P>
<P>
   For an experience in contrast, check out (or into) the Chelsea
Hotel. Steeped in history of a different kind, this hotel has been
the domain of the creative spirit for a century. The guest list
twinkles with literary and musical lights: Mark Twain, Thomas
Wolfe, Arthur Miller, Virgil Thompson, Bob Dylan. On the dark side,
Sex Pistol Sid Vicious killed his girlfriend in their room, which
has been dismantled. Artists of various persuasions still call the
Chelsea home.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1882 as a cooperative apartment, it was clearly once a
looker. The wrought-iron balconies on the front and the staircase
inside are among the last vestiges of its former glory. Today, the
400-room hotel, still partly residential, exudes a shabby, bohemian
air. It's not just the art of dubious merit crammed into the lobby
and hung in the corridors, but the assortment of people who hang
out here.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with its creative clientele, no two rooms are
decorated alike. Author Pete Hamill, who had occupied one suite I
visited, would probably have disapproved of its current chartreuse
and hot pink color scheme. At $150 a night, you sleep here for the
history.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Leo House, 332 W. 23rd St., 1-800-732-2438.
Chelsea Hotel, 222 W. 23rd St., 212-243-3700.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
