<HEADER>
A2094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOLIDAYS-CHELSEA06     12-03 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOLIDAYS-CHELSEA06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 6
 &HT;    Gritty West Chelsea winning over art set
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Aleen and Michael Pierce stood at the corner of 23rd
and 10th Avenue, looking a bit bewildered. As we waited for the
light to change, she asked a fellow tourist plaintively, ``Where
are all the boutiques?''
</P>
<P>
   Seems the Pittsburgh couple had intended to visit SoHo, the art
district that has become boutique heaven, and ended up instead in
West Chelsea, the industrial area that is fast becoming a hot new
art gallery district.
</P>
<P>
   Come back in a year or two, guys. There should be boutiques
aplenty. Signs advertising gallery space for lease are ubiquitous.
Cute little restaurants have sprouted. The sounds of hammers and
drills reverberate from apartment buildings on the edge of the
district that are clearly on their way to becoming co-ops. Can
Dolce &AMP; Gabana be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   Unlike SoHo, which took several decades to make the transition
from industrial lofts to chic shopping, West Chelsea is changing at
lightning speed. No sooner did a few major galleries, like Paula
Cooper, a pioneer in SoHo, and Matthew Marks, transform a couple of
garages into elegant white boxes two years ago, than a gold
rush-like migration began.
</P>
<P>
   Already, about 80 galleries occupy storefronts and low-rise
buildings in the area running from 14th to 26th streets between
10th Avenue and the Hudson River. They include some of the most
familiar names of the contemporary art gallery scene and some of
the trendiest, all mediums, definitely serious.
</P>
<P>
   The shift is such that Carrie Przybilla, the High Museum of
Art's curator of modern and contemporary art, finds herself
spending more time in Chelsea than SoHo when she visits New York.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, West Chelsea is still a work in progress, a collage of
unlikely neighbors. It is not as architecturally appealing or
visually stimulating as SoHo _ yet. Call it bleak meets sleek. Auto
repair shops abut gallery storefronts. An abandoned train trestle
looms overhead. This has got to be the only place in town where you
can get your car washed (if you are nuts enough to drive in New
York) and go gallery-hopping while you wait.
</P>
<P>
   You still need to consult a map (in guides usually available at
the galleries) to find all the spread-out venues, though the
occasional limo parked in front and the new glass facades are
reliable signs. But if you fancy yourself the urban pioneer, or are
actually intent on seeing art, you will enjoy tramping up and down
these otherwise unpeopled streets.
</P>
<P>
   Gallery owners actually like West Chelsea's grit. Fed up with
the, well, commercial ambiance of SoHo (as well as the soaring
rents), they figure that visitors are going to be at least a little
serious if they make the effort to make the rounds in a
neighborhood where art is still the sole reason to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't concentrate in SoHo. I like this environment much
better,'' says Caelum Gallery owner Misuzu Takemoto, who took a
spot in the 10-story Wolf Building, formerly a book bindery, in
February.
</P>
<P>
   As a reminder that art has a way of changing places, the odor of
dead sea creatures had replaced any vestige of glue or paper during
my visit. The culprit: a vessel at Caelum constructed of dried fish
and filled with video monitors.
</P>
<P>
   If the Wild Lily Tea Room, a sliver of a space next door to Max
Protetch Gallery, is a sign of kind of commercial adjuncts to come,
then Chelsea will someday be as much a pedestrian pleasure as the
most distinctive New York neighborhoods. Inez Kim and her staff
serve tea and goodies in a long narrow room as serene and elegant
as a Japanese garden. In fact, you can see a quiet pool when you
peer into the window. Ceramic plates are shaped like lily pads, and
you can take tea in artist-made cups and pot, which are for sale as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I opened in here in September after looking all over town,''
Kim said. ``I chose Chelsea because of the cutting-edge galleries.
If people are interested in art, they'll be interested in food. Tea
is cultural. It has a lot of depth.''
</P>
<P>
   The aesthetic of the tearoom has a kinship with the irregular,
gray, rough-cut rock markers that line 22nd Street. ``7000 Oaks,''
an installation by the late Joseph Beuys, is sponsored by the DIA
Center for the Arts. The grand dame of the neighborhood and a locus
for avant-garde art, DIA set down roots in West Chelsea in 1987,
long before it was anything approaching trendy.
</P>
<P>
   It is a quiet presence, too classy to say, ``I told you so.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   DIA Center for the Arts, 548 W. 22nd St. 212-989-5566.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Lily Tea Room, 511 W. 22nd St. 212-691-2258.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Cooper Gallery, 534 W. 21st, Street. 212-255-1105.
</P>
<P>
   Caelum Gallery, 526 W. 26th St. 212-924-4161.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Marks galleries, 523 W. 24th St. and 522 W. 22nd. St.
212-243-0200.
</P>
<P>
   Solex, a French bistro, 10th Ave. at W. 23rd St. 212-627-1331.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
