<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACHBUZZ-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Always in a holiday mood
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTWELL, Ga. _ You could say Hartwell Mayor Joan Saliba was
first in the neighborhood to have her Christmas tree up this
season. It's been up since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided seven years ago not to take it down,'' Saliba,
70, told us Thursday. ``I have a beautiful artificial tree and
beautiful ornaments, so I just put it in the corner of the living
room. I just don't light it the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to see it when they come by in July. Everyday here
is Jesus' birthday!''
</P>
<P>
   Saliba, mayor for 20 years in the town about 100 miles north of
Atlanta, says builders are catching onto her idea. ``Some new
houses here come complete with a living room closet where you can
store your tree without taking it down,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Yuletide shopping for the grandmother is also a snap. ``I just
give my kids and grandkids my credit card and tell them to go out
and get what they want for themselves and put it under the tree.
It's always a surprise to see what I give them.''
</P>
<P>
   Her Honor only has two stipulations: ``It has to be
gift-wrapped, and they have to purchase it here in Hartwell. I have
to support that local economy, you know!''
</P>
<P>
   `Full' speed ahead
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two weeks after author Tom Wolfe left town, his
Atlanta-based ``A Man in Full'' continues to burn up sales charts
at local bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hot every day,'' Thom Bales said of sales at Border's
Books &AMP; Music, the Atlanta store where Wolfe signed 2,000 copies
during his visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doing superb. It's the No. 1 book in our store for the
holidays,'' said Sue Tierney of Barnes &AMP; Noble in Atlanta. ``It's
not only No. 1, it's an extraordinarily strong No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   At 13 Chapter 11 bookstores around metro Atlanta, the novel has
sold 5,076 copies, according to the chain's Elizabeth Wilson.
``It's continuing to do extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantans aren't the only readers who've taken to the novel.
It's No. 1 on The New York Times Bestseller List.
</P>
<P>
   Emery on the record
</P>
<P>
   He never had a hit record, but Ralph Emery is as much of a
Nashville legend as the Grand Ole Opry. The former all-night DJ and
Nashville Network talk show host has been on the inside of the
country music industry since the 1950s, collecting
behind-the-scenes tales about Loretta Lynn, Chet Atkins, Vince
Gill, Patsy Cline and a jukebox full of other artists.
</P>
<P>
   He's put his tales together in ``The View From Nashville: On the
Record With Country Music's Greatest Stars'' and is in the Atlanta
area today and Saturday to sign copies.
</P>
<P>
   The chatty memoir shares Emery's feelings about such events as
Faron Young's suicide, the messy battle over Conway Twitty's estate
and the making of the Judds. Catch him from 7 to 8:30 tonight at
Chapter 11 books at Peachtree Battle Shopping Center or noon to 2
p.m. Saturday at Chapter 11 Books in Gainesville, Ga., (Thompson
Bridge store).
</P>
<P>
   Not just another face
</P>
<P>
   ``Mona Lisa'' has nothing on Atlantan Anita Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Thomas' portrait, painted by Alabama artist Nall,
will be unveiled at the Louvre. Nall, who has done portraits of
Ringo Starr and Prince Albert of Monaco, is having the Thomas
painting included in his exhibit at the Paris museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the portrait, I'm wearing a lace antique dress and a large
straw gardener's hat trimmed with roses, lilies and cornflowers,''
said Thomas, the former jewelry designer Anita Mobley. ``And I'm
holding a Bo Peep-style staff. Bo Peep is the name my grandchildren
call me, so Nall titled the portrait after this nursery rhyme
character.''
</P>
<P>
   The artist, who lives part time in France with his wife, Tuscia,
met Thomas and her husband, Michael, last year on a ski trip to
Aspen, Colo. Michael commissioned Nall to paint his wife's
portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen members of the Thomas clan will be on hand for the
Paris unveiling. But Thomas won't be wearing the dress in the
portrait. She will have on a blue Chanel, also a gift from her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: Marylin Johnson, Miriam Longino and Tom Sabulis
</P>
