<HEADLINE>
`60 MINUTES II' IS SET FOR JAN. 13 DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS announced Thursday that the new CBS News program ``60
Minutes II,'' a spinoff of the 30-year-old Sunday evening news
magazine program, will make its debut on Wednesday, Jan. 13, at 9
p.m., and will have Wednesdays from 9 to 10 p.m. as its regular
time slot.
</P>
<P>
   The new show has four correspondents: Dan Rather, the anchor and
managing editor of ``CBS Evening News''; two CBS News
correspondents, Bob Simon and Vicki Mabrey, and Charlie Rose, who
will also continue as producer and host of his weeknight interview
program for public television. The executive producer, Jeff Fager,
was most recently the executive producer of ``CBS Evening News.''
</P>
<P>
   The new program faced potential competition from NBC's
``Dateline'' if the network moved that program from 8 to 9 p.m. But
in reshuffling its prime-time lineup this week, NBC did not move
the Wednesday edition of ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Hewitt, the executive producer of ``60 Minutes,'' and others
inside CBS News opposed an added version when the idea was first
broached, fearing it would dilute the franchise. But the original
program dependably draws such a large audience that CBS executives
wanted to extend its reach to another night.
</P>
</TEXT>
