<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-INJECTION-TRIAL-     12-03 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-INJECTION-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ON TRIAL FOR INJECTING SON WITH HIV TO AVOID CHILD-SUPPORT
PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Ill.)  (bl) 
 By JO THOMAS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. CHARLES, Mo. _ Brian Stewart, a hospital laboratory
technician, never gave his little son a birthday present. Instead,
prosecutors say, when the baby was 11 months old, Stewart secretly
gave him an injection of blood infected with HIV, hoping to kill
the boy and avoid paying child support.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, described by his doctor as a cheerful, energetic child,
started losing weight and running fevers in 1996 at the age of 5.
Shortly afterward, he was diagnosed with AIDS. Now 7, he attends
school and stays alive on a round-the-clock regimen of tube
feedings and medications. His father is on trial here in the St.
Charles County Circuit Court on charges of first-degree assault.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Ross Buehler, contends that at the time the
child contracted the virus, his father could have safely assumed
that the child would die.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's lawyer, Joseph Murphy, has called the case a
``tragedy'' but not a crime. In his opening statement Wednesday,
Murphy dismissed the prosecution's largely circumstantial case and
contended that the child had contracted the disease some other way.
</P>
<P>
   Two people who lived in the same household were intravenous drug
users, Murphy said, and two convicted sex offenders may also have
come into contact with the child.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that health officials have tested everyone who
may have come in contact with the child, including the drug users
and sex offenders, and none have tested positive for HIV. The
child, who was identified as ESJ, has also been examined for sexual
abuse, and no sign has ever been found.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 32, who lives in Columbia, Ill., was employed as a
phlebotomist, drawing blood at a hospital laboratory, at the time
he went to his son's room in another hospital, where the child was
being treated for asthma and pneumonia, on the morning of Feb. 6,
1992. Prosecutors say that while Stewart's girlfriend, the boy's
mother, was out of the room, he injected the baby with infected
blood stolen from the lab.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the boy's mother, who has been identified only as
Jennifer, told the jury that when Stewart appeared that morning in
1992, she followed his suggestion that she get a soft drink from
the cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to see Stewart sitting in a rocking chair with the
infant in his lap. The infant was hysterical, she said. ``He kept
crying and screaming, and I couldn't seem to quiet him down,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She called nurses for help, but could find nothing wrong, she
said. Shortly afterward, Stewart left. The baby kept crying until
he was exhausted, she said, but there was no visible cause.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's pediatrician, Dr. Linda Steel-Green, testified
Thursday that she became alarmed because the child was lethargic
and breathing fast, with a rapid heart rate. Suddenly, his
condition was much worse.
</P>
<P>
   His symptoms were consistent with a bad reaction to an infusion
of incompatible blood, the doctor testified today, but she
suspected nothing because the baby had never received a
transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steel-Green had never treated an AIDS patient before, and it
was not until May 1996, when the boy had become desperately ill and
she remembered the boy's family telling her that the father said
the child would not live long, that she had him tested for the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, his mother wept as she described her child's
suffering and slow progress with help from new medications which
have also left him nearly deaf. Stewart listened impassively,
taking notes now and then.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer met Stewart in January 1990, and became pregnant five
months later.
</P>
<P>
   She testified that she gave birth to their son in February 1991,
and that her relationship with Stewart ended in August 1992. She
called Stewart that month from a local clinic where she was
undergoing treatment for stress.
</P>
<P>
   She testified that, when she told him he was financially
responsible for their son, he denied paternity and ``started in
with these threats of `I told you, when I leave, I'm going to leave
for good. I'm not going to leave any loose ends or ties behind.'''
</P>
<P>
   She testified that he told her, ``You won't need to look me up
for child support anyway, because your son's not going to live that
long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him what he meant by that, and he said: `Don't worry
about it. I just know that he's not going to live to see the age of
five,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``He's told me that if I tried to find him, he
could have me taken care of, and no one would ever be able to trace
it back to him.''
</P>
<P>
   She sued Stewart twice for child support, and in 1997, after
paternity was established, was awarded $267 a month.
</P>
<P>
   At a preliminary hearing, Amy Braun, a subsequent girlfriend of
Stewart's, testified that he told her ``he didn't want the child
from the beginning, that he wanted the mother to get an abortion
and that the child would be dead soon anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Sgt. Kevin Wilson of the St. Charles County Sheriff's
Department testified that Stewart's co-workers told him they
usually knew which patients had HIV or AIDS because hospital staff
and patients let them know. It also would have been easy to draw
extra tubes of blood, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer testified that Stewart took needles, syringes and
tourniquets home from work when they were living together and that
she twice found vials of blood in her freezer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
