<HEADLINE>
DOW FALLS 184.86 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks fell broadly on Thursday, buffeted by more
projections of reduced earnings and a budgetary setback in Brazil
that caused its Bovespa index to plunge nearly 9 percent. Seemingly
ignored was a coordinated interest-rate cut in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the old devils of international economies and earnings
outlooks are coming back again,'' said John Shaughnessy, the chief
strategist at the Advest Group.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also pointed to a lack of a strong new sector during
the market's rebound from the October lows, a situation they said
helped put investors in a mood to cash in profits.
</P>
<P>
   The three most popular American gauges each dropped about 2
percent, with the Dow Jones industrial average ending down 184.86
points. Of the 30 blue-chip components, only Allied Signal managed
even a fractional advance.
</P>
<P>
   This was another session of exceptional volatility, the fourth
straight in which the Dow's gyrations created a gap between its
high for the day and its low that exceeded the 30-day average. The
last time the daily range was more than 100 percent of the average
for so long was from Aug. 27 through Sept. 1, when the market hit
its 1998 low.
</P>
<P>
   In such a climate, said Fane Lozman, chairman of the
Chicago-based Scanshift, which analyzes stock market data,
investors should be more careful in placing orders to buy and sell
since they may wind up in a fast-moving market with unacceptable
prices by the time their orders are executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to pay attention to slippage on a market order,''
one executed at whatever price prevails when it reaches the
market-maker or exchange specialist, Lozman said. Using a limit
order, one that will be executed only at a specified price, can be
used as protection though it may also keep the transaction from
getting done at all.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks were caught up in Thursday's pounding as Ebay
skidded 16, Onsale 12| and Amazon.com 10.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors may have turned to Ticketmaster
Online-CitySearch, the latest hot first public offering. Shares of
the online company, 7 million of which were offered at 14, began
trading at 52 and then changed hands as high as 56] before closing
at 40\.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you own no Internet stocks, you're not playing'' these
days, said Larry Rice, the chief investment officer at Josephthal.
He bemoaned a lack of market breadth of late and called the market
overvalued at more than 22{ times next year's expected earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market focus has continued on the same groups and the same
names,'' he said. ``There's no new leadership whatsoever'' that
would befit a proper bull market.
</P>
<P>
   The financial services, computer and drug groups were especially
hard hit on Thursday, which saw the Dow industrials, which closed
at 8,879.68, slip below the 9000 mark for the first time since Nov.
17. It was also the Dow's second loss of more than 2 percent this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise rejection by Brazil's Congress of a tax increase
designed to shrink the country's budget deficit shriveled bank
shares, especially those with heavy Latin American exposure. Among
those down were BankBoston, off 3 11/16, to 38 15/16 and J.P.
Morgan dropping 4 1/16, to 107\.
</P>
<P>
   Most drug stocks also suffered multiple-point losses, with Eli
Lilly down 5[, to 83}, Merck and Bristol-Myers each down 3{ and
Schering-Plough down 3\.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Bond of Bond Procope cited poor ``sentiment and the
underlying tone'' of the market in the last few days and said late
in the session that he had heard that computer-chip stocks had come
under pressure because of higher production in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the case, investors are awfully jittery,'' Bond
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chip makers, who are vulnerable to distress in Brazil, were
mixed but Intel was driven down 4 1/16, to 109{.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, larded with high-technology shares,
fell 40.88 points, a 2.05 percent drop that almost exactly matched
that of the Dow industrials.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard and Poor's index of 500 stocks fared slightly
better, down 21.11 points, or 1.8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
