<HEADLINE>
FINESSING YOUR FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS.: In the last graf, replace (AT) with the typographical `at'
symbol.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I'm a part-time contractor at a high-technology company.
Recently, my supervisor asked if I would be interested in a
full-time job, at less pay per hour but with stock options and
other benefits. The truth is that I'm not interested _ I like the
freedom and my current pay _ but I worry that if I reject his
offer, he'll replace me with someone committed to the long haul.
Any negotiating suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   A: Freedom or security: It's a stark choice _ and one that your
employer may not realize is a tough call for you. Because the
company wants you full time, it clearly likes your work.
Nevertheless, before deciding on a bargaining approach, talk with
your boss about exactly why he made the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that the company is looking to cut expenses or
reduce its number of consultants,'' said Bob Deissig, president of
recruiting services for the Ayers Group, a human resources
consulting firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   If so, you should seek ways to maximize your value _ like
increasing your work load but not your fee _ that would make the
company more willing to keep you on your terms.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, your boss may simply be dazzled by your technical
prowess and is afraid of losing you. Employers are often much more
worried about your taking off than you are about being replaced _
particularly in this tight job market, said Robin Ryan, a
Seattle-based career counselor and author of ``Winning Resumes''
(John Wiley &AMP; Sons, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the operative word is tact. By turning down a
full-time gig, you are saying, in essence: ``I really like you
guys, but not enough to commit.'' Think about how that line played
in your last personal relationship. Employers tend to take
rejection about as well as insecure girlfriends or boyfriends, so
when breaking the news to your supervisor, let him down easy.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the money, Ms. Ryan advised: ``Go to your employer
and say, `I just can't take a salary cut at this time.' '' This
puts your rejection in practical, hard-dollar terms that most
business types can grasp. After all, stock options are a nice perk,
but they can't pay the rent, and they often have no value until you
have been with a company for 3, 5 or 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how practical your reasons, you need to make your
rejection as flattering as possible, Deissig said. ``Tell your
supervisor how honored you are by the offer,'' he said, ``and
stress how terrific you think the organization is.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasize that you have no intention of abandoning the firm.
``Assure them that the offer makes you even more committed to the
organization,'' he added, ``and ask what you can do to make
everyone more comfortable with your consultant status.''
</P>
<P>
   If you do plan to stay, Deissig said, consider negotiating a
long-term contract.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if your employer is desperate to hire you, he may
counter with a second offer at your current pay _ or higher. At
that point, you'll have to re-evaluate just how much you want to
stay footloose and freelance. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she will
respond to readers' questions about career and workplace issues.
Send them by E-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to
Working, Money &AMP; Business, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New
York, N.Y. 10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
