A2140 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      12-03 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP RANKS DIVIDE OVER CENSURE VS. IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the prospect of President Clinton's
impeachment in the House too close to call, a struggle broke out
Thursday in the Republican ranks as a renegade lawmaker split with
GOP leaders and began rallying support for an alternative plan to
hit Clinton with a sharply worded censure and hefty fine.
</P>
<P>
   The move, by Representative Peter T. King of New York, came in
the tense prelude to the House Judiciary Committee's final
impeachment hearings next week, as many GOP lawmakers privately
anguished over how to decide Clinton's fate when the full House
confronts the issue as early as Dec. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the speaker-designate, Robert L. Livingston, told
reporters that no group in Congress should exert pressure to sway
the outcome of the impeachment process, King began organizing
moderate Republicans to support his plan for a censure and fine as
an alternative to removing Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative was seen as a counterstrike against the GOP
majority whip, Tom DeLay, an ardent advocate for Clinton's ouster,
who has been marshaling his potent whip organization in
anticipation of the Judiciary Committee sending at least one
article of impeachment to the full House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want leadership to know there is a lot of support for
censure,'' King said. ``And this is the only alternative because
impeachment is not going to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat who
serves on the Judiciary Committee and supports censure, said the
White House is open to discussing King's proposal, which would
require Clinton to accept a fine of about $300,000. That was the
amount the lame-duck speaker, Newt Gingrich, paid last year to
settle House ethics charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   The King plan also would require Clinton to issue a written
statement acknowledging wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was little evidence to support King's contention
that as many as 20 Republicans would break with the GOP majority
and oppose articles of impeachment in favor of the censure plan.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several GOP lawmakers said support for impeachment may
have strengthened since Clinton refused to admit any legal
wrongdoing in his response last week to 81 questions from the
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the president came out with those absurd responses, I
found that some members who weren't going to vote for impeachment
were of a mind to say, `He just doesn't get it. I'm going to vote
for impeachment almost as a form of punishment,' '' said
Representative Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican who
opposes both impeaching Clinton and censuring him.
</P>
<P>
   The developments unfolded as the House Judiciary Committee
formally abandoned its two-day foray into investigating Clinton's
1996 campaign fund-raising, effectively clearing the way for the
panel to vote next week on proposed articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee chairman, Henry J. Hyde, said he
``informed the White House that the committee will not address
allegations involving abuse of campaign finance laws in its
deliberations currently scheduled for next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats, who had accused Republicans of leading ``a
wild goose chase'' in pursuing the fund-raising allegations, chided
them after the inquiry was dropped. ``Obviously, this spastic lurch
into campaign finance was not well thought out by the committee
majority,'' said Jim Jordan, spokesman for the committee Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also has dropped plans to seek impeachment charges
related to former White House volunteer Kathleen Willey's
allegation that Clinton groped her near the Oval Office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But, Hyde added, ``We feel there is more than adequate
information before the committee to pursue the debate leading to
articles of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee sources said the impeachment articles are expected to
include at least two counts of perjury, one charging Clinton with
lying to a federal grand jury investigating his sexual relationship
with Monica S. Lewinsky. The second count would charge him with
lying under oath in his deposition for the Paula Corbin Jones
sexual harassment lawsuit, which was recently settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   Several committee Republicans also are expected to propose
articles charging Clinton with obstruction of justice and abusing
the power of his office, although the perjury charges are seen as
the strongest.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, in his first public comments after several days of
prodding from Democrats for him to take charge of the impeachment
inquiry, said he expects the full House to vote the week of Dec. 14
if the Judiciary Committee passes articles of impeachment next
week, as the panel is expected to do.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston also maintained neutrality on the censure issue,
although he has said previously that the House should fulfill its
duty to vote on the impeachment issue before lawmakers consider
censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each member of Congress has the responsibility to search his
heart and his conscience and judge for himself the importance to
his constituents, what his vote should be,'' Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   Both DeLay and lawmakers opposed to impeachment claimed they
have enough votes to prevail when the issue reaches the House
floor. But neither side has substantiated their claim, and the
situation remains in flux as King and several Democrats advocate
censure plans and GOP conservatives continue to press for Clinton's
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Three Democrats, all Southern conservatives, are considered
certain to back Clinton's impeachment: Representatives Virgil H.
Goode Jr. of Virginia, Ralph M. Hall of Texas, and Gene Taylor of
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Only three Republicans other than King and Shays have publicly
said they will oppose impeachment charges: Representatives John
Edward Porter of Illinois, Jack Quinn of New York, and Mark Souder
of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   But two other GOP members _ Representative Jim Bunning of
Kentucky and Michael D. Crapo of Idaho _ have said they will not
participate in House impeachment votes because they were elected to
the Senate in November and might be required to vote on removing
Clinton from office if the House sends articles of impeachment to
the Senate for a trial. Bunning and Crapo were seen as likely to
vote for House impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   Although King, Shays and other moderate Republicans say at least
15 other GOP members will oppose impeachment, none have come
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the uncertainty, anxiety reigns on both sides of the
impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans outnumber Democrats in the House, 228-206, with a
lone independent, Representative Bernard Sanders of Vermont,
considered highly likely to oppose impeachment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
