</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: ABC REPLAYS GRUESOME INJURY, WITH WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The grisly broken leg suffered by 49ers defensive tackle Bryant
Young in Monday's San Francisco-Giants game is a reminder that 13
years before, Redskins quarterback Joe Theismann's leg was mangled
in a similarly gruesome fashion, also against the Giants, also on
``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC handled Young's injury without a voyeuristic sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn away, folks, turn away, if you don't want to see this,''
Dan Dierdorf cautioned, as the camera viewed the triage from a
respectful distance.
</P>
<P>
   ABC waited until after a commercial break to show its sole
replay, which showed Young's leg bow grotesquely in slow motion
from the impact of linebacker Ken Norton's helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know the risk of injury is always there,'' Boomer
Esiason said. ``It's the one thing that nobody wants to talk
about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night's'' agreed-upon policy is not to dwell on
sickening injuries, like one suffered on its air several years ago
by Napoleon McCallum.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who didn't see it, you have to replay it, but you
warn people about it, then you get out,'' Al Michaels said
Thursday. ``It serves no purpose to go back and redocument it. When
a leg is sticking out at a 40-degree angle, one replay is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The distant perception of Nov. 18, 1985, is that ABC endlessly
reran Lawrence Taylor's sacking Theismann on a failed flea flicker,
and Theismann's leg being caught awkwardly under Taylor's weight,
causing a compound fracture.
</P>
<P>
   But the injury was actually shown on replay only three times,
twice in the immediate aftermath, the final one in the third
quarter, which may have been unnecessary, but did not constitute
overkill. ``If your stomach is weak, you just don't watch,'' Frank
Gifford warned before the second and third replays.
</P>
<P>
   As Theismann was tended to, ABC never showed the gruesomeness of
the bone's protruding from the quarterback's skin. The camera
zoomed in only once, to a close-up of Theismann's face, framed by
teammates and medical personnel.
</P>
<P>
   But Gifford provided a verbal description of what the camera did
not show. ``There was blood on Joe's right shinbone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, ABC cut from Theismann to Taylor, much as the
network cut to a concerned Norton on Monday night. Gifford said in
1985, ``I have a feeling Lawrence Taylor heard the snap of the bone
in Joe Theismann's leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Young's injury, Theismann felt an awful rush of deja
vu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got chills,'' Theismann, the longtime ESPN analyst, said
yesterday from his Philadelphia hotel room, where he was preparing
for last night's Rams-Eagles game. ``I saw him on the ground and
saw enough. I saw the angle of his leg and I felt a knot in my
stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Before ABC rolled the replay, Theismann walked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife, Robin, said, `Don't look.''' In fact, he said he had
never seen the graphic replay of his broken leg, although it has
been rerun countless times over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only seen the master shot with me on the ground and all
the other people around me,'' he said. ``But if the replay comes on
TV, I turn my face.''
</P>
<P>
   He retains a vivid memory of virtually everything that happened
after the sack, from conversations on the field with his coach, Joe
Gibbs, and Giants coach Bill Parcells, to watching the end of that
night's game on a small black-and-white hospital television set as
he was being prepared for surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can close my eyes and feel it come back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can feel the pressure coming from the left side and hear the
leg break, like two muzzled gun shots. I don't feel pain. I
remember looking up and telling Harry Carson: `Don't retire. I'm
coming back.' And Harry said, `Not tonight.'''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that Taylor called him in the hospital. ``Lawrence
said, `How're you doing?' and I said, `Well, my leg is broken in
two places.' And Lawrence said, `Well, I never do anything
halfway.''
</P>
<P>
   And 16 days ago, Taylor called Theismann ``to wish me a happy
anniversary.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pigskin Delay
</P>
<P>
   NBC and Turner's detailed announcement of its spring-summer pro
football league, which is scheduled to launch in 2000, will be
delayed from this month until early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The planning is going well, but there are lots of things to
work out,'' said Harvey Schiller, the president of Turner Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen one thing that's been an impediment to the
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Airwaves
</P>
<P>
   The high decibel level exercised by ABC's Brent Musburger _ as
exhibited last Saturday during the Texas-Texas A&AMP;M game _ is proof
that (a) you need only an open window, not a TV set, to hear him
and (b) the games he calls must be more exciting than any other
announcer's because he's louder than them all.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN Classic's look back at the 1971 Nebraska-Oklahoma game
was a gem, an adroit blend of old footage and reminiscences.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keith Olbermann is to start anchoring the Fox Sports News on
Jan. 5 or 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
