<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Albright decries slow human rights gains but defends efforts
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright mildly
criticized the Chinese government Thursday, just days after two
prominent dissidents were arrested for trying to form a party to
oppose Communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at Emory University, Albright said the greatest test
for democracy and human rights in the coming century probably will
occur in China, home to more than 20 percent of the world's
population. And while conceding that the Chinese people have a few
more freedoms than they did a generation ago, Albright said the
United States has ``grave concerns'' about the Communist regime's
continued crackdown on individual rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall,'' she said, ``the pace of progress toward full
respect for human rights is disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government said Thursday it will continue to block
efforts by dissidents Xu Wenli and Qin Yongmin to form the China
Democratic Party. Both activists were arrested Monday on grounds of
endangering national security. A third dissident trying to set up
the political party, Wang Youcai, has been in custody for a month.
</P>
<P>
   On another human rights issue, Albright defended the continued
training of Latin American troops at the U.S. Army's School of the
Americas at Fort Benning, Ga. Critics of the school, which opened
in 1984, contend it teaches torture tactics and other repressive
measures. An estimated 7,000 demonstrators gathered in Columbus a
few weeks ago for a yearly protest that started in 1991 with about
a dozen people.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a question-answer session with Emory students,
Albright was asked how the United States can operate the Army
school and still claim to adhere to the fundamentals of human
rights. Albright said that while she and many other policymakers
believe that serious mistakes were made in the past, democracy now
flourishes in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military has now been in all cases subordinated to
civilian control,'' she said. ``It is important for us to continue
to have relationships with this new military in order to instill in
them _ contrary to what was done previously _ democratic principles
and the ability to work in democratic governments and to be
subordinated to civilian control.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the continuing problems with Iraqi leader Saddam
Hussein, Albright said U.S. policy aimed at toppling him could take
quite awhile. Saddam has been contained since the 1991 Persian Gulf
War, she said, through tough economic sanctions imposed by the
United Nations. Now, Albright said, the United States is stepping
up pressure with ``containment-plus,'' a policy of supporting those
seeking to overthrow the Iraqi dictator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that may take a considerable amount of time,'' she
said. ``And the way to make it happen is to work with a variety of
opposition groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright devoted her speech mostly to human rights issues,
touching particularly on the plight of oppressed women. Despite
progress in many countries, she said, appalling abuses continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who suggest that all this is cultural and
there's nothing we can do about it. I say it's criminal and we each
have a responsibility to stop it,'' she said, drawing applause.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who served on President Jimmy Carter's National
Security Council staff, came to Emory to deliver the university's
Rosalynn Carter Distinguished Lecture in Public Policy and was
introduced by the former first lady.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton appointed Albright ambassador to the United
Nations in 1993, and she made history in January 1997 when she
became the first female U.S. secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Being a woman in such a high-powered post has its advantages,
she said. ``If I were a man, you would just see a tired old man.
But thanks to makeup ...
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
