u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH04-COX     12-03 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impeachment focus turns from fund-raising to Lewinsky
relationship
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee
abruptly cast aside their inquiry into campaign fund raising
Thursday and are now drafting three articles of impeachment against
President Clinton focused solely on how he concealed his
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to forgo further investigation of allegations that
Clinton was involved in campaign fund-raising abuses during the
1996 election clears the way for the committee to vote next week on
whether the president committed perjury, obstructed justice and
abused his presidential powers in the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) told fellow
Republicans in a conference call Thursday morning that secret
Department of Justice memos outlining alleged fund-raising abuses,
reviewed by committee staff members Wednesday, did not warrant
inclusion in articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having received reliable information from Justice Department
sources that the memorandum may be of value to the committee's
impeachment investigators, the committee would have been derelict
in its duty had it failed to examine the document,'' said Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde hinted that the campaign finance issue is not over for the
White House, despite not being included in the impeachment inquiry.
``We are far from satisfied that existing campaign finance laws
have not been violated,'' said Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute move to examine the Justice Department memos and
the failure to find anything useful in them prompted Democrats to
accuse the committee of conducting a ``partisan goose chase.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole process looks a little chaotic and disjointed,''
said Rep. Zoe Lofgren (D-Calif.), a member of the Judiciary
Committee.''It is beginning to look like a partisan committee
looking to impeach the president, but they haven't figured out why
yet. They're looking to dress it up.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the committee prepares for a historic vote next week over
whether to recommend removing Clinton from office, both sides
intensified pressure on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people have been calling spontaneously,'' said Randy Tate,
executive director of the Christian Coalition based in Virginia.
Members of the conservative group are calling lawmakers because the
public is frustrated at the way the president responded last week
to 81 questions submitted by Hyde, said Tate.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition has delivered ``hundreds of thousands of
petitions'' to Congress calling for the president to be removed
from office, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lux, vice president of the liberal People for the
American Way, said conservative religious groups are blanketing
Congress with calls for the ouster of Clinton ``because most of the
public does not want impeachment and they see their dream of
impeaching Bill Clinton slipping away.''
</P>
<P>
   Lux said his group would mount its own grass-roots campaign to
push for a quick end to the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Louisiana Republican Bob Livingston, the GOP
choice for House speaker, told reporters he hopes the matter will
be completed before the 106th Congress convenes next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Judiciary Committee could complete its work next week,
it would be my expectation that we could have a vote on the
following week,'' Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure continued to mount for a quick solution and it is
escalating tension between moderates and conservatives in the
Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King (R-N.Y.) circulated a censure proposal calling
for punishment short of impeaching the president. The proposal
would condemn the way Clinton concealed his relationship with
Lewinsky, impose a financial penalty and require an admission of
guilt, according to King's spokesman, Kevin Fogarty.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats met with House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt
(D-Mo.) to craft a way to reach out to wavering Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how many Republicans would support a censure
plan. Last week, some moderates estimated that as many as 20
Republicans in the House would vote against impeachment. But that
forecast seemed to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was before the president's answers to the 81 questions,''
said Rep. Christopher Shays (R-Conn.), who is considered a
moderate. ``He was very obstinate and he made it harder for members
to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The daily verbal battle between the White House and the
Judiciary Committee continued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mooney, the committee's general counsel, wrote to White
House lawyers that they could expect questioning from committee
members and staff following their defense of the president next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The committee does not have some documents the White House
requested in preparation for their defense, Mooney wrote. He noted
in particular that internal Justice Department memos related to
alleged campaign finance abuses are in the possession of the
Department of Justice, not the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Other documents the White House sought, he wrote, will be made
available only in the confines of the committee's heavily guarded
document room.
</P>
<P>
   That sparked a terse response from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee's erratic behavior leaves the fundamental focus
of this investigation unclear,'' said Joe Lockhart, the president's
press secretary. ``Their actions have been chaotic, partisan and
irresponsible, fundamentally limiting the president's ability to
present a coherent defense. At this late date, we still don't know
what the committee is charging, or for that matter, who is in
charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
