</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CONSTITUTION04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Constitutional rewrite would lengthen lawmakers' terms
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A new state Constitution to be proposed today
would give the 31 state senators six-year terms instead of the
current four, a change that would give Texas the longest term of
any state legislature in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The reframers of the Constitution, Sen. Bill Ratliff and Rep.
Rob Junell, who are offering up an almost-total rewrite, say the
150 House members, who now serve two-year terms, should serve four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Most states have two-year terms for House members. Only Alabama,
Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi and North Dakota have four-year
terms. No state has six-year senate terms, though U.S. senators
serve six-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Ratliff-Junell proposal would would take away as well as
give. Though terms would be longer, lawmakers would, for the first
time in Texas, be subject to term limits.
</P>
<P>
   Senators could serve as long as it took to complete nine regular
legislative sessions, 18 years in most cases. House members could
participate in eight regular sessions, generally 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, Ratliff said Thursday, is to let lawmakers spend more
time doing their jobs and less time running for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly for House members, when you run every other year
you spend all your time running for office, it is very hard for
them to do their job if they are constantly having to raise money
and run for office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The current Constitution, adopted in 1876 and amended 377 times
since, has long outlived its usefulness, Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig McDonald, director of the government watchdog group Texans
for Public Justice, said he's not sure what ill is cured by longer
legislative terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ought to be able to stand before the voters more often,
not less,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Smith, Texas director of Public Citizen, another
watchdog group, endorsed the four-year House term concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would reduce dramatically the amount of money members would
have to raise, as well as the time spent campaigning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith opposes lengthening Senate terms and term limits.
</P>
<P>
   The term change is among a list of major overhauls proposed by
Junell and Ratliff, key lawmakers who chair the Legislature's
budget-writing committees.
</P>
<P>
   Untouched, however, would be the Bill of Rights portion that
tops the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rewrite calls for appointment of judges and more of
a cabinet form of government that would put more power in the
governor's office. The land commissioner, agriculture commissioner,
railroad commissioners and State Board of Education, now elected,
would become gubernatorial appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Changing the constitution would require legislative and voter
approval. Junell and Ratliff say winning approval of a new
Constitution is a long shot but a concept that needs to get
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
