r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      12-03 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 When Charity Drives At Work Go Overboard  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  The senior executive in charge of my company's United
Way campaign is putting a lot of pressure on people to contribute _
too much pressure, in my opinion. For instance, he has promised to
give an extra week of paid vacation to any department in which
everyone makes a United Way contribution. This turns the personal
decision about giving into a departmental issue. And it creates an
uncomfortable situation for people like me who prefer to give to
charity directly. What should I do?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Your senior executive probably has the best of
intentions _ maximizing the number of people who contribute to the
local community.
</P>
<P>
   And many companies offer incentives such as T-shirts to
encourage people to support the United Way.
</P>
<P>
   But I agree with you that this exec is going way overboard by
making an individual's charitable giving a factor in whether his or
her co-workers get an extra week off.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, this kind of heavy-handed pressure does more
harm than good _ creating resentment not only against this
particular manager, but against the company in general and the
whole United Way idea.
</P>
<P>
   What can you do? There are three possible responses, and the one
you should choose depends on your values and specific workplace:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ignore the pressure and give to charity exactly the way you
normally would. Three months from now, no one may remember or care
that you were the one United Way holdout who kept them from getting
a week off. In fact, many of your co-workers may share your
resentment at the way the campaign is being run.
</P>
<P>
   _ Express your concerns to the human resources department. The
HR manager may be able to ask this executive to modify the
incentive program while keeping your identity confidential.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give a token amount just to be part of the team. Even a
onetime $5 contribution will push you into the ``contributor''
category _ helping your department reach that 100 percent
participation goal.
</P>
<P>
   You should note that today, people can earmark their United Way
donations for a specific nonprofit group _ even one that's out of
town or not listed in the United Way brochure.
</P>
<P>
   United Way takes an 11 percent cut to cover its processing and
fund-raising costs, so your chosen charities wouldn't net quite as
much as if you wrote them a check yourself. But earmarking your
donation might be a good compromise that would allow you to fund
the groups you want while helping your department win that free
week of vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Q: I'm an assistant manager at a 70-person company and
currently am on leave due to a work-related injury. I was surprised
to get a letter from my firm, after being off for just five weeks,
saying that I was expected to pay for my own health insurance. Can
I recover the payments that I've had to make?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: If you've worked for this company for a year and put in
more than 1,250 hours, you're covered by the federal Family and
Medical Leave Act.
</P>
<P>
   FMLA entitles workers to up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave a year
if they or a family member have a serious health problem.
</P>
<P>
   More relevant to your case, the law requires employers to
continue providing health coverage to workers while they're on FMLA
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person should not have to pay for those benefits,'' said
Doris Ng, an attorney with Equal Rights Advocates, a nonprofit
group in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Give a call to ERA's free advice and counseling line at (800)
839-4372. One of their attorneys will go over the details of your
situation and call the company on your behalf.
</P>
<P>
   If that fails, you can file a complaint with the U.S. Department
of Labor or a parallel state agency such as the California
Department of Fair Employment and Housing. But that shouldn't be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear in the law that they're required to keep
providing health benefits for 12 weeks,'' Ng said. ``If the
employer is reasonable, they will refund the money.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Q: How many days in a row can an employee work before
overtime is required? I work for a health care provider, and my
schedule often has me working Thursday through Sunday of one week,
followed by Monday through Friday the next. That makes a total of
nine days without a break. Is this legal?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Overtime in California isn't based on the number of days
you work _ it's based on the number of hours worked over the course
of a week.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, most nonunion employers are required to pay overtime
after you put in 40 hours over a seven-day work week. (A few
employers, like hospitals, don't have to pay overtime unless
workers put in 80 hours over a 14-day period.)
</P>
<P>
   There &LR;  are  &LR; some laws limiting the number of days in a row that
people can be asked to work.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, most California employers are required to give
their workers one day off out of seven. But those days off can be
postponed due to business necessity, as long as people receive the
equivalent of one day off out of seven by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, the company clearly is giving you one day off each
week. And unless your hours add up to more than 40 in one work week
(or 80 hours over two weeks in cases like hospitals), you're not
owed any overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot? Your schedule may be inconvenient, but it's probably
legal.
</P>
<P>
   Want to double-check the overtime rules for your particular job?
You can find wage orders for different industries on the Web site
of the California Department of Industrial Relations, at
 &UR; www.dir.ca.gov/dir &LR; 
 &UR; /Labor(UNDERSCORE)law/DLSE/IWC(UNDERSCORE)Order(UNDERSCORE)Index9 &LR; 
 &UR; 8.html.  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
