<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      12-03 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE FUND-RAISING PRACTICES DROPPED FROM CONSIDERATION IN
IMPEACHMENT PROBE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee backed
away Thursday from plans to examine President Clinton's campaign
fund raising, leaving only sex and perjury allegations at the
center of a likely vote next week on impeaching the president.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans signaled their retreat as incoming Speaker
Bob Livingston repeated his desire for the full House to vote on
articles of impeachment before Christmas _ a timetable reportedly
endorsed overwhelmingly in a survey of GOP members.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Judiciary Committee could complete its work next week,
it would be my expectation that we could have a vote on the
following week,'' said Livingston, a Louisiana Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republicans and Democrats worked separately on
alternatives to impeachment, resolutions that would rebuke the
president for his admitted affair with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky and efforts to hide the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Judiciary Committee, conducting only
the third presidential impeachment investigation in the nation's
history, has scheduled hearings next week with the final three days
set aside to debate articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   At least one article is expected to emerge from the 11 possible
offenses outlined by independent counsel Kenneth Starr, whose
report to the committee accused Clinton of perjury, obstruction of
justice and abuse of power in the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Thursday, committee Chairman Henry Hyde
told his GOP colleagues on the panel that White House fund-raising
practices during the 1996 campaign would no longer be considered as
articles of impeachment are drafted.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's decision came after consulting with the panel's
Republican investigator David Schippers who, along with a
Democratic counterpart, was allowed Wednesday to read secret
Justice Department memos alleging fund-raising irregularities by
top Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   While Hyde told his colleagues the memos contained nothing
usable in their impeachment effort, he issued a statement late
Thursday saying the information gleaned by Schippers would prove
useful in the committee's oversight of the Justice Department. ``We
are far from satisfied that existing campaign finance laws have not
been violated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also notified the White House that the president's lawyers,
who are preparing his defense, do not need to worry about
addressing the fund-raising issue during hearings next week.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the Judiciary
Committee's sudden expansion of the investigation on Tuesday and
abrupt contraction on Thursday ``have been chaotic, partisan and
irresponsible, fundamentally limiting the president's ability to
present a coherent defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, a New York Democrat on the committee, said
he was not surprised by Hyde's decision to back off the
fund-raising issue. ``I expected it,'' Nadler said. ``It was
obviously just a bone that he was throwing to his extremists in the
committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of Hyde's decision was late reaching Charles LaBella, a
federal prosecutor who wrote one of the internal Justice Department
memos recommending an independent investigation of President
Clinton's campaign fund-raising role in 1996. LaBella was enroute
from California to Washington to discuss his memo with committee
investigators when he received news of Hyde's decision by pager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're running for the hills,'' LaBella later told
the Associated Press when asked about the Republicans' decision not
to press the fund-raising issue.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Republicans quietly decided against including
Kathleen Willey's complaints about the president in the impeachment
inquiry. Willey has accused Clinton of groping her during a private
meeting at the White House in November 1993. He acknowledged the
meeting but denied any inappropriate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Willey also claimed that Democratic financier Nathan Landow, a
Maryland developer, talked to her about not publicly discussing the
encounter. When he was subpoenaed by Starr and by the Judiciary
Committee, he declined to answer questions citing his 5th Amendment
right against self-incrimination. Investigating further was ruled
out. ``There's no time to get into it,'' one staff member said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Starr told the committee that he had found no
evidence of impeachable offenses in his investigation of misuse of
FBI files at the White House, the firings at the White House travel
office or, so far, in the failed Arkansas land deal known as
Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks, Livingston has kept a low profile on
impeachment, and on Thursday only discussed it because he was
pressed during a fireside press conference with Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott. And then Livingston focused on his desire not to
drag out the inquiry. ``If the Judiciary Committee doesn't conclude
its work next week, it will be pretty certain it would have to be
carried over'' to next year, Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   And like their leader, most House Republicans want to avoid
having the impeachment issue awaiting their return in January. A
telephone survey of 60 of the 228 House Republicans by the staff of
Texas Rep. Tom DeLay, the GOP Whip, found unanimous support for
closing out the inquiry and voting on articles of impeachment by
the end of the year. Likewise, those surveyed were near unanimity
in opposing having to vote on anything but impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want an up-or-down vote on impeachment. They don't want a
half-step, some sort of censure resolution,'' one DeLay aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate Republican Rep. Paul King of New York said he was one
of 15-20 GOP members willing to support a form of censure. The
House has 435 members _ 228 Republicans, 206 Democrats and one
independent.
</P>
<P>
   Censure ``is the only alternative, because impeachment's not
going to pass,'' said King, who is drafting a resolution that would
rebuke the president, require him to make a statement of contrition
and pay a fine.
</P>
<P>
   King explained that if the only vote by House members is for or
against impeachment and it fails, then the president gets off
without any penalty. ``Congress must go on record saying
(Clinton's) conduct is wrong,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several days, committee Democrats have worked
privately on their own censure resolution condemning the
president's behavior but with no other penalties. While Democrats
plan to offer their version as a substitute for articles of
impeachment during Judiciary Committee hearings next week, Hyde has
indicated he would rule any Democratic alternatives to impeachment
``out of order.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic censure-drafters _ including Houston Rep. Sheila
Jackson Lee, Massachusetts Rep. William Delahunt and Virginia Rep.
Rick Boucher _ met behind closed doors with House Democratic leader
Dick Gephardt. In addition to discussing whether one or several
alternatives should be offered, Democratic staff sources said, the
group began outlining how to win support from Republicans not on
the Judiciary Committee once the issue emerges from the committee
for consideration by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   But Livingston would not say Thursday if he would allow a vote
on the House floor to censure Clinton. ``I'm just not going to make
a decision on that,'' Livingston said. ``I'm not going to make any
decisions about procedure until we see the report, have a chance to
digest it, and understand exactly what Henry Hyde and the Judiciary
Committee are recommending.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
