<SLUG> BC-GOP-BACKLASH:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTER BACKLASH AGAINST THE GOP
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By CHUCK COLBERT 
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert is a founder of the Gay and Lesbian Alumni of
Notre Dame/St. Mary's College, and serves on the board of directors
of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Gay voters made up 4 percent of the 1998 mid-term electorate,
according to exit polling conducted by Voter News Service (VNS).
That's a piece of post election analysis largely ignored by the
mainstream media, although only African Americans (10 percent) and
Latinos (5 percent) exceeded the numbers of gay voters this year,
VNS found.
 &HT;    But the 4 percent turn out was not lost on the leadership of the
Democratic Party, which for the most part benefited from the gay
vote. In California, for example, where the Democrats routed the
GOP, 73 percent of lesbian and gay voters supported gay-friendly
Gray Davis for governor, while 68 percent supported Sen. Barbara
Boxer's re-election.
 &HT;    Likewise, in New York, 77 percent of the gay voters supported
Democrat Rep. Charles Schumer in his upset victory over incumbent
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, a Republican, who, contraversially, had been
endorsed by the Human Rights Campaign (HRC), the nation's largest
gay and lesbian political organization.
 &HT;    The Democratic Party also made history in Wisconsin, with the
election of Tammy Baldwin as the first openly lesbian member of
Congress.
 &HT;    ``These results remind us of what we already knew,'' said
Democratic National Committee Chair Steve Grossman. ``Gay men and
lesbians are a very powerful voting block and grassroots organizing
force. When Democratic candidates are actively involved in the
struggles of their constituents and committed to the Democratic
platform of equality and non-discrimination for gays and lesbians,
community members lend their support and their votes,'' he said.
 &HT;    The Democrats picked up five additional House seats, bucking a
post World War II trend of the party in control of the White House
losing an average of 27 House seats and four Senate seats. The
composition of the Senate remains the same after the election.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, the gay National Log Cabin Republicans were quick
to point out that one-third of the gay vote _ about one million
votes _ supported GOP House candidates, according to VNS.
 &HT;    ``These polling numbers solidify the growing body of evidence
each year that the gay vote is more in play between the parties
than widely believed and that gays should not be written off by the
GOP,'' said Richard Tafel executive director of Log Cabin
Republicans.
 &HT;    But gay voters had good reason to vote Democratic this year.
Last summer the Republican controlled House of Representatives
succeeded in passing four out of five anti-gay amendments, covering
everything from banning adoptions by gay couples in the District of
Columbia and restricting local and federal funds there for needle
exchange programs that prevent the spread of HIV; to denying
federal housing money to the city of San Francisco for its liberal,
one-of-a kind domestic partnership ordinance; to cutting federal
housing money for people living with AIDS.
 &HT;    Not only did the Republicans assault gay and lesbian Americans
in Congress, but also the Christian Right, closely allied with the
GOP leadership, launched a national ad campaign characterizing gays
as unrepentant sinners, suffering from a mental illness.
 &HT;    ``We've been through one of the most vitriolic and hostile years
in recent memory for gay, lesbian, bisexual, and transgendered
people,'' said Kerry Lobel of the National Lesbian and Gay Task
Force.
 &HT;    Still, ``American voters rejected the mean-spirited, anti-gay
positions that have been expressed throughout this election season,
and registered their dissatisfaction at the polls,'' said Elizabeth
Birch, HRC's executive director.
 &HT;    By way of comparison, 90 percent of HRC's endorsed candidates
and 75 percent of Log Cabin-endorsed candidates won their races
compared to only 46 percent of candidates backed by Gary Bauer's
far-right Campaign for Working Families, according to HRC and Log
Cabin.
 &HT;    Before the election John Rowland, the Republican governor of
Connecticut, told The New York Times that ``our party doesn't get
it at the national level. Beating up on gays _ all that stuff. That
turns my stomach. We're never gong to win the White House again
unless we have an ability to reach out to people.''
 &HT;    Tafel of Log Cabin was equally as blunt after the election:
``All these religious right candidates running for president in
2000 _ John Ashcroft, Gary Bauer, Steve Forbes, Dan Quayle, and Bob
Smith _ shouldn't bother packing their bags for New Hampshire. If
the religious right continues to dominate the party in 2000, we
will not only lose the White House yet again, we will probably lose
the Congress.''
 &HT;    With Newt Gingrich gone as Speaker of the House and new
Republican leadership on the horizon, it remains to be seen if the
GOP has learned its lesson _ gay bashing just doesn't work.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Chuck Colbert 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
