u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SUSPECTS:CONTRE     12-03 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SUSPECTS:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUND-UP THE USUAL SUSPECTS!
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Movies, perhaps America's greatest cultural asset and
contribution to the world, have long served as a means of
propaganda, information and entertainment. But they also serve as
incisive statements of philosophy, fact and dangerous propositions
to be discussed, debated and portrayed.
 &HT;    Strong movie statements can move populations and their leaders
into and out of turbulent issues like no other medium. When
properly portrayed, for example, American political issues have
been decided one way or the other by how they were played in movies
or on television.
 &HT;    Such is the case of the latest movies, ``The Siege'' and ``Enemy
of the State.'' These two movies are important, to be viewed by
anyone concerned about the continuing encroachment on the rights
guaranteed to Americans by the Constitution.
 &HT;    Take, for example, the use of American troops to police
Americans as was seen in the movie, ``The Seige.'' This is
outlawed, and for good reason. The ability to search for suspects
or contraband in door-to-door searches is illegal because it is
unconstitutional.
 &HT;    Broad, warrantless searches violate the 4th Amendment of the
Constitution that states, ``The right of the people to be secure in
their persons, houses, papers and effects, against unreasonable
searches and seizures, shall not be violated, and no warrants shall
issue, but upon probable cause, supported by oath or affirmation,
and particularly describing the place to be searched and the
persons or things to be seized.''
 &HT;    Unfortunately, most Americans have little knowledge of the 4th
Amendment. It takes movies like ``The Seige'' and ``Enemy of the
State'' to awaken American citizens.
 &HT;    There are people like Ross Perot, for example, who have called
for broad, warrantless searches of Dallas Black and Mexican
neighborhoods encircled by National Guard troops, all in an effort
to locate guns and drugs. Perot denied he took such a position, but
eyewitnesses confirmed he did.
 &HT;    Taking similar positions that parallel Army troops rounding up
Arab-origin men in ``The Siege'' are people calling for exactly
such searches in California to root out illegal aliens from Mexico.
No mention is made of the hundreds of thousands, perhaps millions,
of illegal aliens from Canada.
 &HT;    No, only those with brown skin are targeted for broad,
warrantless searches and seizures. Of course, illegals wouldn't be
the only ones targeted for the unconstitutional searches and
seizures. Legal citizens, too, would be violated not because they
are illegal, but because their skin is the same color as mine,
brown.
 &HT;    The setting up of concentration camps for Japanese Americans
during World War II by hysterical army generals and President
Franklin Delano Roosevelt provide us with a glimpse at what might
happen if the hysterical extremists among us today were to have
their way with mass searches, road blocks, sweeps and arrests _ all
in an effort to save America's ``sovereignty'' from bedraggled farm
workers and busboys who total, by the way, less than 2 percent of
America.
 &HT;    But you don't have to go to these two movies to have the hair on
your neck raised. Travel north or west of San Diego and you'll
encounter roadblocks manned by the Border Patrol searching cars of
American citizens, willy nilly, without warrants, looking for
``drugs'' and ``illegal aliens.''
 &HT;    Life imitates art. The Constitution is trashed by men in green
uniforms, wearing federal badges and carrying big guns.
 &HT;    Unfortunately, there are no Denzel Washingtons, Will Smiths or
Gene Hackmans to protect us, just congressmen, some of whom bounce
checks, take dirty campaign money and lie through their teeth when
they run for reelection and have never read or understood the 4th
Amendment.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
