<SLUG> BC-GRANDCHILDREN-CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GRANDMOTHER'S HOPE CHEST
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By KIRSTEN CHAPMAN 
 &HT;    (Kirsten Chapman writes a weekly column for the Columbus
Dispatch in Columbus, Ohio, and is the author of three books,
including the recently published ``The Way Home.'') 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    With Christmas around the next chimney, I have enough to worry
about without inventing more.
 &HT;    Yet, at 55, I fret over ``grandchildren.''
 &HT;    When will I meet them?
 &HT;    Both my 30-year-old son and my 27-year-old daughter are
unmarried. Neither hears wedding bells in the near future.
 &HT;    So, for now, I'm able to share my wish.
 &HT;    If they had spouses, I couldn't even address the issue. I'd be
considered _ and rightly so _ a meddling mother-in-law.
 &HT;    I am blessed, of course, to have two children, but I yearn for
grandchildren _ and have for some time.
 &HT;    Five years ago or maybe 10, I recall, I was up in the attic with
my son and daughter. They were horsing around, pulling some of
their childhood toys from a box.
 &HT;    ``Be careful,'' l admonished them in a tone that surprised even
me. ``I'm saving those for my grandchildren.''
 &HT;    They were taken aback at my siding with someone other than them.
 &HT;    Until that moment, I wasn't aware that I'd been thinking about
grandchildren. Yet, on a deeper, subconscious level, I must have
been. Why else would I have intervened, protecting their interests
instinctively?
 &HT;    Poised at evening's threshold, I knew I'd grown old.
 &HT;    How many more Thanksgivings will pass without highchairs? We
can't choose to have grandchildren as we once did children.
 &HT;    Would-be grandparents simply have to wait and wait, all the
while realizing that we, too, have biological clocks that are
winding down.
 &HT;    I would have been a better grandmother at age 48 or 52 than I
would make today or in a few years. Not only do I tire more easily,
but each passing year puts that much more distance between me and a
grandchild.
 &HT;    What was most difficult about a recent move from the home where
our family had lived for 13 years was packing items from the attic
_ those leftovers I'd often pictured in the hands of a future
granddaughter and grandson: my children's books and toys, some of
their clothes and costumes. Up there, too, were a dollhouse, a
small table and chairs, a little fort, even an old saddle from my
husband's childhood. The sum of it all? A grandmother's hope chest.
 &HT;    More than once, I envisioned myself playing with my children's
offspring in the attic. Now the playthings are buried deep inside a
storage locker.
 &HT;    Even with no grandchildren on the horizon, I find myself losing
sleep over the thought of them. Will I be ready to drop everything
at a moment's notice and help? Or will I see my grandchildren only
during the holidays and on vacations?
 &HT;    We think we make those choices once and for all with our own
children. Little do we realize we'll confront them again a
generation later.
 &HT;    While waiting, at least, I get to observe those who've gone
before _ and learn from them.
 &HT;    I know that my children are hoping to find the right partners. I
also understand that people today are marrying later than they did
before.
 &HT;    Still, others keep telling me they are experiencing one of the
greatest joys in life.
 &HT;    ``We're so sorry you don't have grandchildren,'' they say. ``We
wish you did so you'd know the happiness we feel.''
 &HT;    I wish I did, too.
 &HT;    At this rate, I probably won't meet my great-grandchildren; but,
hopefully, I'll see a grandchild or two come into the world, before
I go the other way out.
 &HT;    Now that will be a time to give thanks for.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Kirsten Chapman 
