<HEADER>
A2226 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOP-TEN-ASIANS-NEWAME     12-03 3250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOP-TEN-ASIANS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISIONARIES: 10 HOT ASIAN AMERICAN ENTREPRENEURS UNDER 30
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 By HUGH SON, KENNETH LI, ANGELO RAGAZA, JIM CHO, JUDY PISNANONT,
BRANDY TUZON, KAREN LAM and HUGH SON 
 c. 1998 A. Magazine: Inside Asian America 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Whether it's a cutting-edge internet company or an organization
that provides urgently needed programs to an underserved community,
realizing a personal vision means taking risks, raising money,
managing allies, and keeping the faith in the face of sometimes
heartbreaking obstacles. Here are 10 individuals who redefine what
it means to be young, Asian American, and on their own.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    DANNY SEO, 21, Executive Director, Earth 2000, Washington, D.C.
 &HT;    Danny Seo, award-winning activist and author, doesn't celebrate
April 22 just because it's his birthday. It's also Earth Day _ a
coincidence, but a fitting one for Seo who, at the age of 12,
founded the environmental organization Earth 2000 (now 20,000
members strong). The goal: to reverse the impact of environmental
destruction by the end of the millennium. Although his first
project, an attempt to save 66 acres of forest from developers in
his native Pennsylvania, ended in failure, he didn't let that
discourage him. His organization has since organized anti-whaling
protests, headed campaigns against companies selling fur, and
helped to construct homes for Habitat for Humanity.
 &HT;    The centerpiece of Seo's campaign for promoting Earth-friendly
lifestyles is his upcoming book ``Free, Green, &AMP; Beyond: A Guide to
Cruelty-Free, Ecologically Sound Living,'' which is being launched
Earth Day '99 and which he describes as ``Greenpeace meets Martha
Stewart.''
 &HT;    While Seo's good deeds have gotten much media mention, his Asian
background hasn't. ``I don't live up to their stereotypes,'' he
says. But he doesn't shy away from the question _ he's been known
to introduce himself at conferences by saying, ``In case you don't
know who I am, I'm the other Asian activist.''
 &HT;    Seo's recipe for success? First, he says, always innovate rather
than imitate. ``If you find someone who inspires you, great. But
don't try to be that person.'' Secondly, always keep the faith:
``There will be moments when everybody thinks you're wrong. But if
you stick with it and believe in yourself, the outcome is usually
in your favor.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CECILIA PAGKALINAWAN, 29, President, Boutique Y3K, New York.
 &HT;    ``Retailing is the third oldest profession in the world,''
Cecilia Pagkalinawan explains. ``Since merchants began selling on
the street, it hasn't changed too much.''
 &HT;    But this scion of Silicon Alley has joined the fray to reinvent
retail _ on the Net. Less than a year old, her company, Boutique
Y3K, is helping companies like Nine West hock their wares online.
The 7-employee operation also creates and operates online shopping
boutiques for high-traffic Web sites like hipper-than-thou teen
site Bolt and smut page for the literary set, Nerve. ``We've gone
from being considered geeks to being considered cool,'' she jokes.
 &HT;    Dabbling in America Online while at a prestigious ad agency six
years ago, ``I immediately saw the Internet as an alternate medium
(for advertising),'' she says. That led her to take a job creating
one of the first online malls, ``marketplaceMCI,'' for clients like
Foot Locker, Lady Foot Locker, and Champs. At her next stop, the
financiers presented her with a unique opportunity _ by pulling
out. So at the age of 28, she bought out the owners and set up
shop.
 &HT;    ``We just changed the sign on the door,'' she says.
 &HT;    Y3K is estimated to clock revenues of $1.5 million by the end of
its first year. But Pagkalinawan's passions go beyond profit. Last
year, she co-founded MOUSE (Making Opportunities for Upgrading
Schools and Education). The non-profit's 500 volunteers work to
wire up resource-strapped public high schools, thus helping to
bridge the tech gap between New York's young haves and have-nots.
``To expose the kids to technology, so that it wouldn't be a
mystery to them when they go to the workforce, is to make the
difference between the employable and the unemployable in the
future,'' says Pagkalinawan.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I look at these kids and see all this potential and
hope. To reach out and affect those kids, to allow those kids to
think that it is all doable, that is very impactful.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SABEER BHATIA, 29, CEO, Hotmail, Sunnyvale, Calif.
 &HT;    What took online giant America Online six years to do only took
14 months for Hotmail co-founders Sabeer Bhatia and Rex Smith. With
a startup investment of $300,000, they've lured over 22 million
subscribers (and an additionall 100,000 daily) to Hotmail, one of
the Net's first free E-mail service providers and now the largest.
Unlike other providers who require special software, all Hotmail
users need is a browser and an Internet connection, while
advertisers pay for coveted space targeting specific demographics.
Sweet, simple-and lucrative.
 &HT;    It was only a matter of time before acquiring minds came
knocking. On the verge of Hotmail's IPO last December, Microsoft
head Billl Gates arrived with check in hand, snapping up the
company for a cool, estimated $400 million. Bhatia has remained on
board as CEO of Hotmail, now a wholly owned subsidiary of
Microsoft.
 &HT;    Not bad for a guy who once had doubts about striking out on his
own. The Bengalore-born Indian American dropped out of the Birla
Institute of Technology after landing a scholarship at Caltech in
1988. After getting his master's degree in electrical engineering
and PhD at Stanford, he went on to take a job as a system
integrator at Apple Computers. ``I was scared,'' Bhatia told India
Today. ``All around me young people were taking big risks and
joining start-up firms. I just couldn't sit there and not get
involved.''
 &HT;    It's fitting that Bhatia and Smith launched Hotmail on
Independence Day 1996. Freed from the confines of a dreary job at
yet another techie corporate giant, they haven't looked back since.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SANDY DALAL, 22, Designer, Sandy Dalal, New York.
 &HT;    In the realm of menswear, Nautica's David Chu was for years the
lone Asian American designer of note _ until Sandy Dalal came
along. Last year, Dalal held the menswear establishment in thrall
with a debut collection that was youthful, immaculately tailored,
forward-thinking and yet inspired by the rich aesthetics of his
Indian heritage. This year, he became the youngest designer ever to
win the CFDA award _ fashion's equivalent of the Oscar. Now, his
clothes are a hot item with style-conscious shoppers at Barneys,
Saks, and specialty stores around the country.
 &HT;    Ironically, Dalal saw the volatile fashion industry as a
professional safety net. ``I wasn't really that good a student,''
he confesses. He raised investment from family and close friends
(he estimates that so far, his company has spent around 1.4 million
dollars in launch capital.) But Dad, a CPA, and Mom, a garment
production consultant, also contributed a work ethic. ``People who
work for you, give them infinite respect,'' Dalal says,
``especially when working from the ground up.''
 &HT;    This year, Dalal expects to generate a million dollars in sales
_ but getting to that level has required enormous sacrifice. While
still a sophomore at the University of Pennsylvania, he commuted
weekly between classes in Philadelphia and his fledgling operations
in New York, ultimately suspending his studies. ``If I had it to do
again, I would have done all four years together,'' he admits.
Today time management continues to be an issue (``Do I get enough
sleep? No way!''), but Dalal has his eyes on the long haul.
``Things work themselves out over time,'' he says, adding that all
labor should be for love _ if not, then ``it's not worth your
time.''
 &HT;    NOEL LAXAMANA, 28
 &HT;    ELVIN REYES, 27
 &HT;    KORMAN ROQUE, 29
 &HT;    Founders, Classified Records, San Francisco.
 &HT;    As artists, producers, and consumers, Asian Americans are the
``Area 51'' of the music industry: It is known they exist, but
rarely are they spotted on the front lines. The founders of
Classified Records are changing all that. When the three (plus
co-founder Rino Que who now has limited involvement) got the idea
to start a record label to promote the Bay Area's rich Filipino
American music talent, they used their existing music studio and
put together more than $20,000 in start up money. All they needed
was a radio-ready artist.
 &HT;    Six months later, they fell on urban vocalist Jocelyn Enriquez.
Her hit single ``I've Been Thinking About You,'' caught the
attention of record companies and radio stations across the
country. By 1997 Classified entered a joint venture with Tommy Boy
to produce her second album, a single from which, ``A Little Bit of
Ecstasy,'' topped Billboard's Hot Dance charts for six weeks.
 &HT;    But Classified says it's not beholden only to dance music or,
for that matter, Asian American musicians. ``We are doing dance
music, R&AMP;B, and alternative,'' says Roque. And along with Filipino
American artists like Julie Plug, Drop N' Harmony, Pinay,
Classified has added names like Latino artist M:G.
 &HT;    Roque likens the future road of Classified to the one traveled
by the legendary Motown Records, which consolidated a community's
talent and resources to turn musical unknowns into household names.
He envisions Classified doing the same: propelling Asian American
artists out of the backwaters of pop music and into the mainstream.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    DINEH MOJAHER, 25, CEO and President, Hard Candy, Inc. Beverly
Hills, Calif.
 &HT;    Ever hear of nail polish with attitude? Meet Dineh Mojaher, who
founded Hard Candy, the hottest new name in cosmetics, out of her
parents' Beverly Hills home. Now a fave among the young and the
style-conscious, Hard Candy started three years ago when Mojaher, a
second semester senior at the University of Southern California,
found herself in a fashion emergency _ baby-blue heels and no
matching nail polish. In a pinch, she mixed different nail polishes
until she got the color she wanted.
 &HT;    Today, Hard Candy offers more than 35 colors of nail polish _
with funky names like ``trailer trash'' and ``pimp'' _ as well as a
full spectrum of cosmetics. Mojaher admits that the road to posting
$10 million dollars in annual sales is not without its pitfalls.
``My mistakes happened to be being naive, hiring out of
desperation, and out of need, which you can't avoid in business,''
says Mojaher. ``My best advice for entrepreneurs is to learn from
your mistakes, surround yourself with the right team, and try to be
straight-forward with yourself and go with your gut.''
 &HT;    Mojaher runs the business with the help of her sister and
boyfriend. The cosmetics magnate also got a $50,000 investment
boost from mom and dad, although that meant putting school on hold.
``My dad, who is actually a doctor, is disenchanted with what the
medical field is like,'' says the potential M.D. ``So he was glad
and excited for me.'' Eventually, Mojaher plans to return to finish
her undergraduate degree, but for now she enjoys minding the candy
store.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    JULIUS PARAS, 28, Founder, Project PULL, Mountain View, Calif.
 &HT;    When Julius Paras was an undergrad at Stanford, he didn't see
many other Filipino Americans on campus. So in 1994, a year after
graduating, he started Project PULL, a non-profit which preps young
Filipinos and other high school students of color _ who might
otherwise have thought that they weren't ``college material'' _ to
get into college. Project PULL coaches students into reassessing
themselves and their educational potential, and provides them with
much-needed role models of academic achievement.
 &HT;    Paras began by presenting leadership workshops at Filipino
American student conferences, followed by the creation of an online
networking resource for Filipino American youth, the BARANGAY
website, at www.projectpull.org. A year-and-a-half later, with a
$15,000 seed grant from the echoing green foundation and support
from Filipinos for Affirmative Action in Oakland and the Asian
American Activities Center at Stanford, he launched a one-week
summer leadership academy for high school teens.
 &HT;    Admittedly, says Paras, raising funds and recruiting help hasn't
been easy, but the rewards speak for themselves. This fall, all of
the students who were high school juniors during the inaugural 1997
program enrolled in community colleges or four-year universities.
Two-thirds of the original participants were so energized they
returned this year to help out as volunteers.
 &HT;    The key to achieving a 100 percent success rate? Paras says,
``Be positive, stay focused, and keep promises to yourself and to
others.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MARY CHUNG, 31, Founder and Executive Director, National Asian
Women's Health Organization, San Francisco.
 &HT;    OK, so she's over 30. But Mary Chung founded NAWHO, the nation's
leading health organization for Asian women, at the tender age of
26.
 &HT;    As a youngster, Chung had her mind set on the law school trek.
But her career plans changed when she took a stint at San
Francisco's Asian Law Caucus during a two-and-a-half year hiatus
from the University of San Francisco. Upon completing her economics
degree, she withheld the law school applications and joined a
women's reproductive rights organization instead. It was there that
it occurred to her to fuse both sides of her identity as an Asian
woman in her community work. Suddenly, the idea for NAWHO clicked.
``I realized I wanted to do national work, to get involved in the
politics, the public policy debates,'' she says. ``I wanted to
change the debate on Asian American women. Period.''
 &HT;    In 1993, Chung began NAWHO with a $25,000 start-up grant from
the Jesse Smith Noyes foundation, a voice-mailbox hooked up to her
home, and three volunteers. Now, NAWHO has a $1 million budget and
offers the country's first toll-free hotline for information and
referral on breast and cervical cancer available in four Asian
languages. With its numerous educational programs and research
studies, health leaders and policymakers alike recognize NAWHO as
the first stop when it comes to the health concerns of Asian
American women. There are ``stereotypes reflected in (mainstream)
health-related policies and programs which have limited their
effectiveness in assessing and responding to the health care needs
of Asian women and girls,'' says Chung. She created NAWHO to combat
just that.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ENG HERR, 29, Executive Director, The Hmong Minnesota Pacific
Association, St. Paul, Minnesota.
 &HT;    After gaining professional experience in public relations and
doing outreach with the local Boys and Girls Club, Eng Tonva Herr
saw the need for a special organization in St. Paul _ one which
would serve the city's 65,000-strong Hmong community and promote
self-sufficiency among its high percentages on public assistance.
 &HT;    It was far from easy, Herr admits. His first challenge was to
get people, despite his youth, to take him seriously. ``They think
young people can't do this and can't do that,'' he recalls. But in
1992, Herr pooled his own money with donations from other
individuals and founded the Hmong Minnesota Pacific Association.
The Hmong Association now offers tutoring, job counseling, health
education, child care, and housing placement among its many
programs. Herr's perseverance is already paying off: Where local
Hmong American youth were once at high risk for dropping out of
school, the Association is largely responsible for boosting the
area's graduation rates to 90 percent in high school and 85 percent
in college.
 &HT;    The Association's ultimate goal, Herr says, is to integrate
Hmong Americans into the American mainstream and to give political
voice to a people alienated and displaced by the devastation of
war. ``We're the only human beings in the world that possess a
nation without a state,'' says the young visionary, who is low-key
about the kudos he's received, like the St. Paul Companies
Leadership in Neighborhood Award and the City of St. Paul Parks and
Recreation Award. ``If I do something good,'' he says, ``I usually
don't tell people about it, because it's part of my job to give
back to the people I grew up with.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WELLY YANG, 25, Artistic Director, Second Generation
Productions, New York.
 &HT;    ``There's so much incredible performing talent in the community
that's not being harnessed,'' says actor Welly Yang. ``So I wanted
to be like Ben Franklin and create some electricity.''
 &HT;    After finishing a two-year stint on Broadway as Thuy in ``Miss
Saigon,'' Yang pulled together colleagues from the entertainment
industry and financial support from the Asian American community to
found Second Generation, a theater company devoted to celebrating
the history and achievements of Asian Americans. So far, the
company has mounted successful music theater showcases at small
venues in New York and colleges around the country. But ultimately,
Second Generation plans to launch a full-book musical called
``Making Tracks,'' a rock opera with dramatic vignettes depicting
different eras of Asian American history.
 &HT;    Needless to say, this will take some money. To run the company,
Yang has been able to rely on the good will of friends ``like a CPA
doing accounting stuff, graphic designers, friends helping me make
phone calls to colleges.'' Ultimately, he says, a healthy, small
theater company putting out two or three productions a year will
require a budget of a half-million dollars. ``Until then, you're
working out of your apartment.''
 &HT;    Still, the payoff from their first production, for which they
raised $20,000, was about far more than money. Yang says audience
members watched the staged commemoration of a massacre that
happened in Taiwan 50 years ago and were ``moved that young people
really cared about what happened in the past.'' For Yang, putting
Asian American faces and experiences on stage is about shattering
the isolation that Asian Americans, especially artists, have felt
from history and from each other. ``Our history gives us purpose,''
he says. ``And the community gives us strength.''
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 A. Magazine: Inside Asian America 
