<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTOONIST'S SATIRE LOST ON SOME READERS. Columnist Bill Maxwell
used to think that opinion columnists, those natural-born
curmudgeons, were the loneliest souls at newspapers. ``I now
believe that editorial cartoonists are the ultimate outsiders,'' he
writes. ``They are the most misunderstood of all journalists
because their craft _ alternately making us laugh, curse and think
_ is finicky and strange to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-SATIRE-MISUNDERSTOOD:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   VOTER BACKLASH AGAINST THE GOP. Gay voters made up 4 percent of
the 1998 mid-term electorate, according to exit polling conducted
by Voter News Service (VNS). ``That's a piece of post election
analysis largely ignored by the mainstream media,'' writes
columnist Chuck Colbert, noting that only African Americans (10
percent) and Latinos (5 percent) exceeded the numbers of gay voters
this year. But the 4 percent turn out was not lost on the
leadership of the Democratic Party, which for the most part
benefited from the gay vote, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-GOP-BACKLASH:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   ROUND-UP THE USUAL SUSPECTS! Strong movie statements can move
populations and their leaders into and out of turbulent issues like
no other medium, notes columnist Raul Lowery Contreras. ``When
properly portrayed, for example, American political issues have
been decided one way or the other by how they were played in movies
or on television,'' he writes. Such is the case of the movies,
``The Siege'' and ``Enemy of the State.'' ``These two movies are
important,'' he says, ``to be viewed by anyone concerned about the
continuing encroachment on the rights guaranteed to Americans by
the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-MOVIE-SUSPECTS:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   A GRANDMOTHER'S HOPE CHEST. What was most difficult about a
recent move from the home her family lived in for 13 years was
packing items from the attic, notes columnist Kirsten Chapman _
those leftovers she'd often pictured in the hands of a future
granddaughter and grandson: her children's books and toys, some of
their clothes and costumes. ``The sum of it all? A grandmother's
hope chest,'' she writes. Her two children are unmarried and
neither hears wedding bells in the near future. ``At 55, I fret
over `grandchildren.' When will I meet them?'' she wonders. Her
biological clock, she says, is winding down.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-GRANDCHILDREN-CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   VISIONARIES: 10 HOT ASIAN AMERICAN ENTREPRENEURS UNDER 30.
Whether it's a cutting-edge internet company or an organization
that provides urgently needed programs to an underserved community,
realizing a personal vision means taking risks, raising money,
managing allies, and keeping the faith in the face of sometimes
heartbreaking obstacles. A. Magazine offers 10 individuals who
redefine what it means to be young, successful, Asian American, and
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-TOP-TEN-ASIANS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a'' general
news.
