<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   11 EUROPEAN NATIONS MOVE TO LOWER INTEREST RATES
</P>
<P>
   Eleven European nations simultaneously cut their interest rates
to a nearly uniform low level in the most coordinated action yet
toward European monetary union.
</P>
<P>
   The move came a month before the nations adopt the euro as a
single currency and marked a drastic shift in policy. As recently
as two months ago, European central bankers had adamantly refused
to lower rates because they were intent on establishing the
credibility of the euro and the fledgling European Central Bank in
world markets.
</P>
<P>
   AGREEMENT REACHED ON ENCRYPTION
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government announced that an agreement had been reached
in Vienna that was expected to produce new international controls
on the export of data scrambling software and hardware, a
long-contentious issue pitting individual privacy against national
security in the information age.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement is a compromise that places new restrictions
on the exporting of mass-market software with keys above 64 bits in
length.
</P>
<P>
   TOSHIBA AND FUJITSU FORM VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba and Fujitsu announced a joint venture that they said
should allow both companies to reduce costs and development time
for the next generation of their computer memory chips.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. PRODUCTIVITY RISES 3 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Productivity in the United States rose at a revised 3 percent
annual rate in the three months ended in September, a sign that the
almost eight-year-old expansion of the economy will stay on track
into the new year. But the Labor Department said first-time jobless
claims rose 12,000, to a seasonally adjusted 313,000 for the week
ended last Saturday, after falling 39,000 the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government said Thursday that the economy had
shrunk at an annual rate of 2.6 percent in the third quarter,
signaling deeper troubles ahead for Japan as it struggles through
its worst recession since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIALTY STORES HAVE GOOD MONTH
</P>
<P>
   Specialty stores and discounters outdistanced major department
store chains in holiday sales during November, according to monthly
results from big retailers. Analysts attributed the gains at
discounters and specialty chains to efforts to focus on a core
customer group or product category.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHT-TRUCK SALES EXCEED CAR SALES
</P>
<P>
   Americans bought more sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks and
vans than cars last month, for the first time since a brief period
at the end of World War II, as very low gasoline prices, low
interest rates and a strong economy kept overall auto sales brisk.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of so-called light trucks reached 50.8 percent of the
market last month. The broad popularity of these vehicles has
accelerated in the last three years with the introduction of much
bigger models like the Ford Expedition and Dodge Durango.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T TESTS CABLE TV SERVICES
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has set up demonstrations of its ability to offer phone
services over cable-television networks as the company prepares to
use cable TV to break into the $100 billion market for local phone
service in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   TICKETMASTER OFFERING SOARS
</P>
<P>
   Investors snapped up the initial public offering of Ticketmaster
Online-City Search, an on-line seller of tickets and city guides,
sending its shares as high as four times their offering price.
</P>
</TEXT>
