<SLUG> BC-TICKETMASTER-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYERS LIFT TICKETMASTER SHARES TO 4 TIMES OFFERING PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors snapped up the initial public offering of Ticketmaster
Online-City Search Inc., an online seller of tickets and city
guides, sending its shares as high as four times their offering
price.
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster shares closed at $40.25 in Nasdaq trading, after
trading as high as $56.38. Because the shares opened at $52, many
investors who bought in the first hour of trading lost money on the
stock. The company sold seven million shares at $14 each on
Wednesday, up from the $11 to $13 range set by the lead
underwriter, Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities LLC.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a ticker-symbol mix-up, the initial public offering of
Ticketmaster also prompted an unusual flurry of trading in the
shares of Temco Service Industries, a provider of building
maintenance and security services. Temco shares, which trade under
the symbol tcmo, and traded under the symbol tcms prior to Oct. 7,
soared as high as $65 before investors realized they were not
buying Ticketmaster, which now uses tcms. Temco shares closed at
$25.50, down $3.25, in over-the-counter trading. At $40.25,
Ticketmaster's 69.5 million shares outstanding give it a market
valuation of $2.80 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Allen, an analyst with Forrester Research, said
Ticketmaster needed to distinguish itself from other online city
guides, but added that ``event ticketing is going to be one of the
key drivers for electronic commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Forrester estimates online ticket purchases growing from $115
million this year to $2.75 billion by 2003, Ms. Allen said.
Ticketmaster, however, needs to find better ways to link its city
guides with the ticket business, Ms. Allen added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 2123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981203.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-MOORE-COLUMN04-CO     12-03 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MOORE-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BCS `the best system we could have now'
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Let's see. To win the national championship, Tennessee
must conquer Mississippi State in Saturday's SEC championship game,
then somebody else during the Fiesta Bowl, then everything from a
slew of computer rankings to the quality of their quartile.
</P>
<P>
   Computers? Quartiles? Not only that, the Vols' strength of
schedule and their standing in the two major polls will determine
where they finish after this first year of the Bowl Championship
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Good.
</P>
<P>
   Now the BCS isn't the loveliest thing for separating the best
from the rest in college football. It isn't the lousiest, either.
It is simply lovelier than anything shy of what would rank among
the greatest horrors known to mankind, and that is a playoff system
at the Division I-A level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never supported having a playoff system at this level,
and I never will,'' said Georgia associate athletics director Dick
Bestwick, sounding like the wise man that he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best system we could have now,'' Bestwick said.
``Still, the better way is to do what (Georgia athletics director)
Vince Dooley has espoused in recent years, and that is to structure
everything around the bowl games. In the end, you could take the
top two teams and have them play for the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, but there always is this: If the NCAA's objective
is to get as close as it can to selecting the top college football
team in the country at its highest level, then it must have a
January Jubilee to match its March Madness in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, that shouldn't be the NCAA's objective. Soon after
a January Jubilee, we'd see efforts to get more of the Division
I-A's 112 teams involved to create a February Festival. After that,
we'd eventually see tackling right up to the first dribble of March
Madness.
</P>
<P>
   So why is this a problem? Although it is flawed, there still is
this concept known as the student-athlete that separates college
sports from the professional ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand that, except on game days and the
camaraderie you have with others, football is about as fun as
digging a ditch,'' said Bestwick, a 40-year veteran in athletics,
ranging from coaching at Virginia to serving as a scout for the
Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, going to a bowl is fun for the kids. They spend
about a week to 10 days at the site. That definitely would change
with a playoff system that would have kids going into a city the
day before a game and probably leaving right afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just imagine how terrible the media would be. You'd have these
kids going into a Super Bowl mode. But I don't think any of this
will happen. If it does, the college presidents would be the
biggest hypocrites of all. There would be no academic justification
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   None. As for those who mention that Division I-A is the only
level of college football without a playoff system, Bestwick said,
``It isn't anywhere near the same game. The players at this level
are bigger and faster. There's more pounding on their bodies, and
that only would increase by adding more games to their season.''
</P>
<P>
   So the solution here is obvious: If you have problems with the
BCS, well, simply get over it.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
