<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2251 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-MSTATE-ANALYSIS04     12-03 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MSTATE-ANALYSIS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dogs win with tenacity
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mention the seeming hopelessness of their cause
against Tennessee, and watch Mississippi State players grin. Not to
conceal anger, but as a familiar reaction to what is being called a
mismatch for the SEC championship.
</P>
<P>
   The top-ranked Volunteers appear to have it all: speed and depth
at virtually every position, playmakers, an excellent kicking game
and survival skills _ not to mention luck _ that have bailed them
out of their closest calls.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 23 Bulldogs are well aware that they're unknown and
practically unloved outside of their cloistered environs. They
foiled a Tennessee-Arkansas rematch by knocking off the Razorbacks
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet State isn't without some strong suits that have helped it
turn in a respectable 8-3 mark, the program's best in five years.
They have 13 senior starters, including four on a solid offensive
line; some good quickness and flexibility on defense; a strong
kicking game and special-teams play; and a gritty mind-set that has
contributed to clutch wins late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Tennessee coach) Phillip (Fulmer) says they have no
stars, that's not really true,'' coach Jackie Sherrill said,
rattling off the names of Tee Martin, Al Wilson, Peerless Price and
the injured Jamal Lewis. ``We don't have any players with a lot of
name recognition, or anybody who is going to be a high draft
choice. But we have guys with no quit in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, they're 14-point underdogs, which might be a generous
line for the Dogs, who have absorbed some brutal losses to bad
teams (LSU, Oklahoma State) on a schedule brimming with exactly one
team currently ranked (No. 11 Arkansas).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a problem for us,'' starting free safety Eric Daniel
said. ``I think we play better that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Edward Smith, who might be playing as well at his
position as anyone in the league, is happy to chime in: ``We've
been overlooked, and we're being overlooked now. We showed we were
the better team against Arkansas, and Tennessee just barely beat
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are five keys for the Bulldogs against the Volunteers:
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line, Johnson Senior tailback James Johnson, the SEC's
leading rusher, has seen limited action the last two games with a
groin pull and a strained shoulder. If he does play, he is far from
100 percent. Without him, State has been unable to establish a
running game, and redshirt freshman quarterback Wayne Madkin
doesn't have enough experience or options to fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   A hefty, talented offensive line, which averages 310 pounds,
needs to contend with a quick Tennessee defensive front seven to
keep State close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know their line is active,'' guard Randy Thomas said. ``But
we can really move, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Contain Tee Martin
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Joe Lee Dunn's bag of tricks features an
array of formations, in part to make up for a lack of size. The
ends, Smith and Cornell Menafee and nose guard Kenwoynne Smith, all
weigh around 230. But they're good blitzers, and State seems
willing to let its SEC-best pass defense handle long throws
downfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have an athletic quarterback,'' Sherrill said,
``you're better off keeping him in the pocket and letting him throw
rather than flushing him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Create turnovers
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs have scored five touchdowns on defense and four on
special teams. Brian Hazlewood kicked five field goals against
Arkansas and has good range, with a 52-yard best.
</P>
<P>
   Big plays on offense
</P>
<P>
   Senior flanker Kevin Prentiss, only 5 feet 8, has played well
the past two games, leaping to make big receptions and running well
after the catch. Given the Vols' weak link in the secondary, his
acrobatics might be the most reliable weapon State can employ.
</P>
<P>
   Maintain level of confidence
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs think that they don't have much to lose against a
team needing a win to keep its national championship hopes alive.
And they've got the experience factor, if not the stockpile of
talent, on their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our maturity level helped us finish the season strong,''
defensive back Tim Nelson said. ``It's been up to us. We just
didn't give up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
