<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OLEARY-GATECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Stability' for Tech, O'Leary
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech football coach George O'Leary signed a
new contract Thursday, giving Tech some insurance that he will be
around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's new deal is a six-year rollover contract worth
$600,000 annually, an increase of $184,000 a year from his previous
five-year rollover contract. Under the new contract, if O'Leary
leaves Tech for another college coaching job, he would have to pay
a $1.5 million penalty, the same amount Tech has to pay O'Leary if
the school terminates his contract.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, which goes into effect Jan. 1, the day Tech plays
Notre Dame in the Gator Bowl, includes incentives worth as much as
$100,000. Under the previous contract, O'Leary could have left for
another job without paying a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to get it done and move on,'' said O'Leary, who is
27-21 in his fourth full season at Tech and headed to a second
consecutive bowl. ``The biggest thing you get out of this contract
is stability in the program and in the coaching staff, and
consistency in a football program is essentially what it takes to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, whose name was mentioned in the coaching searches at
Auburn and South Carolina, hopes the signing of this contract
reaffirms his commitment to Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never changed my stance,'' O'Leary said. ``I'm very happy at
Georgia Tech. I needed to get some things ironed out; it just took
some dialogue to get that done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech athletics director Dave Braine said his goal has been to do
a new deal with O'Leary since Braine joined the program in the
spring of 1997 and heard concerns that Tech lost every good coach
it got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everybody thinks this had something to do with
(Auburn),'' Braine said. ``It did not. He's done a great job with
this program, and he's a good fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
