<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SEC-CHAMPIONSHIP0     12-03 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-CHAMPIONSHIP04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Springboard to No.1
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the powers that be in the SEC raised the concept
of a conference championship game in 1991, the traditionalists
scoffed. Then they predicted all manner of dire results.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, said the naysayers, a tough extra game would ruin the
conference's shot at another national title. In fact, they said,
the conference wouldn't even get a chance to play for the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Today, on the eve of the seventh SEC championship game, it can
be said: They were wrong. If No. 1 Tennessee (11-0) beats No. 23
Mississippi State (8-3) Saturday in the Georgia Dome, the Vols have
a good chance to be the fifth SEC championship game winner in seven
years to advance to a bowl game that could determine the national
championship. Two of those previous four winners, Alabama in 1992
and Florida in 1996, used a victory in the SEC championship game as
a springboard to the national title. Not bad for a game that was
supposed to rip the competitive guts out of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly can't say it surprises me,'' said Tennessee coach
Phillip Fulmer, who is looking for his second SEC title in a row.
``If you go through this league undefeated, as tough as it is, you
certainly should be in the mix of teams for the national
championship. Week in and week out, there is no tougher experience
than going through an SEC schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   With a win, Tennessee should finish no worse than second in the
Bowl Championship Series standings, which will be released Sunday
afternoon. If the two other undefeated teams at the top of the BCS,
Kansas State and UCLA, both win Saturday, Tennessee would play one
of them in the Fiesta Bowl for the national championship. If the
Volunteers win the SEC title again, Fulmer said, he has no doubt
that his team belongs in the Fiesta Bowl. ``We've beaten four of
the Top 25 (Florida, Georgia, Arkansas and Syracuse) and three of
those teams were in the Top 10 when we played them,'' Fulmer said.
``But more than that, I just think that if you're the SEC champion
and you're 12-0, you have got to be in the big game.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick look at the event backs up Fulmer's point:
</P>
<P>
   1992
</P>
<P>
   Alabama was 11-0 and ranked second when it faced Florida in the
inaugural SEC championship game at Legion Field in Birmingham. A
win would guarantee the Crimson Tide a date with No. 1 Miami in the
Sugar Bowl. The Gators put a scare into the mostly Alabama crowd
when they scored to tie the game at 21 with 8:21 left. But Antonio
Langham returned an interception 27 yards for a touchdown and
Alabama went on to a 28-21 win. The Crimson Tide beat Miami 34-13
in the Sugar Bowl for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   1995
</P>
<P>
   Florida was 11-0 and ranked No. 2 when it beat Arkansas 34-3 at
the Georgia Dome for the conference title. That victory set up a
national championship game with No. 1 Nebraska in the Fiesta Bowl.
The Gators hung tough early but were no match for the Cornhuskers,
losing 62-24.
</P>
<P>
   1996
</P>
<P>
   Florida was 10-1, ranked No. 4, and seemingly out of the
national picture when it arrived at the SEC championship game
against Alabama. But earlier in the day, No. 3 Nebraska was upset
by Texas in the Big 12 championship game. Florida beat Alabama
45-30 at the Georgia Dome and the next day was No. 3 behind No. 1
Florida State and No. 2 Arizona State. With Arizona State committed
to the Rose Bowl, Florida was invited to the Sugar Bowl for a
rematch with Florida State, which had beaten the Gators 24-21 in
the last game of the regular season. On Jan. 1, Arizona State was
upset by Ohio State in the Rose Bowl. On Jan. 2, Florida trounced
Florida State 52-20 in New Orleans and won its first national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   1997
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee was 10-1 and ranked No. 3 when it rallied to beat
Auburn 30-29 for the SEC title. The Vols then traveled to the
Orange Bowl to meet Nebraska, ranked No. 2. Had No. 1 Michigan lost
to Washington State in the Rose Bowl on Jan. 1, the Orange Bowl on
Jan. 2 would have been for the national championship. Michigan won,
however, and claimed the AP national title. Nebraska thumped
Tennessee 42-17 and was rewarded by the coaches who vote in the USA
Today/ESPN poll, who gave their national title to Tom Osborne and
the Cornhuskers.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that history, if an SEC team is undefeated and wins in
December in the SEC championship game, it should be playing for the
national title in January. Even with a loss, the SEC champ still
has an outside shot.
</P>
<P>
   One coach who believes in the SEC championship game as a
toughening ground is Florida's Steve Spurrier, who had a team in
five of the six previous games. The SEC championship ``is all we
talk about around here, and it's all we will talk about,'' said
Spurrier, who won five SEC titles 1991-1996. ``That's because it's
a real championship that you can win on the field. That other thing
is nice, but people have to vote you in and there's a lot of luck
involved. That was certainly the case when we won it. That year,
God was certainly smiling down on the Gators.''
</P>
<P>
   SEC commissioner Roy Kramer was aware of the potential negative
impact of the game when he and his staff brought the concept to
reality. Kramer, a longtime football coach before getting into the
administrative end of the sport, said he thinks that the game
actually improves an SEC team's chances of winning the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to win the game, of course,'' Kramer said, ``but if
you do win, your team is going to be battle-tested. Chances are
they won't face anything in a bowl game they haven't seen before.
If you ask the coaches who have been involved, they'll tell you
that the SEC championship game is really more intense than most
bowl games. It's more of a Super Bowl-type atmosphere. Once your
kids have played in this thing, they are not going to have their
heads turned by anything they see in a bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer can attest to that, after his team played in the SEC
championship game for the first time last December. Tennessee was a
solid favorite over Auburn, but the Vols came out tight and
preoccupied with their surroundings. They fell behind 20-7 before
rallying behind Peyton Manning to win 30-29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that it's really not something you can prepare for,
because the SEC championship game is so unlike any other game we
had played in,'' Fulmer said. ``The festive atmosphere is great.
The noise is incredible in the Dome. We play in a lot of loud
places. Our place (Neyland Stadium) is pretty loud with 107,000
people. But our guys had to make some adjustments. Fortunately, we
were able to do it and win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Tennessee, if it can defeat Mississippi State, will become
the next team to use the SEC championship game as a springboard to
a chance at the national championship. The trend, Fulmer said,
should not end anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
