<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TENN-ANALYSIS04-C     12-03 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-ANALYSIS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols must stop sweep
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Until last December, Phillip Fulmer had never been to
an SEC championship game. ``No,'' the Tennessee coach said and
chuckled, ``I really don't want to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as a spectator, anyway. Fulmer wanted to go in style, in
character, as coach of the SEC Eastern Division champions. He
finally got the opportunity last year and guided UT to its 12th SEC
title. Now the Vols are back in the Georgia Dome again, their
Saturday opponent Mississippi State, but their eyes ultimately on a
much bigger prize: A national championship in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Before going to Tempe, though, UT must go 12-0. How? Here are
five keys:
</P>
<P>
   Stop the MSU sweep
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to pound the football at you,'' UT defensive
coordinator John Chavis said. ``Pound you, pound you, pound you,
then throw play-action passes. But they want to run the football,
first and foremost.''
</P>
<P>
   And first and foremost, the Bulldogs run the sweep. Whether it's
the banged-up James Johnson, the SEC's leading rusher (1,345 yards)
or backups Dicenzo Miller and Chris Rainey running behind a huge
offensive line, MSU sees every quarter of every game as a sweeps
period. ``We haven't seen a lot of sweep, and they're committed to
it,'' said Chavis, whose defense is eighth nationally against the
run, allowing 96.5 yards a game. ``They run the sweep better than
anybody in the country. They run well between the tackles, but they
run the sweep.''
</P>
<P>
   Limit turnovers
</P>
<P>
   In last year's SEC title game, Tennessee made six turnovers
against Auburn. The Vols fumbled six times, losing four, and threw
two interceptions. They trailed 20-10 at halftime before rallying
for a 30-29 win. This year, ball security has been a UT strength.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols lead the SEC in turnover margin at plus 15, their 1.36
average tying for fifth nationally. They have committed just 15
turnovers _ nine fumbles, six interceptions _ while forcing 30, 16
fumble recoveries, 14 interceptions. Tennessee has fumbled just 21
times, compared with 33 total fumbles last season, and cut its '97
interception total of 12 in half. In last Saturday's 41-0 rout of
Vanderbilt, UT turned six Vandy turnovers into 24 points.
</P>
<P>
   Running game must work
</P>
<P>
   When Peyton Manning left, it was clear that Tennessee needed
offensive diversification. But when the Vols lost tailback Jamal
Lewis with a knee injury in the fourth game, the ground game didn't
grind to a halt. Rather, it has thrived behind tailbacks Travis
Henry (850 yards rushing) and Travis Stephens (427), who play
behind a great offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Tee Martin (307 yards rushing, seven touchdowns) has
helped UT become the SEC's top running team (216.8 yards a game,
13th nationally). A sound ground game will help nullify Mississippi
State's offensive strength; the Bulldogs' were outgained in rushing
in two of their three losses.
</P>
<P>
   Tee Martin needs big game
</P>
<P>
   Since adjusting to the starter role in the season's first month,
Martin has been outstanding, starting with the second half at
Georgia, when he threw for two touchdowns, turning a 9-3 halftime
lead into a 22-3 game. After completing less than 50 percent of his
passes in the first five games, throwing four interceptions, he's
sizzled in the past six UT wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't trade him for any other quarterback in the
country,'' Fulmer said. Martin is second in the SEC in passing
efficiency (148.26) and 14th in the nation. In the past six games,
Martin is 87-of-130 (66.9 per cent) for 1,291 yards, eight
touchdowns and one interception. He hasn't thrown an interception
in his past 59 pass attempts. Martin has thrown and rushed for a
score in each of the past four games. If he continues against the
stunting schemes of Mississippi State defensive coordinator Joe Lee
Dunn, Martin gives UT a big edge over Bulldogs redshirt freshman
quarterback Wayne Madkin.
</P>
<P>
   Jump to an early end
</P>
<P>
   In each of its three losses, Mississippi State fell behind
quickly. In the clamor of the Georgia Dome, that could prove
damaging. Tennessee was admittedly tight in its first championship
game a year ago. This year, the Vols know what to expect, while
Mississippi State will find a far more frenzied atmosphere than in
its two Peach Bowls here, in 1993 and '94.
</P>
<P>
   But Tennessee must focus on Dec. 5, not Jan. 4, when the
national championship will be decided in the Fiesta Bowl, between
the top two teams in the Bowl Championship Series rankings. Despite
being a 14-point favorite, UT can't overlook MSU.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
