</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-SEASON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tennessee season in review
 &HT;    By Leo Willingham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 34, SYRACUSE 33
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 5 at Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hall kicked a 27-yard field goal as time expired as the
Volunteers escaped with the victory. Quarterback Tee Martin
completed only nine of 26 passes in his first start of the season,
but led the team on a 72-yard drive in the final minutes to set up
Hall's field goal. Jamal Lewis rushed for 141 yards and a touchdown
for Tennessee. Record: 1-0
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 20, FLORIDA 17
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 19 at Knoxville
</P>
<P>
   Hall provided the game-winner for the second contest in a row, a
41-yarder in overtime as the Volunteers ended their five-game
losing streak against Florida. Big plays were the difference for
the Vols as they scored on a 57-yard run by Shawn Bryson and a
29-yard pass from Martin to Peerless Price. Linebacker Al Wilson
led the defense by forcing three of Florida's four fumbles. Record:
2-0.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 42, HOUSTON 7
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 26 at Knoxville
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers appeared flat in the nonconference game against
the Cougars, one week after their emotional win over Florida and a
week before a key conference game at Auburn. Despite committing 11
penalties and two turnovers, the Vols cruised as Martin passed for
four touchdowns and Lewis rushed for 135 yards and two touchdowns.
Record: 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 17, AUBURN 9
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 3 at Auburn
</P>
<P>
   Lewis rushed for 140 yards and a touchdown but injured a knee,
sidelining him for the remainder of the season. Shaun Ellis scored
on a 90-yard interception return of a shovel pass by Auburn
quarterback Ben Leard. Record: 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 22, GEORGIA 3
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 10 at Athens
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers won their eighth in a row over Georgia,
dominating both lines of scrimmage in a game that was more
one-sided than the score would indicate. Martin passed for two
touchdowns and Hall kicked three field goals as the Vols moved into
sole possession of first place in the SEC East. Record: 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 35, ALABAMA 18
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 24 at Knoxville
</P>
<P>
   Price's 100-yard kickoff return in the third quarter helped the
Vols pull away for their fourth victory in a row over the Crimson
Tide. Martin completed 10 of 14 for 117 yards and also rushed for
two touchdowns. Record: 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 49, SOUTH CAROLINA 14
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 31 at Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Martin set two NCAA records with 23 consecutive completions.
Martin, who ended the Alabama game with a completion, broke the
existing NCAA records for consecutive completions in one game (22)
and two games (23). Record: 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 37, ALA.-BIRMINGHAM 13
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 7 at Knoxville
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers held Alabama-Birmingham to 71 passing yards, and
Travis Henry rushed for 104 yards to lead an offense that gained
447. The win, coupled with Ohio State's loss to Michigan State,
vaulted the Vols to the nation's No. 1 ranking for the first time
since 1956. Record: 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 28, ARKANSAS 24
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 14 at Knoxville
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers' stay at the top of the rankings nearly ended
after one week, but they capitalized on a late Arkansas fumble and
drove 43 yards for the winning touchdown with 28 seconds remaining.
Henry rushed for a career-high 197 yards, including the winning
touchdown. The Vols rallied from a 21-3 deficit for the win.
Record: 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 59, KENTUCKY 21
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 21 at Knoxville
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats were supposed to provide a stiff challenge, but the
Vols opened a 38-7 halftime lead and clinched their second
consecutive division title. Martin passed for 189 yards and a
touchdown and ran for another score while the defense sacked
Kentucky's Tim Couch six times and held him to only two touchdown
passes. Record: 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 41, VANDERBILT 0
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 28 at Nashville
</P>
<P>
   The previous three games in the series had been decided by a
total of 19 points, but the Vols dominated the Commodores and
recorded their first shutout since 1995. The defense held
Vanderbilt to 174 total yards and had four interceptions, and Henry
added 136 yards rushing and a touchdown. Record: 11-0.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
