<SLUG> BC-FBN-MORA04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mora keeps calm as Colts keep losing
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ More than two years after Jim Mora's personal
Chernobyl, the self-inflicted wounds have healed and the physical
and mental rehabilitation is complete.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many thoughts about the emotional meltdown of Oct.
20, 1996, which signaled the end of a stormy tenure in New Orleans
and the beginning of his much-needed hiatus from the NFL. His
ballistic reaction to the Saints' demoralizing 19-7 loss at
Carolina that day, if not a life-altering incident, has been
catalogued carefully as a learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   After having spent the subsequent years debunking the notion
that he is a raving lunatic and fielding probing questions about an
embarrassing tantrum that became his defining ESPN moment, Mora
learned the lesson well.
</P>
<P>
   Scared by the snide suggestion he might require a straitjacket
to overcome occupational burnout, Mora suddenly is a man at peace
with himself.
</P>
<P>
   So a trim and healthy-looking 63-year-old Mora is justifiably
excited about his young Indianapolis Colts team and is handling a
2-10 record with far more aplomb and patience than skeptics thought
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know how to handle things better now, I think,'' said
Mora, whose team plays the Atlanta Falcons at the Georgia Dome on
Sunday. ``We've lost some tough ones, and after those games, darn
right, you're in the tank a little bit. But you know what? I
recover a lot quicker than I used to. You learn to bounce back.
That probably comes from being more at ease with myself as a coach
now, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   The mental image of a laid-back Mora _ calm after the bitter
34-31 loss to the San Francisco 49ers earlier this season in which
the NFL publicly admitted two officiating gaffes that robbed the
Colts of an upset _ runs contrary to experience.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been no vein-bulging sideline eruptions in his
first campaign with the Colts, players here admit he has delivered
a few halftime admonitions that could have stripped the paint from
the locker room walls. And he has not attempted to camouflage his
unhappiness with the officiating this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mora is, after all, a man who rarely holds his emotions totally
in check.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, he ranks among the most human of NFL coaches, a
rare straight-shooter who does not mince words, is devoid of
pretense and regards the game more seriously than he does himself.
He is a man's man, a guy who looks you in the eye and isn't above
mixing an off-color allusion to accentuate a point, a coach who
seeks solutions more than excuses.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom-line world of the NFL, it's appropriate there are
no gray areas with Mora.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk away from a conversation with him you understand
exactly where he stands on things,'' former University of Georgia
star and Colts offensive right tackle Adam Meadows said.
</P>
<P>
   The irony there is that Mora might be one of the most
misunderstood coaches of this era, a man afforded only grudging
credit for his success. A startling statistic: In his 10 full
seasons in New Orleans, the Saints won 91 regular-season games. In
his 10 years in San Francisco, the sainted Bill Walsh won 92
regular-season contests.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there was justification for focusing on New Orleans'
postseason collapses in Mora's stint there and for bashing a stodgy
offense designed by coordinator Carl Smith. And the conscious
decision to retool an aging roster by cutting one-time stars like
Rickey Jackson may have been ill-advised. What often went
overlooked, however, is that Mora inherited a club that had never
been to the playoffs before his arrival and led it to the only four
postseason berths in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those last three or four years (in New Orleans) were hard
years, man, very hard years,'' Mora said after a Colts practice
session. ``They took it to me pretty good. We had teams that I
thought would be better than they were. Things got pretty personal
and I took them that way. Geez, it was a tough time.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been no such problems in Indianapolis, where the lack
of expectation surrounding the '98 Colts has afforded Mora and team
president Bill Polian a grace year. But where the fans of New
Orleans were ungrateful, the public here, even 14 years after the
Colts' arrival, remains unsophisticated. Sports fans still care
more about Bob Knight's recruiting classes than budding superstar
quarterback Peyton Manning, so the incremental steps Mora and the
team have taken this year have been ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the perception he is an extreme football
conservative, Mora has had offensive coordinator Tom Moore open the
offense up for Manning, and the result is it's No. 11 in the
league. There remains a daunting rebuilding task on defense, and a
disadvantageous salary cap situation for '99 could slow progress.
</P>
<P>
   But for Mora, who has rebuilt his image after the Carolina
incident and reassessed his priorities, there have been more
difficult challenges. His season away from the game _ a '97
campaign in which he was interviewed for vacancies in St. Louis and
San Diego but ended up working as a studio analyst for NBC _
certainly has re-energized him. More important, it has improved his
flagging self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those last couple of years in New Orleans, I definitely lost
some (confidence),'' Mora said. ``You want to talk about
frustration, that was it. So now, looking back, I'm glad I had the
year off. I'm refreshed. I'm upbeat. I look down the road and
there's hope here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, I know I'm a good coach and I don't give a damn what
anyone else thinks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
