<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLBEST04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Next Bledsoe test is facing Steelers
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two weeks ago, New England's Drew Bledsoe culminated a
frenetic last-minute rally against Miami, when free safety Brock
Marion fell down backpedaling. The Patriots quarterback, despite
having fractured the index finger of his throwing hand a few snaps
earlier, took advantage of the Dolphins' pratfall to find a
wide-open Shawn Jefferson with the winning touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, officials enabled Bledsoe to pull out a game with
their controversial pass interference call in the end zone which
set up a touchdown pass to tight end Ben Coates with no time
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   So what kind of excitement is on tap for Sunday's game at Three
Rivers Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I've played there,'' Bledsoe said, ``it might take
another miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Pittsburgh Steelers own six consecutive home
victories against the Patriots, the most recent a 7-6 squeaker in
the 1997 playoffs. The loser between these talented, but
torturously inconsistent, teams likely will miss the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   After the '97 playoff game, in which Bledsoe lost a fumble and
threw an interception on New England's final two possessions,
teammates came down hard on him. It didn't help, of course, that
Bledsoe demonstrated no public remorse at his blunders. Instead, he
spent his postgame time schmoozing with agent Leigh Steinberg and
fellow client Ryan Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's heroics in recent days has all but expunged those
memories from some teammates. But Bledsoe hasn't forgotten, and he
enters Three Rivers in search of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a win and I need to play well against those guys for a
change,'' Bledsoe said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the NFL ``bests'' for this weekend:
</P>
<P>
   _ Upset opportunity: Tampa Bay has lost six in a row to Green
Bay and averaged only 9.0 points. A loss on Monday night all but
eliminates the Buccaneers from a wild-card spot. The Bucs will find
a way to win against a Packers team with plenty of injuries and the
distractions accompanying the pending exit of coach Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual matchup: The in-line collisions between Tennessee
tailback Eddie George and Baltimore middle linebacker Ray Lewis
will be bone-rattling. But we prefer a duel between Colts tailback
Marshall Faulk and Falcons linebackers Cornelius Bennett and Keith
Brooking. The Indy star has become the NFL's biggest threat out of
the backfield. The Falcons linebackers have superior coverage
skills.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fantasy play: Niners quarterback Steve Young needs one
touchdown pass to reach the 30 mark for the second time in his
career. Against a crippled Carolina secondary, he'll get it in the
first five minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grudge match: Neither Kansas City linebacker Derrick Thomas
nor Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe is likely to forget the
late-game debacle of three weeks ago. The refs will be watching
these two from the time they step off the bus. Thomas won't draw
three personal fouls again, but there's going to be some bad, bad
blood.
</P>
<P>
   _ Division game: The games usually aren't good, but there always
seems to be a subplot or two when the Cardinals and Giants meet.
This time is no different. New York quarterback Kent Graham was
once the starter in Arizona but was dumped in favor of Jake
Plummer. Giants coach Jim Fassell is a one-time Cardinals offensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
