WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: TORY REBELLION
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ William Hague, the Conservative Party leader, found
himself at odds with one group he thought he could count on, the
Tory peers in the House of Lords. Hague dismissed his party's
leader in the House of Lords, Viscount Cranborne, for striking a
deal that could let 10 percent of the 759 hereditary peers retain
their voting rights. Hague later endorsed the same legislative
proposal himself, prompting the entire Tory leadership of the Lords
to resign their front bench posts.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: AIR ROUTE TALKS CONCLUDE
</P>
<P>
   BEIJING _ U.S. officials from the Department of Transportation
concluded two days of ``encouraging'' meetings with their Chinese
counterparts to pave the way for expanded air routes between the
two countries. The officials said current passenger and cargo
schedules between the United States and China are inadequate,
considering the growing trade relationship.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: CRIME PACKAGE CLEARS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The Congress approved laws toughening penalties
for people who escape house arrest, use credit cards fraudulently,
possess chemicals to produce drugs or exploit minors. President
Ernesto Zedillo proposed the anti-crime package a year ago.
Opposition legislators criticized some of the measures as
repressive.
</P>
<P>
   GRENADA: ELECTIONS PLANNED
</P>
<P>
   Parliament was dissolved to make way for new elections after the
New National Party's majority collapsed when Foreign Minister
Raphael Fletcher resigned last weekend. Fletcher accused the
governing party of corruption. Prime Minister Keith Mitchell
accused Fletcher of plotting with Libya to topple him.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: ANNIVERSARY OF LAND-MINE PACT
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ Jody Williams, Nobel Peace Prize winner, returned to
Ottawa to mark the first anniversary of the signing of the global
treaty to ban land mines. More than 10 million stockpiled land
mines have been destroyed since 120 nations signed the treaty.
</P>
