<HEADER>
A2262 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-ISRAEL04-COX     12-03 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ISRAEL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush visits Mideast leaders on vacation
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, still weary from an
overseas journey with presidential overtones, said Thursday he
learned that Israel is a nation with unlimited potential and Italy
is a country with many mopeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel is short on natural resources in terms of resources you
find in the ground, but it is very long on the most natural
resource of all, which is brain power,'' said Bush. ``Israel has
got a tremendous amount of talent, smart folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush returned Wednesday from a three-day trip organized by the
National Jewish Coalition, a Republican organization. Govs. Mike
Leavitt of Utah, Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts and Marc Racicot of
Montana also made the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The governors met with Israeli leaders. A proposed meeting with
Yasser Arafat did not happen because the Palestinian leader was in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's trip began with a family vacation in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unbelievable experience to go to a place where there
are millions of mopeds and artifacts from centuries ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While in Italy, Bush took a sidetrip to meet Egyptian president
Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there to listen and learn, and I learned a lot,'' Bush
said of his Middle East trip. ``I learned a lot about the history
of Israel and the history of my own particular religion and the
history of religions that are now the dominant religions of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been involved in a dialogue with Abraham Foxman,
president of the Anti-Defamation League, a vigilant voice against
anti-Semitism, concerning Bush's 1993 comment that he believed
heaven was open only to followers of Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Foxman, who believes Bush harbors no religious intolerance, said
earlier this week he is expecting a letter from Bush expanding on
his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said he addressed the issue in an October letter to
Foxman. The governor declined on Thursday to release the letter,
which he deemed a ``personal matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it communicated the same thoughts he laid out at
Thursday's news conference, which he said have been consistent for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My faith tells me that acceptance of Jesus Christ as my savior
is my salvation,'' he said. ``And I believe that. I also, though,
made it very clear that it's not the governor's role to decide who
goes to heaven. I That's God's role.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he has shown his appreciation for all faiths while in
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have shown people that I'm a tolerant person. And my job as
governor is to use my office to promote dialogue and discussion and
mutual understanding and mutual respect. I've got great respect for
the other religions of the world. But I happen to firmly believe
what I just told you about the tenets of Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he believes heaven is open only to Christians, Bush
said, ``No, I don't believe that. I believe God decides who goes to
heaven, not George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
