<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CURRIE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASA to try Endeavor launch again
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEDY SPACE CENTER, Fla. _ NASA launch managers prepared space
shuttle Endeavour for another launch attempt at 3:36 a.m. today
after deciding an alarm that thwarted Thursday's launch wasn't a
real problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to crank this thing up and try it again,'' NASA
spokesman Dwayne Brown said Friday evening as the launch team began
refueling the shuttle's huge external tank. The tank's loads of
supercold liquid oxygen and liquid hydrogen were drained after
Thursday's scrub.
</P>
<P>
   NASA weather experts gave a promising forecast of 60 percent
odds for weather favorable to a launch, but it was less than a
guarantee: A good forecast early Thursday turned into a nailbiter
waiting for scattered showers to drift out before launch time.
</P>
<P>
   They did, but the launch was scrubbed 19 seconds before liftoff
after a cockpit alarm stopped the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything for this mission because Endeavour must
enter a precisely planned orbit to rendezvous with Zarya, a
Russian-built craft in space.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour carries another piece of hardware, the Unity
connecting node, that is to be docked with Zarya in the first step
of assembling the International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's six-person crew includes former Troy resident
Nancy Currie, the astronaut who will use Endeavour's robot arm to
position the two modules for docking.
</P>
<P>
   The master caution alarm sounded on Endeavour's flight deck four
minutes before liftoff. The alarm puzzled the crew and launch
engineers because no other messages or lights went on to signal a
specific problem.
</P>
<P>
   Launch controllers stopped the clock at minus 31 seconds, while
engineers checked data on the shuttle's myriad systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conservative approach is not to progress with something we
don't understand,'' launch integration manager Donald McMonagle
said.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers pinned the alarm to a brief pressure spike in the
shuttle's hydraulic system and decided it wasn't a real problem.
Launch controllers resumed the countdown, but they called it off
seconds later because too much liquid oxygen propellant had drained
away during the countdown hold.
</P>
<P>
   The oxygen draining is part of the shuttle's engine starting
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Another scrub today could put a serious kink in Endeavour's
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   A single 10-minute launch window exists each morning, but Roe
expressed concern for the launch team, which went through its
second sleepless night Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If today's launch were scrubbed, ``one of the things we will
want to look at is team fatigue,'' Roe said.
</P>
<P>
   Further delays would shortly put Endeavour's launch in conflict
with plans to launch the Mars Climate Orbiter, scheduled for a
liftoff on an unmanned Delta 2 rocket. Shuttle managers say
Endeavour has to fly by Tuesday or be rescheduled, possibly after
the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
