<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT TIME FOR STEVENS' TOTAL ECLIPSE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  &HT;     By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Is this the year Gary Stevens finally wins the
Eclipse Award as the nation's outstanding jockey?
</P>
<P>
   It could depend on which version of the ``official'' statistics
is mailed to Eclipse voters at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who is based here in Southern California, ranks first
in earnings with more than $18.8 million in purses this year,
according to the list put out by the Equibase Company under the
auspices of the National Thoroughbred Racing Association.
</P>
<P>
   But he's only third, with $16.2 million, behind Kentucky's Pat
Day ($17.2 million) and New York's Jerry Bailey ($17 million), in
the list published more widely by the Daily Racing Form.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that the Racing Form doesn't count races run
outside North America, costing Stevens credit for Silver Charm's
$2.4 million victory in the Dubai World Cup last March and other
foreign earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings isn't the definitive statistic when it comes to
comparing jockeys _ there is no definitive statistic _ but it's the
first one the voting reporters and racing executives are likely to
read. Thus, the Racing Form and the NTRA have a decision to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find ways to unify all the data,'' said Irwin
Cohen, a Racing Form senior vice president, whose goal is ``a level
playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Eclipse is for North American jockeys, voters won't
be out of line if they consider the results of the Dubai World Cup,
which has emerged the past few years as one of the sport's biggest
events and always draws top U.S. horses and riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how you really can overlook a race like the Dubai
World Cup when one of the leading horses (Silver Charm) in the
United States is going over there,'' said Chris Scherf, executive
VP of the Thoroughbred Racing Associations, which runs the Eclipse
voting.
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to give riders credit for purses earned when
they ride North America-based horses overseas but not when they
ride foreign-based horses overseas. That way, Stevens' Dubai World
Cup money would count, because 1997 Kentucky Derby winner Silver
Charm is all American, but the $250,000 Stevens earned in the Dubai
Duty Free the same week would not, because he won that race aboard
an Arab-based horse.
</P>
<P>
   But such a policy would require judgment calls and produce more
controversy than it prevents.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, Cohen said, the keepers of the racing statistics
will agree to include the Dubai World Cup and the Dubai among about
a dozen foreign races ``in which Americans routinely ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, it will be up to Eclipse voters to decide which of each
jockey's accomplishments to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Which is how it works when voters compare the horses who are up
for divisional Eclipse Awards. Horses' foreign races are included
in the Racing Form past-performance charts that are mailed with the
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, 35, was voted into racing's Hall of Fame in 1997 but
has never won an Eclipse, although he's been close, coming in
second to Jose Santos in 1990 and to Bailey more recently.
</P>
<P>
   He has three factors going for him in '98:
</P>
<P>
   All of his important numbers compare well with the other
contenders. His horses' earnings per race ($22,481, if you include
Dubai) dwarf Bailey's $16,575 and Day's $14,051. His million-dollar
victories (five) dwarf Bailey's two and Day's one. And although
Bailey leads with 14 Grade I wins, five of those came aboard Skip
Away, two involved Banshee Breeze and two involved Escena; Stevens'
six Grade I wins involved six different horses.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens did well in the brightest spotlights, riding two winners
on Breeders' Cup Day and riding Victory Gallop to a dramatic win
over Real Quiet and Kent Desormeaux in the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Voters might be tired of Bailey, who has won the award the past
three years, an Eclipse record for jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Stevens is out of the country again this week,
riding in Japan before returning to Hollywood Park on Sunday to
ride Manistique in the Bayakoa Handicap. Will the Japan earnings
count? We'll have to wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The weekend: &LR;  The race that produced Hollywood Park's
first-ever walkover in 1997 might be close to a one-horse race in
'98.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sharp Cat circled the track alone to win the Bayakoa
Handicap. Sunday, Manistique might have only two opponents in the 1
1/16-mile race for fillies and mares.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Stripes and India Divina, South America-breds who have
yet to win a stakes in this country, are the only other confirmed
starters.
</P>
<P>
   Manistique was the nation's hottest 3-year-old after she won her
first three races, including the Hollywood Oaks, by a combined 31
lengths. But she has been sidelined because of a throat infection
since finishing third to Banshee Breeze in the Alabama Stakes at
Saratoga in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously have big plans for her,'' said John Shirreffs,
who trains the huge daughter of 1990 Kentucky Derby winner
Unbridled for owner Marshall Naify. ``But, for now, we just want to
get her through (the Bayakoa).''
</P>
<P>
   Not much will stand in her way. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-03-98 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
