<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TUITION-CAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD CAP TUITION AT STATE SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Taking the unusual step of having the entire state
Senate co-sponsor legislation, lawmakers proposed a bill Thursday
that would cap tuition and fees at state colleges and universities
at one-third or less what it costs to educate each student.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Legislature has aimed to limit student costs in
budgets for the state's colleges and the University of
Massachusetts over the past two years, Thursday's move would put it
into statute, effectively making it illegal to raise tuition beyond
a certain point in a state that for years has had some of the most
expensive state colleges and universities in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Ways and Means Chairman Stan Rosenberg, who has filed the
bill in past years, said he hopes the fact that the entire Senate
has signed onto this year's proposal will increase its chances of
getting support from the House and Gov. Paul Cellucci. But as an
additional inducement, the bill also adds a provision that would
require schools to meet certain performance standards or risk
losing state money. This would prevent costs from rising too much _
and the state being stuck with the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters call it ``Ed reform for higher ed,'' likening it to
the 1993 Education Reform Act that required the state to pay at
least 50 percent of what it costs to run public elementary and
secondary schools, and at the same time demanded more of those
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about it is that it's a strong commitment to
public higher education, which is just ancillary to our commitment
to K-12, and it does insist on acccountability,'' said Senate
President Thomas F. Birmingham. ``That's the explicit bargain we
struck with the Commonwealth when we passed the Education Reform
Act, and that is the type of symmetry the taxpayers can reasonably
demand. People are decent and inclined to be generous to education,
but they are not patsies, and they don't want their money to be
thrown down a black hole.''
</P>
<P>
   For students and for schools, the so-called ``fair-share'' bill
would mean stability and predictability.
</P>
<P>
   Many students were squeezed out of public higher education in
the 1980s and early 1990s, as state funding was slashed 22 percent
and tuition and fees more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, by 1994, Massachusetts' community colleges were the
most expensive in the nation, state colleges the seventh most
expensive, and UMass the fourth most expensive state university.
</P>
<P>
   Under fair share, which first came out of a 1994 report by a
commission of legislators and academics, students at state colleges
and UMass would pay no more than one third their tuition and fees,
and community college students would get even more of a break, with
their tuition and fees capped at 25 percent of the cost of their
education.
</P>
<P>
   With tuition cuts set by the state Board of Higher Education,
students now pay 33.2 percent of the cost of their education at
UMass. At state colleges, students pay anywhere from 40 percent of
the cost of education (at Bridgewater State) to 19.5 percent the
cost (at Massachusetts Maritime Academy). Community college
students pay anywhere from 27 to 40 percent the cost of their
education.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition at schools with higher costs would shrink to the
one-third or one-quarter share within three years. If the state
were to slash funds to schools, tuition would drop.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also requires schools to achieve a certain level of
support from federal grants, endowment, and fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost of the proposal would be $269.2 million over the
four years.
</P>
<P>
   James F.Carlin, head of the state's board of higher education,
and the force behind both tuition cuts and increased
accountability, said he supported the Senate proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want to work hard to fine tune it so it will get broad
support,'' he said. ``There is one aspect of fair share that has to
be resolved before it will get house or administration support and
that is, how do you manage the aggregate cost of higher education
in a realistic, workable manner.If there can be controls on cost,
the proposal will have much smoother sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Carlin said, he supports performance standards,
which have now been adopted in some form in over half the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of higher education in the US and in Massachusetts
over the last 20 years has gone up double the inflation rate,'' he
said. ``We also know the cost of higher education has gone up
nationally faster than the cost of health care. Unless the fair
share proposal has some workable mechanisms for cost control, it's
going to be very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gov. Cellucci said the governor would not
comment on the proposal until he has seen it. But, said Nicole St.
Peter, ``The governor is committed to making the state's colleges
and universities affordable for all families.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Hillary Sargent contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
