<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKOOLCHAPS04-COX     12-03 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOOLCHAPS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Group promises to fight use of chaplain in Ohio school system
 &HT;    By David Kepple
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A Washington-based group that works to protect
the principle of church-state separation has informed Brookville
school officials it will fight any attempt to establish an
``educational chaplaincy'' program in the school system.
</P>
<P>
   If Brookville proceeds with the tentative proposal, it could
become the first public school district in the nation to use the
regular, full-time services of a chaplain _ who would function
roughly along the lines of a military chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the ``educational chaplain'' would be available
to help students, faculty and staff of all backgrounds, and would
not seek to impose a religious agenda on anyone, nor espouse the
beliefs of one religious group over another.
</P>
<P>
   Americans United for Separation of Church and State, a group
claiming more than 50,000 members, describes itself as ``working to
protect the constitutional principle of church-state separation, a
vital cornerstone of religious liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We urge the school board to reject the proposal for a
volunteer school chaplain,'' wrote Ayesha Khan, a lawyer for the
group, in a warning letter to Brookville Superintendent Larry
Henry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our review of the job description and the relevant case law
leads us to believe that the proposal is unconstitutional,'' Khan
wrote. ``In the event you elect to proceed . . . we would have
little choice but to bring a legal challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Khan said Thursday that she is unaware of any public school
district in the nation that employs a chaplain, and that Brookville
evidently would be the first if the district were to pursue the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a very peculiar and rare proposal,'' Khan said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial plan has yet to officially reach the school
board, but is being approached with a mix of interest and caution
by district officials. A nine-member steering committee made up of
school officials and community representatives is reviewing the
proposal. That advisory panel hosted about 100 citizens at an Oct.
22 ``town meeting'' to receive public comment on the idea _ with
most of those present supporting the concept.
</P>
<P>
   School board vice president Mark Poesch, who moderated the town
meeting and who serves on the steering committee, said the school
board does not intend to fund the position with tax dollars, nor
would the board spend money to mount a legal defense if the plan
was approved and then challenged in court.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, who also serves on the steering committee, said the
informal panel is set to meet Wednesday and will soon make a
recommendation to the school board about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the chaplaincy idea are the Rev. Howard M. Lee, founder
and director of a group called Public School Chaplaincy for
America, and Lee Behnken, a 40-year-old Brookville native and
evangelical Christian known for his music ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, formerly of Dayton and now living in St. Louis, has
established the PSCA's headquarters in Dayton. Behnken and Lee
approached Henry earlier this year with the chaplaincy concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our public schools are in a national state of emergency,'' Lee
wrote in a document outlining the chaplaincy proposal. ``The need
for motivation, moral support and spiritual support of our students
must be met to alleviate the stresses they suffer from in this
violent society. . . . These stresses can be addressed by a public
school chaplain.''
</P>
<P>
   Behnken, who has written a song called The Christian Anthem in
support of public school chaplaincy, said he'd love to see his
hometown be the first public school system in the U.S. to adopt the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Miller, deputy director of legal services for the Ohio
School Board Association, said Thursday he couldn't comment on the
Brookville matter.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking generally, Miller said, ``I think a district must
be careful, because (case law) is clear that there not only cannot
be an endorsement of one religion over another, but of any
religion. Any sort of religious reflection has to be student driven
_ with a capital 'S.' ''
</P>
<P>
   According to reports in the New York Daily News , a member of
the New York state assembly is supporting a bill that calls for a
voluntary chaplaincy program at the school district level. That
effort is unrelated to the Public School Chaplaincy of America's
program.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Ruben Diaz Jr. drafted a bill _ which he plans to
introduce in January _ calling for school chaplains in New York
City schools after Bronx teacher Mildred Rosario was fired earlier
this year for leading her class in prayer. The bill requires
parental consent before a student could be sent to a chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Americans United also have criticized the
Diaz proposal.
</P>
<P>
   In Brookville, Henry said school board members ``were kind of
neutral'' after the original discussion with Behnken and Lee last
spring. ``They said we need to find out more, get the feeling of
the community - and that's what we've been doing ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Poeschl and Henry declined comment on the letter from Americans
United, but Poeschl did say: ``We've received some very good input,
both pro and con, and we are weighing that. We will use all of that
as we reach a decision on what we're going to do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
