<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Dec. 3, 1998 -- ELECTRA-THEATER-REVIEW, 12-03
-- Marin Hinkle, left, and Zoe Wanamaker in Sophocles' ``Electra''
at the Barrymore Theater. Leave it to a playwright who has been
dead for 2,400 years to jolt Broadway out of its dramatic doldrums.
Sophocles's ``Electra'' opened at the Barrymore Theater in a
magnificent new production that represents soul-satisfying drama at
its most passionate. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Dec. 3, 1998 -- FORSYTHE-DANCE, 12-03 -- A
performer with the Frankfurt Ballet dances around Maxim Franke
playing the violin during a dress rehearsal at the Brooklyn Academy
of Music for ``Eidos: Telos,'' by the choreographer William
Forsythe. Forsythe, the American choreographer who has been
artistic director of the ballet in Germany since 1984, is a
prodigious talent but no prodigal son. He refuses to come home but
does drop in occasionally to create new work and restage old ones
for major American ballet companies. (Michelle V. Agins/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
