<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE04-COX     12-03 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Minor alarm keeps Endeavor grounded, but NASA to attempt launch
again today
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ NASA was to again attempt to launch the
space shuttle Endeavour this morning after its scheduled take-off
Thursday was aborted moments before liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   A master warning alarm had forced NASA programmers to put
Endeavour's scheduled 3:59 a.m. Thursday launch on hold with less
than a minute to go in the countdown.
</P>
<P>
   The alarm came after shuttle pilot, Maj. Rick Sturckow, started
the Endeavour's auxiliary power unit. It powers the shuttle's
landing gear, engine valves, control structures such as aelerons
and other hydraulic systems.
</P>
<P>
   Under NASA criteria, if a master alarm sounds, programmers must
either eliminate it as a threat to the flight or scuttle. They
ultimately decided the problem was caused by a loose switch and was
minor.
</P>
<P>
   After resuming the countdown, NASA officials scrubbed the launch
with only 19 seconds left because it had missed a 10-minute window
to send Endeavour into space.
</P>
<P>
   The slim time frame was set so Endeavour could rendezvous with
the Russian Zarya control module for the International Space
Station on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour's flight had been questionable for hours before the
alarm because showers and cloud cover were expected to impede the
launch. But with less than 30 minutes remaining in the countdown,
NASA officials cleared Endeavour for takeoff because the showers
for the most part had come ashore to the north of the launch site.
</P>
<P>
   This morning's launch was also iffy, with NASA weather
forecasters predicting a 60 percent chance of showers for the
scheduled 3:36 a.m. launch.
</P>
<P>
   The flight is a major event for NASA and its 15 international
partners. It will carry the first U.S.-built component for the $60
billion station into space.
</P>
<P>
   The mission is expected to last 12 days, as astronauts will take
two space walks to deploy the module.
</P>
<P>
   If Endeavour's launch is again postponed, NASA will be forced to
bear added costs. Thursday's delay was estimated to cost an
additional $600,000 in overtime labor costs and fuel, some of which
evaporates when it is removed from the shuttle's external tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
