<HEADER>
A2310 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEGABUCK-HOMES-LADN     12-03 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEGABUCK-HOMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S HIGH-END HOMES RED-HOT PROPERTIES IN THIRD QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- California's high-end real estate sparkled during
the year's third quarter as the number of million-dollar homes sold
hit an all-time peak, an industry tracker reported.
</P>
<P>
   Between July and September, 1,555 homes sold for more than $1
million, including more than 100 in the suburban San Fernando
Valley area, said Acxiom Corp.'s DataQuick Products Division. The
number jumped 41 percent from the year-ago period, 5.1 percent from
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the ZIP code with the highest sales count was
90210 -- Beverly Hills -- with 63.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of these pricey homes are well ahead of the surge of the
late 1980s, when million-dollar sales activity peaked at 1,246
mansions during the third quarter of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers reflect strong consumer confidence, an increase in
the number of new millionaires in the state and price appreciation.
A lot of houses that carried six-figure price tags a year ago have
now crossed the million-dollar threshold.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of the buyers paid for their palatial digs in
cash. The median down payment was $390,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth in the economy has been kind of top-down,'' said
DataQuick market analyst John Karevoll. ``High-income households
are making a lot more money now than five years ago, and because of
the growth in the stock market and the economy, more people can
afford these homes.''
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive home sale during the quarter was a
seven-bathroom, five-bedroom, 10,060-square-foot estate on 2.3
acres in Bel-Air that went for $10 million. Eighteen California
homes sold for $5 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   There were 91 condominium sales in the million-dollar category,
mostly in West Los Angeles and San Francisco. The median price per
square foot for all million-dollar homes was $402 last quarter, up
from $365 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
