<SLUG> BC-TOURS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 On-the-Job Experience  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hundreds of round white cardboard containers slid down the assembly
line. An overhead pipe spurted each one full of silken-soft vanilla
ice cream. Then, barely a second later, the conveyor belt whisked
them off to a giant freezer with a temperature of 20 degrees below
zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could get vicious,'' muttered Arthur Boerner, a
grandfather from Colorado who was watching the ice cream containers
zip past.``We didn't have breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   Boerner and 11 members of his extended family had skipped
breakfast and forked over $2 each to join a 9:15 a.m. tour of the
Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream plant in Union City.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20,000 people a year take the Dreyer's tour _ one of
about two dozen public tours offered by Bay Area manufacturing
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the number of firms that allow the general public to
visit their factory floors is dwindling because of management
worries about issues like liability and trade-secret theft.
</P>
<P>
   But those firms that do offer tours are becoming increasingly
sophisticated about it, sometimes building multimillion-dollar
visitor centers to supplement the actual factory-floor visit.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Herman Goelitz _ which guided 377,000 people last
year through its Jelly Belly candy plant in Fairfield _ will open
an adjacent $6.5 million visitor center in March.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that offer tours say the hassle is far outweighed by
the payoff: a kind of customer loyalty that can't easily be
quantified but that goes far deeper than the return from even the
snazziest TV ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``A commercial during the Super Bowl costs millions of dollars
for 30 seconds,'' said Patty Laustrup, who oversees tours for about
39,000 people a year at the Anheuser-Busch brewery in Fairfield.
``We get people's attention for one hour for just $7.40, the cost
of a tour guide. And it's total immersion into our product. You
can't get any better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no hard data on the number of U.S. companies that offer
tours to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   But people who have researched factory tours say the number is
shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Hershey's no longer lets visitors inside its world-famous
chocolate factory in Hershey, Pa. Instead, it offers a ride through
a make-believe factory in a giant cocoa-bean tram.
</P>
<P>
   And Kellogg's halted its factory tour in the 1980s for fear of
cereal spies, instead opening up a company museum in Battle Creek,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a trend toward museums, which meet some of
the same needs as going on a factory tour,'' said Karen Axelrod,
co-author of a book about factory tours, ``Watch It Made in the
USA: A Visitor's Guide to the Companies That Make Your Favorite
Products.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's not the same excitement for visitors as when
you're right there in the middle of all the noise and movement and
sparks flying,'' Axelrod added.
</P>
<P>
   Both nationally and in the Bay Area, companies offering tours
tend to sell brand-name products _ especially food or drink _ to
the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Dreyer's, Herman Goelitz and Anheuser-Busch, firms with
local tour programs include Anchor Brewing Co., Levi Strauss, Mrs.
Grossman's Paper Co., Norcal Waste Systems and New United Motor
Manufacturing, the joint car-making venture between Toyota and
General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   These firms say there's a lot more to running a successful tour
program than simply adding a couple of extra ``visitor'' spaces in
their parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   They've sometimes had to purchase extra liability insurance.
Some have had to train staff in first aid and set up procedures to
deal with potential medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of seniors visiting, and the tour involves five
blocks of walking with great fluctuations of heat and cold, after
they've had some alcohol,'' said Laustrup of Anheuser-Busch.
``We've had situations where seniors occasionally become weak. We
use our radios and have a truck come to get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies also have had to negotiate special deals with state
workplace-safety regulators. For instance, Anheuser-Busch had to
get state officials to waive their normal rule requiring people on
the brewery floor to wear closed-toe shoes and long pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite an ordeal to get those releases, but we hated
telling people they couldn't go on the tour because they were
wearing shorts or sandals,'' Laustrup said.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the challenge of training tour guides _ people who
must be both product experts and amateur diplomats capable of
handling antsy children and occasionally rude adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``We send out letters saying no children under 6, and no
strollers or babies in backpacks,'' said Michele Massari, a tour
guide at Dreyer's. ``But people show up at the door with a baby in
a frontpack and say, `Well, you didn't mention frontpacks.' I just
bring them in here (to the gift shop) and give them ice cream while
the rest of their group goes on the tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies find that gift-shop sales pay for the cost of
their tour programs. The tiny Marin French Cheese Factory in
Petaluma, which gets 500 to 1,000 visitors per week, does about
half its total sales from its on-site shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``If 10 people come through, nine are going to buy something,''
said general manager Kandace Millhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Goelitz sells more than $3 million worth of candy and
souvenirs to tour participants each year, out of total sales of
more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never intended it to be, but the tour became a profit
center,'' said Peter Cain, marketing director for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Other firms subsidize their tours but still find them
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we break even or not, but when people leave
here, I like to think we made them happy,'' Massari said. ``I get
notes from people saying things like, `My mom went out and bought
the flavor we tasted.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Boerner certainly was one happy visitor _ especially when
his group each got two scoops of ice cream at the end of their
Dreyer's tour. Boerner actually ended up with more than his share
because he finished off his grandchildren's uneaten portions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pillsbury has their doughboy _ I'd like to be the Dreyer's
boy,'' Boerner said as he polished off his fifth scoop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
