<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 At Conference, Amazon.com Chief Speaks to His Former Brethren  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
When Amazon.com chief executive Jeffrey Bezos speaks, money
managers listen.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he was one of them. He helped build a black box
computer-trading hedge fund for D.E. Shaw. (Yes, the same
investment firm whose colossal losses prompted BankAmerica's Hugh
McColl to send David Coulter packing. But don't hold that against
Bezos. He left the now-infamous firm earlier this decade.)
</P>
<P>
   For another, some of the best and brightest institutional money
managers _ who aren't exactly dim bulbs themselves _ think he's a
pretty smart guy. In fact, many of them will even admit that they
think Bezos is smarter than they are.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Bezos has been anointed lord of electronic commerce
by the digerati. Thus, when a ``Fireside Chat With Jeff Bezos'' was
scheduled for yesterday at the Credit Suisse First Boston
technology conference here in Scottsdale, Ariz., you knew it was
going to be a full house. Of course, getting the chief executive to
come and wax virtual with his former peers commanded a price: No
press allowed. The Internet executive presumedly was concerned that
something he might say would move markets.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, my curiosity was piqued, and I figured readers of
this column would like to hear what was on the guru's mind. So,
thanks to a couple of libertarian-minded conference goers who
volunteered as Street Smarts correspondents, the following are some
poignant comments made by the chief executive of the world's
leading e-tailer.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of the chat (and a long ways from the days of
Franklin D. Roosevelt), an image of virtual flames was projected on
a huge screen behind Bezos while an interviewer read questions from
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase, Bezos was asked how he felt about Amazon's
exceedingly rich stock evaluation. Shares closed yesterday at
$189.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell everyone in our company to wake up terrified,'' he told
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to say that the lofty stock price should serve as an
incentive for his employees to work diligently toward serving
Amazon's customers because their endorsement of the Internet
retailer is more important than any advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right thing to be afraid of is our customers. They are the
ones that pay us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So, what is the single-most important lesson on running an
Internet business?
</P>
<P>
   The balance of power shifts from the retailer to the consumer on
the Internet. One customer can tell 5 million people that
Amazon.com stinks.
</P>
<P>
   And when that happens, Amazon needs to satisfy five new
customers to make up for the one unhappy customer, Bezos figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to be able to have a lousy Internet product and
overcome that with great marketing, but you can't do that
anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos was queried about other Internet businesses that he
admired, particularly ones which had yet to go public.
</P>
<P>
   One that caught his eye is PriceLine, a seller of excess
capacity on airlines. He thinks that it could revolutionize the
commercial airline business.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet pioneer also indicated that he was impressed with
eBay, the online auctioneer whose recent initial offering caught
fire.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Bezos was asked what was behind Amazon's decision
to hire some top-level employees from discount titan Wal-Mart, one
of the nation's most efficient retailers. Wal-Mart is suing Amazon
over the matter, accusing it of pilfering some of Wal-Mart's
proprietary distribution know-how.
</P>
<P>
   To which he responded: ``We aren't interested in anyone's trade
secrets. But we are very interested in hiring talented people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
