<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Groups Protest Pac Bell Plan to Raise 411 Rates  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pacific Bell's proposal to raise rates for directory assistance met
with stiff opposition yesterday from senior citizens, consumer
advocates and others who say the increase is undeserved and will
hurt customers.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing before the California Public Utilities Commission,
members of the public spoke about Pac Bell's application to raise
411 rates from 25 cents to 50 cents per call. Pac Bell is seeking a
cap of $1.10 per call, which means it could charge that amount just
by giving the PUC 30 days notice.
</P>
<P>
   The phone company also wants to cut the number of free 411 calls
from five per month to three. Business customers, who currently get
three free 411 calls a month, would get no free directory
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC is expected to vote on Pac Bell's application in May.
Consumer advocates and others said the rate increases will hurt the
communities that can least afford it _ low-income, senior citizen
and minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Berzok, a member of California's American Association of
Retired Persons state legislative committee, said directory
assistance is vital to elderly people, many of whom are on fixed
incomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Directory assistance is very important to our members, who may
need it because the print in the telephone book is too small or
it's too heavy to lift,'' Berzok said. ``This proposal amounts to
nothing more than gouging.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Burns, who lives in San Francisco, said that while the
rate increase may not seem like a lot, it can destroy the budget of
someone who's struggling to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even 50 cents sometimes is a little more than we can add to
our telephone bill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people who spoke at yesterday's hearing, the sixth
hearing to be held statewide, said Pac Bell should not be allowed
to raise rates because it has a lock on the market. Customers can
get local phone numbers from a few other companies but must dial
special access codes to reach those providers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's proposal did get support from some retired Pac
Bell employees, union officials and some disabled customers.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Senhaux, who is legally blind, said Pac Bell's
application should be approved because the company has been a good
corporate citizen. Senhaux said Pac Bell provides free directory
assistance to anyone with a disability, something it may not be
able to afford if the rate increase isn't granted.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell officials said they need to raise rates in order to
cover costs for directory assistance. The company said it has not
raised 411 rates since 1984 and is losing money on each call.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Cain, Pac Bell director of product and market management,
said the company does not plan to charge $1.10, even though it's
asked for that as a rate cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only asking for an increase to 50 cents. Period,'' said
Cain. He said the money is needed to pay for salaries of operators,
who answer 411 calls 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates say they expect Pac Bell to raise rates
to $1.10 if the application is approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carriers request the rates they want to charge,'' said Kelly
Boyd, senior telecommunications analyst with the Office of
Ratepayer Advocates. ``The clear purpose of requesting a rate above
the ceiling is to forgo regulatory oversight when the next increase
is implemented.''
</P>
</TEXT>
