<HEADLINE>
HOUSE IMPEACHMENT VOTE MAY HINGE ON AS FEW AS 10 LAWMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House impeachment vote may hinge on the verdicts
of as few as 10 undecided lawmakers, including Arizona Republican
Rep. Jim Kolbe, according to a private head count by leading
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The count, shared Thursday with ``The Arizona Republic,''
forecasts a dramatically close vote. The outcome would rest largely
on whether Kolbe and other undecided Republicans buck their party
by declining to support any articles of impeachment against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tt is increasingly clear that this thing is down to less than
10 and arguably less than five votes, of which he (Kolbe) is one,''
said a top Democratic vote-counter. ``It could be the biggest vote
of his entire political career.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a vote, incoming House Speaker Bob Livingston,
R-La., says he wants it to occur before Christmas. Republicans have
said privately that they probably have enough votes to support a
perjury charge.
</P>
<P>
   However, neither Democrats nor Republicans have released any
public vote counts, and pundits have disagreed on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led House voted 258-176 on Oct. 8 for an
open-ended impeachment inquiry by the House Judiciary Committee.
But a vote on actual impeachment would certainly be much closer,
because many of the 31 Democrats who joined the GOP in endorsing
the inquiry aren't expected to support articles of impeachment.
Also, some Republicans have been defecting.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe is just the sort of lawmaker whose support Clinton's
backers are seeking as they try to prevent House approval of a
perjury charge or other impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been targeting moderate Republicans from
congressional districts not considered overwhelmingly Republican.
Kolbe's district is split almost evenly between Democratic and
Republican voters. He won re-election last month, but with only 51
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe is in Europe this week attending meetings on security and
trade. Awaiting him in his congressional office is a thick briefing
book with background on the impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man intends to do his homework,'' said Frances McNaught,
Kolbe's chief of staff. ``No one should read anything into this
(his indecision). He looks upon himself as a grand juror and feels
he should not be making decisions until he has an opportunity to
review the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee has committed itself to voting on
articles of impeachment by the end of next week. After that, the
full House would need to be summoned back to Washington to approve
or reject any articles the committee passed. Any article of
impeachment endorsed by the House would send the entire matter to
the Senate; it would require 67 Senate votes to remove the
president from office, and that scenario is considered unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   No Arizonan besides Kolbe showed up on the Democratic list of
swing votes. The list prominently includes Rep. Michael Castle,
R-Del., another undecided lawmaker who heads a moderate Republican
faction known as the Tuesday Group.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, buoyed by polls showing public disapproval of
the impeachment inquiry, is counting on at least a dozen Republican
defections.
</P>
<P>
   So far, GOP vote-counters have identified only five Republicans
dead-set against impeachment, according to ``Roll Call,'' a Capitol
Hill publication. They are Reps. Christopher Shays of Connecticut,
Mark Souder of Indiana, John Porter of Illinois, Jack Quinn of New
York and Peter King of New York. Majority Whip Tom DeLay has polled
dozens of GOP members and says there may be enough Republican votes
to impeach Clinton on a perjury charge, according to ``Roll Call.''
But Congress may also weigh an alternative, such as a censure,
which would stop short of impeachment. &QL; 
Jeff Barker can be reached at 202-662-7264 or at
jeff.barker(at)pni.com via e-mail.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
