<SLUG> BC-MA-ENVIRONMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DURAND TO TAKE STATE ENVIRONMENTAL POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State Senator Robert A. Durand has accepted Governor
Paul Cellucci's offer to become state secretary of environmental
affairs, a move likely to delight environmental groups but create
some prickly political problems for Cellucci's efforts to fill top
administration positions.
</P>
<P>
   Durand, a hunter and outdoorsman, is a close Cellucci family
friend, four-term Marlborough Democrat and longtime chairman of the
Natural Resources Committee who is now the fourth-ranking Senate
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   According to individuals on Beacon Hill familiar with talks,
Durand told Cellucci Wednesday he will take the job, after weeks of
considering whether he had a more promising future staying in the
Senate. He apparently concluded he did not have clear support to
succeed President Thomas F. Birmingham down the road, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   Durand has been enthusiastically supported for the environmental
job by representatives of the Massachusetts Audubon Society, the
Environmental League of Massachusetts and several other groups that
liked his Senate record on bills to protect land, improve state
parks and restrict development along Massachusetts rivers.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to take the post, however, may work against one of
his Democratic colleagues, state Senator James P. Jajuga of
Methuen, a former State Police detective who has been aggressively
lobbying to be named secretary of public safety. Jajuga's major
competitor is outgoing Norfolk County District Attorney Jeffrey
Locke, a Republican defeated by state Senator William R. Keating, a
Sharon Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon Hill staffers said Cellucci may find it politically
difficult to appoint two Democrats to his Cabinet, particularly
explaining the move to Republican loyalists. ``This gives Locke
some breathing room,'' said one administration insider, referring
to Durand's pending appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci refused to comment on his personnel decisions, but did
say that ``there's no limits, no quotas'' for the number of
Democrats he might name to the six-person cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for people who can help us get the job done,''
Cellucci said in a brief interview, adding that ``I think we'll
have something to announce next week'' on the environmental affairs
post.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci is also trying to negotiate a peace within the
29-member House Republican caucus where House Minority Leader David
Peters of Charlton is facing an ouster by Representative Francis
Marini.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that was met with some astonishment among his
Republican colleagues, Peters Thursday sent House GOP members an
unprecedented, full-color ``year end legislative message'' that
attempts to justify his two-year tenure while acknowledging
``frustration'' among the Republican cohort.
</P>
<P>
   Peters is telling colleagues he has the votes to remain the
leader, but Republican insiders say Marini has a clear majority to
take the job from him.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are said to be fed up with Peters's cozy
relationship with House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, who was elected
speaker two years ago with backing from Peters and the rest of the
House's Republicans over the more liberal Richard Voke of
Charlestown, and for failing to bolster Republicans' precarious
hold on House seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking to exit gracefully, but some of the members are
feeling he's fooling around too much with Marini,'' said one top
Republican source. ``But clearly, he's miscalculated. Marini is
ready for an all-out war if he doesn't go.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters is said to be ready to accept Cellucci's offer to make
him state commissioner of fisheries and wildlife, but does not want
to look like he was pushed from power, Beacon Hill sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Anderson of Citizens for Limited Taxation and Government
said it would be ``good news if Dave Peters is gone. Dave Peters
has just been too close to Finneran, and it's essential on Beacon
Hill that you have an active minority party. What we need now more
than anything on Beacon Hill is an opposition voice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
