<HEADER>
A2340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NORTHWESTERN-2NDT     12-03 0282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHWESTERN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHICAGO: a game.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The school suspended Lundy and Lee, and turned over the
information to the U.S. attorney's office. Lee was one of the
people sentenced to prison last week for trying to fix basketball
games. Northwestern has expunged the names of Lee and the other
players from its record books.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney and the FBI commended Northwestern for
cooperating with the federal investigation. The NCAA said
Northwestern would not face any sanction in the case, because it
did not know of the gambling.
</P>
<P>
   A Northwestern spokesman, Allen Cubbage, said the school wasis
trying harder to persuade student athletes that gambling is
dangerous. ``They get the speech, and they get the literature,''
said Allen Cubbage.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA said it believed many athletes yield to the temptation
to gamble. It said one study showed that 25 percent of players on
Division I basketball and football teams have bet on college
sports, and about 4 percent have bet on their own teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any college athletic program is at risk for sports wagering,''
said William Saum, NCAA director of agent and gambling activities.
``People need to realize that gambling is not a victimless crime.
The other players on the team, the cheerleaders, the fans, the
alumni, the other team _ these are the victims. We need to convince
colleges to remove the student bookies from our college campuses.
We need the media to realize that printing point spreads in the
newspaper is not OK.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Saum said: ``We're not concerned about the
integrity of our game as it exists today. We're confident that the
games are square and on the up and up.''
</P>
<P>
