r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHTOUR-SFCHRON &LR;      12-03 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHTOUR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Silicon Valley Tour _ Hype But No Depth   By Carolyn Said 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The saga of Silicon Valley has spawned enough intrigues, grand
failures and dazzling successes to stock a few dozen operas.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has inspired a superdeluxe limousine tour from Los Gatos
startup Tech-Tours that purports to give a sense of the historical
significance of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, a group of journalists, tech executives and a British
vice consul embarked on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the tour guide's bland recitation of dates and
names made the experience as flat as the roofs of the shoebox-style
buildings that cluster off Highway 101.
</P>
<P>
   Like an earnest high school teacher, Tech-Tours President and
co-founder Deborah Lynn was determined to give her audience a
thorough grounding in every fact and figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, let's step back a few centuries and review some of the
background of the technology,'' she offered early on.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn and business partner Nathan Cocozza, who said they have
years of experience in high-tech marketing and sales, launched
Tech-Tours a few weeks ago, after noticing Silicon Valley's notable
failure to show off its high-tech wonders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably every visiting group I talk to asks about a high-tech
tour,'' said Ann Marshall, marketing manager at the San Jose
Visitors &AMP; Convention Bureau. ``We've had nothing to offer them.
You can't get into companies for security reasons, clean-room
issues. The closest thing has been the Intel Museum and now the
Tech Museum of Innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   The limo drove past a lot of tan, prefab buildings with signs
identifying them as Silicon Graphics, Sun Microsystems, Intuit and
Cisco. There weren't any trips inside the buildings, perhaps
because the people inside were too busy inventing the future.
</P>
<P>
   There was a fleeting mention of Hewlett-Packard being started in
a garage, but no one got to see any garage.
</P>
<P>
   One of the shoeboxes, called the Repo Depot, bore a big sign
advertising deals on used office furniture. But long before its
present incarnation, it was known as Fairchild Semiconductor and
was a birthplace of the computer revolution.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:40 a.m., the tour paused outside the Repo Depot to view
the bronze plaque commemorating Fairchild's invention of the
``first commercially practicable integrated circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 12:20 p.m. that the guide mentioned that some
Fairchild guys went on to start another company called Intel.
</P>
<P>
   The group also learned that a guy named Jim Clark started a
company called Netscape along with another guy named ``Marc
Anderson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anderson was a young programmer,'' guide Deborah Lynn
explained, mangling Marc Andreessen's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netscape is one of the many Silicon Valley success stories,''
she continued.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  After a steady diet of factoids, some of the passengers began
to rebel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me something scandalous about Silicon Valley, so I can
tell it at my next cocktail party,'' pleaded one. ``I want some
juicy tidbits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's stick to the facts,'' said the valiantly smiling Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some of the passengers seemed to know more about
Silicon Valley than the guide. One explained that the reason
high-tech companies build a series of small offices _ rather than a
grand edifice _ is because they never know if they'll make it or
not and want to be able to give up some space in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Driving past Alza Corp., another guest noted that the firm is
working on a male-contraceptive patch.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting yesterday's ``special media launch day,'' which was
a bargain at $175 per head, Tech-Tours has conducted two outings
for paying customers: one for a quartet of Hollywood screenwriters
scoping out the valley for material, and one for a group of
businessmen from the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple _ partners in life as well as business _ have
high hopes that their ``moving museum'' will take off.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's sightseers appeared bemused by the constant stream
of data.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit like driving around in a goldfish bowl,'' said Jo
Enefer, the British vice consul who was contemplating sending
visiting dignitaries on the tour. Being so confined to a car _ even
a 30-foot Lincoln Town Car limo _ might be a problem, she said.
Some of them ``would be champing at the bit to meet a real
person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from a thick leather binder, Lynn rattled off the names
of companies that pioneered breakthroughs like point-contact
transistor amplifiers and symmetric multiprocessing. There was a
discussion of teraflops and gigaflops and the distinctions between
them _ ``The difference ... is like a whole lot,'' Lynn explained.
</P>
<P>
   Tech-Tours is not for your average out-of-towner who wants to
kill a couple of hours and see what the Silicon Valley hubbub is
all about.
</P>
<P>
   It aims straight at upper-echelon digerati: visiting corporate
VIPs, government dignitaries, foreign investors _ people who like
to go first-class and think nothing of dropping $250 or more for a
five-hour limo jaunt.
</P>
<P>
   The most deluxe part of the tour was the limo. Unfortunately,
only three people get to sit facing forward. One was the driver.
</P>
<P>
   The other passengers &UR;  &LR; _ sitting sideways and backward _ started
to suffer from mal de mer after a while.
</P>
<P>
   The other elegant touch was the lunch, at Sunnyvale's Lion &AMP;
Compass, a palace of stained glass and oak. While there was a vague
reference to important tech talks being conducted there, there was
no mention that Nolan Bushnell started the restaurant in the early
1980s with his loot from Pong and Atari.
</P>
<P>
   The tour's grand finale was a visit to the Computer Museum
History Center at Moffett Field.
</P>
<P>
   There, in a tribute to technology's ease of use, it took four
uniformed guards using NASA computers 20 minutes to check in seven
guests in the ``Visitor Badging Area.``
</P>
<P>
   The center's aptly named curator Dag Spicer invested his tour
with all the spice and wit that the deluxe tour lacked.
</P>
<P>
   He showed off a truck-sized maze of vacuum tubes; the first
punch-card machine used in the 1890 census; and a piece of the
ENIAC, the world's first ``electronic stored program digital
computer'' which is a lot like saying it was the world's first
computer. The entire ENIAC was 18,000 square feet and had less
computing power than his wristwatch, Spicer said.
</P>
<P>
   Now housed &UR;  &LR; in a warehouse, the museum &LR;  (www.tcm.org)  &LR; needs $30
million and five to seven years before it flings open its doors.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Spicer conducts public tours on Wednesdays from 1-3
p.m. and by appointment.
</P>
<P>
   You have to chauffeur yourself and bring your own lunch, but for
a taste of Silicon Valley history, the Moffett Field outpost
delivers the goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
