u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-AG-BOS &LR;      12-03 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-AG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS. AG MAY SUE TO BLOCK PATRIOTS MOVE TO CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Attorney General Scott Harshbarger is considering
filing a lawsuit against the New England Patriots and the National
Football League to prevent the team from leaving Massachusetts, his
office confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The action would likely be modeled after one or more suits filed
or threatened by other states _ including Washington, Missouri,
Florida, and Ohio _ that were faced with losing a professional
sports team, and could challenge the team's antitrust exemption as
well as the legality of breaking the lease at the team's current
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to speculate on the likelihood of a lawsuit,''
said Harshbarger's spokesman, Ed Cafasso. ``I'm simply saying that
it's an issue that's on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Cafasso confirmed that lawyers in Harshbarger's office have
begun researching actions taken by attorneys general in other
states against professional teams. While in most instances those
suits were dropped or thrown out of court, they succeeded in
applying pressure that yielded desirable results.
</P>
<P>
   A potentially fertile area is filing an antitrust suit, which
other states have done to attack a number of issues regarding a
team's threats to move if it does not receive a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility being explored is a legal challenge to the NFL's
apparent promise to Patriots' owner Robert Kraft that it would not
allow another football team into New England to compete with the
Patriots after the team moves to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Such a suit could be filed preemptively to delay or prevent the
Patriots' departure, or could be filed after the team relocates to
pressure the league to allow another team to play in the Boston
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were another NFL team that wanted to move to the
Massachusetts market and they were blocked by NFL rules from doing
that, that's the kind of situation that would increase the
likelihood of a lawsuit,'' Cafasso said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Patriots declined to comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general in Ohio filed an antitrust suit in 1996 in
an attempt to keep the Cleveland Browns football team from moving
to Baltimore, where state lottery proceeds paid for a new $200
million open-air facility for the newly named Ravens. Cleveland
lost the team, but Ohio cut a deal with the league to get an
expansion team with the Browns' name and colors.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri used antitrust claims against the NFL, which refused to
allow the Los Angeles Rams from moving to the smaller TV market of
St. Louis, thereby reducing revenues that are shared with all teams
in the league. The state had already built the $280 million
publicly financed Trans World Dome in St. Louis with the hopes of
luring a team.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of the suit, and the treble damages accompanying it,
pressured NFL owners to change their vote and approve the move.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Florida officials sued professional baseball's National
League in an action that, through the legal-discovery process,
allowed the state's attorney general to investigate the blocked
sale of the San Francisco Giants to Tampa Bay investors. As a
result, the team remained in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has occurred in other states has been researched here and
it has been discussed over the years, whenever the issue of the
Patriots leaving Massachusetts has become a possibility,'' Cafasso
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Washington case, the attorney general used a binding
stadium lease that the Seattle Seahawks signed with the county as
leverage to delay the football team from bolting to Los Angeles in
1996. As pretrial jurisdiction issues hit the appellate level,
Microsoft cofounder Paul Allen stepped in to buy the team with a
promise to keep it in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to exploit the Patriots' lease in Foxborough is one
approach Harshbarger could take, although it still needs to be
explored, Cafasso said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not done the kind of intensive analysis that would be
required to speculate about the likelihood of success in
Massachusetts,'' Cafasso added. ``Each case is driven by certain
facts and certain situations and agreements in effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, who also owns Foxboro Stadium and many acres of land
around the facility, does not own the footprint beneath the
concrete bowl. Foxboro Stadium Associates, which Kraft owns, has a
longterm lease for that property with the town of Foxborough. That
unique situation could allow the franchise to vacate without any
legal consequences, particularly because Kraft intends to keep The
New England Revolution, a Major League Soccer team, at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have a lease to remain at the stadium only through
2001, which coincides with the target date for the team's proposed
move to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other cases differ significantly from the one in
Massachusetts because in nearly every instance, the legal challenge
involved taxpayer money or other public support for a pro team.
With Massachusetts officials unwilling to dedicate public money to
the Patriots, Kraft had agreed to spend more than $200 million of
his own money on a new facility and had sought approval of a Senate
bill offering $72 million in public support only for improvements
on surrounding land and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been among the least generous stadium deals in the
country, but House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran opposed the land
component and no compromise was struck.
</P>
<P>
   Given the increasingly sweet taxpayer deals that NFL teams are
getting, coupled with the hostile political climate locally,
Massachusetts may not be any team's first choice to relocate, even
if the state could force the league to drop its ban against a
second New England team.
</P>
<P>
   It also is unlikely that Kraft would allow another franchise to
play at Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not a suit we would bring lightly,'' Cafasso
said. ``But it's always an option. A suit of that magnitude would
be incredibly resource-intensive. It would require numbers of
experts and a great deal of spadework to do it right. And this is
the kind of lawsuit that would require some support from the
governor and the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither branch has inquired about the possibility of a suit, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   However, Harshbarger could file a suit independently, without
the support or approval of Governor Paul Cellucci, the House, or
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should,'' said Stephen Ross, an expert on such litigation
and a law professor at the University of Illinois. ``People in
Boston are losing a team, and taxpayers in Connecticut are getting
hosed for hundreds of millions of dollars because of the NFL's
anticompetitive way that they set up issues concerning stadium
funding and financing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said the most radical suit would be to demand the breakup
of the NFL into two leagues, thereby opening professional football
to competitive forces, just like in the 1960s when the American
Football League existed. Such a case would have to build upon a
1986 verdict, in a suit brought by the now-defunct USFL, that found
the NFL was a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Competition would create more teams, allowing more cities to
host them without such lavish stadium deals. The teams would come
hat in hand, rather than having communities seeking the prestige of
having a franchise.
</P>
<P>
   State-sponsored antitrust suits have become popular, Ross said,
because money-generating facilities are one of the only ways
franchises can distinguish themselves within the NFL, where most
other revenue is shared among all the teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has a lot of bad effects, especially the incentive for
owners to move to see where they can rip off the taxpayers the
most,'' Ross said, adding that lease lawsuits are more
state-specific and technical.
</P>
<P>
   One problem for Massachusetts is that Harshbarger, who gave up
his position to run for governor, leaves office Jan. 20 and will be
replaced by Middlesex District Attorney Thomas F. Reilly, whose
administration would have to fight the legal battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of transition and whether the Reilly administration
would be supportive of this type of litigation would have to be
resolved,'' Cafasso said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
