<HEADLINE>
TEXAS-ESCAPE-1STLD 
 
ESCAPED TEXAS DEATH ROW INMATE FOUND DEAD, FLOATING IN RIVER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC BERGER 
and PAUL McKAY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Death row inmate Martin Gurule, who broke
out of the Ellis Unit late Thanksgiving night, was found dead in
Harmon Creek Thursday, just one mile from the prison, officials
said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Two off-duty correctional officers who were fishing near the
community of Riverside about 5:30 p.m. spotted Gurule's bloated
corpse in the creek, which feeds into the Trinity River, prison
spokesman Larry Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said it appeared that the 29-year-old killer had
drowned and they estimated that Gurule's body had been in the water
at least a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   But Wayne Scott, the prison's executive director, also said
there was a wound on the body. It was unclear, he said, whether
Gurule injured himself on the prison's razor-wire fences or was
shot by prison guards as he fled a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long grueling seven days,'' spokesman Fitzgerald said
of the manhunt that involved hundreds of law officers and dozens of
tracking dogs. ``We believe it was the intense pressure put on by
prison employees and other law enforcement agencies that indeed
forced Gurule from his hiding place.''
</P>
<P>
   The inmate's body was taken to the Huntsville Funeral Home and
was to be transferred to the University of Texas Medical Branch in
Galveston for an autopsy. Fitzgerald said it could be several days
before a cause of death is determined.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule, who was facing the death penalty for killing two men
during a 1992 Corpus Christi robbery, was the only one of seven
condemned killers to succeed in escaping. After using a hacksaw
blade to cut through the fence of a recreation yard just before
midnight on Thanksgiving, the group spent several hours on the roof
of a prison building before sliding to the ground and running for
the fences before dawn last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said Gurule, the first Texas inmate to flee death row
since 1934, had strapped cardboard around his body, under his
prison clothing, to protect him from the razor wire that tops the
two 10-foot chainlink fences he scaled before disappearing into the
foggy woods.
</P>
<P>
   The other six would-be escapees surrendered when guards began
shooting. None was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had launched a massive, round-the-clock search for
Gurule, but tracking dogs lost his scent in a marshy area near the
prison. Seven days of searching, including flyovers by helicopters
with heat-sensing devices, had turned up no leads until the body
was found.
</P>
<P>
   All seven inmates involved in the escape were part of the
nation's first prison work program to employ death row inmates.
Prisoners in the program were allowed much more freedom to move
about the prison than other death row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the killers who tried to escape with Gurule had
attempted escape before. Despite that 1993 attempt, he was returned
to the work program, which produces prison clothing and other goods
for the corrections system.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial program was suspended by Criminal Justice
Board Chairman Allan Polunsky earlier this week, pending an
investigation. The captured inmates have been placed in
administrative segregation, a high-security setting in which they
are allowed to leave their cells for only an hour a day.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Texas Gov. George W. Bush demanded answers and
asked the Texas Rangers to step in and conduct their own
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset about it,'' Bush said during an Austin news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, the investigative arm of the Texas Department of
Public Safety, had participated in the hunt for Gurule since
Monday, three days after the break, officials said. But Bush said
he wanted a full investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule was sentenced to death for shooting Minas ``Mike''
Piperis on Oct. 12, 1992, during a robbery at a Corpus Christi
restaurant which Piperis co-owned with his brother, George. Gurule
also was charged with killing restaurant worker Anthony Staton, but
that case never went to trial. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
