<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ESCAPE-SIDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF-DUTY PRISON EMPLOYEES FISHING, SPOT BODY OF DEATH ROW INMATE  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
and LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERSIDE, Texas _ Mark Humphrey and Doug Smith were about to
call it quits with fishing about 5:30 p.m. Thursday, when they
motored out into Harmon Creek to check the trot lines they had run
near the community of Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a dispatcher for the prison system's Wynne Unit in
Huntsville, noticed something resembling a mannequin floating in
the middle of the creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun was going down,'' said Smith, 41. ``We were heading
toward one of our lines. I looked up and said, `Mark, look at
that.' We were pretty sure it was the inmate. The face was swollen.
We couldn't identify him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A bad thought came into my mind,'' said Humphrey, a
39-year-old prison truck driver who also works at the Wynne Unit.
``I said, `Oh, man, if it's got fingernails, it's not a mannequin.
I saw those fingernails, and I said, `That's a convict.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Smith grabbed the clothes with a fishing gaff to keep the body
of escaped death row inmate Martin Gurule from floating off.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Humphrey said the body had several pieces of
cardboard wrapped around it with some kind of tape. While Smith saw
blood on the inmate and holes in his clothes _ but no bullet wound
_ Humphrey did not see them.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities later confirmed that the body was that of Gurule,
who escaped late Thanksgiving night from the Ellis I Unit.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Criminal Justice had launched a massive
search for Gurule, using about 500 law enforcement officers from a
variety of agencies, along with high-tech equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But Humphrey said it would have been nearly impossible to spot
Gurule's body from the banks of the creek. The creek is about a
quarter of a mile wide at that spot, he said, and the body was
floating so low in the water it would have looked like a log. And
helicopters would have had difficulty finding it, too, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them spotting it with a helicopter would have been like
finding a needle in a haystack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey estimated Gurule, who was found floating face up, had
been in the water since shortly after he escaped because the body
was so badly swollen.
</P>
<P>
   The face was unrecognizable, but he had dark curly hair similar
to Gurule's, Humphrey said. ``He had convict attire on. Not prison
whites, but thermal underwear. To me it look like it had been dyed
black.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey and Smith said that Gurule had cardboard around his
belly, most likely to protect him when he scrambled over the razor
wire atop the prison's perimeter fences.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey dialed 911 on the cellular phone he was carrying and
was advised to stay with the body until authorities arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was minding my own business fishing,'' Humphrey added
with a wry laugh. ``And then I have to (go through) all that. It's
not something I want to do every day.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is Humphrey's second episode with finding escaped
convicts.
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago, as he was hauling a load of prison pig
hides to Milwaukee, he was pulled over at a weigh station in Hope,
Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Three convicts working at a prison packing plant had cut holes
in three pig hides and crawled inside, and rode out with the
trailer load of hides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fate, I guess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gurule's maternal grandmother, Amalia Marez of Corpus
Christi, Texas, wept uncontrollably at the news of her grandson's
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have said a final goodbye to my baby,'' said
Marez, who helped raise Gurule after his mother died just before he
turned a year old. ``He was my first grandson. It's so sad because
I love him so much. He was so special to me.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she got news of his death when reporters called her;
Gurule's father was notified by the Nueces County sheriff's
department, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had been ``praying and praying'' for God to watch
over him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him, `Send your invisible angels and watch after my
baby.' I was praying for him constantly. Now that he's gone, that's
probably the way he wanted it to be.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
