<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCAPEE-FOUND04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death row escapee caught
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino and Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ One of the largest manhunts in Texas history
ended Thursday when two off-duty Texas prison officers on a fishing
trip found the body of death row escapee Martin Gurule floating in
a creek just a mile from the prison he boldly broke out of a week
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bloated body, still garbed in prison-issue shoes and
clothing, was found about 5:30 p.m. He apparently died days ago,
prison officials said, after trying to swim swift-running Harmon
Creek near a road outside the Ellis Unit, which houses Death Row.
Officials said it was uncertain if there were additional wounds
because of the condition of the body.
</P>
<P>
   The condemned killer was found wrapped in cardboard inside two
layers of thermal underwear, a homemade get-up apparently designed
to protect him from razor-wire atop the 10-foot prison fences he
scrambled over late Thanksgiving night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the weight of the world has been lifted off me,''
said prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this supports our theory all along that he never
moved from the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurule, 29, was one of seven death row inmates who outfoxed the
state by cutting through a recreation yard fence, hiding on a roof
for hours, and then dropping to the fog-shrouded ground to try to
scale two other razor-topped fences to the outside world. Gurule,
who was convicted of gunning down a Corpus Christi restaurant owner
in 1992, was the only one to make it out of the prison compound.
The other six gave up when prison officers began shooting from
towers 200 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule's body, identified through fingerprints, was found by two
prison transportation officers from the Wynne Unit, Doug Smith and
Martin Humphrey. They were in a fishing boat running a trot line
when they saw Gurule's floating body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at peace now,'' said George Piperis of Corpus Christi, the
cousin of one of Gurule's victim, restaurant owner Minas ``Mike''
Piperis. ``It was tense, him being out on the loose and not knowing
what he might do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will not bring my cousin back, but at least now justice has
been done.''
</P>
<P>
   The audacious breakout of death row stunned a state that has
gained a reputation for showing no mercy toward condemned killers,
carrying out far more executions than any other state in the
nation. The escape put a spotlight on the state's little-known
practice of allowing death row inmates to perform prison chores
that allowed them movement outside their cells.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 death row prisoners worked in a prison factory
that made uniforms for correctional officers. Gurule, who had been
a well-behaved prisoner since his incarceration, held a janitorial
job, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After the break-out, the Texas Department of Criminal Justice
came under severe criticism for running the work program, a system
no other state operates. The unusual work program was suspended
this week, and all 454 death row inmates have been locked in their
cells since the unexpected escape.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule was the first death row inmate to escape a Texas prison
since the 1934 breakout of a member of the Bonnie and Clyde gang.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past week, the Texas Department of Criminal Justice
conducted a round-the-clock search in the area around the Ellis
Unit, located about 15 miles northeast of Huntsville. As many as
500 officers, including many on horseback, aided by bloodhounds and
helicopters with infrared equipment patrolled 17,000-acres around
the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Hounds picked up Gurule's scent outside the 10-foot chain-link
fence where spots of blood were found later. But the dogs quickly
lost his scent on a nearby road.
</P>
<P>
   Roadblocks were set up in the around the Ellis Unit, and a house
to house search was conducted in the cluster of neighborhood of
correctional officer homes just outside the prison.
</P>
<P>
   The search was called off a few hours after Gurule's body was
pulled from the creek. Until about 8 p.m., corrections officers
were still posted as sentries along the roads around the prison,
huddled over small fires to ward off mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The search is over,'' said Gary Johnson, head of the prison
division. ``We're relieved. This was an issue of public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials said all along they believed Gurule would not
make it out of the prison vicinity. But on Thursday, the state
began circulating wanted posters with three photos of the wanted
killer and posted a $5,000 reward for him. Texas Crime Stoppers, a
state government program, offered the reward for information
leading to Gurule's capture.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday, Gov. George W. Bush had called on the Texas
Rangers to help figure out how Gurule escaped. ``I'm upset about
it,'' said Bush. ``I've asked the Texas Rangers to step in and
answer the question for me and for Texas . . . to find out why a
death row inmate escaped and is still at large.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It concerns me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had been involved in the search for Gurule since
early in the week. At Bush's direction, they had begun
investigating how the prisoner's escape plan had been hatched and
carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they found him,'' said one guard posted along a road
nearby and who said he was not allowed to give his name. ``Now
maybe we can get up off this road.''
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman Capitol Bureau Chief Ken Herman contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
