<HEADLINE>
BOEING OFFERS FREE PROGRAMS FOR EMPLOYEES FACING JOB LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ May Lau, 28.
</P>
<P>
   Engineer, loads and dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Objective: a job in aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   May Lau is hopeful. ``I'm pretty marketable,'' she said.
``There's lots of jobs in other fields. But it's tight in
aerospace.''
</P>
<P>
   Lau is in the third wave of layoffs; she got her 60-day warn
notice Nov. 25. She has a job at The Boeing Co. until the end of
January.
</P>
<P>
   The first wave got their warn notices Oct. 2. They're on the
street today.
</P>
<P>
   The second wave got its 60-day notices Oct. 30. The next wave
gets its notices Dec. 18.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes, as Washington state's largest company slims
down. As Boeing Chairman Phil Condit said Wednesday, ``When your
revenues go down, you've got to shrink the whole business.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing made the news Tuesday by forecasting a sharply lower
production rate in 2000 and cuts of 42,600 jobs in addition to cuts
already made since June. But airplane production goes up next year,
to 620 airplanes from 550. And while Boeing aims to build those
planes with fewer people, the ramp-up still means that many of the
early cuts will be non-assembly people such as planners, analysts
and engineers.
</P>
<P>
   People like May Lau. A recent graduate of the University of
Washington with a master's degree in aeronautics and astronautics,
Lau has been at Boeing only two years.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, she was at Boeing's Career Transition Center
in Renton, Wash., working on her resume. Clad in a sweater and
jeans, she was the only one there _ an indication, perhaps, of
less-than-burning urgency on the part of many co-workers, or an
urge to shove the distasteful task to the other side of Christmas.
Lau wasn't waiting; she said if she was going to be laid off, it
might as well be now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an advantage to be early,'' she said. ``As next year goes
on, it's going to get tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   The service she was using is the latest thing in corporate
downsizing, and is available at Renton and Everett, Wash. The
center offers workshops (``Identifying Your Marketable Skills''),
video interview training, personal counseling and use of the
Internet, word processing, mailing supplies, postage and
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   These services, minus the Internet, were offered in the early
1990s. And though the market cost of the service is $1,500 to
$2,000 per user, Boeing spokesman Bob Jorgensen said the company
believes it is worthwhile to offer it as a free benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   First _ the reason the company likes to talk about _ it's the
right thing to do. ``Phil Condit says it's the right thing to do,
and we need to do it,'' Jorgensen says. ``These are not employees
leaving because of poor performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, ``There's going to be an upturn down the road; there
always is.'' Boeing wants to be able to call people back. The
company doesn't want sour faces on those who are leaving _ or those
staying.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the company doesn't want any incidents. ``In the last
downturn there was not a single case of workplace violence,''
Jorgensen said. Part of the job of the counselors is to defuse
anger, including temperamental outbursts at the boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managers like this program a lot,'' he said. All affected
managers received tapes showing how to deal with five different
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth _ the reason the company doesn't like to talk about _ is
lawsuits. People who are treated decently are less likely to file
them.
</P>
<P>
   The centers are open to salaried and hourly employees alike. The
two groups tend to use them differently. ``The salaried employees
tend to feel more confident they know what to do,'' Jorgensen said.
Like May Lau, they're there to use the computers and other
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hourly employees tend to need more support. They'll take
classes and sign up for counseling,'' Jorgensen said. ``But they
tend to find a job faster, because their skills are more
transferable.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate program is offered through the Aerospace Machinists
union, which includes up to $2,500 per year for three years in
retraining grants. The engineers' union, the Seattle Professional
Engineering Employees Association, has an informational package
that goes to all members facing layoffs. SPEEA also plans a job
fair in the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody needs all this help.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of people who can go out on their own,'' said
Lau, as she finished up work in the Boeing center. ``But it's nice
that they provide it for the people who need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lau is hoping to find work in Boeing; she grew up in Oregon, and
hopes to stay in the Pacific Northwest. But she said that depends
on what's available.
</P>
<P>
   Confident?
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, yes,'' she said. ``We'll see as my layoff dates
comes closer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
