<HEADLINE>
TAPE OF TRIPP SLIPS OUT  
 POLITICAL PROPS PUT TO GOOD USE  
 HELP FOR HUDSON RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has been talk that LINDA TRIPP, who tape-recorded her
talks with MONICA LEWINSKY, is talking about talking to LARRY KING
on CNN. For now, anyway, it is just talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda has made no commitment to appear on any show,'' said a
person close to her who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``She
has met with representatives of several media outlets and will meet
with others. As of now, however, she has not agreed to any
interview.''
</P>
<P>
   So why was Ms. Tripp seen last week on the tabloid-television
show ``Hard Copy''?
</P>
<P>
   She wanted ``to get some new pictures circulated,'' the person
close to Ms. Tripp said, so she agreed to be videotaped by the
television personality DAPHNE BARAK. No questions were asked _ or
answered _ and Ms. Tripp was not paid for the session, the person
close to her said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The footage turned up on `Hard Copy,''' the person said,
``because Paramount, which owns the show, is one of the outlets
Barak is affiliated with.''
</P>
<P>
   Political Props Put to Good Use
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every day, elected officials cram their calendars
with ``same old, same old'' ceremonies. They give speeches. They
have their pictures taken. They do a lot of handshakes. Rarely does
inspiration strike.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Home Depot, the huge home-improvement retailer,
called a news conference in the Bronx to announce a tool-collection
drive for victims of Hurricane Mitch, which devastated Honduras and
Nicaragua last month. The company said it had chosen the Bronx
because it has one of the highest concentrations of Hondurans in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx borough president, FERNANDO FERRER, attended. He shook
hands. He gave a speech. Then it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see the light bulb go off as he was going through
his prepared remarks,'' said FRANK MARINO, a spokesman for Home
Depot. ``He said something like `Who needs to keep those mementos
on the walls?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer was talking about hard hats and shovels, the trophies
every elected official is given at groundbreaking ceremonies. The
bookshelves in Ferrer's office are crowned with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hats stacked upon hats,'' said his spokesman, CLINT
ROSWELL. ``It's sort of like walking into a construction area.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. Ferrer ordered his office cleaned out and the hats
and shovels delivered to Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Help for Hudson River
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Considering the blue-collar origins of Hudson
Riverkeeper, an environmental group formed in 1983 by fishermen and
former Marines, one might not expect it to be honored at a
celebrity-heavy event.
</P>
<P>
   But Hudson Riverkeeper is now run by ROBERT F. KENNEDY JR., so
the rich and famous arrived in full force. BILLY BALDWIN, AIDAN
QUINN and EDWARD JAMES OLMOS were among those who turned out at the
brand-new Paul &AMP; Shark sportswear shop on Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ANDREA DINI, the president of Paul &AMP; Shark, said the company
expected to give Kennedy's group $30,000 to $50,000 from its sales
of limited-edition jackets, caps and sweaters with the Riverkeeper
logo.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing one of the $497 yachting jackets, Kennedy christened the
store. He also treated the crowd to a brief history of his group's
efforts to fight suspected polluters like Exxon and General
Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's colleague, JOHN CRONIN, then led the crowd in
something of a chant, asking them to claim the Hudson as the
property of citizens, not polluters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under whose authority do we protect the Hudson River?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine!'' shouted the actress LORRAINE BRACCO, before the rest
of the crowd could chime in, ``Ours!''
</P>
</TEXT>
