<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 GIULIANI VOWS TO PUSH CONTROVERSIAL GARBAGE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani vowed Thursday to forge ahead
with his plan to ship most of New York City's residential trash to
transfer stations in New Jersey, saying that politicians furious
about the proposal would calm down once they realized the economic
benefits that their constituents stood to reap.
</P>
<P>
   The unveiling of the plan on Wednesday piqued the interest of a
number of New Jersey towns eager to do business with the city,
Giuliani said, adding that he had received calls from ``at least
three public officials'' who were ``very, very anxious to make
deals with us.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Giuliani unflinchingly predicted that the plan would be
in place by the end of 2001, when the Fresh Kills landfill on
Staten Island is scheduled to close, opponents in both states were
threatening to do everything in their power to thwart it. In New
Jersey, elected officials said they would block construction of
huge transfer stations in Newark and Carteret, where garbage from
Manhattan and Queens would be shipped under the plan.
</P>
<P>
   And in Brooklyn, where a third transfer station would be built,
community groups were considering a lawsuit on grounds that the
plan violated environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, a Republican whose second term will end just as Fresh
Kills is supposed to close, has a lot resting on the proposal.
Overwhelming support from Staten Island helped him win the mayoral
elections of 1993 and 1997, and that backing would also be
important if he decides to run for the U.S. Senate in 2000. If the
garbage proposal failed, it could also hurt any plans Giuliani
might have to seek a national office by raising questions about his
ability to carry out plans he proposes.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, the mayor insisted that the plan would be
relatively easy to carry out _ even as he admitted that his
administration made what he called ``a good faith mistake'' by
waiting until the last minute to tell the New Jersey governor,
Christie Whitman, about the plan. Giuliani said his administration
kept the plan from public officials in New Jersey until it was
complete because of New York City's strict rules for reviewing
bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``On reflection, it certainly should have meant that Gov.
Whitman was briefed,'' Giuliani said in a rare show of contrition.
``That was a mistake, but it wasn't a bad-faith mistake. It was a
good-faith mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lhota, the deputy mayor for operations, said he had
discussed the plan with Mrs. Whitman's chief of staff in several
phone conversations Thursday, and that officials from both
administrations would continue the talks in person. But while Mrs.
Whitman's aides said they were not necessarily against having some
of the city's garbage brought to the state, they promised to fight
Giuliani's plan to ship it to Newark and Carteret on barges and to
build new transfer stations to store it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about New York City's trash,'' said Pete McDonough,
chief spokesman for Mrs. Whitman. ``It is about the method for
receiving it.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., also denounced the plan,
using even sharper language than the governor's aides. ``This is
not going to happen,'' said Torricelli. ``Garbage cannot be
transferred on barges off of beaches without impacting the quality
of life in New Jersey. We must present a united front in opposition
to this plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
