<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANKINGS DON'T IMPRESS BIBBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC is picking up steam nationally, garnering
votes in both top 25 polls and rising to 25th in computer guru Jeff
Sagarin's power ratings.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell Trojans coach Henry Bibby, who claims to care
less about any rankings, even though USC (4-0) is off to its best
start in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about a poll. It doesn't mean anything,'' Bibby
said. ``It's as bad as the Internet. It's a lot of gossip. I enjoy
being 4-0. I enjoy winning one game at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Bibby to change his message. He adopted the same
one-game-at-time cliche two years ago as USC made its run to the
NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do what you're supposed to do, everything will fall
into place,'' Bibby said. ``I don't know about anything (power
ratings). That's something that gets you sidetracked.''
</P>
<P>
   Leadership vacuum? Bibby said one of his concerns is that the
Trojans do not have a veteran player who has emerged in a
leadership role. He continues to hope junior forward Jarvis Turner
will eventually become that player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need that leadership role from an elder
statesman,'' Bibby said. ``No one's really taken over yet. (Senior
guards) Larry (Ayuso) and Adam (Spanich) are not that. We're
looking for an older person who can bring that.''
</P>
<P>
   A logical candidate would seem to be junior-college transfer
Brian Scalabrine, who leads USC in scoring (15.8 points) and
rebounding (7.5 per game).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's new,'' Bibby said. ``He's only played four games.''
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier shines: Sophomore guard Jeff Trepagnier has been the
hit of the young season, according to Bibby. He is the Trojans'
most complete player, averaging 10.5 points, 3.5 rebounds, 1.75
blocks and 1.75 steals per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the key to our team,'' Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His contribution is not on the stat sheet,'' Bibby added.
``It's his energy on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Swillis waiting: After not playing a single minute in the past
two games, forward Shannon Swillis met with Bibby earlier this week
about his role on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby said he told Swillis to be patient as he tries to see what
some of the new players can contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what Shannon Swillis can do. I know what he brings to
the table,'' Bibby said. ``I'm looking and fishing to see where
everybody fits in. Everybody can't be happy. Every player has to
find a role where he can help the basketball team. It's not
anything against anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   One way for Swillis to increase his minutes would be to switch
back to power forward from small forward. The coaching staff wasn't
exactly thrilled last year when Swillis expressed the desire to
become a small forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice has been to take each practice one day at a time,''
Bibby said. ``We have to look past the selfish mode from last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Power player: Freshman forward Sam Clancy is USC's
second-leading rebounder, averaging 5.8 per game despite playing
just 13 minutes a game. Clancy is averaging a rebound every two
minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
