<HEADER>
A2524 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYSE-MOVE-ART-505&AMP;ADD     12-03 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYSE-MOVE-ART-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 ELEVENTH-HOUR TINKERING KEEPS PLAN FOR BIG BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Stock Exchange on Thursday failed to
ratify a $900 million plan to build a new trading complex in lower
Manhattan and said it would resume consideration of a move to New
Jersey, but a bit of last-minute tinkering appears to have saved
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   City and state officials in New York, who had expected the
directors of the exchange to approve the deal Thursday, were
stunned to learn about the sudden revision in what had been a
carefully written script.
</P>
<P>
   But after several tense hours, Richard Grasso, the chairman of
the Big Board, drove to City Hall from Wall Street for a 5 p.m.
meeting with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. The 60-minute parley ended
peacefully with an agreement to resolve what both sides described
as ``some minor issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor and Dick Grasso just concluded a meeting,'' the
mayor's press secretary, Colleen Roche, said Thursday evening.
``They made good progress, and we expect to wrap up the deal in a
couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Adamonis, a spokesman for the exchange, also said the
meeting resolved some open issues. ``We're hopeful there'll be a
speedy resolution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal appeared to have hit a serious snag earlier Thursday
when the exchange issued a statement: ``No vote was requested at
the board meeting. Discussions continue with the city and state of
New York and with the state of New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of dickering, city and state officials in New York
had agreed to acquire an entire block across the street from the
exchange's historic home on Wall Street and to build a trading
complex at an estimated cost of $450 million. The officials would
also provide the exchange with up to $160 million in tax breaks and
low-cost electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange, in turn, would pay rent starting at $10 million a
year for the trading complex, which would rise on the block bound
by Wall Street and Exchange Place between Broad and William
streets. City and state officials hope to offset the estimated $300
million cost of acquiring the property by selling the right to
build a large office tower over the trading box.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials have been pursuing the stock market since
May, after exchange officials complained that City Hall seemed more
interested in building a new stadium for the Yankees than it was in
retaining the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange has also talked to Mack Cali Realty Corp., which
was willing to build a 1.2-million-square-foot headquarters at its
Harborside Financial Center complex in Jersey City, N.J. But
real-estate executives on both sides of the Hudson River said there
was little chance that the exchange would leave Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   John Dyson, chairman of the mayor's council of economic
advisers, played down the brief contretemps with the exchange
Thursday and the threat to move to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't like to let go of the Jersey card until the last
minute,'' Dyson said. ``We have a handshake deal with Grasso.
Honorable men do not easily give their handshake. We just have a
few details to work out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If the deal with the New York Stock Exchange is completed, it
would end an often contentious, decade-long poker game in which
each of the city's four financial markets has threatened to flee to
New Jersey in order to extract a package of subsidies and tax
breaks. Bluff or not, the city has agreed to provide nearly $1
billion in subsidies, including $599 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of arrangement has prompted reproaches from Giuliani's
critics. ``The mayor's ideology of limited government obviously
excludes this kind of mega-handout of public resources for private
purposes,'' said Harvey Robins, the city's director of operations
under former Mayor David Dinkins. ``These resources are better
spent on the long-term investments in schools, transportation,
parks and libraries, which make the city a better, more competitive
place to live and to work for all New Yorkers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
