<HEADER>
A2528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BAVETTA-PROFILE-A     12-03 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BAVETTA-PROFILE-ART-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOVIAL REFEREE IS EAGER FOR CALL TO PLAY BALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The basketball referees are restless, jangly,
suspicious of a world without carefully painted lines and
half-circles underfoot. When the National Basketball Association's
doors locked on the players, the refs got their paychecks but not
their whistles or striped uniforms. So now they sit around at home
watching old game tapes and calling each other with pop quizzes.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a clear-path-to-the-basket foul or not? Answer yes or
no, fast.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Bavetta, one of the best-known referees in the game, gets
out his trampoline and jumps on it, runs eight miles every day
around his neighborhood in the Mill Basin section of Brooklyn, and
tops it off with a bike ride. He puts on his NBA cap and visits
hospital wards, his lean face instantly recognizable even to casual
basketball fans. He speaks to school assemblies that regard him
warily as some kind of hoops cop.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not enough to replay calls in his mind and keep his
58-year-old body taut, waiting for the call that a settlement has
been reached; there is more being lost in this lockout than the
orderly demonstration of sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Bavetta's other mission in life, almost as well-known as his
encyclopedic knowledge of the rule book, is to sandblast the
stone-faced image of the sports official, to soften it with humor,
spontaneity and even the occasional lindy with team mascots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to deliver the goods,'' he said Thursday in his
den, amid the exercise equipment. ``But once you've done that,
you've also got to show that you don't take yourself too seriously.
It's just part of my personality, and I just hope the league
doesn't mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The league doesn't mind. In fact, among basketball insiders, who
trade Bavetta stories like sports cards, Bavetta's antics have
become some of the most memorable moments of the last few decades,
missed this season almost as much as the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   There was the time, a few years ago, when the Chicago Bulls
mascot trotted onto the court, followed by three small children
dressed as baby bulls. The littlest one kept tripping over her
costume, so Bavetta _ the father of two daughters _ ran out to
midcourt and carried her as she went through her mascot routine,
cozying up to players and even kicking the other two officials. The
crowd laughed hysterically.
</P>
<P>
   About six years ago, the Coyote mascot of the San Antonio Spurs
tried to get Bavetta into a mock punching match during a game,
urging the referee to really let him have it. Bavetta shrugged and
socked him in the mesh breathing area of the costume, sending the
coyote flying across the court.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd went wild as attendants came and removed the mascot on
a stretcher, figuring it was all part of the act, but in fact
Bavetta had broken the actor's nose and knocked him unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since then, other league mascots have made an elaborate
show of avoiding the man they call Boom Boom Bavetta, whose job
description, of course, includes throwing out players for
unsportsmanlike conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he wears five pairs of socks to every game. He likes the
padding on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not just one of the top referees in the game,'' said
Garry St. Jean, the former coach and now the general manager of the
Golden State Warriors. ``He's also the guy who will dance with the
mascots, and give the ball to a 5-year-old at his first game during
a time out, and say hello by name to the ball boys and equipment
managers. He just makes you light up when you see him on the floor,
even if he did call me for a technical once.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ruefully, ``Right now, we need more characters like
Dick Bavetta.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That wasn't the case back in the 1960s, when Bavetta was
frantically writing letters to the league, begging to be considered
for an official's job. He was working on Wall Street then,
officiating at weekend small-college games and occasionally for the
old Eastern Basketball Association, which became the Continental
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to drive out of my way to go by Madison Square Garden,
fantasizing that maybe one day I could referee a game in there,''
he said. ``I kept trying to get someone from the NBA to come to a
game where I was officiating. I guess by 1975 they just felt sorry
for me and let me in.''
</P>
<P>
   He became an energetic, gutsy official, never hesitating to make
big calls when games hung in the balance, a favorite among coaches
for his willingness to admit, after a game, that he might have
blown a call or two. (Assuming the tapes are incontrovertible, that
is.)
</P>
<P>
   Imposing order may have come naturally to the son of a New York
City police officer, whose brother was also a police detective.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown up in Park Slope, Brooklyn, listening to his father
talk about prohibition and Al Capone, he saw officiating as the
perfect mixture of sports, show business and law enforcement, and
has sacrificed for it. His wife left him when he was hired by the
NBA, preferring a husband who was home for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   And so, having fashioned his life around his role, he waits for
the phone to ring with good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``My body is crying out to me, `Bavetta, what are you doing
speaking at a grammar school?''' he said. ```You should be in the
Meadowlands.' It's just because I love this more than anything.
We'll get back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
