<SLUG> BC-TV-HOUDINI-375&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOUDINI'S' APPEAL PROVES ILLUSORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harry Houdini, stud muffin.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the TNT movie ``Houdini'' threatens to send your eyes
rolling back into their sockets (hint: early, often), they put
actor Johnathon Schaech in a loincloth.
</P>
<P>
   And usually, right about then, somebody bangs on a gong.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't do much for me, frankly, but I'll presume that the
effect is positively volcanic on some sectors of the cable viewing
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed and produced by Pen Densham (``The Outer
Limits''), the film will show three times Sunday on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   You can find George Segal, Rhea Perlman, Ron Perlman, Paul
Sorvino and David Warner in the cast. But they're like illusionist
tricks themselves; now you see them, now you don't.
</P>
<P>
   The real principals are Schaech (he sounds like Harry Hamlin and
played the lead singer in ``That Thing You Do!'') as Houdini and
Stacy Edwards (``Chicago Hope'') as his wife, Bess.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, and Grace Zabriskie, who proved in ``Twin Peaks'' that
she has an eye for the unusual. Here she's Houdini's mother, listed
in the credits as Mother.
</P>
<P>
   I would summarize the movie this way: I love my wife but oh, you
Mother.
</P>
<P>
   Mother is a Hungarian Jew who doesn't speak English. Zabriskie
plays her as a woman who has apparently entered the spirit realm
years before her death. She's icy, cadaverous and shows her eldest
son no physical affection.
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, Harry is crazy about her. When she dies, he
scorches a path to every spiritual medium on the continent in hopes
of reaching her. Then he becomes obsessed with exposing all mediums
as charlatans. And meanwhile, Bess seeks comfort in a stout bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Schaech has a rather small screen presence to play the great
escape artist, who died on Halloween in 1926 and, so far as we
know, has not popped up for a bow.
</P>
<P>
   But give Schaech some credit. He does gamely throw himself into
several of Houdini's seemingly dangerous routines. Hence the
loincloth and gong wake-up calls.
</P>
<P>
   Densham professes to a long-standing fascination with Houdini.
Sure enough, the film is earnest and admiring. But watch-worthy?
Not really.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ Showtime's ``Girls' Night,'' showing Sunday, is a narrower
miss, and with even more knockout talent on display.
</P>
<P>
   The English film stars two Oscar nominees, Brenda Blethyn
(``Secrets &AMP; Lies'') and Julie Walters (``Educating Rita'').
Joining them, for the fun of it, is gnarly old Kris Kristofferson.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's rewarding to watch the women work. But ``Girls'
Night'' is achingly slow and, at least for me, ultimately
unaffecting.
</P>
<P>
   Blethyn and Walters play sisters-in-law and factory co-workers
in northern England. Their predictable, somewhat forlorn lives are
brightened when they win a national jackpot at a bingo parlor.
</P>
<P>
   Then Blethyn learns that she has a cancerous brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls' Night'' gets a much-needed lift when the two women fly
to Las Vegas for an impulsive holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're bloody talking!'' exclaims Walters when she first
sees the massive casino at the Riviera, and by that stage of the
movie, I shared her sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas experience also includes Kristofferson as a
saddle-worn bachelor cowpoke who's doggone tired of being lonely.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's back to England and another sag in the story. ``Girls'
Night'' ends as a shameless tearjerker. I was just checking the
clock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
