<HEADER>
A2536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LABOR04-COX     12-03 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With season in jeopardy, Jordan joins labor talks
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On Monday, NBA players lost their second pay day of
the locked out season. On Tuesday, teams were busy processing
refunds, plus 6 percent interest, to ticket holders for games lost
the month of November.
</P>
<P>
   With that as backdrop and the clock ticking toward a drop dead
date, the NBA and the players association were back at the
bargaining table late Thursday night in New York.
</P>
<P>
   There was a small sign of optimism when Michael Jordan showed up
after an uneventful morning session, then returned at mid-evening
after a three-hour break for a personal appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``His understanding was that a new proposal was going to be made
(by the owners), and he wanted to be there to listen to it,'' agent
David Falk said. ``You can read into it that he's continuing to be
involved and supportive of the union leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was also the underlying pessimism of Deputy
Commissioner Russ Granik who saw small potential for compromise and
the combative thrust of at least one player, Miami's Alonzo
Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   The combustible player walked into the first session Thursday
throwing verbal darts at ownership. ``This lockout won't end until
the owners get as much as they can out of the players,'' said the
player who made $11.25 million last season. ``It comes down to
greed on their part.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Danny Schayes of Orlando put matters into perspective,
commenting that ``It's not even about finding a middle ground that
both sides can be happy with, it's about finding a middle ground
that the sides can be equally unhappy with.''
</P>
<P>
   This was only the third full negotiating session since training
camp was canceled. Meetings Oct. 28 and Nov. 20 held some promise,
but showed no tangible results. Indeed, the only results appeared
to be a hardening of positions.
</P>
<P>
   But while both parties agreed to start with a fresh agenda, it
was learned that the owners and players instead tried to salvage
the work of the last session, which blew up with debris of charges
and counter-charges threatening to destroy the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   However, the reality is that the players know they will miss at
least two more checks before the earliest possible starting date in
early January.
</P>
<P>
   The owners know they will be forced at the minimum to refund all
ticket money for December games on top of November. For the Hawks
that involves about 6,000 tickets a game, split among the Georgia
Dome and Georgia Tech so that costs cannot be specific. But for a
middle tier team like Orlando it came to this for the opening
month: a per-game refund cost of $640,000, based upon the average
ticket price of $46 with 13,900 season ticket-holder.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals put on the table Nov. 20 would include players
having 10 percent or 15 percent of their paychecks withheld if
spending on overall player salaries exceeded a targeted percentage
of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   After vowing not to exceed a 50-50 split, the owners moved to 53
percent on Nov. 20 and the players dropped to 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
