<HEADER>
A2540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TOBACCO-SUIT-580&AMP;A     12-03 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOBACCO-SUIT-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY CHALLENGES STATE PLAN TO SPLIT TOBACCO MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arguing that the proposed tobacco lawsuit settlement
would shortchange New York City by as much as $2 billion, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani is contesting New York state's planned allocation
of its share of the money.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's lawyers notified a state judge Thursday that the
city is challenging the state's formula for sharing the money and
reserving the right to drop out of the joint settlement and pursue
its own lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the state attorney general, Dennis Vacco, who is in charge
of the state lawsuit, defended the formula and said New York City
is being treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   New York state is part of the nationwide tobacco litigation,
which includes a proposed settlement estimated at $206 billion over
25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide share of that is about $24 billion. Vacco's office
said the formula would split that amount about equally between the
state government and local governments, with New York City getting
$6.7 billion and the counties outside the city getting about $5.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlement gives a higher allocation to counties outside
New York City on a population basis, on a damages basis, on almost
any basis you look at,'' said a senior adviser to the mayor,
Anthony Coles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor is not going to allow a settlement that gives New
York City less than what it is entitled to. He is going to fight
for fairness, and he has directed the corporation counsel to be as
aggressive as he can be until and unless the city gets its fair
share.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the state formula appears to give New York City more
than its share based on population _ more than half the funds for
local governments, though the city represents less than half the
state's population. But the city contends in its court case that it
bears a greater burden in paying for tobacco-related illnesses than
other local governments. The city did not make clear Thursday night
how it arrived at its reckoning of a possible $2 billion shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   The city was the first entity in New York to sue the tobacco
companies, but it joined with the state and the counties that
followed. Coles said the city is reserving its right to contest
whether the state as a whole is getting its fair share of the
proposed national settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed Thursday in state Supreme Court in Manhattan,
the city said the scope of the litigation makes it ``a most
unusual, if not unique, case.'' The city complained that it needed
more time to study the ``extraordinarily complex'' formula, which
it said was disclosed only on Wednesday. An initial review, the
city said, indicated that counties outside the city ``will, on
average, get nearly twice their proportionate share.''
</P>
<P>
   Disputing the city's claims, the attorney general's spokesman,
Chris McKenna, said, ``Dennis Vacco worked extra hard to make sure
the settlement was more than fair to New York City.'' The city is
getting more than half the share for local governments statewide,
he said. The city's own lawyers ``were involved in crafting the
formula, so it's curious that this is coming up at the eleventh
hour,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, McKenna said, ``the city has a choice: They can opt out
of the settlement and proceed with their own suit.'' Friday is the
deadline for the city to make that choice, but part of its appeal
seeks to postpone that deadline and be given a chance to make its
argument in a ``fairness hearing'' in the state courts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The city's actions come at an awkward moment politically.
Giuliani and Vacco are both Republicans, and the mayor campaigned
for the attorney general's re-election last month. The Democratic
challenger, Eliot Spitzer, has claimed victory, albeit by a thin
margin of about 21,000 votes, but Vacco has refused to concede.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, who has criticized the proposed tobacco settlement on
other grounds, said Thursday night that the allocation issue offers
another reason for delay. Despite his bitter campaign exchanges
with the mayor, Spitzer said is willing to review the city's
claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
