<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TAPIA-NYT &LR;      12-03 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TAPIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.M.)  
 STILL FIGHTING AND STILL UNBEATEN AGAINST ALL ODDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ ``Mi Vida Loca'' (my crazy life) is
embroidered on his ring robe. Somehow, that does not begin to
describe the troubles that the bantamweight Johnny Tapia has
endured.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is amazing Tapia is still boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia's father was shot to death when his mother was pregnant
with Tapia. When he was 8 years old, his mother was kidnapped,
raped, hanged and stabbed to death with an ice pick by five men in
Albuquerque, N.M., the Tapias' hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very, very brutal murder,'' Tapia said. ``She was
stabbed 21 times. It had to do with jealousy. She was a beautiful
woman. I got from the DA the results of my mom's death and they got
all five of the guys. But, bless their hearts, they're all dead
now.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was 12, Tapia was a passenger on a bus that plunged 100
feet off a cliff. He walked away with a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia has served time in jail for intimidating a witness in the
murder trial of a cousin. He is on probation for a spousal-abuse
charge in which he pulled a loaded gun on his wife and manager,
Teresa.
</P>
<P>
   Cocaine addiction kept him out of the ring from 1990 to 1994.
When he returned to the ring, he went on a tear that made him one
of the most dangerous 115-pound boxers in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Through all his pain and failings, Tapia is undefeated (44-0-2)
and in good position to defeat Nana Yaw Konadu (39-3-1) in a World
Boxing Association championship bout at the new Atlantic City
Convention Center on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very comfortable in the ring, but outside the ring I'm a
very lonely person,'' Tapia, 31, said Thursday afternoon inside a
crowded, noisy meeting room at Bally's Park Place Casino before his
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got people in my life that love me for me now. I'm just
taking it one day at a time and having Jesus in my life to guide me
and protect me. I have a lot of faith in God, and what he has done
for me, to turn my life around, has been amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapia said he did not blame anyone for the bad things that had
occurred in his life, particularly the things that he brought on
himself. He seems to have made peace with his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of yesterday, because it's gone, and I don't
think of tomorrow, because it might never come,'' Tapia said.
</P>
<P>
   He is moving up in weight, adding 3 pounds to fight Konadu, a
hard-hitting puncher from Sunyani, Ghana, who once held the World
Boxing Council superflyweight championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia has been saying he was going to move up to the
bantamweight division since 1988, but once he won the World Boxing
Organization junior-bantamweight title (115 pounds) with an
11th-round technical knockout of Henry Martinez on Oct. 12, 1994,
promoters kept putting a string of No. 1 contenders in front of
him, and he kept beating them. His thinking: Why mess with a steady
paycheck?
</P>
<P>
   Tapia added the International Boxing Federation
junior-bantamweight title when he won a 12-round decision over
Danny Romero on July 18, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That bout put Tapia more in the public eye. It was a
neighborhood feud played out on television. Tapia was friends with
Romero and was trained by Danny Romero Sr. before the two had a
bitter split.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Tapia has gone through trainers the way Murphy Brown
went through secretaries. He once hired the venerable trainer Eddie
Futch for three weeks to prepare him for a fight. He dismissed
Teddy Atlas, after Atlas objected to his wife's being at training
camp. He hired Freddie Roach, a Futch disciple who worked with the
heavyweight Michael Moorer and has a way with temperamental boxers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still learning, so I pick up things from different
trainers,'' Tapia said. ``As soon as I stop learning, I'll quit
boxing. I've found a good one this time, and a good friend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
