<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2564 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOGUS-AIRLINE-TICKETS     12-03 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOGUS-AIRLINE-TICKETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIES DEFINITELY UNFRIENDLY IF YOUR AIRLINE TICKET'S A FAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- With the holiday season under way, just about
everybody is looking for a cheap plane ticket -- and criminals are
willing to sell you one.
</P>
<P>
   A rash of burglaries and robberies at travel agencies in the
suburban San Fernando Valley in recent weeks is boosting an already
thriving underground market in stolen tickets, police said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As many as two dozen stolen or fraudulent tickets are seized
each month at Los Angeles International Airport, leaving hapless
travelers stranded or faced with paying the full price, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Five percent to 10 percent of advertised budget fares involve
stolen or fake tickets, usually sold for less than the going price,
police said. But most often, these stolen tickets are sold on the
street by people hanging out near legitimate travel agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's too good to be true, then it (ITAL)is(END ITAL) too
good to be true,'' said Detective Al Aldaz of the Los Angeles
Police Department's Van Nuys Robbery Section.
</P>
<P>
   The thieves typically hand the tickets to a fraud ring that
prepares them for use by imprinting them with legitimate agent
codes from other businesses, said Detective Ron Ponzi, who
specializes in airline fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The rings also research the going rates for travel to various
regions so they can offer their stolen tickets for a hard-to-ignore
price, Ponzi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know the travel-agent lingo,'' he said. ``It's a very
sophisticated and complex network of individuals involved in these
crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they have a difficult time breaking these
rings because travelers seldom can provide enough information. The
meetings between buyers and sellers usually are short, and
transactions often happen through a ``friend of a friend,'' Ponzi
said.
</P>
<P>
   With at least two Valley-area travel agencies robbed and one
burglarized within the past two months, batches of stolen airline
tickets have hit the market, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask TK Travel owner Laurie Stalick, who was robbed Nov. 3
of between 400 and 500 tickets by two masked gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them pulled a gun from his waistband and cocked the
trigger and said: We want airline tickets. We're sorry that we had
to do this, but we lost our jobs and we want to go see our
families,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Six of those tickets ended up being sold on the street, police
told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a time of year when they need quick cash, so I
think we're all vulnerable because cash flow is real tight,''
Stalick said at her office in suburban Northridge. ``I just think
we're living in a real sorry world.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the New Age Travel Agency in suburban Sherman Oaks
was robbed by two armed men who stole 500 blank coupons that can be
made into about 100 usable airline tickets, Aldaz said.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 12, Travel Mart in suburban Woodland Hills also reported
a burglary in which the thieves rammed a vehicle into the front
door to steal six boxes of coupons that can also be made into
usable airline tickets, said Detective Jary Quinones of the LAPD's
West Valley Division.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported in the robberies and the burglary. As
of Thursday, no suspects had been arrested, police said.
</P>
<P>
   All of the stolen tickets are usable, but any alert airline
ticket counter clerk should be able to tell by computer that they
are stolen by typing in the ticket's stock number, Aldaz said.
</P>
<P>
   But many times, the bogus tickets can slip through the airlines,
travel industry officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ticket agent has to be sharp,'' Ponzi said. ``If there's
20 people lined up to get on an airplane, that's the hard part. If
the ticket agent is really busy, sometimes they'll get through.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Salfen, director of consumer affairs at the International
Airline Passengers Association in Dallas, said agents often fail to
check stock numbers at the counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can definitely assure you that they're not checking each
stock number,'' he said. ``They don't have time.''
</P>
<P>
   So in most cases, the passengers will go on board unnoticed,
Salfen said.
</P>
<P>
   However, some airline agents are trained to look for stolen
tickets, and if a passenger should get caught with a bad ticket, he
or she loses out and must pay the full fare to travel, Salfen said.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank-Glendale-Pasadena Airport in suburban Burbank sees an
average of one illegal ticket per month, said airport spokesman
Sean McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, an individual comes in and has been duped into buying
the ticket,'' McCarthy said.
</P>
<P>
   At LAX, stolen tickets are immediately confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't let you get on the plane unless you pay for a new
full fare,'' said Sgt. Charles Oats of the Los Angeles Airport
Police, which during busy times can take in about a dozen stolen
tickets during a two-week period.
</P>
<P>
   TICKET-BUYING ADVICE: The following are tips for travelers to
avoid buying stolen or bogus airline tickets during the holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   Police and airline officials say that before buying a ticket,
travelers should:
</P>
<P>
   --Try to do business directly with an airline or reputable
travel agency.
</P>
<P>
   --Check the ad for the travel agency's ``seller of travel''
number. The Attorney General's Office can confirm a travel agency's
legitimacy if the information is faxed to (213) 897-8846.
</P>
<P>
   --Call the American Society of Travel Agents at (800) ASK-ASTA
to check an agent's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   --Call the airline to make sure it travels to the place
indicated on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   --Have the seller book the reservation before handing over any
money, and check with the airline for your reservation before the
sale. Often, fraud rings will not bother making reservations.
</P>
<P>
   --Be wary of agencies or independent sellers who do not accept
credit cards. Never buy tickets off the street.
</P>
<P>
   --When buying tickets through a friend, track down the source of
the sale.
</P>
<P>
   --Get a receipt.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
