<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-AIDS-SHAME (Durban, South Africa) _ Across sub-Saharan
Africa, the AIDS epidemic is everywhere. In several countries, one
out of four people are now infected with the virus and will
probably die within 10 years. But go to a village and ask if anyone
is suffering from AIDS and the answer will likely be no, there is
only malaria or tuberculosis or diarrhea. It is hard to find anyone
who publicly admits to being HIV-positive. Many go to their graves
with their secret, so great is the stigma attached to AIDS. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-PALACE (Caserta, Italy) _ When a fire broke out recently
in an attic of the Royal Palace here, the flames were quickly
detected and extinguished. But that accident reignited a simmering
controversy over the way the palace is being used that is far more
difficult to stamp out. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT27) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Podujevo, Yugoslavia) _ Though there is little
combat, the war in this province of the Yugoslav republic of Serbia
has taken a new turn. Ethnic Albanian rebels are spreading their
influence to places they had not controlled before NATO threats
made the Serbian government withdraw many police and army units.
Expanding the area they control without having to fight for it
allows the ethnic Albanian rebels to undercut U.S. efforts to
fashion a negotiated settlement to the war. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL (Yaron, Lebanon) _ In the last two weeks, seven Israeli
soldiers have been killed by the Iranian-backed Hezbollah
guerrillas in southern Lebanon. The spate of funerals, all
televised, prompted anew what has been a cyclical re-examination of
the 20-year-old Israeli occupation of this ``security strip'' along
the Israeli-Lebanese border. While the politicians discussed
military tactics and diplomatic strategies, many Israelis asked
aloud if there remained a purpose in putting lives on the line. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT24,28) have been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS-STADIUM (Hartford, Conn.) _ As new questions arise
every day about the expense and feasibility of a stadium deal that
economists say will be the biggest giveaway in the history of
professional sports, Democratic lawmakers are growing increasingly
wary. But the governor and legislative leaders continue to push the
plan, even though they don't know for certain where the stadium
will be built or what it will cost. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-CDC (Undated) _ After declining for many years, the
number of abortions has gone up slightly, according to data from
the Centers for Disease Control from 1995-96. The reasons for the
increase are unclear, some say it could be a decrease in popularity
of Norplant or a return to work of those receiving welfare. By
Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT grpahics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SURF (Half Moon Bay, Calif.) _ Surfers tackle the biggest
waves that come once a year. Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photo [NYT25) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHRISTMAS-WINDOWS (New York) _ Expensive, over-the-top,
department store windows at Christmas time are a ritual as integral
to the season in New York City as overpriced chestnuts sold at
street vendors and snarls of traffic near Rockefeller Center. But
what amounts to a moment's thrill for those who pass by the windows
is the result of months and months of tedious, highly-guarded
planning among retailers, who are looking for much more than
general gawking from the world: they see the windows as a
competitive tool for increasing media attention and store traffic.
By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-GENE (Undated) _ Scientists discover that some/many of
the HIV-infected people who progress quickly to illness have a
variation in a particular gene. They theorize that this kind of
variation may be behind differences in susceptibilities to all
kinds of diseases. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS _ As House Republicans push toward a vote to
impeach President Clinton, not only is public sentiment
overwhelmingly against them, but so are many prominent Republicans
across the country. A look at the divisions among Republicans over
impeachment and the reasons for them. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT17,21) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-STARR _ Kenneth Starr's prosecutors did not forbid
Monica Lewinsky to call her lawyer when they first confronted her
at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel on Jan. 16, and in fact gave her several
opportunities to call anyone she chose, a Federal district judge
concluded in a finding unsealed this week. By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
