<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GOVERNOR LEADS EFFORT TO INFLUENCE CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reflecting concerns among many Republican officials
that their national party is adrift, New York Gov. George Pataki
said Thursday that he and other Republican governors intend to play
a more forceful role in setting the party's agenda in Congress next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be the tail of the dog,'' Pataki said in a
telephone interview from his New York City office. ``We want to
have a true, strong dialogue where decisions in Washington are
supportive of the efforts of what we are doing in the states.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who is said to be pondering a run for national office,
plans to bring that message to Washington on Friday when he and
several other members of the executive board of the Republican
Governors Association are to meet with Rep. Robert Livingston,
R-La., who is virtually certain to be elected House speaker in
January.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governors clearly view themselves as one of their
party's biggest success stories, and Pataki's cheerleading on their
behalf reflects their desire to flex more political muscle as the
party prepares for the 2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is considered a leading contender
for the party's presidential nomination. And Pataki, who has been
traveling the country trying to establish a national image, is one
of several Republican governors who have been mentioned as possible
vice presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Republicans lost one governor's seat in last month's
elections, they will still hold the governorships of 31 states in
January. In several large states, Republican incumbents, including
Pataki, breezed to victory. At the same time, the Republican Party
lost five seats in the House, prompting a shake-up in its
leadership, including the resignation of Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican officials have complained that voters consider
their party members in Congress to be scandal-obsessed and
unconcerned about solving the nation's problems, a perception that
they worry could harm Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki echoed such concerns Thursday, saying the results of the
November elections showed that voters were willing to elect
Republicans governors who could point to tangible legislative
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that there was a clear recognition that
Republican governors across the country have done very well,''
Pataki said. ``You didn't see that in the Washington elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he and other Republican governors would urge
Livingston to press for a package of tax cuts in the coming
legislative session. He said the governors also want Congress to
enact legislation that gives states more control over job-training
programs, federal health-care funding and education aid. And he
said he would like to see Congress create a program that helps
states pay for water-treatment plants and clean-air initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he thought the Republicans in Congress could improve
their public image by taking up the governors' agenda. ``The
partnership between successful Republican governors and the
Republican leadership in Washington would be of benefit to that
leadership,'' he said, ``when those governors have had enormous
successes in their own states.''
</P>
</TEXT>
