<HEADER>
A2581 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURDERER-TEACHER-AZR &LR;      12-03 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDERER-TEACHER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC OUTRAGE SPURS DECISION TO BAR EX-CON FROM TEACHING ASU
CLASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN VAN DER WERF  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona State University, inundated by angry calls, reversed
course Thursday and will not allow convicted murderer James Hamm to
teach criminal justice classes this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ASU said it would honor its contract with Hamm, and pay him the
$6,000 that he was to make as an adjunct professor. Hamm, however,
will be assigned to duties other than direct classroom instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reassigning Mr. Hamm to non-teaching duties is in the best
interest of the university,'' said Milton Glick, ASU provost and
senior vice president. ``The debate surrounding Mr. Hamm's
employment in the classroom at ASU would be too disruptive to the
educational environment, as evidenced by the reaction to his
hiring.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU received scores of calls Thursday. Glick said he received
calls, as did President Lattie Coor's office, the ASU School of
Law, the School of Justice Studies, and other departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think a lot of people were offended by the decision, and
the media coverage has been explosive,'' Glick said. ``I don't
think this is an issue of safety. It is more a matter of the
statement this hiring made to the public, that it offended their
values.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, an adjunct professor in criminal justice studies
resigned in reaction to Hamm's hiring. Angry calls also flooded
into ``The Arizona Republic.'' Some people threatened to cut off
support for the university. Three callers to ``The Republic'' said
they intended to mail back their ASU diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as ASU opens, I plan on contacting the registrars
office and ask what methods it takes to expunge myself as a
graduate. I can't be associated with a facility that hires
executioners, drug dealers and murderers on their faculty,'' said a
caller, who identified himself as Chad Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm said Thursday afternoon, ``Obviously, I am disappointed. I
would have prefered to have moved into teaching these two courses,
then expand that to more courses. (Teaching) is still my personal
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Glick would not answer directly when asked whether ASU would
hire Hamm in the future, but said he doubts it. ``I'm not dealing
with the future right now,'' he said. ``Obviously, there will be a
debate on this campus over the next year about this issue. I would
not predict he would be hired here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm said he understands the university's concerns, and said he
is negotiating with the school over what his role will be.
</P>
<P>
   He declined the university's first offer _ helping with research
projects _ and said he is exploring other options, including
curriculum development and serving as a guest lecturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do something oriented toward my strengths, which are
corrections and rehabilitation. I think that is the core of what I
would bring to ASU, the unique perspective I could provide,'' Hamm
said.
</P>
<P>
   Glick said Hamm's contract is valid, and must be honored.
However, he said, Hamm would be paid with non-public funds.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm was paroled in 1992 after serving 17 years in prison. He
was convicted of killing Willard Morley in a drug deal gone sour
north of Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time Hamm has shaken up ASU. The first hubbub
came over the Law School's decision in 1993 to admit him.
</P>
<P>
   And just as with the Law School admission, ASU has decided to
overhaul its policies as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Glick announced Thursday that in the future, the dean of the
college where an adjunct professor will work will also have to
approve of the hiring.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm was hired last month by Dennis Palumbo, interim director of
the School of Justice Studies. Palumbo said he was on the verge of
canceling two classes because the ``four or five lawyers'' who
usually teach them were not interested this year. Then Hamm
applied, and he was hired to teach a class dealing with the Bill of
Rights called Individual Rights and Public Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect the (hiring) decision,'' Glick said. ``He (Palumbo)
was working within the authority of his office, and he was making a
judgment call. Clearly, it is a judgment call I disagree with, but
that doesn't mean I question his integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Hamm was admitted to ASU Law School, Coor
announced that in the future, the school's dean would be required
to approve the admission of any convicted felons.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm graduated from the ASU Law School in December 1997. He has
failed in his only bid to pass the state Bar Exam, but he said he
plans to take it again in February.
</P>
<P>
   Glick said there were a lot of conflicting emotions that went
into the decision to overhaul Hamm's hiring as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a decision we do not take lightly,'' Glick said. ``On
one hand, we have a person who has been deemed rehabilitated by the
state, and who has attended and graduated from our law school. On
the other hand, many people are concerned about the message sent by
Mr. Hamm as a part-time faculty associate and the impact that the
attention accompanying the debate can have on the university
climate and the surrounding community.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Foster, who attended law school with Hamm and now teaches
part-time in the justice studies program, e-mailed a letter to
Glick Thursday morning, resigning from his teaching position and
all other associations with ASU because of Hamm's hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many, many . . . qualified individuals that have
qualified to sit for and passed the Bar that could have been chosen
to teach these students,'' Foster wrote. ``The university has an
obligation to the community and its students to seek qualified
individuals; it has failed in this regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone later Thursday, Foster said he was
withdrawing his letter based on the change in ASU's hiring
decision, and hopes to teach next semester. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
