<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-DISCRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT SAYS MINORITY STUDENTS IN NEW YORK STATE GET INFERIOR
EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Civil Liberties Union filed a federal
lawsuit Thursday against New York state contending that the
education that minority students receive is so inferior that it
constitutes discrimination under civil rights law.
</P>
<P>
   The state Education Department's own records show, the suit
asserts, that officials have discriminated against children in
predominantly minority schools by allowing them to be taught by
larger numbers of uncertified teachers, tolerating lower academic
standards, relegating them to dilapidated and unsafe schools,
supplying them with out-of-date textbooks and failing to provide
sufficient remedial instruction.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, covers
schools that have minority enrollment of 80 percent or more, from
schools in Long Island and suburban Westchester County to Albany,
Syracuse, Rochester and Buffalo, but does not include New York
City, where a similar suit is pending.
</P>
<P>
   The basis for the lawsuit represents a departure from most
anti-discrimination lawsuits brought against school districts in
that it does not focus on equity of financing among school
districts but rather on student performance. In so doing, it
follows the reasoning of federal courts in a Yonkers desegregation
case, which said that patterns of poorer achievement by minority
students can be used as the basis to prove discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not bringing this litigation simply to force the state
to spend more money,'' said Norman Siegel, the executive director
of the New York Civil Liberties Union. ``We are challenging a range
of state educational practices that, while racially neutral on
their face, are having a discriminatory impact upon high minority
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit parallels an action involving New York City brought
last year by another group, the Campaign for Fiscal Equity, which,
following the more traditional model, contends that the state's
failure to provide adequate financing for city students constitutes
discrimination against them.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the two actions are the broadest legal challenge
to date against a state educational system that concedes it has not
applied the same academic standards to all students and, as a
result, has recently been moving to correct that disparity with
more rigorous academic requirements for all students.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers in the case filed Thursday argue that the state's
efforts to dictate new academic standards from the top have not
sufficiently ensured equal treatment for minority students.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the New York State Education Department, Alan
Ray, declined to comment on the lawsuit, because the matter was
pending before the courts.
</P>
<P>
   As a remedy, the suit seeks to force the state to ensure that
minority students receive, among other things, equal access to
fully licensed teachers, adequate remedial instruction and courses
geared at helping them earn honors diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   The suit does not spell out how the state should accomplish this
goal. But a lawyer for the civil liberties union, Christopher Dunn,
said that state education officials could choose any number of
options, from taking over poorly performing schools to carrying out
court-ordered desegregation plans.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit represents about 80,000 minority students, many of
them attending school districts in some of the state's largest
cities. The average school district in the state has about 2,000
students.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations in the suit are based on academic performance
records obtained from the state education department that date back
to 1989. Lawyers for the civil liberties union said it took them
more than two years to compile the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Among the contentions of the suit are that students in
predominantly minority schools are twice as likely to be taught by
unlicensed teachers, six times as likely to be denied remedial
instruction, twice as likely to drop out and a third less likely to
earn the states highly competitive Regents high school diploma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
